<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<bible xml:lang="bko" backtTranslaltionDefaultLanguage="en" oxes="2.0">
  <book id="GEN" stage="Rev" version="M">
    <Annotation class="History">
      <Message author="John Wimbish" created="2009-10-05 05:40:30Z" when="2009-10-05 05:40:30Z" stage="Draft">draft based on Kupang Genesis; 1-36 drafted by Lazarus Aplugi; 37-50 drafted by Michael Sina; Coordinator: Rev. Dr. Ayub Ranoh; Advisor: Dr. C. Grimes; team revision included Lazarus Lusi and Paul, (but doesn't appear that changes made it into the computer file from the team revision) ; Advisor check in Darwin, March 2004 with Michael, Lazarus A. &amp; Chuck, Ayub came for 1 week; UNS check with Dhao fishermen in Namosain by Michael and Lazarus, 29 April-4 May 2004; Consultant check with Marge Crofts 28 Sep Kupang , Sinode; checked *priest, a'a-ari, Jahudi, June 2007</Message>
    </Annotation>
    <p class="Header" usfm="h">Lii lolo dhu uru tèka</p>
    <p class="Title Main" usfm="mt">Lii lolo dhu uru tèka<bt>The story of the beginning</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">Nèti Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i dedha-liru dènge rai-haha<bt>About God making/creating heaven and earth</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p" />
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i dedha-liru, rai-haha, dènge isi ra<bt>God creates heaven, earth, and their contents</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="1" />
      <v n="1" />Uru-uru tèka, Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i dedha-liru dènge rai-haha.<bt>In the very beginning, God created heaven (sky-above) and earth (land-below).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Begins Seder (major division for reading"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Begins Seder (major division for reading on a three-year cycle) reʔshit: starting point in time, first (with a sense of also the best). Parallels John 1:1.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>baraʔ: create (something new), bring into existence, cause to be; used only with God as subject shamayim: heavens, sky, air around us; the atmosphere below the "firmament"<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Lod'o rai-haha j'aj'i mèka, aa'i-aa'i dhae mèci mèka. Dhu abhu, èi. Aa maroga aatu-aatu saguru nare ne. Ka Roh Lamatua lela ètu dedha èi èèna.<bt>Before the earth was created, there was not yet anything. What there was, was water. And pitch black/dark enveloped/covered it. And2 the Spirit of God2 flew above that water.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haytah: become, happen, exist, copula tohu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">haytah: become, happen, exist, copula tohu: wasteland, emptiness, formlessness, chaos. Change order, sounds better.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>bohu: void, waste choshekh: night, darkness<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>tehom: primeval ocean, deep sea. An emotionally charged word used a lot in poetry, not just "deep" as a measurement. ruaH ʔəlohiym: could be "the Spirit of God" or "a wind from God" or "a mighty wind" (pagan Nineveh is "a city of God" in Jonah, meaning it's a huge city, not that it's a godly city or a sacred city).<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>mrachefet: hovering tremblingly</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Ibrani ètu ne'e, sasoa na bisa &lt;Roh Lamatua&gt;, bisa &lt;ngèlu nèti Lamatua&gt;, bisa &lt;koasa nèti Lamatua&gt; kahèi.<bt>According to the Hebrew language here, its meaning can be &lt;God2's Spirit&gt;, or &lt;wind from God2&gt;, or also &lt;power from God2&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="3" />Hèia Ama Lamatua peka, &lt;&lt;Hud'i ku dènge saraa.&gt;&gt; Ropa peka nare sèmi ne'e, ka saraa j'aj'i dènge ka.<bt>Then God spoke, &lt;&lt;There must be light.&gt;&gt; When [He] spoke like this, the light happened straightaway.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔor: light of day, brightness, appearing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔor: light of day, brightness, appearing in the spatial setting defined in verse 2.</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ropa nèdhi saraa ne, d'ara Na karej'e, lula ngaa dhu Na ad'u, mema be'a. Hèia Na hag'e eele saraa nèti maroga, sèna ka èci-èci ka dènge taa na.<bt>When [He] saw the light, His insides were happy, because what He had done/made, was really good. Then He selected out the light from the dark, so that each had its own time.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyraʔ ... ki: saw the light,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayyraʔ ... ki: saw the light, that it was good = saw how good the light is. "look someting" is not the same as "look at someting." "Stay" with "good" might be taken that it isn't an inherently good thing in itself (which is what the Hebrew implies and theology emphasizes), but that it was okay for the present and might change. "Saw how good it was" is a positive affirmation, not a last minute check to make sure nothing had gone wrong. yavdel (bdl hif): distinguish between ("put someting" + locative noun is standard; "put on" may be overkill.<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Ka pangare saraa ne &lt;mèu&gt;, aa maroga na &lt;mèda&gt;. Ne'e ne, lod'o ka èci kèna.<bt>And [He] named the light &lt;daylight/daytime&gt;, and the dark &lt;night&gt;. This was day one/first day.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqraʔ: give a name yom: daylight"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiqraʔ: give a name yom: daylight hours; also 24-hour period, time for something, long period during which certain things happen<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>laylah: at night ʕerev: evening, sunset<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>boker: light of daybreak, morning</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="6-7" />Hèia Ama Lamatua lii hari, Na peka, &lt;&lt;Hud'i dènge ku era talele, sèna ka hag'e eele èi. Nèti èèna ka, èi re dedha, aa abhu kahèi èi re haha.&gt;&gt; Ropa peka nare sèmi èèna, hèia èi b'agi dènge mi dua.<bt>Then God spoke again, He said, &lt;&lt;There must be an empty place, to separate out the water. So there will be water above, and also water below.&gt;&gt; When He had spoken like that, then the water divided into two.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raqiyaʕ: beaten metal plate; vault of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">raqiyaʕ: beaten metal plate; vault of heaven, solid dome (not implied by the Hebrew, but used in LXX, possibly under the influence of Alexandrian philosophy (TWOT: also In the OT, however, Isaiah insists that God "stretches out the heavens [lit.] like gauze (do4q, Isa 40:22); and even Ezekiel's limited canopy (ra4q|&lt;a() is "as the [lit.] eye of awesome ice" (Ezk 1:22), i.e. transparent, "shining like crystal" (RSV), though so dazzling as to be terrifying (KD; cf. Dan 12:3 "brightness").) tok: middle, throughout<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>mavdil: participle, a distinction, segregated yaʔash: manufacture, create (when God does it), produce<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>mitchat: that is underneath ʕal: over<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>vayhi ken: that's how it came out</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ka Na pangare èi re dedha na, &lt;liru&gt;. Ne'e ne, lod'o ka dua kèna.<bt>And He named the water above, &lt;sky&gt;. This was day two.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="era talele = tempat kosong"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">era talele = tempat kosong</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of P section</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="9" />Hèia Ama Lamatua peka hari, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èi re haha hud'i pakaboko ku mi ca era, sèna ka abhu rai kamango.&gt;&gt; Ropa padhai lii nare sèmi ne'e, j'aj'i dènge ka rai mango.<bt>Then God spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;The water below must gather/collect in one place, so that there is dry land.&gt;&gt; When He had finished speaking like that, the dry land happened straightaway.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqqawu (qwh nif): come together, be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiqqawu (qwh nif): come together, be collected (intransitive) ʔel-maqom echad: one place (doesn't say where), area<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>vteraʔah: become visible hayyabbashah: dry land, opposite of ‘sea’<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>miqveh: accumulation (what you get when qwh happens)</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ka era rai mango, Na pangare na &lt;rai-dedha&gt;; aa era èi dhu kaboko èèna, Na pangare na &lt;dhasi&gt;. Ropa nèdhi aa'i-aa'i ne, d'ara Na karej'e, lula ngaa dhu Na ad'u, mema be'a.<bt>And the place of the dry land, He named &lt;earth/land&gt;; and the place of the gathered water, He named &lt;sea&gt;. When he saw all of it, His insides were happy, because what He had done/made, was really good.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yammim: seas, like the Mediterranean, that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yammim: seas, like the Mediterranean, that were more familiar than the mysterious tehom; all the different bodies of water</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Ka Ama Lamatua lii hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Rai hud'i pamamuri ku rupa-rupa ana aaj'u. Sèna ka abhu aj'u dhu hua, dhu dènge lamusi, aa dhu dènge rèu mangèru. Sèna ka aj'u-aj'u se, hua-hela madhutu rupa rèngu.&gt;&gt; Ropa padhai lii nare sèmi ne'e, j'aj'i dènge ka ana aaj'u aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>And God spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;The land must cause to live various sorts of trees/plants (not just trees) So that there are plants which have fruit, which have seed, and which have green leaves [Remapping into locally relevant categories.] So that these plants produce according to their kind.&gt;&gt; When He had finished speaking like that, all the plants happened straightaway.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tadsheʔ: be green with grass, sprout"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tadsheʔ: be green with grass, sprout desheʔ: new fresh grass like what comes up after it rains<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʕesev mazriaʕ zeraʕ: technical term for the green plants of the rainy season, seed-producing plants rather than perennials ʕets: trees in general<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>peri: fruit bearing kind ʕosheh: manufacturing, producing<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>minu, minehu: species zarʕu: form seed, zarʕu-vu seed in it<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ètu dedha-rai, ana aaj'u se hua-hela ka madhutu rupa rèngu. Ropa nèdhi aa'i-aa'i se, d'ara Na karej'e, lula ngaa dhu Na ad'u, mema be'a.<bt>On the land, various sorts of plants produced according to their kind. When He saw all this, His insides were happy, because what He had done/made was really good.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="totseʔ (= yatsaʔ): bring forth, produce,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">totseʔ (= yatsaʔ): bring forth, produce, what the ground does minehu, minu: species, type<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Ne'e ne, lod'o ka tèlu kèna.<bt>This was day three.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kamango = dry, kering (land, not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">kamango = dry, kering (land, not clothes); 11: ana aaj'u-ana aaj'u = plants (not just trees) ; hua-hela = menghasilkan, mengeluarkan hasil (lit. buah-bunga)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="14-15" />Hèia Ama Lamatua lii hari, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Re bèka dedha, hud'i abhu ku mèdha dhu saraa, ho pasaraa rai-haha ne. Hud'i abhu mèdha dhu pasaraa re mèu, aa abhu kahèi dhu pasaraa re mèda. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i se, j'aj'i tadha, ho sèna ka bisa ige lod'o, hèru, dènge tèu.&gt;&gt; Ropa padhai lii nare sèmi ne'e, mèdha dhu heo aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i dènge ka.<bt>Then God spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;On the upper side/part, there must be things that shine, to shine onto this earth. There must be a thing to shine during the daytime, and there must also be [one] to shine at night. All of them will be signs, so that [people] can count days, months/seasons1, and years/seasons2.&gt;&gt; When He had finished speaking like that, all the things which shone2 happened immediately.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mʔorot: luminaries, things that give out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mʔorot: luminaries, things that give out light birqiyaʕ: in the vault = v. 6<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>l-: for the purpose of. In the context of "let there be X," the infinitives give the functions of X. Pidgin grammar can subordinate these with "fo," but it gets dull fast that way. Telling what they are supposed to do sounds better. havdil (bdl hif inf): the distinguishing or separating of something - also used of the "firmament"<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʔotot: marks, signs, banners; omens announcing things to come moʕədim: appointed time, fixed day, time of feast, religious festivals, special days to worship God, or possibly parts of the year<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>yamim: day-long periods shanim: years<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>birqiyaʕ: in the vault = v. 6 haʔiyr (ʔwr hif inf): to illuminate<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʔarets: world, land, ground</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Ka Na tao ka mèdha kapai dua dhu pasaraa rai-haha. Dhu kapai risi, pasaraa re mèu; aa dhu ako ana iiki, pasaraa re mèda. Aa Na tao hua-hètu kahèi.<bt>And He placed/made two large things which shone on the earth. The larger, shone during the daytime; and the slightly smaller, shone at night. And He also made the stars.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyaʕas (ʕsh narrative): the next thing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayyaʕas (ʕsh narrative): the next thing that happened was that he made. Ross's suggestion "had made" would fit better if it were ʕasah. shni: years (construct)<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>haggadolim: great (in importance) memshelet: ruling power<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>hayyom ... hallaylah: in the daytime ... in the nighttime qatan: be small, trifling<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>kokhavim: stars</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Na tèke mèdha dhu saraa sèra ètu dedha-liru, sèna ka loti mai asa rai-haha.<bt>He arranged/placed (long-term) the things which shone up in the sky, so they could face/scrutinize/spotlight toward the earth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitten: put, provide ʔotam: them|i(17) |r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yitten: put, provide ʔotam: them<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ka mèdha se, pasaraa ka re mèu, aa pasaraa re mèda. Dènge j'ara ne'e, Na hag'e eele saraa nèti maroga. Ropa nèdhi aa'i-aa'i se, d'ara Na karej'e, lula ngaa dhu Na ad'u, mema be'a.<bt>And these things shone during the daytime, and shone at night. In this way, He separated out light from dark. When He saw all those, His insides were happy, because what He had done/made, was really good.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bayyom ... ballaylah: during the day"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bayyom ... ballaylah: during the day ... during the night Here the infinitives should be translated as complementizers ("fo") to play down the information, since it has already been given once.<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>ki-tov: as in v. 4</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Ne'e ne, lod'o ka èpa kèna.<bt>This was day four.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="re = 1) melalui, lewati (re"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">re = 1) melalui, lewati (re kota Sidon), 2) pada, waktu (re mèda) heo = 1) menyala, terang, 2) lingkar,; 18: ka (second) = ligature</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00600c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left" />
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="20" />Hèia Ama Lamatua padhai lii hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Hud'i abhu ku ae-ae dhu mamuri ètu d'ara èi. Dènge hud'i abhu ku rupa-rupa manu-bhui dhu lela ètu dedha rai-haha ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then God spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;There must be many sorts of things which live in the water. And there must be various sorts of birds which fly above this earth.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishrtsu: a place swarms with or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yishrtsu: a place swarms with or teems with something alive sherets: tiny animals occurring in large numbers somewhere<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>Hayyah: animals ʕof: flying creatures = bugs and birds<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>ʕal: two complementary human perspectives: above the ground, across the sky</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ka Na tao ka i'a aa'i-aa'i dènge badha kapai dhu mamuri ètu d'ara èi. Na paj'aj'i kahèi manu-bhui aa'i-aa'i. Ropa nèdhi aa'i-aa'i se, d'ara Na karej'e, lula ngaa dhu Na ad'u, mema be'a.<bt>And He made all the fish and the large animals which live in the water. He also created all the birds. When He saw all these, His insides were happy, because what He had done/made, was really good.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taninim: sea-monsters, sea-dragons haromeshet: swarming creatures,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">taninim: sea-monsters, sea-dragons haromeshet: swarming creatures, teeming creatures<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>minehem: species, kind kol-ʕof kanaf<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Ka Na padhai lii ho sèna ka hia berkat mi aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri, peka na, &lt;&lt;I'a se, hud'i laa bèba-kacanga sèna ka papènu èi ètu mia-mia. Aa manu-bhui, asa tabha kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>And He spoke to give blessing to everything that was alive, and said, &lt;&lt;These fish must flourish/increasing in number so that they fill the waters everywhere. And the birds must also increase in number2.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yvarekh: make someone able to fulfill"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yvarekh: make someone able to fulfill his or her destiny, do what they were designed to do, bestow power for success (English "bless" in its most basic sense; other senses have to do with verbal actions intended to bring this about or showing appreciation for it) pru: be fruitful<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>rvu: become numerous milʔu: fill up<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>yammim: in the seas</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Ne'e ne, lod'o ka lèmi kèna.<bt>This was day five.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="i'a iu = shark ; lugi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">i'a iu = shark ; lugi rai = whale ; ruj'u = duyung ; ènyu = penyu ; èla = sayap; 22: bèba kacanga ; mèngi-nale = Kuno, not known by all</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="24-25" />Ka Ama Lamatua peka hari, na, &lt;&lt;Hud'i abhu ku rupa-rupa badha dhu mamuri ètu rai-dedha. Sèmi: badha-manu dhu ani, badha hui, dènge badha dhu rod'o, èci-èci ka dènge rupa na.&gt;&gt; Ropa padhai lii nare sèmi ne'e, badha aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i dènge ka. Ropa nèdhi aa'i-aa'i se, d'ara Na karej'e, lula ngaa dhu Na ad'u, mema be'a.<bt>And God spoke again, &lt;&lt;There must be various kinds of animals which live on the earth. Such as: domestic animals, wild animals, and animals that crawl, each with its own kind.&gt;&gt; When He had finished speaking like that, all the animals happened immediately.When He saw all of these, His insides were happy, because what He had done/made, was really good.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="totseʔ (ytsʔ hif imperf): produce v.12"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">totseʔ (ytsʔ hif imperf): produce v.12 chayyah: living things<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>bəhemah: animals in general, here probably domestic animals in contrast with Hayto remes: collective of small animals including reptiles -- everything except large animals and birds. It would include mice and rats and mongoose, as well as lizards and snakes.<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>chayto: living beings, animals, especially untamed land animals ʔadamah: soil producing plants<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ka Ama Lamatua peka hari, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hua iia, mai Ta paj'aj'i dhèu, madhutu rupa Èdhi. Hud'i laa ra leru dènge ator i'a aa'i-aa'i ètu d'ara dhasi, manu-bhui aa'i-aa'i ètu dedha-liru, badha-manu dhu ani, dènge badha leo aa'i-aa'i ra dhu mamuri ètu rai-haha ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>And God spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;It would be good for Us-inc to create humans, according to Our type/kind/shape. They must look after and manage [see Hamilton] all the (kinds of) fish in the sea, all the (kinds of) birds in the sky, the domestic animals, and all the (kinds of) other animals which live on the earth.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="1:26" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kolose 1:16</note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00604c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Hèia Na paj'aj'i dhèu rai-haha ne madhutu rupa Na. Na paj'aj'i si, dhèu mone dènge dhèu bhèni.<bt>Then He created humans (=people of the earth) according to His kind/type/shape. He created them male person and female person.</bt><v n="28" />Ka Na padhai lii ho sèna ka hia berkat mi rèngu, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu hud'i bèba-kacanga ku, sèna ka pea papènu rai-haha ne, ho mi ator ne. Ja'a hia miu koasa, sèna ka mi ator i'a, manu-bhui, dènge badha-manu aa'i-aa'i ra ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>And He spoke to give blessing to them, saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl must increase (in number) so that you live filling up this earth, so that you can manage it. I give you power/authority, so that you can manage the fish, the birds, and all the animals that are on this earth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pru: be fruitful, bear fruit rvu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">pru: be fruitful, bear fruit rvu: become many<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>kivshuah (kbsh imperv): make subservient, subdue rdu (rdh imperv): rule<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>Hayyah: beasts, living things romeset (partcpl fem sg): creeping, crawling<span class="Italic">(28)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Mi nanene paie-iie! Ja'a hia miu rupa-rupa nganga'a ètu rai-haha ne'e. Sèmi: ana aaj'u dhu dènge hua, dhu dènge lamusi, aa dhu dènge rèu mangèru.<bt>Listen well! I give you various/all sorts of food on this earth. Such as: trees/plants which have fruit, which have seed, and which have green leaves.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕesev: every plant zoreaʕ: producing seeds|i(29)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕesev: every plant zoreaʕ: producing seeds<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>hinneh: emphasizes the following clause, something unexpected. I doesn't mean to look at something; it has more to do with the fact that what he is about to say is significant</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Ja'a hia rupa-rupa ana aaj'u kahèi sèna ka j'aj'i nganga'a badha. Nganga'a hia badha-manu dhu ani, badha hui, badha dhu rod'o, dènge manu-bhui.&gt;&gt; Ropa padhai lii nare sèmi ne'e, nganga'a badha sèra aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i dènge ka.<bt>I also give various/all sorts of trees/plants to be animal food. Food for the domestic animals, the wild animals, the crawling animals, and the birds.&gt;&gt; When He had finished speaking like that, all those sorts of animal food happened straightaway.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yereq: green plant, verdure"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yereq: green plant, verdure</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Ropa nèdhi aa'i-aa'i se, d'ara Na karej'e, lula ngaa dhu Na ad'u, mema be'a. Ne'e ne, lod'o ka èna kèna.<bt>When He saw all this, His insides were happy, because what He had done/made, was really good. This was day six.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lalole = model, pinggang ; dhèu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">lalole = model, pinggang ; dhèu rai-haha; 28: tao ai-hèba = taro perhatian; 30: tesa-tesa = tersedia</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of P section</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="2" />
      <v n="1" />Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna ka, Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i dedha-liru, rai-haha, dènge isi ra aa'i-aa'i.<bt>In that way, God created heaven, earth, and all their contents.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yikhullu (klh puʕal): were completed, finished"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yikhullu (klh puʕal): were completed, finished tsvaʔam: the host of them; host of heaven: heavenly objects, i.e. sun, moon, stars<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="2" />Ropa Na sab'a èle, asa bèli èèna, lèke dènge lod'o ka pidhu. Hèia Na ae nèti sasab'a-la'a Na.<bt>When He had finished working, the following day, fell on day seven. So/then He stopped from His work.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ykhal (klh piʕel narr): he finished"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ykhal (klh piʕel narr): he finished mlaʔaktu: his job, the work he was doing, his task<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>yishbot: stop working, come to a standstill</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Dènge j'ara ne'e, Na tao lod'o ka pidhu ne, lod'o dhu kapai risi nèti lod'o dhu leo sèra. Na tao sèmi èèna, lula Na pa'èle aa'i le sasab'a Na, ka ètu d'ara lod'o ka pidhu na, Na ae.<bt>In this way, He made/placed day seven, to be a day greater than the other days. He did that, because He had finished all His work, and on day seven, He stopped/rested.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yvarekh (brk piʕel narr): he blessed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yvarekh (brk piʕel narr): he blessed yqaddesh (qdsh piʕel narr): he set it apart for himself<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>shavat: more like taking the day off because he was finished, not because he was tired. baraʔ: created (used only of God)<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4a" />D'ai sange ne'e ka, lii lolo Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i dedha-liru dènge rai-haha ne.<bt>That's the extent of the narration/report about God creating heaven and earth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ae ai na = barenti tangan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">ae ai na = barenti tangan (&lt;istirahat tidak bekerja) ;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tolədot: life and times; the other"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tolədot: life and times; the other ten times this word is used in Genesis in refers to a group of generations defined by a genealogy. Here there's no generation yet, but the idea of what went on during a significant period remains. UBS and several modern translations relate it to Chapter 1, though it could be read as introducing the rest of Chapter 2. In Chapter 10 it is also used to point backwards, so the UBS idea makes sense. The style changes in the next sentence. hibarʔam (brʔ nif inf pl): being created, acts of creation<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i dhèu mone dènge dhèu bhèni<bt>God creates male person and female person</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 19:4-6; Markus 10:4-9; 1 Korintus 6:16; 15:45,47; Epesus 5:31-33)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4b" />Lod'o Ama LAMATUA heka paj'aj'i dedha-liru dènge rai-haha èèna,<bt>When LORD God had not yet created heaven and earth,</bt><v n="5-6" />dhae abhu mèka ana aaj'u, lula Na papuru mèka èj'i. Taa èèna, dhoka sèb'u èi di, mai nèti d'ara rai ho pabasa rai re dedha. Aa abhu mèka dhèu rai-haha dhu tao oka-tedhe.<bt>there were not yet trees/plants, because He had not yet sent down the rain. At that time, there was only vapour, coming from inside the ground to cause to be wet the ground above. And there were not yet humans who worked the fields (doublet).</bt><v n="7" />Èle èèna ka, Ama LAMATUA nare rai ciki, ka Na paj'aj'i dhèu rai-haha. Hèia Na tiu a'ae Na asa d'ara sahènga dhèu na, ka na mamuri dènge ka.<bt>After that, the LORD God took a little ground/soil, and He created humans. Then He blew His breath into the nostril of the person, and he came to life straightaway.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sèbu èi = uap ; pabasa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">sèbu èi = uap ; pabasa = membasahi; 7: tiu = tiup ; lai ngèlu = udara ; a'ae</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="changed Kupang also; Heb structure a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">changed Kupang also; Heb structure a b a b (rain, humans, vapour, humans) &gt; a a b b (rain, vapour, humans, humans)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Hèia Ama LAMATUA bhoke oka cue ètu rai Eden, re bèka dhimu. Hèia Na hia dhèu ne pea ètu d'ara oka na.<bt>Then the LORD God opened/made a (new) garden/field in the land of Eden, on the east side. Then He had/allowed the man stay in that garden.</bt><v n="9" />Ètu d'ara oka èèna, Na pamamuri rupa-rupa aj'u dhu be'a, dhu dhèu bisa ra'a. Aa Na pamamuri kahèi aj'u dua kapua ètu talora aae oka èèna. Ladhe dhèu ra'e hua nèti aj'u èci, na mamuri taa-taa. Aa ladhe dhèu ra'e hua nèti aj'u èci hari, ne'a hag'e mia dhu be'a, aa mia dhu karehe.<bt>Inside that garden, He brought to life various sorts of good trees/plants, which people could eat. And He also created two kinds of trees in the middle of that garden. If people ate fruit from the one tree, s/he would live forever. And if people ate fruit from the other tree, s/he would know how to distinguish what is good, and what is bad.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ètu era èèna, abhu loko èci dhu hae nèti d'ara oka èèna. Loko èèna, èpa kacanga.<bt>In that place, there was a river which flowed from that garden. That river had four river-branches [not tree-branches].</bt><v n="11" />Kacanga ka èci na, ngara na Pison. Nèngu ka dhu hae pale-lème rai Hawila dhu abhu hualaa ae-ae.<bt>The one branch was named Pison. It is the one that flowed winding throughout the land of Hawila where there was much gold. [NOTE: This is of extreme interest to this ethnic group of goldsmiths and silversmiths, so don't be surprised if we get more questions about exactly where this is.]</bt><v n="12" />Ètu era èèna ka, abhu poe-pai, aj'u dhu raa na hèu mèngi, dènge hadhu kale'e.<bt>In that place there was pure gold2, trees/plants whose sap was aromatic, and shiny/precious stones.</bt><v n="13" />Kacanga ka dua, ngara na Gihon. Kacanga ne, hae pale-lème rai Kus.<bt>The second branch, was named Gihon. This branch flowed throughout the land of Kus.</bt><note reference="2:13" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Uru èèna, rai ne, ngara na &lt;Kus&gt;. Limuri ne, rai Kus ne ca bèka ètu negara Etiopia dènge negara Sudan, ètu Afrika re dhimu.<bt>Formerly, the land was named &lt;Kus&gt;. Now this Kus land is part of the country of Etiopia, and the country of Sudan on the eastern side of Afrika.</bt></note><v n="14" />Kacanga ka tèlu, ngara na Tigris. Kacanga ne'e ka, j'aj'i mi too rai Asyur<bt>The third branch was named Tigris. This branch was the boundary of the land of Asyur</bt><note reference="2:14" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Asyur ne'e, negara dhu limuri ne, ngara na &lt;Irak&gt;.<bt>That Asyur, is the country which is now named &lt;Irak&gt;.</bt></note>re ca bèka dhimu. Kacanga ka èpa, ngara na Efrat.<bt>along the eastern side. The fourth branch was named Efrat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kacanga = branch of river ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">kacanga = branch of river ; dadana = branch of tree; 11: palelème = zigzag ; palème = go around; 12: poe-pai = pure gold, emas murni/asli ; hadhu kale'e = batu mangkilat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ka Ama LAMATUA hia dhèu pea ètu d'ara Eden, ho na ladhe-leru oka èèna.<bt>And the LORD God had/allowed people/person to live inside Eden, to look after that garden.</bt><v n="16" />Hèia Na hia paredha mi dhèu ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hua aaj'u aa'i-aa'i ètu d'ara oka ne, èu bisa mu'a.<bt>Then He commanded the person, saying, &lt;&lt;Fruit from all the trees/plants inside this garden, you may eat.</bt><v n="17" />Te ngaa èci dhu èu bisa boe mu'a. Nuka hua nèti aj'u dhu ne'a hag'e mia dhu be'a, aa mia dhu karehe. Ladhe mu'a, èu madhe dènge.&gt;&gt;<bt>But, one you must not eat. That is fruit from the tree which distinguishes which is good, and which is bad/evil. If you eat, you will (certainly, immediately?) die.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ka Ama LAMATUA tuhu haru lii Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Babe'a na aad'o, ladhe dhèu ne mamuri mesa na. De Ja'a neo paj'aj'i hia ne, anga ca dhèu dhu pamèci dènge ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>And the LORD God continued speaking, saying, &lt;&lt;There is no goodness, if people/person lives alone. So I am going to create for him a companion person to join/match with him.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamèci = cocok, sesuai, sepadan, serasi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pamèci = cocok, sesuai, sepadan, serasi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19-20" />Lod'o èèna, Ama LAMATUA nare rai ciki, ka Na tao rupa-rupa badha dènge manu-bhui. Hèia Na pangèd'u si asa dhèu ne, sèna ka na pangare si. Ka dhèu ne pangare badha se dènge manu-bhui aa'i-aa'i ra, èci-èci ka dènge ngara ra. Te ngaa dhèu ne abhu mèka anga dhu pamèci dènge nèngu.<bt>That day/time, the LORD God took some land/soil, and He made various sorts of animals and birds. then He turned over/entrusted them to the person, so he could name them. And the person named the animals, and all the birds, each according to their names. But the person did not yet have a companion to join/match with him.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00603c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:bottom" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Hèia Ama LAMATUA pabhèj'i luu dhèu ne'e. Ropa na bhèj'i, Ama Lamatua nare rui karasa na calaa, ka Na pakateme hari nu'a deo na.<bt>Then the LORD God put the person into a deep sleep. When he was asleep, God took one of his rib-bones, and then He restored/made whole that aforementioned wound.</bt><v n="22" />Nèti rui ne, Na paj'aj'i bhèni ca dhèu. Hèia Na pangèd'u bhèni ne mi dhèu èèna.<bt>From that bone, He created/made a female person. Then He turned over/entrusted the woman to that person.</bt><v n="23" />Ropa ladhe nèdhi bhèni ne, ka dhèu na peka, aku nèngu na,<bt>When he saw tha woman, the person spoke, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pabhèj'i luu = cause to sleep,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pabhèj'i luu = cause to sleep, put to sleep ; rui karasa = rib ; calaa = satu batang ; pakateme = bekin anteru</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Waaa! Ne'e ne ku! Sèmi ne'e ku, heka pamèci dènge ja'a kèna!<bt>&lt;&lt;Waaa! This is the one! Only now does this one join/match with me!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Rui na, sama èci èèna ka dènge rui ja'a.<bt>Her bones, are just like my bones.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Aa isi na, sama kahèi dènge isi ja'a.<bt>And her flesh/meat/muscle, is the same as my flesh.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="isi ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">isi =</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula nèngu ne, j'aj'i nèti dhèu mone, nèti èèna ka ja'a pangare ne, &lt;dhèu bhèni&gt;.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because she jadi from male-person, that is why I name her &lt;female-person&gt;.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="2:23" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">D'ara lii Ibrani, dhèu mone ngara na &lt;<span class="Italic">ish</span>&gt;. Aa bhèni na, &lt;<span class="Italic">isha</span>&gt;. Ka ètu ne'e ne, ra pab'unge lii padhai, peka na, &lt;&lt;<span class="Italic">isha</span> (dhèu bhèni) j'aj'i nèti <span class="Italic">ish</span> (dhèu mone).&gt;&gt;<bt>In the Ibrani language male person is &lt;<span class="Italic">ish</span>&gt;. And female is &lt;<span class="Italic">isha</span>&gt;. So here they (non-referential) are playing with words, saying, &lt;&lt;<span class="Italic">isha</span> (female-person) came into being from <span class="Italic">ish</span> (male-person).&gt;&gt;</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="24" />Nèti èèna ka, dhèu mone hud'i tèke eele ku ina-ama na,<bt>Because of that, a male person must leave behind his mother-father,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho la'e mamuri d'ara èci dènge dhèu èmu-kamali na,<bt>to go live with one insides with his spouse (doublet),</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu èmu-kamali = suami-isteri"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">dhèu èmu-kamali = suami-isteri</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula dua ra, j'aj'i le èci.<bt>because the two of them, have become one/united/joined.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Lod'o èèna, dua ra dhu dènge boe mèdha-papake, te ngaa ra makae boe.<bt>At that time, the two of them were without clothes, but they were not ashamed/embarrassed.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu ro'o boe madhutu lii Ama Lamatua<bt>People do not want to follow/obey what God says</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="3" />
      <v n="1" />Nèti badha aa'i-aa'i dhu Ama LAMATUA paj'aj'i ètu rai-haha ne, mege ka dhu mèu risi kapod'e-kabèli. Ca lod'o, mege karèi bhèni na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a, do? Ama Lamatua kai miu baku mi'a hua aaj'u aa'i-aa'i ètu d'ara oka ne'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>From/among all the animals which the LORD God had created on this earth, the snake was the most clever at deception/lying. One day, the snake asked the woman, saying, &lt;&lt;Is it true, or (not)? God forbade you-pl to not eat any of the plant fruit inside this garden.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕarum: subtle, shrewd, clever; crafty, sly,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕarum: subtle, shrewd, clever; crafty, sly, wise -- wise, but with an evil agenda. In Hebrew the word sounds like ʕarummim "naked" in 2:25 ʔaf: really? even; agreeing but not agreeing<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00606c.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2-3" />Ka bhèni na b'ala, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Ji'i bisa nga'a! Dhodhoka aj'u ca kapua ètu talora oka ne, Ama Lamatua kai, baku nga'a hua na. Na peka na, ji'i baku nga'a, aa baku g'ag'e hua èèna kahèi, te aad'o na, ji'i madhe!&gt;&gt;<bt>The woman replied, &lt;&lt;No! We-exc can eat! Only one tree in the middle of the garden, God forbade, we should/may not eat its fruit. He said, we could not eat it, and not touch/feel its fruit either, cuz otherwise we would die!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pen: lest, so that ... not,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">pen: lest, so that ... not, prevent an otherwise predictable event tmutun: for you to die<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Te ngaa mege na dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Waa! Sèmi boe èèna! Miu se madhe boe!<bt>But, the snake responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Waa! It's not like that! You-pl will not die!</bt><v n="5" />Ama Lamatua mema kai tare'a sèmi èèna, lula dhu ne'a le, ladhe mi'e hua aaj'u èèna, miu j'aj'i d'èlu-mèu sèmi Nèngu. Ho èèna na me'a mia dhu be'a, aa mia dhu karehe.&gt;&gt;<bt>God really did forbid you like that, because He knows that, if you-pl eat the fruit of that tree, you will become knowledgeable/wise like Him. So that you would know which is good, and which is bad/evil.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nifqəhu: passive, be opened (eyes, not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nifqəhu: passive, be opened (eyes, not other things) -- metaphor for coming to understand (see) things after not knowing, which is like wandering around in the dark ʕeyneychem: your eyes<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>yodʕey (partcpl pl): those who know</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Aa bhèni ne ladhe na aj'u ne be'a titu kèna, dènge hua na ele boe kee. Na ngee, &lt;&lt;Ladhe ja'a ku'a hua aj'u ne'e, ja'a d'èlu-mèu.&gt;&gt; Hèia puu nare ka hua aj'u èèna, ka na'e. Na'e nare, nèti hia dhèu èmu na, ka na'a kahèi.<bt>And the woman saw that the tree was very nice/beautiful, and its fruit was probably sweet. She thought, &lt;&lt;If I eat fruit from this tree, I will be wise/knowledgeable.&gt;&gt; So she picked fruit from that tree, and ate. After eating, she took and gave it to her spouse, and he also ate.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taʔəwah-huʔ: longing, desire; it was a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">taʔəwah-huʔ: longing, desire; it was a delight to the eyes nechmad: desirable<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>lhaskil (skl hif inf): make you understand, make you be keen and clever mipiryo: some of its fruit<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>gam: associating, adding, too</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ra'a rare ka, heka re'a na rèngu dhu pake boe mèdha dhu hutu ua rèngu. Nèti èèna ka, ra lui rèu aj'u ho pa'abhe era makae rèngu.<bt>After they ate, only-then did they know/realise that they were not wearing clothes to cover their bodies. That is why they stitched tree leaves to block/cover the place of their shame (=genitals).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ele boe = mangkali ; kee"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">ele boe = mangkali ; kee = manis; 7: kabhèdi laa = takuju ; ka'ola = telanjang (tidak sopan) ; lui = natok ; era makae</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tipaqachnah (nif): were opened, the eyes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tipaqachnah (nif): were opened, the eyes of the two of them ʕeyrummim (adj): naked<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>yitpəru (tpr): sew things together (fasten?) ʕaleh: leaves, foliage. SK "would have been cheaper"<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>tʔenah: fig, Ficus Carica has fairly big leaves, bigger than your hand but smaller than a taro leaf; FF 118,119 chgorot: loincloths, belts, sashes, something around the middle; a band (made out of leather or cloth) or a piece of cloth worn around the waist<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />D'ai lod'o nihia, dua ra tadèngi lii core haga Ama LAMATUA ètu d'ara oka èèna. Ka dua ra rai lasi lu'u asa ca bèka aj'u, sèna ka LAMATUA baku nèdhi si.<bt>That late-afternoon, the two of them heard the sound of the steps of the LORD God inside that garden. The two of them ran and hid behind a tree, so that the LORD wouldn't see them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mithallekh (hlk hitp partcpl): walking vayyishimiʕu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mithallekh (hlk hitp partcpl): walking vayyishimiʕu: they heard<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>qol: voice, sound vayyitchabeʔ (chbʔ hitp sg with pl NP): be in a place where one can not be readily seen, often used in contexts implying danger<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Te ngaa Ama LAMATUA paroa mi dhèu mone èèna, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Adam! Èu ètu mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>But, the LORD God called to the man, saying, &lt;&lt;Adam! Where are you?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii core haga = bunyi langkah,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">lii core haga = bunyi langkah, sound of footsteps ; lu'u = sembunyi</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqraʔ: call out to somebody lo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiqraʔ: call out to somebody lo ʔayyekah: ?<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Hèia mone na dhaa, &lt;&lt;Ja'a tadèngi lii Lamatua ètu ne'e. Te ngaa ja'a makae, lula ja'a pake boe mèdha ètu ua. Nèti èèna ka, ja'a rai pahuni iisi.&gt;&gt;<bt>And the man answered, &lt;&lt;I heard the Lord's sound/voice here. But I was ashamed/embarrassed, because I was not wearing anything on my body. That is why I ran and hid myself.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔiyraʔ: I was afraid"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔiyraʔ: I was afraid</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ka Lamatua peka na, &lt;&lt;Cee ka dhu peka, na èu dhu pake boe mèdha-papake? De tasamia? Tatu èu mu'a le hua aj'u dhu Ja'a kai na, sina ma?&gt;&gt;<bt>And the Lord said, &lt;&lt;Who is it that said you were not wearing any clothes? How about it? Surely you have eaten the fruit of the tree which I forbade, right?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mi: who? higgid (ngd hif): announced"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mi: who? higgid (ngd hif): announced to you (sg)<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʕeyrom: naked ha-: is it ...? isn't it ...?<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>tsiwwiyticha: I ordered you, I forbade you lbtilti: non-existence, not to do something<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʔəkhal (inf): to eat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ka na b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Bhèni dhu Èu hia ho pa'anga dènge ja'a èèna, ka dhu hia ja'a ku'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>And he replied, saying, &lt;&lt;The woman that You gave to companion me is the one who gave me to eat!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'anga = temani ; pa'ango ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pa'anga = temani ; pa'ango = saling membujuk utk diterima, try to seduce, rayu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="natattah: you gave, put here ʕimmadi:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">natattah: you gave, put here ʕimmadi: my company, with me to help me [SK laugh]<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ʔokhel (narrative): I ate [it]</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Hèia Ama LAMATUA peka dènge bhèni na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka, èu ad'u madha j'ara èèna?&gt;&gt;<bt>So the LORD God spoke to the woman, saying, &lt;&lt;Why did you do this thing/way?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka bhèni ne dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Te mege ne ka dhu ag'o ja'a! Nèti èèna ka, ja'a ku'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>And the woman responded, saying, &lt;&lt;It was the snake who tricked me! That is why I ate it.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ag'o = tipu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">ag'o = tipu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mah-zzot: what is this? why? This"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mah-zzot: what is this? why? This is an accusing question, accuses the person addressed of doing something wrong ʕasit: do, make, bring about<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>hishshiʔani (nshʔ hif): duped, tricked, deceived</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua dhoo si<bt>God curses them</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Èle èèna ka, Ama LAMATUA dhoo mege èèna, aku Nèngu na,<bt>After that, the LORD cursed that snake, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhoo = kutuk"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">dhoo = kutuk</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">&lt;&lt;Ja'a huku èu, lula tatao èu. Nèti badha aa'i-aa'i, dhoka èu di dhu abhu huku sèmi ne'e. Mulai nèti deo ne'e toke èu madhe, èu dhoka rod'o dènge kakara, aa mu'a ètu rai di.<bt>&lt;&lt;Because of your deed, I will punish you. From/among all the animals, only you get a punishment like this. Beginning from right now until you die, you will only crawl on your chest, and just eat on the ground.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔarur (ʔrr partcpl passive): inflicted with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔarur (ʔrr partcpl passive): inflicted with a curse (by God) miqol habehemah: away from all the animals, in a way that the animals are not (also 4:11), domestic or wild<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ghon: belly of a reptile telek (halak): go, characteristic was of getting around. For snakes, crawl or creep<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʕafar: dry, fine particles of dirt, dust, loose soil, rubble from something that has been destroyed. Carries with it the idea of something perishable and transitory toʔchal: eat, probably metaphorically rather than physically. The two lines mean about the same thing. Should they be collapsed?<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Ja'a tao sèna ka, èu loe boe pamusu dènge bhèni ne. Aa ana-èpu miu dua mi sèmi èèna kahèi. Ana-èpu èu, èèna na kadhi hui tèdhu dhèu. Te ngaa ca dhèu nèti ana-èpu bhèni ne, èèna na dhedhe palaho kètu èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>I will make it so you will not stop being mutual-enemies with this woman. And the children-grandchildren (=descendants) of the two of you will be the same as well. Your descendants will bite the heel of people/person. But one of the descendants of this woman, will pound smashing your head.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hui tèdhu = tumit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">hui tèdhu = tumit</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeyvah: hostile intention, enmity, enemy ʔashit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔeyvah: hostile intention, enmity, enemy ʔashit (shayat): I order, put, appoint, direct, make something into something<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>zeraʕ: seed, offspring. Can be plural, all humans. Can be singular, one particular descendent, a prophecy of Christ yshufcha (shwp): he will crush you [SK picha!]<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>roʔsh: head tshufennu (shwp): you will snap at, snatch at him, Holladay lists as different - why?<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>ʕaqev: heel End of S section<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Èle èèna ka, Ama Lamatua peka dènge bhèni ne,<bt>After that, God spoke to the woman,</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">&lt;&lt;Èèna na, Ja'a pasusa tabha èu, ropa èu dènge babia; lod'o mora iisi, èu asa tabha j'èra. Masi ka sèmi èèna, d'ara èu d'èi taruu dhèu èmu èu, aa nèngu ka dhu ator èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;I will make your trouble/suffering/difficulty increase, when1 you are pregnant; and add to the suffering, when2 you give birth. Even that being the case, your insides will continue to want/desire your spouse, and he is the one who will manage you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mora iisi (2s) &lt; nara iisi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">mora iisi (2s) &lt; nara iisi (3s)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="harbah ʔarbeh: I will definitely make"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">harbah ʔarbeh: I will definitely make greater ʕitstsəvonech: your hardship, pain, distress<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>heronech: your pregnancy ʕetsev: pain, hardship<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>teldi (yalad): you will bear children tshuqatech (shuq): your urge, craving, impulse, also in 4:7 and SS 7:10 (4:7 suggests it could be an urge to dominate that will be frustrated, but SS 7:10 is sexual desire). UBS suggests it covers any kind of strong urge.<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>Exchange between MC &amp; JEG: [MC] "4:7 is an extended metaphor. I think this refers just to sexual desire, in spite of painful childbirth, as youʔve translated it." [JEG] "The relationship between the parts seems to be that even though pregnancy and childbirth will be more painful than they would have been, it will be worth it to you [and he will reciprocate? and he will be in a dominant position over you? be your leader?]" yimshal (qal): rule, govern, dominate, control; but also "repeat, be like," hif "compare with" (rare, not in Qal except here, if this is that verb). "Be like" never occurs in the qal unless this is the one instance. It is the stem behind mashal ʔproverb, analogyʔ, so it would fit one meaning of the passage. But the "control" meaning occurs 80 times in the qal.<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ka Ama Lamatua peka dènge mone ne,<bt>Then God spoke to the man saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">&lt;&lt;Èu madhutu boe lii paredha Ja'a, te ngaa èu nanene dhoka lii dhèu èmu èu di, ka èu mu'a hua aj'u dhu Ja'a kai èèna. Nèti èèna ka, èu abhu huku kahèi. Aa rai lèke huku kahèi. Nèti deo ne'e, toke d'ai èu madhe, hud'i èu kabèli rai, heka èu abhu nganga'a kèna. Dènge sab'a bia sèmi ne'e ka, èu heka mamuri kèna.<bt>&lt;&lt;You did not follow/obey My command, but you just listened to the voice of your spouse, and you ate the fruit of the tree which I had forbidden. Because of that, you will also be punished. From now, until you die, you must turn the soil (first stage of farming, represents the hardest work of the whole process), and only-then will you get food. With hard work like that, only-then will you (be able to) live.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsivitiach: I ordered you leʔmor: infinitive,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tsivitiach: I ordered you leʔmor: infinitive, to say<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʔarurah: passive participle, cursed. A curse will be placed on the ground, God will make something bad happen to the ground, and probably by saying so, God made it happen right then and there baʕavureach: on account of you<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʕitsavon: pain, hardship, distress [= v. 16]</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Masi ka èu sèle rupa-rupa hini èèna ka, te ngaa dhu muri mai dhodhoka dhudhu-sete di.<bt>Even if you plant all sorts of seeds, nevertheless what grows will be only various thorns-weeds (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qots: thorn bush dardar: whorl, a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">qots: thorn bush dardar: whorl, a kind of thistle, Centaurea pallescens or iberica, very thorny and prickly<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>tatsmiach: make plants grow ʕesev: broad term that includes weeds, grass, vegetables, cereals, grains, wild and cultivated both. Up to this time they had been eating the things God planted for them inside the park<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>[JEG] Syntacticians distinguish "benefactive" from "malefactive"; but in many languages the actual semantics is "applicative," affecting you in some way, good or bad. That's how SK take "fo you." But we put in "too" because some of the seed does actually come up.</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Hud'i èu èi kabhèsu haa ku, heka rai hia èu nganga'a kèna. Èu hud'i sab'a bia sèmi èèna ku, toke d'ai lod'o èu madhe. Èu ne, Ja'a paj'aj'i nèti rai. De ladhe èu madhe, èu j'aj'i hari rai.&gt;&gt;<bt>So you must just sweat, and only-then will the ground give you food. You must work hard like that until the time when you die. You here, I made you from the ground/soil. So when you die, you will become ground/soil again.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="laka = banting; 18: sèle ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">laka = banting; 18: sèle = tanam ; sete = kurang dikenal (fine thorns) onak ; dhudhu = duri ; dhudhu-sete = category of thorny plants</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zeʕat: sweat ʕad: up to the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">zeʕat: sweat ʕad: up to the time, during<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>shuvach: your return ʔadamah: soil<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>luqqkchta: you are one who has been taken ʕafar: dust, crumbled dry dirt<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Èle èèna ka, Adam pangare dhèu èmu na &lt;Hawa&gt; (dhu sasoa na &lt;dhu mamuri&gt;), te nèngu ka j'aj'i ina nèti dhèu dhu mamuri aa'i-aa'i.<bt>After that, Adam named his spouse 'Hawa' (which means 'that which lives'), cuz she is/became the mother of all people who live.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chawwah: &quot;Eve&quot; in Hebrew reminds people"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">chawwah: "Eve" in Hebrew reminds people of chay "alive"</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:20" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Ibrani, &lt;<span class="Italic">adam</span>&gt; sasoa na &lt;dhèu rai-haha&gt;.<bt>According to the Ibrani language, &lt;<span class="Italic">adam</span>&gt; means 'human'.</bt></note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00605c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Hèia Ama LAMATUA tao mèdha-papake nèti ka'uri badha, ka papake dua ra.<bt>Then the LORD made clothes from animal skins, and clothed the two of them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katnot: long shirt-like undergarments, like a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">katnot: long shirt-like undergarments, like a long t-shirt, but made out of animal hides ʕor: skin, hide<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>yalvishem: cause somebody to put on a garment, clothe somebody [no need "fo wear" SK] End of S section.<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua babège eele Adam dènge Hawa<bt>God evicts Adam and Hawa</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ka Ama LAMATUA peka, &lt;&lt;Limuri ne, dhèu re'a le, mia dhu be'a dènge mia dhu karehe, sèmi Èdhi kahèi. De mage dhoka, rèngu ra'a hua aj'u dhu èci hari na, dhu hia mamuri taa-taa.&gt;&gt;<bt>And the LORD said, &lt;&lt;Now, the people already know what is good, and what is bad; just like Us-inc. So may it not be that they eat the fruit from the other tree which gives eternal life.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Begins new Seder. vayyoʔmer: said (to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Begins new Seder. vayyoʔmer: said (to himself, in this case)<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>kʔachad mimmennu: like one of us viʕattah: so now, in the present situation, introducing a new thought<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>pen-yishlach: in order to keep him from putting out his hand yado: his hand<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>gam: in addition to the other ʕolam: long time, all the coming time, forever<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Èle èèna ka, Na babèga eele si nèti d'ara oka Eden èèna, ho lasi asa era leo, sèna ka ra mamuri dènge sab'e oka-tedhe. Lula dhèu j'aj'i nèti rai, de mamuri kahèi nèti rai.<bt>Then He evicted them from inside that garden of Eden, to go to a different place, so they could live by working the fields (doublet). Because people came into being from the ground/soil, so they also live from the ground/soil.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yshallechehu: he drove them out, sent"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yshallechehu: he drove them out, sent them away laʕavod<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>luqqach: was taken from</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Babège nare si, ka Lamatua paredha ana pajuu Na nèti sorga, dhu dènge èla,<bt>After evicting them, God2 commanded His servants from heaven, which had wings,</bt><note reference="3:24" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Ibrani, peka na, ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga sèra ètu ne'e, ngara ra &lt;<span class="Italic">kerubim</span>&gt;.<bt>According to the Ibrani language, it says these servants of the Lord from heaven are called, &lt;<span class="Italic">kerubim</span>&gt;.</bt></note>ho lasi j'aga oka èèna re ca bèka dhimu. Rèngu dènge samala dhu heo ha'a-ha'a, dhu seru la'e-mai. Lamatua pua si bèdho eele j'ara la'e sa d'ara, te Nèngu d'èi boe dhèu puu rare hua aj'u dhu hia ra mamuri taa-taa èèna.<bt>to go guard that garden on the eastern side. They were with sword [not marked for number] which glittered/flashed, and slashed going-coming. God2 ordered them to close off the path/way going inside, cuz He didn't want people to pick the fruit of that tree which gives eternal life.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="manèro = lestari; 24: heo robhe-robhe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">manèro = lestari; 24: heo robhe-robhe = glow ; kadila = glitter ; heo ha'a-ha'a = glitter, flash back-and-forth (menyala tajam)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhu papare asa haa, asa dhimu."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">dhu papare asa haa, asa dhimu. ; seru la'e-mai, aa kadila kahèi.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ygaresh: banish, drive out yashken: settle"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ygaresh: banish, drive out yashken: settle somebody in a place, make them live there<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>miqqedem: in front = on the east side hakkruvim: fierce living beings with wings, the body of a lion or a bull, and the face of a man. In Ezekiel they are spoken of only as "living beings" in Chapter 1 and "cherubim" in Chapter 10. They guard holy places. In the Bible they are never classified as angels (messengers who serve God and do his bidding), because that is not their job, though they seem to be a similar kind of being.<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>Exchange between MC &amp; JEG: [MC] Isnʔt Ezekiel in the Bible? (note is confusing); [JEG] Most mentions of them are as artistic objects; only here and in Ezekiel 1 and 10 are they referred to in their living form. lahat hacherev: flaming blade of a sword (dagger or short sword)<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>hammit happechet: ? turning every which way lishmor: to guard [=2:15]<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kaen dènge Habel<bt>Kaen and Habel</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="4" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia Adam j'unu dènge dhèu èmu na, Hawa. Ka bhèni ne dènge babia. Hèia nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu. Ka na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a abhu le ana mone ca dhèu, lula Ama LAMATUA soru nare le ja'a.&gt;&gt; Ka na pangare ana ne, <span class="Italic">Kaen</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;abhu&gt;).<bt>One time, Adam slept with his spouse, Hawa. And the woman got pregnant. Then she gave birth to a son. And she spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;I have gotten a son, because the LORD God has helped me.&gt;&gt; And she named the child, <span class="Italic">Kaen</span> (which means &lt;gotten&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yadaʕ: knew, a euphemism for sex"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yadaʕ: knew, a euphemism for sex tahar (harah): she got pregnant<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>teled (yalad): she had a baby qayn, qaniti (qanah): "Cain" sounds like "get" in Hebrew. Acquire, buy<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʔet: with the help of, together with, in the presence of (not ʔet accusative)</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Hèia Hawa nara iisi hari ana mone èci. Ka na pangare ne <span class="Italic">Habel</span>.<bt>Then Hawa gave birth to another son. And she named him <span class="Italic">Habel</span>.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="soru nare = sambut, tolong"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">soru nare = sambut, tolong</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dua ra kapai ka, Habel j'aj'i dhèu madhenge badha. Aa a'a na Kaen, sab'a oka-tedhe.<bt>When the two of them grew up, Habel become a person who guarded/watched animals. And his elder-sibling Kaen, worked fields (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatosef (yasaf): she went on to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vatosef (yasaf): she went on to do, continued doing, did it again laledet: to have a child<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>achiv: his brother roʕeh: shepherd<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>tsoʔn: small livestock (sheep and goats) ʕoved ʔədamah (ʕavad): cultivator, tiller of the soil, dirt farmer<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Ca lod'o, Kaen nèti isi rai na cahag'e, ka hia LAMATUA.<bt>One day/time, Kaen brought some of his produce of the land/ground, and gave it to the LORD.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qets: limit, boundary, miqqets yamim some"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">qets: limit, boundary, miqqets yamim some time later, at the end of a period yaveʔ (boʔ hif.): cause to come, bring in<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>pəriy: some of the fruit. May be more generic. minchah: present, gift to show respect; sacrifice of homage or allegiance<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Habel nèti ana-ana uuru kahib'i-kalèbho na. Na roro kahib'i-kalèbho se, ka nèti sisi dhu be'a hia Lamatua. D'ara Ama Lamatua karej'e ropa ladhe nèdhi korban nèti Habel ne.<bt>Habel brought the first offspring of his goat-sheep. He slaughtered those goat-sheep, and brought the best meat to God2. God's insides were happy/pleased when [He] saw the sacrifice (loan) of Habel.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bchorot: firstborn mehelvehen (chelev): fat in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bchorot: firstborn mehelvehen (chelev): fat in the body, choicest part of the meat for offering<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yishaʕ (shaʕah): look with favor. In Gen 4:4-5, it means to look at with approval, to approve of.</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Te ngaa Na d'èi boe korban unu Kaen. Hèia Kaen nasa bia, ka rèhu na mare boe.<bt>But He didn't like the sacrifice owned by Kaen. So Kaen became furious, and his face was not smiling. [CHECK: UNS change from /rèhu na bai/ "face swollen" &gt; /rèhu na mera boe/ "face was not flat/even"]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="korban ;; 5: bai = bengkak"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">korban ;; 5: bai = bengkak (but collocate with anger when describing face) ; mare boe = tidak senyum (trivial); mera = geram (boe) = guilty, mara banyak</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yichar (charah apocopated): became angry, anger"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yichar (charah apocopated): became angry, anger broke out in Cain yipplu (nafal fall): face fell, he was downcast.<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ka LAMATUA lii dènge Kaen, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Kaen! Nga tao ka èu nasa sèmi èèna, ka rèhu èu mare boe?<bt>And the LORD spoke to Kaen, saying, &lt;&lt;Kaen! Why are you so angry like that, and your face is not smiling?</bt><v n="7" />Ladhe tatao èu be'a, na Ja'a sèmi èu dènge hua iia. De mu pangee uuru ku! Ladhe èu tao bhelu, na bhabhelu èèna na'e hari èu, sama sèmi meo neo pacèli maraho. De sèmi èu neo tao bhabhelu, be'a risi core eele ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>If your deeds/behaviour/character is good, I will receive/accept you very well. So think first! If you do evil, that evil will eat/consume you in return, just like a cat which is about to pounce on a mouse/rat. So if you are about to do evil, it would be better to get rid of it!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèle = telan ; pacèli ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">dhèle = telan ; pacèli = pounce</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔim-tetiv (ytv hif): if you behave"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔim-tetiv (ytv hif): if you behave well, make things go well sʔet: exaltation, raising oneself up; lift up, smile, opposite of hang face. Can mean receiving the sacrifice, or feeling good about it<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>petach: entrance, doorway, opening of a tent, a city hattaʔt: sin (miss a goal, displeasing, offend, blameworthy or guilty, needs confessing and clearing up)<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>rovets (rvts pt): lie down with chest to the ground like an animal. Some commentators take this as the name of a demon, but others take it as a metaphor teshuqato: craving, impulse (to take over, same word as in 3:16)<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>timshal-bo: are to rule, govern, gain dominion over it, get control</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00617c.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Kaen neo pamadhe Habel<bt>Kaen is about to kill Habel</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ca tèka, Kaen gale Habel, na peka na, &lt;&lt;Mai lati ngad'o oka, we.&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, Kaen invited Habel, saying, &lt;&lt;Let's go visit the field, we.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="4:8" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Abhu pèri-pèri sasuri dhu uru sa, dhu pake lii padhai lii Kaen na, te ngaa lii sèra abhu boe ètu d'ara sasuri lii Ibrani uru na.<bt>There are several old writings which use Kaen's words, but these words are not in the oldest Ibrani writings.</bt></note>Ropa dua ra d'ai d'ara oka, Kaen kalabhe pamadhe ari na.<bt>When the two of them arrived in the field, Kaen beat his younger-sibling to death.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The main Hebrew manuscripts donʔt have"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">The main Hebrew manuscripts donʔt have the words Cain used, but the Aramaic ones do. bihyotam (hyh inf 3pl m obj): when they were there<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>yaqam: stood up; he went and did something, he up and killed him yahargehu: he killed him, murdered (also used of executions and war, slaughtering an animal -- deliberate)<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ka LAMATUA karèi Kaen, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Kaen! Ari mu ka mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>And the LORD asked Kaen, saying, &lt;&lt;Where is your younger-sibling?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Kaen dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ke'a boe na ètu mia! Èu ngee na, ja'a dhèu kèpe haga na, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>So Kaen responded, saying, &lt;&lt;I don't know where he is! Do You think that I am the person who holds his leg/foot, huh?&gt;&gt; (Idiom: = hang around all the time and watch him)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔey: where? hashomer: the one who"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔey: where? hashomer: the one who looks after him, his protector, guard, custodian<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ka Lamatua b'ala, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka èu bhelu sèmi èèna? Baku pangee na, èu pahuni more le raa ari èu ètu d'ara rai, te Ja'a dhu kèdhi aa'i-aa'i le!<bt>And the Lord replied, &lt;&lt;Why are you evil like that? Don't think that you can hide away your younger-sibling's blood from in the ground, cuz I am the one who has seen everything!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meh ʕasita: what have you done?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">meh ʕasita: what have you done? assumes it was bad. In Pidgin it needs the "hah" [actually nasalized] to make it an accusation; with just the verb it would be an information question, which is not what God needs. dmey: (plural) blood shed in violence, for which a relative (or in this case, God) is supposed to take vengeance<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>tsoʕaqim (participle, plural agreeing with "blood"): raise a cry, wail, call for help (mostly to God). BDB This root means to call out for help under great distress or to utter an exclamation in great excitement. ʔelay: toward me<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>Consultant exchange: [MC] was he/it calling for help or for vengeance? ; [JEG] The Hebrew is specifically a call for help. So calling for vengeance would be reading something into it that's weakly founded, though if it were me I'd probably call for vengeance. One could argue that the only way God could help Abel now is by avenging him -- still, that doesn't sound like Abel.</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />De lii dhoo lèke le mi dedha èu. Lod'o èu pamadhe ari èu, rai sakid'o nare raa na. De limuri ne, rai bisa heka nèti mamuri mi èu.<bt>So a curse is upon you. When you killed your younger-sibling, the ground sucked up/absorbed his blood. So now, the ground/soil can no longer bring life to you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="weʕattah: introducing a new thought, and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">weʕattah: introducing a new thought, and now ʔarur: cursed so that you canʔt work the soil, or cursed even more than the soil was (in 3:17)<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>min-haʔadamah: away from the ground, in a different way than the ground was cursed? more than the ground was cursed? patstah (fem): it has opened wide<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>piyah (peh): mouth, metaphor laqachat: to receive, accept<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>miyyadecha: from your hand</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />De ladhe èu sab'a oka-tedhe, rai ne hia heka èu ngaa-ngaa. Nèti deo ne'e, èu lu'u sa haa-sa dhimu, sèmi dhèu dhu dènge boe era paleo-palu'u.&gt;&gt;<bt>So, when you work the fields (doublet), the ground will no longer give you anything. From now on, you will hide to the west and to the east, like a person who has no place of residence (doublet).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhènu = tutup dgn pasir, tana;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">dhènu = tutup dgn pasir, tana; 11: sakido = isap ; camuci = suck isap maen-maen; 12: lu'u = sembunyi</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taʕavod: you are going to try"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">taʕavod: you are going to try to work the ground tosef (yasaf): it (the ground) will not go on doing<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>kochah: strength (of a field = its yield) naʕ: roaming around withut shelter or home, homeless<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>nod: swaying, being aimless, homeless</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Te ngaa Kaen b'ala LAMATUA, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Haii! Ama Lamatua, ee! Lamatua dhoo ja'a bia titu kèna, de ja'a pasae mèke boe nga.<bt>But Kaen replied to the LORD, saying, &lt;&lt;Haii! God, ee! God2 has cursed me very heavily, so I can no longer bear it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕavoni: my activity that is crooked"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕavoni: my activity that is crooked or wrong, offence, sin, also guilt or punishment. Here it's the punishment he is complaining about; he never addresses the guilt of what he did. nsoʔ (nsʔ inf): more than I can be made to lift, more than I can show my face to<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Lula Lamatua bège eele ja'a nèti era ne'e, ja'a kaj'èu nèti Ama Lamatua. Ja'a kako lole-laa asa mia-mia. De ladhe paraga dènge dhèu, èèna na ra pamadhe ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because God2 has evicted me from this place, I am/will be far from God. I will wander (without work) everywhere. So when I meet someone, they will kill me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kako lole-laa = wander, sonde ada"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">kako lole-laa = wander, sonde ada pekerjaan, sonde ada tujuan, tapaleuk</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hen: demonstrative interjection and conjunction gerashta:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hen: demonstrative interjection and conjunction gerashta: drive out, banish<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʔoti: me meʕal: from over, from upon, down from<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>mippaneycha: from your presence ʔessater: I will hide<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>motsʔi (mtsʔ partcpl): who happens to meet me by chance</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Te ngaa LAMATUA dhaa na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o sèmi èèna! Dhèu cee dhu pamadhe èu, èèna na Ja'a huku ne, babia na pidhu hari risi nèti èu.&gt;&gt; Hèia LAMATUA tao tadha mi Kaen, sèna ka dhèu re'a ho baku pamadhe ne.<bt>But the LORD responded, &lt;&lt;It won't be like that! Whoever kills you, I will then punish him, seven times more heavily than you.&gt;&gt; Then the LORD place a sign on Kaen, so that people would know not to kill him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lachen: therefore, indeed horeg (partcpl): killing|i(15)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">lachen: therefore, indeed horeg (partcpl): killing<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>shivʔatayim: sevenfold yuqqam (naqam): be avenged (stative passive)<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>yasem (sym): put in a place, make be there ʔot: sign, like a mark of kapu<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>lbilti: non-existence, so that nobody would hakot-oto (nkh inf.): make him be hit, beat, kill<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Hèia Kaen tèke eele dènge era èèna. La'e pakaj'èu nèti LAMATUA, asa era èci, ètu bèka dhimu oka Eden. Era ne'e, ngara na <span class="Italic">Nod</span> dhu sasoa na, &lt;lole-laa&gt;. Ka na pea ètu era èèna.<bt>Then Kaen left that place. He went far from the LORD, to a place on the eastern side of the garden Eden. This place was named <span class="Italic">Nod</span> which means, &lt;wander&gt; (doublet). And he stayed in that place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aree = hukum (kuno) ; dèta"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">aree = hukum (kuno) ; dèta = tattoo; 16: oro-rai = tapaleuk ; kako leli = jalan sembarangan ; kako j'ara ponai = tapaleuk (kurang dikenal) ; pa'oro</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyetseʔ: go out, go forth nod:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayyetseʔ: go out, go forth nod: become aimless, homeless<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>qidmat-ʕeden: east of Eden</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-èpu Kaen<bt>The descendants of Kaen</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Hèia Kaen leo-èmu, ka dhèu èmu na dènge babia. Ka nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu, dhu pangare na Henok. Hèia Kaen patitu rae cue, ngara na Henok, madhutu ngara ana na.<bt>Then Kaen married, and his spouse became pregnant. And she gave birth to a son, whom they named Henok. Then Kaen founded a village [following CEV and TH], named Henok, following the name of his child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatahar: get pregnant, conceive a baby"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vatahar: get pregnant, conceive a baby vateled (yld): bear a child<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>boneh: build ʕiyr: city = town with walls<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>vayyiqraʔ hashem: called its name, named it</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ka Henok matana Irad. Hèia Irad matana Mehuyael. Mehuyael matana Metusael. Aa ana Metusael, Lamek.<bt>And Henok had a child Irad. Then Irad had a child Mehuyael. Mehuyael had a child Metusael. And the child of Metusael, was Lamek.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiwwaled: be born to, either directly"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiwwaled: be born to, either directly as father or skipping generations as ancestor</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00613c.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Dhèu èmu Lamek, dhèu dua. Èci ngara na Ada, aa ca dhèu hari, ngara na Sila.<bt>The spouses of Lamek, were two. One was named Ada, and the other was named Sila.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyiqqach-lo (lqh): took for himself (as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayyiqqach-lo (lqh): took for himself (as wives), married nashim (ʔisshah): women<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ana Ada, ngara na Yabal. Ana-èpu na, j'aj'i dhèu piara badha. Mamuri ra ètu boe ca era, aa ra pea dhoka ètu d'ara paleo di.<bt>The child of Ada, was named Yabal. His descendants became people who raise animals. They did not live in one place, and they lived only in tents/shelters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔohel: tent miqneh: livestock|i(20) |r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔohel: tent miqneh: livestock<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ari Yabal, ngara na Yubal. Ana-èpu Yubal, j'aj'i dhèu gai sasadhu, dènge tiu sakino.<bt>Yabal's younger-sibling was named Yubal. the descendants of Yubal became people who played sasando (trad. stringed instrument), and blew the flute.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sasadhu = sasando ; sakino ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">sasadhu = sasando ; sakino = suling ; tèbhe = blow conch ; baba = gong ; dere = tambur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tofes: handle, have to do with,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tofes: handle, have to do with, deal with kinor: lyre, a stringed instrument with a sounding-board or sound box<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ʕugav: vertical flute</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="Hk-lb\Hk00188c.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Mèdha musiik<bt>Musical things</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Dhèu èmu Lamek èci hari, Sila, nara iisi Tubal Kaen. Ana-èpu na j'aj'i tuka bèsi, ka ra tuku mèdha ae-ae tao nèti bèsi, dènge tabaga. Ana hèni Tubal Kaen, ngara na Na'ama.<bt>Lamek's other spouse, Sila, gave birth to Tubal Kaen. His descendants became ironsmiths, and they pounded many things made from iron and bronze (loan). Tubal Kaen's daughter was named Na'ama.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tabaga ; besi ; tuka besi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">tabaga ; besi ; tuka besi</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lotesh: sharpening, working as a smith"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">lotesh: sharpening, working as a smith or metalworker choresh: craftsman, plower, engraver, cutter<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>nchoshet: copper, bronze (= copper + tin) barzel: iron<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ca tèka, Lamek padedha iisi na ètu madha dhèu èmu dua ra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mi nanene, ee! Deo na, ana mone ngèru èci neo game ja'a. Te ngaa ja'a dhadhedhe ne, toke madhe.<bt>One time, Lamek elevated himself (proudly) in front of his two spouses, saying, &lt;&lt;Listen up, ee! Earlier, a young man wanted to beat me up. But I beat2 him to death.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haʔəzennah (ʔzn hif): lissen to someting"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">haʔəzennah (ʔzn hif): lissen to someting ʔimrati: my word, opinion (poetic)<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>haragti: I killed someone, I would kill anyone who wounded me lfitsʕi: to my wounding; inflict bruises, crush<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>chabburati: my wounding, striping, even a boy who bruised me</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Dhèu dhu pamadhe Kaen, abhu huku pidhu hari. Te ngaa cee ka dhu neo b'ala ho pamadhe ja'a, abhu huku pidhu nguru pidhu hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>The person who kills Kaen will get punished seven times. But whoever wants revenge to kill me, will get punished 77 times.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shivʕatayim: sevenfold, seven times as much"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shivʕatayim: sevenfold, seven times as much (Sounds like good old Middle East invective, like Saddam Hussein in the first gulf war, "mother of all battles.") yuqqam (nqm qal passive): be avenged, stative passive = v. 15<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>shivʕim vshivʕah: 77 times</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana Adam dhu leo, ngara na Set<bt>Adam's other child, named Set</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ka Hawa nara iisi hari ana mone ca dhèu. Hèia ra pangare ne, <span class="Italic">Set</span> (dhu sasoa na, &lt;hia&gt;), lula aku Hawa na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua hia ja'a ana ne, sèna ka gati madha Habel, dhu Kaen pamadhe ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Hawa gave birth to another son. Then they named him <span class="Italic">Set</span> (which means &lt;give&gt;), because Hawa said, &lt;&lt;God gave me this child, to replace Habel, whom Kaen killed.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕod: again shet: Seth|i(25) (25) |rshat-li:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕod: again shet: Seth<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>shat-li: put for me, "give, establish" sounds like "Seth" in Hebrew zeraʕ: seed, offspring, descendants<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>ʔacher: another one in a series, following one, next tachat: instead of, for the sake of<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Pe d'ai nèbhu ku, Set abhu ana mone ca dhèu, dhu pangare na Enos.<bt>Eventually Set got a son, whom they named Enos.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Tèu èèna, dhèu mulai manèngi-mangaj'i mi Ama LAMATUA.<bt>At that time, people began to worship the LORD God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yullad: passive, was born to Seth"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yullad: passive, was born to Seth az: then<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>huchal (chll hof): was begun liqraʔ: invoke, appeal to for help<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>bshem: name, reputation, renown End of P section.<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>“worship the name of the Lord”: HCE = “Dat was da time wen da peopo firs start fo aks Yahweh fo help um cuz dey know wat kine God him.” [JEG] We worked this out for the New Testament, and it works even better than "name" in many passages in the Old. The exceptions are things like "taking the Lord's name in vain", which is "use my name an ack like dat give you da right fo do wase time kine stuff", and places where Yahweh wants his people to know what his name is.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-èpu Adam toke Noh<bt>Descendants (&lt;child-grandchild) of Adam until Noh</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="5" />
      <v n="1-2" />Lod'o Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i dhèu rai-haha, Na tao si sama sèmi rupa Nèngu. Na paj'aj'i si, dhèu mone dènge dhèu bhèni. Ka Na pangare si &lt;dhèu rai-haha&gt;, aa Na hia si berkat.<bt>When God made/created humans (&lt;people of the earth), He made them like His shape/characteristic/form/face. He created them, male and female. And He called them &lt;human&gt;, and He gave them *blessing (~peace &amp; prosperity/well-being).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dhèu dhu uru, ngara na Adam. Ana-èpu Adam, nuka sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>The first person was named Adam. The descendants of Adam were like this:</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Begins new Seder. Sefer: writing, book;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Begins new Seder. Sefer: writing, book; list, record<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>tolədot: life and times ʔadam: Adam the individual, but the same word means "mankind"<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>bəroʔ (inf): creation (used of God) bidmut (dmh ʔbe likeʔ, dmut ʔpattern, form, shapeʔ): as something like, a form or shape, an image<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>zakhar: male (opposite to female) nqevah: female<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>vayvarek otam: he bestowed power for success, prosperity, fertility. Also declared them endowed with power for success or prosperity or fertility. One person can express a wish that another will have the power for the same, and can declare that God is the origin of that power for success or prosperity or fertility in people hibarʔam (brʔ nif inf): the day of his creating them<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="3" />Lod'o Adam d'ai 130 (ca ngasu tèlu nguru) tèu, na matana ana mone ca dhèu, dhu rèhu na nare Adam. Ka pangare na, <span class="Italic">Set.</span><bt>When Adam reached 130 years, he begat a son. His face/shape/likeness was like his father. And he named him <span class="Italic">Set.</span></bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yoled (yld hif narrl): he caused"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yoled (yld hif narrl): he caused him to be born ktsalmo (tselem): as the spitting image of him<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ka Adam mamuri hari d'ai 800 (aru ngasu) tèu, hèia na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>And Adam lived 800 more years, and then he got/had more/other sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="holiydo (yld hif): he caused him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">holiydo (yld hif): he caused him to be born</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Umur Adam 930 (ceo ngasu tèlu nguru) tèu, heka madhe kèna.<bt>Adam's age was 930 years, only.then did he die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="6" />Lod'o Set d'ai 105 (ca ngasu lèmi) tèu, na abhu ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Enos.<bt>When Set reached 105 years, he got/had a son, named Enos.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yoled (yld hif narr): caused to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yoled (yld hif narr): caused to be born</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ka Set mamuri hari d'ai 807 (aru ngasu pidhu) tèu, na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>And Set lived another 807 years, and got/had other sons and daughters.</bt><v n="8" />Umur Set 912 (ceo ngasu canguru dua) tèu, heka madhe kèna.<bt>Set's age was 912 years, only.then did he die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="9" />Lod'o Enos mamuri d'ai 90 (ceo nguru) tèu, na matana ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Kenan.<bt>When Enos had lived reaching 90 years, he begat a son, named Kenan.</bt><v n="10" />Ka Enos mamuri hari d'ai 815 (aru ngasu canguru lèmi) tèu, na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>And Enos lived another 815 years, and got/had other sons and daughters.</bt><v n="11" />Umur Enos 905 (ceo ngasu lèmi) tèu, heka madhe kèna.<bt>Enos' age was 905 years, only.then did he die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="12" />Lod'o Kenan d'ai 70 (pidhu nguru) tèu, na matana ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Mahalalel.<bt>When Kenan reached 70 years, he begat a son, named Mahalalel.</bt><v n="13" />Ka Kenan mamuri hari d'ai 840 (aru ngasu èpa nguru) tèu, ka na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>And Kenan lived another 840 years, and he got/had other sons and daughters.</bt><v n="14" />Umur Kenan 910 (ceo ngasu canguru) tèu, heka madhe kèna.<bt>Kenan's age was 910 years, only.then did he die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="15" />Lod'o Mahalalel d'ai 65 (èna nguru lèmi) tèu, na abhu ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Yared.<bt>When Mahalalel reached 65 years, he got/had a son named Yared.</bt><v n="16" />Ka Mahalalel mamuri hari d'ai 830 (aru ngasu tèlu nguru) tèu, na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>And Mahalalel lived another 830 years, and got/had other sons and daughters.</bt><v n="17" />Umur Mahalalel 895 (aru ngasu ceo nguru lèmi) tèu, heka na madhe kèna.<bt>Mahalalel's age was 895 years, only.then did he die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="18" />Lod'o Yared d'ai 162 (cangasu èna nguru dua) tèu, na abhu ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Henok.<bt>When Yared reached 162 years, he got/had a son named Henok.</bt><v n="19" />Ka Yared mamuri d'ai 800 (aru ngasu) tèu, na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>Then Yared lived another 800 years, and got/had other sons and daughters.</bt><v n="20" />Umur Yared 962 (ceo ngasu èna nguru dua) tèu, heka madhe kèna.<bt>Yared's age was 962 years, only.then did he die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="21" />Ropa Henok mamuri d'ai 65 (èna nguru lèmi) tèu, na matana ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Metusalak.<bt>When Henok had lived 65 years, he begat a son, named Metusalak.</bt><v n="22" />Ele èèna, Henok mamuri d'ara èci dènge Ama Lamatua d'ai 300 (tèlu ngasu) tèu. Ka na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>After that, Henok lived one inside (idiom=best friend, know intimately) with God for 300 years. And he got/had other sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayithalek (hitp): he walked back and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayithalek (hitp): he walked back and forth, around, walk constantly</Message></Annotation><v n="23-24" />Na mamuri d'ara èci dènge Ama Lamatua. Hèia lod'o na d'ai 365 (tèlu ngasu èna nguru lèmi) tèu, ka na ele, lula Ama Lamatua paca'e ne sa dedha.<bt>He lived one inside with God. Then when he reached 365 years, he disappeared, because God elevated him up above/heaven.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeynennu: there was no more of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔeynennu: there was no more of him End of P section.<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="25" />Lod'o Metusalak d'ai 187 (cangasu aru nguru pidhu) tèu, na matana ana mone èci, ngara na Lamek.<bt>When Metusalak reached 187 years, he begat a son, named Lamek.</bt><v n="26" />Èle èèna ka, Metusalak mamuri hari d'ai 782 (pidhu ngasu aru nguru dua) tèu, ka na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>After that, Metusalak lived another 782 years, and he got/had other sons and daughters.</bt><v n="27" />Umur Metusalak 969 (ceo ngasu èna nguru ceo) tèu, heka madhe kèna.<bt>Metusalak's age was 969 years, only then did he die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="28" />Lod'o Lamek mamuri d'ai 182 (ca ngasu aru nguru dua) tèu, na matana ana mone ca dhèu.<bt>When Lamek lived reaching 182 years, he begat a son.</bt><v n="29" />Lamek pangare ne <span class="Italic">Noh</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;pakarej'e d'ara&gt;), lula na peka na, &lt;&lt;Ana ne, èèna na pakarej'e d'ara èdhi nèti sasab'a dhu bia, ètu rai dhu Ama Lamatua dhoo le.&gt;&gt;<bt>Lamek named him <span class="Italic">Noh</span> (which means &lt;comfort/please insides&gt;), because he said, &lt;&lt;This child, will comfort/please our-inc inside from our heavy work, on the land which God has cursed.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ynakhmenu (nkhm piel): reassure, comfort mimaʕsenu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ynakhmenu (nkhm piel): reassure, comfort mimaʕsenu (maʕseh): what happens to someone, work activity<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>ʕitsvon: distress, hardship, pain ʔerərah (ʔrr piel): inflicted with a curse<span class="Italic">(29)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Ka Lamek mamuri taruu d'ai 595 (lèmi ngasu ceo nguru lèmi) tèu, aa na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>And Lamek lived on for another 595 years, and he got/had other sons and daughters.</bt><v n="31" />Umur Lamek 777 (pidhu ngasu pidhu nguru pidhu) tèu, heka na madhe kèna.<bt>Lamek's age was 777 years, only.then did he die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakarej'e dara = kasi hibur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pakarej'e dara = kasi hibur</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Lod'o Noh mamuri d'ai 500 (lèmi ngasu) tèu, na matana ana mone dhèu tèlu, Sem, Yafet dènge Ham.<bt>When Noh lived reaching 500 years, he begat three sons, Sem, Yafet and Ham.</bt><note reference="5:32" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ham èèna, ana limuri. Ladhe ètu <span class="Italic">Lii Lolo Uru</span> 9:24-25.<bt>That Ham was the youngest child. See <span class="Italic">Story of the Beginning</span>. 9:24-25.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Bhabhelu-katub'a dhèu rai-haha<bt>The evil (doublet) of humans</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="6" />
      <v n="1" />Taa èèna, dhèu rai-haha, asa bèba-kacanga. Ka ra papala-palème rai-haha. Dhèu se matana kahèi ana-ana bhèni.<bt>At that time (broad), humans kept increasing (in number). And they spread/scattered all over the earth. These people also begat (various) daughters.</bt><v n="2" />Ana-ana mone nèti Lamatua<note reference="6:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii &lt;ana-ana mone nèti Lamatua&gt; sèra, mèu iia boe. Abhu dhèu d'èlu-mèu cahag'e dhu peka, rèngu sèra, ana-ana dhèu aae. Cahag'e hari peka, rèngu sèra, kapua nèti dhèu rai-haha boe. Cahag'e hari dhu ngee, na, rèngu sèra ana pajuu Ama Lamatua nèti sorga. Te ngaa abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu re'a mèu.</note>ladhe rèdhi ana bhèni nèti dhèu rai-haha se, bhèni iia hua. Ka lasi todhe rare ana bhèni mia dhu ra d'èi.<v n="3" />Ka LAMATUA peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a roca le dènge tatao dhèu dhu lèke-lèke boe se. Roh Ja'a dhu pamamuri rèngu sa, d'èi heka hia ra mamuri manèro.<bt>Sons of the Lord saw the daughters of humans, [that they were] very female.beautiful. And they went and married the girls/daughters whom they liked.</bt><note reference="6:3" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasoa lii Ibrani ètu ne'e mèu iia boe.<bt>The meaning of the Ibrani language here is not clear.</bt></note>Hud'i rèngu madhe ku. De èèna na, mamuri rèngu se dhoka d'ai 120 (ca ngasu dua nguru) tèu di.&gt;&gt;</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Taa èèna, dènge taa-tebho dhu limuri nèti èèna hari, abhu le dhèu raksasa ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>At that time (broad), and the times/ages following that as well, there were giant people (loan) on this earth.</bt><note reference="6:4" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Ibrani peka na &lt;dhèu Nefil sèra&gt;. Te ngaa sasoa na mèu iia boe.<bt>The Ibrani language says &lt;people of Nefil&gt;. But the meaning is not clear.</bt></note>Ropa ana mone nèti Lamatua leo rare ana bhèni dhèu rai-haha se, ka rara iisi dhèu kapai, nuka: kapala musu, dhèu re'a madhutu lii lolo uru-uru sèra.<bt>When the sons of the Lord married the (aforementioned) daughters of humans, [they] gave birth to great people, that is: war heads/champions whom people know according to the stories of old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu palaka = nakal, ; kapala"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">dhèu palaka = nakal, ; kapala musu = kepala perang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nfilim: miscarriage [nefel]? giants produced by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nfilim: miscarriage [nefel]? giants produced by miscarriages? physically powerful men? giants? freaks? consultant exchange: [MC] That sounds a bit far-fetched to me! ; [JEG] Holladay again: Exo 21:22 possibly ʔmiscarriageʔ. Here, ʔgiantsʔ produced by miscarriage or thrown out of heaven (Nephilim comes from NPL ʔfallʔ); gigantic early population of Palestine Num 13, of mythological origin Gen 6:4, see commentaries. UBS: The fact that the term nefilim was known and used in Mosesʔ time does not necessarily mean that these kinds of men survived the flood. It can mean that just the name and the concept survived. There is no doubt that Middle Eastern mythology knew about giants, and that belief in the existence of such men was common at the time of the writing of Genesis. There have been many guesses made to explain the history of the word Nephilim, but none has any real likelihood of being true. Those who understand the sons of God in verse 2 as human beings and not supernatural beings, reject any reference to the Nephilim as offspring of human and heavenly unions, and so the Nephilim are taken to be powerful and violent men who existed along with those men who carried the title of "sons of God.ʔʔ Martin Luther for instance interpreted the Nephilim not as giants but as tyrants who fell upon the people and treated them violently.<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>gibboriym: strong, mighty ones meʕolam: from antiquity<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ʔanshey hashem: men of renown, famous men, big names End of P section<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Taa èèna, LAMATUA ladhe nèdhi bhabhelu-katub'a dhèu rai-haha dhu seli-kolane. D'ara rèngu pangee dhoka bhabhelu di.<bt>At that time (broad), the LORD saw the evil (doublet) of humans was excessive/past the bounds. Their insides thought only about evil.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rabah: was getting to be more"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">rabah: was getting to be more and more raʕat: evil, harm to somebody, evil intent, perverseness, trouble, crime<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>yetser: thought, impulse, tendency machshəvot: thought, idea, intention, plan, design<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>raq only</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ka LAMATUA manyasa, lula Na paj'aj'i le rèngu se ho pea ètu rai-haha ne. Tatao rèngu ne'e ka dhu papèd'a d'ara Lamatua.<bt>And the LORD felt.regret, cause/that He had created them to live on the earth. These deeds of theirs were what pained the insides of the Lord.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yinachem (nchm): regretted, allowed himself to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yinachem (nchm): regretted, allowed himself to be sorry yitʕatstsev (ʕtsv hitp impf): felt outraged, grieved; grieved himself<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Nèti èèna ka, Na peka na, &lt;&lt;Dènge tatao rèngu sèmi èèna na, Ja'a huku pamadhe dhèu rai-haha aa'i-aa'i dhu paj'aj'i kore si le. Manu-bhui dènge badha leo sèra, Ja'a palaho aa'i si kahèi. Te Ja'a manyasa, nèti Ja'a ka paj'aj'i si.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because of that, He said, &lt;&lt;With their deeds like that, I will punish them to death all the humans that I have created. The birds and other animals, I will also destroy all of them. Cause I feel.regret that I created them.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔemcheh: I will wipe out baraʔtiy:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔemcheh: I will wipe out baraʔtiy: I created<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>remes: creeping animals nichamti (nchm nif): I regret having made them<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Te ngaa Noh di dhu pakarej'e d'ara LAMATUA.<bt>But, Noh alone pleased the LORD's insides.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chen: agreeableness, approval; find pleasure, satisfaction"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">chen: agreeableness, approval; find pleasure, satisfaction in someone else's eyes End of P section<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii lolo Noh<bt>The story of Noh</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9-10" />Lii lolo Noh sèmi ne'e ka: Ana mone na, dhèu tèlu, nuka Sem, Yafet dènge Ham. Noh mamuri dènge mola, koe-kapengo boe. Taa èèna, nèngu di dhu mamuri mola. D'ara na dhodhoka ètu Ama Lamatua.<bt>The story of Noh is like this: He had three sons, that is Sem, Yefet and Ham. Noh lived straight/right/pure, without bent/deceit. At that time, only he lived straight/right. His insides were exclusive at/to God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="koe-kapengo = babengko (benda dan sifat)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">koe-kapengo = babengko (benda dan sifat) Lawan = mola</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Begins new Seder. toldot: genealogy plus,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Begins new Seder. toldot: genealogy plus, something like "the life and times of Noah"<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>tsadiq: something examined and found to be in order, right, innocent, guiltless, morally upright, righteous, godly tamim: whole, entire, intact, unobjectionable, blameless<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>dorotav: all his adult contemporaries, a time with its noteworthy events &amp; people hithhalek-noach: walk back and forth, walk around, walk constantly (with God) as in 5:22<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>yoled (hif): he had three boys</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11-12" />Te ngaa dhèu leo se, Ama Lamatua ladhe ra bhelu aa'i mèu-mèu. Ètu mia-mia èèna ka, j'ara mamuri dhèu se ele iie aa'i. Ama Lamatua nèdhi dhodhoka bhabhelu di, ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>But those other people, God saw they were thoroughly evil. Everywhere, the way of life of those people was completely messed up (broken). God saw only evil on the earth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tishshachet (shcht nif): became corrupt, spoiled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tishshachet (shcht nif): became corrupt, spoiled timmaleʔ (mlʔ nif): was full, was filled<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>chamas: violence, wrong, violent treatment hinneh: with reference to that time<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>nishchatah ki hishchit (shcht nif, hif): it became corrupt, spoiled because its ways have become corrupt, because they made their ways corrupt End of Seder section.<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Hèia Ama Lamatua peka dènge Noh, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a kèdhi dhoka bhabhelu dhèu di, dhu pale-lème rai-haha ne. Ka Ja'a pama'ète kore le, sèna ka Ja'a palaho aa'i rai-haha ne dènge isi na aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Then God spoke to Noh, saying, &lt;&lt;I see only evil of people all over the earth. So I have decided that I will totally destroy the earth and all its contents.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qets: the end, limit hinəni: here"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">qets: the end, limit hinəni: here I am (introduces an unexpected new development)<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>khamas mipneyhem: violence in front of them (in mind constantly) mashchitam: their destroyer (same lexeme as in 11 and 12, but the play on words - poho - doesn't seem to work in Pidgin)<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />De sèmi ne'e, Noh! Èu tao kapa aae cue, dhu tao nèti aj'u adhu. Re d'ara roa na, èu bagi mi kama-kama. Aa re d'ara dènge li'u kapa, èu lame dènge èi dama.<bt>So it's like this, Noh! You [must] make a large ship, made of hardwood. In its belly (=inside), you [must] divide in into rooms. And inside and outside the ship, you [must] smear it with tar/asphalt/varnish.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tevat: chest, ark, box, ship gofer:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tevat: chest, ark, box, ship gofer: Nobody is sure what kind of wood this is, but its similarity to the Greek word for cypress suggests that it may be the evergreen cypress Cupresus sempervirens, or possibly the Cilician fir Abies cilicica. The Phoenicians used the cypress in building ships.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>qinim: compartments kafarta: spread pitch over it, cover it with pitch<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>bayit: inside chuts: outside<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>kofer (same stem as kafarta): pitch, bitumen that seeps out of the ground</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Mu sab'e kapa na, madhera na 133 (ca ngasu tèlu nguru tèlu) meter; bhabhèla na 22 (dua nguru dua) meter; dènge katitu na 13 (canguru tèlu) meter.<bt>You will make/work the ship, its length being 133 meters; its width 22 meters; and its height 13 meters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔammah: (ordinary) cubit: linear measure of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔammah: (ordinary) cubit: linear measure of 44.5 cm (17.5 inches; elbow to fingertips, 24 fingers, 6 palms, 2 spans); (royal) cubit: linear measure of 51.81 cm (7 palms); roughly 18 inches, 2 cubits = about 1 yard. 300 cubits long, 50 cubits wide, 30 cubits high. A fathom of rope is about 2 cubits, measured with the arms stretch out to both sides. ʔorekh: length<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>rachbah: its breadth qomatah: its height<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Èu tao èmu ètu dedha kapa na. Te ngaa paconga ca laa ai nèti kadidhi re dedha. Èu bagi kapa ne mi tèlu tad'a. Aa re karasa na, tao babèdho èci.<bt>You [must] put a house/roof on top of the ship. But leave free a cubit/forearm at the top of the wall(s). You [must] divide the ship in three levels/layers. And at its side, make a closure/door.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aj'u adhu = kayu keras ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">aj'u adhu = kayu keras ; lane = kotak-kotak ; èi dama = varnish ; lame = gosok tempel,; 15: bhabhèla = lebarnya ;; 16: paconga = kasi farei ; ca laa aai = satu hasta ; babèdho = pintu, penutup</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsohar: roof (only here) tkhalennah (piʕel):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tsohar: roof (only here) tkhalennah (piʕel): you are to finish<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>milmaʕlah: down from above petach: door<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>tsiddah (tsad): its side tasim: you are to put<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>tachtiyim shniyim ushlishim: underneath things (=decks) second and third</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Sanèd'e paie-iie! Bèli-camèd'a, Ja'a papuru èi aae lala, ho pacène eele rai-haha ne, sèna ka pamadhe aa'i dhu mamuri.<bt>Remember/think well! I, in the future will bring down floodwater, to drown out the earth, so that [I] kill everything that lives.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mebiʔ (bwʔ hif partcpl): bringing in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mebiʔ (bwʔ hif partcpl): bringing in mabul: heavenly ocean, deluge<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>lshachet (piʕel): to destroy ruach chayyim: spirit of life, breath of life<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>yigwaʕ: die (unusual poetic word, used 12 times in Genesis for "perish")</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Te ngaa Ja'a pa'èki lii pajaji dènge èu. Èèna na, èu maso d'ara kapa èèna, mèti dènge dhèu èmu èu, ana-ana èu, dènge dhèu èmu ana-ana èu.<bt>But I bind my promise with you. Later, you will enter into that ship, taking your spouse, your children, and the spouses of your children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pacène eele = tenggelamkan ; dhènu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pacène eele = tenggelamkan ; dhènu eele = timbuni ; èi aae lala = banjir; 18: lii padhadha = janji, sumpah = lii pamoa</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haqimoti (qwm hif): I will set"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">haqimoti (qwm hif): I will set up, carry out</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19-20" />Badha aa'i-aa'i ra, èu hag'e more ca pasa-ca pasa, eo mèti asa d'ara kapa, ho ra abhu mamuri dènge èu kahèi. Sèmi: badha ani, manu-bhui, dènge badha dhu rod'o, sèna ka ra abhu mamuri.<bt>[Of] All of the animals, you [must] select out a pair of each, bring them onto the ship, so they can also live with you. Like: domestic animals, birds, and animals that crawl, so they can live.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taviyʔ (hif imperf): you are to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">taviyʔ (hif imperf): you are to bring lhachəyot (hif inf): to preserve alive<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>ʔitakh: along with you zakhar: male<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>nəqevah: female lmiynehu, lmiynah: in its kind, species<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>yavoʔu: they will come</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Èu hud'i mèti dènge nganga'a-nganginu, pala miu dènge pala badha sèra hèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>You must bring food, for you-pl and also for those animals.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maʔəkhal: food yiʔakhel (ʔkl nif): that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">maʔəkhal: food yiʔakhel (ʔkl nif): that is eaten<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ʔaSafta (ʔSp perf): gather, collect</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00625c.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:bottom">Noh mulai sab'e kapa aae<bt>Noh begins to make a big ship</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ka Noh sab'e madhutu sèmi lii paredha Ama Lamatua aa'i-aa'i sèra.<bt>And Noh worked according to all the commands of God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsiwwah: order, direct, command, put in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tsiwwah: order, direct, command, put in charge of doing End of Seder section.<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Èi aae lala<bt>The big floodwaters</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="7" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna ka, LAMATUA peka dènge Noh, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ladhe le palème, te ngaa abhu dhoka èu di dhu d'ara mola. Nèti èèna ka, èu dènge bhèni-ana niki èu, lami ka asa d'ara kapa.<bt>After that, the LORD said to Noh, &lt;&lt;I have looked everywhere, but I find only you who have a straight/pure inside. Because of that, you and your wives + children + spouses of children will go inside the ship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dor: generation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">dor: generation</Message></Annotation><v n="2-3" />Mèti dènge badha-badha dhu bisa mi'a, aa bisa hia Ja'a kahèi, de mèti pidhu-pidhu pasa asa d'ara kapa. Mèti kahèi rupa-rupa manu-bhui pidhu-pidhu pasa. Te ngaa badha dhu leo, mèti dhoka ca pasa-ca pasa di. Sèna ka badha dènge manu-bhui se, j'aj'i hini, ho baku ma'ète.<bt>Take along the animals you-pl can eat, and can also give to Me, taking seven paris of each into the ship. Also take seven pairs each of various kinds of birds. But the other animals, take only a single pair of each. So that these animals and birds will become seed, so they won't break (=end the line).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Təhorah: approved for sacrifice, cultically clean,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Təhorah: approved for sacrifice, cultically clean, ritually all right to eat zakhar: male<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>nəqevah: female lchayyot (chyh piʕel inf): to preserve alive (CHYH in the piʕel can have the meaning "bring back to life.")<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>zeraʕ: seed, offspring</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Sanèd'e paie-iie, oo! Di pidhu lod'o ka, Ja'a papuru èj'i aae mai dhu bhoka boe ca lod'o sa, toke d'ai èpa nguru lod'o mèu-mèda. Dènge sèmi ne'e, Ja'a pamadhe aa'i ngaa-ngaa dhu mamuri ètu dedha-rai, dhu Ja'a paj'aj'i kore le.&gt;&gt;<bt>Remember well, oo! In seven days, I will bring down huge rain which won't stop for s single day, for 40 day-night (cycles). In that way, I will kill off everything that lives on the land, which I have made/created.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhèni ana niki = isteri-anak (+"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">bhèni ana niki = isteri-anak (+ anak mantu, cucu)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕod: still shivʕah: seven days from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕod: still shivʕah: seven days from now, in one week, seven days after today<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>mamtir (mtr hif): make torrential rain come down, enough to cause severe flooding ʔarbaʕim yom vʔarbaʕim laylah: forty days and forty nites, for forty days, nite and day<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>umachiti (mchh): I will wipe out, destroy yəqum: what subsists, what is living<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ka Noh tao aa'i sèmi lii paredha LAMATUA.<bt>And Noh did everything as the LORD commanded.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsiwwahu: he commanded him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tsiwwahu: he commanded him</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Lod'o èi aae lala, umur Noh 600 (èna ngasu) tèu.<bt>When the great water flooded, Noh's age was 600 years.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mabul: heavenly ocean, deluge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mabul: heavenly ocean, deluge</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Noh dènge dhèu èmu na, dènge ana niki na, aa dènge dhèu èmu ana ra di, lasi asa d'ara kapa, ho ra abhu mamuri.<bt>Noh and his spouse, and his children, and their spouses, went into the ship, so they could live/get saved.</bt><v n="8-9" />Madhutu lii paredha LAMATUA, ka Noh pamaso manu-bhui dènge badha leo sèra, èci-èci ka dènge pasa na, nèti dhu bisa ra'a, dènge dhu bisa boe ra'a.<bt>Obeying the command of the LORD, Noh put in birds and other animals, one pair of each, from those they could eat, and those they couldn't eat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeynennah: there was none"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔeynennah: there was none</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ropa èle pidhu lod'o, cag'ag'a laa èi aae lala, ka rai-haha ne, mulai cène.<bt>After seven days, suddenly the flood came, and the earth began to drown.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00626c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Lèke dènge umur Noh 600 (èna ngasu) tèu, risi dua hèru, canguru pidhu lod'o, ka mulai èi aae lala. Lod'o èèna, sèmi babèdho liru dhu bhoke eele sa, ka èi na tao sabhori mai. Aa èi madha-èi madha ètu rai-haha sabhoka, ka sèmi tao sabhuu sa dedha.<bt>When Noh's age was 600 years, two months, and 17 days, the flood water began to come. That time, it was as if a door in the sky opened wide, and water came pouring/dumping in/down. And the springs in the earth burst open, like they were spitting upwards.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nivqʕu (bqʕ nif): split open, burst"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nivqʕu (bqʕ nif): split open, burst open maʕəynot: springs of water, powerful sources of water<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>tehom: primeval ocean, deepest parts of the sea, subterranean waters ʔərubot: windows<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>niftachu: they were opened</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ka èj'i bhori mai loe boe èpa nguru lod'o mèu-mèda.<bt>And the rain poured down without stopping for 40 day-nights.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sabhuu = sumbur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">sabhuu = sumbur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="geshem: torrential rain, as in v."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">geshem: torrential rain, as in v. 11</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Te ngaa lod'o èèna, Noh dènge dhèu èmu na, dènge ana mone na dhèu tèlu: Sem, Yafet dènge Ham, dènge dhèu èmu ra, maso lasi asa d'ara kapa.<bt>But that day, Noh and his spouse, and his three sons, Sem, Yafet, and Ham, and their spouses, went into the ship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕetsem: bone, body, self, the very"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕetsem: bone, body, self, the very same day</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Lasi palere dènge badha aa'i-aa'i ra, sèmi: badha ani, badha hui, badha dhu rod'o, manu-bhui, dènge badha-badha leo dhu dènge èla sèra.<bt>They went together with all those animals, such as: domestic animals, wild animals, animals that crawl, birds, and other animals that have wings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chayyah: animal, being miynah: its species|i(14)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">chayyah: animal, being miynah: its species<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>tsippor: bird (generic) kanaf: wing<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="15-16" />Ca pasa-ca pasa nèti aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri, lasi asa d'ara kapa palere dènge Noh, madhutu sèmi lii paredha Ama Lamatua.<bt>A pair each of everything that lives, went into the ship together with Noh, following the commands of God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa aa'i-aa'i ra d'ai d'ara kapa, LAMATUA bèdho babèdho kapa èèna.<bt>When all of them arrived inside the ship, the LORD closed the door of that ship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patèke = kunci"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">patèke = kunci</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔəsher-bo ruach chayyim: which had the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔəsher-bo ruach chayyim: which had the breath of life in it yiSgor: shut<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>baʕədo: for him (for it)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17-19" />Èj'i aae puru ma'ète boe d'ai èpa nguru lod'o. Hèia kapa èèna taleb'o. Èi ca'e loe boe toke hutu nare kolo ledhe dhu dedha aae.<bt>Big rain came down without a break for 40 days. Then the ship floated. The water ascended without stopping until it covered over the peaks of the highest mountains.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayirbu (rvh qal): became great vayisʔu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayirbu (rvh qal): became great vayisʔu (nsʔ): lifted, raised high. Is this what rising water does to boats?<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>vataram (rwm hif): raise, lift, pick up, lift up vayigbəru: swelled, rose, became strong<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>yirbu (rbh): became much vatelek (hlk): went here and there, floated around, drifted<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>yəkhussu (ksh pual): were covered with water gvohiym: high mountains<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Èi ca'e taruu, ka marèma na seli èpa rèpa risi nèti kolo ledhe sèra.<bt>The water kept rising, and its depth exceeded four fathoms above those mountain peaks.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taleb'o = ta'apung; 20: merèma ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">taleb'o = ta'apung; 20: merèma = dalamnya ; rèpa = depa</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maʕəlah: above gavru: became strong|i(20) (20)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">maʕəlah: above gavru: became strong<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>yəkhussu: they were covered</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21-23" />Dènge j'ara èèna, ngaa-ngaa dhu mamuri ètu dedha-rai sèra, madhe aa'i mèu-mèu. Nuka: dhèu, badha ani, badha hui, badha dhu rod'o, dènge manu-bhui aa'i-aa'i ra. Ate dhoka Noh dènge aa'i-aa'i dhu ètu dedha kapa.<bt>In that way, everything that lives on the land, died off completely (lit: clean-clean). That is: people, domestic animals, wild animals, animals that crawl, and all the birds. What remained was only Noh and everything on the ship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayigvaʕ: breathed its last, died (poetic)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayigvaʕ: breathed its last, died (poetic) basherets: swarming things, tiny animals occurring in large numbers<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>nishmat (cs nishmah): the blowing of the breath of life, breath; blast (of wind); breath; breath of life; breathing beings; breath (of God) bʔafayw: in its nostrils, nose<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>charavah: dry ground vayimach (mchh): (God) wiped out<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>yəqum: substance, being yimmachu (mchh nif): they were wiped out<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>vayishshaʔer (shʔr nif): was left over, remained ʔakh: only<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Èi na, kura boe toke 150 (ca ngasu lèmi nguru) lod'o.<bt>The water did not (begin to) reduce for 150 days.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Rai mango noo-noo<bt>The land dries out slowly</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="8" />
      <v n="1" />Masi ka sèmi èèna, Ama Lamatua bhèlu boe Noh si dènge badha-manu aa'i-aa'i dhu ètu dedha kapa. Hèia Na hia ngèlu g'oro, ka èi na kura ka noo-noo.<bt>Even that being the case, God did not forget Noh and all the various animals on the ship. So He sent a wind-breeze and the water reduced slowly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tevah: chest, ark, big boat (in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tevah: chest, ark, big boat (in this context) vayaʕaver (ʕvr hif): made a wind sweep across, cause to pass<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>vayashoku (shkk): they went down, abated, drained off</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Na katange èi madha aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne, aa Na taha èj'i kahèi.<bt>He covered/closed all the springs on the earth, and He also restrained the rain.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiSSakru (skr nif): the cosmic springs"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayiSSakru (skr nif): the cosmic springs were stopped up. In Kealakekua and Kalapana, Hawaii, and Lahaina, Maui, there are fresh water springs that come out under the ocean; Starlight remembers the ones in Kalapana. maʕəynot: springs of water<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>təhom: primeval ocean, deep ʔarubot: windows<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>vayikkaleʔ (klʔ nif): were kept back (of water) The opposite of 7:11<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Ka èi kura noo-noo ka. D'ai cangasu lèmi nguru lod'o, èi marèma heka.<bt>And the water reduced slowly. After 150 days, the water was no longer (so) deep.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayashuvu (shwv): go back where they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayashuvu (shwv): go back where they came from halokh (inf): walk<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>vayachSru: diminished, became less miqtseh: from the edge, from one end, the far edge; at the end of 150 days<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Lèke dènge hèru ka pidhu, risi canguru pidhu lod'o, kapa eta ètu kolo ledhe aae èci, ngara na Ararat.<bt>In the seventh month, and 17 days, the ship alighted on the peak of a high mountain, named Ararat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatanach (nwch): settled gently into position."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vatanach (nwch): settled gently into position. Like happens with a small boat when the tide goes out and the boat is left resting on the reef or the bottom, stuck but not damaged, or like locusts floating down on land chodesh: lunar month<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ʕal: down onto</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Èi kura taruu toke lod'o ka èci, hèru ka canguru, ka kolo-kolo ledhe cèu noo-noo.<bt>The water continued to reduce until the first day of the tenth month, and the peaks of the mountains appeared slowly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="g'oro = sapoi-sapoi (breeze) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">g'oro = sapoi-sapoi (breeze) ;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chaSor (inf): go down, diminish ʕad:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">chaSor (inf): go down, diminish ʕad: clear up to, until, indicates the distance from<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>raʔshey: heads of</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00631c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Noh patalale koro j'aha ci'u<bt>Noh releases a dove</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Risi nèti èpa nguru lod'o, hèia Noh bhoke jendela èci.<bt>After 40 days, then Noh opened a window (Port loan).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiftach: he opened chalon: hole in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiftach: he opened chalon: hole in the wall for air and light, window opening. It was probably covered with a wooden cover to keep the rain out, not with glass like a modern window.<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ka na patalale lakaa ci'u. Manu-bhui ne lela la'e-mai, toke èi puru. Ka na lèpa heka asa kapa.<bt>And he release a crow/raven [confirmed with bird book]. This bird flew going-coming, until the water descended. And it didn't return to the ship anymore.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayshalakh (shlkh piel): he stretched out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayshalakh (shlkh piel): he stretched out his hand and let it go free. He probably held the bird outside the door, then gave him a little push to make him fly away. ʕorev: raven, genus Corvus. Looks like the ʕalala, but eats dead meat<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>vayetseʔ yatsoʔ: went out, went away shov: came back. The idea of a raven flying around (Holladay) and not coming back for more than seven days, and maybe for a lot longer time, then finally coming back is traditional, but it depends upon the notion that the raven found dead animals still floating on the water to eat ten months or more after the flood started is questionable because of decomposition. But having a raven fly in and out at will without bringing back any useful evidence of what was going on outside is perfectly plausible.<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>ʕad-ybosheth (ybsh inf): up to the time of the water drying up</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Hèia Noh patabuli hari, koro j'aha ci'u, sèna ka neo ne'a èi na puru le, do dhae.<bt>And Noh again released a dove [also confirmed with bird book], so that he could find out if the water had descended, or not yet.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yonah: dove. Doves donʔt eat dead"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yonah: dove. Doves donʔt eat dead meat as ravens do, so it needed to find freshly grown plants haqalu (qll): if the waters were lighter, if the waters were growing less<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Te ngaa, lula èi hutu nare dedha-rai era, ka koro ne abhu boe era tèka. Ka lèpa hari asa kapa. Hèia Noh j'ole ai na, kèpe nare, ka na pamaso hari asa d'ara kapa.<bt>But, because the water still covered the land, this bird couldn't find a place to alight. So it returned to the ship. Then Noh stretched out his hand, and caught it, and he brought it back into the ship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lakaa = burung gagak, (confirmed w/book)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">lakaa = burung gagak, (confirmed w/book) itam, makan belalang, cicak, bangkai, ; koro j'aha = burung pompa (confirmed w/book) ; koro iia ~ koro mananga ~ koro èi = tekukur (confirmed w/book)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="manoach: resting place lkaf-raglah: for the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">manoach: resting place lkaf-raglah: for the sole of the foot<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>tashav ʔelayw (masc): she (Hebrew gender) returned to him (Noah, masc) to the boat (fem) yiqqacheha (lqch): took it<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ka Noh tatae hari d'ai pidhu lod'o, hèia na patabuli hari koro j'aha deo na.<bt>Noh waited again seven more days, then he again released that same dove.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayakhel: waited ʔəcheriym: other|i(10) (10) |rvayosef:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayakhel: waited ʔəcheriym: other<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>vayosef: he additionally ..., he went on to ...</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />D'ara lod'o nihia sa, koro ne lèpa hari la'e asa Noh, tutu nèti dènge rèu saitun ca rèu dhu heka tutu nare kèna. Nèti èèna ka, Noh heka ne'a kèna, èi na dhu puru le tare'a di.<bt>That afternoon, this bird came back to Noh, picked bringing a /saitun/ (olive, loan) leaf, which it had just picked. Because of that, Noh now knew that the water had really gone down.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕəleh-zayit: foliage, leaves of an olive"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕəleh-zayit: foliage, leaves of an olive tree taraf: freshly plucked<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>bfiyah: in its beak, mouth qallu: the waters were light, not much (= v. 8)<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ka na mate hari d'ai pidhu lod'o, hèia na patalale hari koro j'aha ca hari ni. Te ngaa ca tèka ne, koro ne lèpa heka.<bt>And he waited again for seven more days, then he released that dove another time. But this time, this bird did not return.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tutu nèti = bawa dgn paru,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">tutu nèti = bawa dgn paru, toto bawa ; pago = tangkai</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="one nodda week? one week moa?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">one nodda week? one week moa? yiyyachel (ychl nif): he waited?<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>yaSfah (ySp): continue, repeat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Lod'o Noh mamuri d'ai 601 (èna ngasu ca) tèu, lèke lod'o ka èci hèru èci, èi mèti aa'i le. Hèia Noh bhoke jendela, ka na ladhe palème, nèdhi rai dhu mango le.<bt>When Noh had lived for 601 years, on the first day of the first month, the water had dried up. So Noh opened the window, and he looked around, seeing the land was already dry.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="riʔshon: first kharvu: drain off (the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">riʔshon: first kharvu: drain off (the water), dry up (the land) - redundant<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>yaSar (Swr): turn aside. Stepped out of his usual routine? mikhSeh: covering, like the covering of a tent - sort of like a tarpaulin<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />D'ai hèru ka dua, lod'o ka dua nguru pidhu, dedha-rai ne dhu mango meto le.<bt>Arriving at the second month, the 27th day, the surface of the land was really dry.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ka Ama Lamatua peka dènge Noh,<bt>And God said to Noh,</bt><v n="16" />&lt;&lt;Noh! Aa'i-aa'i mi puru ka nèti dedha kapa èèna.<bt>&lt;&lt;Noh! All of you can get down from onboard the ship.</bt><v n="17" />Papuru aa'i badha-manu sèra! Nuka: badha ani, badha hui, badha dhu rod'o, dènge manu-bhui aa'i-aa'i ra. Hud'i si, sèna ka ra bèba, papènu rai-haha ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Disembark all the animals! Such as: the domestic animals, wild animals, animals that crawl, and all the birds. Let the go so they can reproduce, and fill this earth.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="basar: flesh, species? remes: the creeping"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">basar: flesh, species? remes: the creeping mass<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>hwtsʔ (ytsʔ hif imperv): make them go out vshartsu: let them swarm, teem, be innumerable<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>faru (prh): let them be fruitful</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18-19" />Èle èèna ka, Noh dènge dhèu èmu na, dènge ana-ana na, aa dènge dhèu èmu ana na sèra, aa'i-aa'i ra puru nèti dedha kapa èèna. Badha se, aa'i-aa'i ra, kalua ka madhutu anga ra èci-èci.<bt>After that, Noh and his spouse, and his children, and the spouses of his children, all descended from the ship. The animals, all of them went out according to each of their companions.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lmishpəchotehem: in all their extended families"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">lmishpəchotehem: in all their extended families (species)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Noh hia korban makasi mi Lamatua<bt>Noh gives a thank offering to the Lord</bt></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\Hk00252c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Ra pudhi hadhu tao mei korban<bt>They arrange stones to make an *offering table</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Hèia Noh pudhi hadhu, tao mei korban hia LAMATUA. Nèti badha-badha dhu bisa ra'a sèra, Noh nare ci'u-ci'u, ka na roro, tunu ètu dedha mei deo na, ho j'aj'i mi tadha makasi mi LAMATUA.<bt>Then Noh stacked rocks, making an *offerring table to the LORD. From/among the sorts of animals which they can eat, Noh took one each, and he slaughtered it, burning/roasting it on top of that aforementioned table, to be a sign of thanks to the LORD.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mizbeakh: altar for God Təhorah: acceptable,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mizbeakh: altar for God Təhorah: acceptable, ritually "clean"<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>vayaʕal (ylh hif): he took the animals up ʕolot: offerings completely burned on an altar<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ropa LAMATUA sangèd'u nare hèu gèmu korban deo na, d'ara Na karej'e. Ka Na ngee na,<bt>When the LORD smelled the delicious smell of that sacrifice, His insides were happy. And He thought,</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">&lt;&lt;Nèti deo ne'e ne, Ja'a huku heka rai-haha ne, lula bhabhelu-katub'a dhèu. Masi ka rèngu dhoka ngee bhabhelu di, Ja'a pa'ele iie heka ngaa-ngaa dhu mamuri, sèmi dhu Ja'a heka tao kore èèna.<bt>&lt;&lt;Beginning now, I will not punish again this world because of the evil of humans. Even though they can only think evil, I will not again destroy everything that lives, in the way that I have done.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yarach (rwch hif): enjoy the smell"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yarach (rwch hif): enjoy the smell of something; metaphor for looking favorably on the sacrifice reach: odor, scent<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>nichoach: soothing ʔoSif (ySp hif): I will not continue<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>lqallel (piel): declare something cursed ʔadamah: ground, soil<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>baʕavur: on account of yetser: thought<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>nəʕurayw: his youth (stage of life) lhakot (nkh): strike, batter, destroy<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Lod'o rai-haha ne era, hèru dènge tèu, kako madhutu atora. Sèmi: hèru sèla dènge hèru puu-g'ètu, hèru pacuhi dènge hèru sagoro, hèru hadhu dènge hèru èj'i lai, mèu dènge mèda.&gt;&gt;<bt>As long as this world still is, the months and the years will keep going systematically. Such as: planting month/season and harvest month, cold months and hot months, dry season (lit. rock season) and rainy season, daytime and night time.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pudhi (2) = susun ; ~"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pudhi (2) = susun ; ~ pagodo; 21: sangèd'u = cium ; hèu gèmu = bau enak; 22: hèru sèla = misim tanam ; hèru puu g'ètu = musim panen</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zeraʕ: seed, offspring qatsiyr: yield of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">zeraʕ: seed, offspring qatsiyr: yield of the harvest<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>qor: cold chom: heat<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>qayits: summer, summer fruit choref: autumn, winter<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>yishbotu: they will [not] cease</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua pajaji dènge Noh<bt>Lord God mutually binds a promise with Noh</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="9" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia Ama Lamatua pala-bagi berkat mi Noh dènge ana-ana na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu matana pa'ae-ae, sèna ka papènu rai-haha ne.<bt>Then God divided out blessings to Noh and his children, saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl should have many children, so that you can fill the earth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəbarek (piel): bestow power for success,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yəbarek (piel): bestow power for success, prosperity, fertility. God did it for people, animals, a field, the seventh day. Also God or another person declares somebody to be endowed with power of that kind, or wishes them success. A person can declare God to be the source of power for success, prosperity, or fertility; a form of praise pəru (prh command): bear fruit, be fruitful (and multiply)<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>umilʔu: and fill up something (ergative-absolute?)</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ladhe èèna na, badha hui, manu-bhui dènge i'a aa'i-aa'i ra madha'u dènge miu. Miu ka dhu ator si.<bt>Later all the wild animals, birds and fish will fear you. You-pl are the ones who must manage them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="moraʔkhem: the fear of you chitkhem:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">moraʔkhem: the fear of you chitkhem: the terror of you<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>byedkem: in your hand nitanu bayad (nif): they are given into your power, turned over to you<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Sisi badha aa'i-aa'i, miu bisa mi'a, sèmi dhu mi'a hua-hela, dènge rèu ana aaj'u se. Aa'i-aa'i se, Ja'a hia miu.<bt>The meat from all animals, you may eat, just like you may eat the fruit and leaves of plants. All these, I give to you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padhadha = membuat kesepakatan, sofia"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">padhadha = membuat kesepakatan, sofia</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="remesh: all the animals, except large"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">remesh: all the animals, except large animals and birds yerek: greens, vegetables, green plants<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>ʕesev: non-perennial plants that grow during the rainy season, including weeds, grass, vegetables, and cereals</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Dhoka sisi dhu dènge raa era, miu madha mèu mi'a, lula samanga badha ètu raa na.<bt>Only meat that still has blood, you may under no circumstances (Idiom: clear eyes = strong prohibition) eat, because the soul/life-force of the animal is in its blood.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="akh: particle of assurance or emphasis,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">akh: particle of assurance or emphasis, restrictive</Message></Annotation><v n="5-6" />Ja'a paj'aj'i dhèu madhutu raropa Ja'a. Nèti èèna ka, baku pamadhe dhèu. Ladhe abhu dhèu, do badha, dhu pamadhe dhèu, na, pamadhe ne kahèi. Ne'e, lii paredha nèti Ja'a.<bt>I created people according to My form/image. That is why you may not kill people. If there is a person, or animal, which kills a person, na, they must also be killed. This is a command from Me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔedrosh, ʔedrəshenu (with et-): I will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔedrosh, ʔedrəshenu (with et-): I will demand someone's blood (of them), call them to account, inquire about the matter miyad ʔish ʔakhiw: from the hand (responsibility) of a man, his brother<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>shofek (shfk): shed blood, pour out a liquid, spill tselem: model, image, drawing, statue<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Miu se hud'i matana pa'ae-ae ku, sèna ka papènu hari rai-haha ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>You-pl must have lots of children, so that you can refill this earth.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madha mèu = coba-coba (Idiom &lt;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">madha mèu = coba-coba (Idiom &lt; mata tarang) (strong prohibition)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shirtsu: swarm, be innumerable End of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shirtsu: swarm, be innumerable End of S section<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ka Ama Lamatua tuhu hari lii padhai lii Na,<bt>And God continued speaking,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔitto: &lt;object&gt; 3s, sounds awkward in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔitto: &lt;object&gt; 3s, sounds awkward in Pidgin</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />&lt;&lt;De ne'e ne, Ja'a pajaji dènge miu, toke d'ai lai ana lai èpu.<bt>&lt;&lt;So now, I make a promise with you, that goes on to your children and to your grandchildren (Idiomatic).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meqim (qwm hif participle): setting up,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">meqim (qwm hif participle): setting up, carrying out, performing, keeping one's word, establishing zarʕəkhem: your seed = your descendants<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Lii pajaji ne, lèke kahèi mi aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri, sèmi: badha ani, badha hui, dènge manu-bhui. Peka ka laa, lèke aa'i-aa'i dhu kalua palere-lere dènge miu nèti dedha kapa.<bt>This promise, also affects everything that lives, such as: domestic animals, wild animals, and the birds. The important thing (resumptive), it affects everything that accompanied you out of the ship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yotsʔey (ytsʔ partcpl pl): the ones"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yotsʔey (ytsʔ partcpl pl): the ones coming out</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Lii pajaji Ja'a sèmi ne'e: Ja'a hia heka èi aae lala, ho pamadhe aa'i ngaa-ngaa dhu mamuri, aa dènge pa'ele iie rai-haha ne.<bt>My promise is like this: I will not again give a huge flood to kill off everything that lives, and destroy the earth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lai ana lai èpu = phrase;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">lai ana lai èpu = phrase; 10: Peka kalaa = pokoknya</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="həqimoti (qwm hif): I am setting"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">həqimoti (qwm hif): I am setting up vloʔ-yikkaret (krt nif imperfect): will not be eliminated, rooted out, extinguished, cut off<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>mimmey: from the waters of mabul: flood<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>lshachet (piel): wipe out, ruin, spoil</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12-13" />Ja'a pasa saroo ètu dedha-liru, sèna ka j'aj'i tadha pasanèd'e lii pajaji Ja'a dhu ma'ète boe dènge miu, dènge aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri, aa dènge rai-haha ne.<bt>I will fasten a rainbow in the sky, as a sign of remembance of My promise which will never break with you-pl, with everything that lives, and with the earth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔot: sign, distinguishing mark, sign to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔot: sign, distinguishing mark, sign to bring to mind a covenant obligation beni ubenekhem: between me and you<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ldorot: for generation after generation qashti: my bow (for shooting), metaphor for a rainbow<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ʕanan: mass of clouds</Message></Annotation><v n="14-17" />Ladhe abhu ra'i-liru, ho saroo cèu, èèna na pasanèd'e Ja'a nèti lii pajaji èèna. Na peka na, èi aae pa'ele iie heka aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri. Dènge j'ara ne'e ne ka, lii pajaji Ja'a dhu ma'ète boe, pa'èki tèke le dènge miu, aa dènge aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri.&gt;&gt;<bt>When there are clouds in the sky, and the rainbow appears, that will remind Me about that promise. That, the big flood will never again destroy everything that lives. By this means, My promise which does not break, is bound with you-pl and with everything that lives.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕanəni (piel inf): cause something to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕanəni (piel inf): cause something to make an appearance nirʔətah (nif): be seen, appear<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>vzakharti: I will remember, I will be thinking about End of P section.<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Noh mahu<bt>Noh gets drunk</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ana-ana Noh dhu puru nèti dedha kapa, Sem, Yafet dènge Ham (Ham èèna, ama Kana'an).<bt>Noh's children that came down from the ship were Sem, Yafet and Ham. (That Ham, was Kana'an's father).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hayotsʔim (partcpl): the ones who came"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hayotsʔim (partcpl): the ones who came out vayihyu: there were, starts a new section of the story<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra ètu rai-haha ne, j'aj'i nèti ana Noh dhèu tèlu sèra.<bt>Everyone on earth /jadi/ (came into being) from Noh's three sons.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naftsah: scattered, spread out, were dispersed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">naftsah: scattered, spread out, were dispersed</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\Hk00112c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Ana aaj'u anggor<bt>Grape vine/tree</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Noh èèna, dhèu sab'a oka-tedhe. Nèngu ka dhu uru j'ara tao oka anggor.<bt>Noh was a person who worked the fields. He is the first to make an anggor (grape) field.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yachel (chll hif): let something be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yachel (chll hif): let something be profaned. From the meaning "untie" associated with this, comes the idea of "begin" vayiTTaʕ (nTʕ): plant (a garden, a vineyard, a tree, desolation)<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>karem: vineyard</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ca tèka, na ninu èi anggor, ka na mahu titu kèna. Hèia na puru eele mèdha-papake nèti ua na. Ka na j'unu lega-loli dènge boe mèdha-papake ètu d'ara paleo na.<bt>One time, he drank anggor juice/wine, and he became very drunk. Then he took off his clothes from his body. And he slept sprawled face-up without any clothes inside his tent/shelter.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayishkar: he got drunk vayitgal (glh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayishkar: he got drunk vayitgal (glh hitp): exposed himself<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>btok: in the middle of ʔahəlah: the tent place<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Ropa Ham ladhe nèdhi era makae ama na, ka rai li'u la'e, lolo dènge a'a na, Sem dènge Yafet.<bt>When Ham saw his father's place of shame (genitals), he ran outside, reporting to his elder-siblings, Sem and Yafet.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕerwat: genital area of either sex,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕerwat: genital area of either sex, nakedness. This reflects Middle East cultural values, but seems strange in Hawaii (UNS). It doesn't block understanding, as people in Hawaii are highly aware that not everybody holds to the same cultural values. vayaged (ngd hif): put something up conspicuously in front of someone, tell, inform, denounce. Not just giving them information, but disrespectfully tattling on his own father.<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>bachuts: on the outside</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Hèia dua ra rare sig'i-kalolo ca bèla, ka ra bhoke mema ètu kabela-kao ra. Ka dua ra kako kabodho lasi asa d'ara paleo ama ra, sèna ka ra pahutu mi ngi'u na. Dènge sèmi èèna, rèdhi boe era makae ama ra. Èle èèna ka, ra kalua sa li'u.<bt>So the two of them took a blanket, and the opened it up on their shoulders. And the two of them walked backwards going into their father's tent, so they could cover his body. In that way, they did not see their father's place of shame. After that, they went outside.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lega-loli = laloli; 22: kaha'e ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">lega-loli = laloli; 22: kaha'e = sepotong; 23: era makae = (a bit more acceptable)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="simlah: mantle, wrapper (both garment and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">simlah: mantle, wrapper (both garment and under-blanket) shkem: both shoulders, the neck and upper part of the back<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>shneyhem: the two of them ʔachoranit: (walk) backwards<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>yəkaSSu (kSh) (piʕel): cover with something, with accusative for what was covered but the covering unexpressed</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ropa Noh mase'a, na ne'a tatao nèti ana limuri na, Ham.<bt>When Noh became aware/came out of his drunk, he found out what his youngest child, Ham, had done.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiyqets: wake up (intransitive) from sleep"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiyqets: wake up (intransitive) from sleep or from being drunk qatan: younger or youngest? Ham is always mentioned second, but most English translations translate "qatan" as ʔyoungestʔ anyway.<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Ka na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;He! Ama Kana'an! Ja'a dhoo èu! Èu ne, èèna na j'aj'i ènu nèti a'a mu si!<bt>And he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;He! Kana'an's father! I curse you! You will become a slave to your elder-siblings!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mase'a = sadar (also for coming"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">mase'a = sadar (also for coming out of a drunk, coming down from malarial fever, coming out of sea-sickness); 25: butu-bajo-lau (di Ndao) ; binongko (di Kupang)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqets: qatan: small, youngest|i(25) (25) |rʕeved"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiqets: qatan: small, youngest<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>ʕeved ʕəvadim: a slave of slaves, forced to do work that even ordinary slaves would not do. ʔachiyw: his (Canaan's) brothers; it probably means all of Noah's descendants, but it is phrased in such a way that it could be taken as cousins, the children of Shem and Japheth, plus possibly Ham's other children. But "ach" evidently can refer to uncles too. What the commentaries don't make clear is why the curse is directed to Canaan (unless it is simply eponymous, referring symbolically to the Canaanite people at the time of the Exodus that the Jews are supposed to exterminate and justifying their going after those people rather than others), not on Ham.<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="26" />Koa-kio LAMATUA, lula Sem!<bt>Praise the LORD, because of Sem!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baruk (qal cs): filled with power,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">baruk (qal cs): filled with power, God be praised</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te ngaa Kana'an j'aj'i ènu Sem.<bt>But Kana'an will become the slave of Sem.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="27" />Hud'i laa, Ama Lamatua pataleo rai unu Yafet.<bt>May God widen the land owned by Yafet.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa ana-èpu na mamuri mera-milu dènge ana-èpu Sem.<bt>And his descendants live in peace-prosperity with the descendants of Sem.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Te ngaa hud'i Kana'an j'aj'i ènu Yafet.&gt;&gt;<bt>But as for Kana'an, may he become the slave of Yafet.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaft (yph hif impf): provide ample"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yaft (yph hif impf): provide ample space (sounds like Jafet's name), may he make spacious vyishkon: and may he settle down to live<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>bʔahaley-shem: in the tents of Shem lo: it isn't clear grammatically from the Hebrew whether the Canaan line is to be slaves to the Jafet line or the Shem line. The line is word for word the same as the last line of 26, but that doesn't mean it has the same referent for its pronoun.<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Nèti èle èi aae lala, Noh mamuri era d'ai 350 (tèlu ngasu lèmi nguru) tèu.<bt>From the end of the flood, Noh lived on another 350 years.</bt><v n="29" />Umur Noh d'ai 950 (ceo ngasu lèmi nguru) tèu, heka madhe kèna.<bt>Noh's age reached 950 years, only-then did he die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-èpu Noh dènge ana-èpu Yafet<bt>The descendants of Noh and the descendants of Yafet</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="10" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èi aae, ka ana-ana Noh abhu ana-èpu. Nuka ana-èpu nèti Sem, Yafet, dènge Ham.<bt>After the flood, Noh's children had children-grandchildren. They were the children-grandchildren of Sem, Yafet, and Ham.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiwwaldu (yld nif): were born"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiwwaldu (yld nif): were born</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="2-5" />Ana-èpu Yafet, nuka: Gomer, Magog, Madai, Yawan, Tubal, Mesek dènge Tiras. Èci-èci ka dènge lii, suku, aa dènge rai ra.<bt>Yafet's children-grandchildren were: Gomer, Magog, Madai, Yawan, Tubal, Mesek and Tiras. Each with their own language, tribe, and land.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">Ana-èpu Gomer, ka: Askenas, Rifat dènge Togarma.<bt>Gomer's descendants were: Askenas, Rifat and Togarma.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">Ana-èpu Yawan, ka: Elisa, Tarsis, dhèu Kitim, dènge dhèu Dodanim dhu pea ètu sebhe dhasi.<bt>Yawan's descendants were, Elisa, Tarsis, the people of Kitim, and the people of Dodanim who live at the edge of the sea.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kittiym: Cyprus dodaniym: Rhodes|i(2) (2) |rmeʔelleh:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">kittiym: Cyprus dodaniym: Rhodes<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>meʔelleh: from these? some of these? nifrədu (frd nif): branch off<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>ʔiyey: islands of, coastlands of; coast, island, shore, region ʔartsotam: their lands<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>lilshono: according to their own language lmishpachotam: according to their own ethnic and national subdivisions, felt blood relationships. BDB: a subdivision of a larger group such as a tribe or nation. Thus in Num 11:10 Moses hears the people weeping "by families." In Josh 7:16-18, in which the search is carried out to find the man guilty of causing God's displeasure on Israel, first the tribe of Judah is isolated, then the "family" (mishpa4h[a=) of the Zerahites, then the next smaller unit, the "household" (be=t) of Zabdi. Do Pidgin speakers make all these distinctions? Holladay: plural, races, subdivisions of ethnic and national groups.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>bəgowyehem: by their peoples - their own presumed ethnicity? It seems to be talking social groupings here, not genetics.</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:4" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Abhu sasuri cahag'e dhu uru sèra, peka na &lt;Rodanim&gt;.<bt>There are several old writings which say &lt;Rodanim&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-èpu Ham<bt>Ham's descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ana-èpu Ham, ka: Kus, Misraim, Put, dènge Kana'an.<bt>Ham's descendants were: Kus, Misraim, Put, and Kana'an.</bt><note reference="10:6" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Kus èèna, nuka &lt;Etiopia&gt;. Aa Misraim, nuka &lt;Masir&gt;.<bt>That Kus, that is &lt;Etiopia&gt;. And Misraim is &lt;Masir&gt; [Egypt].</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="7" />Ana-èpu Kus, ka: Seba, Hawila, Sabta, Raema dènge Sabteka.<bt>Kus's descendants were: Seba, Hawila, Sabta, Raema and Sabteka.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">Ana-èpu Raema, ka: Syeba dènge Dedan.<bt>Raema's descendants were: Syeba and Dedan.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ana mone Kus, ka, Nimrod. Nèngu ne, kapala musu dhu uru tèka, aa èra.<bt>Kus had a son, Nimrod. It is he who was the first strong war chief.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hekhel (khll hif): he began gibor:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hekhel (khll hif): he began gibor: manly, vigorous, heroic; macho man, also a pushy despot<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />A'èra na mai nèti LAMATUA, aa nèngu kahèi j'aj'i dhèu dhu èra bia magèla badha. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu biasa peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèna ka èu more dhèu dhu èra bia magèla badha, sèmi Nimrod, dhu abhu a'èra nèti LAMATUA.&gt;&gt;<bt>His strength/greatness came from the LORD, and he also became the greatest hunter of animals. That is why people often said, &lt;&lt;May you be a great hunter, like Nimrod, who got his strength/greatness from the LORD.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsayid: hunting, game killed while hunting"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tsayid: hunting, game killed while hunting yeʔamar (nif): be talked about as, be called<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Era na, mulai uru nèti rae Babel, Erek Akad, toke Kalne. Rae se aa'i-aa'i ra, ètu rai Sinear.<bt>His place began from village/city of Babel, Erek Akad, until Kalne. All of these villages/cities were in the land/country of Sinear.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="reʔshit: beginning, first, best, main sources"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">reʔshit: beginning, first, best, main sources of power mamlakhto: his rulership<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="10:10" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sinear èèna, ngara leo nèti Babel. Limuri ne, era èèna ètu Iran dènge Irak.<bt>That Sinear, is another name for Babel. These days, it is in the land of Iran and Irak.</bt></note><v n="11" />Nèti era sèra, na nare hari Asyur. Ka na patitu kota Niniwe, Rehobot-Ir, Kala,<bt>From those places, he also took Asyur. And he erected/founded the cities of Niniwe, Rehobot-Ir, Kala,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yatsaʔ: went out. It implies that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yatsaʔ: went out. It implies that he took over Assyria</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />dènge Resen, ètu talora aae Niniwe dènge Kala. Aa'i-aa'i sèra, kota-kota kapai hua.<bt>and Resen, between Niniwe and Kala. All of those were important cities.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mora = 2s-sama"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">mora = 2s-sama</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="13" />Ana-èpu Misraim, ka: dhèu Ludim, dhèu Ananim, dhèu Lehabim, dhèu Naftuhim,<bt>Misraim's descendants were: the people of Ludim, the people of Anamim, the people of Lehabim, the people of Naftuhim,</bt><v n="14" />dhèu Patrusim, dhèu Kasluhim, dènge dhèu Kaftorim. Dhèu Kasluhim nuka bèi-baki nèti dhèu Pilistin.<bt>the people of Patrusim, the people of Kasluhim, and the people of Kaftorim. The people of Kasluhim, were the Filistin people's ancestors.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="15" />Ana uuru Kana'an, nuka, Sidon. Kana'an j'aj'i bèi-baki nèti dhèu Het,<bt>Kana'an's oldest child was, Sidon. Kana'an was became the ancestor of the people of Het,</bt><v n="16" />dhèu Yebusi, dhèu Amori, dhèu Girgasi,<bt>the people of Yebusi, the people of Amori, the people of Girgasi,</bt><v n="17" />dhèu Hiwi, dhèu Arki, dhèu Sini,<bt>the people of Hiwi, the people of Arki, the people of Sini,</bt><v n="18" />dhèu Arwadi, dhèu Semari, dènge dhèu Hamati.<bt>the people of Arwadi, the people of Semari, and the people of Hamati.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ana-èpu Kana'an se, pea palème d'ai era dhu kaj'èu,<bt>These descendants of Kana'an lived spread out in far-away places,</bt><v n="19" />toke too rai rèngu mulai nèti Sidon taruu asa Gerar, d'ai Gasa. Nèti èèna, la'e d'ai Sodom, Gomora, Adma dènge Seboim, d'ai kota Lasa.<bt>until their land boundaries began from Sidon going on to Gerar, arriving at Gasa. From there, going on to Sodom, Gomora, Adma, and Seboim, until coming out at the city of Lasa.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nafotsu (pwts nif): they were scattered"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nafotsu (pwts nif): they were scattered gəvul: boundary, territory<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>boʔəkhah (bwʔ partcpl): when you are going</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Rèngu aa'i-aa'i sèra, ana-èpu Ham. Èci-èci dènge lii, suku, aa dènge rai ra.<bt>All of them were Ham's descendants. Each with their own language, tribe/clan, and land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-èpu Sem<bt>Sem's descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Sem, a'a Yafet, nèngu ka j'aj'i bèi-baki dhèu Eber.<bt>Sem, the older-brother of Yafet, is the one who became the ancestor of the Eber people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yullad (qal passive): was born to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yullad (qal passive): was born to him (here as elsewhere, the person named can be either the father or a more remote ancestor, with generations skipped in between)</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:21" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Abhu dhèu d'èlu-mèu cahag'e dhu peka na, dhèu Eber sèra, nuka &lt;dhèu Ibrani&gt;.<bt>There are some knowledgable people who say those Eber people , are &lt;the Ibrani' [Hebrew] people&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="22" />Ana-èpu Sem, ka: Elam, Asyur, Arpaksad, Lud dènge Aram.<bt>Sem's descendants were Elam, Asyur, Arpaksad, Lud and Aram.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="23" />Ana-èpu Aram ka: dhèu Us, dhèu Hul, dhèu Geter, dènge dhèu Mas.<bt>Aram's descendants were, the people of Us, the people of Hul, the people of Geter and the people of Mas.</bt><note reference="10:23" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Mas, ngara leo na, &lt;Mesek&gt;.<bt>Mas's other name is &lt;Mesek&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="24" />Ana Arpaksad ka, Sela. Ana Sela ka, Eber.<bt>Arpaksad's child was Sela. Sela's child was Eber.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="25" />Ana Eber, mone dhèu dua. Ana uuru, ngara na Pelek (dhu sasoa na &lt;palème era&gt;), lula taa èèna dhèu pea palème ètu rai-haha ne. Ngara ari na, Yoktan.<bt>Eber had two sons. The oldest, was named Pelek, (which means &lt;scattered around&gt;), because at that time, people were scattered around on the earth. His younger-brother's name was Yoktan.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="&quot;Peleg&quot; is the regular word for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">"Peleg" is the regular word for an artificial irrigation channel. PLG in the nifʕal is used only of this occasion (also 1 Chronicles 1:19), so there's no evidence that any other kind of division is involved, like political division or even geological separation. It's reasonable to take it as a reference to the development of irrigation-based societies, where water rights became prominent in law and encouraged the codification of law, and irrigation agriculture made it possible for a lot of people to live in a small area, which went along with the need for consistent laws. It points plausibly to the introduction of irrigation, which brought about a lot of political changes because now somebody could control who got how much water. Similar social changes took place in the eastern part of the Valley of Mexico when started digging irrigation ditches. Hawaiʕi is still arguing about the allocation of irrigation water in 19th century ditches even though the sugar cane and pineapple fields are no longer under cultivation. [JEG] nifləgah (plg nif fem sg): the earth/land was divided, cut open, split with channels (the noun is used for an artificial water-channel, like a water ditch, in Isaiah 30:25 and elsewhere). Job 29:6 has ditches full of olive oil. Job 38:25 has the piʕel form "open a channel, split with channels." Psalm 55:10 has pallag, which Holladay says has to be read as peleg. Modern Hebrew pilleg ʔsplitʔ, pullag ʔbe splitʔ.<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="26" />Ana-èpu Yoktan, ka: Almodad, Selef, Hasar-Mawet, Yera,<bt>Yoktan's descendants were: Almodad, Selef, Hasar-Mawet, Yera,</bt><v n="27" />Hadoram, Usal, Dikla,<bt>Hadoram, Usal, Dikla,</bt><v n="28" />Obal, Abimael, Syeba,<bt>Obal, Abimael, Syeba,</bt><v n="29" />Ofir, Hawila, dènge Yobab. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i se, ana-èpu Yoktan.<bt>Ofir, Hawila, and Yobab. All of these were the descendants of Yoktan.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Era pea rèngu, mulai nèti Mesa, taruu d'ai Sefar, nuka era dhu kabhuku re sebhe dhimu.<bt>Their dwelling place began from Mesa, continued on to Sefar, that is the hilly region in the eastern side.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabhuku = menonjol, berbukit,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">kabhuku = menonjol, berbukit,</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="moshavam: their area of residence Har"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">moshavam: their area of residence Har Haqedem: the Eastern Mountains = the northern border of Sinai?<span class="Italic">(30)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Rèngu aa'i-aa'i se, ana-èpu Sem. Èci-èci ka dènge lii, suku, aa dènge rai ra.<bt>All of these were Sem's descendants. Each with their own language, tribe/clan, and land.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Aa'i-aa'i se, ana-èpu Noh, èci-èci ka dènge suku ra. Ropa èi aae lala èle, rèngu se'e ka pea papènu lème rai-haha ne.<bt>All of these were Noh's descendants, each with his own tribe. When the big flood ended, these are the people who spread out to fill the world.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nifrədu: divided into family groups, branched"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nifrədu: divided into family groups, branched off (v. 5) End of P section.<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Manara Babel<bt>The tower (loan) of Babel</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="11" />
      <v n="1" />Uru-uru tèka na, dhèu ètu rai-haha ne, dhoka lii èci di.<bt>Long ago, people in the world had only one language.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="safah: lip; manner of speaking. Doublet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">safah: lip; manner of speaking. Doublet doesn't transfer gracefully into Pidgin in this case. dvariym: words<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Lod'o rèngu cahag'e lasi asa ca bèka dhimu, ra d'ai era mera ètu Sinear, ka ra pea ètu èèna.<bt>When they moved to the east, they arrived at a flat place in Sinear, and they stayed there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bnaSʕam (nSʕ inf): in their pulling"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bnaSʕam (nSʕ inf): in their pulling up tent stakes and moving, going on from one place to another, living in each place for a while. Used of nomads like today's Bedouin graups. yimtsʔu: they reached a place, found what they were looking for, ran into it by chance<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>biqʕah: valley-plain, broad with shallow walls (like between Dallas and Ft. Worth, or around Sacramento). In this case, it is the broad valleys of the Tigris and Euphrates rivers in modern Iraq and the fairly level ground in between.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Ibrani &lt;lasi asa ca bèka dhimu&gt; sasoa na bisa kahèi &lt;mai nèti ca bèka dhimu&gt;. Ngara leo nèti <span class="Italic">Sinear</span>, na, &lt;Babel&gt;.<bt>&lt;Went to the east&gt;, in the Ibrani language can also mean &lt;come from the east&gt;. Another name for <span class="Italic">Sinear</span>, is &lt;Babel&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00638c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3-4" />Rèngu aa'i-aa'i rare lii èci, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'ari, ee! Mai ta patitu kota kapai aae cue. Ti tao hadhu bata; ti tunu pa'adhu. Èèna na, èdhi pudhi sa dedha, ho ti tape dènge èi dama. Ho èèna na, ti patitu manara dedha aae èci, dhu kolo nèngu na d'ai dedha-liru, sèna ka èdhi abhu kolongara kapai. Ho sèna ka èdhi j'aj'i ca kabarai aae, dhu pahag'a ia ka.&gt;&gt;<bt>They all came to an agreement, saying, &lt;&lt;Elder-younger siblings! Let's build a huge city. We'll make brick rocks; we'll bake them hard. Then we'll stack them up, so we'll stick them together with tar/varnish/damar liquid/asphalt. So then, we'll build a very tall tower (loan), whose peak reaches the sky, so the we can get a great name/reputation. So that we-inc can become a great populace, which is no longer separated out/divided up.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tape = tempel, lem"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">tape = tempel, lem</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="reʕehu (reaʕ): their friends, compatriots, people"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">reʕehu (reaʕ): their friends, compatriots, people like them havah (yhb cohortative plural): come on = "let's do something"<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>nilbənah (nlb cohortative plural): let's mold bricks (mix mud and chopped up straw and put it into rectangular molds and let it dry in the sun. Then they stack them up along with a lot of firewood inside a big brick building with a rounded roof and a hole in the top, and light the firewood. The heat makes the bricks hard enough to last hundreds of years, so they can be used for large scale building just like stone blocks.) ləveniym: bricks<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>vnisrəfah: let's burn them thoroughly (fire them inside a kiln, not just bake them in the sun -- the kind of hard brick that sugar mill smokestacks are made of) sərefah: place of burning, brick kiln<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>chemar: bitumen, a natural derivation of crude petroleum that leaked out of the ground (that's where the Iraq oil fields are today) chomer: mortar for buildings<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>migdal: tower; watch tower, temple tower, fortress tower pen-nafuts: in order not to scatter (could be from pressure by enemies, or from not having a home base)<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>nafuts (pwts qal 1pl): we be scattered</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia LAMATUA puru mai laladhe kota dènge manara dhu ra patitu èèna.<bt>Then the LORD descended to have a look at the city and its tower that they were building.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bney haʔadam: the sons of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bney haʔadam: the sons of the earth, the sons of Adam; humans, the people doing the building as distinct from God</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ka Na peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu rai-haha se, aa'i-aa'i ra ca kabarai, dènge lii èci di. Ngaa dhu rèngu tao ne, heka mulai kèna. Bèli-camèd'a ladhe rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i mi èci sèmi ne'e, èèna na, ngaa dhu rèngu neo tao, j'aj'i aa'i mèu-mèu.<bt>Then He spoke saying, &lt;&lt;All these people are one race/populace, and they use just one language. What they are doing here now, is just the beginning. In the future (doublet: tomorrow-next day), if they are all united as they are now, then whatever they want to do, will all happen.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lkhullam: for all of them chillam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">lkhullam: for all of them chillam (chll hif inf): their beginning<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>yibtsar: will be impossible yazmu (zmm impf): they plan to do<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />De be'a risi, Èdhi puru lati ho tao lii si baka-leo, ho sèna ka èci ne'a boe lii èci.&gt;&gt;<bt>So it would be best if We-inc go down to make their language chaotic/confused, so that one doesn't understand the other.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nirdah (yrd cohortative): let's go down."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nirdah (yrd cohortative): let's go down. Plural of majesty, as in 1:6? nivlah (bll impf): moisten with oil, pour oil, we will mix up, confuse, shake up<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Hèia Lamatua puru, ka kakeho lii ra. Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, Na pacèri si palème rai-haha ne. Ka ra pakèd'i taruu heka kota deo na.<bt>So God2 descended, and confused (?) their language. In that way, He separated them from each other all over the earth. And they no longer kept building that aforementioned city.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayafets (pwts hif): he made them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayafets (pwts hif): he made them scatter, disperse (the very thing they did not want to do) vayachdəlu (chdl event + inf): they stopped building (should this be said first? They gave up on the town and moved out all over the world.)<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Nèti èèna ka, ra pangare kota na, <span class="Italic">Babel</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;pab'ingu&gt;), lula LAMATUA kakeho lii ra, aa pacèri eele si palème rai-haha ne.<bt>That is why they named that city, <span class="Italic">Babel</span> (which means &lt;cause confusion&gt;), because the LORD made their language chaotic, and he scattered them all over the world.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakèdi = dirikan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pakèdi = dirikan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="həfiytsam (pwts hif0: he scattered them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">həfiytsam (pwts hif0: he scattered them End of P section.<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>exchange w/consultant: [MC] He did a good job, didnʔt He? [JEG] Job security for linguists.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Nèti ana-èpu Sem, toke d'ai Abram<bt>From the descendants of Sem until Abram</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Se'e se, ana-èpu Sem. Ropa èle èi aae lala dua tèu sa, Sem mamuri cangasu tèu kèna, ka na abhu ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Arpaksad.<bt>These are Sem's descendants. When the big flood had stopped for two years, Sem had lived 100 years, and he had a son, named Arpaksad.</bt><v n="11" />Ka Sem mamuri hari d'ai 500 (lèmi ngasu) tèu, na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>And Sem still lived another 500 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Lod'o umur Arpaksad d'ai 35 (tèlu nguru lèmi) tèu, na abhu ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Sela.<bt>When the age of Arpaksad was 35 years old, he had a son, named Sela.</bt><v n="13" />Ka Arpaksad mamuri hari d'ai 403 (èpa ngasu tèlu) tèu, na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>And Arpaksad still lived another 403 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Lod'o umur Sela d'ai 30 (tèlu nguru) tèu, na abhu ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Eber.<bt>When the age of Sela was 30 years old, he had a son, named Eber.</bt><v n="15" />Ka Sela mamuri hari d'ai 403 (èpa ngasu tèlu) tèu, na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>And Sela still lived another 403 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Lod'o umur Eber d'ai 34 (tèlu nguru èpa) tèu, na abhu ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Pelek.<bt>When the age of Eber was 34 years old, he had a son, named Pelek.</bt><v n="17" />Ka Eber mamuri era d'ai 430 (èpa ngasu tèlu nguru) tèu, na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>And Eber still lived another 430 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Lod'o umur Pelek d'ai 30 (tèlu nguru) tèu, na matana ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Rehu.<bt>When the age of Pelek was 30 years old, he had a son, named Rehu.</bt><v n="19" />Ka Pelek mamuri era d'ai 209 (dua ngasu ceo) tèu, na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>And Pelek still lived another 209 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Lod'o umur Rehu d'ai 32 (tèlu nguru dua) tèu, na abhu ana mone èci, ngara na Seruk.<bt>When the age of Rehu was 32 years old, he had a son, named Seruk.</bt><v n="21" />Ka Rehu mamuri era d'ai 207 (dua ngasu pidhu) tèu, na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>And Rehu still lived another 207 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Lod'o umur Seruk d'ai 30 (tèlu nguru) tèu, na matana ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Nahor.<bt>When the age of Seruk was 30 years old, he begat a son, named Nahor.</bt><v n="23" />Ka Seruk mamuri era d'ai 200 (dua ngasu) tèu, ka na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>And Seruk still lived another 200 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Lod'o umur Nahor d'ai 29 (dua nguru ceo) tèu, na abhu ana mone èci, ngara na Tera.<bt>When the age of Nahor was 29 years old, he had a son, named Tera.</bt><v n="25" />Ka Nahor mamuri era d'ai 119 (cangasu canguru ceo) tèu, ka na abhu hari ana mone dènge ana bhèni.<bt>And Nahor still lived another 119 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Lod'o umur Tera d'ai pidhu nguru tèu risi, na abhu ana mone, dhèu tèlu: Abram, Nahor, dènge Haran.<bt>When the age of Tera was over 70 years old, he had three sons: Abram, Nahor, and Haran.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-èpu Tera<bt>Tera's descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ana-èpu Tera, sèmi ne'e: ana mone na, ka: Abram, Nahor, dènge Haran. Haran abhu ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Lot.<bt>The descendants of Tera were like this. His sons were: Abram, Nahor, and Haran. Haran had a son, named Lot.</bt><v n="28" />Haran madhe ètu rae èta-èsu na, ngara na Ur, rai dhèu Kasdim. Lod'o èèna, ama na Tera mamuri era.<bt>Haran died in the village of his origins, named Ur in the land of the Kasdim people. At that time, his father Tera was still alive.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yamat: he died moladto: his family|i(28)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yamat: he died moladto: his family<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>ʔur: Usually taken as the city of Ur in southern Mesopotamia, a cultural center. But because Abram was a nomad and lived in tents, some scholars feel there must be another Ur in northern Mesopotamia, probably not too far from Haran. Nobody is sure. kasdiym: Chaldeans<span class="Italic">(28)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Abram madhèdi dènge Sarai. Nahor leo dènge ana bhèni Haran, ngara na Milka. Haran abhu ana mone èci kahèi, ngara na Yiska.<bt>Abram married1 Sarai. Nahor married2 Haran's daughter, named Milka. Haran also had a son, named Yiska.</bt><v n="30" />Te ngaa Sarai dènge boe ana.<bt>But Sarai was barren, (&lt;without children).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕəqarah: sterile, barren"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕəqarah: sterile, barren</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ca tèka, Tera nèti ana na Abram, dènge Sarai dhèu èmu Abram, dènge èpu na Lot, lasi tèke eele rae Ur, neo lasi asa rai Kana'an. Te ngaa lasi d'ai rae Haran, rèngu pea ka ètu èèna.<bt>One time, Tera took his child Abram, and Sarai, Abram's spouse, and his grandchild Lot, going leaving behind the village of Ur, wanting to go to the land of Kana'an. But going until arriving at the village of Haran, they stayed there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalato: his daughter in law: a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">kalato: his daughter in law: a woman who is first under control of her father, then of her husband and her father-in-law (as her father's representative) yetsʔu (ntsʔ): they went out<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Tera madhe ètu èèna, dènge umur na 205 (dua ngasu lèmi) tèu.<bt>Tera died there, with his age 205 years.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua pili nare Abram<bt>God chooses Abram</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="12" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o èèna, LAMATUA peka le dènge Abram, peka na, &lt;&lt;Abram! Èu pakèd'i nèti era èu ne, tèke eele ina-ama èu, èmu ina-ama mu, dènge rae-lesa èu. Lamu asa era èci, dhu pe Ja'a peka dènge èu.<bt>At that time, the LORD had spoken to Abram, saying, &lt;&lt;Abram! You will leave your place there, leave behind your mother-father, your mother-father's house, and your village + villagers. Go to a place which I will later tell you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rae-lesa = isi kampung @@KM also"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">rae-lesa = isi kampung @@KM also</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meʔartskha: from your land (probably your"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">meʔartskha: from your land (probably your native land, not your piece of property) moladtkha: your relatives<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>beyt avikha: your father's household ʔarʔekha (rʔh hif): I will show you<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="2" />Èèna na, Ja'a hia mèngi-nale mi èu.<bt>Later, I will give blessings to you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa ana-èpu èu, èèna na, bèba-kacanga,<bt>And your descendants will increase in number,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">j'aj'i suku dhu kapai, toke dhèu tadhe kolongara èu.<bt>becoming a great tribe, to the point that people know your-sg name/reputation.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ho bèli-camèd'a, èu j'aj'i berkat hia dhèu leo kahèi.<bt>So in the future, you will be/become a blessing2 to other people as well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔəvarkhah: and I will bestow on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔəvarkhah: and I will bestow on you the power for success, prosperity, fertility (= I will bless you) həyeh: you are to be<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>bərakhah: blessing</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />Èèna na, Ja'a hia berkat mi dhèu dhu hia berkat mi èu.<bt>Then I will give blessing2 to people who give blessing2 to you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te ngaa Ja'a huku dhèu cee dhu dhoo èu.<bt>But I will punish whoever curses you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nanene paie!<bt>Listen carefully! [NOTE: Why this transition? See Hamilton "The grand finale in this catalogue of blessings and promises is: (so that) by you all the earth's clans shall be blessed. Again, the syntax of this passage helps isolate this climactic phrase. This unit began with an imperative, continued with a number of first singular imperfects (punctuated with an imperative that has imperfective force), and now climaxes with a perfect (niþrƒ±û)...."]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Pe èèna na, dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne abhu berkat lula èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>In the future, all the people on the earth will get blessing2 because of you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔəvarəkhah (brk piʕel): I will bless"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔəvarəkhah (brk piʕel): I will bless məvarkheykha (brk piʕel partcpl): the one who blesses you<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>mqallelkha (qll piʕel partcpl): the one who curses you ʔaʔor (ʔrr piel): I will inflict with a curse<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>nivrəkhu bəkha (brk nif passive): they will be blessed in their relationship to you, through you. (The nifʕal inflection here has also been taken as equivalent to a hitpaʕel "they will bless themselves, consider themselves fortunate") mishpəchot: clans, lineages<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4-5" />Lod'o èèna, umur Abram 75 (pidhu nguru lèmi) tèu. Na nèti dhèu èmu na Sarai, aa dènge ana ari na, Lot, dènge mèdha-panyau ra aa'i-aa'i, aa dènge dhèu sab'a na aa'i-aa'i dhu na abhu ètu kota Haran. Hèia Abram si lasi ka, tèke eele kota Haran, asa era dhu LAMATUA peka le dènge ne. Ka ra kako taruu, d'ai rai èci, ngara na Kana'an.<bt>At that time, Abram's age was 75 years. He took his spouse Sarai, and the child of his younger-sibling, Lot, and all their possessions, and all their workers which they got in the city of Haran. Then Abram mob went, leaving behind the city of Haran, toward the place which the LORD had told him. And they continued on, until arriving at a land/region/country named Kana'an.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tseʔto (ntsʔ inf): at his departure"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tseʔto (ntsʔ inf): at his departure rəkhusham: their property<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>rakhashu: they had accumulated, gathered nefesh: company of people<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />D'ai era èèna, Abram kako palème rai ne, toke d'ai padètu dènge rae èci, ngara na Sikem. Ka ra pea taha ètu èèna, padètu dènge aj'u aae ca kapua ètu More. Lod'o èèna, dhèu Kana'an dhu pea ètu èèna era.<bt>Arriving at that place, Abram went all through the land, until arriving near a village named Sikem. And they stayed temporarily there, near a large tree at More. At that time, the people of Kana'an were living there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məqom: place, spot ʔelon: oak tree"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">məqom: place, spot ʔelon: oak tree FF 154, 155, 183, Quercus coccifera or Quercus aegilops, or perhaps terebinth (turpentine tree), Pistacia terebinthus. The main point is that it was a prominent tree used for worship.<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʔaz: then, earlier. The Canaan people were already living around Shekem when Abram showed up. Moreh: may come from "teacher" or "oracle," related also to Torah ʔinstructionʔ; so possibly it's a site where people would come to consult the gods, like Delphi in Greece.<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>HCE “Da Canaan peopo dat live ova dea awready stay go Moreh, fo find out wat dea gods like dem fo do.” [MC] Do you think there will be "static" at having this spelled out? I notice "The Message" here has only "the Oak of Moreh", whereas later on, Peterson renders "sex-and-religion places". [JEG] Here neither sex nor sacrifice is in focus, but divination. And it's the place where Abraham is given the kind of information that others would pay a diviner big bucks for. This all depends on how descriptive the term "Moreh" is, which nobody knows for sure.</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ètu era èèna ka, LAMATUA pad'elo iisi Na mi Abram, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èèna na, Ja'a hia ana-èpu èu rai ne'e ne.&gt;&gt; Ka Abram pudhi hadhu tao mei korban hia LAMATUA dhu pad'elo iisi Na dènge nèngu ètu era èèna.<bt>In that place, the LORD revealed himself to Abram, saying, &lt;&lt;Later I will give your descendants this land.&gt;&gt; And Abram stacked rocks making a table for sacrifice to the LORD, who revealed himself to him in that place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeraʔ (rʔh nif): allowed Abram to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yeraʔ (rʔh nif): allowed Abram to see him nirʔeh (rʔh nif partcpl): who allowed Abram to see him.<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>exchange w/consultant: [MC] How does "let Abram see him" fit with "no man has seen God at any time"? [JEG] This isn't a textual or a translation problem; it's a theologiansʔ problem. There are numerous places where Yahweh "appears" to somebody, using the same type of verb: the elders of Israel, for example, or Isaiah. But none of the passages where the verb is used in this way actually say what God looked like. They tell what they saw in his vicinity: a colored pavement, his train filled the Temple. The theologians have concluded that God let them see that it was him there, but no details. Others, like Abram and Gideon, saw a stranger and deduced from what the stranger said and did that it was God in disguise.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00640c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Abram mangaj'i mi Ama Lamatua<bt>Abram worships God</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Èle èèna ka, Abram si pidha hari asa ledhe re balèu. Ka ra pea taha ètu talora rae Betel dènge rae Ai. Ètu èèna, na patitu mei korban èci ho na mangaj'i mi LAMATUA.<bt>After that, Abram mob moved again to a mountain to the south. And they stayed temporarily between the village of Betel and the village of Ai. There he erected a table for sacrifice, to worship the LORD.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="beyt-ʔel: House of God, named that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">beyt-ʔel: House of God, named that later by Jacob yaʕteq: (ʕtq hif): moved on<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>yeT (nTh imperf): spread out, pitched a tent ʔhlh (ktiv) ʔohelah (qereʔ): tent<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>yiqraʔ bəshem yʔ: invoked the name of Yahweh, summoned Yahweh shem: name as standing, reputation, renown (make a name for oneself), fame<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Èle èèna ka, na pidha-pidha era, d'ai rai Negeb re ca bèka balèu nèti rai Kana'an.<bt>After that, he kept moving location, until he came to the land of Negeb on the southern side of the land of Kanaan.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiSSaʕ (nSʕ qal): depart halok: continuation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiSSaʕ (nSʕ qal): depart halok: continuation and progress of the action, journeyed further and further south, bit by bit<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>naSoaʕ: making his way negbah: to the Negev, the desert in the south of Israel<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abram la'e asa rai Masir<bt>Abram goes to the land of Masir [Egypt]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ca tèka, rai Kana'an lèke manganga aae. Nèti èèna ka, Abram si lasi asa bèka balèu, ka ra d'ai rai Masir. Ka ra manubha taha ètu nèi.<bt>One time, the land of Kana'an experienced great hunger/famine. Because of that, Abram mob went to the south, and they arrived at the land of Masir. And they stayed there temporarily (on land belonging to others).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʕav: famine lagur (gwr): live for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">raʕav: famine lagur (gwr): live for a limited time as an alien<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>khaved: heavy</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Ropa oe d'ai Masir, Abram peka dènge dhèu èmu na, Sarai, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sarai, èu bhèni iia, nia boe.<bt>When they were about to arrive in Masir, Abram spoke to his spouse, Sarai, saying, &lt;&lt;Sarai, you are female-beautiful, excessively so.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hiqriyv (qrb hif): he drew near"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hiqriyv (qrb hif): he drew near yəfat marʔeh: beautiful to look at<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />De ladhe dhèu Masir rèdhi èu bhèni iia sèmi ne'e, mage dhoka ra pamadhe ja'a, lula ja'a dhèu èmu-kamali èu. Dènge sèmi èèna, ra parame rare èu.<bt>So if Masir people see your beauty like this, they will probably just kill me, because I am your spouse. In that way they will snatch you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəchayyu (chyh piʕel): they will let"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yəchayyu (chyh piʕel): they will let you stay alive, keep you alive</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />De be'a risi, èu peka dènge ra, na ja'a ne, ana mone èu. Dènge sèmi èèna ka, rèngu pamadhe boe ja'a, aa ra be'a-be'a dènge ja'a, lula èu ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>So it would be better, that you tell them that I am your brother. In that way, they won't kill me, and they will treat me well, because of you. &gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔimriy: tell lmaʕan: in order that,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔimriy: tell lmaʕan: in order that, so that<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>yiyTav-liy: it will turn out well for me ʕəvurek: for the sake of you<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>chaytah nafshiy: my soul will live, I will stay alive biglalek: on account of you<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00646c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Sarai ètu èmu dhèu aae Masir<bt>Sarai in the house of the Masir king</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ropa Abram si d'ai Masir, dhèu ètu èèna, ladhe laa na, Sarai ne bhèni iia titu kèna.<bt>When Abram mob arrived in Masir, people there saw that Sarai was very female-pretty.</bt><v n="15" />Ropa dhèu sab'a dhèu aae sèra ladhe rèdhi ne, aa ra koa bhabhèni iia na ètu madha dhèu aae. Ka rèti bhèni ne, asa èmu dhèu aae.<bt>When the workers of the king saw her, they kept praising the woman's beauty in front of the king. Then they brought that woman to the king's house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sarey: officers of yəhaləlu: they praised|i(15)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">sarey: officers of yəhaləlu: they praised<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>tuqakh: she got taken as a wife</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Hèia dhèu aae be'a-be'a ka dènge Abram, lula Sarai. Ka na parasee Abram mèdha rupa-rupa. Nuka badha sèmi: kahib'i-kalèbho, kahib'i-ka'ia, sapi, keled'ei, dènge onta. Na parasee kahèi, ènu dhèu mone dènge dhèu bhèni.<bt>Then the king treated Abram well, because of Sarai. And he presented (assim. loan) Abram with various sorts of gifts. That is animals like: goat-sheep, goat-goat, cow, donkey (loan), and camel (loan). He also gave gifts of male and female slaves.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parasee = parsen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">parasee = parsen</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heyTiyv (yTb hif): do well, treat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">heyTiyv (yTb hif): do well, treat well baʕəvurah: on account of her<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>chəmoriym: donkeys ʔətonot: female donkeys<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>gmalim: one-humped camel, Camelus Dromedarius (FF 13, 14). Some scholars thought there were no camels in Egypt in Abraham's time, but later research by Free showed camel figurines and pictures from before Abraham's time. Camels originated east of Palestine, but they got around because they were important for carrying things to sell. shfachot: female servants or slaves<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Lula na nare dhèu èmu dhèu asa d'ara èmu na, nèti èèna ka, LAMATUA hia huku rupa-rupa mi dhèu aae dènge isi èmu na.<bt>Because he had taken another person's spouse into his house, that is why the LORD gave various sorts of punishment to the king and his household.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaynagaʕ (piʕel) ngaʕim gdolim: afflicted them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vaynagaʕ (piʕel) ngaʕim gdolim: afflicted them with severe sicknesses (ngʕ touch)</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Hèia dhèu aae Masir paroa Abram, ka na karèi ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne tao tasamia mi ja'a ne? Nga tao ka èu peka boe na, bhèni ne dhèu èmu èu?<bt>Then the king of Masir summoned Abram, and asked him, saying, &lt;&lt;What have you done to me? Why didn't you tell me that this woman is your spouse?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="higdəta (ngd hif): you did not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">higdəta (ngd hif): you did not put forward the information, speak out</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Te ngaa aku èu na, nèngu ne ana hèni èu! Nèti èèna ka, ja'a oe kore ne j'aj'i dhèu èmu ja'a! Dhèu èmu èu ka ne'e! More hari ka, aa pakaj'èu ka nèti madha ja'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>But you said, she in your sister! Therefore I nearly took her to be my spouse! Here is your spouse! Take her back, and distance yourself from before me!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔamarta: you have been saying"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔamarta: you have been saying</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Hèia dhèu aae paredha dhèu sab'a na sèra, babège eele Abram, dhèu èmu na, rèti dènge dhèu aa mèdha-panyau aa'i-aa'i ra, kalua nèti rai èèna.<bt>Then the king commanded his workers to evict Abram, his spouse, taking all his people and possession, out from that land/country.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yətsaw (tswh piʕel): order someone to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yətsaw (tswh piʕel): order someone to do something yəshalkhu: they escorted them out, went with them to the border, sent them away<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abram dènge Lot pacèri<bt>Abram and Lot separate</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="13" />
      <v n="1" />Ka Abram si tèke eele Masir, lasi asa rai Negeb. La'e dènge dhèu èmu na, aa dènge dhèu aa mèdha-panyau aa'i-aa'i ra. Ana ari na Lot madhutu ra kahèi.<bt>Then Abram mob left Masir, going to the land of Negeb. He went with his spouse, and all his people and possessions. The child of his younger-sibling Lot also followed/accompanied them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaʕal (ʕlh): went up (always used"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yaʕal (ʕlh): went up (always used for going from Egypt to Palestine; the reverse route is always ʔwent downʔ) kaved: rich<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>miqneh: possessions, especially livestock</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Abram èèna, kaja ae titu kèna. Badha-manu na, mèdha hualaa dènge mèdha hualaa-pudhi na, ae titu kèna.<bt>Abram was extremely wealthy. His animals, his gold things and silver things, were many.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Nèti Negeb, ra pidha-pidha era, ka d'ai hari talora rae Betel dènge rae Ai. Dhu uru èèna, ra pea rèdhi le ètu era èèna.<bt>From Negeb, they kept moving on, and arrived again between the village of Betel and the village of Ai. Previously, they had lived in that place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yelekh (hlk): he went here and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yelekh (hlk): he went here and there lmaSSaʕayw: in his daily breaking of camp, by a series of daytime marches<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>təchillah: the beginning</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Aa dhu Abram patitu le kahèi mei korban, ho na mangaj'i mi LAMATUA ètu era èèna.<bt>And Abram had also erected a table for sacrifice, so he could worship the LORD in that place.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Lot dhu madhutu Abram èèna, unu badha-manu dènge dhèu sab'a ae kahèi.<bt>Lot, who accompanied Abram, also owned many animals and workers.</bt><v n="6-7" />Te ngaa era èèna taleo boe, ho Abram dènge Lot aa dènge kakaja ra bisa pea pa'èci. Nèti èèna ka, ana madhenge badha Abram dènge Lot sèra j'aj'i patao-palaha, lula j'u'u ètu era èèna d'ai boe hia badha rèngu. (Lod'o èèna, dhèu Kana'an dènge dhèu Feris, dhu pea ètu èèna era.)<bt>But that place wasn't wide enough, for Abram and Lot and their wealth to lived together.Because of that, Abram and Lot's herders began to argue/dispute (doublet), because grass in that place wasn't enough for their animals. (At that time, the Kanaan people and the Feris people were still living there.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nasaʔ: fit, get enough room lashevet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nasaʔ: fit, get enough room lashevet (yshb inf): to live<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>yachdaw: together rəkhusham: their property<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>vayhi riv ben roʕe miqneh-Avram uben roʕe miqneh-LoT: a dispute arose between the herders of the herds of Abram and the herders of the herds of Lot riyv: quarrel, dispute, with lots of words<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>haknaʕəni: the Cannanite haprizzi: the Perizzite<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʔaz: then yoshev: living<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00647c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Abram dènge Lot pabagi era<bt>Abram and Lot divide up the place</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ka Abram peka dènge Lot, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èdhi se, pa'a'ari. Mage dhoka èdhi, èci dènge èci be'a boe, lula dhèu sab'a èdhi se patao-palaha taruu.<bt>And Abram spoke with Lot, saying, &lt;&lt;We-inc here are family (reciprocally-elder-younger-sibling). May it not be that we become not good (relationships) with each other, because our workers are continually arguing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təhiy (hyh): for there to be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">təhiy (hyh): for there to be məriyvah: quarrel<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />De hua iia dua ti pahag'a ka laa. Rai ne, taleo. De ladhe èu d'èi rai ca bèka kariu na, ja'a abhu re ca bèka g'ana. Te ngaa ladhe èu d'èi re ca bèka g'ana, na ja'a re ca bèka kariu.&gt;&gt;<bt>So it would be good if the two of us go separate ways. This land is broad. So if you-sg want the land on the left side, I will get it on the right side. But if you want it on the right side, then I on the left side.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'abhu hui"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pa'abhu hui</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="həloʔ: isn't it true that ...?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">həloʔ: isn't it true that ...? hippared (prd hif): let's split up<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>smoʔl: the left side ʔeyminah (ymn cohortative): let me go to the right<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>yamiyn: right side, south ʔasməʔiylah: let me go to the left<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Hèia Lot ladhe palème. Ka na ladhe nèdhi rai taleo ètu sebhe loko Yarden dhu madha èi ae, toke d'ai rae Soar. Era ne, rai hèu mèngi sama sèmi oka LAMATUA, dènge rai Masir kahèi. (Lod'o èèna, LAMATUA dhae huku mèka kota Sodom dènge kota Gomora. De rai èèna, be'a era.)<bt>So then Lot looked all around. And he saw the wide land beside the Yarden river which had many springs, up until the village of Soar. This place, was fertile land like the garden of the LORD, and also the land of Masir. (At that time, the LORD had not yet punished the city of Sodom and the city of Gomora. So that land was still good.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yissaʔ (nsʔ): lift up his eyes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yissaʔ (nsʔ): lift up his eyes kikkar: disk-shaped pita bread, lead disk, talent (75-lb disk of gold or silver used for money), circuit, the environs (on all sides)<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>mashqeh: well irrigated shachet (shcht piʕel): destroy<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>boʔəkhah (bwʔ inf): as you go</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Hèia Lot pili nare era sebhe loko Yarden èèna. Ka dua ra pahag'e ka. De Lot la'e sa ca bèka dhimu.<bt>So Lot chose that place along the edge of the Yarden river. And the two of them went separate ways. So Lot went to the eastern side.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yivchar l-: he chose yiSSaʕ (nSʕ):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yivchar l-: he chose yiSSaʕ (nSʕ): pull out, depart, pull up stakes<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>miqqedem: eastward (min from, but here a general adverbial; Lot was on the west bank of the Jordan at the time) yippardu (prd nif): they separated, they were separated<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʔachiyw: his brother</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Te ngaa Abram pea taruu ètu rai Kana'an. Aa Lot la'e pea ètu rae-rae dhu padètu dènge kota Sodom ètu sebhe loko Yarden.<bt>But Abram continued living in the land of Kana'an. And Lot went to live in the villages near the city of Sodom along the edge of the Yarden river.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kikkar: district yeʔəhal: he pitched his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">kikkar: district yeʔəhal: he pitched his tent<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ʕad: off in the direction of</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Te ngaa dhèu-dhèu Sodom sèra bhelu-katub'a titu kèna. Rèngu ro'o boe nanene LAMATUA.<bt>But the people of Sodom were extremely evil. They didn't want to listen to/obey the LORD.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʕim: bad quality, disagreeable, unwholesome, of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">raʕim: bad quality, disagreeable, unwholesome, of no value, contemptible, evil, morally depraved, vicious, harmful chaTTaʔim: inclined to sin, fallible, sinners, with faults<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ropa Lot pacèri dènge Abram, ka LAMATUA padhai lii dènge Abram, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu ladhe palème aa'i ku, rai aa'i-aa'i nèti era titu èu èèna. Ladhe paie re madha, re kabodho, re ca bèka g'ana, dènge ca bèka kariu mu.<bt>When Lot separated from Abram, the LORD spoke with Abram, saying, &lt;&lt;Look all around you, at all the land/country from the place you are standing on. Look/inspect carefully in front, behind, to the right side, and to your left side.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="saʔ naʔ ʕeyneykha (nsʔ imperv): lift"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">saʔ naʔ ʕeyneykha (nsʔ imperv): lift up your eyes, look around tsafonah: to the north<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>yammah: to the west, toward the sea (makai)</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Rai aa'i-aa'i dhu èu ladhe mèdhi sèi, bèli-camèd'a Ja'a hia mi èu, dènge ana-èpu èu, sèna ka j'aj'i pusaka ra, toke d'ai mia-mia.<bt>All the land that you see yonder, in the future (doublet) I will give to you, and to your descendants, so that it is their inheritance (loan), forever.</bt><v n="16" />Èèna na Ja'a paj'aj'i ana-èpu èu ae sama sèmi salae dhasi, toke dhèu ige rare boe.<bt>I will make your descendants to be many like the sand of the sea, to the point that people cannot count them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="samti: I will put kaʕəfar haʔarets:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">samti: I will put kaʕəfar haʔarets: like the dry, fine particles of dirt, dust<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>limnot (mnh inf): count yimmaneh (mnh nif): be counted, be open to counting<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="17" />De lamu kako palème madhutu madhera dènge bhabhèla na. Te rai se aa'i-aa'i ra, Ja'a hia mi èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>So you walk all around according to the length and width of it. Cuz this entire land I am/will give to you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhabhèla = lebar (n)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">bhabhèla = lebar (n)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qum (imperv): stand up, get going"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">qum (imperv): stand up, get going hithallekh (hlk hitp): go around here and there<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʔarkah: the length of it rachbah: the breadth of it<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Hèia Abram si lèpa hari asa era pea ra, dhu dètu dènge aj'u-aj'u aae ètu Mamre, dhu padètu dènge Hebron. Èle èèna ka, na pudhi hadhu tao mei korban ho na mangaj'i LAMATUA ètu èèna.<bt>Then Abram mob returned to their living place near the big trees at Mamre, which is near Hebron. After that, he stacked rocks to make a table for sacrifice so he could worship the LORD there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeloney: oaks of mamreʔ: name of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔeloney: oaks of mamreʔ: name of an Amorite, in 14:13<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>End of P section</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abram la'e parame nare Lot nèti kacui-aai musu<bt>Abram goes to retrieve Lot from a war situation</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="14" />
      <v n="1" />Tèu èèna, dhèu aae èpa dhu pa'èci. Rèngu se ka: Amrafel, dhèu aae rai Sinear. Ariok, dhèu aae rai Elasar, Kedarlaomer, dhèu aae rai Elam. Dènge Tideal, dhèu aae rai Goyim.<bt>At that time, there were four rajas who were joined/united/allied. These were: Amrafel, the king of the land/country of Sinear. Ariok, the king of the land/country of Elasar. Kedarlaomar, the king of the land/country of Elam. And Tideal, the king of the land/country of Goyim.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="goyim: nations, nonspecific. Later it came"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">goyim: nations, nonspecific. Later it came to mean "Gentile nations," not Jews, but in Genesis 12:2 God tells Abram "I will make you become a great nation (goy)," showing that it has a general meaning. "Goyim," which is simply transliterated in some translations, is not a place name or a people name as far as we know. But to render it as nonspecific "King over some nations whose names I canʔt remember but it doesn't matter" makes good sense. UBS says "Tidal is the name of several Hittite kings, but the narrator does not associate the name with the Hittites. King of Goyim means ʕʕking of nationsʔʔ and may be an honorific title," which is another possibility, but to push it would result in a more complex rendering for a very minor identification.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu aae leo dhèu lèmi, pa'èci kahèi. Nuka: Bera, dhèu aae rai Sodom. Birsa, dhèu aae rai Gomora. Sinab, dhèu aae rai Adema. Semeber, dhèu aae rai Seboim. Dènge Bela, dhèu aae rai Soar. Ka èpa dhèu aae se, lasi pamusu dènge lèmi dhèu aae sèra.<bt>At that time, there were also five other kings who gathered. They were: Bera, the king of the land/country of Sodom. Birsa, the king of the land/country of Gomora. Sinab, the king of the land/country of Adema. Semeber, the king of the land/country of Seboim. And Bela, the king of the land/country of Soar. Then the four kings went to war against the other five kings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="milkhamah: crowding, shoving; scuffle, combat, war"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">milkhamah: crowding, shoving; scuffle, combat, war</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Dhèu aae, dhèu lèmi sèra pakaboko dènge sordad'u ra, ètu d'ara mamoo Sidim, (dhu limuri ne, ngara na Dhasi Madhe).<bt>The five kings gathered with their armies/soldiers in the valley/wilderness of Sidim, (which now they call the Dead Sea).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mananga = air laut naik (pasang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">mananga = air laut naik (pasang besar), dgn airnya kering sendiri</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />J'aj'aj'i pamusu na, sèmi ne'e ka: Uru èèna, dhèu aae, dhèu lèmi se dhu ta'alo mi dhèu aae Kedarlaomer, canguru dua tèu kèna. Te d'ai tèu ka canguru tèlu, ka rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra lab'a ne.<bt>The cause (&lt; nominalizing reduplication of "become") of that war is like this: Previously the five kings had lost/paid homage to king Kedarlaomer for 12 years. But in the 13th year, all of them opposed him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ta'alo ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">ta'alo =</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chavru: join forces ʕemeq: valley|i(4) (4)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">chavru: join forces ʕemeq: valley<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yam hammelach: the Salty Lake, known now as the Dead Sea, but it has land all around it, and you can see from one side to the other. maradu: they revolted politically, rebelled<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ka maso tèu ka canguru èpa, Kedarlaomer dènge angalai na dhèu aae dhèu tèlu sera, mai dènge sordad'u ra. Hèia ra pamusu ka, ka ra segi pèri-pèri rai. Nuka: dhèu Refaim ètu rai Asterot-Karnaim; dhèu Susim ètu rai Ham; dhèu Emim ètu rai Sawe-Kiryataim,<bt>Upon entering into the 14th year, Kedarlaomer and his three king friends, came with their armies. And they warred and they beat several lands/countries/states. They were: the Refaim people the land/country of Asterot-Karnaim, the Susim people of the land/country of Ham, the Emim people of the land/country of Sawe-Kiryataim,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaku (nkh hif): strike"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yaku (nkh hif): strike</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />dènge dhèu Hori dhu ètu ledhe Seir, d'ai sebhe mamoo El Paran.<bt>and the Hori people who are at the Seir mountain until to the edge of the wilderness of El Paran.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="harəram: their mountains hammidbar: area not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">harəram: their mountains hammidbar: area not cultivated, wilderness, range pasture<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Èle èèna ka, ra lèpa hari asa En Mispat (dhu limuri ne ngara na Kades). Ka ra segi rai dhèu Amalek, dènge dhèu Amori dhu pea ètu rae Haseson-Tamar.<bt>Afterwards, they returned again to En Mispat (which now is named Kades). Then they destroyed the land/country of the Amalek people, and the Amori people who live in the village/region of Haseson-Tamar.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayashuvu (shwv): motion back in the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayashuvu (shwv): motion back in the direction of their point of departure</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8-9" />Hèia, lèmi dhèu aae se ator sordad'u ra ètu d'ara mamoo Sidim, ka lasi pamusu dènge dhèu aae dhèu èpa sèra.<bt>So then, the five kings organised their soldiers in the valley of Sidim, and they went warring against those four kings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yetseʔ (ntsʔ imperf): go out vayaʕarkhu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yetseʔ (ntsʔ imperf): go out vayaʕarkhu: set in rows, draw up in battle order, form up<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>milchamah: battle</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ètu d'ara mamoo èèna, dhu abhu mananga èi dama pèri-pèri. Ropa ra pamusu, dhèu aae Sodom dènge dhèu aae Gomora dènge sordad'u ra, rai. Ka cahag'e manahu asa d'ara mananga èi dama se. Aa cahag'e hari rai asa ledhe lasi.<bt>In that valley, there were several pools of tar/asphalt/varnish/damar sap. When they were warring, the king of Sodom and the king of Gomora with their soldiers, ran. And some fell into the tar pools. And others ran on to the mountains.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="beʔərot: holes, wells, openings chemar: bitumen,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">beʔərot: holes, wells, openings chemar: bitumen, tar, like asphalt<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>yanuSu (nwS): they fled, escaped, slipped away yiplu: they fell (could also mean ʔcast themselvesʔ, like to hide, but they could have slipped or tripped just as well)<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>shammah: into there (the tar pits). The implication is that they died. nishʔariym (shʔr nif partcpl pl): the ones that remained. It's possible to read the text in such a way that the two kings of Sodom and Gomorrah are the only ones that fall into the tar pits, and everybody else runs for the mountains, but it can also be taken that some of the soldiers fell in and some got away.<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Ka èpa dhèu aae dhu segi se, lasi parame rèti mèdha-panyau dènge nganga'a-nginu nèti Sodom dènge Gomora. Èèna ka, ra lèpa dènge ka.<bt>And the four kings who won, went and snatched up the belongings and the food-drink of Sodom and Gomora. Then they went home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èi dama = tar, asphalt (itam)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">èi dama = tar, asphalt (itam)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rəkhush: property yelekhu (hlk): they continued"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">rəkhush: property yelekhu (hlk): they continued on their way<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Te ngaa Lot, ana ari Abram, dhu pea ètu Sodom. Ka èpa dhèu aae sèra, ère rèti Lot si, dènge mèdha-panyau ra aa'i-aa'i.<bt>But Lot, Abram's yB child, lived in Sodom. And those four kings captured Lot mob, and all their belongings.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Te ngaa dhèu èci rai nèti era èèna. Ka la'e lolo dènge Abram, dhèu Ibrani èèna. (Lod'o èèna, dhèu Amori èci, ngara na Mamre. Aa Abram pea dètu dènge aj'u-aj'u aae unu Mamre. A'ari Mamre dhèu dua, ngara na Eskol dènge Aner. Rèngu se dhu pa'anga dènge Abram.)<bt>But one person ran from that place. He went and reported to Abram, the Ibrani person. (At that time, there was an Amori person, named Mamre. And Abram lived near the big trees owned by Mamre. Mamre had two siblings, named Eskol and Aner. The were mutual-friends of Abram.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="palit: fugitive who had escaped from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">palit: fugitive who had escaped from the invading army shokhen (partcpl): had settled, was living<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ʔəchiy: brother of, kinsman of baʕle bərit: partners in an agreement<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>exchange w/consultant: [MC] Is this the first occurrence of the word "Hebrew" in the Bible? Do you want a footnote re. it means the same as Jewish people? ; [JEG] "Jew" doesn't figure until after the split kingdom or even the Exile. Most references are to "Israel." Abraham isn't referred to as a Jew in the Torah. ʕivriy means from an ethnic group whose story involves crossing a piece of land or a river (ʕbr), like "Abraham the Transient." Weʔre in the mental world of 2000 BC.</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Ropa Abram tadèngi na dhèu kèpe rèti le Lot, ana ari na, ka Abram pakaboko nare dhèu-dhèu sab'a na dhu re'a pamusu. Aa'i-aa'i ra 318 (tèlu ngasu canguru aru) dhèu. Ka lasi magèla èpa dhèu aae sèra, asa badae aae lasi d'ai rae Dan.<bt>When Abram heard that people had captured Lot, the child of his younger-sibling, Abram gathered up his workers who were skilled at war. All of them were 318 people. And they went pursuing those four kings, to the north until the village of Dan.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Te ngaa mamalo ka, = but"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">Te ngaa mamalo ka, = but fortunately ; pa'anga = sekutu, allie</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishmaʕ: he heard, he learned, he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yishmaʕ: he heard, he learned, he found out nishbah (nif): had been captured<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>yareq (ryq hif): he led out, emptied out; called out all of them chnikhav (singular): his followers, vassals. May be related to chnk "train" as in Prov 22:8, which also means "dedicate a house or an altar"<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ylidey: born (singular) shmonah: eight<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>beyto: as part of his household, in his camp; homeborn slaves, children of his servants vayirdof (rdf): set off after them to catch up with them, hostile; set out in pursuit<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ètu era èèna, Abram hag'e dhèu na sèra, mi pèri-pèri kaboko. D'ara mèda èèna kahèi, lasi age si, dènge j'ara pa'oke. Ka Abram si lasi bate dhèu se d'ai rae Hoba, ètu bèka badae kota Damsik.<bt>In that place, Abram divided his people into several groups. That same night, they went and attacked them from various directions. And Abram mob went chasing these people as far as the village of Hoba, to the north of the city of Damsik.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yechaleq (nif): they split up, divided"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yechaleq (nif): they split up, divided themselves (singular) yakem: they struck them<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>smoʔl: left side - north?</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Hèia Abram abhu hari Lot, dènge dhèu-dhèu nèngu, aa dènge mèdha-panyau ra aa'i-aa'i. Na abhu kahèi dhèu-dhèu leo.<bt>So Abram was able to get Lot back, with his people and all their belongings. And he got other people as well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bate = kejar ; age ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">bate = kejar ; age = serang, serbu (lit. overcome, mengatasi) ; lasi pa'oke = kepung, dari berbagai jurusan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeshev (shwb hif imperf): brought back"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yeshev (shwb hif imperf): brought back heshiyv (shwb hif): bring back people and things as booty<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Melkisedek la'e paraga dènge Abram. Nèngu ne, ca dhèu dhèu aae aa ama agama kahèi<bt>Melkisedek, a person who is both a king and a religious head, goes to meet with Abram</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ropa Abram segi nare dhèu aae èpa sèra, ka na lèpa. Hèia dhèu aae Sodom mai soru ne ètu d'ara mamoo Sawe (dhu dhèu biasa peka na, Mamoo Dhèu Aae).<bt>When Abram beat the four kings, he went home. Then the king of Sodom came to greet him in the valley/wilderness of Sawe (which people normally call the Valley of Kings).</bt><v n="18" />Tèu èèna, Melkisedek, j'aj'i dhèu aae kota Salem.<bt>At that time, Melkisedek, was king of the city of Salem.</bt><note reference="14:18" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Abhu dhèu d'èlu-mèu cahag'e peka na, ngara Salem dènge ngara Yerusalem èèna, kota èci di.<bt>There are some knowledgeable people who say that the name Salem and the name Yerusalem are the same city.</bt></note>Aa nèngu ne j'aj'i kahèi ama agama nèti Ama Lamatua dhu Dedha Risi Eele. Na mai soru Abram, nèti roti dènge èi hua anggor.<bt>And he was also religious head for God who was Most High. He came to greet Abram, bringing bread and juice/wine from the anggor fruit.</bt><v n="19-20" />Ka na padhai lii ho hia berkat mi Abram, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a sanao sèna ka Ama Lamatua, dhu Dedha Risi Eele èèna, dhu paj'aj'i dedha-liru dènge rai-haha ne, hia mèngi-nale mi dedha èu. Koa-kio Ama Lamatua dhu hia le èu segi musu.&gt;&gt;<bt>And he spoke to give blessing2 to Abram, saying, &lt;&lt;I hope that God, who is Most High, who created heaven and earth, will give blessings1 to you. Praise (doublet) to God who made/had/allowed you to beat your enemies.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəvarkhehu: he blessed qoneh (partcpl): creator,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yəvarkhehu: he blessed qoneh (partcpl): creator, or possibly purchaser<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Èle èèna ka, Abram bagi hia Melkisedek ca pala nèti canguru pala mèdha-panyau dhu na abhu hari sèra.<bt>After that, Abram divided to Melkisedek one part from ten parts of the belongings which he had gotten back.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hia, bagi canguru nèti ngaa-ngaa dhu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">hia, bagi canguru nèti ngaa-ngaa dhu ...</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miggen (piʕel): delivered tsareykha: your oppressor,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">miggen (piʕel): delivered tsareykha: your oppressor, adversary, enemy (tsar narrow, distress, dread)<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Hèia dhèu aae Sodom èèna pahaha iisi na mi Abram, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama. Mèdha-panyau dhu èu abhu hari nèti musu ja'a sèra, hud'i laa ama ku abhu aa'i si. Te ngaa dhu ja'a manèngi hari, dhoka dhèu-dhèu ja'a sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the king of Sodom bowed/paid respect to Abram, saying, &lt;&lt;Father. The belongings that you have gotten back from my enemies, it's fine if you get/keep them all. But I only ask that you return my people.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Hèia Abram b'ala ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a subha ètu madha Ama Lamatua dhu Dedha Risi Eele, dhu tao dedha-liru dènge rai-haha,<bt>Then Abram replied saying, &lt;&lt;I oath-swear before God who is Most High, who made heaven and earth,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hərimoti yadi (rwm hif pf): I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hərimoti yadi (rwm hif pf): I have lifted up my hand (= sworn)? I hereby swear? UBS likes the immediate form, but the perfective aspect of the verb makes it sound more like he had already made up his mind and sworn his oath. NIV, RSV, and NLT translate it as perfective; the discussion in UBS makes it sound like a defense of the TEV. Waltke and OʔConnor, however, give four other examples of what they call the "instantaneous perfective" for a situation occurring at the very instant of speaking or making a gesture associated with speaking, in Deut 26:3, 2 Sam 17:11, 2 Sam 19:30, and Psalms 143:6.</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />na, ja'a kore boe mèdha-panyau èu, masi ka ciki èèna ka. Masi ka loa hèngu ca'èta sa, ja'a kore boe. Dènge j'ara sèmi ne'e, èu baku peka na, &lt;Kakaja Abram sèra mai nèti ja'a.&gt;<bt>that I will not take your belongings, not even one tiny bit of them. Even a length of thread, I will not take. In that way, you can't say, &lt;Abram's wealth came from me.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="michuT: thread, cord, thin rope heʕəsharti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">michuT: thread, cord, thin rope heʕəsharti (hif): I made him rich<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Ja'a parluu boe ngaa-ngaa. Dhoka mia dhu dhèu ja'a se pake le, sèra èle le, ale ia ka. Aa hud'i laa, angalai ja'a dhèu tèlu se: Aner, Eskol dènge Mamre, hag'e rare unu rèngu di.&gt;&gt;<bt>I don't need anything. Only whatever my people have already used, they are gone, so don't mention them anymore. And let my companions, these three people: Aner, Eskol, and Mamre, select out their share.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bilʕaday: without me, not involving me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bilʕaday: without me, not involving me raq: only<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>cheleq: part, portion End of S section<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua pajaji dènge Abram<bt>God's mutual-promise with Abram</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="15" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna ka, LAMATUA pad'elo iisi Na mi Abram. Ka Na peka, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Abram! Èu baku madha'u. Lula Ja'a ka dhu j'aj'i mi tami ho bhiri èu nèti musu. Aa Ja'a hia a'oto mi dedha èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, the LORD revealed himself to Abram. And He spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Abram! You must not be afraid. Because I am the one who is the shield that protects you from your enemies. And I give advantage/reward to you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tami = pele (not widely known)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">tami = pele (not widely known) ; pa'abhe ; biri = pele ;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hadvarim haʔeleh: these things (chapter 14)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hadvarim haʔeleh: these things (chapter 14) bamakhzeh: in the vision (seeing as a seer sees, not a regular dream)<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>magen: shield, metaphor for protection or refuge skarkha: your wages, your reward; also expenses, maintenance, fare for Jonah's boat trip<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>harbeh (rbh hif inf): to make you great</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2-3" />Te ngaa, aku Abram na, &lt;&lt;Masi ka Ama Lamatua hia ae-ae èèna ka, j'aj'i boe mi ngaa sa èci. Lula ja'a ne dènge boe ana matana, ho hia ja'a ana-èpu. De dhu neo unu ae-ae sèmi èèna, tao mi ngaa? Neu-neu ka, noto mi ènu ja'a Elieser, dhèu Damsik èèna. Nèngu ka dhu sèmi nare aa'i-aa'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Abram said, &lt;&lt;Even though God gives so much to me, it doesn't amount to anything. Because I have no birth child to give me descendants. So, to receive so many possessions like that, what's the point? At the very best, it will fall to my slave Eliasar, that Damsik person. He is the one who will receive it all.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Neu-neu ka = paling-paling, kalo-kalo ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">Neu-neu ka = paling-paling, kalo-kalo ; noto = jato ke</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mah titten liy: ʔwhat are you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mah titten liy: ʔwhat are you going to give me?ʔ is not a question about how much Abraham will inherit, but a rhetorical question ʔwhat of significance could you possibly give me? I am already rich but I donʔt have any heirs to pass it on to.ʔ holek: I will go my way = die<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>ʔəriyriy: alone, in solitude (no children) ben mesheq beyti: unexplained. Son of the possessions of my house = my sole heir? Pun on Dammeseq "Damascus"? Servant born in my household?<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>ben-beyti: son of my house, servant born to my retinue? yoresh (partcpl): stands to inherit, be the heir<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="Hk-old\Hk059a.jpg" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Te ngaa LAMATUA dhaa na, &lt;&lt;J'ara na sèmi boe èèna! Ana d'èlu èu ku, dhu unu pusaka sèra. Ènu èu abhu boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the LORD responded, &lt;&lt;That's not the way it is! Your own birth child is the one who will get that inheritance. Your slave will not get it.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hineh: stresses the following word yiyrashkha:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hineh: stresses the following word yiyrashkha: will be your heir<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>meʕeykha: inside your body, as seat of the origin of man</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia nèti Abram asa li'u, ka Na peka, &lt;&lt;Èu ladhe ku asa dedha-liru nèi. Ladhe paie ku hua-hètu sèi. Bisa iga more, do aad'o? Bèli-camèd'a, ana-èpu èu sama sèmi hua-hètu sèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he took Abram outside, and said, &lt;&lt;You look up yonder into the sky. Look carefully at those stars yonder. Can you count them, or not? In the future, your descendants will be the same as those stars yonder!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="night time; the sacrifice was next"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">night time; the sacrifice was next afternoon. habeT-naʔ (nbT hif imperv): look!<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ka Abram sèmi nare lii padhai LAMATUA. Aa LAMATUA tadhe ne, dhèu mola, lula Abram lèka Ne.<bt>So Abram accepted what the LORD said, and the LORD was recognised him as a straight/righteous person, because Abram *believed Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="counted as righteous /tadhe Abram sèmi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">counted as righteous /tadhe Abram sèmi dhèu mola/; fixed KM also</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vheʔmin (hif ʔmn): trust someone, rely"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vheʔmin (hif ʔmn): trust someone, rely upon, treat someone as reliable vayakhshəveah: valued that (feminine) for him, reckoned; have an opinion with regard to someone or something: consider, count as<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>tsdaqah: in this case, Abram has a good relationship with God; also can refer the behavior which God expects man to show to God, blameless behavior, honesty, justice "do da right ting"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Èle èèna ka, LAMATUA tuhu hari lii Na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, Ama Lamatua. Ja'a ka dhu lere kèti èu nèti rae Ur, ètu rai dhèu Kasdim sèra. Aa rai ne'e ne, Ja'a hia èu, sèna ka j'aj'i pusaka mu.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, the LORD continued speaking, &lt;&lt;I am God. I am the one who led you out from the village of Ur, in the land of the Kasdim people. And this land here, I give to you, so that it is your inheritance.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasdiym: Chaldean people lərishtah: to inherit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">kasdiym: Chaldean people lərishtah: to inherit it, possess it<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa Abram karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia, LAMATUA? Dènge j'ara sa mia ka ho ja'a ke'a na, rai ne j'aj'i pusaka ja'a?&gt;&gt;<bt>But Abram asked, saying, &lt;&lt;How it that, LORD? How can I know that this land will become my inheritance?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔadonai yahweh: to be read as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔadonai yahweh: to be read as ʔadonai ʔelohim, rather than as ʔadonai ʔadonai, because of the pointing</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ka Na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Mai ti tao madha j'ara èci, dhu pa'èki lii padhai lii Ja'a deo na. De lamu more sapi rena ci'u, kahib'i rena ci'u, dènge kahib'i-kalèbho mone ci'u. Aa'i-aa'i sèra hud'i dhu umur tèlu tèu. Aa mèti kahèi koro iia ci'u, dènge koro j'aha ci'u.&gt;&gt;<bt>And He responded, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this! Let's make a ceremony, to bind what I have said just-now. So you go get one female cow, one female goat, and one male sheep. They must all be three years old. And you also get one turtledove, and one dove [both confirmed by bird book].&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕeglah: young cow məshulleshet (puʕal particpl):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕeglah: young cow məshulleshet (puʕal particpl): three years old<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>ʕez: female goat ʔayil: male sheep<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>tor: dove, Columba livia or Turtur communis, Streptopelia turtur gozal: baby bird (turtledove, eagle)<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>Habərit ben habaturim: the covenant between the pieces (Hebrew title)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ka Abram la'e nare badha sèra. Hèia na kacèb'e bagi mi dua, sapi, kahib'i, dènge kahib'i-kalèbho sèra. Ka na pale sisi se mi rai, dhu èci patangara dènge èci, j'aj'i mi dua b'aris. Te ngaa na kacèb'e boe manu-bhui sèra.<bt>So Abram went and got those animals. Then he split them in two pieces, the cow, the goat, and the sheep. And he divided out the meat on the ground, one facing the other, becoming two lines (loan). But did not split the birds.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəvatter (piʕel): cut in pieces. Jeremiah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yəvatter (piʕel): cut in pieces. Jeremiah 34:17ff describes a similar ceremony to finalize an agreement. He cut them down the spine, not with the head in one piece and the tail in the other. ʔish bitro: each one of them (animate) put his part. Sounds like God put his pieces in one row, Abram in another; but it's probably Abram putting each half animal opposite the other half of the same animal, like two rows.<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>liqraʔt: opposing sides reʕehu: their counterparts<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Ka manu-bhui dhu tema ra'a sisi sèra, mai ho neo ra'a sisi se'e. Te ngaa Abram bhabhoo eele si.<bt>The birds that normally eat meat, alighted on the meat wanting to eat it. But Abram shooed them away.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kacèb'e = belah (tubuh hewan) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">kacèb'e = belah (tubuh hewan) ; sèg'i = belah (batang kayu), atau belah untuk kasi keluar perut ; paloko = kasi kumpul ; pale = divide up many pieces</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayered: whenever they came down NJB"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayered: whenever they came down NJB ʕayiT: birds of prey (SK mentioned crows, then vultures)<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>hapgarim: carcasses yashshev (nshb hif): drive away<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ropa lod'o cèna, Abram bhèj'i luu. Na nii, kuri na maroga mai sarimu nare nèngu, ka na madha'u titu kèna.<bt>When the sun set, Abram slept soundly. He dreamt as if darkness came and blanketed/covered him, and he was terrified.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kuri = sepertinya"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">kuri = sepertinya</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Late afternoon, toward the end of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Late afternoon, toward the end of the full day after the nite time remark about the stars laboʔ (inf): going (down)<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>tardemah: not regular sleep, but a deep sleep or a trance. Same word used when God anesthetized Adam to make Eve. Groggy, couldnʔt make out what was happening. ʔeymah: terror, dread<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>chəshekhah: absence of daylight ʔeymah chəshekah gədolah: N N A, horror of great darkness (does gdolah go with ʔemah too, or just with chshekah? One Jewish commentator thinks chshekah is a gloss on ʔeymah, but with no textual or exegetical basis. great dark dread, dark fear<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13-15" />Ka Ama Lamatua peka dènge ne,<bt>Then God spoke to him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Abram! Èèna na èu mamuri toke heka bhoro, aa madhe dènge be'a, ka ra padhane èu dènge be'a.<bt>&lt;&lt;Abram! You will live until you are very old, but will die in peace, and they will bury you properly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heka bhoro = tua kakalok"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">heka bhoro = tua kakalok</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te ngaa ana-èpu èu, èèna na j'aj'i dhèu tao mai ètu kabarai dhèu.<bt>But your descendants will become immigrants in other people's country.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu tao mai = pendatang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">dhèu tao mai = pendatang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ho èèna na, dhèu isi rai sèra, tao si sèmi ènu sa, ka ra ènyi aa paj'èra si, toke èpa ngasu tèu.<bt>Then the people from that land/country will make/treat them like slaves, and they will oppress and cause them suffering, for 400 years.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ènyi = tekan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">ènyi = tekan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te, ladhe èèna na, Ja'a huku si.<bt>But later I will punish them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ho èèna na, Ja'a kèti hari ana-èpu èu nèti era èèna, aa dènge mèdha-panyau ra ae-ae.<bt>And I will bring back your descendants from that place, and they will bring lots of belongings.</bt><note reference="15:13-15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 7:6-7</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="16" />Aa èèna na, Ja'a ator ho ana-èpu èu dhu ka lèmi kèti hari si asa ne'e mai.<bt>I will arrange it so your fifth descendants will return home to this place.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Limuri ne, dhèu Amori dhu pea ètu rai ne'e. Dhèu se'e dhèu bhelu, te ngaa dhae bhelu iia mèka.<bt>Now, the Amori people are living in this land. These people are evil people, but they are not yet truly/fully evil.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ladhe ana-èpu èu sèra lèpa hari asa era ne'e, Ja'a neo pake si ho huku palaho dhèu Amori sèra. Lula d'ai taa èèna, bhabhelu ra asa hino.&gt;&gt;<bt>When your descendants come back to this place, I am going to use them to punish destroying those Amori people. Because when that time arrives, their evil will be increasingly savage/ferocious.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dowr: generation, span of time. Some"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">dowr: generation, span of time. Some commentators suggest "century," which would fit the context. rəviyʕiy: fourth<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>hennah: they, fem (dowr is masculine - why?) shalem: complete, finished up, rounded out<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>ʕəwon: transgression, sin; guilt (caused by sin); punishment (for guilt) ʔəmoriy: can be generic for any inhabitant of Canaan<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ropa d'ai mèda sa, cag'ag'a laa ètu era èèna, abhu èru rai èci dhu sèb'u poka-poka, dènge badhu ai èci dhu heo, kako re sasanga sisi dua baris se.<bt>When it was dark, suddenly in that place, there was a smoking clay pot, and a flaming torch, moving by in between the two lines of meat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕəlaTah: darkness tanur: fire-pot, furnace, oven;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕəlaTah: darkness tanur: fire-pot, furnace, oven; portable brazier or pan full of coals<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʕashan: ascending smoke lapiyd: torch<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>gəzarim: the two rows of pieces of animals that were sacrificed. Custom for ratifying a covenant</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Lod'o èèna, LAMATUA pa'èki lii pajaji dènge Abram. Na peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a jaji mema èu kèna, bèli-camèd'a Ja'a pangèd'u mi ana-èpu èu rai ne'e ne, mulai nèti loko Masir,<bt>At that time, the LORD bound promise with Abram. He said, &lt;&lt;I truly promise you, I will entrust to your descendants this land, beginning from the Masir river,</bt><note reference="15:18" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Loko Masir èèna, ele boe ka loko Misraim ètu Sinai, do ele boe kahèi kacanga nèti loko Nil re bèka dhimu.<bt>That Masir river, could be the Misraim river/stream in Sinai, or it could also be the eastern branch of the Nil river.</bt></note>d'ai loko Efrat,<bt>until the Efrat river,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karat brit: make a covenant by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">karat brit: make a covenant by cutting up a sacrificial animal nahar: watercourse that always has water in it<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>nahar mitsrayim: "river of Egypt," referred to also in Numbers 34:5 and Joshua 15:4 and 47, is probably the Wadi ʔArish in the eastern Sinai, which is a "nahal" ʔbrookʔ, not a "nahar" like the Euphrates because it doesn't have water in it all the time. pərat: Euphrates<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19" />dènge rai dhèu Keni, dhèu Kenas, dhèu Kadmon,<bt>with the land of the people of Keni, the people of Kenas, the people of Kadmon,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔet X ʔet Y ... are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔet X ʔet Y ... are objects of "give" in 18.</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />dhèu Het, dhèu Feris, dhèu Refaim,<bt>the people of Het, the people of Feris, the people of Refaim,</bt><v n="21" />dhèu Amori, dhèu Kana'an, dhèu Girgasi, dènge dhèu Yebus.&gt;&gt;<bt>the people of Amori, the people of Kana'an, the people of Girgasi, and the people of Yebus.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rao = tungku ; pareuk ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">rao = tungku ; pareuk = periuk ; tape = form clay (verb) ; rai tapa èru = tana liat ; badhu ai = obor</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Hagar dènge ana na Ismael<bt>Hagar and her child Ismael</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="16" />
      <v n="1-3" />Tèu èèna, Abram lèpa hari le nèti Masir, ka na pea le canguru tèu ètu Kana'an. Dhèu èmu na Sarai abhu mèka kolo. Sarai dènge ènu bhèni ca dhèu nèti Masir, ngara na Hagar.<bt>At that time, Abram had returned from Masir, and had lived ten years in Kana'an. His spouse Sarai, di not yet have [any] children (Idiom: had no tip). Sarai had a female slave from Masir, named Hagar.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="noun phrase beginning the chapter: new"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">noun phrase beginning the chapter: new scene lo: children for Abram, not children in general<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>shifchah: female slave, maidservant. How important is the fact that Hagar had no say in what went on?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ca lod'o, Sarai peka dènge Abram, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'a. LAMATUA hia boe ja'a ana. De hua iia, lamu j'unu dènge ènu ja'a, Hagar, sèna ka na hia ja'a ana.&gt;&gt;<bt>One day, Sarai was talking with Abram, saying &lt;&lt;Older-brother! The LORD has not given me children. So it would be good if you go and sleep with my servant Hagar, so she can give me children.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕətsarani miledet: he has held me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕətsarani miledet: he has held me back from giving birth ʔulai: perhaps, in the sense of hope, entreaty, or fear<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʔibbaneh (nif): I will be built = I will live on in a child from here. Pun on "ben"? miminah (min + 3sgf): from Hagar<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>Calvin, "the deadliness of interpretation." They didnʔt just trust God; they figured they needed to do something that he wasnʔt doing.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Abram madhutu lii dhèu èmu na. Ka Sarai hia Hagar j'aj'i dhèu èmu ka dua Abram.<bt>Then Abram followed what his spouse had said. So Sarai gave Hagar to become Abram's second spouse.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miqets: at the end of ten"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">miqets: at the end of ten years of Avram living ... ləshevet (yshb inf): of living<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>titen: Sarai give Hagar to Abram. That makes sure Hagar's status stays low. If Abram had married Hagar as a regular wife, Sarai would have had no more leverage. ʔishshah: wife, not pilgash "concubine." Gen 25:6.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Hèia Abram j'unu dènge Hagar, ka na dènge babia. Ropa Hagar ne'a nèngu dènge babia le, ka na padedha iisi na, aa na pahae heka Sarai.<bt>So then Abram slept with Hagar, and she became pregnant. When Hagar knew she was pregnant, she became arrogant, and no longer valued/respected Sarai.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabake aae = bunting (manusia, kasar)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">kabake aae = bunting (manusia, kasar) ; kahadhu = bunting (binatang) ; pahae = hargai</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatahar (hrh): she became pregnant vateqal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vatahar (hrh): she became pregnant vateqal (qll): she came to esteem her lightly. Probably not outright contempt, more like putting on airs. QLL covers quite a range.<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00644c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ka Sarai peka dènge Abram, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ka dhu hia nèngu mi èu j'aj'i dhèu èmu ka dua. Te ngaa ropa na dènge babia, na pusi pahae heka ja'a! Ne'e ne, sala èu! De hud'i laa, sèna ka LAMATUA ka dhu pama'ète lii èdhi dua ti! Heka èu me'a kèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Sarai spoke to Abram, saying, &lt;&lt;I'm the one who gave her to be your younger spouse. But as soon as the woman knows that she's pregnant, she shows contempt for me. This is all your fault! May the LORD decide this dispute between the two of us-inc. Then you'll know! [lang of threat]&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="/kabake aae/ (kasar)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">/kabake aae/ (kasar)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chəmaSi ʕalekha: this evil action on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">chəmaSi ʕalekha: this evil action on me is upon you, your fault becheyqekha: in your embrace, the area where two people touch when they are hugging sexually<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>tereʔ: she sees ʔeqal (qll qal): I am lightly esteemed in her eyes<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>yishpoT: will judge, will decide</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ka Abram dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e, wee! Èu ne, dhèu èmu uru. Aa nèngu, dhèu èmu limuri. De èu ne dhu mèd'u paredha. De èu neo tao ne tasamia, èèna ètu èu na!&gt;&gt; Ka Sarai mulai tao sakaa hua dènge Hagar, hèia na rai.<bt>And Abram responded, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this, wee! You are the first/prior spouse. And she is the behind spouse. So you are the one who holds rule. So whatever you want to do to her, that's up to you!&gt;&gt; And Sarai began to be regularly cruel to Hagar, so she ran off.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ej'a = angkat kaki, berangkat ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">ej'a = angkat kaki, berangkat = pakèdi ; sakaa hua = selalu kasar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Abram is not taking sides. He"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Abram is not taking sides. He cops out. ʕəsiy (ʕsh imperv)<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>təʕaneah (piʕel): she humiliated her, made her feel dependent, oppressed. The mistreatment is psychological, not physically beating her up tov bəʕenekah: no norm. Used in Judges for every person doing whatever "was right in their own eyes." Not "use your best judgment."<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Na rai d'ai d'ara mamoo. Hèia ana pajuu LAMATUA nèti sorga ca dhèu, rage ne dètu dènge madha èi, ètu j'ara la'e asa Sur.<bt>She ran to the wilderness/empty place. And an *angel of the LORD from heaven encountered her near a spring on/at/by the road to Sur.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayimtsaʔah: find, doesn't imply that she"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayimtsaʔah: find, doesn't imply that she was lost, only that he met her there. It can imply that he went looking for her. angel of the Lord: angel who was the Lord (in theophanies)?<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>ʕal: facing, over against, off from, down from. The spring wasnʔt right on the trail, but you could see the trail from there exchange w/consultant: [MC] Now this parenthesis IS important! ; [JEG] Some contain major content as here, some are merely helpful. Very few are really irrelevant. The true identity of the angel comes out only in 10 and 13, and saying "one angel messenja guy from the Boss#" (a possible reading of the Hebrew) guarantees that most readers will miss the identity, because the person who sends a message is not often the messenger and "from" confirms it, so Verse 10 will seem out of kilter.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ka na lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne Hagar, ènu Sarai. Nga tao ka èu ètu ne'e? Èu mai nèti mia, aa lamu mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>And s/he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;You are Hagar, Sarai's slave! Why are you here? Where are you coming from, and where are you going?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Hagar dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a rai nèti d'ara èmu lamatua ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Hagar answered, saying, &lt;&lt;I ran away from the house of my mistress/lord.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔey-mizzeh: where from this? ʔanah: where|i(8)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔey-mizzeh: where from this? ʔanah: where<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>telekhiy: are you going (what's the -iy?) mifne: from the presence of Sarai, not just "from Sarai"<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>borachat (partcpl fem): running away</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ka ana pajuu èèna pamako ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Be'a risi, èu lèpa hari asa adhe-aai Sarai, lamatua èu. Masi ka na tao èu tasamia èèna ka, sèmi la.<bt>So the angel coaxed her, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this! It's best if you go home to the hand of Sarai, your mistress. Whatever (+however) she does to you, just accept it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hitʕani (ʕnh hitp): humble yourself under"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hitʕani (ʕnh hitp): humble yourself under her hand/domination. This verse was cited by slaveholders in the U.S. around 1850 as proof that slavery was ordained by God.</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Baku madha'u. Bèli-camèd'a, Ja'a pabèba ana-èpu èu pa'ae-ae, toke dhèu ige rare boe.<bt>Don't be afraid. I will make your descendants many, to-point-that people will not be able to count them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="harbah ʔarbeh (rbh hif inf abs):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">harbah ʔarbeh (rbh hif inf abs): I will make you many vloʔ yiSSafer (nif): be counted<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>merov: innumerable malʔakh yhwh: the angel turns out to be the Lord; note first person. So it's more "an angel who was the Lord" than it is "an angel of the Lord." Ambiguous reading.<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Èu dhu dènge babia. Nèbhu heka, èu mora iisi ana mone ca dhèu. Èèna na mu pangare ne Ismael (dhu sasoa na &lt;Lamatua tadèngi&gt;), lula LAMATUA tadèngi le lii roma iisi èu.<bt>You are now pregnant. In a little while, you will give birth to a son. You must name him Ismael, (which means &lt;the Lord hears&gt;), because the LORD has heard your complaint.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕanyekh (ʕani, ʕnh): your miserable situation,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕanyekh (ʕani, ʕnh): your miserable situation, be bowed down (pun on "humble yourself" v. 9?), pitiful, dependent, humiliated, overwhelmed by want, poor, wretched</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ropa ana ne kapai, na mamuri pakaj'èu nèti a'ari na. Lula nèngu ne, sama sèmi jara hui dhu d'èi boe nanene lii paredha. Sad'i dhèu cee èèna ka, na sisu. Aa dhèu aa'i-aa'i lab'a ne kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>When the child grows up, he will live far from his relatives (=bad relationships). Because he is like a wild horse which does not want to listen/obey commands. Whoever it is, he opposes2. And everyone else also opposes him.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="adhe aai = tangan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">adhe aai = tangan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pereʔ: zebra, wild ass, onager. Syrian"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">pereʔ: zebra, wild ass, onager. Syrian onager, now extinct. Not a symbol of stubbornness, but a free spirit, unrestricted, untrammeled, because they live outside the normal human realm of domesticated animals [and people]: Psalm 104:11 the wild donkeys quench their thirst ... He promises Hagar that Ishmael will be independent and free, not a slave like her. Lines 2 and 3 probably an expository apposition (in what way is he going to be like a wild donkey?) [JEG] "Wild donkey" is the ground of comparison, not "donkey." Donkeys (Equus asinus) are the antithesis of outsiders; wild donkeys (Equus hemionus), as in Psalm 104:11, the epitome of animals that could adapt to human shelter and fodder but arenʔt about to buy into it. Changing the punctuation helps slightly. Pereʔ doesn't apply to domestic donkeys; all three of the species the word covers are a different species from the donkey. In Hawaiʕi we got cowboys before the Wild West had them because some cattle given as a gift to King Kamehameha I in the 1790s went wild in the Kamuela area and became a danger to everybody; but I donʔt think weʔve ever had Equus asinus go wild. (Kamehameha asked the Mexican government in California for vaqueros to train his guys, who started a subculture called Paniolo, from español, still going, that produced some world class cowboys.)<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>yishkon: he will settle down, live ʕal-pny: at odds, not "to the east of" as in some contexts<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>yishkon: will dwell, stay</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ropa tadèngi nare, Hagar ngee ka ètu d'ara na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a kèdhi le LAMATUA, dhu ladhe-leru aa madhenge ja'a.&gt;&gt; Hèia na hia ngara mi Lamatua, &lt;&lt;Lamatua dhu ladhe-leru ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>When she heard that, Hagar thought to herself, saying, &lt;&lt;I have seen the LORD, who watches over and guards me.&gt;&gt; Then she gave a name to the Lord, &lt;&lt;The Lord who watches over me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔatah: &quot;you&quot; is actually part of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔatah: "you" is actually part of the name she gives him. roʔi: may mean both I see God and he sees me.<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Nèti èèna ka, dhèu pangare madha èi na, <span class="Italic">Beer Lahai Roi,</span> dhu sasoa na &lt;&lt;Madha èi nèti Nèngu dhu mamuri, dhu ladhe-leru ja'a.&gt;&gt; Era na, ètu talora aae nèti rae Kades dènge rae Beret. Madha èi ne, abhu era toke d'ai sange ne'e.<bt>That is why people named that spring, <span class="Italic">Beer Lahai Roi,</span> which means, &lt;&lt;Spring from Him who lives, who cares for me.&gt;&gt; That place is in between the village of Kades and the village of Beret. That spring is still there to this day.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roʔi: again, nonspecific as to subject"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">roʔi: again, nonspecific as to subject "Well of the Living One [?] Seeing"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Èle èèna ka, Hagar lèpa hari. Hèia nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu. Abram pangare ne <span class="Italic">Ismael.</span><bt>After that, Hagar went back home. And she gave birth to a son. Abram named him <span class="Italic">Ismael.</span></bt><v n="16" />Lod'o Hagar nare iisi Ismael, umur Abram 86 (aru nguru èna) tèu kèna.<bt>When Hagar gave birth to Ismael, Abram's age was 86 years old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua pa'èki lii pajaji dènge Abram dènge tadha suna<bt>God binds a promise with Abram using/with the sign of *circumcision (loan for prudes)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="17" />
      <v n="1" />Ropa umur Abram d'ai 99 (ceo nguru ceo) tèu, LAMATUA mai pad'elo iisi dènge ne. Ka Na peka dènge Abram, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, Ama Lamatua dhu Koasa Risi Eele. Èu hud'i madhutu taruu dad'èi Ja'a, dènge j'ara mamuri èu hud'i mola.<bt>When Abram's age reached 99 years, the LORD revealed himself to him. And He spoke with Abram, saying, &lt;&lt;I here, am God who is Most Powerful. You must continue to follow/obey My will, and your life way must be straight/pure.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="13 years have passed since the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">13 years have passed since the Hagar incident. vayeraʔ ʔel-(nif): was seen, appeared to<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>shadai (shdd? devastate) hithallekh lfanay (hitp): go about in my presence; walk back and forth, move, walk constantly. Purposive holoholo. 1 Sam 2:21 has ʕim, but lifnay is a respectable variant.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>hyeh (imperv): be tamim: without blemish, blameless 5:22, 24; 6:9; 24:40; 48:15.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ja'a neo pa'èki lii pajaji dènge èu. Aa Ja'a neo pabèba kacanga ana-èpu èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>I am going to bind a promise with you. And I am going to (make) your descendants to be aduntant.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔetnah (ntn cohortative): I confirm, apply"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔetnah (ntn cohortative): I confirm, apply (not "make") ʔarbeh (rbh): I will make you (your line) many people<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>biməʔod məʔod: really a lot</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Hèia Abram patitu kètu urutuu, ka na pacud'u kètu d'ai rai. Ka Ama Lamatua tuhu hari lii padhai lii Na, aku Nèngu na,<bt>So Abram knelt, and bowed2 his head to the ground. And God continued speaking to him, saying.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayipol (qal): fall, bow down"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayipol (qal): fall, bow down</Message></Annotation><v n="4-5" />&lt;&lt;Lii pajaji Ja'a dènge èu sèmi ne'e ka: èèna na, èu j'aj'i bèi-baki nèti suku ae-ae. Nèti èèna ka, èu pake ia ka ngara èu <span class="Italic">Abram</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;ama dhu dhèu tadhe&gt;), te ngaa <span class="Italic">Abraham</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;bèi-baki nèti suku ae-ae&gt;).<bt>My promise with you is like this: Later you will become the ancestor for many tribes. Because of that, you will no longer use the name <span class="Italic">Abram</span> (which means &lt;father whom people know&gt;), but <span class="Italic">Abraham</span> (which means &lt;ancestor for many tribes&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔani hineh ... vʔatah (v. 9):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔani hineh ... vʔatah (v. 9): correlative and causal (Wenham); since my covenant is with you, I will do ... You, for your part, will do ... vhayita lʔav: you will become the father<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>həmon: crowd, big stack goyim: ethnic groups<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yiqqareʔ (nif): your name will not be called Abram ʕowd: still, continuation<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ʔavraham etymology? ʔAV-RAV-HMON? ʔAV-RAM-HMON from former name?</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ja'a neo pabèba kacanga ana-èpu èu ae-ae. Ja'a paj'aj'i si suku ae-ae. Aa Ja'a ded'e dhèu aae ae nèti rèngu sèra.<bt>I am going to cause your descendants to increase greatly. I will cause them to become many tribes. And I will elevate/appoint many kings from them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tanga-tanga = berlapis-lapis"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">tanga-tanga = berlapis-lapis</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hifreti (prh hif): I will make"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hifreti (prh hif): I will make fruitful yetseʔu (qal): will come out<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>Ishmael : Isaac :: Saul : David. The first one was not God's choice, but God allowed people to try their own ideas and made things come out his way anyway.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ja'a sanèd'e taruu lii pajaji Ja'a dènge èu, aa dènge ana-èpu èu sèra. Lii pajaji ne ma'ète boe toke taa-taa, lula Ja'a ne'e ka Ama Lamatua nèti èu dènge ana-èpu mu.<bt>I will always remember my promise with you, and with your descendants. This promise will not be broken/cease until forever, because I here am the God of/for you and your descendants.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lev 26 blessings &amp; curses. V."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Lev 26 blessings &amp; curses. V. 44, even with the curses, one thing remains: I am still their God. həqimoti (qwm hif): I am setting up<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>beni uvenekha uven zarʕəkha ʔachrekha: between me and you and your progeny after you. Removed the repetition of zrʕ. lədorotam (dor pl): in [each of] their generations, for generation after generation<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>librit ʕolam: as my perpetual contract with you</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Rai Kana'an ne aa'i-aa'i, bèli-camèd'a Ja'a hia mi èu dènge ana-èpu èu. Ne'e ne, èu dhoka pea manubha di ètu ne'e. Te ngaa èèna na, j'aj'i mi unu ana-èpu èu toke taa-taa. Aa Ja'a j'aj'i Ama Lamatua rèngu sèra kahèi.<bt>This entire land/country of Kana'an, in the future I will give to you and your descendants. Now, you are only staying here on other people's land. But in the future, it will become the property of your descendants until forever. And I will also be their God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔet ... ʔet: piling up accusatives."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔet ... ʔet: piling up accusatives. ʔerets məgurekha: the land where you have protected status as an alien<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>laʔchuzzat: as your property, your possession (not you and the Canaanites)</Message></Annotation><v n="9-10" />Te ngaa èu dènge ana-èpu èu sèra, hud'i kèpe pa'èra lii pajaji ne, dènge d'ara kateme ku. Dhèu mone aa'i-aa'i ra, hud'i suna ku.<bt>But you and your descendants, must hold firmly to this promise, with your whole(hearted) insides. All the males must get *circumcised (loan).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lədorotam: generation by generation himmol (mwl"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">lədorotam: generation by generation himmol (mwl nif inf abs): be circumcised<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11-13" />Ne'e ne, mone aa'i-aa'i hud'i suna, mulai nèti umur aru lod'o. A'ari èu, dhèu-dhèu sab'a èu, dènge ènu dhu èu hèli more nèti rai leo, aa'i-aa'i ra hud'i suna si. Suna na j'aj'i tadha mi ngi'u miu, dhu pa'èki èdhi taa-taa.<bt>Now, all males must get circumcised, beginning from age of eight days. Your relatives, your workers, and the slaves which you bought from other lands, must all be circumcised. That circumcision will be a sign on your bodies, which binds us-inc forever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nmaltem (nif): and you will be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nmaltem (nif): and you will be circumcised lʔot: as a distinguishing mark<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʕarlatkhem: the foreskin of their penis yimmol (mwl nif): be circumcised<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>lakhem: where does it connect? yəliyd: son, one born in the household<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>miqnat-kesef: a purchase involving money, purchased for money ben nekhar: from any foreigner who is not from your ohana<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Mone mia dhu suna boe, rèngu sèra maso boe ètu d'ara lii pajaji Ja'a ne, aa rèngu sèra j'aj'i boe dhèu Ja'a kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Whatever male is not circumcised, they will not/cannot enter into this promise of Mine, and they cannot become My people.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lai ana-lai èpu = turunan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">lai ana-lai èpu = turunan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕarel: foreskin, metonymy for an uncircumcised"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕarel: foreskin, metonymy for an uncircumcised person nikhrətah (krt nif): he is to be excluded from the community, rooted out, cut off<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʕammeyha: from its (fem) community hefar (prr hif): invalidate, put an end to, break, destroy<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>End of S section</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Èle èèna ka, Ama Lamatua peka hari, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nèti deo ne'e ne, èu paroa ia ka ngara dhèu èmu mu <span class="Italic">Sarai,</span> te ngaa <span class="Italic">Sara.</span><bt>After that, God spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;From now on, you will no longer call your spouse <span class="Italic">Sarai,</span> but <span class="Italic">Sara.</span></bt><v n="16" />Èèna na Ja'a hia mamèngi ae-ae mi Sara, sèna ka nara iisi hia èu, ana mone ca dhèu. Tare'a! Bèli-camèd'a, Sara j'aj'i bèi nèti suku ae-ae. Aa èèna na, Ja'a ded'e dhèu aae ae-ae nèti ana-èpu nèngu.&gt;&gt;<bt>I will give many blessings1 to Sara, so that she will bear you a son. That's right! In the future, Sara will become grandmother/ancestress to many tribes. And in the future, I will elevated many kings from her descendants.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Hèia Abraham patitu kètu urutuu ka pacud'u kètu d'ai rai. Te ngaa na mari ètu d'ara. Na pangee, na, &lt;&lt;Mone heka bhora dhu cangasu tèu sama sèmi ja'a ne, bisa abhu ana era? Aa Sara dhu heka gagoo-gagehu ne, dhu ceo nguru tèu kèna, nara iisi hari sa mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Abraham knelt and bowed to the ground. But, he laughed/smiled inside. He thought, &lt;&lt;A shrivelled old man who's 100 years old like me, can still have children? And Sara who's a 90 year old feeble old lady, how can she still give birth?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitschaq: he laughed blibo: in his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yitschaq: he laughed blibo: in his heart<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>halven: interrogative, to a son meʔah-shanah: 100 years<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>yiwwaled (nif imperf): will be born teled: she will have a baby<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ka na peka dènge Lamatua, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hud'i ka laa, Ismael ka dhu abhu pusaka ja'a èèna ka, ngaa-ngaa tao boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>So he spoke with the Lord, saying, &lt;&lt;Just let Ismael be the one who gets my inheritance, that'll be alright/it doesn't matter.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gagoo-gagehu = ganggok"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">gagoo-gagehu = ganggok</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lu: O that, I wish yichyeh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">lu: O that, I wish yichyeh lfanekha: he will live in your sight, your presence<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Te ngaa aku Ama Lamatua na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o sèmi èèna! Bèli-camèd'a, dhèu èmu mu Sara, nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu. Pangare ne <span class="Italic">Isak.</span> Lii jaji Ja'a ne, lèke mi nèngu dènge ana-èpu na toke mia-mia.<bt>But spoke God saying, &lt;&lt;It won't be like that! In the future, your spouse Sara, will give birth to a son. Call his name <span class="Italic">Isak.</span> This promise of mine, hits/affects him and his descendants forever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔəval: an interjection that introduces something"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔəval: an interjection that introduces something that will not please the hearer həqimotiy (qwm hif): I will set up<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ja'a tadèngi le ngaa dhu èu manèngi kahèi, hia Ismael. Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a hia berkat mi nèngu kahèi, aa hia ana-èpu na tabha ae. Bèli-camèd'a ana-èpu Ismael ne, j'aj'i mi canguru dua kapala suku. Aa ana-èpu na suku èci dhu kapai.<bt>I have heard what you were asking for Ismael. Because of that, I will give blessings to him as well, and cause his descendants to increase (in numbers). In the future, the descendants of Ismael, will become the heads of 12 tribes. And his descendants will be a great tribe.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hifreytiy (prh hif): I will make"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hifreytiy (prh hif): I will make him fruitful hirbeytiy (rbh hif): I will increase the number<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>nəsiʔim: minor kings, chiefs, leaders of lineages ntatiw lgoy gadol: and I will grant to him to be a great people<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Masi ka sèmi èèna, lii pajaji Ja'a ne, lèke dhoka mi ana mu Isak di. Tèu mai ni, hèru sèmi ne'e kahèi, Sara nara iisi le.&gt;&gt;<bt>Even that being the case, this promise of Mine, hits/affects only your child Isak. Next year, also in the month like this, Sara will have given birth.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔaqiym (qwm hif): I will set"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔaqiym (qwm hif): I will set up</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Ropa padhai lii nare, ka Ama Lamatua tèke eele Abraham.<bt>When He finished speaking, then God left Abraham behind alone.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəkhal (klh piʕel): finished"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yəkhal (klh piʕel): finished</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23-27" />Lod'o èèna kahèi, Abraham tao dènge ka, madhutu sèmi lii paredha Ama Lamatua. Ka na suna. Na suna ana na, Ismael, dènge dhèu mone aa'i-aa'i dhu pea dènge ne. Lod'o èèna, umur Abraham 99 (ceo nguru ceo) tèu le, aa Ismael 13 (canguru tèlu) tèu.<bt>That same day/time, Abraham straightaway did according to God's command. So he got circumcised/circumcised himself. And he circumcised Ismael, his child, and all the males that lived with him. At that time, Abraham's age was already 99 years, and Ismael was 13 years.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yamal (mwl narr): he circumcised bʕetsem:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yamal (mwl narr): he circumcised bʕetsem: in bone; complete identity, that very day<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>meʔet ben nekhar: bought from a foreigner End of P section.<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu tèlu mai paraga dènge Abraham<bt>Three people come and meet with Abraham</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="18" />
      <v n="1" />Ca tèka, Abraham pea padètu dènge aj'u aae canau ètu Mamre. LAMATUA mai pad'elo iisi Na mi nèngu ètu era èèna. Lii lolo na sèmi ne'e ka: lod'o èèna, sagoro ae titu kèna, ka Abraham madhèdi ètu hèb'a paleo na, sèna ka abhu ngèlu g'oro ciki.<bt>One time, Abraham was living near a big tree at Mamre. The LORD cam and revealed Himself to him in that place. The story goes like this: That day was very hot, and Abraham was sitting at the door of his tent/shelter, so he could get a little breeze.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Begins a new Seder (major division"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Begins a new Seder (major division to give a three-year reading cycle, S section) ʔelon: big tree, species not specified, usually taken as oak or terebinth<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>kəchom: at the hottest part of the day [JEG] Pagan worship here is superfluous. Still, the worship was for real. A place for divination, if not sacrifice. 13:18 identifies them as "sacred"; So Abram moved his camp and settled near the sacred trees of Mamre at Hebron, and there he built an altar to the LORD. BDB: Terebinth, oak. (ASV and RSV usually translate "oak" with a marginal note "terebinth." The KJV erroneously translates as "plain.") It is generally conceded to be the same as )e4la=. The tree figures often in Abraham's travels (Gen 12:6; 13:18; 14:13; 18:1). A noted one is mentioned near Ebal and Gerizim (Deut 11:30). The RSV translates the term on one occasion "divining Oak" (Jud 9:37), while ASV follows KJV in translating "the oak of Meonenim." Apparently certain such trees became so famous as landmarks that they were generally recognized by all as suitable for specifying rendezvous. But all that doesn't enter into the story at this point.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ropa Abraham boti kètu na, ladhe nèdhi dhèu tèlu dhu titu kaj'èu boe nèti era èèna. Hèia na rai la'e soru nare si. Ropa na d'ai madha si, na patitu kètu urutuu na,<bt>When Abraham lifted his head, he saw three people standing not very far from that place. So he ran over to greet them. When he arrived in front of them, he bowed,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nitstsavim ʕalaw (nif ptcpl): who had"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nitstsavim ʕalaw (nif ptcpl): who had taken their stand. If they had walked up, he probably would have seen them coming from miles away. Sounds like they appeared out of nowhere. yarats: he ran<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>vayishtakhu (khwh hishtafal): bown down deeply ʔartsah: to the ground? toward the earth?<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />ka na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama si. Mai dhuli ku ho minu èi ciki.<bt>and spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Fathers. Come stop in so you can drink a little water.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔadonai: Lord, Master, polite vocative. With"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔadonai: Lord, Master, polite vocative. With qamets on the last syllable rather than petach, could be "my lords"; but bʕenekha later in the verse is singular chen: favorable attitude<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>ʔal-naʔ taʕvor: lest you go on past (Middle East courtesy with a flourish). Josephus comments on the misoxenia of the people of Sodom, unwilling to share and eager to exploit; this is a great example of philoxenia, willingness to share. Jacques Ellul, The Meaning of the City, uses Babylon as a symbol of people making their own creation without reference to God.</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ama si ae ciki mi mamaho ne'e. Ho ana-ana iiki rèti èi, sèna ka rasa haga miu.<bt>You fathers should take a short break/stop/rest in this shade. My underlings/children will fetch water to wash your feet.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yuqach-naʔ (lqch qal impv impf): please"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yuqach-naʔ (lqch qal impv impf): please take mʔat: a little bit<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>rachətsu: wash hishshaʕənu (nif impv): stretch out and rest<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Pe ja'a laku lalau nganga'a-nginu ho ama si mi'a ciki, sèna ka ako kadhii ciki, heka lami taruu kèna. Te ja'a karej'e bisa lalau ama si.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then I will go prepare food-drink so you fathers can eat a little, so that you can regain your strength and continue your journey. Cuz I am happy to be able to serve/look to your needs.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="g'oro = sapoi yg hembus, breeze;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">g'oro = sapoi yg hembus, breeze; 3: dhuli; 5: ako kadhii = agak kuat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ooo. Ji'i dhuli.&gt;&gt;<bt>And they responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Ooo [=affirmative]. We will stop in.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="fat: little bit Saʕədu libkhem (imperv):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">fat: little bit Saʕədu libkhem (imperv): strengthen yourselves, support<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>ʔachar taʔvoru: later you will go on</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Hèia Abraham pamèri sa d'ara paleo, la'e peka dènge Sara, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mèri! More tarigu dhu be'a risi, ca saku, ho tao roti!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Abraham hurried inside the tent, going to speak with Sara, saying, &lt;&lt;Hurry! Get the best flour, one sack, to make bread!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shlosh Səʔim: three seahs = 21"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shlosh Səʔim: three seahs = 21 liters = about five gallons = capacity of an oversize bucket, more than three or four people could possibly eat qemach Solet loshi: knead up some wheat flour ground fine from the inner kernels of the wheat. Same quality as God prescribed later for the Bread of the Presence.<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʕugot: several circular, flat bread like modern pita bread, baked in ashes or on top of hot stones; pita bread, thick flour tortillas</Message></Annotation><note reference="18:6" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Ibrani peka na, &lt;more tarigu tèlu <span class="Italic">seah</span>&gt;. Tèlu seah èèna, sama kahèi ca saku tarigu (20-25 kilo).<bt>The Ibrani language says &lt;get three <span class="Italic">seah</span> of flour&gt;. Those three saehs are like a single sack of flour (20-25 kilos).</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ka rai la'e hari asa era sapi na, hèia kèpe ana sapi kabèb'u ci'u. Ka na pua dhèu sab'a na sa, pare.<bt>Then he hurried off to the place of the cows, and caught a fat/healthy cow. And he ordered his workers to slaughter it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baqar: herd rakh: tender, delicate. A"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">baqar: herd rakh: tender, delicate. A full-grown cow would have to hang a while after butchering before they could eat the meat; the meat of a calf could be fixed right away because it's still tender.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Hèia la'e nare susu, keju dènge sisi dhu heka nasu èèna, nèti hia tamu sèra ra'a. Abraham titu taruu ètu mamaho aj'u, ho na lalau si.<bt>Then he fetched milk, cheese [Port loan, check if they've found anything closer to curds yet], and meat that they had just boiled/cooked, taking them for those guests (loan) to eat. Abraham kept standing in the shade of the/a tree, to serve them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabèb'u = gemuk ; roro (kambing-sembelih)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">kabèb'u = gemuk ; roro (kambing-sembelih) ; pare (sapi-potong) ; kèj'i (babi-tikam) ; hake (ayam - pukul kepala) ; sui (ikan - belah, filet) ; buri (ikan - slice into pieces) ;; 8: susu kahore (?)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chemʔah: curdled milk, almost like yogurt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">chemʔah: curdled milk, almost like yogurt (like Isaiah's curds and honey) ʕalehem: like he's hovering over them, waiting on them like a waiter.<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Hèia ra karèi ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu èmu mu Sara, ka mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they asked him, saying, &lt;&lt;Where is your spouse, Sara?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Na dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nuka d'ara paleo èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>He responded, saying, &lt;&lt;She's probably inside the tent.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔelayw: to him. This is one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔelayw: to him. This is one of 15 instances of the word marked with four diamonds. Whether the Masoretes thought it should be deleted, or posed a doctrinal problem, nobody is sure. ʔayyeh: where?<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00655c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Sara nanene nèti kabodho babèdho<bt>Sara listens from behind the door</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ka ca dhèu nèti rèngu se padhai lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Pe d'ai tèu mai nèi, Ja'a lèpa hari mai. Lod'o èèna, dhèu èmu èu Sara nare iisi le ana mone ca dhèu.&gt;&gt;<bt>And one of them spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Next year, I will come back here. At that time, your spouse Sara will have given birth to a son.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa rèngu padhai lii èèna, Sara nanene nèti kabodho babèdho.<bt>When they spoke like that, Sara was listening from behind the door.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕet: time, same time; OK for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕet: time, same time; OK for the yearly cycle, or only the daily cycle? chayyah: alive, but ʕet chayyah "the same time next year"<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>huʔ ʔacharaw (read as hiʔ): she was behind him -- Abraham canʔt see Sarah.</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Lod'o èèna, Abraham dènge Sara dhu heka bhoro le, ngaa hari Sara dhu abhu heka hèru.<bt>At that time, Abraham and Sara were already very old, and furthermore Sara no longer got months/menstruation.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baʔim bayamim: who were getting along"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">baʔim bayamim: who were getting along in years chadal: it had ceased, gone<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʔorakh kanashim: the manner of women; past the menopause kanashim: archaic genitive (Frank Anderson)<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ropa Sara tadèngi padhue-padhai rèngu se, ka na mari kèmu. Na pangee na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a dhu heka roto-roto sèmi ne'e ne, aa dhèu èmu ja'a dhu roe nia heka. Tasamia ji'i bisa tao sèmi ana ngèru dhu leo-èmu hiu, ho abhu ana?&gt;&gt;<bt>When Sara heard their discussion, she laughed. She thought, &lt;&lt;I am old and wrinkled like this, and my spouse is weak/soft in his old age. How can we-exc do like young people who have just married, to get children?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hèru = 3) mens ; abhu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">hèru = 3) mens ; abhu hèru = raa mai (latter more kasar); 12: heka roto-roto = heka bhoro ; roe nia heka = terlalu lemah; /mari kèmu/ = bursting to laugh but trying to restrain it</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bqirbah: the inward part of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bqirbah: the inward part of the body, considered the seat of laughter. Probably positive; it's so neat that now it's really going to happen! But other commentators think she is laughing in disbelief, at how preposterous the idea is, which may fit better with taking V. 13 as a reprimand. bloti: I am all used up, worn out, exhausted<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ʕednah: pleasure, including sexual, but can be the joy of having a baby</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ka LAMATUA peka dènge Abraham, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka Sara mari? Ele boe na ngee na, lii padhai Ja'a ne j'aj'i boe, lula nèngu heka le.<bt>Then the LORD spoke with Abraham, saying, &lt;&lt;Why did Sara laugh? Perhaps she thinks what I am saying can't happen, because she is already old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haʔaf (intrj): even ʔumnam: really?|i(13) |r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">haʔaf (intrj): even ʔumnam: really?<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Ja'a ne, LAMATUA! Abhu boe ngaa èci sa dhu Ja'a bisa boe tao. Sanèd'e paie. Tèu mai, ladhe Ja'a lèpa hari mai, Sara dhu nara iisi le, ana mone ca dhèu.&gt;&gt;<bt>I am the LORD! There is nothing that I cannot do! Remember well. Next year, when I return here, Sara will have already given birth to a son.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="həyippaleʔ (nif imperf): is it difficult,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">həyippaleʔ (nif imperf): is it difficult, too hard lmoʕed: on the fixed day<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ropa tadèngi lii èèna, Sara j'aj'i madha'u. Ka na pasili, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a mari boe, nga!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing that comment, Sara became afraid. So she denied it, saying, &lt;&lt;I didn't laugh, [+protest]!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa Lamatua b'ala, na, &lt;&lt;Deo na, èu mari, nga.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the Lord answered, saying, &lt;&lt;You did laugh just now, [+protest].&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tkhachesh (piʕel): she denied it yareʔah:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tkhachesh (piʕel): she denied it yareʔah: she was afraid<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abraham pamako Lamatua sèna ka baku huku dhèu Sodom<bt>Abraham (tries to) persuade the Lord to not punish the people of Sodom</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Èle ka, dhèu tèlu se pakèd'i neo lasi asa kota Sodom. Ka Abraham lere si d'ai talora j'ara. Nèti era èèna, ladhe rèdhi kota Sodom.<bt>After that, the three people left, wanting to go to the city of Sodom. And Abraham escorted them to the middle of the journey. From that place, they could see the city of Sodom.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaqumu (narr construct): they stood up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayaqumu (narr construct): they stood up vayashqifu ʕal-pney (hif narr): they looked out over the edge of the hill and down toward Sodom. ʕal-pney: taking in the whole scene, which was not very far away<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>lshalləcham (piʕel inf): to see them on their way -- politeness. Next morning he goes back to the same spot.</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ka LAMATUA ngee ètu d'ara Na, &lt;&lt;Hua iia Ja'a peka dènge Abraham, Ja'a neo palaho kota Sodom.<bt>And the LORD thought to himself, &lt;&lt;It would be better if I tell Abraham, I am going to destroy the city of Sodom.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yhwh: yhwah with double dot over"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yhwh: yhwah with double dot over w in 18:1 different from vayhwah here with single dot over w and circle over h. The circle (Massora parva) indexes the Massora magna, a type of concordance listing for this word. The double dot in 18:1 is the cholem (o) plus the single dot. say to himself, think to himself - not out loud. "Yahweh had wondered." Some Jewish authors think this is an informal meeting of the heavenly council.<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʕoseh (ptcpl): not eventive - the thing I am about to be doing hamkhaSSeh (piʕel ptcpl): keep something secret from somebody. Amos says that prophets are told the secrets of God, so this scene validates Abraham as a prophet. (rabbinical view)<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Te ladhe èèna na, ana-èpu na asa tabha ae, aa suku dhu kapai. Aa nèngu ne, èèna na, j'aj'i berkat mi suku aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>Cuz in the future, his descendants will increase becoming many, and be a great tribe. And this one here, in the future, will become a blessing to all the tribes on this earth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hayo (hyh inf): being ʕatsum: mighty,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hayo (hyh inf): being ʕatsum: mighty, powerful. Tanakh "populous, mighty in numbers"<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>nivrkhu (nif): they will wish for themselves blessing like Abraham's (= Gen 12:3) bo: Abraham takes on an iconic stature<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Ja'a hag'e kore le nèngu, ho na nori ana-èpu na dènge dhèu leo, sèna ka madhutu taruu j'ara LAMATUA, ho ra mamuri dènge mola. Ladhe rèngu mamuri sèmi èèna, Ja'a tao aa'i lii dhu Ja'a pajaji dènge Abraham.&gt;&gt;<bt>I have selected/chosen him to teach his descendants and other people, so that they always follow/obey the way of the LORD, so they live straight/pure. If they live like that, I will do everything which I have promised to Abraham.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakèpu = kasi angus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pakèpu = kasi angus</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ydaʕtiw: select, choose, take up his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ydaʕtiw: select, choose, take up his cause; singled him out, entered into a special relationship lmaʕan ʔasher: in order that<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>beto: children and household both ytsawweh (tswh piʕel): appoint, order<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>shamru derekh yhwh: they will keep the way of the Lord. Derekh Yʔ -- how much does Abraham know of it at this point? The Sodom people know general moral things. The Way of the Lord is introduced here, in Psalm 1, and elsewhere in the Torah. umishpat: legal decisions<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>habiʔ (hif): bring diber (piʕel): he told him. The angel of the Lord speaks like Yahweh, and speaks about him -- if this is not a theophany. Or there may be seams in the redaction.<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Hèia LAMATUA peka dènge Abraham, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Ja'a tadèngi le, lii roma iisi dhèu ae, peka na, dhèu kota Sodom dènge Gomora bhabhelu ra seli-kolane.<bt>Then the LORD spoke with Abraham, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this! I have heard the complaints of many people, saying, the evil of the people of the city of Sodom and Gomora has passed the threshold/is too much.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zaʕqat: cry for help chaTTaʔtam: their"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">zaʕqat: cry for help chaTTaʔtam: their sin<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>khavdah: heavy, grievous, weighty</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a puru madha ku mai, sèna ka kèdhi unu ku, ngaa dhu Ja'a tadèngi sèra, tare'a, do aad'o. Ladhe aad'o, pe Ja'a ke'a unu ku.&gt;&gt;<bt>That is why I have come down myself, so I can see for myself, whether what I have heard is true, or not. If not, I will know for myself.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔerədah-naʔ: I am going down naʔ:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔerədah-naʔ: I am going down naʔ: urgency, politeness<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>hakətsaʕəqatah: the fact that they are calling for help. Who is calling for help? Probably visitors to Sodom who are being treated like Lot and the angels, wronged victims of the Sodom people. In Sodom they may have had a policy of denying hospitality vigorously so as not to attract strangers, whom they despised. kalah: completion (fo real), destruction<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ropa LAMATUA padhai lii era dènge Abraham, dhèu dua se lasi taruu sa kota Sodom.<bt>While the LORD was still speaking with Abraham, the other two people continued on toward the city of Sodom.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayifnu: they turned, went on ʕodenu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayifnu: they turned, went on ʕodenu (ʕod 3sg): still<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Hèia Abraham la'e padètu dènge Lamatua, ka na pamako Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia? Ama neo pamadhe aa'i dhèu-dhèu be'a pa'èci dènge dhèu-dhèu bhelu, do?<bt>Then Abraham approached the Lord, and tried to pursuade/coax him, saying, &lt;&lt;How about it? Is father going to kill off the good people together with the evil people, right?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayigash (ngsh): he stepped up to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayigash (ngsh): he stepped up to make a case, like a plaintiff before a judge haʔaf: even<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>tispeh: you will sweep away, snatch</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Ladhe abhu dhèu lèmi nguru dhu be'a ètu d'ara kota èèna, Ama pamadhe si hèi? Do, Ama palaho heka kota sèra, lula rèngu se'e, do?<bt>If there are 50 good people in that city, will Father also kill them? Or, will Father no longer destroy those cities, because of these ones, or (what)?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔulay: expression of hope, entreaty, fear;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔulay: expression of hope, entreaty, fear; perhaps? haʔaf: also, even: addition, emphasis, ascending importance, contrast ʔand yetʔ, implied question<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>tispeh: wipe them out, sweep away the place vloʔtisaʔ (nsʔ): lift up [someone's head = pardon them]; and will not pardon them<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Ama baku tao sèmi èèna! Mage dhoka, dhèu be'a sèra madhe hèi, lula Ama neo pamadhe dhèu bhelu sèra. Ama ka dhu pama'ète lii ètu dedha-liru dènge rai-haha. De Ama ku unu Mu dhu me'a j'ara èèna adil boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>Father should not do that! May it not be that the good people also die, because Father wants to kill those evil people. Father is the one who decides/judges disputes/issues in heaven and on earth. So Father Yourself knows that this way is not just/fair (loan).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chalilah: with min + infinitive, far"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">chalilah: with min + infinitive, far be it from you to do such a thing. From chll ‘profane’. Always adversive (Holladay). ləhamiyt (mwt hif inf cs): for you to kill. Waltke &amp; OʔConnor [536] "The wəqatalti construction [wəhayah] after an infinitive construct [ləhamiyt] functions in ways similar to those we have observed in connection with other leading verbs. The line between an apodosis and a consequent situation is often fuzzy in the construction. The examples can be taken as conditional sentences ..." The translation is "to kill the righteous with the wicked AND SO the righteous BECOME as the wicked." For k- ʔasʔ [642], "The particle k- can be used with two compared things, the effect being that the situation of one of them is likened to that of the other" and they translate "And the state of the righteous would be like the state of the wicked."<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>shofet: the one judging, the judge mishpaT: judgment, sentence, decision. Your job is to uphold the distinction between good and bad people. Same stem as shofet; being a judge means maintaining the difference between right and wrong.<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ka LAMATUA dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe abhu dhèu be'a lèmi nguru dhèu ètu kota Sodom, Ja'a huku boe kota èèna, lula rèngu.&gt;&gt;<bt>And the LORD responded, saying, &lt;&lt;If there are 50 good people in the city of Sodom, I will not punish that city, because of them.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baʕvuram: on account of them, for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">baʕvuram: on account of them, for the sake of them</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Hèia Abraham padhai lii hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama, ja'a manèngi abho, lula ja'a neo padhai lii hari ciki. Ja'a ne dhoka dhèu goa di, dhu ke'a boe ngaa-ngaa.<bt>Then Abraham spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;Father, I ask forgiveneness (loan), because I want to speak a little more. I am only a dumb/stupid person, who doesn't know anything.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaʕan (ʕnh): came back at him,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayaʕan (ʕnh): came back at him, replied, responded, picked up on what God said. He's sticking his neck out hoʔalti (yʔl hif): make a beginning, said politely and modestly, go on to do something else<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>ʕafar vaʔefer: dirt particles on the ground and loose soil crumbling to dust (put on the head as a sign of mourning)</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Sèmi d'ai boe dhèu lèmi nguru dhu be'a, te ngaa dhoka èpa nguru lèmi di, tasamia? Kura dhoka dhèu lèmi di, na Ama neo palaho eele kota èèna, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>If perhaps there are not 50 good people, but only 45, how about it? For lacking only 5 people, is Father going to destroy that city, or (what)?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Lamatua b'ala, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Ja'a abhu dhèu be'a èpa nguru lèmi, Ja'a palaho boe kota èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>And the Lord replied, saying, &lt;&lt;If I find 45 good people, I will not destroy that city.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yachsrun: they wonʔt make it, there"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yachsrun: they wonʔt make it, there will be a lack of five of the good people htashchit: will you ruin, spoil<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>ʔashchit: will destroy, needs explicit object or will be taken as destroying the good people</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ka Abraham pamako hari, na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi abhu dhoka èpa nguru dhèu be'a di, tasamia, Ama?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Abraham coaxed/bargained again, saying, &lt;&lt;If perhaps there are only 40 good people, how about it, Father?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Na dhaa, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Ja'a abhu èpa nguru dhèu be'a, Ja'a huku boe si.&gt;&gt;<bt>And He responded, &lt;&lt;If I find 40 good people, I will not punish them.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayosef ʕod: and he went on,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayosef ʕod: and he went on, added, continued d yimatsʔun (nif): are found<span class="Italic">(29)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Abraham pamako hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama baku nasa. Te abhu dhoka tèlu nguru dhèu be'a di, na tasamia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Abraham coaxed/bargained again, saying, &lt;&lt;Father don't be angry (+ I'm sorry). Cuz if there are only 30 good people, how about it?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Na dhaa, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Ja'a abhu tèlu nguru dhèu be'a, Ja'a huku boe si.&gt;&gt;<bt>So He responded, &lt;&lt;If I find 30 good people, I will not punish them.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yichar (chrh): become hot, become angry"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yichar (chrh): become hot, become angry</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Hèia Abraham peka hari, &lt;&lt;Ama mage nasa ladhe ja'a karèi hari ciki. Sèmi abhu dhoka dhèu dua nguru di dhu be'a, na tasamia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Abraham spoke again, &lt;&lt;Father please don't be angry if I ask a little more. If perhaps there are only 20 good people, how about it?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Na dhaa hari, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi abhu dhèu dua nguru di dhu be'a, Ja'a palaho eele boe kota èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>And He responded again, saying, &lt;&lt;If perhcnace there are 20 people who are good, I will not completely destroy that city.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hineh-naʔ: look, again ... hoʔalti ldaber:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hineh-naʔ: look, again ... hoʔalti ldaber: take up the matter, push ahead, go on<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ka Abraham katange lii padhai na, aa na karèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ja'a padhai lii hari ca tèka, te ngaa baku nasa dènge ja'a. Tasamia, ladhe abhu dhoka canguru dhèu di dhu be'a?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Abraham closed his discussion, and asked, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! I will speak one more time, but do not be angry with me. How about if there are 10 good people?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Na dhaa, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Ja'a abhu canguru dhèu dhu be'a ètu era èèna, Ja'a palaho boe kota èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>So He responded, &lt;&lt;If I find 10 people who are good in that place, I will not destroy that city.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔakh: only, surely, nevertheless ʔakh happaʕam:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔakh: only, surely, nevertheless ʔakh happaʕam: only this one time<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Padhai lii èle sèmi èèna, LAMATUA la'e dènge ka, aa Abraham lèpa kahèi.<bt>When they finished discussing like that, the LORD went on, and Abraham returned home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="killah (klh piʕel): he finished"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">killah (klh piʕel): he finished</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Bhabhelu-katub'a dhèu Sodom<bt>The evil [excessive serious big-time evil] of the people of Sodom</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="19" />
      <v n="1" />Ètu d'ara Lamatua dhu padhue-padhai era dènge Abraham, ana pajuu Na dhèu dua, lasi le asa kota Sodom. D'ai nèi, lod'o oe cèna kèna. Ka Lot dhu madhèdi ètu hèb'a tedhe kota.<bt>While the Lord was still discussing with Abraham, His two servants had gone one to the city of Sodom. Arriving yonder, the sun was about to set. And Lot was sitting at the fence mouth/gate to the city.</bt><note reference="19:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Uru-uru sèra, hèb'a tedhe kota j'aj'i mi era dhèu-dhèu heka madhèdi ho pama'ète lii, aa era dhu rèngu pake ho padhue-padhai.<bt>Long ago, the city gate was the place where the respected elders sat to decide disputes and a place for them to use to discuss things.</bt></note>Ropa nèdhi dhèu dua se, la'e soru nare si. Ka na patitu kètu urutuu, aa pacud'u kètu ètu madha ra.<bt>When he saw the two people, he went to greet them. And he knelt and bowed his head before them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vlot: first in sentence, marked, possibly"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vlot: first in sentence, marked, possibly emphasizing "at just the time when the angels came, Lot was there." shaʕar: city gate, the place where the prominent people talked over and decided all the affairs of the city. Possibly Lot was there so he could rescue strangers from the Sodom welcoming committee. (Canʔt prove it, and it doesn't affect the translation; but it does fit in with 2 Peter 2:7, "God rescued Lot out of Sodom because he was a good man who was sick of all the immorality around him.")<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>vayakam (qal qwm): got up, stood up vayishtakhu (khwh hisht) he bowed down deeply, all the way to the ground<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʔafayim (ʔaf dual): his nose, nostrils, the area around his nose, his face</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ka na padhai lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mai lati dhuli ku èmu ja'a la. Sèna ka ama si rase haga, aa j'unu ètu èmu ja'a. Pe bèli mad'ae, heka ama si kako hari kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>And he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Come stop-in at my house. So that fathers can wash your feet, and sleep at my house. Then tomorrow morning, you fathers can continue on.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Makasi. Te ngaa repo ia ka. Hud'i laa ji'i j'unu ètu d'ara lapa.&gt;&gt;<bt>They responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Thanks. But there's no need to trouble/busy yourself. Just let us sleep on the broad field [town field used for ball games, parades, ceremonies and public gatherings].&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔadonai (pl): my lords (to the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔadonai (pl): my lords (to the two) suru (swr imperv pl): turn aside from your road<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>linu (lwn imperv): spend the night, remain over. Washing the feet is mentioned after staying the night, possibly as a detail of what "staying the night" entails. Raki thinks the order is iconic with time, so that Lot can say "they have just arrived and havenʔt even had time to wash their feet yet." But in Pidgin the washing needs to come before the sleeping or it doesn't make sense. rachətsu (imperv): wash<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>vhishkamtem (shkm hif): you get up early, load up for travel rkhov: in the open public square or plaza, just inside the gate (not "in the street"). This was part of God's test of Sodom's people.<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Te ngaa Lot pamako si loe boe, ka lasi manubha asa èmu na. Ka Lot si tunu roti, lalau mei, ka ra'a-rinu pa'èci.<bt>But Lot did not stop coaxing them, so they went and stayed in his house. And Lot baked bread, set (food on) the table, and they ate-drank together.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiftsar-bam: urged them strongly vayasuru: they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiftsar-bam: urged them strongly vayasuru: they turned aside, stopped off at his house<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>mishteh: drinks for a feast, prepare a feast with wine matsot: unleavened bread, no yeast. It could be prepared quite fast, whereas regular bread with sourdough or yeast would take a long time to rise before it could be baked. At the time of the Exodus, five centuries later, unleavened bread took on religious symbolism, and yeast became a symbol for sin; but in Abraham's time there is no evidence of either -- Lot was in a hurry, that's all. Sarah the day before had had a lot more time for her breadmaking.<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>ʔafah: he baked. Not enough time to raise dought with yeast. Raki thinks it was a Passover type of celebration, but there too the reason for unleavened bread was the urgency of the situation, not the symbolism of purification from sin that was attached to it at Sinai.</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Dhu dua ra lasi mèka j'unu, cag'ag'a laa, dhèu mone Sodom aa'i-aa'i, ana mone ngèru toke d'ai mone heka, mai reo rare èmu Lot.<bt>The two of them had not yet gone to sleep, when suddenly, all the men of Sodom, from young men/boys up to old men, came and surrounded Lot's house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Terem + imperfect = before they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Terem + imperfect = before they Xed Terem yishkavu: before they lay down<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>vʔanshey haʕiyr ʔanshey Sədom: why the doubling? Actually four references to the subject. Too much for Pidgin. naSabu (Sbb nif): surrounded<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>miqqatseh: to the end = every last man in town, or all the people clear out to the outskirts of town</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Dhèu se'e pa'oo-parodha, peka mi Lot, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;He, Lot! Mone dua deo sa, ètu mia? Bhabhodho si mai, sèna ka ji'i j'unu dènge ra!&gt;&gt;<bt>These people were shouting out (doublet), speaking to Lot, saying, &lt;&lt;He, Lot! Those two men/officials earlier, where are they? Bring/send them out here, so that we may sleep with them!&gt;&gt; [We had to fight to get this explicit in this prudish culture.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Bhabhodho = kasi muncul"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">Bhabhodho = kasi muncul</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔayyeh: where? with nouns, not verbs;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔayyeh: where? with nouns, not verbs; where is ...? hotsiʔem (ytsʔ hif): make them come out, bring them out<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>nedʕah (ydʕ 1pl cohortative): let us know them = euphemism for sodomy, have homosexual sex with them. The antithesis of hospitality; gang rape would not have been tolerated anywhere, though homosexuality was known. Suggested by some Jewish scholars that the cities were wealthy, and did this kind of thing to keep strangers away (misoxena), so as not to spend their money on them. NIV and NLT use "make sex."</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00651c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Lot padhai lii dènge dhèu Sodom sèra<bt>Lot speaks to the people of Sodom</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Hèia Lot li'u la'e, ka na bèdho hari èmu.<bt>Then Lot went outside, and closed the door of the house again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="petchah: entrance, location to go in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">petchah: entrance, location to go in through delet: door, piece that moves<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>sagar: shut something (doesn't need et-)</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ka na lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'ari, ee! Baku miu tao bhelu mi tamu ja'a se.<bt>And he spoke2, saying, &lt;&lt;Elder-younger siblings! Don't do this evil thing to my guests.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔachai: my kinsmen (which they werenʔt)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔachai: my kinsmen (which they werenʔt) tareʕu (rʕʕ imperf 2pl): do something bad. "Do no harm" has been suggested, but their reaction shows that they take loʔ tareʕu as fighting words.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Mi nanene ku ja'a laa! Ana bhèni ja'a, dhèu dua. Dua ra dhu pa'èci mèka dènge dhèu mone. Ja'a hia miu. Mere, ho mi tao tasamia èèna ka, sad'i madhutu dad'èi miu. Sad'i miu baku tao karehe mi tamu ja'a dhèu dua se. Lula madhutu ad'a èdhi, ja'a ka dhu hud'i j'aga si.&gt;&gt;<bt>Listne to me! I have two daughters. The two of them have not yet joined with a male. I will give them to you. Take them so you can do whatever you-pl desire with them. As long as you don't do evil to these two guests of mine. Because according to our-inc adat, I must protect them.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔotsiʔa naʔ (ytsʔ cohortative): I will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔotsiʔa naʔ (ytsʔ cohortative): I will make them come out, let me bring them out katov bʕenekhem: usually means that anything goes, not that they are to consider the moral consequences<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>raq: only baʔu: implicit cultural obligation to make sure one's guests are safe when they are with him, needs to be made explicit for Local culture. He's trying to protect the men.<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>btsel: to the shade qorati: the beams of my house = my house; under the shadow of my roof beam<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Masi ka sèmi èèna, dhèu Sodom se pa'oo ma'ète boe, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne, baku patabha! Te èu ne, dhèu tao mai ètu kabarai ji'i ne! De èu dènge boe hak ho kai ji'i. Hua iia, èu pakaj'èu nèti era ne'e. Te, ladhe lamu boe, ji'i tao èu bia risi nèti dhèu dua se'e!&gt;&gt; Ka ra tule eele Lot, hèia aa'i-aa'i ra rai lasi j'èje babèdho èmu.<bt>Even though (he spoke) like that, (nevertheless) the people of Sodom had no break in their shouting, saying, &lt;&lt;You-sg here must not mexendo! Cuz you are a person who has come/migrated to our-exc country here! So you have no right to forbid us. It would be better if you distance yourself from this place. Cuz, if you do not go, we will do to you heavier (=more severely) than to these two people!&gt;&gt; And they shoved Lot, and they all ran forward (trying to) break in the door of the house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patabha = 1) tambah, 2) campur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">patabha = 1) tambah, 2) campur ; j'èje = injak, (break in door by kicking it in)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gesh halʔah: stand back, get out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">gesh halʔah: stand back, get out of the way ngsh: step forward, step away?<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>halʔah: to there, farther haʔechad: the one, this guy, this character<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>yishpoT: he is acting as judge naraʕ (rʕʕ hif 1pl): we will do evil to you<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>mehem: more evil to you than to them vayiftsru: they urged him strongly<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>baʔiysh bəloT: why the duplication? lishbor: to break down the door, smash it (the door, not Lot)<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Te ngaa dhèu dua se soro kacui-aai ra, ère pamaso Lot, ka ra patèke èmu nèti d'ara.<bt>But the two people reached out their hands and yanked Lot back in, and they barred/locked the door from inside.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaviyʔu (bwʔ hif): they brought him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yaviyʔu (bwʔ hif): they brought him into the house sagaru: shut<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Dua ra tao pabèdhu ana madha dhèu Sodom aa'i-aa'i ra, ka rèdhi heka ngaa-ngaa. Ra gogo tenge babèdho, te ngaa abhu boe.<bt>Then the two of them made blind all the Sodom people's eyeballs, so they couldn't see anything. They were groping for the door, but they couldn't find it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pabèdhu = bekin buta, blinded"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pabèdhu = bekin buta, blinded</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="petach: at the doorway hikku (nkh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">petach: at the doorway hikku (nkh hif): strike someone with a disability<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>baSSanwerim: in dazzling light miqqaton: from the insiginificant ones to the great ones<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>vayilʔu (lʔh): they gave up, got tired of doing it (the men from the town)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua kalua eele Lot si nèti Sodom<bt>God2 brings Lot mob out from Sodom</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lot si rai eele Sodom"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">Lot si rai eele Sodom</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12-13" />Hèia tamu dhèu dua se, peka dènge Lot, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;LAMATUA ne'a le, bhabhelu-katub'a dhèu Sodom se. Nèti èèna ka, Na paleha ji'i dua mi mai, sèna ka palaho eele kota ne. De èu dhu dènge a'ari leo dhu ètu d'ara kota ne, do aad'o? Ladhe dènge ana mone, do ana bhèni, do dhèu èmu ana èu, do, sad'i cee èèna ka, lamu more si, ho rai ka nèti d'ara kota ne lai-lai!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the two guests spoke to Lot, saying, &lt;&lt;The LORD already knows the terrible-evil of these people of Sodom. That is why He sent the two of us-exc here, to destroy this city. So, do you have any other relatives here in this city, or not? If there are sons, or daughters, or children's spouses, or whoever, go fetch them, to flee from this city immediately!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕod mi-lkha: is there still anybody"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕod mi-lkha: is there still anybody else with you poh: here<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>chatan: related by marriage (a son-in-law, bridegroom) baneykha: your sons<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>banoteykha: your daughters mashchatim (shcht hif partcpl): ones who are going to destroy. Participles for things about to take place, but the events havenʔt actually occurred yet<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>tsaʕəqatam: their cries for help (the victims of Sodom) lshachtah: to ruin it, spoil it, wipe it out. The final -h with dagesh is marked as a feminine suffix (for haʕir). With a locative -h, the accent would never be on the last syllable.<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Hèia Lot la'e paraga dènge ana mone dhèu dua, dhu lii d'ai ana bhèni na. Ka na peka, &lt;&lt;Dua mi nanene paie! Rai ka nèti d'ara kota ne, te LAMATUA neo palaho eele ne!&gt;&gt; Te ngaa ra pangee na, Lot padhai lii paleko di.<bt>Then Lor went to speak with the two men who had asked (to marry) his daughters. And he said, &lt;&lt;The two of you listen carefully! Run/flee from this city, cuz the LORD is going to (completely) destroy it!&gt;&gt; But they thought that Lot was just kidding around.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paleko = maen gila"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">paleko = maen gila</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="loqche bnotaw: in the process of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">loqche bnotaw: in the process of taking his daughters soon. Unusual expression. Were these engaged to become his sons-in-law, or were they married to two other daughters who did not live with him? Probably the first. mashchit (shcht hif partcpl): imminent destruction<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ki-mtsacheq (tschq piʕel partcpl): he was joking, mocking at them. REB "they did not take him seriously"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Bèli mad'ae aae era, ana pajuu Lamatua dhèu dua se, pakaseti Lot si, ho lasi karohe asa era kaj'èu. Ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Lami ka! Ère mèti dhèu èmu mu, dènge ana bhèni èu dhèu dua sèra, ho rai ka. Tèke eele kota ne'e! Mage dhoka miu madhe aa'i palere-lere dènge kota ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Early the next morning, the two underlings/servants of the Lord, forced/pressed Lot to leave immediately for a distant place. They said, &lt;&lt;Go on! Drag away your wife, and both your daughters, to flee now. Leave this city behind. May you-pl not all die from stupidity/pointlessly, along with this city.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mati bodo-bodo = mati parcuma"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">mati bodo-bodo = mati parcuma</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="khmo: k- proclitic participle of comparison,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">khmo: k- proclitic participle of comparison, as hashshakhor: the reddish light before dawn, very early<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>ʕalah: was going up vayaʔitsu (ʔwts hif): they urged, tried to hurry<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>hanimtsaʔot (mtsʔ nif partcpl fem pl): the ones who happen to be, who are found here - the two daughters and the wife (does this mean that the sons-in-law lived elsewhere with two other daughters?) pen-tiSSəfeh (Sph nif): lest you get snatched away<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>ʕəwon: activity that is wrong, sin, guilt, punishment</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Te ngaa Lot neka-neka era, masi ka LAMATUA neo hia ne mamuri. Nèti èèna ka, tamu dhèu dua se nuni Lot, dhèu èmu na, dènge ana bhèni dhèu dua sèra, rèti asa li'u kota.<bt>But Lot kept delaying, even though the LORD wanted him to live/wanted to save him. Because of that, the two guests pulled Lot, and his spouse, and his two daughters, going outside the city.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitmahmah (mhh hitpalpel): delayed, lingered, fiddled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yitmahmah (mhh hitpalpel): delayed, lingered, fiddled around, dawdled, dithered yachziqu (chzq hif): take hold, seize, grab, strong-arm somebody<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>bchemlat: by the compassion, forbearance yotsiʔuhu (ytsʔ hif): they caused him to go out<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>nichuhu (nwch hif): they caused him to settle down, give rest</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Hèia ca dhèu nèti tamu dhèu dua sèra paredha si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Rai palasa, sèna ka abhu sod'a! Mage mi kabib'a kabodho! Baku ae ètu d'ara mamoo! Rai taruu, asa ledhe nèi, sèna ka miu baku madhe!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then one of the two guests commanded them, saying, &lt;&lt;Run quickly, so that you can be safe/saved! Don't look back! Don't stop on the flat place! Keep running on to that mountain yonder, so that you-pl do not die!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="neka-neka = ba'eok = delay; 17:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">neka-neka = ba'eok = delay; 17: palasa = cepat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hotsiʔam (ytsʔ hif inf): as they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hotsiʔam (ytsʔ hif inf): as they got them out hachutsah: to the outside [of town]<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>himmaleT (mlT nif imperv): get yourself to safety for your life, escape, run for your life ʔal-tabbit (nbt hif): donʔt look in a specific direction, behind you<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʔal-taʕmod: donʔt stand still, stop, stay bkhol hakikar: in any of the environs<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Te ngaa Lot peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Iraa ee! Baku sèmi èèna!<bt>But Lot spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Iraa, ee! [+complaint, protest] Not like that!</bt><v n="19" />Mema ama si pamamuri le ji'i se. Te ngaa ledhe nèi kaj'èu bia nèti ne'e! Mage dhoka ji'i d'ai mèka nèi, j'aj'èra dhu magee nare le ji'i èèna, ètu talora j'ara.<bt>You fathers have really saved us. But that mountain yonder is very far from here! May it not be that we have not yet reached there, and the suffering/destruction blocks/encounters us on the way.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="matsaʔ ʕavdəkha chen bʕeyneykha: has found"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">matsaʔ ʕavdəkha chen bʕeyneykha: has found favor in your eyes, treated me with favor chasdəkha: loyalty, solidarity, faithfulness<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>ləhachəyot (hyh hif inf): to preserve me alive pen-tidbaqani: so it wonʔt fasten itself on me, cling to me, stick<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>matiy: I die</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ama ladhe ku laa. Rae iiki cue dhu kaj'èu boe nèti era ne'e. Rae nèi dhu kolongara aad'o. Ladhe ama d'èi, ji'i la'a pasoru iisi asa nèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>Father have a look. There is a small village not far from this place. That village has no name/reputation. If you want/agree, we will just go seek shelter/protection there!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasoru iisi = berlindung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pasoru iisi = berlindung</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lanuS (nws inf): escape, slip away,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">lanuS (nws inf): escape, slip away, flee mitsʕar: modest, few<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>Repetitious. Lot is pleading for his life, but he's so stressed out he is bumbling and stumbling. Hebrews 11 must use Lot as the example of minimal faith, barely squeaking through but making it somehow. At least he did it.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ka na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Oo! Lami ka! Te èèna na, ja'a palaho boe rae nèi.<bt>So he responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Oo! [affirmative] Go on! Cuz there, I will not destroy that village yonder.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nasaʔti panekha: I will allow that,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nasaʔti panekha: I will allow that, pay attention to you; I will show favor, have regard gam: in addition to all the other slack they already cut him<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>lbilti hafkiy (inf cs): for the nonexistence of the destruction, not to destroy. This courtly language, like a king to a subject, shows the angel's reaction to Lot's panic. hafki: (I will not) overthrow; turn upside down or on its side<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="22" />De rai karohe ka, lami asa nèi! Te ja'a tao mèka ngaa-ngaa, ladhe miu d'ai mèka era nèi.&gt;&gt; Karèi nèti lod'o èèna, dhèu pangare rae ne <span class="Italic">Soar,</span> dhu sasoa na &lt;ana iiki-iiki&gt;.<bt>So, run quickly, and go there! Cuz I cannot yet do anything, if you-pl have not yet arrived in that place yonder.&gt;&gt; Beginning from that time, people called that village <span class="Italic">Soar,</span> which means &lt;tiny/insignificant&gt;.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="himmaleT (mlT nif imperv): escape ʕad-boʔəkha"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">himmaleT (mlT nif imperv): escape ʕad-boʔəkha (bwʔ inf): until your arrival<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>Initial NPs may identify a bunch of near simultaneous things, not in sequence tsoʕarah (tsʕr): trifling, insignificant. The name was given on this occasion, but also used to identify its king earlier in the light of the name the town came to be known by.<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kota Sodom dènge Gomora kèpu-ladhu ai<bt>The cities of Sodom and Gomora get burned up with fire</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00656c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ropa lod'o rea, Lot si d'ai Soar.<bt>When the sun began to rise, Lot mob arrived in Soar.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rashi suggests that God made the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Rashi suggests that God made the fire come at the transition from night to day in order to hit both the sun worshippers and the moon worshippers. Jude holds that Sodom and Gomorrha and the three other cities left their first estate (rather than the angels?) tsoʕərah: to Zoar. Accent is on the first syllable, as the last is a locative that never takes the accent. The -h may be a mater lectionis to identify the "a" vowel.<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Cag'ag'a laa, LAMATUA sadutu ai dènge èi nasu nèti dedha-liru asa Sodom dènge Gomora.<bt>Suddenly, the LORD poured-out fire and sulpher from the sky toward Sodom and Gomora.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="himTiyr (hif): make rain come down,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">himTiyr (hif): make rain come down, make sulfur come down like rain gafrit: sulphur<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>vʔet: hendiadys, burning sulphur</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />LAMATUA pakèpu-ladhu ai kota dènge rae aa'i-aa'i ètu d'ara rai èèna, dènge ngaa-ngaa dhu mamuri ètu èèna, nuka: dhèu, badha-manu, dènge ana aaj'u.<bt>The LORD burned up (doublet) all the cities and villages in that country/region, and everything that lived there, that is: humans, animals, and plants.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ladhu ai = angus; 24: sadutu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">ladhu ai = angus; 24: sadutu = po'a ; èi nasu = belerang (lit = air rebus)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yahafokh (hpk): destroy. He wiped out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yahafokh (hpk): destroy. He wiped out everything that was attractive to Lot. The valley had been "like the garden of the Lord" haʔel: God (old term)<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>tsemach: growth, what sprouts</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Lod'o rèngu rai, dhèu èmu Lot kabib'a kabodho. Cag'ag'a laa, na j'aj'i agarii masi.<bt>When they ran, Lot's spouse looked back. Immediately she became a post/pillar of salt.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Not clear if this is in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Not clear if this is in sequence, or just one of the many things that was going on. tabet (nbt hif): look, gaze, have a look in a specific direction, glance<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>meʔacharaw (masc) or meʔacharay (fem): looked behind Lot to the destruction? if she was going first; as she was following along behind Lot she looked back? natsiv: pillar, post, military garrison or outpost<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>melach: salt, but hard rock, not like Hawaiian salt crystallized from sea water or the salt you buy in the supermarket. More like the salt rock in the caves near Bogota.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Asa bèli èèna, dhu mad'ae aae era, Abraham la'e asa era dhu med'a na, na pamako LAMATUA.<bt>Early the next morning, Abraham went to the place where yesterday he had coaxed the LORD.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yashkem (hif): got up early, eagerly."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yashkem (hif): got up early, eagerly. Usually goes with hlk (vayelekh) ʕal-panay: In 18:22, the Massoretes guessed that it originally said that Yahweh stood in front of Abraham. This verse suggests they were wrong.<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Hèia na ladhe sa haha asa Sodom dènge Gomora, aa asa d'ara mamoo èèna. Na ladhe la'a na, sèb'u poka-poka sèna, dhu ca'e asa dedha-liru. Aa ai na'e aa'i le ngaa-ngaa.<bt>And he looked down toward Sodom and Gomora, and that whole valley. He looked, and all over the place smoke was billowing up into the sky. And fire had eaten up everything.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="forom = archaic ; ofen ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">forom = archaic ; ofen ; tungku bakar kapur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayashqef: looked down, usually from the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayashqef: looked down, usually from the point of view of someone below, but probably not here. Same thing in v. 18. Anyway, Abraham is in the up country, and the towns are in a flat area at the foot of some rather steep hills qiTor hakivshan: thick smoke like the smoke that comes from a furnace for smelting metal or a forge. Rashi says it can also be a pit where stones are burned to make plaster. Same thick, oily look as the clouds that obscure Sinai in Exodus.<span class="Italic">(28)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ama Lamatua patalale Lot si nèti hahuku èèna, ropa Na pakèpu-ladhu ai kota-kota sèra, lula Na ngee nèdhi lii pajaji Na dènge Abraham.<bt>God rescued Lot mob from that punishment, when God burned up those cities, because He thought/remembered His promise with Abraham.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="restructure KM ***"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">restructure KM ***</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Te ropa Ama Lamatua pakèpu-ladhu ai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">Te ropa Ama Lamatua pakèpu-ladhu ai kota-kota sèra, ka ngee nèdhi lii pajaji Na dènge Abraham. Nèti èèna ka, Lamatua patalale Lot si nèti hahuku èèna.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bshachet (inf): on the occasion of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bshachet (inf): on the occasion of destroying (not ʔas he destroyedʔ) zqr: remember in the sense of activating his covenant relationship<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>vayshallakh (piʕel): let Lot go free mitokh: from in the middle<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>hfekhah: destruction</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lot dènge ana-ana bhèni na<bt>Lot and his daughters</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Lod'o èèna, Lot madha'u pea taruu ètu rae Soar. Nèti èèna ka, nèngu dènge ana bhèni na dhèu dua sèra, lasi asa ledhe ka ra pea ètu d'ara loe cue.<bt>At that time, Lot was afraid to continue staying in the village of Soar. Because of that, he and his two daughters went to the mountain(s) and they lived in a cave.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bamʕarah: in the cave (was it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bamʕarah: in the cave (was it pointed out in later years as a sort of tourist attraction? Did the Moabites and the Ammonites venerate it?)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ca lod'o, ana bhèni uru èèna, peka dènge ari na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ètu era ne'e ne, abhu boe dhèu mone ca dhèu sa, dhu bisa leo dènge èdhi se. Aa ama èdhi asa heka, de ladhe èèna na, na bisa heka abhu ana.<bt>One day, the oldest daughter spoke with her younger-sibling, saying, &lt;&lt;In this place there is no man who can marry us-inc. And our-inc father is old, so in the future, he can no longer have children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsəʕiyrah: young, little laboʔ ʕalehu: to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tsəʕiyrah: young, little laboʔ ʕalehu: to come to us (for sex)<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>kderekh: in the way of all the world. Theyʔre so thoroughly indoctrinated by the life they have lived that they react like Sodom people.</Message></Annotation><v n="32" />De be'a risi, ti hia ne ninu mahu, sèna ka èdhi dua ti j'unu dènge ne, ho ti abhu kolo hia ama èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>So it would be good if we get him drunk, so that the two of us can sleep with him, so we can get tips (children) from our father.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lkhah (hlk): come on! not necessarily"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">lkhah (hlk): come on! not necessarily feminine. Samaritan text makes it masculine. nashqeh (shqh hif): give something to drink<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>nishkəvah: we will have sexual intercourse with him. Wenham says it's a coarse expression, like the F word. nəchayyeh (Hyh piʕel): we will preserve life<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ka ropa d'ai mèda, dua ra hia ama ra ninu èi anggor toke mahu. Hèia ana bhèni uru èèna, la'e j'unu dènge ama na. Lula ama na dhu mahu ae, ka ne'a boe nèngu dhu j'unu dènge ana na.<bt>So when night arrived, the two of them gave their father to drink grape juice/wine until he was drunk. Then the oldest daughter went and slept with her father. Because her father was so drunk, he didn't know he was sleeping with his daughter.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mahu ae ~ mahu aae"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">mahu ae ~ mahu aae</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tashqeyna (shqh hif): they gave him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tashqeyna (shqh hif): they gave him to drink tishkav: she lay down (standard expression for having sex)<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Hèia asa bèli èèna, a'a na peka dènge ari na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mèda deo na, ja'a j'unu le dènge ama èdhi. De mèda ne'e, èu kèna. Èdhi hia ne hari ninu mahu, ho lamu j'unu dènge ne. Sèna ka èdhi dua ti abhu ana, ho hia ana-èpu mi ama èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the next day, the older-sibling spoke to her younger-sibling, saying, &lt;&lt;Last night I slept with our father. So tonight, it's yours. Let's get him drunk again, so you go sleep with him. So that the two of us can have children, to give descendants to our father.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mèda meda = yesterday's night (=2"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">mèda meda = yesterday's night (=2 nights ago) ; mèda deo na = tadi malam, last night</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chen: particle, focuses on the next"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">chen: particle, focuses on the next thing No attempt to convince with naʔ or the other usual particles. Just "do this, do that."<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>ʔemesh: yesterday evening boʔiy (imperv): you go<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Ka d'ara mèda na, dua ra hia hari ama ra ninu mahu. Ka ana bhèni limuri ne, la'e ka j'unu dènge ama na. Te ngaa, lula ama ra dhu mahu titu kèna, nèti èèna ka, ne'a boe ngaa dhu nèngu tao mi dedha ana bhèni na.<bt>And that night, the two of them again had their father drink until drunk. And the youngest daughter went and slep with her father. But, because their father was so greatly drunk, that is why he didn't know what it was that he did to his daughter.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Dènge j'ara ne'e ne ka, dua ra dènge babia nèti ama d'èlu rèngu.<bt>In that way, the two of them became pregnant from their own birth father.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tahareyna (hrh): they got pregnant"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tahareyna (hrh): they got pregnant</Message></Annotation><v n="37" />Hèia ana bhèni uru èèna nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu. Ka na pangare na <span class="Italic">Moab</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;mai nèti ama&gt;). Ana ne'e ka dhu j'aj'i bèi-baki nèti dhèu Moab.<bt>Then the oldest daughter gave birth to a son. And she named him <span class="Italic">Moab</span> (which means &lt;came from father&gt;). This child is the one who became forefather of the people of Moab.</bt><v n="38" />Ka ana bhèni limuri ne, nara iisi ana mone èci kahèi. Na pangare na <span class="Italic">Ben Ami</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;mai nèti dhèu ja'a&gt;). Ana ne ka dhu j'aj'i bèi-baki nèti dhèu Amon.<bt>And the youngest daughter also gave birth to a son. She named him <span class="Italic">Ben Ami</span> (which means &lt;comes from my people&gt;). This child is the one who became ancestor of the people of Amon.</bt><note reference="19:37-38" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Èèna na, dhèu Moab dènge dhèu Amon sèra paj'èra taruu dhèu Isra'el sèra.<bt>Later on, the Moab people and the Amon people continually caused trouble for the Isra'el people.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abraham monya dhèu aae Abimelek<bt>Abraham deceives king Abimelek</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="20" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna, ka Abraham nèti Mamre, pidha asa rai Negeb, dhu ètu re balèu, ka na pea ètu talora rae Kades, dènge rae Syur. Te ngaa na pea nèbhu boe, ka pidha hari asa rae Gerar.<bt>After that, Abraham from Mamre moved to the land of Negeb, to the south, and he lived between the village of Kades, and the village of Syur. But he didn't stay long, and moved again to the village of Gerar.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiSSaʕ (nSʕ): depart, pull out yagar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiSSaʕ (nSʕ): depart, pull out yagar (gwr): live as an alien, for a limited time<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Hèia na peka dènge dhèu ètu sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sara ne, ana hèni ja'a.&gt;&gt; Nèti èèna ka, Abimelek dhèu aae Gerar, pua dhèu lasi lii d'ai Sara. Ka nèti ne mai asa d'ara èmu dhèu aae.<bt>Then he spoke with the people there, saying, &lt;&lt;Sara here, is my sister.&gt;&gt; Because of that, Abimelek the king of Gerar, sent people to engage (marriage step) Sara. And brought her into the house of the king.</bt><v n="3" />D'ara ca mèda sa, Ama Lamatua pad'elo iisi Na dènge dhèu aae ètu d'ara nii. Na peka, &lt;&lt;Mamadhe èu ne dètu kèna! Lula èu more dhèu èmu dhèu.&gt;&gt;<bt>One night, God revealed Himself to the king in a dream. He said, &lt;&lt;Your death is nearing now! Because you took a person's spouse.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lasi lii dai = maso minang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">lasi lii dai = maso minang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bʕulat baʕal (qal pass partcpl): one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bʕulat baʕal (qal pass partcpl): one who belongs to a man as engaged or married to him</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4-5" />Hèia Abimelek dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lamatua! Ja'a dhae pa'èci mèka dènge bhèni na. Aa ja'a sasala aad'o. Abraham unu na ka dhu peka, bhèni na, ana hèni nèngu! Aa bhèni na dhaa sèmi èèna kahèi. Nèti èèna ka, ja'a hia dhèu lasi lii d'ai ne, dènge d'ara mola. De Lamatua baku pad'ui ja'a sasala!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Abimelek responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Lord! I have not yet joined with that woman. And I have no wrong. Abraham himself is the one who said that woman is his sister! And the woman responded the same as well. Because of that I sent people to go engage her, with a straight/pure insides. So God2 shouldn't make me bear that wrong!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padui = kasi pikul ; dui"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">padui = kasi pikul ; dui ~ d'ui</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsaddiq: innocent, in the right in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tsaddiq: innocent, in the right in this context. This is the same argument as Abraham used with God in 18:25. btom lvavi: in the integrity of my heart; guilelessness, good faith<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>bniqyon kapai: in cleanness of hand, innocence</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ka Lamatua dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a. Mema Ja'a ke'a d'ara èu mola. Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a ka dhu taha èu, ho baku pa'èci dènge ne. Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, èu tao boe sala mi Ja'a hèi.<bt>And God2 responded, saying, &lt;&lt;True. I really know your insides are straight/pure. Because of that, I am the one who restrained you, so you wouldn't join with her. In that way, you did not also do wrong to me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔechsokh (chskh): I restrained you, held"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔechsokh (chskh): I restrained you, held you back; to keep something or someone under control: to restrain, hold back, keep from, prevent, withhold, spare chəTo (chTʔ inf): to sin against me<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>lnagoaʕ (inf): to touch</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />De èu mèti hari ka bhèni ne, lèpa sa dhèu èmu na. Mone na ka dhu nèti lii padhue-padhai Ja'a. De lamu manèngi ne, sèna ka na sabaj'a hia èu, ho èu baku madhe. Sanèd'e paie! Ladhe èu hia boe bhèni na lèpa, èu dènge kabarai èu madhe aa'i mèu-mèu.&gt;&gt;<bt>So, you will take back that woman, returning her to her spouse. Her husband is the one who is My spokeseperson. So go ask him, so that he prays for you, so you don't die. Remember well! If you do not send that woman home, you and your populace will all die off.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mamadhe dènge mamopo = death1 and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">mamadhe dènge mamopo = death1 and death2</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hashev (shwb hif imperv): give back"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hashev (shwb hif imperv): give back yitpallel (pll hitp): he will pray<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>baʕadkha: for you chəyeh (chyh imperv): live<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>meshiyv (shwb hif partcpl): giving her back daʕ (ydʕ imperv): know this<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Bèli mad'ae aae èèna, dhèu aae pakaboko nare dhèu-dhèu kapai na aa'i-aa'i, ka na lolo lii nii na. Hèia aa'i-aa'i ra madha'u.<bt>Early the next morning, the king gathered all the important people, and he narrated to them his dream. Then they were all afraid.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yashkem (shkm hif imperf): he got"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yashkem (shkm hif imperf): he got up early bʔaznehem: in their ears<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ka dhèu aae paroa Abraham. Na karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a tao sala ngaa mi èu, ka èu neo paj'èra ja'a dènge kabarai ja'a? Èu ne ele-ho'a ka dènge tao madha j'ara sèmi ne'e ne.<bt>And the king summoned Abraham. He asked, saying, &lt;&lt;What wrong have I done to you, that you want to make me and my populace suffer? You must repent/stop doing things like that.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heveʔta ʕali: you caused this to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">heveʔta ʕali: you caused this to come upon me, brought it on me, got me into this bad situation mamlakhti: my dominion, what I rule over<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>chəTaʔah: morally and/or ethically wrong act (not necessarily committed on purpose) or the state of guilt which is its consequence: sin, guilt maʕsim: things done, behavior toward someone<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>yeʕasu (nif): they were done</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ngangee èu tasamia ka, mu tao sèmi ne'e ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>What was your thinking, that your did this thing?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ele ho'a = berenti, bertobat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">ele ho'a = berenti, bertobat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mah raʔita: what did you perceive"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mah raʔita: what did you perceive</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ka Abraham dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama dhèu aae! Ja'a pangee na, miu aa'i-aa'i mi, kabarai ne dhèu dhu tadhe boe Ama Lamatua. De ele boe cahag'e neo pamadhe ja'a, sèna ka parame rare dhèu èmu ja'a.<bt>And Abraham responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Father king! My thinking was that all of you were a populace who did not know God. So (I thought) probably some would want to kill me, so they could take my spouse.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yirʔat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yirʔat</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Mema ja'a dhu peka tare'a, nèngu ne, ana hèni ja'a. Lula ji'i dua mi ca ama, te ngaa ina baka-leo. Nèti èèna ka, ji'i dua mi paleo.<bt>I really did tell the truth, she is my sister. Because the two of us have the same father, but different mothers. Because of that, the two of us married.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔamnah: in reality ʔakh: certainly, only|i(12)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔamnah: in reality ʔakh: certainly, only<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Ka ropa Ama Lamatua pua ji'i ho tèke eele era paleo-palu'u ji'i, lod'o èèna ja'a peka dènge dhèu èmu ja'a, aku ja'a na, &lt;Ladhe èdhi lati asa era leo, ho dhèu karèi èu, dhu èdhi se dhèu èmu-kamali, ladhe èu dhu sue ja'a, na dhaa la, peka na èdhi se, dua ti pa'a'ari.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>And when God ordered us to leave behind our homeland (doublet), at that time I spoke with my spouse, saying, &lt;If we-inc go to a different place, so people ask you, if we-inc are husband-wife, if you love me, then respond saying that we two are mutually elder-younger siblings.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hitʕu (tʕh hif): made me wander"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hitʕu (tʕh hif): made me wander off, caused me to stagger ʔomar: I said<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>chaSdekha: (loving)kindness, solidarity, joint liability, grace ʔimriy (ʔmr imperv fem): say "he is my brother"<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14-16" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu aae Abimelek pangèd'u hari Sara la'e asa Abraham. Ka na peka dènge Sara, &lt;&lt;Èèna na, ja'a hia ana mone mu doi iia ca riho, sèna ka j'aj'i tadha ja'a tao boe sala ngaa-ngaa mi èu. Ho hud'i sène, dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra re'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, king Abimelek turned Sara back over to Abraham. And he said to Sara, &lt;&lt;Now, I am giving your husband 1,000 silver coins, as a sign that I have not done anything wrong to you. Let everyone know this!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia dhèu aae peka dènge Abraham, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Kabarai ja'a ne, dhu bhoke tèke hia èu. Èu neo pea mi era mia èèna ka, ja'a hia èu.&gt;&gt; Ka Abimelek hia Abraham sapi, kahib'i-ka'ia, dènge kahib'i-kalèbho. Na hia kahèi ènu dhèu mone dènge dhèu bhèni.<bt>Then the king spoke with Abraham, saying, &lt;&lt;This country of mine, is opened up to you. You want to live in whatever place, I allow you.&gt;&gt; And Abimelek gave Abraham cows, goats, and sheep. And he also gave male and female slaves.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shev (yshb imperv): settle, live kəSut"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shev (yshb imperv): settle, live kəSut ʕeynayim: covering for the eyes = public declaration of unbesmirched honor of a woman<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>nokhachat: ahead of you</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17-18" />Uru èèna, lula Abimelek nare dhèu èmu Abraham, ka LAMATUA hutu eele era ana nèti bhèni aa'i-aa'i dhu pea ètu kabarai dhèu aae èèna. Te ngaa ropa Abimelek hia Sara lèpa hari sa dhèu èmu na, ka Abraham sabaj'a ho Lamatua bhoke hari era ana nèti bhèni se. Ka ra abhu hari ana.<bt>Previously, because Abimelek had taken Abraham's spouse, the LORD closed off the child place (=womb) of all the women who lived in the country of that king. But, when Abimelek gave Sara back again to her spouse, Abraham prayed so God2 would open the wombs of these women again. And they could have children again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yirpaʔ: he healed ʔamhotayw: his female"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yirpaʔ: he healed ʔamhotayw: his female slaves<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʕatsar: he held them back baʕad: for<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>rechem: every womb End of S section.<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sara nara iisi Isak<bt>Sara gives birth to Isak</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="21" />
      <v n="1-7" />Èle èèna ka, LAMATUA hia Sara mèngi-nale madhutu lii pajaji Na. Lod'o Sara dènge babia, Abraham dhu heka le. Ropa Sara nara iisi, umur Abraham d'ai cangasu tèu kèna. Lod'o Sara d'ai hèru, ka nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu. Ka Abraham pangare ne, <span class="Italic">Isak</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;na mari&gt;).<bt>After that, the LORD gave Sara blessings according to His promise. When1 Sara became pregnant, Abraham was already old. When2 Sara gave birth, Abraham's age had reached 100 years. When1 Sara's month arrived, she gave birth to a son. And Abraham named the child, <span class="Italic">Isak</span> (which means &lt;s/he laughs&gt;).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Sara peka hèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua tao ja'a mari, lula ja'a karej'e. Dhèu ae ka dhu pangee na, ja'a ètu d'ara heka sèmi ne'e ne, abhu heka ana. Masi ka dhèu èmu ja'a heka bhoro le, te ja'a bisa kora iisi ana hia ne. Èèna na, ladhe dhèu tadèngi j'ara ne'e, rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra mari kahèi dènge ja'a ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Sara also spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;God has made me laugh, because I am happy. Many people thought that I in my old age, would no longer have children. Even though my spouse is already old and withered, I nevertheless gave birth to a child for him. Now, when people hear of this event, all the them will also laugh with me.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa Isak d'ai aru lod'o, Abraham suna ne, madhutu paredha Ama Lamatua.<bt>When Isak was eight days old, Abraham circumcised him, according to the commands of God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paqad: took up the cause of,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">paqad: took up the cause of, take care of. Also used of Hannah. The word appears in many different contexts and is translated in a corresponding variety of ways: generally "do something about something"? yaʕas: he did. The verse is pleonastic, but not poetic, so the two halves need to be partly collapsed for Pidgin.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ben lizqunayw (pl): son of his old age lamoʕed: at the fixed time, at the time appointed. 25 years after Genesis 12; that sheds light on what Hebrews calls "not wavering in faith"<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʔoto (masc): him (Abraham) ʔelohim: does switching between yahweh and ʔelohim complicate things?<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>The convoluted syntax builds up to the name as punch line. The promise means nothing without the boy. Also of interest to Moses in legitimating Israel as a nation. yamal (mwl): circumcised<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>tsiwwah (piʕel): ordered. Parallel to dibber ʔoto ʔəlohiym in verse 2. bəhiwwaled (yld nif inf): at the time Abraham fathered him. Ishmael is 14 to 16, naʕar. "lo" ʔfor himʔ is redundant here in Pidgin.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>tschoq (noun? infinitive construct?): because there can be bitter laughter and sneering laughter as well as happy laughter and funny laughter, or as Kafka pointed out, laughter at the absurdity of it all, "feel good" ʔbe happyʔ is needed to eliminate the negative senses. The laughter that gave Isaac his name in Chapter 17 is embarrassed laughter; this is the laughter of pure delight. Tschoq sometimes goes with laʕag l- ʔscornʔ in poetry. So even "laugh at" is possible. hashomeaʕ: whoever hears.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>millel (piʕel pf): say, speak. Odd collocation: Alter calls it poetic, and several translations treat it as poetry. It's a birth announcement. heyniqah (ynq hif pf): nurse a baby<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>baniym: sons (Pidgin uses a generic noun, because in reality there was just the one)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra babège eele Hagar dènge Ismael<bt>They evict Hagar and Ismael</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Isak kapai ka noo-noo. Ropa oe d'ai lod'o luri susu, Abraham tao tatao aae.<bt>Isak grew steadily. When the day neared to wean him, Abraham made a big celebration.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="luri susu = sole, wean"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">luri susu = sole, wean</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiggamal (gml nif): he got weaned,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayiggamal (gml nif): he got weaned, finished being nursed. In Pidgin, "nurse" is what a mother does to a baby; the same expression doesn't say what the baby does. Probably around the age of 3, to celebrate a triumph over high infant mortality. The long time to weaning may also have had a contraceptive function. mishteh: drinking bout, drinks for a feast, banquet with wine; kind of like a one-year birthday luʕau, but later in honor of his weaning. All the detail about the luʕau is there because it is the setting for the blowup between Sarah and Hagar.<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>higgamel (gml nif inf): his weaning</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9-10" />Ca tèke, Sara ladhe nèdhi Ismael, ana nèti dhèu èmu limuri Abraham, padadisi dènge Isak. Ropa nèdhi sèmi èèna, Sara peka dènge dhèu èmu na, &lt;&lt;Bège eele ènu Masir nèi dènge ana na! Te, ja'a ko'o boe ana ènu èèna unu pusaka, masi ka ciki oo'e èèna ka. Dhoka ana ja'a Isak di, dhu abhu sèra aa'i-aa'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, Sara was watching Ismael, the child of Abraham's youngest spouse, scorning/abusing Isak.When she saw that, Sara spoke to her spouse, saying, &lt;&lt;Evict that Masir slave with her child! Cuz I do not want that child of the slave to have an inheritance, not even a little bit. Only my child Isak who will get everything.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padadisi = olok"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">padadisi = olok</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ishmael is 14 or 15 when"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Ishmael is 14 or 15 when this happened, teen ager mtsacheq (piʕel partcpl): playing, fooling around, normal kind of thing (Alter). It doesn't say he was playing with Isaac. Laughing at Isaac? with him? laughing at Sarah? (Wenham). Mocking? (piʕel canʔt have that sense without a preposition) The word is used of sex play between Isaac and Rebecca in Genesis 26:8. But the negative readings are probably called on to justify Sarah's fury with Hagar, which isn't needed. More likely, seeing the two boys together, she started thinking about Abraham's inheritance (which she didnʔt control) and something snapped.<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>garesh (piʕel impv): banish, divorce, expel, drive out ʔamah: female slave<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>yiyrash: will take possession, be the heir (together with someone)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ropa Abraham tadèngi lii padhai Sara ne, ka d'ara na ako be'a boe, lula Ismael ne, ana d'èlu na kahèi.<bt>When Abraham heard what Sara was saying, he felt uncomfortable, because Ismael was also his birth child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayeraʕ bəʕeyney (rʕʕ impf): it was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayeraʕ bəʕeyney (rʕʕ impf): it was displeasing to him, went wrong, got him all steamed up, ticked off. When God is raʕaʕ, he destroys cities; yet this is the only place it is intensified with mʔod. In the Code of Hammurabi and the Lipit Ishtar (Mesopotamian legal codes from before Abraham's time) if a man accepted a child, the child inherited. Another wife cannot kick the mother out. But if the father gives a slave mother her freedom, then her son loses the inheritance. The main wife's son takes precedence over an adopted son or the son of a concubine, even if the main wife's son is younger. ʕal-ʔodot: on account of<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Te ngaa Ama Lamatua lii dènge Abraham, peka na, &lt;&lt;Abraham! Èu baku ngee pa'ae dhèu èmu limuri èu, dènge ana na. Madhutu la dad'èi Sara ne, lula bèli-camèd'a, èu abhu ana-èpu dhu Ja'a moa tèke èèna, nèti Isak ne'e ka.<bt>But God advised Abraham, saying, &lt;&lt;Abraham! You should not think/worry about your younger spouse. Follow Sara's desires, because in the future, you will have the descendants that I have promised from this Isak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔal-yeraʕ bʕenekha: donʔt let it be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔal-yeraʕ bʕenekha: donʔt let it be displeasing to you. This is the aftermath of the shock, hence "bodda" in 11 and "sore inside" naʕar: young man, youth (marriageable male while still single); a teen-ager's parents in those days would have been thinking about getting him married off fairly soon<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ʔəmatekha: your slave woman byitskhaq: in connection with Isaac -- a direct clash with the Moslem Qurʕan, but highlighting the contrast between the two boys<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>yiqareʔ (nif): be named</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Te ngaa Ja'a hia kahèi mèngi-nale mi ana nèti dhèu èmu limuri mu, lula nèngu ne, ana d'èlu èu kahèi. Bèli-camèd'a, ana-èpu na j'aj'i suku èci kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But I will also give blessing to the child from your younger spouse, because he is also your birth child. In the future, his descendants will also become a tribe.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="canau-canadha = satu himpunan/kumpulan yg banyak"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">canau-canadha = satu himpunan/kumpulan yg banyak</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The reference to Ishmael is fronted"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">The reference to Ishmael is fronted to highlight it. ʔəsimenu l- (sim impf): I will set them up as a people<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Bèli mad'ae aae èèna, Abraham tao gee j'ara hia Hagar, aa na kadhoe èi d'ara babo'i cue mi kabela-kao na. Hèia na patabuli ka bhèni ne dènge ana na Ismael, ho lasi. Ka ra kako palème d'ara mamoo dhu dètu dènge Beer-Syeba.<bt>Early the next morning, Abraham made trailfood for Hagar, and he hung water in a gourd on her shoulder. Then he released the woman and her child Ismael, to go. And they went around the wilderness which is near Beer-Syeba.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chemat: goatskin stopped at both ends"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">chemat: goatskin stopped at both ends with pitch, for water, wine, oil, etc. Maybe 3 gallons, which would weigh 30 pounds, which is not extravagant in a culture where most things are moved on somebody's back. sam ʕal-shikmah: put it on top of both shoulders (the water skin, not the boy!) People going away "show you their back (shekhem)". Noah's sons put a blanket "on their shoulders" to approach their drunk father.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>vatetaʕ (tʕh): she wandered off, wandered around</Message></Annotation><note reference="21:14" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lod'o èèna, umur Ismael canguru èpa tèu risi le. Ladhe ètu Sasuri <span class="Italic">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka</span> 16:16; 21:5, 8.<bt>At that time, Ismael's age was around 14 years or so. See Gen. 16:16; 21:5, 8.</bt></note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00659c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Hagar dènge Ismael<bt>Hagar and Ismael</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ropa èle èi rinu ra, Hagar tèke eele ana na ètu d'ara mamaho aj'u iiki ca kapua.<bt>When their drinking water was gone, Hagar left her child behind in the shade of a small tree/bush.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yikhlu (klh): finished, gone tashlekh: and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yikhlu (klh): finished, gone tashlekh: and she tossed him down (same word as used for throwing Joseph into the pit). Here, however, he stays and she leaves, so "left him there" or "made him stay there" makes more sense. Maybe for Joseph too.<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>ʔakhad hasikhim: one of the bushes</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Ka na pangee ètu d'ara na, &lt;&lt;D'ara ja'a la'e boe, ladhe ja'a kèdhi mamadhe ana ja'a.&gt;&gt; Ka na madhèdi ako kaj'èu nèti ana na, pe d'ai lèmi nguru meter sa. Ka na tangi dènge lii roma iisi.<bt>She thought to herself, &lt;&lt;My insides cannot stand it, if I watch the death of my child.&gt;&gt; And sat a little far from the child, around 50 meters. And she cried requesting/complaining.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karoki = thick brier patch, push"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">karoki = thick brier patch, push that is difficult to get through</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mineged: opposite lah: by herself|i(16) (16)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mineged: opposite lah: by herself<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>harkheq (rkhq hif): at a good distance away mətachəvey (Tchh piʕel partcpl pl construct, may be dual ʔtwo bowshots awayʔ): as a bow ranges -- about as far as an archer shoots<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>qeshet: bow bmot hayeled: look on the death of the child. She can see him from a hundred yards away, but perhaps she couldnʔt stand to hear him crying.<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>vatisaʔ (nsʔ): lift, raise, show face, support, stand it; lift up her voice and wept; burst into tears</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Lula Ama Lamatua dhu tadèngi lii tangi Ismael, ka ana pajuu Na mai nèti sorga, ka paroa Hagar, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hagar! Nga tao ka, èu j'èra ae sèmi ne'e ne? Baku madha'u ia ka, te Lamatua tadèngi le lii tangi ana èu.<bt>Because God had heard Ismael's weeping, His servant/underling came from heaven, and called Hagar, saying, &lt;&lt;Hagar! Why are you in such difficulty like this? Don't be afraid anymore, cuz God2 has heard the crying of your child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqraʔ: called out min-hashamayim: not God's"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiqraʔ: called out min-hashamayim: not God's dwelling, but the voice comes from above her or near her. Not like a loudspeaker in a helicopter, but somebody calling that you canʔt see. "Heavens" in Hebrew includes the air right around us, the air where the birds fly, the place where the clouds are, and the place of the stars, so it's much broader than English "sky" or "heavens".<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />De kèd'i lamu more ana nèi. Pa'èra d'ara na, te bèli-camèd'a Ja'a paj'aj'i ana-èpu na, suku èci dhu kapai.&gt;&gt;<bt>So get up and go to the child yonder. Strengthen/encourage his insides, cuz in the future I will make his descendants, a great tribe.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lamore = pi ame /lamu +"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">lamore = pi ame /lamu + more/</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="səʔiy (nsʔ imperv fem): take, lift"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">səʔiy (nsʔ imperv fem): take, lift up, carry, convey hachəziqi et-yadekha bo (chzq hif): hold your hand in protection over him; encourage him, strengthen, hold him in your arms<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>yeled / naʕar: check out the pattern of use</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ka Ama Lamatua pasaraa musi madha na. Cag'ag'a laa nèdhi dènge, èi ca madha ètu era èèna. Hèia la'e soli èi asa d'ara babo'i, ka na panginu ana na Ismael.<bt>And God cleared up her eyes. Suddenly she saw a spring in that place. Then whe went and scooped/filled water into the gourd, and had her child Ismael drink.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="panginu = kasi minum"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">panginu = kasi minum</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yifqach: he opened tashq (shqh hif):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yifqach: he opened tashq (shqh hif): she cause him to drink<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20-21" />Ka Ismael dènge ina na Hagar pea dènge ka ètu d'ara mamoo Paran. Ismael asa na kapai, aa ne'a mèu kataki. Ka ina na paleo ne dènge ana bhèni Masir ca dhèu. Se'e se j'aj'i, lula Ama Lamatua bera-bera dènge Ismael.<bt>And Ismael and his mother Hagar lived in the wilderness of Paran. Ismael continued to grow, and became skilled with the bow. And his mother married him to a Masir woman. These things happened, because God was with Ismael.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="todhe = pull on lead"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">todhe = pull on lead</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roveh qashshat: bowman bowman, both hapaxes."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">roveh qashshat: bowman bowman, both hapaxes. May mean a superhunter, a hunter's hunter. End of P section.<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abraham padame dènge Abimelek ètu Beer Syeba<bt>Abraham and Abimelek make RECIP-peace at Beer Syeba</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu aae Abimelek dènge kètu kapai sordad'u na, Fikol, mai pangad'o dènge Abraham. Hèia dhèu aae padhai lii, ka na peka, &lt;&lt;Abraham! Ji'i se nge'a Ama Lamatua bera-bera dènge èu. Nèti èèna ka, sad'i èu ad'u ngaa sa èci, j'aj'i dènge be'a.<bt>At that time, king Abimilek with his big head of soldiers, Fikol, came and paid a visit to Abraham. Then the king spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Abraham! We-exc know God is with you. Because of that, whatever you do (Lit. as long as you do even one thing), it will be good.</bt><v n="23" />De ja'a manèngi, sèna ka èu subha ètu katanga madha Ama Lamatua, dhu peka na, èu bisa boe kapod'e-kabèli ja'a, dènge ana-èpu ja'a aa'i-aa'i ra. Sèmi dhu ja'a tao le be'a mi èu, na, èu hud'i tao be'a kahèi mi ja'a dènge kabarai ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>So I ask that you swear-oath before God, saying, you cannot deceive/con me, and all my descendants. In the same way I have done good to you, na, you must also do good to me and my populace.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pangad'o ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pangad'o =</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishshavʕah (shbʕ nif): swear an oath"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hishshavʕah (shbʕ nif): swear an oath hennah: here, now<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>ʔim tishqor li: if you deal falsely with me niyniy: my offspring<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>nekhed: my progeny cheSed: obligation to community, relatives, friends; unity, solidarity, loyalty, faithfulness<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>gartah bah: you have been living in it temporarily, not as a citizen</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ka aku Abraham na, &lt;&lt;Ooo! Ja'a subha.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then said Abraham, &lt;&lt;Good! I swear.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Te ngaa èle èèna ka, Abraham lapor dènge dhèu aae, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu-dhèu ama dhèu aae parame rare èi ja'a ca madha.&gt;&gt;<bt>But, after that, Abraham reported to the king, saying, &lt;&lt;Father king's people have robbed one of my wells.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hokhiach (ykch hif): set right, reprove,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hokhiach (ykch hif): set right, reprove, reproach someone for something, settle a quarrel, arbitrate ʕal-ʔodot: on account of<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>gazlu: they took away by force, tear away</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Tadèngi sèmi èèna, hèia na peka, &lt;&lt;Waa! Ja'a heka tadèngi kèna j'ara ne'e ne. Tasamia ka karèi nèti ca hari ni, èu peka boe dènge ja'a? Ja'a dhae ke'a mèka, ne'e ne tatao cee ka ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing that, he said, &lt;&lt;Waa! I have just-now heard of this matter. Why haven't you reported this before? I don't yet know who did this thing.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="higadta (ngd hif): reported, spoke out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">higadta (ngd hif): reported, spoke out</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27-28" />Èle èèna ka, Abraham dènge Abimelek pa'èki lii pajaji. Ka Abraham hia Abimelek sapi dènge kahib'i-kalèbho. Èle èèna ka, Abraham hag'e nare hari kahib'i-kalèbho èni pidhu ngi'u.<bt>After that, Abraham and Abimelek bound a mutual promise. And Abraham gave Abimelek cows and goat-sheep. After that, Abraham selected out another seven young female sheep.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayikhrətu brit: cut a deal vayatstsav"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayikhrətu brit: cut a deal vayatstsav (ntsb hif): cause to stand, put to one side, set aside<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>kivsot: young ewe-lambs lvadhen: by themselves, isolated<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Hèia dhèu aae karèi ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka èu tao sèmi èèna?&gt;&gt;<bt>And the king asked him, saying, &lt;&lt;Why are you doing that?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èni = tenak, mai yg belum"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">èni = tenak, mai yg belum beranak</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ka Abraham peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama dhèu aae. Sèmi la kalèbho èni pidhu ngi'u se, sèna ka j'aj'i tadha dhu ama peka le na, ja'a ka dhu kèi èi na.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Abraham spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Father king should accept these seven young female sheep, as a sign that you have said/acknowledged I am the one who dug this well/water.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kèi = gali"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">kèi = gali</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="was me an my guys dat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">was me an my guys dat wen dig dat puka, baʕavur: in order that<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>lʕedah: as a public witness chafartiy: I dug<span class="Italic">(30)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Lula dua ra dhu pa'èki le soo-subha ètu èèna, ka era na ra pangare na <span class="Italic">Beer-Syeba</span> (dhu sasoa na, &lt;madha èi soo-subha&gt;).<bt>Because the two of them bound an oath there, they named that place, <span class="Italic">Beer-Syeba</span> (which means, &lt;oath well&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shavaʕ: seven or oath - like"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shavaʕ: seven or oath - like kaona nishbəʕu (shbʕ nif): they swore an oath<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="21:31" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Ibrani, Beer Syeba sasoa na bisa &lt;madha èi dame&gt;, bisa &lt;madha èi kalua hua iia&gt;, bisa &lt;madha èi pidhu&gt;, dènge bisa &lt;madha èi soo-subha&gt;.<bt>According to the Ibrani language, Beer Syeba can mean &lt;well of peace&gt;, can mean &lt;well of good fortune/luck/descent&gt;, can mean &lt;seven wells&gt;, or &lt;well of swearing-an-oath&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ropa pasubha èle, ka dhèu aae dènge kètu kapai sordad'u na lèpa ka, asa era rèngu, rai dhèu Pilistin.<bt>When they had finished mutual oath-swearing, the king and the big head of his soldiers returned home to their place, the land of the Filistin people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yikhrətu bəriyt: they cut the deal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yikhrətu bəriyt: they cut the deal</Message></Annotation><v n="33" />Èle èèna ka, Abraham sèle aj'u tamareska<bt>After that, Abraham planted a tamareska</bt><note reference="21:33" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Aj'u <span class="Italic">tamareska</span> aad'o ètu rai Sona Ba'i dènge ètu Dhao. Aj'u èèna, mamuri rai mango, te ngaa rèu na mangèru taruu. Amo na maso d'ai marèma ètu ro'a rai. Kahib'i ra'a rèu na.<bt>There are no <span class="Italic">tamareska</span> trees on Dhao. That tree lived in dry land, but its leaves are evergreen. Its root pierces deeply into the ground. Goats eat its leaves.</bt></note>ca kapua ètu Beer Syeba. Karèi nèti lod'o èèna, aj'u ne pasanèd'e Abraham, lula ètu era èèna ka, nèngu mangaj'i LAMATUA dhu Mamuri Toke D'ai Mia-Mia.<bt>tree at Beer Syeba. Beginning from that time, that tree reminded Abraham that that is the place where he had worshipped the LORD who Lives Until Forever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiTTaʕ (nTʕ): planted ʔeshel: tamarisk (Tamarix"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiTTaʕ (nTʕ): planted ʔeshel: tamarisk (Tamarix aphylla, gallica, syriaca, and others). A small (up to 30 feet), fast-growing evergreen tree with durable wood, to be found abundantly in deserts, dunes and salt marshes. T. aphylla is leafless and has green branches and a wide crown. It soaks up lots of water, and excretes salt through its leaves. It has small white flowers, and its fruit is a capsule with feathery seeds. Planted from cuttings for its shade and soft branches that sheep can eat. 12 species in Israel. Looks like the cedar, which is not native there. There is also a wild Nile tamarisk (T. nilotica) which grows in nearly every deep wadi of the desert. NEB has "planted a strip of ground". Could be a kind of ironwood.<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="34" />Ka Abraham pea dènge ka ètu talora dhèu Pilistin sèmi dhèu tao mai.<bt>Then Abraham stayed on as an immigrant among the Filistin people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sona ba'i = Timor ; rai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">sona ba'i = Timor ; rai sota = tanah tandus, infertile</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pəlishtiym: Philistines. They came later from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">pəlishtiym: Philistines. They came later from the north into the coastal parts of Canaan, probably between the time of Abraham and the time of David.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua pua Abraham tao Isak sama sèmi badha korban<bt>The Lord orders Abraham to make Isak like an animal sacrifice</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 3:17, 17:5; Markus 1:11, 9:7; Lukas 3:22, 9:35; 2 Petrus 1:17)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="22" />
      <v n="1" />Nèbhu boe, hèia Lamatua sèku neo ne'a d'ara Abraham. Neo ne'a Abraham madhutu Lamatua, do aad'o. Ka Lamatua paroa ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Abraham!&gt;&gt;<bt>Not long after that, the Lord tested Abraham, to his insides/character. He wanted to see if Abraham listened/obeyed the Lord, or not. And the Lord called him, saying, &lt;&lt;Abraham!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sèku = uji = test their"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">sèku = uji = test their mettle, positive, from God; coba = mau kasi jato, dari setan dong</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ooo, Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>So he responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Yes, Lord.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ka Ama Lamatua peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Mu nanene paie-iie! More ana pasue èu mone mesa na. Mèti ne asa rai Moria, ho tao ne j'aj'i korban tunu hia Ja'a. Pe d'ai nèi, Ja'a heka paj'uj'u era dhu ètu ledhe èci.&gt;&gt;<bt>And God said to him, &lt;&lt;You need to listen carefully! Take your only son whom you love. Take2 him to the land of Mira, to make him be a burnt sacrifice (loan) to Me. Arriving yonder, only-then will I show the place on a mountain.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />D'ai bèli mad'ae aae na, Abraham sèg'i aj'u sèna ka tao kadhèna. Na èki, ka na hue asa dedha keled'ei. Ka dua ra dènge Isak, aa dènge dhèu sab'a na dhèu dua, pakèd'i asa era dhu Lamatua peka dènge ne.<bt>The next morning, Abraham split wood for firewood. He tied it up, and he loaded in on donkey(s). The two of them (he) with Isak, and two of his workers, left for the place which the Lord told him.</bt><v n="4" />Ra kako taruu, ka d'ai camèd'a èèna, Abraham nèdhi le era èèna nèti kaj'èu.<bt>They kept walking, and the day after the next day, Abraham saw that place from afar.</bt><v n="5" />Hèia na peka dènge dhèu dua sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dua mi mate taha mi ne'e dènge keled'ei ne. Ja'a dènge ana ja'a la'a asa dedha nèi, ho mangaj'i Ama Lamatua. Ladhe èle na, ji'i lèpa hari mai.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he spoke to the two people, saying, &lt;&lt;The two of you wait here temporarily with this donkey. I and my child will go up yonder, to worship God. When we are done, we-exc will come back here.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sèg'i = belah ; kadhèna ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">sèg'i = belah ; kadhèna = kayu api</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ka Abraham nare kadhèna dhu neo tunu korban, ka na tao mi kabela-kao Isak. Aa nèngu nèd'u tud'i, dènge suu ai. Ropa dua ra palere lasi,<bt>And Abraham took the firewood for the burnt sacrifice, and he placed it on Isak's shoulder. And he held a knife, and fire on the end of a stick. When the two of them were going,</bt><v n="7" />hèia Isak paroa ama na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama!&gt;&gt;<bt>Isak asked his father, saying, &lt;&lt;Father!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Abraham dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao, ana?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Abraham responded, saying, &lt;&lt;What's the matter (&lt;why), child?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Isak karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èdhi neo lati tunu korban. De ai dènge kadhèna ka se'e le. Te ngaa ana kahib'i-kalèbho dhu èdhi pake j'aj'i korban, ka mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Isak asked, saying, &lt;&lt;We-inc are going to make a burnt sacrifice. So here is the fire and the firewood. But the sheep offspring (=lamb) for us to use as the sacrifice, where is it?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa, aku Abraham na, &lt;&lt;Pe Ama Lamatua unu Na ka dhu hia ana kalèbho, sèna ka j'aj'i mi korban.&gt;&gt;<bt>But said Abraham, saying, &lt;&lt;Later God himself is the one who will give a lamb to be the sacrifice.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00663c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Abraham pa'èra tao ana na Isak j'aj'i mi korban<bt>Abraham prepares to make his son Isak be a sacrifice</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka dua ra ca'e lasi taruu.<bt>So the two of them kept on climbing.</bt><v n="9" />Ropa dua ra d'ai era dhu Lamatua peka èèna, ka Abraham pudhi hadhu ho tao mei korban. Hèia na paloko kadhèna ètu dedha mei korban ne. Ka kèpe ana na Isak, èki patarenga ne ètu dedha kadhèna.<bt>When the two of them arrived at the place that the Lord had said, Abraham stacked rocks to make a table for sacrifice. Then he arranged the firewood on top of that table for sacrifice. And hee took him son Isak, binding him face-up on top of the firewood.</bt><v n="10" />Ka nare tud'i, ho neo kèj'i pamadhe ana na.<bt>Then he took the knife to kill his child.</bt><v n="11" />Cag'ag'a laa, ana pajuu LAMATUA lii nèti dedha-liru, peka na, &lt;&lt;Abraham! Mata ku!&gt;&gt;<bt>But suddenly, the LORD's underling shouted from heaven/sky, saying, &lt;&lt;Abraham! Wait!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paloko = ator"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">paloko = ator</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Abraham dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao, Lamatua?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Abraham responded, saying, &lt;&lt;What is it, Lord?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ka na peka hari, na, &lt;&lt;Baku pamadhe ana èèna! Baku tao ngaa-ngaa mi nèngu. Ja'a ke'a le, èu ne tare'a-re'a madhutu dad'èi Lamatua. Lula èu dènge d'ara kateme hia ana èu ca dhèu mesa èèna, sèna ka j'aj'i mi korban hia Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;Don't kill that child! Don't do anything to him. I know that you truly follow/obey the will of God2. Because you with a whole heart gave your only child, to be a sacrifice to Him.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <fig path="Hk-lb\Bk00008c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Hèia Abraham ladhe nèdhi kahib'i-kalèbho mone ci'u, dhu tadhu na pakai nare dadana aaj'u dhu karoki. Ka na la'e kèpe nare, ho tunu j'aj'i mi korban hia Ama Lamatua, gati ana na.<bt>Then Abraham saw a male sheep, whose horns were caught in the branches of a small tree. So na went and caught it, to burn as a sacrifice to God, replacing his child.</bt><v n="14" />Ka Abraham pangare era èèna, na, &lt;Lamatua sadia tèke ngaa dhu parluu.&gt;<bt>So Abraham named that place, &lt;God2 prepares/supplies what is needed.&gt;</bt><note reference="22:14" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Ibrani, peka na, <span class="Italic">Yahova Yire</span>, sasoa na, &lt;Pe Lamatua sadia tèke ngaa dhu parluu.&gt;<bt>According to the Ibrani language, it says <span class="Italic">Yahova Yire</span>, which means &lt;the Lord is prepares/supplies what is needed.&gt;</bt></note>Nèti èèna ka, d'ai sange ne'e, dhèu peka na, &lt;&lt;Ètu ledhe LAMATUA èèna, Na sadia tèke ngaa dhu parluu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because of that, to this day, people say, &lt;&lt;On the mountain of the LORD, He prepares/supplies what is needed.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sadia tèke = sudah disiapkian ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">sadia tèke = sudah disiapkian ; sadia tèke ngaa = apa yg disiapkan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Èle èèna ka, ana pajuu Lamatua lii hari nèti dedha-liru, peka na,<bt>After that, the servant of the Lord spoke again from heaven, saying,</bt><v n="16" />&lt;&lt;LAMATUA unu Na, peka, &lt;Ja'a subha dènge kolongara Ja'a mesa ku, sèmi ne'e: èu sadia le hia Ja'a ana mu ca dhèu mone mesa na ho j'aj'i mi korban. Nèti èèna ka,<bt>&lt;&lt;The LORD himself, says, &lt;I oath-swear by My own name/reputation, like this: You were prepared to give Me your one and only son to be a sacrifice. Because of that,</bt><v n="17" />bèli-camèd'a, Ja'a pala-bagi èu dènge ana-èpu èu mèngi-nale ae-ae. Èèna na, ra bèba-kacanga, toke dhèu ige rare boe, sèmi hua-hètu ètu dedha-liru, aa salae ètu sebhe dhasi. Ana-èpu èu sèra, èèna na, segi aa'i musu rèngu sèra.<bt>in the future, I will distribute to you and your descendants many blessings. Later they will increase greatly in number (doublet), until people can't count them, like stars in the sky, and sand at the edge of the sea. Those descendants of yours will overcome/beat all their enemies.</bt><v n="18" />Nèti ana-èpu èu, dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne abhu mèngi-nale lula èu madhutu le lii paredha Ja'a.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>From your descendants, all peoples in the world will get blessing, because you have followed My command.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Èle hèia, Abraham dènge Isak, lèpa hari asa era dhu dhèu sab'a na sèra. Ka lasi palere asa Beer-Syeba. D'ai nèi, Abraham si pea dènge ka.<bt>After that, Abraham and Isak returned to the place where their two workers were. And they went together to Beer-Syeba. Arriving there, Abraham mob stayed there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-èpu Nahor<bt>Nahor's descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ca lod'o, Abraham tadèngi na, dhèu èmu ari na Nahor, dhu ngara na Milka, nara iisi ana na.<bt>One time, Abraham heard that the spouse of his younger-sibling Nahor, who was named Milka, had born children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yuggad (ngd hofʕal): it was reported"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yuggad (ngd hofʕal): it was reported to him</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ana uru, ngara na Us. Ari na, Bus. Èle ka, nara iisi hari Kemuel (dhu j'aj'i ama Aram.)<bt>The oldest child, was named Us. His younger-sibling, was named Bus. After that, she gave birth again to Kemuel (who was the father of Aram).</bt><v n="22" />Ka na abhu hari Kesed, Haso, Pildas, Yidlaf, dènge Betuel.<bt>Then there were also Kesed, Haso, Pildas, Yidlaf, and Betuel.</bt><v n="23" />Betuel èèna, ama nèti Ribka.<bt>That Betuel, was Ribka's father.</bt><v n="24" />Nahor abhu ana kahèi nèti bhèni piara na, ngara na Reuma. Ana Reuma, nuka: Teba, Gaham, Tahas, dènge Maaka.<bt>Nahor also had additional children from his mistress/concubine (&lt;pet wife/kept wife), named Reuma. Reuma's children were: Teba, Gaham, Tahas, and Maaka.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhèni piara = selingkuh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">bhèni piara = selingkuh</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="piylagsho: his concubine (Some Asians know"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">piylagsho: his concubine (Some Asians know about concubines and understand "concubine wife", but not all speakers do. CHECK PARALLELS. End of S section.<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abraham padhane dhèu èmu na Sara<bt>Abraham buries his spouse Sara</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="23" />
      <v n="1-2" />Lod'o Sara madhe, umur na 127 (ca ngasu dua nguru pidhu) tèu le. Lod'o na madhe èèna, Abraham si pea ètu rae Kiryat-Arba (nuka Hebron), ètu rai Kana'an. Ka Abraham beke aa tangi dhèu èmu na dènge d'ara pèd'a.<bt>When Sara died, here age was 127 years. When she died, Abraham mob were living in the village of Kriyat-Arba (that is Hebron), in the land of Kana'an. And Abraham waked and mourned his spouse with sadness.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shəney chayyey Sarah: the years of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shəney chayyey Sarah: the years of the life of Sarah chevrown: Hebron<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>liSpod: to sound a lament, beat his breast as a sign of mourning livkotah (bkh inf): to weep for her<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Hèia Abraham kèd'i la'e paraga dènge dhèu-dhèu Het. Ka na peka dènge si, aku nèngu na,<bt>Then Abraham got up and went to meet with the people of Het. And he spoke to them, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meto (mwt partcpl): his dying (why"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">meto (mwt partcpl): his dying (why masculine?) "town gate" isn't mentioned in Hebrew until after the deal is made, but it may need to be mentioned here to set the scene<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />&lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, dhèu tao mai ètu talora miu se. Ja'a dhu dènge boe rai ca kasib'i sa, sèna ka padhane dhèu èmu ja'a. De ladhe miu sue ja'a, ja'a hèli kore rai miu d'ai ca kasib'i sa, ho tao era padhane ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;I am a migrant/visitor in your midst. I have not even a plot of land where I can bury my spouse. So if you love/pity me, I will buy off a plot of your land to make it a burial place.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ger: a man who, either alone"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ger: a man who, either alone or with his family, leaves his village and tribe for one of several reasons, and seeks shelter and sojourn elsewhere, where his right to own land, to marry, and to participate in the administration of justice, worship, and war is curtailed toshav: means about the same as ger, but may imply that the person is more isolated from the local people, a real outsider<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>tənu (ntn imperv): give; but in the situation, it is a polite way of waying "sell". This is a very formal bargaining situation, kind of like dealing with the owners of a cemetery here. achuzzat-kever: property for a gravesite; possession<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>milfanay: out of my sight meti: my dead one (singular)<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>Hebron is on a limestone-chalk ridge, so there are probably lots of caves around</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia ra dhaa, aku rèngu na,<bt>The they responded, saying,</bt><v n="6" />&lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e, ama! Nèbhu nare sange ne'e, ji'i se tadhe le ama, dhu sama sèmi ca dhèu, dhèu heka dhu ji'i pakab'ua. De sad'i ama d'èi rai mia dhu be'a, dhu pamèci dènge dad'èi ama. Ji'i se dhoka ngo'o di; dhèu èci sa dhu magee boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;It's like this, father! For a long time, we-exc have known father, who is like a respected elder whom we respect. So, as long as there is a piece of good land that you desire, which matches your desire, (just choose it [implied by the "as long as" construction]). We-exc will just go along with/accept it; there is not one person who would refuse.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shəmaʕenu: lissen to our suggestion -"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shəmaʕenu: lissen to our suggestion - downplayed SK nsiʔ elohim: a person God has given high rank to, used for a chief or a minor king<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>bətokhenu: among us mivchar: choice<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>qvareynu: our burial sites qvor (imperv): bury<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>yikhleh (klʔ): restrain, keep back miqqvor (inf): from burying<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Hèia Abraham pacud'u iisi ho hia hormat mi lamatua rai, dhèu Het sèra.<bt>So Abraham bowed to show respect to the landowenrs, the people of Het.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishtachu (chvh hishtafal): bowed down deeply,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yishtachu (chvh hishtafal): bowed down deeply, did obeisance</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ka na padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe miu sèmi lii ja'a na, ja'a manèngi ho peka dènge ana mone Sohar, dhu ngara na Efron.<bt>And he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;If you accept what I have to say, I ask to speak with the son of Sohar, who is named Efron.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔim-yesh ʔet nafshəkhem: if it is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔim-yesh ʔet nafshəkhem: if it is on your souls, if you are in favor of this figʕu-li: put pressure on someone for me, urge someone to do something for me<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Peka dènge ne, ladhe na d'èi, na pahia dènge ja'a loe na, Makpela, dhu ètu karasa oka na. Na manèngi ca ngaa èèna ka, ja'a tihe. Ja'a neo tihe pama'ète kab'ua na, ètu madha miu aa'i-aa'i mi, sèna ka rai èèna j'aj'i unu ja'a. Ja'a neo tao era èèna, j'aj'i mi ro'a dhèu madhe ji'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>Tell him that, if possible, he should sell me his cave, Makpela, which is next to his field. Whatever he asks, I will pay. I want to pay its price in full, in front of all of you, so that the land becomes my property. I want to make that place, to be a burial place for our-exc people (OR grave for our dead people).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tua tana = 1) (manusia), 2)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">tua tana = 1) (manusia), 2) also tukang songgo; 9: tihe = bayar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məʕarat: cave qaseh: the end, the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">məʕarat: cave qaseh: the end, the border, far end. Efron has a field in the Makpelah area, on the east side of Hebron, and the cave is located at the far end of the field from Hebron<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>maleʔ: full; full price, what it is worth yittənennah liy: for him to give it (fem, the cave) to me<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Lod'o èèna, Efron madhèdi ètu era èèna kahèi, dènge dhèu-dhèu Het sèra. Ka na tadèngi kahèi lii padhai lii Abraham deo na. Hèia na kèd'i titu, ka na b'ala Abraham ètu madha dhèu heka aa'i-aa'i ra ètu sèra, aku nèngu na,<bt>At that time, Efron was also sitting there among the Het people. So he had also heard what Abraham had said. Then he stood up and responded to Abraham in front of all the elders, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yoshev: sitting among"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yoshev: sitting among</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />&lt;&lt;Baku sèmi èèna, ama! Sèmi ne'e ka laa! Oka dènge loe Makpela èèna, ja'a hia iia ama. Sèna ka mu padhane dhèu èmu èu mi èèna. Ja'a pangèd'u rai èèna mi ama, ètu madha dhèu-dhèu ja'a se. Sèna ka rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i sakasii!&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;Not like that, father! Like this! The field and the cave of Makpela, I just give it to father. So that you can bury your spouse there. I turn over that land to father, in front of all my people here. So that they all are witnesses!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="extremely polite, Near Eastern courtesy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">extremely polite, Near Eastern courtesy</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ka Abraham pacud'u kètu hari mi dhèu Het se.<bt>Then Abraham bowed-head again in front of the Het people.</bt><v n="13" />Hèia na peka dènge Efron, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi èèna oo, be'a kahèi. Te ngaa miu nanene lii ja'a, la ma. Ja'a neo hèli pama'ète rai na, sèna ka j'aj'i era padhane dhèu-dhèu ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he spoke to Efron, saying, &lt;&lt;That would also be good. But please listen to what I have to say. I want to pay for that land in full, so that it becomes a burial place for my people.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rai udhu rui = tempat kuburan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">rai udhu rui = tempat kuburan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="akh: assurance or emphasis, surely, indeed,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">akh: assurance or emphasis, surely, indeed, only do this lu: oh that I might, let me do this<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>shəmaʕeni: lissen to what I have to say</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14-15" />Hèia, aku Efron na, &lt;&lt;Rai èèna, kab'ua na, dhoka èpa ngasu doi pudhi di. Guna ngaa èdhi dua ti padhue kab'ua rai ciki oo'e èèna, dhu sasoa na aad'o. De lamu ka, ho mèti dhèu madhe na, sèna ka padhane ne ètu nèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then said Efron, &lt;&lt;That land, its price, is only 400 silver coins. What use is it for the two of us to bargain over such a small price, which has no meaning. So go, fetch your dead person, so that you can bury her there.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔarbaʕ meʔot sheqel-kesef: 400 silver shekels"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔarbaʕ meʔot sheqel-kesef: 400 silver shekels is way overpriced; Efron is screwing Abraham and Abraham and everybody else know it, but because of the death nobody says anything. Maybe he was a used car salesman. There werenʔt many (if any; coins may have come from Anatolia around the 5th or 6th centuries BC) coins in use in Abraham's day; silver and gold were handled by weight, as in the gold rush days in the U.S. and Australia. The weighing unit was called the "shekel", around 12 grams or just under a half ounce by our weights. That would come to around $1,000 if we were to buy that much silver today, but its buying power was a lot more then beni ubenkha mah-hiʔ: between me and you, what's 400 shekels worth of silver? The implication is "no big deal, donʔt mention it"<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ka Abraham d'èi kahèi dènge kab'ua na sange èèna, madhutu sèmi lii Efron. Hèia ètu madha dhèu ae-ae sèra, na ige nare doi pudhi èpa ngasu, tihe kab'ua rai èèna mi Efron.<bt>So Abraham agreed to the price of that land, following what Efron had said. So, in front of all those people, he counted out 400 pieces of silver money, and paid the price of that land to Efron.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishmaʕ: he heard, in this case"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yishmaʕ: he heard, in this case he agreed to the deal. yishqol: weighed out the silver<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>ʕover: crossing over, passing; at the current rate for silver lasocher: for the merchant, buying-agent; Abraham weighed out silver at the going price of silver, equivalent to the standard shekel weight, which was around 1/2 ounce or 12 grams. He probably had a respected merchant bring his personal weight and use that for the weighing in front of everybody<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17-19" />De dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, Abraham abhu dènge rai ne nèti Efron, j'aj'i mi unu na. Rai na nuka ètu Makpela, padètu dènge Mamre (nuka Hebron). Na hèli pama'ète rai ne dènge oka na, dènge loe na, aa dènge aj'u aa'i-aa'i ra. Dhèu-dhèu heka nèti suku Het, aa'i-aa'i ra ka dhu j'aj'i sakasii, peka na, rai èèna dènge isi aa'i-aa'i j'aj'i le unu Abraham.<bt>So, in that way, Abraham obtained that land from Efron, to be his property. That land was at Makpela, near Mamre (that is Hebron). And he paid off the land with its field, and its cave, and all its trees.The elders of the tribe of Het were all witnesses, that, the land with all its contents had become Abraham's property.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Èle èèna ka, Abraham la'e padhane Sara ètu d'ara loe èèna, ètu rai Kana'an.<bt>After that, Abraham went and buried Sara in that cave in the land of Kana'an.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaqam (qwm): it came to be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yaqam (qwm): it came to be lifne: before, facing; spatial, no motion<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>bkhol-gvulo: in all its boundary (gbl establish a boundary around an area, share a boundary with) saviv (as adverb): in a circuit; all around<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>lmiqnah: as an acquisition by purchase, made over to Abraham by purchase. The collective memory of the witnesses was the deed to the land, since there was no way of writing it down.</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Dènge sèmi èèna, dhu uru èèna oka dènge loe na unu dhèu Het, limuri ne j'aj'i le rai unu Abraham. Ka na tao j'aj'i mi era udhu rui ra.<bt>In that way, what had previously been a field with its cave the property of Het people, now became land owned by Abraham. And he made it into their burial ground.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="***"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">***</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="laʔachuzzat-qever: as the property for a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">laʔachuzzat-qever: as the property for a grave-site End of S section.<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tenge dhèu èmu hia Isak<bt>Looking for a wife for Isak</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="24" />
      <v n="1" />Tèu-tèu mamuri Abraham madhera titu kèna. LAMATUA ladhe-leru ne dènge be'a, aa hia ne mamuri dènge mera-milu.<bt>The years of Abraham's life were very long. The LORD looked after him well, and gave him life and peace-prosperity.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="berakh: had bestowed power for success,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">berakh: had bestowed power for success, prosperity, fertility bakol: in all different ways. enumerate?<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2-3" />Abraham dhu dènge dhèu èci dhu na lèka ho ladhe-leru mèdha-panyau na. Ca lod'o, Abraham paroa nare, ka peka dènge ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mu pasa dhilu èu paie-iie! Ja'a manèngi sèna ka èu subha madhe dènge kolongara LAMATUA.<bt>Abraham had a person whom he trusted to manage/oversee his belongings. One day, Abraham summoned hims and told him, saying, &lt;&lt;Put on your ears to pay careful attention! I ask that you swear a death oath [=serious consequences or death if oath broken] using the name/reputation of the LORD.</bt><note reference="24:2-3" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Ibrani, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tao kacui-aai èu mi d'ara sanga ja'a.&gt;&gt; Sasoa na, subha madhe.<bt>According to the Ibrani language, it says &lt;&lt;Put your hand in my crotch.&gt;&gt; It means, swear a death-oath.</bt></note>Nèngu ka, Ama Lamatua dhu tao dedha-liru dènge rai-haha ne. Dhu peka na, èu bisa boe more ana bhèni nèti dhèu Kana'an, ho paleo dènge ana ja'a Isak.<bt>He is the God who made heaven and earth. (An oath) Which says, you will not take a woman from the Kana'an people, to marry with my child Isak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zqan: old; oldest in years? longest"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">zqan: old; oldest in years? longest association with Abraham? moshel (partcpl): the one who was in charge<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>tachat yərekhi: under my thigh: the fleshy portion of the upper thigh, area of sexual organs, around to the hip-socket and butt. Hand placed there in making oaths during the period of the patriarchs and probably earlier. The idea is that one is swearing an oath by his posterity, or saying that if he doesn't do what he promises, may his own posterity be cut off. ʔashbiyʕəkha (shbʕ hif): I will make you swear<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>bayahweh: swear by Yahweh, ask Yahweh to make sure you do everything you are about to promise, or else exchange w/consultant: [MC] When do you leave this descriptive name in small letters and when do you put it in caps? [JEG] YHWH ʔəlohey hasshamayim vəʔəlohey haʔarets ʔYahweh, god of the heavens and god of the earthʔ doesn't occur anywhere else. If we put the verb "stay" in it, then it's clearly a description of which god he means, not a trade marked name.<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Te ngaa èu hud'i lamu ku asa rai èta-èsu ja'a, asa a'ari ja'a. Ho tenge ètu rèngu sèi, ana bhèni ca dhèu, ho mu paleo dènge ana ja'a ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>But, you must go to my country/land/village of origin, to my relations. You will look among them there, for a young-woman for us-inc to marry to my child.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dara sanga = lelak = between"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">dara sanga = lelak = between thighs, pohon paha</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔel ʔartsi vʔel-moladti: hendiadys, to my"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔel ʔartsi vʔel-moladti: hendiadys, to my land and my origin (moladti is not "my family", it's "my birthplace")</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia dhèu sab'a ne karèi Abraham, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Be'a, ama! Te ngaa, sèmi ana bhèni na d'èi boe mai asa ne'e, na tasamia? Ladhe sèmi èèna, hud'i ja'a kèti ana ama ku, ho hia ne leo-èmu ètu nèi, do tasamia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the worker asked Abraham, saying, &lt;&lt;Fine, father! But what if that young-woman doesn't want to come here? If that's the case, should I take father's son there to marry yonder, or what?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔulai: expression of hope, entreaty, fear;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔulai: expression of hope, entreaty, fear; perhaps toʔveh (ʔbh): is willing<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>hehashev ʔashiv (shwv hif inf abs): take somebody back, bring somebody back yatsaʔta: you came away from<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Hèia, aku Abraham na, &lt;&lt;Èu nanene paie! Masi ka tasamia èèna ka, mage èu mèti ana ja'a ne, asa nèi kahèi!<bt>Then, said Abraham, &lt;&lt;You listen carefully! No matter what happens, you must not take my child yonder!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishshamer ləkha (nif impv): be on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hishshamer ləkha (nif impv): be on your guard, be careful</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Mu sanèd'e, te LAMATUA dhu nèd'u koasa ètu dedha-liru, ka dhu lere ja'a nèti rai èta-èsu ja'a, asa dedha-rai ne'e ne. Aa dhu Na pa'èki le lii pajaji dènge ja'a, dhu peka na, &lt;Èèna na, Ja'a hia rai ne aa'i-aa'i mi ana-èpu èu.&gt; De èu baku madha'u. Sad'i lamu. Te èèna na, Lamatua pua ana pajuu Na nèti sorga, mai bhoke j'ara hia èu, sèna ka èu paraga dènge ana bhèni, dhu èèna na j'aj'i dhèu èmu ana ja'a.<bt>Remember that the LORD who holds power/authority in heaven, is the one who escorted/led me from the land of my origins, to this land here. And He is the one who bound a promise with me, saying, &lt;Later, I will give this entire land to your descendants.&gt; So you should not fear. Just go. Cuz later, the Lord will send His servant/underling from heaven, to come open the way for you, so that you can encounter the woman who will become the spouse of my child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔerets moladti: compresses Verse 4, the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔerets moladti: compresses Verse 4, the land of my birth</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Te ngaa ladhe ana bhèni na d'èi boe mai asa ne'e, lii soo-subha ne lèke boe èu. Masi ka tasamia na, èu bisa boe mèti ana ja'a asa nèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But, if that woman does not want to come here, this oath is no longer affecting you. No matter what happens, you cannot take my child yonder.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niqita (nqh nif) you are exempt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">niqita (nqh nif) you are exempt from, free from the obligation of the oath raq: only<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Hèia dhèu ne, ded'e subha dènge Abraham, ka na peka, èèna na, nèngu tao madhutu dad'èi Abraham aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Then this person, put up an oath with Abraham, and said that he would do according to the whole will of Abraham.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ka dhèu èèna pili nare badha onta canguru ngi'u. Hèia na hua rupa-rupa mèdha dhu kab'ua asa dedha onta se. Hèia la'e ka asa kota Nahor, ètu rai Mesopotamia.<bt>And that person chose 10 camels (loan). Then he loaded various kinds of expensive things on top of these camels. Then he went toward the city of Nahor, in the land of Mesopotamia.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="migmale ʔadonaw: from his master's camel"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">migmale ʔadonaw: from his master's camel herd khol-Tuv: all sorts of the best things of his master, the choice stuff. Does the bride price need to be spelled out here, or only in v 53?<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>bəyado: in his hand, under his control</Message></Annotation><note reference="24:10" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Ibrani, ngara era èèna, <span class="Italic">Aram-Naharaim</span>. Limuri ne, era èèna ètu Siria re bèka badae.<bt>According to the Ibrani language, the place is called <span class="Italic">Aram-Naharaim</span>. These days, the place is in the north part of Siria.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Nèbhu-nèbhu ka mone ne d'ai kota èèna. Hèia na ae kabhèsu dènge onta sèra ètu sebhe kota èèna, dètu dènge madha èi èci. Na ae èèna d'ara lod'o nihia le, ropa ana bhèni-ana bhèni kota èèna mai rara èi ètu madha èi èèna.<bt>Eventually the man arrived at that city. Then he stopped to rest with his camels at the edge of that city, near a well. He stopped when it was late afternoon, when the girls of the city came to fetch water at that well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="After some days he finally arrived"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">After some days he finally arrived at his destination. It's over 300 miles with a lot of rough country, so even riding camels it could have taken 10 days to 2 weeks each way yavrekh (brk hif): caused to kneel down<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>bʔer: deep dug hole with water. At this one they let clay jars holding 5 or 10 gallons down into the hole with a rope, let them fill, and pulled them back up, or else went down steps inside and climbed back up ʕet: time<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>tseʔt (ytsʔ inf): to go out shoʔəvot (partcpl): the women going to draw water<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Hèia dhèu ne sabaj'a, peka na, &lt;&lt;LAMATUA, Èu ka dhu j'aj'i Ama Lamatua nèti lamatua ja'a, Abraham. Bhoke j'ara hia ja'a, sèna ka kakako ja'a ne dènge kab'ua. Pad'elo sasue Èu mi lamatua ja'a, aa baku bhèlu lii pajaji ne dènge ja'a. De hia la ja'a paraga dènge ana bhèni dhu èèna na j'aj'i dhèu èmu Isak.<bt>Then the person prayed, saying, &lt;&lt;LORD, You are the one who is God to my master, Abraham. Open the way for me, so that my journey is successful (achieves its value). Show Your love to my master, and do not forget his promise to me [from TH &amp; CEV/TEV, TWOT Heb. /hesed/ is "loyalty...fidelity to covenantal obligations real or implied...freely given...kindness...on the basis of a relationship...lovingkindness"; Speiser "true loyalty"; referring to Abraham's promise that God would look after the servant in vs.7 here. (/hesed/ in v12, 27, (42 success), 49, (56 success)]. So, allow/cause me to meet the female who will become Isak's spouse.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Nahum Sarna points out that this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Nahum Sarna points out that this is the first time somebody calls out to Yahwe. No priest, no offering, no special posture. Just hinneh "well, here I am" haqreh-naʔ (qrh hif): let something happen, set things up; make them go well for me<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>lfanay (pl): before me, ahead of me ʕaseh-chesed: act in loyalty to the community<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Lamatua, ja'a ka titu ètu karasa madha èi ne. Aa ana bhèni-ana bhèni nèti kota ne, mai rara èi ètu ne'e.<bt>Lord, I am standing here beside this well. And the girls from this city are coming to fetch water here.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nitstsav (ntsb nif partcpl): while I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nitstsav (ntsb nif partcpl): while I am standing here, make something happen. Gunkel -- complete trust in God plus worldly wisdom. ʕal-ʕen hamayim: here it's a spring, but later it's a dug well; probably a spring made into a well by digging a hole that would hold the water coming out of the spring to make it easier to get it by letting a clay pot down on a rope or going down steps<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>bnot ʔanshe haʕir: young women old enough to get married; 12 to 15 years mostly, and responsible to their fathers yotsʔot (qal partcpl): are coming out<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />De ja'a manèngi sèmi ne'e: ladhe ja'a padhai lii dènge ana bhèni èci, peka na, &lt;Ana, ee! Papuru ku èru èi èu hia ja'a kinu.&gt; Ho ladhe na dhaa, peka na, &lt;Ama, minu la! Aa, pe ja'a hia dènge onta ama, rinu hèi!&gt; J'ara ne'e ne j'aj'i tadha dhu peka na, ana bhèni ne ka dhu Ama Lamatua paj'uj'u, j'aj'i mi dhèu èmu Isak! Dènge tadha sèmi ne'e, ja'a ke'a na Lamatua pad'elo le babe'a mi Abraham, lamatua ja'a èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>So, I ask like this. If/when I speak to a girl, saying, &lt;Child, ee! Lower your water jar for me to drink.&gt; If she responds, saying, &lt;Father, go ahead and drink! And I will give drink to father's camels as well!&gt; This way will be a sign, which says/indicates, this is the girl whom God has designated to become Isak's spouse! With a sign like that, I (will) know that the Lord has shown goodness/grace/favour to Abraham, my master.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** KM"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">*** KM</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nəʕar (qri hanʕarah): the girl (usually"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nəʕar (qri hanʕarah): the girl (usually masculine, read as feminine) hati-naʔ (nth hif): cause to incline, tip the water jar a bit so water will pour out<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>kadekh: your large pottery jar for water -- tall clay pot that held 3 to 5 gallons or even more ʔeshteh: and I will drink. Imperative + wa + imperfect = let down your jar so I may drink<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʔashqeh (shqh hif): I will give a drink to your camels too. Ten camels who have just crossed the desert can drink up a huge amount of water! John has a figure of 25 gallons per camel. hokhachta (ykch hif): you give judgment, determine, assign<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʕositi chesed: you have acted in solidarity, faithfulness, loyalty, with someone. Gordon Clark, collocations of chesed with ʔemet.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu sab'a Abraham paraga dènge Ribka<bt>Abraham's worker meets Ribka</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15-16" />Dhu na sabaj'a nare mèka, ana bhèni ca dhèu mai. Ngara na Ribka. Nèngu ne, èpu nèti ari Abraham, nuka Nahor, dènge dhèu èmu na, Milka. Ama Ribka, ngara na Betuel. Ribka ne, bhèni iia nia boe, aa pa'èci nèdhi mèka dènge mone. D'ai era èèna, puru asa d'ara èi la'e, ka na isi èru èi na. Nèbhu boe, ka ca'e mai sa dedha.<bt>Before he finished praying, a girl came. Her name was Ribka. She was a granddaughter of Abraham's younger-sibling, that is Nahor, with his spouse Milka. Ribka's father was named Betuel. This Ribka, was very female-beautiful, and had never joined with a male. When she reached that place, whe went down into the well, and whe filled her water jug. She soon came back up top.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kad: baked clay pot that holds"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">kad: baked clay pot that holds 5 or 10 gallons, used all over that part of the world for water Terem: before<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>killah (klh piʕel): he finished hinneh: here she comes<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>yulldah (yld qal pass): was born to Betuʕel shikhmah (shkhem): her shoulders. Usually refers to both shoulders, including the neck and the upper part of the back<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>Is the genealogy clear? Abraham and Nahor were brothers. Nahor married Milkah. They had a boy Betuʕel. Betuʕel was Rebecca's father. So Isaac and Rebecca were first cousins once removed in English terms, because Betuʕel and Isaac were first cousins. tovah marʔeh: beautiful to look at<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>bətulah: a girl old enough for sex, but either still a virgin or a young widow still of marriagable age, so still her father's responsibility tered (yrd): she went down<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>haʕaynah: the spring. Where the water came out, people had dug a hole big enough for the water to collect in, with a path or steps down from ground level. She would have climbed down inside, filled up the clay pot from the small pool at the bottom, and then climbed out carrying the clay pot full of water</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00668c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ropa nare dedha, ka dhèu sab'a Abraham èèna, la'e padètu dènge ne. Hèia na manèngi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ana. Hia ku ja'a kinu ciki.&gt;&gt;<bt>When she reached the top, Abraham's worker approached her. Then he asked, saying, &lt;&lt;Child. Give me a little to drink.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayarats: he ran (might mean he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayarats: he ran (might mean he hurried) liqraʔtah (qrʔ II): to meet her, toward her, to come to her<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>hagmiʔini (gmn hif impv): let me sip; not the same words he used in his prayer. Could be he's really excited by how quickly God answers his prayer. gamaʔa is a swallow at most. mʕat: a little bit<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ka na dhaa, &lt;&lt;Minu la, ama!&gt;&gt; Hèia na papuru ka èru èi na, ka na hia dhèu ne ninu.<bt>Then, she responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Just drink, father!&gt;&gt; Then she put down her water pot, and she let the person drink.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təmaher: she hurried tored (yrd hif):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">təmaher: she hurried tored (yrd hif): she took down<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>tashqehu (shqh hif): let him drink</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Ropa ninu èle, ka ana bhèni ne peka na, &lt;&lt;Pe ja'a laku dhui hari èi, sèna ka hia onta ama se, rinu toke bècu.&gt;&gt;<bt>After drinking, the girl said, &lt;&lt;I will scoop/fetch more water so your camels can drink until full.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tkhal (klh piʕel): she finished ləhashqoto"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tkhal (klh piʕel): she finished ləhashqoto (shqh hif inf): letting him drink<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>ʔeshʔav: I will draw water ʕad: until<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>killu (klh piʕel): they are finished</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ka la'e bhori èi dhu risi, asa d'ara karab'a badha. Hèia na ca'e-la'e mai pèri-pèri hari, dhui èi, ho hia onta se rinu toke bècu.<bt>Then she poured the remaining water into the feeding-drinking trough for animals. And she went up and down several times, fetching water, to let the camels drink until full.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tmaher: she hurried, did something quickly."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tmaher: she hurried, did something quickly. Verb where English would use an adverb. təʕar (ʕrh piʕel): she poured out<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>shoqet: watering trough tishʔav: she drew water<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>Camels just in off the desert can drink a huge amount of water! 25 gallons</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Te ngaa dhèu sab'a Abraham, titu ka mau-mau, na taru kira ka ana bhèni ne sab'a. Ka na pangee ètu d'ara na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ele boe nèngu èèna ka ne'e, dhu Lamatua paj'uj'u.&gt;&gt;<bt>But, Abraham's worker, stood silently and studied (KM loan) how the girl was working. And he thought to himself, saying, &lt;&lt;She is probably the one whom the Lord has designated.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhui 2 = timba; 20: karab'a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">dhui 2 = timba; 20: karab'a = feeding-drinking trough for animals; 21: taru kira = perhatikan (loan)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishtaʔeh (shʔh hitp ptcpl cs): was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mishtaʔeh (shʔh hitp ptcpl cs): was standing there gazing at her. Have to make sure nothing in the interaction implies that the luna was interested in exploiting her sexually, or that he was quiet because he was angry -- nothing negative. He was watching quietly to see if she was the right one. "with bated breath" machərish (chrsh hif ptcpl): keep still; silently, not saying anything<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ladaʕat (ydʕ inf): to know hahitsliach darkho (tslch hif): interrogative heth, whether [God would] bring his trip to a successful conclusion, make it succeed<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ʔim-loʔ: or not.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Onta se rinu toke bècu. Hèia dhèu ne nare kadheli sahènga, dènge kanau ca pasa. Mèdha se dhu tao nèti hualaa. Ka na pasa mi sahènga dènge pasaluu mi ai kariu dènge g'ana ana bhèni ne.<bt>The camels drank until full. Then the person took a nose ring, and a pair of bracelets. These things were made from gold. And he fastened her nostril with the ring and slipped-the-bracelet on the left and right hand of the girl.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nezem: nose ring beqaʕ: half-shekel, 1/4"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nezem: nose ring beqaʕ: half-shekel, 1/4 ounce of gold, now worth about $88, probably more at that time<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>mishqalo: its weight tzmidim: woman's bracelets<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>yadeah (dual): her two hands, arms, wrists ʕasarah zahav: ten shekels of gold, 5 ounces, now worth about $1,765, probably more at that time<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>mishqalam: their weight (2.5 ounces each)</Message></Annotation><note reference="24:22" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Ibrani, peka na, &lt;kadheli sahènga hualaa èèna, babia na ca tenga <span class="Italic">syekel</span> (nuka 6 baj'u)&gt;. Aa kanau dua sèra, babia ra &lt;10 <span class="Italic">syekel</span> (nuka 114 baj'u)&gt;.<bt>According to the Ibrani language, it says &lt;a gold nose-ring weighing a half <span class="Italic">syekel</span> (that is 6 grams)&gt;. And, the two gold bracelets weighed &lt;10 syekel (same as 114 grams)&gt;. [<span class="Italic">Yes! These goldsmiths have a native word for "gram".</span>]</bt></note><v n="23" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu ne karèi ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ana, ama mu, ngara na cee? Ladhe mo'o, na ja'a manubha taha ètu èmu ama mu.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, the person asked her, saying, &lt;&lt;Child, what is your father's name? If you are favourable, I would like to overnight temporarily at your father's house.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kadheli = cincin ; pasaluu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">kadheli = cincin ; pasaluu = slip over (finger, wrist) ; baj'u = gram (for weighing gold)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bat-miy: daughter of who? hagidi naʔ"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bat-miy: daughter of who? hagidi naʔ li (ngd hif impv): put me into the picture, clue me in<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>hayesh: is there? with interrogative h- lalin (lyn inf): to spend the night. Variant spelling to dissimilate from "lanu"<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Hèia na dhaa, &lt;&lt;Ngara ama ku, na Betuel. Aa ngara baki ku, Nahor. Dènge ngara bèi ku, Milka.<bt>So she responded, &lt;&lt;My father's name is Betuel. And my granfather's name is Nahor. And2 my granmother's name is Milka.</bt><v n="25" />Ètu èmu ji'i, era j'unu ae, de d'ai miu j'unu. Aa j'u'u ae kahèi, ho hia badha miu se ra'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>At our-exc house there are many places to sleep, enough for you-pl to sleep. And there is also much grass, to give to your animals to eat.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="She informs him that they have"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">She informs him that they have plenty, but she isn't the one who can invite him in. teven: chopped stalks of wheat for the animals to eat; straw<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>miSpoʔ: fodder for donkeys lalun: regular form, not dissimilated as in verse 23. Rashi reads "lalin" as "one night's lodging" and "lalun" as "many nights."<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Hèia dhèu sab'a ne pahaha iisi ho mangaj'i mi LAMATUA.<bt>Then the worker humbled himself/bowed to worship the LORD.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqqod (qdd): bowed down, kneeled down"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiqqod (qdd): bowed down, kneeled down (always followed by hishtachva). yishtachu (chvh hishtafal): bow down deeply, do obeisance<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Ka na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Koa-kio kolongara Lamatua! Ama Lamatua bhoke le j'ara hia ja'a, ka ja'a paraga le dènge a'ari lamatua ja'a Abraham ètu kabarai ne'e. Dènge j'ara ne'e, Lamatua pad'elo sasue Na mi lamatua ja'a, Abraham, aa tao madhutu sama sèmi lii pajaji na dènge ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>And he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Praise the name/reputation of the Lord! God has opened the way for me, and I have already with the relatives of my master/lord Abraham in this country/populace. In this way, the Lord shown His love to my master Abraham, and done according to his promise to me. [from TH &amp; CEV/TEV; TWOT Heb. /hesed/ is "fidelity to covenantal obligations real or implied"; referring to vs.7 here. Parallels vs.12; see discussion there].&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** KM"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">*** KM</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="loʔ-ʕazav: he does not abandon, forsake,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">loʔ-ʕazav: he does not abandon, forsake, leave, give up, be deficient in chasdo: obligation to him; loyalty to him<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>ʔamito: truth with him, faithfulness nachani (nchh): he leads me<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>ʔache: kinsmen, plural</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Èle èèna ka, ana bhèni ne rai la'e asa èmu, na lolo dènge isi èmu na ngaa dhu j'aj'i le èèna.<bt>After that, the girl ran to her house, and narrated to her household what had happened.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tarats (rwts imperf): run tagged (ngd"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tarats (rwts imperf): run tagged (ngd hif): announce<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>ʔimah: mother; why the mother's family, when the servant had inquired about the father's family?</Message></Annotation><v n="29-30" />Ana mone Ribka, ngara na Laban. Ropa Laban ladhe nèdhi mèdha hualaa se, aa na tadèngi lii lolo ana hèni na, ka rai asa li'u la'e. La'e soru dhèu sab'a Abraham dhu titu era dènge onta ra ètu madha èi.<bt>Ribka's brother, was named Laban. When Laban saw those gold things, and heard the report of his sister, he ran outside. He went to greet/welcome Abraham's worker who was still standing with their camels by the well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kirʔot ... kshamʕo: Infinitive construct. The"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">kirʔot ... kshamʕo: Infinitive construct. The seeing and hearing took place at the same time. Rashi "He cast his eye on the Mammon."</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Hèia Laban peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! LAMATUA ka dhu lere miu mai dènge karej'e-karae d'ai ne'e. De baku titu mi li'u ne! Mai lati sa èmu ji'i, te ji'i lalau ngare le kama. Nganga'a hia badha se, dhu tesa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Laban spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! the LORD is the one who led you-pl here in safety. So don't just stand outside here. Come to our-exc house, cuz we have already prepared room(s). Food for these animals is plentiful.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʔanokhi: since I have ... piniti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vʔanokhi: since I have ... piniti (pnh piʕel): clear up, fix up<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu sab'a Abraham lii d'ai Ribka hia Isak<bt>Abraham's worker asks to engage Ribka to Isak [=a step in wedding negotiations]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Hèia dhèu sab'a Abraham ne, madhutu dènge ka Laban, lasi èmu Betuel. Ka Laban si papuru mèdha-panyau nèti dedha onta se. Èle èèna ka, ra panga'a onta se. Rèti èi, hia dhèu sab'a dènge anga na se, ho rase haga.<bt>Then Abraham's worker followed Laban, going to Betuel's house. And Laban mob unloaded the belongings from on top of the camels. After that, they fed the camels. They brought water, giving it to the worker and his companions, to wash their feet.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yfatach (ptch piʕel): unsaddled the camls"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yfatach (ptch piʕel): unsaddled the camls for the evening, opened, loosened lirchots: to wash oneself<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="33" />Ropa lalau rare nganga'a-nginu ètu dedha mei, dhèu sab'a ne padhai lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i neo nga'a ne, te ngaa ja'a lole uuru ku, mamai ja'a ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>When they had prepared food-drink on the table, the worker spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;We are about to eat, but I wnat to first explain (the purpose of) my coming.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Laban dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama, mu padhai lii ngaa, na peka ka laa.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Laban responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Father, whatever you have to say, go ahead and say it.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiysam (qəriʔ for vayosam sym hof):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayiysam (qəriʔ for vayosam sym hof): was put, laid; kətiv yisem. The "u" vowel is written so that none of the consonant letters need be changed.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Hèia dhèu èèna peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, dhèu sab'a nèti baki miu Abraham.<bt>So then that person spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;I here, am your-pl grandfather Abraham's worker.</bt><v n="35" />LAMATUA hia Abraham, lamatua ja'a èèna, mèngi-nale ae titu kèna, ka na kaja-su'i. Lamatua pala-bagi ne doi hualaa pudhi dènge hualaa iia; ènu dhèu bhèni dènge dhèu mone, dènge badha-manu ae-ae, sèmi: sapi, onta, keled'ei, kahib'i-ka'ia, dènge kahib'i-kalèbho.<bt>The LORD has given my master Abraham a great many blessings, and he is extremely wealthy. The Lord has distributed to him gold money and silver; male and female slaves, and many animals, such as: cows, camels, donkeys, goats, and sheep.</bt><v n="36" />Lod'o lamatua ja'a se, bhèni-mone d'ai heka ku, ka Sara nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu. Nèngu ka dhu bèli-camèd'a unu aa'i pusaka ama na.<bt>When my male and female masters were very old, Sara gave birth to a son. He is the one who in the future will own the entire inheritance of his father.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Does &quot;fo my boss&quot; make sense?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Does "fo my boss" make sense? Or no need? vayitten-lo: "give him" in the sense of "set up for him to inherit"<span class="Italic">(36)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="37" />Ka Abraham pua ja'a subha, peka na, &lt;Mage èu more ana bhèni Kana'an kahèi, ho paleo dènge ana ja'a, Isak.<bt>So Abraham ordered me to swear-oath, saying, &lt;You may not take a Kana'an female, to marry my child Isak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yashbiʕeni (hif): he caused me to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yashbiʕeni (hif): he caused me to promise</Message></Annotation><v n="38" />Te ngaa èu hud'i more ana bhèni nèti a'ari ja'a unu ku, ho sèna ka j'aj'i dhèu èmu na.&gt;<bt>But, you must take a female from my own relatives, to become his spouse.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔim-loʔ: surely, but rather mishpachtiy: my"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔim-loʔ: surely, but rather mishpachtiy: my clan, my relatives<span class="Italic">(38)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Hèia ja'a karèi ne, aku ja'a na, &lt;Tasamia, ladhe ana bhèni ne, no'o boe madhutu ja'a mai sa ne'e?&gt;<bt>So I asked, saying, &lt;How about if this female does not want to accompany me here?&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔulay: expression of hope, entreaty, fear;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔulay: expression of hope, entreaty, fear; perhaps</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Ka na peka, &lt;LAMATUA dhu ja'a madhutu dad'èi Na, pe Na paleha ana pajuu Na nèti sorga, mai bhoke j'ara hia èu, sèna ka èu abhu ana bhèni ca dhèu nèti a'ari ja'a unu ku, ho j'aj'i mi dhèu èmu ana ja'a.<bt>And he said, &lt;The LORD whom I follow His will, will send His servant/underling from heaven, to come and open the way for you, so that you find a female from my own relatives, to become the spouse of my child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hitəhallakhti (hlk hitp): walk, my life"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hitəhallakhti (hlk hitp): walk, my life style, I conduct myself in his sight hitsəliach (hif): make something succeed, bring it to a successful conclusion<span class="Italic">(40)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="41" />Te ngaa ladhe a'ari ja'a se'e ro'o boe ana bhèni na mai asa ne'e, lii subha na lèke boe mi dedha èu ne.&gt;<bt>But, if my relatives don't want their daughter to come here, this oath is no longer binding on you.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔaz: then tinnaqeh (nqh nif): you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔaz: then tinnaqeh (nqh nif): you will be free from your oath, off the hook<span class="Italic">(41) (41) </span>meʔalati: from my curse, the charge I have laid on you naqi: clear of the responsibility, free from guilt<span class="Italic">(41)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Ka deo na, ropa ja'a d'ai madha èi èèna, ja'a manèngi-mangaj'i ètu d'ara, peka na, &lt;LAMATUA nèti lamatua ja'a Abraham. Bhoke ku j'ara hia ja'a, sèna ka mamai ja'a ne dènge kab'ua. Ho sèna ka ja'a abhu ana bhèni dhu èèna na j'aj'i dhèu èmu Isak.<bt>So just now, when I arrived at that well, I prayed to myself, saying, &lt;The LORD of my master Abraham. Open the way for me, so that my journey is successful. So that I find a female who will become Isak's spouse.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔim-yeshkha-naʔ matsliach: if there is a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔim-yeshkha-naʔ matsliach: if there is a successfull outcome you will bring about matsliach (tslch hif partcpl): causing my way to prosper<span class="Italic">(42) (42) </span>ʕaleyah (ʕlh? ʕal-h): the purpose for which (fem) I am making this trip</Message></Annotation><v n="43" />Lamatua, ja'a titu ètu sebhe madha èi ne. Aa ana bhèni-ana bhèni nèti d'ara kota ne mai rara èi ètu ne'e. De ja'a manèngi sèmi ne'e: ladhe ja'a peka dènge ana bhèni èci, aku ja'a na, &lt;&lt;Ana, ee! Papuru ku èru èi èu, ho ja'a kinu èi ciki.&gt;&gt;<bt>Lord, I am standing at the side of this well. And the young women of this city are coming and fetching water here. So, I ask like this: If I speak to a girl, saying, &lt;&lt;Child, ee! Lower your water jug, so I can drink a little.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nitstsav (ntsb nif partcpl): I am"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nitstsav (ntsb nif partcpl): I am standing haʕalmah: young girl of marriageable age, young woman up to when she has her first child (bətulah can be old enough to have been widowed; ʕalmah emphasizes young age)<span class="Italic">(43) (43) </span>lishʔov: to draw water hashqini: give me a drink<span class="Italic">(43) (43) </span>məʕaT: a little bit qaddekha: your water jar<span class="Italic">(43)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="44" />Ho ladhe na dhaa na, &lt;&lt;Oo. Minu! Aa èle na, ja'a panginu badha ama se kahèi!&gt;&gt; Ladhe j'aj'i madhutu sèmi lii ja'a ne, na èèna ka dhu j'aj'i tadha, ana bhèni ne ka dhu Lamatua paj'uj'u nare hia ana lamatua ja'a.&gt;<bt>If she responds, &lt;&lt;OK. Drink! And when you're done, I will give your animals to drink also!&gt;&gt; If it happens according to what I say, that will be a sign, that this female is the one whom the Lord has already designated her for the child of my master.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hokhiach (ykhh hif): determine, assign"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hokhiach (ykhh hif): determine, assign</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Ja'a dhu dhae èle mèka manèngi-mangaj'i, te Ribka dhu nare le era èèna nèti dènge èru èi na. Ropa na ca'e mai nèti d'ara èi, ja'a lii dènge ne, aku ja'a na, &lt;Ana, ee! Hia ku ja'a kinu èi ciki.&gt;<bt>I had not yet finished praying, and Ribka had come to that place bringing her water jug. When she came up from the water, I spoke to her, saying, &lt;Child, ee! Give me a little water to drink.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔəkhalleh (klh piʕel): I finished kadah:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔəkhalleh (klh piʕel): I finished kadah: large water pot<span class="Italic">(45) (45) </span>shikhmah: her shoulder tered (yrd): she went down<span class="Italic">(45)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="46" />Ka na papuru dènge ka èru èi na, ka na peka, &lt;Oo. Minu! Aa pe ja'a panginu onta ama se kahèi.&gt; Hèia ja'a kinu, aa onta ja'a se oo rinu kahèi.<bt>And she let down her water jug, and said, &lt;OK. Drink! And then I will give drink to your camels as well.&gt; Then I drank, and my camels also drank.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meʕaleyha: from on her shoulder tored"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">meʕaleyha: from on her shoulder tored (yrd hif): causes the thing to come down, lowers it<span class="Italic">(46) (46) </span>ʔesht (shth): I drank</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Ka ja'a karèi ne, &lt;Ama mu, ngara na cee?&gt;<bt>And I asked her, &lt;Your father, what is his name?&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka na dhaa, peka na, &lt;Ama ku, ngara na Betuel. Aa baki ku, ngara na Nahor. Dènge ngara bèi ku, Milka.&gt; Hèia ja'a papake ne kadheli mi sahènga na, dènge pasaluu kanau hualaa ca pasa mi ai kariu dènge ai g'ana na.<bt>And she responded, saying, &lt;My father is named Betuel. And my grandfather is named Nahor. And2 my grandmother is named Milka.&gt; So I cause her to wear a ring in her nose, and slipped a pair of gold bracelets on her left hand and right hand.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeshʔal: I asked for, demanded"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔeshʔal: I asked for, demanded</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="48" />Èle èèna ka, ja'a pacud'u kètu ho mangaj'i mi Lamatua, ka ja'a peka na, &lt;Koa-kio kolongara Lamatua! Lamatua bhoke le j'ara hia ja'a, nèti èèna ka, ja'a paraga le dènge a'ari lamatua ja'a Abraham ètu era ne'e ne. Aa paraga le kahèi dènge ana bhèni dhu èèna na j'aj'i dhèu èmu Isak!&gt;<bt>After that, I bowed my head to worship the Lord, and I said, &lt;Praise the name/reputation of the Lord! The Lord has opened the way for me, and because of that, I have me with the relatives of my master Abraham in this place. And I have also met with the female who will become the spouse of Isak!&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeqqod (qdd): I went down on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔeqqod (qdd): I went down on my knees Wenham: Genesis 11 says that Milcah is Haran's daughter. That means Rebecca is related to both of Abraham's brothers.<span class="Italic">(48) (48) </span>hinchani (hif nchh): led me, brought me bderekh ʔəmet: by the right road (but drk is not construct here). This (or the direct road) is the most common translation.<span class="Italic">(48) (48) </span>ʔəmet laqichat: to take continuing fidelity [?]</Message></Annotation><v n="49" />De ne'e ne, ladhe ama si neo pad'elo sasue mi lamatua ja'a Abraham, na mi peka pamèu dènge ja'a. Te ngaa ladhe aad'o, peka la mola-mola dènge ja'a. Ho ja'a ke'a, sèna ka tao hari ngaa.&gt;&gt;<bt>So now, if father mob want to show love to my master Abraham, na, speak plainly with me. But if not, speak openly with me. So I know what I should do now.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="peka mola-mola = kasi tau terus-terang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">peka mola-mola = kasi tau terus-terang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeshkhem: there is with you all"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yeshkhem: there is with you all ʕosim chesed (ʕsh ptc pl): act in loyalty. This may explain why the servant talks about linking up with his master's family, while Abraham himself did not say that.<span class="Italic">(49) (49) </span>ʔəmet: reliability, security, meeting obligation, lasting kindness, fidelity Imperative + imperfect: do it ... so I may ...<span class="Italic">(49) (49) </span>ʔefneh ʕal-yamin ʔo ʕal smoʔl: and I will turn to the right or the left; yes, or no and Iʔll explore other options; look for somebody else</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">A'ari Ribka sèmi lii karèi dhèu sab'a Abraham hia Isak<bt>Ribka's relatives accept the engagement of Abraham's worker for Isak</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50" />Ropa dhèu sab'a ne padhai lii nare, ka Laban dènge Betuel dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe LAMATUA dhu ad'u nare le madha j'ara ne, ji'i peka lii ngaa hari.<bt>When the worker had finished speaking, Laban and Betuel responded, saying, &lt;&lt;If the LORD is the one who has done this arrangment, what else can we-exc say.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaʕan: answer, singular with plural animate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yaʕan: answer, singular with plural animate NP OK yatsaʔ: came out<span class="Italic">(50) (50) </span>nowkhal (ykl): we are not able ; dabber (piʕel): to speak<span class="Italic">(50) (50) </span>raʕ ʔo tov: bad or good = there's nothing we can say one way or the other</Message></Annotation><v n="51" />Ribka ka ne'e ne. More ho mèti, sèna ka na j'aj'i mi dhèu èmu ana Abraham, madhutu sèmi dhu LAMATUA ator èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Ribka is here. Get her and take her, to become the spouse of the child of Abraham, according to what the LORD has arranged.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hineh rivkah: here is Rebecca tahi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hineh rivkah: here is Rebecca tahi ʔishah (hyh imperf): she will become the wife<span class="Italic">(51) (51) </span>diber yhwh: God hadnʔt said anything to the servant, but he was involved in the matter.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="52" />Ropa na tadèngi nare, dhèu sab'a ne pacud'u kètu d'ai rai, ka na manèngi makasi mi LAMATUA.<bt>When he heard that, the worker bowed his head to the ground, and he gave thanks to the LORD.</bt><v n="53" />Èle èèna ka, nare mèdha nèti hualaa iia dènge hualaa pudhi sèra, dènge mèdha-papake dhu saraga, ka na hia mi Ribka. Aa na hia kahèi mi ana mone na dènge ina na, mèdha-mèdha dhu kab'ua aae.<bt>After that, he took gold things and silver things, and beautiful things, and he gave them to Ribka. And he also gave to her brother and her mother, things of great value.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayotseʔ (ytsʔ hif): he took out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayotseʔ (ytsʔ hif): he took out migdanot (meged): rich gifts, excellent things<span class="Italic">(53)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="54" />Èle aa'i ka, heka dhèu sab'a ne dènge anga na madhèdi ra'a-rinu aa'i-aa'i ra. Ka ra j'unu ètu èèna. Bèli mad'ae èèna, dhèu sab'a ne palangu lii dènge lamatua èmu se, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hia ka ja'a ho lèpa la asa lamatua ja'a Abraham.&gt;&gt;<bt>When all that was done, only then did the worker and his companions all sit to eat-drink. And they slept there. The next day, the worker took his leave from the master of the house, saying, &lt;&lt;Release me to return to my master Abraham.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaliynu (lyn): they stayed overnight shalchuni"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yaliynu (lyn): they stayed overnight shalchuni (imperv): sent me back<span class="Italic">(54)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="55" />Te ngaa ana mone dènge ina ana bhèni na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Te neo hari lèpa lai-lai, tao ngaa ne? Hud'i Ribka pea hari ku dènge ji'i d'ai canguru lod'o sa laa ma, heka lami kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the brother and mother of the girl said, &lt;&lt;What is the hurry to go back? Let Ribka stay on for another 10 days or so, then go.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="teshev (yshb): stay yamim ʔo ʕasor:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">teshev (yshb): stay yamim ʔo ʕasor: a few days or a block of ten days, up to a ten-day period, or possibly ten months; a few days or ten; a year or 10 months<span class="Italic">(55)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="56" />Te ngaa dhèu sab'a èèna dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Waa! Baku kai ja'a! Te LAMATUA sue le ja'a, ka toke ja'a rage le bhèni dhu èèna na j'aj'i dhèu èmu Isak. De patabuli ka ji'i se, la'a peka ku dènge lamatua ji'i Abraham.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the worker responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Waa! Don't block/prevent me! Cuz the LORD has loved/shown mercy to me, and has allowed me to encounter the female who will become Isak's spouse. So release us-exc, to go speak to our master Abraham.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔal-taʔcharu ʔoti: donʔt delay me hitsliach"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔal-taʔcharu ʔoti: donʔt delay me hitsliach (tslch hif): cause to succeed<span class="Italic">(56)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="57" />Hèia ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e ka laa! Mai ti karèi Ribka, sèna ka te'a dad'èi na tasa mera mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they responded, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this! Let's ask Ribka, so we-inc can know what her desires are?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niqraʔ: we will call nishʔəlah (cohortative):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">niqraʔ: we will call nishʔəlah (cohortative): we will request it<span class="Italic">(57) (57) </span>et piah (peh): from her own mouth</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="58" />Hèia ra paroa ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ribka! Di aku èu kèna. Èu neo lamu dènge ka dènge dhèu ne'e do, tasamia?&gt;&gt;<bt>So they summoned her, saying, &lt;&lt;Ribka! It's just up to you. Do you want to go with this person, or how about it?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Ribka dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ko'o.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Ribka responded, saying, &lt;&lt;I want to.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hətelkhiy: will you go?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hətelkhiy: will you go?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Isak dènge Ribka paleo èmu<bt>Isak and Ribka marry</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="59-60" />Hèia ra hia Ribka dènge bhèni dhu leru ne karèi nèti ana iiki ka, ho lasi palere dènge dhèu sab'a Abraham sèra. Ka ra hia Ribka mèngi-nale, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i sanao-maena sèna ka Ama Lamatua hia èu mora iisi ana ae-ae, ho ana-èpu mu d'ai riho-kehi. Aa ji'i sanao kahèi, sèna ka ana-èpu èu sèra segi aa'i musu rèngu sèra!&gt;&gt;<bt>So they let Ribka and the woman who had cared for her from when she was small, go together with Abraham's workers. And they gave Ribka blessing, saying, &lt;&lt;We-exc hope (doublet) that God with let you bear many children, so your descendants reach the thousands. And we also hope that your descendants beat their enemies!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="riho-kehi = thousands"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">riho-kehi = thousands</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔach: sister, kinswoman meniqtah (ynq ʔnurseʔ"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔach: sister, kinswoman meniqtah (ynq ʔnurseʔ hif ptcpl): This woman was probably a slave who had taken over nursing Rebecca when she was a baby, and had worked for her ever since then. Named Deborah.<span class="Italic">(59) (59) </span>ʔat həyiy (hyh imperv): be! lʔalfe rvavah: one thousand times ten thousand (=10,000,000), more people than anybody can count<span class="Italic">(59) (59) </span>yiyrash ... et shaʕar: may you take possession of the gates, inherit, displace from land shaʕar: gate<span class="Italic">(59) (59) </span>sonʔaw: your [zarʕekha] enemy</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="Hk-lb\Lb00040c.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="61" />Èle èèna ka, Ribka dènge bhèni dhu leru nèngu na lalau ka mèdha ra, ka ra ca'e onta, pakèd'i dènge ka, madhutu dhèu sab'a Abraham sèra.<bt>After that, Ribka and the woman who had cared for her made ready their things, and they got on the camels, and left, accompanying Abraham's workers.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taqam ... tirkavnah: she got up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">taqam ... tirkavnah: she got up ... they rode telakhnah: they travelled<span class="Italic">(61) (61) </span>yiqqah ... et rivqah: he took Rebecca. It shouldnʔt imply that he left the other women behind. yelakh: he went<span class="Italic">(61)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="62" />Isak pea ètu rai Negeb. Lod'o èèna, na heka lèpa kèna nèti madha èi Beer Lahai Roi.<bt>Isak was living in the land of Negeb. At that time, he had not yet returned from the well at Beer Lahai Roi.</bt><v n="63" />D'ara lod'o nihia ca lod'o, na kalua nèti d'ara paleo na, la'e pasiar ciki. Ropa na boti kètu, na ladhe laa na onta-onta kako mai asa era nèngu na.<bt>Late afternoon one day, he came out from his tent/shelter, and went for a short stroll. When he lifted his head, he saw camels walking toward his place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lasuach (swch inf): unknown word, dictionary"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">lasuach (swch inf): unknown word, dictionary gives no meaning for it; unexplained, translations are only guesswork, hapax. REB "hoping to meet them", NLT "meditating", CEV "suddenly" basadeh: in the field, in the countryside<span class="Italic">(63) (63) </span>lifnot (pnh ʔturn, pass onʔ inf) ʕarev: as evening was coming on yissaʔ ʕeynayw: he lifted up his eyes, he took a look<span class="Italic">(63)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="64" />Ropa Ribka ladhe nèdhi Isak, hèia na puru lai-lai nèti dedha onta.<bt>When Ribka saw Isak, then she quickly got off from the camel.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tereʔ (rʔh): She didnʔt know yet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tereʔ (rʔh): She didnʔt know yet that it was Isaac, she just saw a man tifol (nfl): she got down quickly (could mean "tumbled" or "fell off", but probably doesn't here)<span class="Italic">(64)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="65" />Ka na karèi dhèu sab'a Abraham, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu mone cee ka mai nèi?&gt;&gt;<bt>And she asked Abraham's worker, saying, &lt;&lt;Who is that man coming yonder?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ridhu = lompat turun"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">ridhu = lompat turun</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka dhèu ne dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu na, ana lamatua ja'a kèna.&gt;&gt; Hèia Ribka nare salalu na, pa'abhe rèhu na.<bt>The person responded, saying, &lt;&lt;He is the child of my master.&gt;&gt; So Ribka took a shawl and covered her face.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hallazeh: this liqraʔtenu: toward us, coming"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hallazeh: this liqraʔtenu: toward us, coming up to meet us<span class="Italic">(65) (65) </span>tsaʕif: shawl, wrapper; possibly for general modesty, to show she was a modest person and not forcing herself on anybody. But a veil over the face was part of the marriage ceremony too, so this may have been her way of letting everybody know that she was ready to marry Isaac even if she had never seen him before in her life vatitkaS (kSh hitp): covered herself<span class="Italic">(65)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="66" />Ka dhèu sab'a ne lolo dènge Isak, aa'i-aa'i dhu j'aj'i le.<bt>And the worker narrated everything which he had encountered/experienced to Isak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəSafer (piʕel): tell all the details"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yəSafer (piʕel): tell all the details</Message></Annotation><v n="67" />Hèia Isak todhe nèti ka Ribka lasi asa d'ara paleo ina na, ka dua ra paleo ka èmu. Lula Isak sue seli eele Ribka, ka na susa heka dènge mamadhe ina na.<bt>Then Isak took Ribka into the tent/shelter of his mother, and the two of them wedded. Because Isak loved Ribka so much, he was no longer troubled with the death of his mother.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəviʔeah: he caused her to go"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yəviʔeah: he caused her to go inside yeʔəhaveha: he loved her<span class="Italic">(67) (67) </span>yinnachem (nchm nif): he was comforted, found consolation End of P section.<span class="Italic">(67)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abraham leo hari èmu<bt>Abraham marries again</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="25" />
      <v n="1" />Ka Abraham leo hari èmu dènge bhèni èci, ngara na Ketura.<bt>And Abraham married another woman, named Ketura.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayosef (hif): do something again. Some"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayosef (hif): do something again. Some commentators take this to have happened while Abraham was married to Sarah, when Esau and Jacob are around 15, partly by taking the references to concubines in verse 6 as including Keturah, since her children received no inheritance (the Code of Hammurabi stipulates that acknowledged children have the right to inherit), and partly because when the servant tells Laban that "my master has given everything to Isaac," it implies that Abraham is already dead and never met Rebecca. Neither point is without problems.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Hèia Ketura matana ana hia ne. Ana se, ngara ra: Simran, Yoksan, Medan, Midian, Isbak, dènge Sua.<bt>Ketura had children for him, These children were named: Simran, Yoksan, Medan, Midian, Isbak, and Sua.</bt><v n="3" />Ana Yoksan ka: Seba dènge Dedan. Ana-èpu Dedan nuka, dhèu Asyur, dhèu Letus, dènge dhèu Leum.<bt>Yoksan's children, were: Seba and Dedan. Dedan's descendants were, the people of Asyur, the people of Letus, and the people of Leum.</bt><v n="4" />Ana Midian ka: Efa, Efer, Henok, Abida dènge Eldaa. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i se, ana-èpu Ketura.<bt>The children of Midian were: Efa, Efer, Henok, Abida and Eldaa. These were all descendants of Ketura.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The Hebrew doesn't mention Abraham. It"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">The Hebrew doesn't mention Abraham. It could be that Moses is playing up the Keturah line as something distinct from the Isaac and Ishmael lines, or that he is playing down Abraham because Keturah's children have no inheritance rights from him.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5-6" />Lod'o dhu Abraham mamuri era, na hag'e nare le mèdha-panyau hia ana Hagar dènge ana-ana Ketura, èci-èci ka dènge unu na. Èle èèna ka, Abraham pua si lasi pea re bèka dhimu rai Kana'an, sèna ka ra pakaj'èu nèti ana na Isak. Ka pusaka na aa'i-aa'i, na pangèd'u mi ana na Isak.<bt>While Abraham was still living, he had selected possession to give to Hagar's child, and the children of Ketura, each with his own. After that, Abraham ordered them to go live on the eastern side of the land of Kana'an, so the they would be far from his child Isak. And all his inheritance, he turned over to his child Isak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hapilagshim: concubines. They had no dowry"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hapilagshim: concubines. They had no dowry or marriage contract, and their children had no rights to inherit. It may cover Hagar and Keturah, or possibly others. The Midianites, including Mosesʔ father-in-law, traced their lineage to Keturah. matanot: gifts as settlements, one time only, possibly seed money for a new start<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>vayshalchem (piʕel): send away bʕodenu: while he was still living<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abraham madhe<bt>Abraham dies</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7-8" />Lod'o umur Abraham d'ai 175 (ca ngasu pidhu nguru lèmi) tèu, na madhe.<bt>When the age of Abraham reached 175 years, he died.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʔeleh: these (used in a summary)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vʔeleh: these (used in a summary) yame shne-chaye Avraham: days of the years of the life of Abraham, his lifetime, period during which he functioned. This 4-term construct is rare, and is used here only, of Abraham. Ishmael in verse 12 gets only shne-chaye Avraham, as do others.<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>vayigwa vayamat: breathed his last and died bsevah: in gray-headedness (he had lived a good life for a long time)<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>vsaveaʕ: sated, satisfied, had plenty of what he wanted vayeʔasef ʔel-ʕamav: gathered together with his family; die. SS prefers the "ancesta" spelling for this and other -Vr words. One of the earliest mentions of the afterlife and conscious immortality. Sarna points out that this phrase occurs only in the Torah; "sleep with one's fathers" is in the later books. Used only for very prominent people. Does not mean "buried with forefathers," but "went to join their illustrious ranks"; it's used of people like Jacob who werenʔt actually buried until quite a while after this is said of them.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9-10" />Ka ana na, Isak dènge Ismael, padhane ne ètu d'ara loe Makpela, dhu padètu dènge Mamre. Rai ne, dhu uru èèna, Abraham hèli nare nèti Efron, ana Sohar, dhèu Het. Ka dhu uru èèna, ra padhane le Sara ètu d'ara loe èèna.<bt>And his children, Isak and Ismael buried him in the cave at Makpela, which was near Mamre. That was the land, which formerly, Abraham had purchased from Efron, the child of Sohar, the Het person. And previously, they had buried Sara in that cave.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqbəru: they buried. ʕal-pne: physically nearby,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiqbəru: they buried. ʕal-pne: physically nearby, as in Verse 18.<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>qubbar (puʕal): was buried</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Èle madha Abraham, ka Ama Lamatua hia mèngi-nale mi Isak, ka na mamuri mera-milu. Lod'o èèna, Isak pea dètu dènge madha èi Beer Lahai Roi.<bt>After Abraham died (After the eyes of Abe = Idiom), God gave blessings to Isak, and he lived in peace and prosperity. At that time, Isak was living near the well at Beer Lahai Roi.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Idiom"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">Idiom</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bəʔer lachay roʔi: Da Puka Wea"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bəʔer lachay roʔi: Da Puka Wea Da God Dass Alive Wen See Me End of S section.<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-èpu Ismael<bt>Ismael's descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ne'e ne, lii lolo nèti mamuri Ismael. Nèngu ne, ana Abraham dènge dhèu èmu limuri na, Hagar, dhu j'aj'i ènu Sara nèti Masir.<bt>This is the story of the life of Ismael. He was the child of Abraham and his younger spouse Hagar, who was Sara's slave from Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tolədot: life and times of somebody,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tolədot: life and times of somebody, sometimes translated as "generations" or "genealogy," but it usually includes more than that. The Joseph story is part of the life and times of Jacob, the last big section of Genesis, which also includes the story of Judah, the other prominent son of Jacob. This section here is not very big, but it wraps up what Genesis has to say about Ishmaʕel</Message></Annotation><v n="13-16" />Ana-ana Ismael, mone dhèu canguru dua. Ngara ra dhu madhutu nèti dhu uru tèka d'ai ana limuri tèka, nuka: Nebayot, Kedar, Adbeel, Mibsam, Misma, Duma, Masa, Hadad, Tema, Yetur, Nafis, dènge Kedma. Ana-ana sèra ka, j'aj'i bèi-baki nèti canguru dua suku, dhu èci-èci ka dènge kabarai ra. Ra pangare kabarai ra èci-èci, madhutu ngara bèi-baki ra.<bt>The children of Ismael, were 12 sons. Their names according to their order from oldest to youngest are: Nebayot, Kedar, Adbeel, Mibsam, Misma, Duma, Masa, Hadad, Tema, Yetur, Nafis, and Kedma. Their children became the forefathers of 12 tribes, each one with their own land/country. They named each of those countries according to the names of their forefathers.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lətowlədotam: in their birth order chatsrehem:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">lətowlədotam: in their birth order chatsrehem: by their settlements (without walls) -- may be a way of reminding the Jews that these people never built real cities<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>Tirotam: and by their tent camps (with stone walls) -- also to emphasize that they never amounted to much nəsiʔim: chiefs or minor kings<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>lʔumotam: their nations, tribes</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ropa umur Ismael d'ai 137 (cangasu tèlu nguru pidhu) tèu, ka na madhe.<bt>When Ismael's age was 137 years, he died.</bt><v n="18" />Te ngaa ana-èpu na sèra, èci pamusu dènge èci. Ka ra pea pahag'a, mulai nèti rai Hawila d'ai rai Syur, dhu palane dènge rai Masir, toke d'ai rai Asyur.<bt>But his descendants, each warred/fought with the other. And they lived scattered, beginning from the land of Hawila until the land of Syur, which borders on the land of Masir, on until reaching Asyur.</bt><note reference="25:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 16:12</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Esau dènge Yakob<bt>Esau and Yakob</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ne'e ne, lii lolo nèti mamuri Isak, ana Abraham.<bt>This is the story of the life if Isak, the child of Abraham.</bt><v n="20" />Lod'o Isak madhèdi dènge Ribka, umur na 40 (èpa nguru) tèu le. Ama Ribka, ngara na Betuel. Ana mone Ribka, ngara na Laban. Rèngu se, dhèu Aram, nèti Padan Aram.<bt>When Isak married Ribka, his age was already 40 years old. Ribka's father was named Betuel. Ribka's brother was named Laban. They were Aram people, from Padan Aram.</bt><note reference="25:20" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Padan Aram èèna, nuka Mesopotamia, ètu ca bèka badae d'ara rai Siria.<bt>That Padan Aram, is Mesopotamia at the north side of the land of Siria.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ribka dhu dènge mèka ana. Nèti èèna ka, Isak manèngi-mangaj'i mi LAMATUA, sèna ka Na bhoke era ana Ribka. Hèia LAMATUA tadèngi lii manèngi Isak, ka Ribka dènge babia.<bt>Ribka didn't yet have any children. Because of that, Isak prayed to the LORD, so that He would open Ribka's child place (=womb). Then the LORD heard Isak's request, and Ribka became pregnant.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʕtar: he pled, entreated, prayed lnokhach:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yeʕtar: he pled, entreated, prayed lnokhach: directly in front of, [pray] for<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ʕəqarah: barren yeʕater (nif): was moved by the entreaty<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>tahar (hrh): she became pregnant</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Te ngaa ana dhu Ribka kad'o ne, dhèu dua. Aa ana se paliku taruu ètu d'ara kabake ina ra. Ka Ribka ngee ka ètu d'ara na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka ana dua se, sèmi ne'e?&gt;&gt; Hèia na pakarèi dènge LAMATUA.<bt>But, the child that Ribka was pregnant with, was two people. And these children wrestled continually inside the belly of their mother. And Ribka thought to herself, &lt;&lt;Why are these two children like this?&gt;&gt; So she asked the LORD. [NOTE from UNS check-I overrode suggestion to go literal in the quote, as per NLT and CEV.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kad'o (2) = 1) bagian di"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">kad'o (2) = 1) bagian di kain di atas perut, 2) hamil, mengandung (kiasan) ; paj'èja = betendang (with bottom of foot) ; paliku = bagulat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayitrotsatsu (hitpolel): push each other around"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayitrotsatsu (hitpolel): push each other around (like sumo wrestlers?) bqirbah: in the inside of her body<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>ʔim-ken: if that's how it is lmah: why? painful pregnancy? threatened miscarriage? Or maybe (Calvin) it's the significance of the activity: If they are fighting now, is this a sign or prodigy of something worse? Syriac has "chayi" -- "If this is the way it is, why am I living?"<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>telekh lidrosh: go [where?] and turn in a petition to somebody</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ka LAMATUA dhaa, peka na,<bt>And the LORD responded, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ètu d'ara kabake èu na, abhu dua suku, dhu èèna na loe boe dènge pamusu.<bt>&lt;&lt;In your belly, there are two tribes, who in the future will not stop warring/mutually opposing/fighting.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhu limuri èra risi nèti dhu uru.<bt>The youngest will be stronger that the oldest.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Ka a'a na, lalau-lalo'o ari na.&gt;&gt;<bt>And the elder-sibling will serve/look to the needs of the younger-sibling.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lʔumim (lʔom): ethnic community, people (archaic)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">lʔumim (lʔom): ethnic community, people (archaic) mimeʕayika (meʕeh): from your belly, from inside you<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>yipparedu (nif): be apart, be cut off; separate themselves, be divided lʔom: people, ethnic community (old word)<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>yeʕəmats (imperf): will be strong, be stronger than (min) rav: the great one. Both terms in this context are referring to the family lines, not the two babies themselves. Alter: the subject is ambiguous, SVO or OVS (no object marker), like the Delphic oracle's speech; note the archaic wording.<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>tsaʕir: the younger one</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ropa lod'o d'ai, Ribka nara iisi ana mone dhèu dua.<bt>When her day arrived, Ribka gave birth to two sons.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tomim (toʔm pl): twins"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tomim (toʔm pl): twins</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Dhu a'a, isi na mea, dènge ngi'u na pènu dènge rèu. Nèti èèna ka, ra pangare ne, <span class="Italic">Esau</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;dènge rèu&gt;).<bt>The elder-sibling had red flesh/colour, and his body was full of body hair/fur. Because of that, they named him <span class="Italic">Esau</span> (which means &lt;with fur&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔadmoni: reddish (red-brown like dried blood)."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔadmoni: reddish (red-brown like dried blood). This is a reddish skin color, not hair color. In medieval times it was thought that there was something sinister about redheads, so Judas was portrayed with red hair. But then, David had red hair: 1Sam 16:12; 17:42. kʔaderet seʕar: like a fur or hair garment, mantle of hair<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>seʕar: hair of head, pubic hair, hair made into a garment like a camel hair coat or a goat hair tent yiqrəʔu: they [probably the parents] called him; compare v.<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Èle èèna ka, ari na heka kalua kèna. Te ngaa dhu na kèpe hui tèdhu a'a na. Nèti èèna ka, ra pangare ne, <span class="Italic">Yakob</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;hui tèdhu&gt;). Lod'o Ribka nara iisi ana na se, umur Isak 60 (èna nguru tèu) kèna.<bt>After that, his younger-sibling then came out. But, he was holding his elder-sibling's heel. Because of that, they named him, <span class="Italic">Yakob</span> (which means &lt;heel&gt;). When Ribka had given birth to these children of hers, Isak's age was 60 years.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hui tèdhu = tumit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">hui tèdhu = tumit</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔochezet (pt): hanging on to, grasping"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔochezet (pt): hanging on to, grasping baʕəqev: by the heel (unless it's a euphemeism for genitals as in Jeremiah 13:22)<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>yiqrʔu ... vayiqraʔ: they called him Esau ... &lt;one person?&gt; called him Jacob. Some texts regularize both to plural, others both to singular. The singular one can be taken as impersonal. No children for 20 years, almost as long as Abraham had to wait (25 years).<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob monya a'a na Esau<bt>Yakob tricks/deceives his elder-sibling Esau's</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Lod'o ana dua se kapai, Esau dhu ne'a mèu kasiro badha hui. Ae ka dhu na pea ètu d'ara j'ami. Te ngaa Yakob dhu mau-mau, dhu d'èi dhoka pea ètu d'ara èmu di.<bt>When the two children grew up, Esau was skilled at hunting wild animals. He often stayed in the matto. But Yakob was a silent type, who just liked to stay in the house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Jump in time from birth to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Jump in time from birth to at least adolescence, maybe even later. tsayid: game, hunting. Hunters are considered virile in our society, but at that time the contrast may have been between a stupid bumpkin that didnʔt have the sense to live a stable life and a smart pastoralist, who knew where his next meal was coming from because he controlled the animals.<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>sadeh: more likely conveys an undomesticated, untrammeled life rather than a rugged outdoorsman. tam: complete, orderly; peaceful, quiet; didnʔt make a lot of trouble. May imply that he had everything all together, self contained. The word is used of Noah to say that he was morally perfect. Here it might mean that Jacob was an ideal man of his time, which Esau wasnʔt. Probably doesn't mean that Esau was a real he-man and Jacob was a momma's boy. Karl Marx noted the frequency with which hunters and gatherers make the transition to a pastoral economy (there's evidence in East Africa that pastoral groups also transition back to hunting when ecological conditions shift JG); he overgeneralized it by elevating it to a principle, but it seems quite likely that at the time, Jacob seemed like the wave of the future (and Moses was part of that future, which Esau's descendants were not).<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>yoshev: living</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Isak d'èi na'a sisi badha hui. Nèti èèna ka, na sue risi Esau. Te ngaa Ribka sue risi Yakob.<bt>Isak liked to eat the meat of wild animals. That is why he loved Esau more. But Ribka loved Yakob more.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bfiw (peh): in his mouth From"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bfiw (peh): in his mouth From this point on, the second half of Genesis revolves around a long string of deceptions.<span class="Italic">(28)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00674c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Esau manèngi nganga'a nèti Yakob<bt>Esau requests food from Yakob</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ca lod'o, Yakob dhu tao bubur kab'ui, aa Esau heka lèpa nèti kasiro badha hui kèna. Na lèpa dènge manganga, ka roe titu kèna.<bt>One time, [when] Yakob was making bean stew, and Esau had just returned from hunting wild animals. He came home hungry, and was very weak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yazed: boiled, cooked nazid: a boiled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yazed: boiled, cooked nazid: a boiled dish (lentils, probably with spices). Commentators suggest Esau may have thought it was a meat stew or a blood broth because it was red.<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>ʕayef: exhausted, pooped; here it probably means famished.</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Ka na peka dènge Yakob, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ari, ee! Hia ku ja'a bubur kab'ui mea ciki ètu d'ara èru èèna, ho ja'a ku'a! Te ja'a manganga bia.&gt;&gt; (Nèti èèna ka, ra pangare na, <span class="Italic">Edom,</span> dhu sasoa na &lt;mea&gt;.)<bt>And he spoke to Yakob, saying, &lt;&lt;Younger-sibling, ee! Give me a little of that red bean stew in that clay-pot, so I can eat! Cuz I'm really hungry.&gt;&gt; (Because of that, they called him <span class="Italic">Edom,</span> which means &lt;red&gt;.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èi kua = broth ; kua"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">èi kua = broth ; kua ; èi kabhète = bubur (lit. air kental) ; kao = nasi</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="halʕiyteni (hif): let me gulp down."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">halʕiyteni (hif): let me gulp down. A coarse word, "devour." In Rabbinical times it was used for feeding animals, but in older Hebrew it didnʔt necessarily have that meaning.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ka, aku Yakob na, &lt;&lt;Be'a a'a. Te ngaa pasilu ku dènge hak a'a èèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>And, said Yakob, &lt;&lt;Good, older-sibling. But turn-over to me your elder rights first!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mikhrah (mkr imperv): sell The Jewish"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mikhrah (mkr imperv): sell The Jewish commentators see this as cleverness or gamesmanship, an astute move on Jacob's part. The birthright had to do with things the father had control over, like possessions. The blessing, which is what Esau really got furious about missing, had to do with things the father had no control over, so it was more like a prophecy or the expression of a wish.<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="25:31" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu ad'a rèngu, ana mone uuru, gati madha ama na, aa abhu pusaka ae risi nèti ari na si.<bt>Following their /adat/, the oldest male-child replaces his father, and gets more inheritance than his younger-siblings.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Hèia Esau dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hak a'a ne, ngaa kèna, hud'i nèngu sèna! Neo more, na more la. Te ja'a manganga bia. Sod'e mèti bubur èèna lai-lai mai, te ja'a taha heka.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Esau responded, saying, &lt;&lt;This elder rights, what's it good for? [idiomatic] If you want to take it, then take it. Cuz I am really hungry. Hurry up and spoon out that steew, cuz I can't stand it anymore.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sod'e = sendok (v) dgn irus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">sod'e = sendok (v) dgn irus (nsai) ; curu = sendok dgn yg kecil</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Te ngaa, aku Yakob hari na, &lt;&lt;Mata ku a'a! Èu subha uuru ku, dhu peka na, èu pangèd'u le hak a'a èèna mi ja'a ne.&gt;&gt; Ka Esau ded'e subha sèmi dhu Yakob peka.<bt>But spoke Yakob again, saying, &lt;&lt;Older-sib wait a second! You [must] swear-oath first that says you have turned-over those rights to me.&gt;&gt; So Esau lifted up an oath like Yakob said.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishshavʕah (shbʕ nif imperv): swear vayimkhor:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hishshavʕah (shbʕ nif imperv): swear vayimkhor: he sold<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="34" />Hèia Yakob sod'e dènge ka hia ne bubur kab'ui deo na dènge roti. Ropa na'a-ninu nare, ka la'e dènge ka.<bt>Then Yakob spooned out and gave him that aforementioned bean stew, and bread. When he had finished eating-drinking, then he left straightaway.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dènge j'ara ne'e ka, Esau pusi boe dènge hak a'a na.<bt>In that way, Esau did not care for his elder rights.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕədashim: lentils, Lens lens The verb"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕədashim: lentils, Lens lens The verb sequence describes Esau's flippant attitude: "and in so doing, he trashed the birthright."<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>yivez (bzh impf): he despised, treated with contempt, thought lightly of End of S section.<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Isak monya dhèu aae Abimelek<bt>Isak deceives king Abimelek</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="26" />
      <v n="1" />Ca tèka, ètu d'ara rai èèna, lèke tèu manganga, èci èèna ka dènge tèu Abraham mamuri era. Ka Isak la'e manèngi Abimelek, dhèu aae Pilistin, sèna ka na pea ètu Gerar.<bt>One time in that land, it was hit by a season of hunger/famine, like the time when Abraham was still living. And Isak went to ask Abimelek, the Filistin king, so he could stay at Gerar.</bt><v n="2" />Na tao sèmi èèna, lula LAMATUA dhu pad'elo le iisi Na mi nèngu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mage lamu ka asa Masir hèi. Pea la mi era dhu èèna na Ja'a paj'uj'u hia èu.<bt>He did that, because the LORD who had revealed Himself to him, said, &lt;&lt;You don't go to Masir. I will designate to you another place.</bt><v n="3-4" />Ladhe èu manubha ètu era èèna, Ja'a sama-sama dènge èu, aa pala-bagi èu mèngi-nale rupa-rupa. Èèna na, Ja'a pabèba ana-èpu èu sama sèmi hua-hètu ètu dedha-liru. Aa Ja'a hia kateme rai ne mi èu dènge ana-èpu èu. Nèti ana-èpu èu ka, dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne abhu mèngi-nale. Dènge j'ara ne'e, Ja'a tao madhutu lii pajaji dhu Ja'a pa'èki le dènge ama mu Abraham.<bt>If you stay on other people's land in that place, I will be with you, and will give you all sorts of blessings. In the future I will multiply your descendants like the stars in the sky. And I will give this entire land to your descendants. From your descendants, all the various people of of the earth will get blessing. In this way, I will do according to the promise I have bound with your father Abraham.</bt><note reference="26:3-4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 3:25; Galati 3:8</note><v n="5" />Ja'a tao sèmi ne'e ne, lula ama mu madhutu dad'èi Ja'a, paredha Ja'a, dènge atora Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>I will do this, because your father followed/obeyed My will, My commands, and My regulations.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="6" />Ka Isak pea taha ètu Gerar.<bt>So Isak lived awhile in Gerar.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ribka ne, bhèni iia titu kèna. Ka ropa dhèu ètu Gerar ladhe rèdhi ne, ra pakarèi. Te ngaa Isak peka na, &lt;&lt;Ribka ne, ana hèni ja'a.&gt;&gt; Na madha'u, ladhe na peka na dhèu èmu nèngu, dhèu se pamadhe ne, aa Ribka parame rare.<bt>This Ribka, was extremely female-beautiful. So when the people of gerar saw her, they queried eahc other. But Isak said, &lt;&lt;Ribka here is my sister.&gt;&gt; He was afraid, if he said she was his spouse, the people would kill him, and Ribka would be taken (lexical choice implies by force).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This section about Abimelek may be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">This section about Abimelek may be displaced from a time before the boys were born; there are no kids hanging around Rebecca. On the other hand, if it is in place chronologically, the boys are grown, and Rebecca is fortyish, but still beautiful. As with Abraham, the men lie to protect themselves, they place their wives in an awkward and dangerous position, and they get called on the carpet anyway.<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>yishʔəlu: they asked, demanded ʔanshey hamaqom: the people of the place<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>yareʔ: he was afraid pen-yaharguni: lest they kill me<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Isak dhu pea nèbhu le ètu nèi, hèia ca lod'o, dhèu aae nèdhi nèti ro'a jendela na, ladhe laa na Isak dènge Ribka dhu pa'ango.<bt>Isak had lived there for awhile, then one day, the king looked from his window, and happened to see Isak and Ribka busy embracing each other (may also imply groping).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔarkhu-lo: days became long, they were"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔarkhu-lo: days became long, they were there a long time Avi-Melek (dagesh): probably not the same person that Abraham tried to con, but his son. But the son probably knew the story, since it could have affected his mother.<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>vayashqef (hif): was looking down (from the point of view of somebody down below) bəʕad: through<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>mtsacheq (piʕel partcpl): laughing, playing; also a pun on name of Isaac, playing around, fondling</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ka na pua dhèu lasi paroa Isak, hèia na peka, &lt;&lt;Isak! Ja'a dhu ke'a le, bhèni ne dhèu èmu èu! Te ngaa tasamia ka, èu peka na, nèngu ne ana hèni èu?&gt;&gt;<bt>And he ordered people to go summon Isak, and then said, &lt;&lt;Isak! I already know that this woman is your spouse! But how is it that you said she is your sister?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'ango = asyik bercinta, bermesraan, peluk,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pa'ango = asyik bercinta, bermesraan, peluk, cium</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Isak dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e ama! Ja'a ne madha'u, ladhe ja'a peka na nèngu ne dhèu èmu ja'a, mage dhoka dhèu pamadhe ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Isak responded, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this, father! I was afraid that if I said she is my spouse, may it not be that people would kill me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔakh: restrictive adverb (Waltke &amp; OʔConnor),"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔakh: restrictive adverb (Waltke &amp; OʔConnor), "often essentially negators of continuity between clauses ... ʔI thought / It seemed to be otherwise but now I realize / it is obvious that...ʔ" Or "Now look! ..." ʔeykh: how? what?<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>ʕaleyah: because of her</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ka dhèu aae dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi dhèu ètu se'e j'unu dènge dhèu èmu èu, tatu èu pasala ji'i! Tasamia ka, èu ad'u j'ara ne'e mi dedha ji'i se?&gt;&gt;<bt>So the king responded, saying, &lt;&lt;If there were people here who slept with your spouse, you would certainly have blamed us-exc! How is it that you have done this thing to us?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mʕaT: almost, nearly; someone might easily"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mʕaT: almost, nearly; someone might easily have taken her shakav: sleep, have intercourse<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>heveʔta (bwʔ hif): you would have caused guilt to come upon us ʔasham: guilt, consequences of doing something wrong. Used in Isaiah 53:10, guilt offering.<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu aae Abimelek pasanèd'e ana kabarai na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu nanene paie-iie! Cee ka dhu bani gagu dhèu ne'e, do dhèu èmu na, èèna na ja'a huku pamadhe ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, king Abimelek reminded/warned his populace, saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl listen carefully! Whoever of you dares to bother this person, or his spouse, I will punish them to death.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yətsaw (tswh piʕel): he ordered hanogeaʕ:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yətsaw (tswh piʕel): he ordered hanogeaʕ: anyone touching<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>mot yumat (hof): is to suffer death, be punished by death</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra patao-palaha lula madha èi<bt>They argue because of wells</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Tèu èèna, Isak sèle hini ètu dedha rai dhèu se'e. Lod'o d'ai puu-g'ètu, ka na abhu isi rai cangasu hari, lula LAMATUA hia ne mamèngi.<bt>At that time, Isak planted seed on the land of these people. When harvest time arrived, he got returns 100 times, because the LORD gave him blessing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yizraʕ: he planted seeds yimtsaʔ: he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yizraʕ: he planted seeds yimtsaʔ: he found, achieved<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>meʔah shʕarim: 100 measures of grain, 100 fold increase (10,000%) shaʕar: measure<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>vayvarkhehu (piʕel): bestowed the power for success, prosperity, fertility on him (goes back to Gen 1)</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Lula mèdha-panyau na asa ae, ka na kaja titu kèna.<bt>Because his possessions kept increasing, his wealth was great.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayelekh halokh: continuation and progress ʕad:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayelekh halokh: continuation and progress ʕad: always, continuing into the future, continually<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Badha-manu na sèmi sapi, kahib'i-kalèbho asa tabha ae. Dhèu-dhèu sab'a na, ae kahèi. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu Pilistin tèka d'ara dènge ne.<bt>His animals such as cows, goat-sheep kept increasing in number. His workers were also many. Because of that, the Filistin people were jealous of him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="NOTE: abhu isi rai cangasu kali"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">NOTE: abhu isi rai cangasu kali lipat = some Kupang-based UNS's feel strongly it should be the Malay loan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miqneh: landed property, livestock that one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">miqneh: landed property, livestock that one owns ʕəvudah: collective, slaves and servants. String of nouns, sounds like the string of verbs at the end of Chapter 25.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>vayqanʔu: they were envious, jealous, furious</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Uru èèna, Abraham, ama Isak, dhu kèi èi ae-ae. Te ngaa limuri ne, dhèu Pilistin dhènu eele aa'i si dènge rai.<bt>Previously, Abraham, Isak's father, had dug many wells. But now, the Filistin people covered/filled them all with soil.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chafru: dug Sitmum (piʕel): they plugged"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">chafru: dug Sitmum (piʕel): they plugged up<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>yəmalʔum: they filled them up ʕafar: loose dirt<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ka dhèu aae Abimelek peka dènge Isak, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Isak! Be'a risi èu pakèd'i ka nèti kabarai ne'e. Lula koasa èu, risi eele le nèti ji'i se.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then king Abimelek spoke with Isak, saying, &lt;&lt;Isak! It would be best if you leave behind this country. Because your power/authority is already more than ours-exc.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕatsamta: you are mighty, vast, numerous"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕatsamta: you are mighty, vast, numerous</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="Hk-lb\Hk00220c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Èle èèna ka, Isak pakèd'i nèti era èèna, ka lasi pea hari ètu d'ara mamoo Gerar.<bt>After that, Isak left that place, and went to live again in the plain/valley/wilderness of Gerar.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yichan (chnh): camped for the night,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yichan (chnh): camped for the night, encamp for longer bnachal-grar: at the Wadi Gerar, intermittent stream<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ètu era ne'e, ra kèi hari madha èi dhu uru èèna, dhèu Pilistin dhènu eele aa'i si. Ka na pangare madha èi se madhutu ngara dhu ama na pangare.<bt>In that place, they again redug former wells, which the Filistin people had filled in. And he named these wells according to the named his father had named them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Some suggest that this verse belongs"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Some suggest that this verse belongs after 15 (REB, but not NRSV) yashav: go back, do something again<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>yachpor: he dug, had dug yəsatmum (stm piʕel): they plugged up the water springs<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>acharey mot avraham: after the death of Abraham - this overloads Pidgin syntax, and is implicit because of all that has been said</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ropa dhèu sab'a Isak se kèi èi ètu d'ara mamoo Gerar, hèi lèke èi madha dhu sabhoka mai.<bt>When Isak's workers dug for water in the wilderness of Gerar, they hit a well that artesianed out.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="banachal: down in the wadi itself"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">banachal: down in the wadi itself chayyim: running water coming out of that well, including in the dry season<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Lula madha èi ne'e ka, dhèu-dhèu madhenge badha nèti Gerar, patao dènge dhèu madhenge badha Isak. Dhèu se peka na, &lt;&lt;Ne'e ne, madha èi ji'i!&gt;&gt; Nèti èèna ka, Isak pangare madha èi na <span class="Italic">Esek,</span> dhu sasoa na &lt;patao-palaha&gt;.<bt>Because of this well, the people watching the animals from Gerar, argued with the people watching Isak's animals. These people said, &lt;&lt;This is our-exc well!&gt;&gt; Because of that, Isak named that well iEsek, which means &lt;argue&gt; (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sabhoka = maspurak"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">sabhoka = maspurak</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yarivu (ryv): dispute, quarrel in public"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yarivu (ryv): dispute, quarrel in public with complaints and reproaches, conduct a legal case, lawsuit hitʕassqu (ʕsq hitp): strive; they quarreled with him<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Hèia dhèu-dhèu Isak se, kèi hari èi leo ca madha. Te ngaa ra patao-palaha hari, lula èi èèna. Nèti èèna ka, Isak pangare na <span class="Italic">Sitna,</span> dhu sasoa na &lt;palab'a&gt;.<bt>Then Isak's people again dug a different well. But they argued again, because of that well. Because of that, Isak named it <span class="Italic">Sitna,</span> which means &lt;oppose each other&gt;.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔacheret: another yarivu: dispute, as in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔacheret: another yarivu: dispute, as in 20<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>siTnah (sTn): accusation</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Èle èèna ka, Isak tèke eele era èèna, la'e kèi hari èi èci. D'ai ne'e ne, ra patao-palaha heka. Ka Isak pangare madha èi ne <span class="Italic">Rehobot,</span> dhu sasoa na &lt;era taleo&gt;. Hèia na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Limuri ne, Lamatua hia le èdhi pea ètu era taleo. Ho ètu era ne'e ne, èdhi asa bèba-kacanga.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Isak left that place, and went to dug another well. Arriving there, they no longer argued. So Isak named that well <span class="Italic">Rehobot,</span> which means &lt;broad place&gt;. Then he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Now, God2 has allowed us-inc to stay in a broad place. So in this place, we can multiply in number.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaʕteq (ʕtq hif): move on, leave"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayaʕteq (ʕtq hif): move on, leave ravu (ryb): didnʔt dispute, contend<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>rchovot: open squares, plazas, from rchv open wide, broaden, extent, make room, provide wide room for, roominess hirchiv (hif): he provided wide room for us<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>parinu (prh): we are fruitful</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ka nèti era ne'e, Isak si lasi hari era pea asa Beer Syeba.<bt>And from this place, Isak mob moved to live at Beer Syeba.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaʕal (ʕlh): go up country, away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayaʕal (ʕlh): go up country, away from Egypt, toward Jerusalem</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Ka mèda na, LAMATUA pad'elo iisi Na mi Isak, hèia Na peka, &lt;&lt;Isak! Ja'a ne, Ama Lamatua nèti ama mu Abraham. De mage mu madha'u, te Ja'a ladhe-leru èu. Èèna na, Ja'a pala-bagi èu mèngi-nale. Aa ana-èpu èu asa bèba-kacanga. Ja'a ad'u madha j'ara ne'e, lula lii pajaji Ja'a dènge ama mu.&gt;&gt;<bt>That night, the LORD revealed Himself to Isak, and He said, &lt;&lt;Isak! I here, am the Lord God of your father Abraham. So, you don't be afraid, cause I am guarding/watching/protecting you. I will give/distribute blessing to you. And your descendants will multiply in number. I do this thing, because of My promise to your father.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lari hari era = pindah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">lari hari era = pindah</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeraʔ (rʔh nif): he appeared, he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yeraʔ (rʔh nif): he appeared, he let himself be seen ʔal-tiyraʔ: do not be afraid<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>berakhtikha (piʕel): I will bless you hirbeytiy (hif): I will make them be numerous<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>baʕəvur: in order that (+ imperfect), in order to, on account of, for the price of; because of Abraham</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Hèia Isak pudhi hadhu, tao mei korban ètu èèna. Ka na manèngi makasi mi LAMATUA. Hèia, na pea ètu era èèna, ka dhèu sab'a na kèi hari èi.<bt>So Isak stacked rocks to make a sacrifice table there. And he gave thanks to the LORD. Then, he lived in that place, and his workers began to dig wells again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The patriarchs seemed to set up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">The patriarchs seemed to set up an altar whenever God spoke to them, which was rarely. It not only let them reciprocate by making a sacrifice; it was a memorial to a life-changing experience. vayeT-sham (nTh): he set up his tent there, stretched it out<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>vayikhru (krh): they dug - different word than before</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu aae Abimelek padame dènge Isak<bt>King Abimelek and Isak RECIP-peace</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu aae Abimelek mai nèti Gerar. Angalai na Ahusat, dènge kètu kapai sordad'u na, Fikol, mai dènge ne, ho paraga dènge Isak.<bt>At that time, king Abimelek came from Gerar. His companion Ahusar, and the big head of his soldiers, Fikol, came with him, to meet with Isak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mereaʕ: intimate, close friend"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mereaʕ: intimate, close friend</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Ka Isak karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama dhèu aae! Uru èèna, miu se dhu babège eele ja'a nèti kabarai miu. De ne'e ne, miu se mai tao ngaa hari?&gt;&gt;<bt>So Isak asked, saying, &lt;&lt;Father king! Previously you-pl evicted me from your country. So now, what else do you want to do?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maduaʕ: why? baʔatem: have you come?|i(27)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">maduaʕ: why? baʔatem: have you come?<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>sneʔtem ʔoti: you hate me. This sounds like an inhospitable statement. God had told Isaac not to be afraid and repeated his promise, so Isaac, instead of being a wuss, stood up to Abimelek.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Hèia ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Ji'i dhu nge'a le, Lamatua dhu j'aga pa'ère èu. Nèti èèna ka, ji'i pangee, hua iia èdhi dua ti pa'èki lii pajaji dhu peka sèmi ne'e: èu j'oka subha, peka na,<bt>Then they said, &lt;&lt;It's like this. We-exc know that God2 guard and protects you. Because of that, we have been thinking it would be good if the two of us-inc bind a promise saying this: You should swear-oath, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʔo raʔiynu (inf abs): we see,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">raʔo raʔiynu (inf abs): we see, we get the picture ʔalah: an obligation by oath which puts a curse on the transgressor<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>beynoteynu: between us beyniynu uveynekha: between you and us<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>nikhrətah brit (krt): let's make an agreement, cut a deal</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />miu se baku tao karehe dènge ji'i, aa ji'i kahèi baku tao karehe dènge miu. Mema ji'i se d'ara be'a dènge miu. Nèti èèna ka, ca hari ni, miu se lami dènge mera-milu nèti kabarai ji'i ne. Ji'i dhu nge'a le, LAMATUA ka dhu pala-bagi mèngi-nale mi miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>that you will not do evil to us-exc, and we will also not do evil to you-pl. Our insides are really good with you (=right relationships). Because of that, that (previous) time, you-pl left in peace from our country. We know that the LORD is the one who has distributed blessing to you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nəjgʕanukha: harm, hurt, touch bshalom: in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nəjgʕanukha: harm, hurt, touch bshalom: in good condition, in peace, unhurt. "let you go way" same word as "throw me outa yoa land" in verse 27.<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>ʕattah: as of now, from this time forward? baruch yʔ: blessed of the Lord (passive partcpl). "see" from v. 28<span class="Italic">(29)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Èle èèna ka, Isak tao pesta, ka ra'a-rinu aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>After that, Isak made a celebration, and they ate-drank together.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishteh: feast with wine"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mishteh: feast with wine</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Ka asa bèli mad'ae èèna, rèngu j'oka lii soo-subha. Hèia Isak patalala si lèpa dènge dame.<bt>Then early the next morning, they made an oath. And Isak released them to return home in peace.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yashkiymu: they got up early yishshavʕu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yashkiymu: they got up early yishshavʕu: they swore oaths each to the other<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>bshalom: cessation of hostilities? good feeling?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Lod'o èèna kahèi, dhèu sab'a Isak mai peka lula-nèti èi dhu rèngu kèi, na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ji'i rage le èi.&gt;&gt;<bt>That day as well, Isak's workers came and told about the well which they dug, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! We-exc have encountered water.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayagidu lo: they reported to him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayagidu lo: they reported to him ʕal-ʔodot: on account of<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="33" />Hèia Isak pangare madha èi ne <span class="Italic">Syeba</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;subha&gt;). Ka ra pangare kota èèna Beer Syeba, toke sange ne'e.<bt>So Isak named that well, <span class="Italic">Syeba,</span> (which means &lt;swear-oath&gt;). So, they named that city Beer Syeba, until now.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕal-ken: as a result End of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕal-ken: as a result End of S section<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="26:33" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Ibrani, <span class="Italic">Syeba </span>sasoa na bisa &lt;subha&gt;, bisa &lt;pidhu&gt;, bisa &lt;kalua mèngi&gt;. Madhutu lii Ibrani, <span class="Italic">Beer</span> sasoa na &lt;madha èi&gt;.<bt>According to the Ibrani language, Syeba can mean &lt;oath&gt;, or it can mean &lt;seven&gt;, or it can mean &lt;good luck/fate&gt;. According to the Ibrani language, <span class="Italic">Beer</span> means &lt;well&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Esau leo dènge bhèni dhèu dua nèti suku leo<bt>Esau marries two women from other tribes/clans</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ropa umur Esau d'ai èpa nguru tèu, na leo dènge bhèni dhèu dua nèti suku Het. Bhèni èci, ana nèti Beeri, ngara na Yudit. Èci hari, ana Elon, ngara na Basmat.<bt>When Esau was 40 years old, he married two young-women from the tribe of Het. One woman was Beeri's child, named Yudit. And the other one, was Elon's child, named Basmat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Esau's action sounds like he is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Esau's action sounds like he is flouting convention and opting to not let a marriage develop the way his father set up for his brother. Isaac is 100 years old at this point. beʔeri: ʔmy wellʔ - perhaps everybody had wells on the brain.<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="35" />Bhèni dhèu dua se, papèd'a d'ara Isak dènge Ribka.<bt>Those two women, made Isak and Ribka's insides sick.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="leo parènga = pada saat yg"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">leo parènga = pada saat yg sama.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tihyeyna: they were morat ruach (mrr"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tihyeyna: they were morat ruach (mrr ʔbitterʔ? mrh ʔprovocationʔ?): bitterness of spirit, affliction<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ribka leko-monya Isak ho hia Yakob mèngi-nale<bt>Ribka deceives Isak to give Yakob a blessing</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="27" />
      <v n="1" />Ropa Isak manahu asa d'ara heka, nèdhi heka ngaa-ngaa, lula musi madha na ahu le. Ka na paroa ana uuru èèna, dhu na sue risi èèna, peka na, &lt;&lt;Esau. Mai ku sa ne'e!&gt;&gt;<bt>When Isak fel into old age, he couldn't see well anymore, because his eyes were foggy/cloudy. And he summoned his oldest child, whom he loved more, saying, &lt;&lt;Esau. Come here!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sasab'a na kasiro badha hui, aa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">sasab'a na kasiro badha hui, aa nèngu ne, ana pasue ama na Isak. Lula Isak ne dhu dèi na'a sisi badha hui. Ka ca lod'o Isak paroa Esau, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Esau mai ku sa ne'e!</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Esau dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia, ama?&gt;&gt;<bt>Esau responded saying, &lt;&lt;What is it, father?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiqraʔ: not clear whether Esau was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayiqraʔ: not clear whether Esau was staying at some distance away, or close by. tikhhena (khh): became expressionless, colorless, clouded [cataracts?]<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>hineni: Here "behold" wonʔt work at all. A response to a greeting from a blind man would be &lt;&lt;Dass me.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ka Isak peka hari, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Ja'a ne, ètu d'ara heka le. Ke'a boe, pèri lod'o ja'a ne madhe.<bt>So Isak spoke again, &lt;&lt;It's like this! I am already old. I don't know when I will die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Isaac may have been discouraged because"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Isaac may have been discouraged because of his encroaching blindness, or just felt like he was going to die. He actually lived for years after this event.</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />De more rèka èu, lamu kataki mèti badha hui ci'u hia ja'a.<bt>So take your weapons, and go hunting for a wild animal for me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="saʔ-na (nsʔ): take up keleykha: your"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">saʔ-na (nsʔ): take up keleykha: your implements<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>telyəkha: your hanger (tlh), quiver for arrows. SK quiver = someting shake qashtekha: your bow<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>tseʔ (ytsʔ): go tsuwdah (tswd imperv): hunt<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>tsedah, ktiv tsayid: provisions for a journey, ktiv game</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Mu pananasu pabe'a-be'a, madhutu dad'èi ja'a, ho mèti mai hia ja'a. Ladhe ku'a-kinu kora, ja'a hia mema èu mèngi-nale. Sad'i èu unu le mèngi-nale èèna, ja'a madhe èèna ka, ngaa-ngaa tao heka.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cook it nicely/deliciously, according to the way I like, and bring it here to me. When I have finished eating-drinking it, I will give you your blessing. As long as you already possess that blessing, even if I die then, it doesn't matter.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="matʕammiym: tidbits ʔahavtiy: I love|i(4) (4)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">matʕammiym: tidbits ʔahavtiy: I love<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>baʕəvur: on account of tvarekhkha nafshi (piʕel imperf): so my soul may bless you<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia Esau la'e dènge ka, kataki badha hui. Te ngaa Ribka dhu tadèngi kahèi lii padhai Isak deo na.<bt>Then Esau left right away to hunt wild animals. But Ribka had also heard what Isak had just said.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shomaʕat: concurrent participle, simultaneous actions bəno:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shomaʕat: concurrent participle, simultaneous actions bəno: Esau is called "Isaac's boy" and "Jacob's brother". Jacob is "Rebecca's boy". Rebecca isn't "Isaac's wife". Maybe Rebecca is the most dysfunctional of the lot.<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ka Ribka la'e peka dènge Yakob, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Yakob! Èu nanene ku! Deo na, ja'a tadèngi ama mu pua Esau sèmi ne'e:<bt>And Ribka went to speak with Yakob, saying, &lt;&lt;Yakob! Listen to me! Just now, I heard your father tell Esau this:</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mdabber (piʕel partcpl): saying"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mdabber (piʕel partcpl): saying</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />&lt;Lamu kataki more ku badha hui ci'u, mai mu pananasu pabe'a-be'a hia ja'a. Ladhe ku'a-kinu kora, ja'a hia èu mèngi-nale ètu katanga madha LAMATUA.&gt;<bt>&lt;Go hunt for a wild animal, and come and cook it nicely for me. When I have finished eating-drinking, I will give you a blessing before the LORD.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vrakhah: I will give you my"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vrakhah: I will give you my formal blessing -- irrevocable, with Yahweh as witness lifne (like bterem): future, impending death<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />De mu nanene paie-iie! Mu madhutu mola-mola lii paredha ja'a ne.<bt>So, listen carefully! You must follow my command in detail.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mtsawwah: I am ordering you to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mtsawwah: I am ordering you to do</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />De lamu ka asa era badha èdhi sèi, ho kèpe more kalèbho èni dhu kabèb'u dua ngi'u. Roro ho mèti sisi mai asa ja'a. Pe ja'a pananasu madhutu dad'èi ama mu.<bt>So go to the place where our animals are, to catch two fat female sheep/goats [CHECK if this should be unambiguously /kahib'i/ "goat"]. Slaughter them to bring their meat here to me. Then I will cook them according to how your father likes it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gdayey ʕizzim: baby goats"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">gdayey ʕizzim: baby goats</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ladhe panasu kore, mèti hia ama mu na'a. Ho èle na, na hia èu mèngi-nale, heka na madhe kèna. Dènge sèmi ne'e ka, èu ka dhu abhu mèngi-nale èèna. A'a mu abhu boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>When I have cooked it, take it to your father to eat. So when he's finished, he will give you a blessing before he dies. In this way, your are the one who will get the blessing. Not your elder-sibling.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baʕəvur: on account of yvarekhəkha: so"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">baʕəvur: on account of yvarekhəkha: so he will bless you. This is a single, irrevocable act.<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Te ngaa Yakob peka dènge ina na, &lt;&lt;Ina! A'a ku Esau, ngi'u na dhu pènu dènge rèu, te ngaa ja'a ne, isi dhu milu aadha-aadha!<bt>But Yakob spoke to his mother saying, &lt;&lt;Mother! My elder-sibling Esau, his body is full of hair/fur, but as for me, (mine) is smooth and clean (doublet)!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hen: look! emphasizes the following word,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hen: look! emphasizes the following word, phrase, or clause. Used in agreeing Gen 30:34 saʔir: hairy, shaggy<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>chalaq: smooth, smooth-skinned</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Mage dhoka ama ku g'ag'e isi ja'a, ladhe na ne'a na ja'a dhu leko-monya na. Hèia na dhoo ja'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>May it not be that my father feels my skin, trying to find out if I am tricking him. Then he will curse me!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="milu aadha-aadha = clean1-clean2 (licin) ~"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">milu aadha-aadha = clean1-clean2 (licin) ~ mèu rèd'e-rèd'e</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔuwlay: perhaps ymusheni (mshsh): he will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔuwlay: perhaps ymusheni (mshsh): he will touch me, feel me<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>mətaʕteaʕ (tʕʕ pilpel): one who acts up (in this case, profaning something solemn) heveʔtiy (bwʔ hif): I will bring on myself<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>qalalah: a curse, both in action and in formula</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ka ina na dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu baku cag'ag'a! Hud'i laa ina ka dhu ator! Ladhe ama mu dhoo èu, pe ina ka pasae! Mu mate ia ka, la more ka kahib'i sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>So his mother responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Don't be anxious! Let your mother be the one to arrange it! Then if your father curses you, mother will be the one to bear it! You shouldn't wait any longer, go fetch those goats.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔakh: assurance, restriction ʔjust do as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔakh: assurance, restriction ʔjust do as I sayʔ</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ka Yakob la'e nare kahib'i dua ngi'u sèra, hèia na roro, ka nèti hia ina na. Hèia Ribka pananasu madhutu dad'èi Isak.<bt>And Yakob fetched the two goats, then he slaughtered them, and took them to his mother. Then Ribka cooked them the way Isak liked.</bt><v n="15" />Ka Ribka la'e nare mèdha-papake Esau dhu be'a, ho na papake mi Yakob.<bt>And Ribka took Esau's good clothes, to have Yakob wear them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bigdey (beged): clothes of chəmudot: desirable,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bigdey (beged): clothes of chəmudot: desirable, precious, delightful<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>talbesh (lbsh hif): she clothed qaTan: small, younger (by minutes, but that didnʔt matter)<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Hèia na pahutu kahèi kacui-aai dènge ladhe goro Yakob, pake ka'uri kahib'i deo sa.<bt>Then she also covered Yakob's hand/arms and neck, using the skin of those aforementioned goats.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕorot: hides hilbishah (lbsh hif): she"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕorot: hides hilbishah (lbsh hif): she put something on somebody, dressed him. Goat hair and hide are not very thick, and feel like human hair much more than sheep's wool does.<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>yadayw: hand and arm, hand and wrist, hand alone. Probably the first. chelqat tsawaʔraw: the hairless, smooth portions of the neck<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>tsawwaʔrayw: the back of his neck</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ka na pangèd'u Yakob nganga'a dhu pananasu nare deo na, dènge roti dhu tunu nare.<bt>Then she handed over to Yakob the food she had just finished cooking, and bread which she had baked.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00679c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Isak hia mèngi-nale mi Yakob<bt>Isak gives blessing to Yakob</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Hèia Yakob ded'e nèti nganga'a se'e, hia ama na na'a. Ka na lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama. Ja'a mai hari le.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob took the food and gave it to his father to eat. And he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Father. I've come back already.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Isak dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Hee! Èu ne, cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Isak responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Hee! Who are you?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ka Yakob dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a, Esau ana mone uuru ama ku! Ja'a sab'e le, madhutu sèmi dhu ama pua deo na. Kèd'i, ho mu'a-minu ka. Lula ja'a pananasu kore le sisi badha hui dhu ja'a kèti nèti d'ara j'ami. Mu'a, ho èle na, ama pala-bagi ja'a mèngi-nale.&gt;&gt;<bt>So then Yakob reponded, saying, &lt;&lt;I am Esau, your oldest child, father! I have already done what father ordered me to do earlier [today]. Get up so you can eat. Because I've already cooked the meat of the wild animal which I have successully caught in the matto. Eat, so afterwards father will distribute blessing to me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shvah (imperv): sit up baʕəvuwr: on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shvah (imperv): sit up baʕəvuwr: on account<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>nafshekha: you (indirect reference to him as a person). Might mean "with all your heart"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Hèia Isak peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne, bia tai nga! Abhu malai titu kèna, badha hui èèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Isak spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;You are very impressive! How [in the world] could you get a wild animal so quickly!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bia tai ngaa ;" title="bia tai nga ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">bia tai ngaa ;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yakob dhaa, &lt;&lt;Ja'a abhu le, lula LAMATUA dhu èu mangaj'i èèna, ka dhu tulu ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yakob responded, &lt;&lt;I got this, because the LORD whom you worship, was the one who helped me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miharta (mhr): you did it quicker"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">miharta (mhr): you did it quicker than expected hiqrah (hif): make something happen, let something happen, ordain, direct, with lifnay for ʔmeʔ<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ka Isak paroa Yakob, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Padètu ku asa ne'e mai, sèna ka ja'a g'ag'e sèku èu. Èu ne, tare'a ana ja'a Esau, do aad'o?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Isak ordered Yakob, saying, &lt;&lt;Approach me here, so I can feel you (to find out). Are you really my child Esau, or not?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gshah-naʔ (ngsh imperv): approach ʔəmushkha (mshsh):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">gshah-naʔ (ngsh imperv): approach ʔəmushkha (mshsh): I will feel you<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Hèia Yakob la'e padètu-dètu dènge ama na, ka ama na g'ag'e ne. Ka Isak peka, &lt;&lt;Lii ne, sèmi lii Yakob! Te ngaa kacui-aai na, kacui-aai Esau.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yakob went closer to his father, and his father felt/groped him. And Isak said, &lt;&lt;This voice, is like the voice of Yakob! But his hands/arms are the arms of Esau.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ymushshehu (mshsh qal): he felt him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ymushshehu (mshsh qal): he felt him</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Te ngaa Isak dhu tadhe iia boe Yakob, lula kacui-aai na rèu sèmi Esau. Ka ropa na neo hia mèngi-nale mi Yakob,<bt>But Isak didn't recognise Yakob, because his hand/arm was hairy/furry like Esau's. And when he was about to give blessing to Yakob,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hikhiro (nkr hif): recognize should this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hikhiro (nkr hif): recognize should this come later?<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>səʕirot: hairy</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />na karèi hari era, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne, tare'a-re'a Esau, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>he asked once again, saying, &lt;&lt;You here, really are Esau, right?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yakob dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a-re'a ama. Ja'a ne, Esau!&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yakob responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Really father. I am Esau!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ka Isak peka na, &lt;&lt;Na, j'ole ka sisina mai, sèna ka ja'a ku'a. Èle ku, pe ja'a hia èu mèngi-nale.&gt;&gt; Hèia Yakob hia sisi dènge èi anggor hia ama na na'a-ninu.<bt>And Isak said, &lt;&lt;Na, slide that meat over here, so I can eat it. When I'm finished, I will give you blessing.&gt;&gt; So Yakob gave the meat and the grape juice/wine to his father to eat/drink.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hagisha li (ngsh hif): bring it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hagisha li (ngsh hif): bring it close to me tvarekhkha (piʕel): for it (me?) to bless you. Why the feminine singular subject?<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Na'a nare ka, Isak lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ana, ee! Mai padètu asa ne'e, ho mu uu ku ja'a laa.&gt;&gt;<bt>After eating, Isak spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Child, ee! Come real close here, to kiss me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gshah-naʔ (ngsh): come close shqah-li (nshq):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">gshah-naʔ (ngsh): come close shqah-li (nshq): kiss me (appropriate for a son to his father)<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ka ropa Yakob padètu dènge ne, ho uu ne, Isak sangèd'u nare hèu mèdha-papake Esau. Hèia na padhai lii hia mèngi-nale mi Yakob, aku nèngu na,<bt>When Yakob came close to him to kiss him, Isak smelled the odour of Esau's clothes. So he spoke giving blessing to Yakob, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sangèd'u = tercium"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">sangèd'u = tercium</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Hèu ana ja'a tare'a-re'a sèmi hèu j'u'u ètu d'ara pad'a, dhu abhu mamèngi nèti LAMATUA.<bt>&lt;&lt;My child's odour, is truly like the odour of grass in the field which has been blessed by the LORD.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Mamuri Manad'u = YG Hidup Samanga"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">Mamuri Manad'u = YG Hidup Samanga ~ Roh yg hidup</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayarach reach (rwch hif): smell the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayarach reach (rwch hif): smell the smell, odor of his clothes rʔeh: look!<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>berəkho: he blessed it</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="28" />Hud'i laa Ama Lamatua patiri èi paringi nèti dedha-liru,<bt>May God drip down dew from the sky,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sèna ka oka-tedhe èu j'aj'i mi rai hèu mèngi.<bt>so that your fields become fertile land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èi paringi = embun ; patiri"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">èi paringi = embun ; patiri = kasi tetes dari atas ; bui tatee = siram dari haik yg dilobangi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Hud'i laa Na hia èu are dhu udhu sobhu-sobhu,<bt>May He give you rice/grain in great abundance,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sobhu-sobhu = limpa2"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">sobhu-sobhu = limpa2</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dènge hua anggor dhu pènu ako-pènu èru.<bt>and fruit of grape which is full of clusters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Tal: dew, light rain shmanne haʔarets:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Tal: dew, light rain shmanne haʔarets: fat (=fertile) fields<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>rov: abundance dagan: cereal grain, not just wheat<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>tirosh: old word for wine; ritual and poetic</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="29" />Suku-suku j'aj'i mi ènu èu,<bt>Tribes will become your slaves,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa dhèu-dhèu leo pahaha iisi mi dedha èu.<bt>And other peoples will show respect/honour upon you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Èu j'aj'i mi lamatua nèti a'ari èu.<bt>You will be master/lord to your siblings/relatives.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa rèngu patitu kètu urutuu ètu madha èu.<bt>and they will kneel before you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu cee dhu dhoo èu, rèngu abhu dhoo kahèi.<bt>Whoever curses you, they will also be cursed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="saseo = kutuk"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">saseo = kutuk</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa dhèu cee dhu hia mèngi-nale mi èu, rèngu abhu mèngi-nale kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>And whoever gives blessing to you, they will also get blessing.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaʕavduwkha: they will work for you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yaʕavduwkha: they will work for you həweh (hwh imperv): become<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>gvir: lord, master acheykha: he only had one brother<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>yishtachəwwu: they will bow down ʔorərekha ʔarur (ʔrr partcpl pl): the ones who curse you will be cursed<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>mvarkhekha barukh: the ones who bless you will be blessed</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Esau lèpa, ka na manèngi Isak ho hia ne berkat kahèi<bt>Esau returns, and asks Isak to also give him a blessing</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ropa Isak hia nare mèngi-nale mi Yakob, ka heka bhodho li'u la'e tèke eele ama na, cag'ag'a laa Esau lèpa nèti kataki badha hui.<bt>When Isak had finished giving a blessing to Yakob, who had just gone outside leaving behind his father, suddenly Esau returned home from hunting wild animals.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="khilah (piʕel): as Isaac finished vayhi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">khilah (piʕel): as Isaac finished vayhi ʔak yatsoʔ yatsaʔ (inf abs + perf): and what do you know? Just as Jacob was on his way out<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>vesaw ʔachiw baʔ: his brother Esau of all people came in</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Hèia la'e pananasu, ka sod'e nèti hia ama na. Ka na parèi ama na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama, kèd'i mu'a. Ja'a lalau kore le sisi badha dhu ja'a kataki kore. Mu'a more ku, pe hia ja'a berkat.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he went and cooked it, and took it to his father. And he wakened/caught attention his father, saying, &lt;&lt;Father, get up and eat. I have prepared the animal meat which I have bow-shot. Eat it, and then give me a blessing2.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gam: where does it fit? yaqum"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">gam: where does it fit? yaqum (3sg imperf): sit up, get up, get ready to eat; deferential<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>yoʔkhal (3sg imperf): eat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Te ngaa Isak malaa, ka na karèi, &lt;&lt;Hee! Te èu ne, cee hari ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>But, Isak was confused, and he asked, &lt;&lt;Hee! Now who else are you?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Esau dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne'e, Esau! Ana uuru ama ku.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Esau responded, saying, &lt;&lt;I am Esau! Your oldest child.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Does this assume that Isaac is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Does this assume that Isaac is getting senile, or that he is getting mixed signals from voice versus other senses?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ka Isak cag'ag'a, hèia na karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, deo na cee ka dhu hia ja'a sisi, ka ja'a ku'a èèna? Ka ja'a hia ne mèngi-nale. Aa mèngi-nale èèna, bisa heka ère hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Isak was startled, so he asked, saying, &lt;&lt;If that's the case, just now who was it that gave me meat, and I ate it? And I gave him a blessing. And that blessing, cannot be pulled back.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yechərad: tremble, shudder; shake violently chəradah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yechərad: tremble, shudder; shake violently chəradah gdolah ʕad-mʔod: with great fear<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>mi-ʔefoʔ: who then?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ropa tadèngi nare, Esau roe ai ca palèpa, ka na tangi d'ara pèd'a dènge roma iisi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ne, ama, ee! Bagi hia ja'a berkat hèi ma.&gt;&gt;<bt>When he heard that, Esau was weak being upset, and he cried bitterly with complaints, saying, &lt;&lt;How about it, father, ee! Give me a blessing too. [+protest]&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayitsʕaq tsəʕaqah: he raised a wailing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayitsʕaq tsəʕaqah: he raised a wailing cry, a loud and bitter cry. Probably not a pun against tsachaq. marah ʕad-mʔod: totally bitter feeling, gloomy heart, provoked, embittered, furious<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Hèia Isak peka, &lt;&lt;Ari mu ka monya ja'a, ka parame nare berkat dhu pala èu di.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Isak said, &lt;&lt;Your younger-sibling has tricked me, and has taken/snatched the blessing2 that was for you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bmirmah: in deceit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bmirmah: in deceit</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Ka aku Esau na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu na leko-monya ja'a dua hari kèna. Uru èèna, parame nare hak a'a. Ka ne'e ne, parame nare hari berkat dhu madhutu iia-iia na unu ja'a. Nèka na, ngara na &lt;Yakob&gt; Te ngaa ele boe ama dhu dènge berkat era, ho hia ja'a. Do, aad'o heka?&gt;&gt; (Yakob sasoa na &lt;kèpe hui tèdhu&gt;, te ngaa sasoa dhu leo &lt;tuka leko-monya&gt;.)<bt>And said Esau, &lt;&lt;He has tricked/conned me two times now. Previously he snatched the elder's rights. And now, he has also snatched the blessing2 which according to what is correct, should be mine. How appropriate that his name is &lt;Yakob&gt; But surely father still has a blessing to give me. Or is there no more?&gt;&gt; (Yakob means &lt;grab the heel&gt;, but whose other meaning is &lt;con artist&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Nèka na = pantas"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">Nèka na = pantas</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaʕəqveni: he cheated me. paʕəmayim (dual):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayaʕəqveni: he cheated me. paʕəmayim (dual): both times<span class="Italic">(36) (36) </span>ʔatsalta (ʔtsl): you have laid by</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Hèia Isak dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a dhu ded'e le nèngu, j'aj'i lamatua èu. Aa a'ari na aa'i-aa'i ra, j'aj'i mi ènu na. Ja'a hia na le, unu are pènu soka-pènu karo, dènge hua anggor pènu ako-pènu èru. De ana, ee! Mamèngi tasamia hari, dhu ja'a ne pala-bagi mi èu?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Isak responded, saying, &lt;&lt;I am the one who elevated him to be your master. And all of his siblings/relatives, will become his slaves. I have already given him, grain in excessive abundance, and fruit of the grape which is full of clusters. So, child ee! What other/additional blessing is there which I can distribute to you?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lakh (fem): for you [?] smakhtiw:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">lakh (fem): for you [?] smakhtiw: I propped him up, supported him with things<span class="Italic">(37) (37) </span>ʔefowʔ mah: what then?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Masi ka tadèngi nare le sèmi èèna, te ngaa Esau loe boe dènge pamako ama na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mamèngi na dhodhoka èci di, do? Tatu ama dènge hari mamèngi dhu leo hia ja'a. Masi ka ciki oo'e èèna ka, sad'i ja'a ne abhu!&gt;&gt; Ka Esau tangi hari dènge d'ara laho mae-mae.<bt>Even having heard that, nevertheless Esau did not cease coaxing his father, saying, &lt;&lt;Is there only just one blessing? Surely father can still find a different blessing for me. Even just a small blessing, as long as I get one!&gt;&gt; And Esau cried again bitterly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maen noki = kokoe, bujuk, minta"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">maen noki = kokoe, bujuk, minta dgn sangat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yissaʔ (nsʔ): he lifted up his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yissaʔ (nsʔ): he lifted up his voice</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Ka Isak b'ala ne, peka na,<bt>After that, Isak replied back to him, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Mamuri èu ne, èèna na kaj'èu nèti oka-tedhe dhu hèu mèngi,<bt>&lt;&lt;Your life will be far from from fertile fields,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula èi paringi patiri boe nèti dedha-liru mai, ho pabasa rai èu.<bt>because there is no dew to drip down from the sky to make wetten your land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="min: in contrast to verse 28,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">min: in contrast to verse 28, which is partitive, this sounds like the directional use. shmanney (shaman): the fat<span class="Italic">(39) (39) </span>mowshavekha: your dwelling place Some Jewish commentators see this blessing as equivalent, though complementary. Protestant commentators tend to see it as negative.<span class="Italic">(39)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="40" />Èu ne, mamuri dhoka nèti samala èu di.<bt>You will just live by your sword.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa tasa mera mia èèna ka, èu ne j'aj'i ènu ari mu.<bt>But no matter what/nevertheless, you will be/become a slave to your younger-sibling.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Dhodhoka ladhe bèli-camèd'a, èu bani lab'a ne, èèna na èu heka rai eele nèti d'ara adhe-aai na.&gt;&gt;<bt>Only if in the future, you dare to oppose him, will you be able to flee from his hand.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taʕəvod: you will work tariyd (ryd?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">taʕəvod: you will work tariyd (ryd? rwd? hif): make you roam around? uncertain; grow restive REB<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>faraqta: you will pull away, tear away ʕullo: his yoke<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>tsawaʔrekha: your neck; get him off your back This verse is the official Masoretic halfway point.<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>[MC] The little Tyndale commentaries (IVP) by Kidner on this section is a gem! (vv. 1-40). He points out that Jacob depends on all his senses (smell, taste, etc) rather than the Lord.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ribka pua Yakob rai<bt>Ribka orders Yakob to flee</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Lula j'ara sèmi ne'e ne ka, Esau tèke d'ara dènge ari na Yakob, lula parame nare mamèngi na. Ka Esau pangee na, &lt;&lt;Nèbhu heka, ama ku madhe. De hud'i laa, pe d'ai ku lod'o. Ladhe èle beke, ja'a pamadhe ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>Because of these things, Esau hated his younger-sibling Yakob, because he had snatched his blessing. And Esau thought, &lt;&lt;Soon, my father will die. So then my day will arrive. After the wake, I will kill him!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yistom (qal): harbor a grudge against"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yistom (qal): harbor a grudge against Jacob, animosity toward him, hated him to the core of his soul. berkho (piʕel): he blessed him<span class="Italic">(41) (41) </span>yiqrəvo: the time is coming near ʔevel: time of mourning<span class="Italic">(41)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42-43" />Ropa Ribka tadèngi Esau dhu neo ad'u j'ara karehe, ka na peka dènge Yakob, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu nanene ku lii ne! A'a mu neo b'ala d'ara pèd'a na, de na neo pamadhe èu. De be'a risi, èu ne rai lai-lai asa to'o mu Laban, ètu kota Haran.<bt>When Ribka heard Esau wanted to do this evil thing, and he spoke to Yakob, saying, &lt;&lt;You listen to what I say/advise! Your elder-sibling wants to avenge his hate, so he wants to kill you. So it would be best for you to run away to your mother's-brother Laban, in the city of Haran.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yugad (ngd hof): it was reported."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yugad (ngd hof): it was reported. Why "ʔet" with hofal? Waltke &amp; OʔConnor 28.3, "The Hophal forms of roots that are transitive in Qal are passive causatives." e.g., somebody caused [ʔet] Rebecca to be informed ... mitnachem (hitp): is scheming revenge against you; literally, is comforting himself concerning you [things will be okay once I kill Jacob].<span class="Italic">(42) (42) </span>shmaʕ bqoli: lissen to my voice = obey me bərach-lakh: flee<span class="Italic">(42)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="44" />Lamu asa nèi, pea ako nèbhu, toke èle nanasa a'a mu.<bt>Go yonder and live there awhile, until your older-sibling is no longer angry at you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕad-ʔasher tashuv chamat: until his anger"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕad-ʔasher tashuv chamat: until his anger returns, turns away ʕad chmat: during the anger of<span class="Italic">(44)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="45" />Ladhe na bhèlu eele ku tatao èu ne, pe ja'a pua dhèu dhiu paroa èu, sèna ka èu lèpa hari mai. Lula ja'a ko'o boe, sèna ka ana ja'a dua-dua mi ele parènga d'ara ca lod'o èèna ka.&gt;&gt;<bt>When he has forgotten your deed, I will send someone to go summon you, so that you can come back home. Because I do not want for both of my children to both be lost in one day.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shakhach ʔet ʔasher ʕasita lo: forget"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shakhach ʔet ʔasher ʕasita lo: forget what you did to him ʔeshkal: I would be bereaved of children<span class="Italic">(45)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />Hèia Ribka roma iisi dènge Isak, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ru'a le dènge dhèu èmu Esau, dhèu Het se! De ladhe Yakob todhe nare hari kahèi ana bhèni nèti dhèu Het se, hua iia ja'a madhe ka laa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Ribka complained to Isak, saying, &lt;&lt;I am already fed up (Idiom: choked) with Esau's spouses those Het people! So if Yakob also marries girls from these Het people, it would be better for me to just die.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mèdhu dhèi = muntah ta'i &gt;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">mèdhu dhèi = muntah ta'i &gt; bosan / KM doak</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qatsti (qwts): I am disgusted mifney:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">qatsti (qwts): I am disgusted mifney: because of<span class="Italic">(46) (46) </span>kaʔeleh: like these, like Esau's wives (indirect); a backhanded slap, reassuring Isaac that giving Jacob the blessing was a good idea. loqeach (participle): on the verge of marrying<span class="Italic">(46)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="28" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia Isak paroa nare Yakob, ka hia ne mèngi-nale aa holo ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sanèd'e paie! Èu mage leo ka dènge ana bhèni Kana'an hèi.<bt>So Isak summoned Yakob, and gave him blessing and advised/instructed him, saying, &lt;&lt;Remember well! You must not also marry girls from Kana'an.</bt><v n="2" />De lamu ka asa Padan Aram, asa baki mu Betuel. Lamu madhèdi dènge ana bhèni to'o mu Laban ca dhèu.<note reference="28:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Padan Aram èèna, nuka Mesopotamia, ètu d'ara negara Siria re badae, padètu-dètu dènge Irak. Haran èèna, kota ètu Padan Aram.<bt>That Padan Aram, is Mesopotamia, in the north part of the country of Siria, very close to Irak. That Haran, is a city in Padan Aram.</bt></note><v n="3" />Hud'i laa Ama Lamatua dhu Koasa Risi Eele na, hia èu mamèngi, sèna ka ana-èpu èu bèba-kacanga, ho nèti rèngu ka j'aj'i suku ae-ae dhu kapai.<v n="4" />Hud'i laa, lii pajaji Ama Lamatua dènge Abraham èèna, noto mi dedha èu ne, dènge ana-èpu èu. Sèna ka èu unu rai dhu Ama Lamatua jaji tèke le mi Abraham.&gt;&gt;<note reference="28:3-4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 3:25; Galati 3:8</note><v n="5" />Padhai lii nare, ka Isak hia Yakob la'e asa Padan Aram, asa èmu to'o na Laban, dènge baki na Betuel.<bt>So, go to Padan Aram, to your grandfather Betuel. Go marry a daughter of your mother's-brother Laban.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Esau leo dènge ana bhèni Ismael<bt>Esau marries Ismael's daughter</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Interlude, similar to the Judah and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Interlude, similar to the Judah and Tamar incident in Chapter 28. Joseph and Judah are the people in focus in the outcome of the whole Jacob story. Deceptions look like part of a cycle: Jacob and Esau, Shekem men, Judah and Tamar, ...<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Esau dhu tadèngi le kahèi, dhu peka na Isak hia Yakob mamèngi, aa kai ne sèna ka baku leo dènge bhèni Kana'an. Aa na tadèngi hèi, dhu Isak hia Yakob leo dènge ana bhèni to'o na Laban ètu Padan Aram.<bt>Esau had also heard that Isak had given Yakob blessing, and forbidden him to not marry females from Kana'an. And he also heard that Isak had sent Yakob to marry a daughter of his mother's-brother Laban in Padan Aram.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayarʔ: realized (not just visual). This"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayarʔ: realized (not just visual). This starts the wrapup of the Jacob-Esau story. bvarakho: in blessing him<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>vaytsaw (tswh): he ordered him</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ka Yakob madhutu lii paredha ina dènge ama na, ka pakèd'i la'e asa Padan Aram.<bt>And Yakob followed the commands of his mother and father, and left for Padan Aram.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii sasue = blessing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">lii sasue = blessing</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shalach ... yelech: is this an"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shalach ... yelech: is this an overlay structure?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Aa Esau dhu ne'a le kahèi, ama na d'èi boe dhèu èmu na, bhèni Kana'an dua sèra.<bt>So Esau also knew that his father did not like his spouses, those two Kana'an women.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yarʔ: saw, realized, perceived, it dawned"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yarʔ: saw, realized, perceived, it dawned on him raʕot: disagreeable, contemptible, displeasing, objectionable<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Hèia na la'e asa ama aae na Ismael, ka leo hari èmu dènge ana bhèni Ismael ca dhèu, ngara na Mahalat. Mahalat ne, ana mone na ka Nebayot.<bt>So he went to his big father (=father's older brother) Ismael, and married again one of Ismael's daughters, named Mahalat. This Mahalat was the son of Nebayot.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ama aae = bapa besar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">ama aae = bapa besar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕesau: Esau goes to his father's"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕesau: Esau goes to his father's half brother, just as Jacob goes to his mother's brother, mirror image. Maybe he still doesn't get it about what his father really wants, and thinks he will make his father happy by marrying a relative instead of somebody from a nearby family. He is close to his father, so he probably isn't doing this to bug him. But he might be. ʕal-nashaw lo: in addition to the wives he had - unusual construction.<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob nii ètu Betel<bt>Yakob dreams at Betel</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ka Yakob tèke eele Beer Syeba, la'e asa Haran.<bt>Then Yakob left behind Beer Syeba, going toward Haran.</bt><v n="11" />Ropa lod'o cèna, Yakob d'ai era èci, ka na j'unu ètu era èèna. Na neo j'unu, nare hadhu cue, tao lalaka kètu na.<bt>When the sun set, Yakob arrived at a place, and he slept in that place. [When] he was about to sleep, he took a stone, and used it as a headrest.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasoro = lay down, tidor maen-maen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pasoro = lay down, tidor maen-maen ; lalaka = pengganti bantal, headrest</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meʔavney: from the stones of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">meʔavney: from the stones of the place. It could read "some of the stones," like a a ring of stones like a wall around his head for protection. But in the morning it's clearly a single stone being used as a head-rest (some would say a pillow). yifgaʕ: he reached a place, ran into someone, met someone<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>yalen (lyn): stay overnight, spend the night yasem (sim): put something somewhere<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>mraʔashotav: what is at the head, as a head-rest for him yishkav: he laid down.<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00683c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />D'ara mèda èèna, na nii. Na ladhe nèdhi langa èci dhu patitu ètu rai, suu na d'ai dedha-liru. Ka ana pajuu Ama Lamatua nèti sorga, ca'e-puru ètu dedha langa èèna.<bt>During that night, he dreamed. And he saw a ladder standing on the ground, with its tip/top reaching the sky. And the servants of God from heaven were ascending-descending on that ladder.</bt><v n="13" />Ètu d'ara nii na, Yakob ladhe nèdhi LAMATUA dhu titu ètu karasa nèngu, hèia na lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne LAMATUA, Ama Lamatua nèti baki mu Abraham, dènge ama mu Isak. Èèna na, Ja'a hia rai ne mi èu dènge ana-èpu èu.<bt>In his dream, Yakob saw the LORD standing beside him, and then he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;I am the LORD, the God of your grandfather Abraham, and your father Isak. Later I will give this land to you and your descendants.</bt><v n="14" />Bèli-camèd'a, ana-èpu èu ae-ae, sama sèmi ahu rai ne. Rèngu se, èèna na, pea palème era-era ètu rai-haha ne. Nèti ana-èpu èu ka, suku aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne, abhu mèngi-nale.<bt>Later, your descendants will be many, like the dust of the ground. They will live scattered in various places on the earth. From your descendants, all the tribes on the earth will get blessing.</bt><note reference="28:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 3:25; Galati 3:8</note><v n="15" />Mage mu bhèlu! Èu ne ètu mia èèna ka, Ja'a bera-bera dènge èu. Ladhe èèna na, Ja'a lere kèti hari èu mai asa dedha-rai ne'e. Ja'a bhera boe èu. Aa èèna na, Ja'a tao aa'i madhutu sèmi lii pajaji Ja'a dènge èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Don't forget! Wherever you are, I am together with you. So in the future I will lead you back to this land. I will not abandon/ignore you. And I will do everything according to My promise with you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="langa = tangga (3 jenis)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">langa = tangga (3 jenis)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ropa Yakob kèd'i nèti bhèj'i, na padhai lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a heka ke'a kèna, LAMATUA dhu ètu era ne'e kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yakob awoke from sleep, he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;I just now understand that the LORD is also in this place.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="17" />Na madha'u, ka na pangee, na, &lt;&lt;Boo! Era ne'e ne pamadha'u ja'a, nga. Tatu Èmu Ama Lamatua ètu era ne'e ne! Aa era ne'e ne, j'aj'i hèb'a babèdho sorga.&gt;&gt;<bt>He was afraid, and he thought, &lt;&lt;Boo! This place frightens me. Certainly the House of God is in this place! And this place is the doorway to heaven2.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="28:12-17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 1:51</note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00685c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Yakob mangaj'i mi Lamatua ètu Betel<bt>Yakob worship's the Lord at Betel</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />D'ara mad'ae aae era, Yakob kèd'i le èèna. Ka nare hadhu dhu na tao lalaka deo na. Hèia na patitu j'aj'i mi tadha. Ka na bhori èi mènyi asa dedha hadhu èèna, hèia na mangaj'i mi Lamatua.<bt>Early in the morning, Yakob got up. And he took the stone which he had just used as a headrest. Then he erected it as a sign. And he poured oil over that rock, and he worshipped God2.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yashkem: get up early mraʔashtav: as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yashkem: get up early mraʔashtav: as a place for his head<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>matstsəvah: standing stone, a memorial standing alone, an unhewn, upright stone for cult or burial or memorial purposes. This was forbidden later; but in its archaic significance it was like one of the altars that Abraham and Isaac built to commemorate dealings with God. yitsoq: he poured oil<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Ka na pangare era ne <span class="Italic">Betel,</span> dhu sasoa na &lt;Èmu Lamatua&gt;. (Uru èèna, era ne ngara na Lus.)<bt>And he named that place <span class="Italic">Betel,</span> which means &lt;House of God2&gt;. (Previously, this place was named Lus.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nanèlu = bantal, alas kepala ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">nanèlu = bantal, alas kepala ; lalaka = bantal dari sembarang bahan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔulam: only lariʔshonah|i(19) |r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔulam: only lariʔshonah<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Èle èèna ka, Yakob ded'e subha, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Ama Lamatua dhu dènge ja'a, aa j'aga ja'a ètu d'ara kakako ja'a ne, aa panga'e dènge papake ja'a,<bt>After that, Yakob swore an oath, saying, &lt;&lt;If God is with me, and guards me on this journey of mine, and feeds and clothes me,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiddar neder (ndr imperf): he made"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiddar neder (ndr imperf): he made a vow (a promise to do something special). This is the key turning point in Jacob's life, dealing directly with God instead of just hearing about him.</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />toke ja'a lèpa dènge sod'a, èèna na LAMATUA j'aj'i mi Ama Lamatua ja'a.<bt>until I return safely, then the LORD will be my God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vshalom: in good condition. This is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vshalom: in good condition. This is not negative; God has already promised to be with Jacob. in Hebrew: He is talking to God. He switches from 3rd person to 2nd within his speech (v. 22 "you"). (Note in eastern Indonesian lgs, 3rd person is often used for direct address.)<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Hadhu dhu ja'a patitu ne, j'aj'i mi era sogo-tagu mi Ama Lamatua. Aa aa'i-aa'i dhu Lamatua pala-bagi mi ja'a, ja'a hia Na ca pala nèti canguru pala.&gt;&gt;<bt>This rock which I erected, will be a place of (traditionally) worshipping God. And everything that God2 distributes to me, I will give Him one part from ten parts.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕasser ʔaʕassərenu lakh: I will give"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕasser ʔaʕassərenu lakh: I will give ten per cent to you</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob d'ai èmu to'o na Laban<bt>Yakob arrives at mother's-brother Laban's house</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="29" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia Yakob kako hari ka asa bèka dhimu.<bt>After that, Yakob went on going to the east.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayissaʔ raglaw (nsʔ): he lifted up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayissaʔ raglaw (nsʔ): he lifted up his feet = left there (hapax) bəne qedem: Easterners (they were actually more to the north and east, but that's how people saw their geography, and their political and religious connections were to the southeast of them, because it was a different culture there)<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ca lod'o, ladhe nèdhi èi ca madha, dètu dènge rae cue. Padètu-dètu dènge madha èi èèna, abhu tèlu kaboko kahib'i-kalèbho, dhu mate rinu èi. Te ngaa hadhu aae cue dhu ra pasaguru mi hèb'a èi na.<bt>One day, he saw a well, near a village. Near the well, there were three groups of sheep-goats, who were waiting to drink water. But there was a large stone covering the wouth of that well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hine: shows things from Jacob's perspective,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hine: shows things from Jacob's perspective, not the narratorʔs basadeh: in an uncultivated area.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>ʕedray: a flock or herd belonging to one individual rovtsim: lying down with chest on the ground<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>yashqu (shqh hif): watered haʔeven: the stone -- why the article? gadolah is predicate; protecting a well with a stone was standard practice, so the stone is given; only the size is unusual.<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Dhu tema le, ladhe kahib'i tesa aa'i-aa'i ra, ana-ana madhenga kahib'i se, lasi bhoke hadhu na, heka ra dhui kèna, panginu kahib'i si. Panginu rare na, ra katange hari hadhu na la'e.<bt>What was the norm, was when the goats (gen) were all there, the goat herders would go open that stone, and then scoop giving drink to the goats. After giving them drink, they would replace the stone.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasaguru = tutu; 3: dhui ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pasaguru = tutu; 3: dhui = timba</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="neʔesfu-shamah (nif): they gathered there. Waltke"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">neʔesfu-shamah (nif): they gathered there. Waltke says the imperfect shows this to be a consequence of Verse 2. The other verbs are perfects. But it could also be a generic imperfect: it was their custom that the sheep gathered there gallu: they rolled the stone off the mouth of the well. The way they managed the flocks was not common practice, as Jacob pointed out. Possibly a local compromise designed to keep the first group there from hogging all the water.<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>hishqu (shqh hif): they caused to drink limqomah: into its place<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ka Yakob kako la'e asa madha dhèu madhenge kahib'i se, hèia na karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu se, dhèu mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yakob went to front up to the goat herders, and then he asked, saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl here, are what kind of person? (=social/geographical identity)&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia ra dhaa, &lt;&lt;Ji'i se, nèti rae Haran ne'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>So they responded, &lt;&lt;We-exc are from the village of Haran here.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="&quot;Brothers&quot; shows he is being friendly,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">"Brothers" shows he is being friendly, though he doesn't know them and he doesn't have any clout with anybody. Joseph's brothers were taking care of their sheep at least 60 miles away from their home, so this might have been quite a ways out of Haran. But it canʔt have been very far, because both Rachel and Laban ran between there and home. So maybe it's over a rise from which the town is not yet visible, though it's actually close by.<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>meʔayin: from where?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ka Yakob karèi hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu tadhe to'o ja'a, Laban, do? Nèngu na, ana Nahor.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yakob asked further, saying, &lt;&lt;Do you-pl know my mother's-brother Laban, right? He is the child of Nahor.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka ra dhaa, &lt;&lt;Ji'i tadhe ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>And they responded, &lt;&lt;We-exc know him.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ben: naming the most famous one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ben: naming the most famous one in the lineage, not the immediate father (Betuʕel). This has implications for lots of genealogies, especially in Genesis. yadaʕnu: Wenham interprets this as a surly reply, not very helpful; but given the nature of other reported conversations in Hebrew it sounds like normal question and response. Besides, in Verse 6 they have a helpful comeback, even though they donʔt know who Jacob is and they could have an interest in protecting Rachel.<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Hèia Yakob karèi hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Na be'a-be'a, sina ma?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob asked again, saying, &lt;&lt;Is he well, or what?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka ra peka, &lt;&lt;Oo, na be'a-be'a. Ladhe, ana bhèni na ka nèi. Ngara na, Rahel. Nuka eo nèti kahib'i ama na mai sa ne'e, ho hia rinu ètu ne'e. Mate ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>And they said, &lt;&lt;Ya, he's well. Look, there's his daughter yonder. Her name is Rahel. She's herding her father's goats coming this way, to give them drink here. Wait a little.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="almost like &quot;as a matter of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">almost like "as a matter of fact, now that you mention Laban, there's his daughter!" The "try look" sounds like they want to be helpful, even though they still donʔt know who Jacob is.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Hèia Yakob peka hari, &lt;&lt;Loo nètu era. De be'a risi, badha mia ètu se'e le, panginu ka si. Sèna ka lere mèti hari asa d'ara pad'a, ho ra'a hari j'u'u.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob spoke again, &lt;&lt;It's noon. So it would be good if whatever animals are already here, are given drink. So that they can be led back to the pastures, to eat grass again.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lonètu &lt; /lod'o nètu/ = noon,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">Lonètu &lt; /lod'o nètu/ = noon,</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hen: demonstrative conjunction. Jacob is probably"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hen: demonstrative conjunction. Jacob is probably talking to hired men or teenagers put in charge of the sheep. He is more curt with them than they are with him. There is no social equal for him to talk to. It also shows he is a take-charge guy who knows what he's about, which may have also attracted Laban's attention as a prospective son-in-law with guts. ʕod: still<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>ʕet heʕasef (nif inf): time to be gathered, gather hamiqneh: the livestock<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>lkhu rʕu (hlk rʕh): let them go graze</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa ra peka, &lt;&lt;We, j'ara na aad'o sèmi èèna! Ji'i mate toke tesa aa'i ku, heka ji'i pakeso hadhu ne, heka panginu badha se kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>But they said, &lt;&lt;We, that's not the way it is! We-exc wait until everyone is here, and only then do we shove over the stone, and only then do we give drinks to these animals.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nowkhal: we canʔt ʕad ʔasher: until|i(8)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nowkhal: we canʔt ʕad ʔasher: until<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>yeʔasfu: they come together, are together gallu: 3rd person. Could be that the people who are talking are the ones that actually move the sheep by the watering troughs, after a designated group of them roll the stone off the mouth of the well.<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Yakob padhai lii era, Rahel d'ai le era èèna dènge kahib'i ama na. Nèngu ka dhu biasa ladhe-leru si.<bt>Yakob was still speaking, when Rahel arrived at that place with her father's goats. She was the one who normally looked after them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakeso = kasi geser"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pakeso = kasi geser</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕodenu: while they were still talking;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕodenu: while they were still talking; their continuation At this point Jacob knows he has found the family. The emphasis is on still on kinship, not yet on Rachel herself.<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00687c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Yakob bhoke hadhu dhu saguru èi<bt>Yakob opens the stone which covers the well</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ropa Yakob nèdhi Rahel dènge kahib'i sèra, la'e dènge ka pa'eso eele hadhu dhu saguru hèb'a èi na. Ka na panginu badha to'o na sèra.<bt>When Yakob saw Rahel with the goats, he went and moved away the stone which covered the mouth of the well. And he gave his mother's-brother's animals to drink.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayigash (ngsh): step up, go forward."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayigash (ngsh): step up, go forward. Jacob may be showing off how strong he is. He's definitely a mover and shaker, and has already taken charge of the situation. yagel: he rolled the stone off the top of the well<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Èle ka, la'e uu Rahel, dènge tangi.<bt>After that, he went and kissed Rahel, and cried.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayishaq (nshq qal): kiss, likely on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayishaq (nshq qal): kiss, likely on both cheeks. Since Rachel still doesn't know who he is, he is flouting convention. vayisaʔ ʔet-qolo: he lifted up his voice; loudly. Why is he crying? "Long lost cousin, wen dey firs meet, dey do." SK<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ka na lolo dènge Rahel, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ari! Ja'a ne, ana nèti Ribka, ana hèni ama mu.&gt;&gt; Hèia Rahel rai sa èmu la'e, peka dènge ama na.<bt>Then, he narrated to Rahel, saying, &lt;&lt;Younger-sibling! I am the child of Ribka, your father's sister.&gt;&gt; Then Rahel ran home, reporting to her father.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'eso = kasi geser"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pa'eso = kasi geser</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaged (ngd hif): informed, announced, put"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayaged (ngd hif): informed, announced, put something up conspicuously in front of somebody. Jacob identifies himself as a kinsman, and probably gives some details, but he also probably doesn't tell the whole story of the intrigues and strife that made him come. achi: not "brothers" in the narrow sense, but "kinsmen".<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>tarats: she ran</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ropa Laban tadèngi lii lolo Rahel, dhu peka na Yakob ana nèti ana hèni na Ribka, ka la'e dènge ka, soru nare Yakob. Ropa na d'ai, liku nare Yakob, ka na uu, hèia gale nèti dènge ka, lasi asa èmu na. Ka Yakob lolo aa'i-aa'i dènge to'o na.<bt>When Laban heard Rahel's story, that Yakob was his younger-sister Ribka's child, he went immediately going to greet Yakob. When he arrived, he embraced Yakob, and kissed him, and then invited him to go to his house. Then Yakob narrated everything to his mother's-brother..</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kishmoaʕ (abs): when he heard. Why"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">kishmoaʕ (abs): when he heard. Why absolute? liqraʔto (qrʔ inf): happening to someone, come to someone, toward someone<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>yəchabbeq: He embraced him ynashsheq (piʕel): kiss fervently? (Jacob kisses Rachel with Qal. Laban kisses Jacob with Piʕel.)<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ysafer: relate, tell. Again, he probably doesn't say that he's on the run, or that he is looking for a wife. But he has to tell enough inside information to prove his identity as a member of the family. Laban had been a player in Rebecca's going away, but Jacob didnʔt show up with ten camels loaded with gold. The Return Of Martin Gere is a novel taken from a medieval French court report of an impostor who showed up and claimed Martin Gere's wife after Gere had gone to war. The impostor knows a lot of Gere family secrets (possibly told to him by the wife, or by Martin), and is accepted. Then the real Martin shows up. There is the same theme in The Sign Of The Fingerpost, a recent novel.</Message></Annotation><v n="14a" />Hèia Laban lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mema tare'a! Èdhi dua ti dhu pa'a'ari.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Laban spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;It's really true! The two of us-inc are RECIP-family!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕatsmi uvsari: my bone and my"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕatsmi uvsari: my bone and my flesh = total being, everything about you is just like me. Laban is convinced that Jacob is the real thing; the family secrets check out.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob nare Lea dènge Rahel, j'aj'i dhèu èmu na<bt>Yakob takes Lea and Rahel to be his spouses</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14b" />Ropa Yakob pea dènge rèngu d'ai ca hèru,<bt>When Yakob had lived with them for a month,</bt><v n="15" />Laban padhai lii dènge ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Yakob! Ja'a ko'o boe, sèna ka èu sab'a hia ja'a dènge iia-iia d'ara, lula èdhi se dhu pa'a'ari. De èu neo sèna ka rui-j'aj'èra èu ja'a b'ae ca ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Laban spoke with him, saying, &lt;&lt;Yakob! I do not want for you to work for me for free (idiomatic), just because the two of us are relatives. So what are you wanting for me to pay you for your bone of suffering (=work, efforts)?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="iia-iia dara = free, gratis"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">iia-iia dara = free, gratis</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chinnam (adv): without compensation, for free"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">chinnam (adv): without compensation, for free hagidah (ngd impv): put forward an opinion, report, announce, tell<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>maskurtekha: your wages</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Laban ne, dhu dènge ana bhèni dhèu dua. Dhu uru, ngara na Lea. Aa ari na, ngara na Rahel.<bt>Laban had two daughters. The older one was named Lea. And her younger-sibling was named Rahel.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rashi points out that in normal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Rashi points out that in normal interfamily relationships, Leah would have been matched with Esau and Rachel with Jacob. Leah may have heard enough about Esau to be glad to settle for the younger son. She falls in love with him, probably after the marriage.</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Lea ne, musi madha na ako ahu.<bt>This Lea, her eyes were rather cloudy/unclear.</bt><note reference="29:17" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Ibrani ètu ne'e, mèu iia boe.<bt>The Ibrani language here is not clear.</bt></note>Te ngaa Rahel, rèhu na bhèni iia, aa ngi'u na saraga bia.<bt>But Rahel, her face was female-beautiful, and her body was very nice/pleasing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rakhot: frail, weak; tender, sensitive, delicate,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">rakhot: frail, weak; tender, sensitive, delicate, soft (Wenham). The word is usually used positively: tender, vulnerable. It sounds like Leah was fairly ordinary looking except for her eyes, which were exceptionally soft and dreamy. Rachel, on the other hand, was a knockout, like Miss Mesopotamia. yfat-toʔar: beautiful figure, shape<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Yakob d'èi risi Rahel. Ka na peka dènge Laban, &lt;&lt;Ladhe to'o ku mo'o, ja'a sab'a hia to'o ku pidhu tèu, sad'i to'o ku hia ja'a madhèdi dènge Rahel.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yakob really liked Rahel. And he spoke with Laban, &lt;&lt;If MB (mother's-brother) agrees, I will work for MB for seven years, as long as MB lets me marry Rahel.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mare boe = muka asam ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">mare boe = muka asam ; kuji = sayu, eye-brows raised at the ends ; ako ahu = agak kabur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʔehav: he fell in love"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yeʔehav: he fell in love</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Hèia Laban dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ko'o! Be'a risi, ja'a paleo èu dènge Rahel, lula èdhi dua ti dhu a'ari. Mage dhoka na madhèdi dènge dhèu leo. De mu pea mi ne'e, sèna ka sab'a hia ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Laban responded, saying, &lt;&lt;I'd like that! It would be better for me to marry you to Rahel, because the two of us-inc are relatives. May it not be that she marries a different person (implies different category, e.g. race, religion). So you live here, so you can work for me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="titi (ntn): infinitive absolute"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">titi (ntn): infinitive absolute</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ka Yakob sab'a hia Laban pidhu tèu, sèna ka na bisa madhèdi dènge Rahel. Lula na d'èi madhe-madhe Rahel, nèti èèna ka, pidhu tèu èèna, na pangee nuka sèmi pèri-pèri lod'o di.<bt>So Yakob worked for Laban for seven years, so that he could marry Rahel. Because he really-really loved Rahel, that is why those seven years, the thought of as only a few days.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ropa risi nèti pidhu tèu, ka na pasanèd'e Laban, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;To'o! Ja'a sab'a le hia to'o ku pidhu tèu, de paleo ka ja'a dènge Rahel.&gt;&gt;<bt>When the seven years had passed, he reminded Laban, saying, &lt;&lt;MB! I have worked for MB for seven years, so marry me to Rahel.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="havah (impv): give, come on! Strange"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">havah (impv): give, come on! Strange form, possibly from yhb. vʔavoʔah (bwʔ impf): I will go in to her (referring to beginning a sexual relation). Take her as my wife. It has sexual overtones, and is kind of coarse, in contrast with "lwn" used for Ruth and Boaz.<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>The time discontinuity seems to be between 20 and 21. This break follows Tanakh, not the Christian versions.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Hèia Laban tao tatao, ka na nèru aa'i rae lesa ètu rae èèna.<bt>So Laban made a feast/celebration, and he invited all inhabitants of that village.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʔsof: gather. This is not a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yeʔsof: gather. This is not a typical Hebrew wedding, where the groom goes to the bride's house or a third party's house to bring her back to his house. Jacob doesn't have a house; he's living with Laban just as Rachel is. ʔanoshey hamaqom: men of the place<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>mishteh: drinking-bout, banquet with wine</Message></Annotation><v n="23-27" />Ropa d'ai mèda èèna, Laban hia boe Rahel, te ngaa na pua Lea maso asa d'ara paleo Yakob. Ka Yakob j'unu dènge ne. Asa bèli èèna, Yakob heka ne'a kèna, nèngu dhu leo dènge Lea di. Hèia Yakob la'e patao dènge Laban, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka, to'o pasèru ja'a sèmi ne'e? Ja'a sab'a sèmi ènu pidhu tèu kateme hia mi èu, sèna ka bisa abhu Rahel! Nga tao ka to'o pasilu dènge Lea?&gt;&gt;<bt>That night, Laban did not give Rahel, but he sent Lea to enter into Yakob's tent/shelter. And Yakob slept with her. The next day, only-then did Yakob know that he had married Lea. So Yakob went to argue/protest to Laban, saying, &lt;&lt;Why has MB decieved me like this? I worked like a slave for seven full years for you, so that I could get Rahel! Why did MB replace her with Lea?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tipu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">tipu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Leah's eyes might have given her"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Leah's eyes might have given her away, even with a veil. Maybe Rachel attended the wedding, and Leah didnʔt show up till they were alone in the dark. Another elaborate deception behind the scenes; both Rachel and Leah must have been in on the switch (Rashi). Mishteh in v. 22 implies that Jacob had been drinking, so maybe he wasnʔt noticing details by that time. hineh: The situation has already been explained to the reader. Hineh gives Jacob's personal reaction to it. Prototype case of the word. "Hineh hiʔ leʔah" is unusual, a unique construction. "Hineh leʔah hiʔ" would be expected. In a Midrash, Jacob has pulled a deception on his father involving touch; Laban deceives Jacob in a way that involves touch too (but Jacob may not have noticed the parallel). Leah has to act the part of Rachel all night. She loves him and knows that he doesn't love her. From there on out, Jacob plays favorites inside the family just as Isaac did.<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>rimitani (rmh piʕel): deceive me, leave me dangling</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Laban dhaa, &lt;&lt;Baku nasa ku! Madhutu ad'a ji'i ètu rai ne'e, ari bisa boe leo uuru èmu nèti a'a. De be'a risi sèmi ne'e! Èu mate hari ku pidhu lod'o, d'ai èle tatao ne, heka èu abhu Rahel kèna. Sad'i èu sab'a hari hia ja'a pidhu tèu.&gt;&gt; Hèia Laban pangèd'u dènge ènu bhèni èci, hia mi Lea. Ngara na Silpa.<bt>And Laban responded, &lt;&lt;Don't be angry with me! According to our-exc adat here in this land, a younger-sibling may not marry before her elder-sibling. It would be better to do like this! You wait another seven days, until this celebration is over, and then you will get Rahel. As long as you work for me another seven years.&gt;&gt; Then Laban turned-over a female slave to Lea. Her name was Silpa.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiten: he gave - is this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiten: he gave - is this like a wedding present on that occasion (the narrative [consecutive] tense sounds like it), or had it happened before the wedding night? Probably put here to delay the punch line, (as both Labov and I have noticed is a characteristic of well told stories), because elsewhere in describing weddings only major gifts are mentioned on the bride's side of the family. shifchato: her maidservant, slave. lshifchato would be more usual.<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>habəkhirah: older sister. Usually used only of males, but this is the feminine form. Jacob may have know the custom but assumed that they would make an exception for him. When they didnʔt, he didnʔt have a leg to stand on, but had to accept Laban's deal. tsʕirah: younger<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>Rebecca going off immediately may have bothered Laban. He takes elaborate steps to keep Rachel and Jacob around for a long time malleʔ (piʕel imperv): fill out this week<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>shvuaʕ zoʔt: the bridal week of this woman. zoʔt and hiʔ are never mixed in Hebrew. zoʔt is used here for both women. ʕod: still, besides, another seven years<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>nitnah: we will give her? I will give her? "we let you marry" is a variant taken from Samaritan, LXX, and other versions. Book of Jubilees: "he served seven years more for Rachel, because Leah had been given to him gratis."</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Lii padhai Laban deo na, Yakob d'èi kahèi. Nèti èèna ka, èle tatao ne pidhu lod'o, ka Laban pamadhèdi hari Yakob dènge Rahel.<bt>What Laban had said earlier, Yakob agreed to it. Because of that, when the seven days of celebration were over, Laban married of Yakob to Rahel.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ymaleʔ (piʕel): he fulfilled the time."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ymaleʔ (piʕel): he fulfilled the time. Jon Rawlings: "Outside of Eden there are no unmixed blessings."</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Ka Laban hia ènu na dhèu bhèni èci, ngara na Bilha, sèna ka j'aj'i mi ènu Rahel.<bt>And Laban gave a female slave, named Bilha, so be a slave to Rahel.</bt><v n="30" />Hèia Yakob pa'èci ka dènge Rahel. Na d'èi risi Rahel nèti Lea. Ka Yakob sab'a hari hia to'o na pidhu tèu.<bt>Then Yakob joined with Rahel. He liked/loved rahel more than Lea. And Yakob worked for his MB another seven years.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-ana Yakob<bt>Yakob's children</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Te ngaa LAMATUA ne'a le, Yakob sue risi Rahel nèti Lea. Nèti èèna ka, Na hia Lea nara iisi ana. Te ngaa Rahel abhu boe ana.<bt>But the LORD knew that Yakob loved Rahel more that Lea. That is why He let Lea bear children. But Rahel didn't have children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This part is not chronologically later"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">This part is not chronologically later than Verse 30. It's the same time span, but focuses on a different set of circumstances. snuʔah (snʔ pt): hate; unable or unwilling to put up with somebody, slighted wife<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>vayiftach et-rachmah: God opened her womb ʕaqarah: barren, without offspring<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Hèia Lea dènge babia, ka nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu. Na pangare ne, <span class="Italic">Ruben</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;mèdhi si, abhu ana&gt;),<bt>So Lea became pregnant, and gave birth to a son. She named him, <span class="Italic">Ruben</span> (which means &lt;look here, there's a child&gt;),</bt><note reference="29:32" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Ibrani, &lt;Ruben&gt; sasoa na &lt;mèdhi, abhu ana&gt;. Aa lii na oe sama sèmi lii èci, dhu sasoa na &lt;na ladhe nèdhi sasusa ja'a&gt;.<bt>According to the Ibrani language, &lt;Ruben&gt; means &lt;look, there is a child&gt;. And it sounds almost like a word which means &lt;he has seen my difficulty&gt;.</bt></note>lula na peka na, &lt;&lt;LAMATUA ladhe nèdhi le sasusa ja'a. Nèti èèna ka, limuri ne, dhèu èmu ja'a tao madha-dhilu mi ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>because she said, &lt;&lt;The LORD has seen my difficulties. That is why now, my spouse will pay attention (Idiom: eye-ear) me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mola dhoo-dhoo = sonde dapa apa-apa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">mola dhoo-dhoo = sonde dapa apa-apa (lit. lurus kutuk-kutuk) kasar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tahar (hrh): get pregnant bʕanyi (ʕani):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tahar (hrh): get pregnant bʕanyi (ʕani): in my affliction, overwhelmed by want, unfortunate, misery. This is strong language, and having a character voice an inner state is rare for Hebrew narrative. Why the b-? look upon?<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>Naming the baby in hope that her husband will love her is poignant.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ka Lea dènge hari babia, hèia nara iisi hari ana mone èci. Na pangare ne, <span class="Italic">Simeon</span> (dhu sasoa na, ele boe &lt;dhèu tadèngi le&gt;), lula na peka na, &lt;&lt;LAMATUA dhu ne'a na, dhèu èmu ja'a sue boe ja'a. Tu d'ai èèna ka, Na hia ja'a ana dhèu èci hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Lea got pregnant again, and bore another son. She named him, <span class="Italic">Simeon</span> (which means, something like &lt;someone has heard&gt;), because she said, &lt;&lt;The LORD knows that my spouse does not love me. So that is why He has given me another child.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="snuʔah: hate, disdain"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">snuʔah: hate, disdain</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Èle èèna ka, Lea kad'o hari ana èci, ka nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu. Na pangare na <span class="Italic">Lewi,</span><bt>After that, Lea was visited by another child (Fig. = pregnant), and she gave birth to a son. She named him <span class="Italic">Lewi,</span></bt><note reference="29:34" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">&lt;Lewi&gt; sasoa na ele boe &lt;pa'èki&gt;, do &lt;paliku padètu-dètu&gt;.<bt>&lt;Lewi&gt; means something like &lt;bound to&gt;, or &lt;hug closely&gt;.</bt></note>lula na peka na, &lt;&lt;Dènge ana ne'e ne, èle dènge lii langu ja'a. D'ara dhèu èmu ja'a, pa'èki dènge ja'a, lula ja'a matana hia ne ana mone, dhèu tèlu kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>because she said, &lt;&lt;With this child, my disputes will be over. The insides of my spouse are/will be bound to me, because I have born him three sons.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hapaʕam: just this once, this time"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hapaʕam: just this once, this time yillaweh (lwh nif): he will join himself. The priestly and kingly lines came about by Laban's deception. Leah was Jesusʔ great-to-the-nth-power grandma.<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Ka Lea dènge hari babia ca tèka, hèia nara iisi ana mone èci. Na pangare na, <span class="Italic">Yahuda</span> (dhu sasoa na ele boe &lt;koa-kio&gt;), lula na peka na, &lt;&lt;Dènge j'ara ne'e ne, ja'a neo koa-kio LAMATUA!&gt;&gt; Èle ka, Lea dènge heka ana.<bt>After that, Lea became pregnant again, and she gave birth to a son. She named him, <span class="Italic">Yahuda</span> (which means something like &lt;praise (doublet)&gt;), because she said, &lt;&lt;In this way, I'm going to praise the LORD!&gt;&gt; After that, Lea didn't give birth again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔodeh (ydh hif imperf): I will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔodeh (ydh hif imperf): I will praise taʕmod miledet: she stopped having children (stand still, go on hold)<span class="Italic">(35)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="30" />
      <v n="1" />Te ngaa Rahel dhu abhu mèka ana. Nèti èèna ka, nèngu tèke d'ara dènge a'a na. Hèia na peka dènge dhèu èmu na, &lt;&lt;A'a! Hia ku ja'a ana laa, ma. Ladhe aad'o, be'a risi ja'a madhe ka laa.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Rahel had no children. Because of that, she was jealous of her elder-sibling. So she told her spouse, &lt;&lt;Older-sibling [=vocative of wife to husband] Give me a child [+demand]. If not, it would be better for me to die.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təqaneʔ: she was envious of her"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">təqaneʔ: she was envious of her sister. Waltke-OʔConnor from Muraoka, qinneʔ ʔet ʔbe jealous of somebody, resent humiliation brought about by somebodyʔ, bə ʔenvy somebody's successʔ, lə ʔbe zealous for somebody or some causeʔ. This one is envy at Leah's success. havah: give, like Jacob to Laban, a demand, with desperate urgency; a request with an edge to it.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>bahim: sons? children? UBS suggests children. metah (mwt partcpl fem): I will die [of shame at being childless]; be mortified. These two verses are the only dialogue between Jacob and Rachel that is recorded. The rabbis considered this the opening ploy in Rachel's plan to have her children with Bilhah as surrogate mother. The Book of Jubilees says that when Leah has a child, she gives it to a nurse. Then she gets pregnant again, which gives her greater prestige in one-upmanship within the family.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Te ngaa Yakob jèke ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu ngee na, ja'a ne, Lamatua, ho bisa hia èu ana!?&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yakob spoke harshly to her, saying, &lt;&lt;Do you think that I am the Lord, so I can give you a child!?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayichar-ʔaf: it was kindled; his nose"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayichar-ʔaf: it was kindled; his nose became hot = he broke out angrily against. WO impersonal of emotion hatachat: underneath, instead of<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>manaʕ: restrains, withholds something from someone, deny something to someone. Jacob's view is that it is God who decides how everything is going to come out. This may echo in Verse 8 with the name Naftali pri-beten: fruit of the womb, offspring<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ka Rahel b'ala na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e: hua iia èu more Bilha, ènu ja'a na. J'unu dènge ne, sèna ka na matana hia ja'a ana.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Rahel replied, &lt;&lt;It's like this: It would be better for you to take Bilha, my slave. Sleep with her, so that she can bear children for me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔamati: my slave girl ʕal-birkhay: bear"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔamati: my slave girl ʕal-birkhay: bear them on my knees, onto my lap (= I will be their recognized mother). Rare for a woman to say this; bearing a child "on someone's knees" is usually what a man does in contracting a surrogate mother to bear a child for his legal wife.<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>ʔibbaneh (bnh nif): I will be built = I will get a child, start a family line of my own gam: also (the same as Leah is doing)<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>They do all the machinations and magic, but there is no indication that it is makes any difference. It is God who makes things come out his way no matter what they do.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Hèia na pangèd'u Bilha mi dhèu èmu na. Ka Yakob j'unu dènge ne.<bt>Then she turned-over Bilha to her spouse. And Yakob slept with her.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lʔishshah: wife, concubine; the same word"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">lʔishshah: wife, concubine; the same word covers both. But Bilhah was a slave, and she had no way of ever getting recognized as Jacob's official wife.</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Ka Bilha dènge babia, hèia nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu.<bt>And Bilha became pregnant, and she gave birth to a son.</bt><v n="6" />Hèia Rahel padhai lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua nanene le lii manèngi-mangaj'i ja'a. Nèti èèna ka, Na hia ja'a ana mone ca dhèu. Ama Lamatua pama'ète le, lii langu ja'a dènge mola-mola.&gt;&gt; Ka na pangare ana ne, <span class="Italic">Dan</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;pama'ète lii&gt;).<bt>Then Rahel spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;God has heard my prayer. That is why He has given me a son. God has decided/settled my dispute justly/fairly.&gt;&gt; So she named that child, <span class="Italic">Dan</span> (which means &lt;decides/settles a dispute&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dananni (dyn perf): bring justice, redress"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">dananni (dyn perf): bring justice, redress a wrong for someone, execute justice. Rachel is being vindicated for giving Bilhah to Jacob: Bilhah has a child, so it must have been God's will.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Èle èèna ka, Bilha dènge hari babia, ka nara iisi ana mone èci.<bt>After that, Bilha became pregnant again, and she gave birth to a son.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sheni: a second time"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">sheni: a second time</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ka Rahel peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a limuri ne pa'uji dènge a'a ku, ka ja'a segi.&gt;&gt; Nèti èèna ka, na pangare ana na, <span class="Italic">Naftali</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;pa'uji&gt;, do &lt;pa'ère&gt;).<bt>And Rahel spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;I have been competing with my older-sibling, and I have won.&gt;&gt; Because of that, she named the child, <span class="Italic">Naftali</span> (which means &lt;compete&gt;, or &lt;pull at each other&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakaj'èla = ba'usir, bakejar ; pa'uji"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pakaj'èla = ba'usir, bakejar ; pa'uji</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naftuley ʔəlohiym: I have struggled mightily"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">naftuley ʔəlohiym: I have struggled mightily (one use of "of God"). Calvin: mighty wrestlings? the struggles of God? I have devised a fine trick against my sister? the twists and turns of God's ways? Sarna: wrestling for God, for God's attention? Aalders: wrestling before God, referring to extraordinary circumstances? ʔəlohiym: God, but probably an intensifier here. Possibly a vocative.<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>niftalti ʕim (nif partcpl perf): twist, struggle, wrestle, be tortuous, subtle yacolti: I can; I win<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ropa Lea ne'a na nèngu ne dènge heka ana, ka na paleo ènu na Silpa dènge Yakob.<bt>When Lea knew that she was no longer having children, she wedded her slave Silpa with Yakob.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yarʔ (rʔh): put two and two"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yarʔ (rʔh): put two and two together, perceive</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ka Silpa nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu.<bt>And Silpa gave birth to a son.</bt><v n="11" />Hèia Lea peka na, &lt;&lt;Kalua ja'a, mèngi le.&gt;&gt; Ka na pangare na, <span class="Italic">Gad</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;kalua mèngi&gt;).<bt>And Lea spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;My fate is now good/straight.&gt;&gt; And she named him, <span class="Italic">Gad</span> (which means &lt;good fate&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bagad: in luck, good luck, good"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bagad: in luck, good luck, good fortune; ktiv baʔ gad "good fortune has come". Calvin didnʔt like the idea of luck here.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ka Silpa nara iisi hari ana mone èci.<bt>Then, Silpa gave birth to another son.</bt><v n="13" />Hèia Lea padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Waa! Limuri ne, ja'a heka karej'e kèna! Mi laladhe ee, te bèli-camèd'a, dhèu bhèni aa'i-aa'i ra, peka na ja'a ne oto bia.&gt;&gt; Nèti èèna ka, na pangare ana ne, <span class="Italic">Aser</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;karej'e&gt;).<bt>Then Lea spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Waa! Now, I can be happy! Look, ee, cuz now all women will say that I am very fortunate.&gt;&gt; That is why she named the child, <span class="Italic">Aser</span> (which means &lt;happy&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔosher: good fortune, happiness baʔashri: ktiv"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔosher: good fortune, happiness baʔashri: ktiv baʔ ʔashri "my good fortune has come"<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ʔishshəruni (ʔshr piʕel): they will consider me happy banot: the other women will be happy with me, consider me happy<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ca lod'o, lèke dènge hèru puu-g'ètu are, Ruben la'e asa d'ara j'ami. Na rage ana aaj'u ca kapua dhu j'aj'i sèmi èi na'i ho hia dhèu bhèni abhu kolo. Ka Ruben nèti hia ina na Lea. Ropa Rahel nèdhi, ka na peka dènge Lea, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'a! Bagi ku ja'a ciki, èi na'i dhu Ruben nèti èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, while it was harvest month/season, Ruben went into the matto. He stumbled upon/encountered a tree/plant which was a kind of medicine to let women have children. And Ruben took it to his mother Lea. When Rahel saw it, she spoke to Lea, saying, &lt;&lt;Elder-sibling! Give2 me a little, of the medicine that Ruben got there.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qtsir: grain harvest (April to June)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">qtsir: grain harvest (April to June) chiTTiym: wheat<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>dudaʔim: mandrakes, Atropa mandragora or A.M. officinarum, a traditional aphrodisiac (but Zohary points out that Mandragora did not grow in the region where Jacob was at the time, and the Testaments of Issachar use the word for apples; otherwise Zohary identifies it as Mandragora autumnalis). In Greek they were called "love apples". The roots sometimes look like a human body, and the idea was that they could make a barren woman conceive a child. Though somewhat poisonous, causing vomiting and diarrhea and some narcosis, they were regarded as aphrodisiac and also a fertility inducer. naʔ: polite request, hedge with min "some of them"<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Te ngaa Lea b'ala, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Wee! Èu ne seli-kolane! Parame more le dhèu èmu ja'a. Te ngaa roca mèka na. Mu neo hari unu aj'u èi na'i èèna nèti ana ja'a? Me'a heka makae d'ara!&gt;&gt;<bt>But, Lea replied, saying, &lt;&lt;Wee! You are too much! You have snatched away my spouse. But that's not enough. You also want to possess the medicinal plant from my child? You no longer know shame!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa Rahel dhaa, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e, a'a! Ladhe ja'a abhu èi na'i na, mèda ne'e èu pa'èci dènge Yakob.&gt;&gt; Ka Lea d'èi kahèi.<bt>But Rahel responded, &lt;&lt;It's like this, elder-sibling! If I get that medicine, tonight you can be joined with Yakob.&gt;&gt; So Lea also agreed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hamʕaT: is it a small matter?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hamʕaT: is it a small matter? qachtekh (lqch inf): for you to take. Leah's up tight response sounds like an overreaction to Rachel's request.<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>laqachat (lqch inf): to take lakhen: if that's how it is<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>yishkav: he will have sex with you</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ka pe d'ai loo nihia sa, Yakob lèpa nèti d'ara oka. Lea la'e soru nare ne, ka na peka, &lt;&lt;A'a! Mèda ne, èu j'unu dènge ja'a! Lula ja'a dhu hèli kore le èu, dènge kab'ua èi na'i ana ja'a!&gt;&gt; Ka mèda na, Yakob j'unu dènge Lea.<bt>That (late) afternoon, Yakob returned from the field. Lea went to greet him, and she said, &lt;&lt;Older-sibling (=wife to husband)! Tonight, you will sleep with me! Because I have paid for you, wih the price of my child's medicine!&gt;&gt; So that night, Yakob slept with Lea.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sakhor sakhortikha (inf abs): I have"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">sakhor sakhortikha (inf abs): I have hired you. The report of the whole situation seems very compressed; a lot more must have been going on. Josephus: Jacob makes love to Leah to please Rachel.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ka Ama Lamatua tadèngi lii manèngi-mangaj'i Lea. Nèti èèna ka, na dènge babia, hèia nara iisi ana mone ka lèmi.<bt>And God heard Lea's prayers. Because of that, she got pregnant, and then gave birth to a fifth son.</bt><v n="18" />Hèia Lea pangare ana na, <span class="Italic">Isaskar,</span> (dhu sasoa na, &lt;b'ae j'aj'èra&gt;), lula na peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua b'ae-baj'a le j'aj'èra ja'a, lula ja'a hia le Silpa madhèdi dènge dhèu èmu ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Lea named her child <span class="Italic">Isaskar,</span> (which means &lt;pay for suffering/misery&gt;), because she said, &lt;&lt;God has paid (doublet) for my suffering/misery, because I gave Silpa to marry my spouse.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bae-baj'a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">bae-baj'a</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="skhari: wages ʔasher: because (rare usage)|i(18)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">skhari: wages ʔasher: because (rare usage)<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>ʔissachar: ktiv - kreʔ never marked in Issachar's name.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Èle èèna ka, Lea dènge babia hari, hèia nara iisi ana mone ka èna.<bt>After that, Lea became pregnant again, and she gave birth to her sixth son.</bt><v n="20" />Ka na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua parasee ja'a mèdha dhu be'a. Ka limuri ne, dhèu èmu ja'a hud'i pakab'ua ku ja'a, lula ja'a matana hia ne ana mone dhèu èna.&gt;&gt; Nèti èèna ka, na pangare ana ne, <span class="Italic">Sebulon</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;pakab'ua&gt;).<bt>And she spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;God has presented me with a good thing. So now, my spouse must appreciate me, because I have born him six sons.&gt;&gt; Because of that, she named the child, <span class="Italic">Sebulon</span> (which means &lt;appreciate&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zvadani ... zeved: he makes a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">zvadani ... zeved: he makes a gift to me, he endows me with a dowry hapaʕam: at last, this once<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>yizbəleni: he will tolerate me, exalt me, he will make me his preferred wife</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ka Lea nara iisi hari, te ngaa ana bhèni, ka na pangare na, <span class="Italic">Dina.</span><bt>And Lea gave birth again, but had a daughter, and she named her, <span class="Italic">Dina.</span> ['but' here = in contrast to previously all males, not females lower value]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dinah: like Dan? Commentary doesn't say."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">dinah: like Dan? Commentary doesn't say. Dinah doesn't get much mention, but the strange thing is that she is mentioned in this list at all. But it's probably because she does come up later, getting involved with the prince of Shekem.<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Te ngaa Ama Lamatua dhu bhèlu boe Rahel, ka sèmi lii manèngi-mangaj'i na. Nèti èèna ka, Na bhoke era ana na.<bt>But God did not forget Rahel, and heard her prayer. That is why He opened her womb (&lt;child place).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yizkor: remembered, was mindful of yiftach"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yizkor: remembered, was mindful of yiftach ʔet-rachmah: he opened her womb. Goes back to Verses 1 and 2 and Jacob's principle, that fertility comes from Yahweh.<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Hèia Rahel dènge babia, ka nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu. Ka na peka, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua saku eele le d'ara makae ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Rahel got pregnant, and gave birth to a son. And she said, &lt;&lt;God has wiped away my shame/embarrassment.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vtahar: got pregnant ʔaSaf: gather, take"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vtahar: got pregnant ʔaSaf: gather, take in, take away. Gathered up my disgrace and dumped it.<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>cherpati: my disgrace, reproach</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Hèia na pangare ana na <span class="Italic">Yusuf</span> (dhu sasoa na ele boe &lt;hud'i laa na hia tabha hari&gt;), lula aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a manèngi, sèna ka Ama Lamatua hia ja'a ana mone ca dhèu hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>And she named the child <span class="Italic">Yusuf</span> (which means something like &lt;let him increase more&gt;), because she said, &lt;&lt;I pray, that God would give me another son.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yosef (ysf qal participle, Holladay): add."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yosef (ysf qal participle, Holladay): add. May he have it in the works. Not a jussive? And not past. yosef (ysf hif imperf, Paratext): add, continue increase. God has chosen to open my womb, so may he do it again! ʔsf "take away", ysf "add", but not necessarily a pun, because they may be there for different reasons.<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>ʔacher: another</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob tenge j'ara ho pa'ae badha-manu na<bt>Yakob looks for a way to increase his</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Lod'o Rahel nara iisi Yusuf, Yakob peka dènge Laban, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;To'o! Ladhe mo'o, ja'a neo lèpa asa rai ètu-èsu ja'a.<bt>When Rahel gave birth to Yusuf, Yakob spoke with Laban, saying, &lt;&lt;MB (mother's brother)! If you agree, I want to go back to the land of my origins.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaʔsher: when, coterminous; Book of Jubilees"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">kaʔsher: when, coterminous; Book of Jubilees says all the births fit into the second 7 year period of Jacob working for Laban shalcheni: send me off<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>ʔelkhah (cohortative): I will go</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Ja'a neo laku dènge ana-dhèu èmu ja'a. To'o, èu dhu me'a le, ja'a ne sab'a tèu-tèu nèti mad'ae d'ai loo nihia. De ja'a b'ae pama'ète le rèngu se. Nèti èèna ka, rèngu se, j'aj'i le unu ja'a ka teme aae.&gt;&gt;<bt>I want to leave with my children and spouses. MB, you already know that I have worked for years from morning until late afternoon (has sense of: I've busted my but for you). And I've paid for them in full. because of that, I have full rights to them (lit. they have become my full property)&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="unu ja'a ka teme aae ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">unu ja'a ka teme aae = hak penuh</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tənah (ntn imperv): give me yəladay:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tənah (ntn imperv): give me yəladay: my children. Are they really his legal children? Several are from concubines and would not normally be recognized for inheritance, like Ishmael.<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>ʔelekhah (hlk imperf cohortative, same meaning as 25): I will go</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Hèia, aku to'o na, &lt;&lt;Ana, ee! Èu nanene ku lii ja'a laa! Madhutu lii malare dhu ja'a abhu, Lamatua hia ja'a mamèngi lula èu.<bt>Then said his MB, &lt;&lt;Child, ee! You listen to me now! According to the divination that I have gotten, the Lord has given me blessing because of you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="matsaʔti: I chanced upon, I found,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">matsaʔti: I chanced upon, I found, I found out. Laban is over a barrel. chen: favor, approval, affection, find pleasure or satisfaction. Laban is talking like an inferior to a superior.<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>nichashti (nchsh piʕel): seek and give an omen, practice divination, I learned through divination. But Wenham reads "I have grown rich." (Waldman and Finkelstein cite Akkadian nakhashu "become full or wealthy". Sarna follows the traditional "learned by divination" reading, as opposed to "learned by experience"; but the Akkadian hypothesis fits the situation better. "observing signs" is not necessarily religious.) biglalekha (gll II): on account of you<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="28" />De èu neo manèngi ca ngaa, peka, sèna ka ja'a b'ae! Sad'i èu baku tèke eele ja'a, te ngaa sab'a taruu hia ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>So whatever you want to request, just say it, so I can pay! As long as you do not leave me, but keep working for me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="malare ; patigi kèdhi le ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">malare ; patigi kèdhi le = 1) maloi, 2) similar to ramalan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="biasa na pake ho ne'a tasa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">biasa na pake ho ne'a tasa mia dènge mamuri dhèu. Mèdha sogo-tagu!</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naqvah (nqv imperv): stipulate, specify skharkha:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">naqvah (nqv imperv): stipulate, specify skharkha: your wages. For future work?<span class="Italic">(28)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ka Yakob peka, &lt;&lt;To'o! Èu mèdhi unu mu le, sasab'a-la'a ja'a. Nèti èèna ka, badha-manu to'o se, bèba-kacanga.<bt>And Yakob said, &lt;&lt;MB! You have seen for yourself, my work (doublet). Because of that, MB's animals have multiplied/increased hugely.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miqnəkha: the livestock you own"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">miqnəkha: the livestock you own</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Lod'o dhu ja'a dhae mai mèka, mèdha-panyau to'o ku ae èèna mèka. Te ngaa limuri ne, to'o kaja le. Lamatua pala-bagi le to'o ku mamèngi, lula sasab'a-la'a ja'a ka. Te d'ai le lod'o na, sèna ka ja'a sab'a hia ana-dhèu èmu ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>When I had not yet come, MB's belongings were not yet many. But now, MB is wealthy. The Lord has distributed to MB blessings, because of my work. So now the day has arrived, for me to work for my children and spouses.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məʕaT: little, small vayifrots: spread out,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">məʕaT: little, small vayifrots: spread out, break out, increase<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>larov: in abundance ləragley: to my feet, everywhere I went<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>matay: how long? when? "my own house" is mainly Rachel.<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>A master shepherd would get about 20% of the value of the flocks he managed. Jacob's offer, which does not stipulate a percentage, gives Laban an apparent advantage.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Hèia Laban karèi ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;De sèmi èèna na, ja'a b'ae èu tasamia?&gt;&gt;<bt>So then Laban asked, saying, &lt;&lt;If that is the case, how should I pay/compensate you?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yakob dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;To'o ku, hia ia ka ja'a ngaa-ngaa. Te ngaa badha-manu to'o ku, ja'a ladhe-leru taruu, sad'i mu tao ku j'ara èci.<bt>And Yakob responded, saying, &lt;&lt;MB doesn't need to give me anything. But I will continue to look after MB's animals, as long as I can do one thing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məʔuwmah: something ʔashuvah: I will go"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">məʔuwmah: something ʔashuvah: I will go back (continue)<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>ʔerʕeh: I will manage your flocks ʔeshmor: I will care for<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Ladhe mo'o, deo ne'e kahèi, ja'a laku asa badha-manu to'o sèi, ho hag'e si. Mia dhu dènge boe katèd'a aa dènge boe karata, sèra sa unu to'o ku taruu. Te ngaa mia dhu dènge katèd'a aa dhu karata, hia mi ja'a. Dènge kahib'i-kalèbho dhu mèdhi, ja'a kora aa'i si. Se'e se, hud'i laa j'aj'i mi bab'ae rui-j'aj'èra ja'a.<bt>If you agree, right now, I will go to MB's animals [remote], to select out/set apart. Those which do not have speckles and do not have splotches, they are the ones that will belong to MB continually. But those that have speckles and splotches, And the goat-sheep that are black, I will take them all. These will be the payment for my suffering/efforts.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeʕevor (ʕvr): I will pass from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔeʕevor (ʕvr): I will pass from one side to the other haSer (swr hif inf): to remove, clear away, cull<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>seh: young sheep, young goat naqod: speckled, spotted; anything but solid color<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>Taluʔ: spotted; anything but solid color chum: an undefined color between white and black; anything but white sheep<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>bakhsavim: among the young rams</Message></Annotation><note reference="30:32" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Uru èèna, dhèu pangee kahib'i-kalèbho dhu pudhi, dhu be'a. Rèngu sèra ae. Aa kahib'i-kalèbho dhu mèdhi, karehe. Te ngaa rèngu se, ciki di. Kahib'i-ka'ia dènge kalèbho dhu katèd'a aa dhu karata sèra, ciki oo'e di.<bt>Long ago, people thought that white goat-sheep, were the good ones. And there were many of them. And black sheep, were not good. But there were not very many of them. Goats and sheep that were speckled, and those that had splotches, were only a few.</bt></note><v n="33" />D'ai lod'o limuri, pe to'o me'a ja'a ne sab'a dènge mola, do aad'o. Sad'i lake more, mai ho mu parisa badha-manu ja'a. Ladhe mu abhu kahib'i-ka'ia dhu dènge boe katèd'a, aa dhu karata boe, do, kahib'i-kalèbho dhu pudhi, èèna na, dhu me'a le èèna, ja'a mana'u badha-manu to'o.&gt;&gt;<bt>Later on, MB can know if I am working honestly, or not. Whenever you have a chance (idiomatic), come so you can inspect my animals. If you find goats that have no speckles, or no splotches, or sheep that are white, then you will know that I have stolen MB's animals.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katèd'a = 1) speckled, 2) celup"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">katèd'a = 1) speckled, 2) celup ujung jari di dalam ; karata = splotched, (spotted &amp; camoflauge &amp; patterned); 33: Sad'i lake more, = kapan ada kesempatan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʕantah-bi tsidqati: you will be in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vʕantah-bi tsidqati: you will be in a position to testify to my blameless behavior machar: tomorrow, in the future; sounds almost poetic here<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>ʕal-shkhari lpanekha: to look at my wages, inspect my flocks that I got from you ganuv: stolen<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>ʔiti: with me (implying that it has also been stolen)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="Hk-lb\Hk00009c.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ka Laban d'èi kahèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Oo! J'ara na sèmi èèna ka.&gt;&gt;<bt>So then Laban agreed, saying, &lt;&lt;Good! Let's do that.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lu: O that ...!"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">lu: O that ...!</Message></Annotation><v n="35" />Te ngaa ètu d'ara lod'o èèna kahèi, Laban hag'e dènge badha dhu katèd'a, dhu karata, dènge kahib'i-kalèbho dhu mèdhi. Ka na pangèd'u mi ana na si, ho ladhe-leru.<bt>But, that same day, Laban separated out the animals that were speckled or splotched, and the sheep that were black. And he turned them over to his children, to look after them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yasar (swr): he removed, diverted. Did"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yasar (swr): he removed, diverted. Did he do this to help Jacob (as UBS suggests; doing what Jacob wanted (verse 33), but hurrying up the process by putting his whole crew on it), or to cheat him? The nonwhite sheep are actually Jacob's property, but Laban reasons that they wonʔt breed as fast if they are segregated from the main flock. exchange w/consultant: [MC] I vote "to cheat". ; [JEG] I vote "to cheat" in spite of Verse 33. Laban was trying to get all the breeding stock out of Jacob's reach. Recessive genes werenʔt discovered until Mendel. But the verse doesn't actually commit itself one way or the other.<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>tyashiym (masc): male goats ʕəqudiym (masc): striped? with twisted tails?<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>Təluʔim (masc): spotted nəquddot (fem): speckled nannies<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>Təluʔot (fem): spotted</Message></Annotation><v n="36" />Hèia eo rèti ka badha se asa era èci dhu kaj'èu na tèlu lod'o kako haga nèti era Yakob si. Ka Yakob madhenge ka badha dhu ata se.<bt>Then they herded away the animals to a place three days' distance for Yakob mob's place. And Yakob watched the remaining animals.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ata = sisa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">ata = sisa</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hanotarot (ytr nif): the remaining sheep"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hanotarot (ytr nif): the remaining sheep</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Èla èèna ka, Yakob poro nare dadana aaj'u nèti aj'u tèlu rupa. Ka na caci pakarata ka'uri aj'u sèra, tao strep-strep.<bt>After that, Yakob cut tree branches from three kinds of trees. And he shaved lengthwise their bark, making stripes (loan).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maqqal: rod (singular, but collective), plural"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">maqqal: rod (singular, but collective), plural at end of verse. livneh: styrax officinalis, storax, like a white poplar, a small tree 9 to 18 feet tall<span class="Italic">(37) (37) </span>lach: a rod that is still moist with sap luz: almond tree<span class="Italic">(37) (37) </span>ʕermon: plane tree, Platanus orientalis, large leaves, grows near water, good shade. The bark peels off in sheets vayfatstsel (piʕel): peel a strip, strip off somethng from them<span class="Italic">(37) (37) </span>pətslot: strips of bark lavan: white. May be a pun on Laban's name. Jacob tries imitative magic, but God gives good breeding anyway.<span class="Italic">(37) (37) </span>machsof (chsf partcpl): peeling the bark, laying bare the wood maqlot: sticks, shoots<span class="Italic">(37)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="38" />Hèia aj'u dhu strep-strep se, na tèke asa d'ara karab'a kahib'i. Badha se dhu tema le pa'ango aa paleo ètu era èèna.<bt>Then wood which was striped, he place inside the trough. The animals often/normally mated (doublet) at that place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yatstsog (hif pf): he set them,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yatstsog (hif pf): he set them, placed them pitstsel (piʕel): he had peeled<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>barahaTim: at the watering troughs, the water receptacles (generic against shoqet, specific kind) shiqətot (shoqet): watering troughs for cattle<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>tavoʔna: where they came (fem) lnokhach: directly in front<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>yechmanah: they were in heat bvoʔan (bwʔ inf): as they (fem) came to drink<span class="Italic">(38)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="39" />De ladhe badha se paleo ètu madha aj'u strep-strep se, ra matana ana dhu rèu ra katèd'a dènge karata.<bt>So when the animals mated in front of the striped wood/trees/poles/branches, they bore offspring whose fur was speckled or splotched.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhadhe = cincang ; caci ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">dhadhe = cincang ; caci = shave, kupas ; caci pakarata = peeled lengthwise; 38: karab'a = palungan, trough ; pa'ango aa paleo = bapacar dan kawin; kahore</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕaqudim: with twisted tail"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕaqudim: with twisted tail</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Ka ladhe badha Laban se neo paleo, Yakob patangare si asa kahib'i dhu katèd'a dènge karata sèra. Hèia ana dhu ra matana sa rèu ra katèd'a dènge karata kahèi. Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna ka, badha na asa ae. Ka na pacèri eele si nèti badha Laban sèra.<bt>And when Laban's animals were about to mate, Yakob made them face the goats which were speckled and splotched. Then the offspring that they bore had fur that was also speckled and splotched. In that way, his animals increased. And he separated them from Laban's animals.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kəshaviym (masc): lambs hifrid (prd hif):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">kəshaviym (masc): lambs hifrid (prd hif): he separated them out<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>ʕaqod: twisted tail, streaked chuwm: dark colored sheep<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>vayashet-lo (shyt): put, set, lay, order, appoint. White sheep facing black goats? ʕadarim: flocks of an individual<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>lbado: be alone</Message></Annotation><v n="41" />Ropa badha dhu èra neo paleo, Yakob nare kadhèli aj'u dhu strep-strep sèra, tao mi d'ara karab'a ètu madha si.<bt>When animals that were strong/healthy were about to mate, Yakob arranged the striped wood, placing in their trough facing them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bkol-yachem (ychm piʕel inf): every time"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bkol-yachem (ychm piʕel inf): every time they were in heat hamqushsharot (qshr puʕal partcpl): the sturdy ones<span class="Italic">(41) (41) </span>among the rods, by the rods</Message></Annotation><v n="42" />Te ngaa ladhe kahib'i dhu roe dènge malaka-god'a neo paleo, Yakob soro tèke si. Ka badha dhu roe, sèra unu to'o na Laban. Aa mia dhu èra, sèra unu nèngu.<bt>But when goats that were weak and scrawny were about to mate, Yakob took them away. And the weak animals, were Laban's property. And those that were strong, were his property.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haʕaTif (ʕtf hif): the weak ones"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">haʕaTif (ʕtf hif): the weak ones</Message></Annotation><v n="43" />Dènge j'ara ne'e ne, Yakob j'aj'i dhèu kaja-su'i. Ka kahib'i-ka'ia na, kahib'i-kalèbho na, onta na, keled'ei na, dènge ènu na bhèni-mone, udhu sobhu-sobhu.<bt>In this way, Yakob became an extremely wealthy person. And his goats, his sheep, his camels, his donkeys, and his male-female slaves, piled up high.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yifrots: busting at the seams shfachot:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yifrots: busting at the seams shfachot: female slaves<span class="Italic">(43) (43) </span>ʕvadim: workers</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob rai tèke eele Laban<bt>Yakob runs away from Laban</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="31" />
      <v n="1" />Ca tèka, Yakob tadèngi lii padhai ana-ana Laban se, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Kakaja-sasu'i Yakob sèra, lula na kao nare aa'i mèdha-panyau ama èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, Yakob heard Laban's children talking, saying, &lt;&lt;Yakob's wealth (doublet) is because he has scratched away all the belongings of our-inc father.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kavod: weight, property"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">kavod: weight, property</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Yakob nèdhi kahèi rèhu to'o Laban mare heka, aa be'a heka dènge ne, sèmi uru èèna.<bt>Yakob also saw the face of MB Laban was no longer pleasant/smiling to him, and no longer good toward him, as before.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kao nare = garu ame ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">kao nare = garu ame = bhabhe nare; 2: mare = smile</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pəney lavan: Laban's face, Laban's attitude"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">pəney lavan: Laban's face, Laban's attitude ʔeynennu: nothing to him; things with Laban were not like before; change in the relationship, gone sour.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>kitmol shilshom: like yesterday and the day before; formerly</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Hèia LAMATUA peka dènge Yakob, &lt;&lt;D'ai le lod'o, ho èu lèpa asa ina dènge ama mu. Ja'a palere-lere dènge èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the LORD spoke to Yakob, &lt;&lt;The day has arrived, for you to return home to your mother and father. I will lead=accompany you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="moladtekha: your country of origin"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">moladtekha: your country of origin</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00692c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Yakob padhai lii dènge dhèu èmu na dua ra<bt>Yakob speaks with his two wives</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ka Yakob hia dhèu lasi paroa Rahel dènge Lea, sèna ka mai paraga dènge ne ètu era ani badha, ètu d'ara mamoo.<bt>And Yakob had people go summon Rahel and Lea, to come meet with him at the place of the animals, in the plain/open field/valley.</bt><v n="5" />Hèia na peka dènge ra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Limuri ne, ja'a ladhe-ladhe na, ama miu na rèhu na mare heka dènge ja'a. Aa babe'a na mi ja'a, sèmi heka uru èèna. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua dhu ama ku sogo-tagu èèna, palere-lere dènge ja'a.<bt>Then he spoke with them, saying, &lt;&lt;Now, I have been seeing that your father's face is not longer smile toward me. And his goodness/favour toward me, is not like before. But God whom my father traditionally-worships, is with me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roʔeh (rʔh partcpl): I see, notice,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">roʔeh (rʔh partcpl): I see, notice, am seeing tmol: yesterday. Same as in Verse 2.<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>shishom: 3 days ago, day before yesterday</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Miu dua mi se me'a le, nèbhu nare sange ne'e, ja'a j'aj'i kuli ètu ama miu!<bt>The two of you already know how for so long I have been a kuli (=slave labour) for your father!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔatenah (2pl fem): you all (not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔatenah (2pl fem): you all (not dual) bkol kochi (koach): in all my strength, to the best of my ability<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Te ngaa sèmi èèna, d'ara na la'e kahèi, ka na kapod'e-kabèli taruu ja'a. Ka na ub'a rui-j'aj'èra ja'a, canguru hari kèna. Masi ka sèmi èèna, Ama Lamatua j'aga pa'èra ja'a.<bt>But even with that, his insides have gone, and he keeps deceiving me. So he has changed my wages (Idiom: bones-suffering/effort), ten times. Even that being the case, God has firmly guarded me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hetel (tll hif): cheat, deceive hechlif"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hetel (tll hif): cheat, deceive hechlif (chlf hif one thing follow another): replace one thing with another, changes wages<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>maskurti (maskhoret): wages ʕaseret: ten<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>monim: times ntano: allowed him (ntn)<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>lharaʕ (rʕʕ ʕim hif): harm someone</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Lod'o ama miu peka na, &lt;Badha dhu rèu ra katèd'a sèra j'aj'i mi unu èu,&gt; ho ladhe lod'o badha se matana, ana dhu katèd'a hua-hua. Lod'o leo hari, na peka, &lt;Badha dhu karata sèra, j'aj'i mi unu èu,&gt; ka badha se matana ana karata aa'i-aa'i.<bt>When your father said, &lt;The animals with speckled fur will be your property,&gt; then when the animals bore young, all their offspring were speckled. Another time, he said, &lt;The animals which are splotched will be your property,&gt; then the animals bore all their offspring being splotched.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔim-koh: whenever nqudim (nqd): spotted, speckled|i(8)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔim-koh: whenever nqudim (nqd): spotted, speckled<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>ʕəqudim: with twisted tails</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ama Lamatua ad'u sèmi èèna na, sèna ka nare aa'i badha-manu ama miu èèna, ho hia mi ja'a.<bt>God did that, so that he could take all your father's animals to give them to me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayatstsel (ntsl hif): snatch away, take"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayatstsel (ntsl hif): snatch away, take away</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ca tèka, ropa badha se paleo, ja'a kèdhi ètu d'ara nii, dhu peka na, badha mone aa'i-aa'i dhu paleo, abhu dhu katèd'a aa dhu karata hèi.<bt>One time, when the animals were mating, I saw in a dream, that, all the male animals which were mating, were also speckled and spotted.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕet: time yachem (piʕel inf): in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕet: time yachem (piʕel inf): in heat<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>ʕessaʔ (nsʔ): lift up (eyes), look ʕatudim: male goats, rams<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>haʕolim (ʕlh): that were breeding brudim: speckled, dappled<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Ka ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga paroa ja'a, peka na, &lt;Yakob!&gt;<bt>Then the Lord's *angel (servant/underling from heaven) called me, saying, &lt;Yakob!&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia ja'a dhaa, &lt;Tasamia, Lamatua?&gt;<bt>So I responded, &lt;What is it, Lord?&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Regular interchange forms."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Regular interchange forms.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ka na lii, &lt;Ladhe ku laa! Badha mone dhu paleo sèra, dhodhoka dhu karata dènge katèd'a di. Ja'a ka ad'u sèra sa, lula Ja'a dhu kèdhi le, ngaa dhu Laban tao mi dedha èu.<bt>And he explained, &lt;Have a look! The male animals that are mating, are only speckled and spotted one. I have arranged that, because I have seen what Laban has been doing to you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Could refer to dreams, though Sarna"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Could refer to dreams, though Sarna thinks not. saʔ (nsʔ imperv): lift up, look<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>rəʔeh (imperv): see</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Ja'a ne, Ama Lamatua, dhu pad'elo iisi mi èu ètu Betel èèna. Ètu era nèi, èu patitu hadhu, ka mu bhori èi mènyi ètu dedha na, ka èu sogo-tagu Ja'a. Ka èu pa'èki lii pajaji dènge Ja'a ètu nèi. De kèd'i ka, tèke eele ka rai ne'e ne, lamu ka asa kabarai ina-ama èu.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>I here am God, who revealed myself to you at Betel. In that [remote] place, you erected a stone, and you poured oil on it, and you traditionally-worshipped Me. And you bound a promise with Me there. So get up and leave this land here, go to the coutnry of your mother-father.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mashachta: you poured oil on the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mashachta: you poured oil on the surface of something matstsevah: standing-stone, usually an unhewn, upright stone for cult, burial-marking, or memorial purposes. Forbidden from Deuteronomy on, but used earlier by Jacob and Moses; also of stones erected to Baal and Egyptian obelisks.<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>nadarta li sham neder (ndr): vowed to me there to do a special deed moladtekha: your relations, descent<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Hèia Rahel dènge Lea b'ala lii na, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;La'a ma! Ji'i dènge heka pusaka ngaa-ngaa nèti ama ji'i Laban.<bt>Then Rahel and Lea replied, saying, &lt;&lt;Let's go! We-exc no longer have any inheritance from our father Laban.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haʕod: no more, nothing else. Would"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">haʕod: no more, nothing else. Would this be because the property would go to Laban's sons? Or because he was managing it poorly? cheleq: share of property<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>nachəlah: inalienable hereditary possession</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Nèbhu nare sange ne'e, mone heka ne tao ji'i sèmi dhèu leo kara sa. Na pahie eele le ji'i se. Ka na'e aa'i le kab'ua-kadheli ji'i se.<bt>For a long time now, the old man has been treating us like foreigners. He has sold us off. And he has eaten/consumed all our bridewealth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haloʔ: doesn't he ... arenʔt we"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">haloʔ: doesn't he ... arenʔt we ... nakhriyyot (nakhri): foreigners, aliens. That's sort of what Jacob was, and it sounds like Laban was treating them that way.<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>nechshavnu lo (chshv nif): we are considered by him as mkharanu: he sells us. This term was used for bride price (dowry) at that time, but the women hadnʔt benefitted from it.<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>yoʔkhal gam-ʔakhol: and he has moreover eaten up kaspenu: the money he paid for us? our money?<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />De mèdha-panyau dhu Ama Lamatua nare sèra nèti ama ji'i Laban, aa'i-aa'i sèra j'aj'i le unu èdhi dènge ana-ana èdhi se. De ladhe aku Lamatua tasa mera mia, te'a dhoka madhutu di!&gt;&gt;<bt>So, the possession which God has taken from our father Laban, all of them have become the property of us-inc and our children. So, whatever the Lord has said, we should just follow that!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu leo kara = orang asing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">dhèu leo kara = orang asing ; kabua-kadhèli = belis (lit. harga-sepotong-sepotong)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕosher: riches hitstsil (ntsl hif): rescue,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕosher: riches hitstsil (ntsl hif): rescue, pull out<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17-18" />Èle èèna ka, Yakob lalau mèdha-panyau na. Hèia na paca'e ana-dhèu èmu na asa dedha onta lasi, aa na eo nèti badha-manu na aa'i-aa'i, dènge mèdha-panyau dhu na abhu ètu Padan Aram, ho lasi asa rai Kana'an.<bt>After that, Yakob arranged his belongings (=packed up). Then he loaded his children and spouses onto camels, and he herded all his animals, and belongings which he had obtained in Padan Aram, to go to the land of Kana'an.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yissaʔ: put them up yinhag: drive,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yissaʔ: put them up yinhag: drive, lead<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>rəkhusho: he had gathered qinyano: his possession<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Lod'o èèna, Laban dhu la'e g'ute rèu kahib'i-kalèbho na. Ka Rahel mana'u nare patung mèdha sogo-tagu ama na.<bt>At that time, Laban had gone to shear the fur of his goat-sheep. And Rahel stole statues (loan) which were objects of traditional-worship of her father.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ligzoz: to shear sheep tignov: she"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ligzoz: to shear sheep tignov: she stole<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>tərafim: idols, figurines or household gods, maybe like Kwanyin or Buddha statues. Probably made of baked clay, very likely images of Ashtarot, the goddess of sex and childbearing. Rachel may have taken them because she wanted to have another baby</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Aa Yakob si lasi palangu boe lii dènge to'o na.<bt>And Yakob mob left without leave-taking from his MB.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayignov et-lev laban: he stole Laban's"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayignov et-lev laban: he stole Laban's heart = he deceived Laban ʕal-bli: because, without<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>higid lo (ngd hif): (without) informing him boreach (partcpl): fleeing<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Na bau nèti aa'i mèdha-panyau na, ka ra kako pamèri-mèri, lasi re loko Efrat, asa ledhe Gilead.<bt>He took away all his belongings, and they left quickly, going by way of the Efrat river, toward the mountain(s) of Gilead.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mau-mau = 1) quietly, 2) slowly"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">mau-mau = 1) quietly, 2) slowly</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayasem et-panaw har hagilʕad (sim): set"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayasem et-panaw har hagilʕad (sim): set his face to the mountains of Gilead; headed for the high country in Gilead. The desert country was fairly level and high to the east of the Jordan Riva, but near the Jordan it went up even higher, with a sharp dropoff and small canyons cutting through it down to the Jordan River about 4,000 feet below. The rest of the chapter takes place not far from Jabbok Stream, which goes from the plateau down to the Jordan and has a wide enough valley that people can follow it between the plateau and the river.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Laban la'e bate Yakob<bt>Laban chases after Yakob</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Rarai Yakob si èèna d'ai tèlu lod'o ku, heka Laban ne'a kèna.<bt>The fleeing of Yakob mob had gone for three days, before Laban found out.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yuggad (ngd hofʕal): he was informed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yuggad (ngd hofʕal): he was informed</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Hèia Laban oru nare ka dhèu-dhèu na, lasi bate Yakob si. D'ai pidhu lod'o ku, heka ra paraga dènge si ètu ledhe Gilead.<bt>Then Laban collected his people, and chased after Yakob mob. On the seventh day, they met them at the mountain(s) of Gilead.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="la'e bate = kejar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">la'e bate = kejar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yirdof: he pursued vayadəbeq ʔoto (dbq"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yirdof: he pursued vayadəbeq ʔoto (dbq hif): they caught up to him (after sticking with his trail)<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ka d'ara mèda èèna, Lamatua pad'elo iisi Na mi Laban ètu d'ara nii. Na peka na, &lt;&lt;Laban! Ladhe èu padhai lii dènge Yakob, j'aga paie hèb'a èu na.&gt;&gt;<bt>And during that night, the Lord revealed Himself to Laban in a dream. He said, &lt;&lt;Laban! If you say anything to Yakob, guard your mouth carefully.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishshamer (nif imperv): take heed to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hishshamer (nif imperv): take heed to yourself</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Mèda èèna, Yakob si dhu patitu paleo ètu ledhe Gilead. Aa Laban si patitu unu ra kaj'èu boe nèti era èèna kahèi.<bt>That night, Yakob mob had erected their tents in/at/on the Gilead mountain(s). Then Laban mob also erected theirs not far from there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yashsheg (nshg hif): he overtook taqaʕ:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yashsheg (nshg hif): he overtook taqaʕ: strike, thrust; set up tents<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Èle ka, Laban mai paraga dènge Yakob. Hèia na lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka, èu rai mèti ana bhèni ja'a se, dènge boe lii ugu-ge'e sa hèi? Mu tao si sèmi dhèu dhu èu segi ètu d'ara papara-pakèj'i.<bt>After that, Laban came and met with Yakob. Then he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Why have you run away taking my daughters, without taking leave? You are treating them like people whom you have conquered in a war.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yoʔmer: he said (but in v."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yoʔmer: he said (but in v. 26 they are in separate camps) tignov: you stole my heart = you deceived me, as in v. 20. "bulai" involves an untruth, but not a deceptive action.<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>vatnaheg (piʕel): carry off, lead away, drive off shvuyot (shvh pt): ones who have by made captive<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>charev: sword</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Èu ne ad'a aad'o, palangu boe sa hèi dènge ja'a! Ladhe èu peka dènge ja'a be'a-be'a, ele boe ja'a tao sisi-kau, ho ta'a-tinu boko-boko, ho lere miu dènge lii sod'a,<bt>You have no adat (=uncivilised), not even taking your leave from me! If you had spoken to me nicley, I would probably have made a festival, and we would have eat-drink festively, to escort you with singing,</bt><note reference="31:27" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Ibrani peka na, &lt;sod'a pake dènge dere iiki aa dènge alat musiik dhu pake dhari sanár&gt;.<bt>According to the Ibrani language, it says &lt;sing with small drums and musical instruments that use strumming strings&gt;.</bt></note>heka ji'i patabuli miu kèna.<bt>and then we-exc would have released you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nachəbeʔta (chbʔ nif): you hid yourself"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nachəbeʔta (chbʔ nif): you hid yourself livroach (inf): to flee<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>tignov: you stole ʔəshallechəkha (piʕel): I would have let you go<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>simchah: joy shiriym: songs<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>bətof: tambourine kinnor: harp, guitar?<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Sasala èu èci hari ka, èu hia boe ja'a uu ana-èpu ja'a hèi. Tatao èu ne goa titu kèna!<bt>You have another wrong, in that you did not give me a chance to kiss my chldren-grandchildren either. This deed of yours is incredibly stupid!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nəTashtani (nTsh): you didnʔt leave me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nəTashtani (nTsh): you didnʔt leave me lənashsheq (piʕel inf): to kiss<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>hiSkalta (skl hif): you behaved foolishly ʕəso (ʕsh inf): its doing<span class="Italic">(28)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Carui boe, ladhe ja'a ne neo paj'èra èu! Te ngaa malo-malo ka mèda-mèda na, Ama Lamatua dhu ama mu sogo-tagu èèna, kai ja'a peka na, ladhe ja'a padhai lii dènge èu, ja'a hud'i j'aga paie-iie ku hèb'a ja'a.<bt>It would have been easy for me to want to cause you suffering/difficulty! But fortunately last night, the God whom your father traditionally-worships, forbade me saying that if I spoke to you, I must guard carefully my mouth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləʔel: in the power of my"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ləʔel: in the power of my hand ʔemesh: last night<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>hishshamer (shmr nif imperv): take care!</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Mema, ja'a dhu ke'a le, èu pakèd'i lula èu dhu neo le lèpa. Te ngaa tasamia ka, èu mana'u mèti patung mèdha sogo-tagu ja'a?&gt;&gt;<bt>I really understand that you are leaving, because you are wanting to go home. But why did you steal my traditional-worship statues?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii ugu-ge'e = pamit; 27: tao"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">lii ugu-ge'e = pamit; 27: tao sisi-kau = bekin pesta</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="halokh (inf abs): go on, walk"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">halokh (inf abs): go on, walk nikhSof nikhsaftah (ksf nif): you are deeply longing for<span class="Italic">(30)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00689c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Laban dènge Yakob<bt>Laban and Yakob</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Hèia Yakob b'ala, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;To'o baku nasa ku dènge ja'a! Ja'a pakèd'i mau-mau èèna, lula ja'a mage dhoka mo'o boe ja'a kèti ana-ana se!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob replied, saying, &lt;&lt;MB should not be angry with me! I left quietly, because I did not want you to not want me to take these children!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pen-tigzol: lest you take away by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">pen-tigzol: lest you take away by force</Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Te ngaa Yakob dhu ne'a nare boe, na dhèu èmu na Rahel ka dhu mana'u nèti. Ka na lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;To'o! Mèdha sogo-tagu èèna, mu tenge ne! Ladhe mèdhi ètu cee, huku pamadhe ne. Parisa aa'i mèu-mèu. Ladhe abhu kahèi pusaka to'o dhu leo, more aa'i si. Hud'i laa, dhèu se'e se j'aj'i sakasii.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yakob did not know that his spouse Rahel was the one who had stolen. And he advised, saying, &lt;&lt;MB! Those objects of traditional-worship, you just look for it! Whoever you (find them) at, punish them to death. Inspect everything carefully. If you also find any of MB's other possessions, take them all. Let these people here be witnesses.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="in front of haker-ləkha (nkhr hif):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">in front of haker-ləkha (nkhr hif): investigate, recognize; look it over as if you had never seen it before and recognize<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Hèia Laban la'e parisa ka asa d'ara paleo se èci-èci. Na la'e uru asa d'ara paleo Yakob. Èle ka, la'e asa d'ara paleo Lea. Èle ka, la'e asa d'ara paleo ènu se dua ra. Te ngaa abhu boe ngaa-ngaa. Paleo Rahel limuri tèka.<bt>Then Laban went to inspect inside eahc of their tents. He went first into the tent of Yakob. After that, he went into the tent of Lea. After tha, he went into the tent of the two slaves. But he did not find anything. The tent of Rahel was last.</bt><v n="34" />Te ngaa Rahel dhu huni le mèdha sogo-tagu sèra ètu d'ara lalaka onta. Ka na madhèdi ètu dedha. D'ai d'ara paleo ne, Laban tenge paie-iie, te ngaa na rage boe.<bt>But Rahel had hiddne the objects of traditional-worship inside the pillow/headrest of the camel. And she sat on top. Arriving inside her tent, Laban searched carefully, but didn't stumble upon it/them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lalaka = alas kapala (pillow, bantal),"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">lalaka = alas kapala (pillow, bantal), alas pantat (saddle, sadel)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kar: saddle yəmashshesh: feel, grope; he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">kar: saddle yəmashshesh: feel, grope; he rummaged through, opening everything up and looking inside<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Hèia Rahel peka dènge ama na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama mage mu nasa kahèi. Te ja'a bisa boe titu, lula ja'a abhu hèru.&gt;&gt; Masi ka sèmi èèna, Laban tenge taruu, te ngaa abhu boe mèdha sogo-tagu sèra.<bt>And Rahel spoke with her father, saying, &lt;&lt;Father should not be angry. Cuz I cannot stand, because I have month/menstruation.&gt;&gt; Nevertheless, Laban kept searching, but did not find those objects of traditional-worship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔal-yichar (chrh): donʔt get angry derek"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔal-yichar (chrh): donʔt get angry derek nashim: the way of women; menstrual period<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>ychafes: he looked for it thoroughly</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Ka Yakob nasa, hèia na pajèka dènge Laban, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne tao bhelu ngaa mi to'o? Ka to'o mai bate ja'a, sèmi dhu ja'a ne, dhèu bhelu-katub'a sa!<bt>So Yakob was angry, and he spoke harshly with Laban, saying, &lt;&lt;What evil have I done to MB? So MB chases me, as if I am an evil person/criminal!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yichar (chrh): became angry vayarev (riv):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yichar (chrh): became angry vayarev (riv): start a quarrel in public, attack verbally<span class="Italic">(36) (36) </span>mah-pishʕi: what is my rebellion against community solidarity? dalaqta: hotly pursue<span class="Italic">(36)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="37" />Mèdha-panyau ja'a, to'o ceb'e eele si. De mu abhu ngaa? More ka mai tèke mi madha ne, sèna ka aa'i-aa'i ti tèdhi. Aa hud'i laa, dhèu se'e ka dhu pama'ète mèdha èèna unu cee.<bt>My belongings, MB has thoroughly scrounged-searched all. So what did you find? Take them and place them here in front of us for all of us to see! Let these people be the ones who decide who owns those things.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishshashta (piʕel): feel, grope yowkhiychu (ykch):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mishshashta (piʕel): feel, grope yowkhiychu (ykch): let them decide<span class="Italic">(37)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="38" />Dua nguru tèu kèna, ja'a sab'a kuli mi to'o. Lod'o ja'a madhenga badha-manu to'o, ci'u sa legu boe. Aa ku'a kèdhi boe ci'u sa hèi!<bt>For 20 years now, I have worked like a kuli for MB. When I was watching MB's animals, not one miscarried. And I did not eat one either!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rcheleykha: your ewes (sheep) vʕizeykha: and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">rcheleykha: your ewes (sheep) vʕizeykha: and nanny goats<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>loʔ shikelu (piʕel): they never had a miscarriage ʔeyley (ʔayil): rams<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>ʔakhalti: I did not eat. SK "He's mad!"</Message></Annotation><v n="39" />Ladhe badha hui-hahi hui, kadhi pamadhe badha to'o ci'u, ja'a peka boe, te ngaa ja'a gati. Aa ladhe dhèu mana'u, to'o pua ja'a gati, masi ka ja'a sala boe.<bt>When the wild animals (doublet) killed and ate one of MB's animals, I did not report it, but I replaced it. And if someone stole, MB ordered me to replace it, even though I had done no wrong.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tərefah: carcass torn by wild animals"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tərefah: carcass torn by wild animals heveʔtiy (hif): I did not bring<span class="Italic">(39) (39) </span>ʔachaTTenah (chTʔ piʕel): I made amends for it, I compensated for it tbaqshenah: you looked for [compensation], asked for<span class="Italic">(39) (39) </span>gənuvti (pass partcpl): I had it stolen</Message></Annotation><v n="40" />Ladhe re mèu, madha lod'o ai pamango ja'a. Aa ladhe mèda, ja'a maringi rig'i-rig'i. Ja'a pasaruru boe ciki sa, toke mèu rai, lula madhenge badha-manu to'o.<bt>When it was daytime, the sun roasted me. And when it was nighttime, I shivered from cold. I did not close my eyes even a little, until daylight, because I was guarding MB's animals.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔəchalaniy: it devoured me, ate me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔəchalaniy: it devoured me, ate me choreb: dryness, heat<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>qerach: frost tidad (ndd imperf fem): it fled, it wandered<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>shənatiy: my sleep</Message></Annotation><v n="41" />Mema tare'a, dua nguru tèu èèna! Ja'a sab'a canguru èpa tèu, sèna ka abhu ana bhèni to'o, dhèu dua se. Ka ja'a sab'a hari èna tèu, sèna ka ja'a unu badha-manu se'e. J'aj'i kuli nèbhu nare sange èèna, te ngaa to'o pakura rui-j'aj'èra ja'a d'ai canguru hari.<bt>It's really true, for 20 years! I worked 14 years so that I could get MB's two daughters. And I worked another six years, so that I could own these animals. I have kuli-worked so long now, but MB has reduced/cut my wages (doublet) ten times.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bishtey: for your two daughters tachəlef"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bishtey: for your two daughters tachəlef (hif): you changed, replaced. Laban was breaking Hammurabi's Code right and left, and also later Jewish code, by not paying up promptly and fairly. SK "He telling um eryting dat go wrong now."<span class="Italic">(41) (41) </span>maskurtiy: my wages ʕeseret monim: ten times = over and over<span class="Italic">(41)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="42" />Malo-malo ka, dènge Ama Lamatua, dhu baki ku Abraham, dènge ama ku Isak, dhu sogo-tagu Ne. Ladhe Na leru boe ja'a ne, ele boe to'o hia ja'a lèpa dènge ai hua da'u-da'u. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua dhu pa'abhe boe musi madha Na mi j'aj'èra ja'a, aa Na tao madha-dhilu mi sasab'a-la'a ja'a aa'i-aa'i. Nèti èèna ka, mèda deo na, Na mai kai to'o, sèna ka baku lii sakaa dènge ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Fortunately, there was God, whom my grandfather Abraham, and my father Isak, traditionally-worshipped. If He had not been leading me, MB would probably be sending me home empty-handed. But God has not blocked His eyes from my difficulties, and He has paid attention to (Idiom: eye-ear) all my work. Because of that, last night, He came to forbid MB, to not speak roughly with me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="legu = meskram; 39: badha hui-hahi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">legu = meskram; 39: badha hui-hahi hui = doublet covering all wild animals; 40: j'angi = menetes, membasahi ; maringi rig'i-rig'i = dingin talalu sampe gamatar ; pasoro = baring-baring istirahat (lit. kasi miring) ; pasaruru boe = mata sonde tatutup sadiki ju, &gt; tidak istirahat (malam); 41: pakura = kurangi, potong; 42: ai hua da'u-da'u = tangan kosong total ; da'u = ra'u</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="luley: if he had not ..."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">luley: if he had not ... [contrary to fact], you would have ... pachad: trembling, terror; the God who makes Isaac feel terrified<span class="Italic">(42) (42) </span>reyqam: empty-handed ʕanyi: me overwhelmed by want, poor, wretched, in a situation of affliction<span class="Italic">(42) (42) </span>ygiyaʕ (ygʕ): exertion, gone to a lot of trouble, hard work kafay (kaf): my hollow, outspread hand, palm<span class="Italic">(42) (42) </span>yokhach (ykch hif): he gave judgment ʔamesh: yesterday evening<span class="Italic">(42)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob dènge Laban pa'èki lii pajaji<bt>Yakob and Laban bind a promise</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />Ropa nanene nare lii padhai Yakob, ka Laban dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Bhèni dua se, ana ja'a. Ana dhu ra matana se, aa'i-aa'i ra èpu ja'a. Badha-manu aa'i-aa'i se, unu ja'a. Aa'i-aa'i dhu èu ladhe mèdhi ètu se'e se, unu ja'a. Te ngaa ja'a neo tao si, tasamia? Ja'a bisa boe magee si.<bt>When he had heard what Yakob was saying, Laban responded, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this! These two women are my children. The children that they have born, are all my grandchildren. All these animals, are mine. Everything that you see here, is mine. But I what am I going to do with them? I can't obstruct them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roʔeh (partcpl): everything you are looking"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">roʔeh (partcpl): everything you are looking at ʔo: particle of choice. SK "I thought he wen give um."<span class="Italic">(43)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="44" />De be'a risi, èdhi dua ti pa'èki lii pajaji. Sèna ka lii pajaji èèna ka dhu èki èdhi dua ti.&gt;&gt;<bt>It would be best if the two of us-inc bind a promise. So that the promise is what binds the two of us.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləkhah (hlk imperv): go nikrətah (krt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ləkhah (hlk imperv): go nikrətah (krt cohortative): let's cut a deal<span class="Italic">(44) (44) </span>ʕed: witness. The contents of the deal were not on paper, but they would be in the minds of everyone; common in preliterate societies like this one.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Hèia Yakob nare ka hadhu aae cue, na patitu ètu èèna, sèna ka j'aj'i mi tadha.<bt>Then Yakob took a large stone, and erected it there, as a sign.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yrimeah (rwm hif): caused it to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yrimeah (rwm hif): caused it to be put up, set it up</Message></Annotation><v n="46" />Hèia Yakob pua dhèu sab'a na, lasi udhu hadhu. Ka ra madhèdi ra'a-rinu ètu era èèna, padètu dènge hadhu sèra.<bt>Then Yakob ordered his workers to go collect stones. And they sat down to eat-drink in that place, near the stones.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="liqTu (lqT imperv): gather up gal:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">liqTu (lqT imperv): gather up gal: heap of stones<span class="Italic">(46)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="47" />Hèia Laban pangare hadhu udhu sèra, <span class="Italic">Yegar Sahaduta</span>. Te ngaa Yakob pangare na, <span class="Italic">Galeed.</span><bt>Then Laban named that pile of rocks, <span class="Italic">Yegar Sahaduta</span>. But Yakob named it <span class="Italic">Galeed</span>.</bt><note reference="31:47" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Aram, <span class="Italic">Yegar Sahaduta</span> sasoa na &lt;hadhu sakasii&gt;. Madhutu lii Ibrani, <span class="Italic">Galeed</span> sasoa na &lt;hadhu sakasii&gt; kahèi.<bt>According to the Aram language <span class="Italic">Yegar Sahaduta</span> means &lt;witness rock&gt;. According to the Ibrani language <span class="Italic">Galeed</span> also means &lt;witness rock&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="48" />Ka Laban padhai lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hadhu udhu se, j'aj'i sakasii mi èdhi dua ti.&gt;&gt; Nèti èèna ka, era èèna ngara na, Galeed.<bt>Then Laban spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;This pile of rocks here, is a witness to/between the two of us-inc.&gt;&gt; That is why that place is named, Galeed.</bt><v n="49" />Laban pangare kahèi era èèna, <span class="Italic">Mispa</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;era j'aga dhu dedha&gt;), lula na peka na, &lt;&lt;Pe èèna na, LAMATUA ka dhu j'aga èdhi dua ti, ho masi ka dua ti pakaj'èu, baku kako eele lii pajaji ne.<bt>Laban also named that place, <span class="Italic">Mispa</span> (which means &lt;high place of guarding&gt;), because he said, &lt;&lt;Later, the LORD is the one who watches the two of us-inc, so that even if the two of us are far from each other, we will not transgress this promise.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mitspah: observation point, place from which"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mitspah: observation point, place from which you can see people coming a long way off, watch tower yitsef (tsph): may he guard, keep an eye on<span class="Italic">(49) (49) </span>niSSater (Str nif): we are hidden from each other, we are out of each other's sight reʕahu: his counterpart<span class="Italic">(49)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="50" />Ladhe èu tao karehe ana ja'a se, do leo-èmu dènge bhèni leo hari, tatu ja'a ke'a boe. Te ngaa mu sanèd'e! Ama Lamatua ka dhu j'aj'i sakasii mi èdhi dua ti.<bt>If you do bad/evil to my children, or marry other women, certainly I will not know. But remember! God is a witness between the two of us.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təʕaneh (ʕnH II piʕel): you humiliate,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">təʕaneh (ʕnH II piʕel): you humiliate, oppress</Message></Annotation><v n="51-52" />Èu ladhe ku hadhu dhu patitu ne, dènge hadhu dhu udhu se. Sanèd'e, hadhu se'e ka dhu j'aj'i mi too dènge lane. Èu bisa boe kako seli hadhu se, ho tao bhelu mi ja'a. Aa ja'a kahèi bisa boe kako seli hadhu se, ho tao bhelu mi èu.<bt>Look at this stone erected here, and the rocks piled here. Remember, these rocks are a boundary (doublet). You cannot walk past these rocks to do evil2 to me. And I also cannot walk past these rocks to do evil2 to you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gal: cairn matstsevah: stone set up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">gal: cairn matstsevah: stone set up as a reminder<span class="Italic">(51) (51) </span>ʕedah: witness, another form (fem)</Message></Annotation><v n="53" />Dua ti pa'èki lii pajaji ne, dènge kolongara Ama Lamatua nèti bèi-baki èdhi. Nuka Ama Lamatua nèti baki mu Abraham dènge baki ja'a Nahor. Nèngu èèna ka, dhu j'aj'i hakim, sèna ka pama'ète lii èdhi dua ti.&gt;&gt;<bt>We bind this promise with the name/reputation of the God of our-inc forefathers. That is, the God of your grandfather Abraham and my grandfather Nahor. He is the one who will be judge (loan), to decide our dispute.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="too dènge lane = doublet (ujung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">too dènge lane = doublet (ujung akhir dan garis batas)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa nanene nare, hèia Yakob j'oka soo-subha dènge kolongara Ama Lamatua, dhu ama na Isak sogo-tagu.<bt>After hearing that, then Yakob swore and oath using the name/reputation of God, whom his father Isak traditionally-worshipped.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishftu: settle the dispute (plural) vayishavaʕ:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yishftu: settle the dispute (plural) vayishavaʕ: swore an oath<span class="Italic">(53) (53) </span>bfachad: by the Terror (v. 42)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="54" />Èle èèna ka, Yakob roro badha, ho j'aj'i mi korban hia mi Lamatua ètu ledhe èèna. Hèia na paroa dhèu aa'i-aa'i mai ra'a-rinu pa'èci, ka ra beke d'ai lod'o rea.<bt>After that, Yakob slaughtered animal(s), to be a sacrifice to God2 on that mountain. The he summoned all the people to come ate-drink together, and they waked until the sun came up.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaliynu (lwn, lyn): they spent the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yaliynu (lwn, lyn): they spent the night</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="55" />Asa bèli mad'ae èèna, Laban la'e liku dènge uu ana-èpu na aa'i-aa'i ra. Ka na hia si mèngi-nale, hèia na lèpa hari asa rai na.<bt>The next morning, Laban went to embrace and kiss all his children-grandchildren. And he gave them blessing, and then he went back to his country.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaynasheq (piʕel): kissed fervently. This was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vaynasheq (piʕel): kissed fervently. This was probably the last time he ever saw any of them.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob madha'u paraga dènge a'a na Esau<bt>Yakob is afraid to RECIP-meet with his older-sibling Esau</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="32" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna ka, Yakob si kako taruu. Hèia ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga sèra mai paraga dènge ne.<bt>After that, Yakob mob continued going. And the Lord's *angels came and met with him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yifgʕu-bo: they encountered him, fell in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yifgʕu-bo: they encountered him, fell in with him. Pidgin "meet" is more intentional, so "see" may convey the chanceness of the meeting better.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ropa ladhe nèdhi si, na lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Era ne'e ne, sèmi era ae sordad'u Lamatua!&gt;&gt; Nèti èèna ka, era èèna na pangare na, <span class="Italic">Mahanaim</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;dua era ae iisi&gt;).<bt>When he saw them he spoke saying, &lt;&lt;This place, is like a resting place for God2's soldiers!&gt;&gt; Because of that, that place he named <span class="Italic">Mahanaim</span> (which means &lt;two resting places&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʔam (rʔh): he sees them machəney:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">raʔam (rʔh): he sees them machəney: a nomadsʔ camp? an army of spirits? if ʔelohim is plural. Can also be a military camp. Pidgin "camp" denotes a fixed camp for plantation workers, like Japanee Camp, so it has to go to "camping out" for temporary stays. The idea is that he is aware of the army of angels as God's protection for him. It is also the place where he splits his entourage into people and animals, which may be the reason behind the dual number.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>End of P section</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ka Yakob pua dhèu na pèri-pèri lasi uuru asa rai Edom (nuka Seir), sèna ka lasi peka dènge a'a na Esau, ho ne'a mamai na.<bt>Then Yakob ordered several of his underlings, to go ahead to the land of Edom (that is, Seir), to go tell his older-sibling Esau that he would know of his coming.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləfanayw: go ahead of him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ləfanayw: go ahead of him</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Hèia Yakob peka dènge si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lami peka dènge a'a ku Esau, sèmi ne'e: &lt;Lamatua Esau! Ènu mu Yakob, hia ji'i ngèti lii karej'e-karae mi a'a na. Peka na, &lt;&lt;Karèi nèti ja'a pakèd'i, toke sange ne'e ne, ja'a pea ètu d'ara èmu to'o Laban.<bt>Then Yakob told them, saying, &lt;&lt;Go say to my edler-sibling Esau, like this: &lt;Master Esau! Your slave/servant Yakob, has sent us to bring greetings to his elder-sibling. Saying, &lt;&lt;Beginning from when I left, until now, I have lived in the house of MB Laban.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕavdəkha: your servant, in the sense"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕavdəkha: your servant, in the sense of giving Esau a higher status ʔechar: I stayed on<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Limuri ne, ènu lamatua na dènge le unu sapi, keled'ei, rupa-rupa kahib'i, dènge ènu bhèni-mone. Ja'a hia uru dhèu se'e dhiu, ho peka dènge a'a ku, mamai ja'a ne. Ja'a sanao sèna ka a'a ku sèmi ja'a dènge d'ara kateme.&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Èle ka dhèu se lasi.<bt>Now, master's slave owns cows, donkeys, various sorts of goat-sheep, and male-female slaves. I have sent these people on ahead, so tell my elder-sibling, about my coming. I hope that my elder-sibling will receive me with whole insides.&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; After that, the people left.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="showr: head of cattle haggiyd (ngd"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">showr: head of cattle haggiyd (ngd hif inf): to announce<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ropa dhèu se lèpa hari mai, ra lolo dènge Yakob, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i paraga le dènge a'a mu Esau. Nuka na mai re limuri nèi, dènge dhèu na èpa ngasu dhèu mone, neo mai paraga dènge èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>When these people came back, they reported to Yakob, saying, &lt;&lt;We-exc have met with your elder-sibling Esau. Now he's coming behnd us, with 400 men, to meet with you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="liqraʔtəkha: on his way to meet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">liqraʔtəkha: on his way to meet you, coming against you (used mainly of soldiers going into battle). "Meet" in Pidgin doesn't leave open the possibility that Esau is hostile, which is Jacob's expectation in the next verse. "Coming by you" may leave open the question of what his attitude is going to be.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ropa na tadèngi nare, sangasa Yakob rèbha-rèbha, aa na madha'u ae. Ka na hag'e eele dhèu na dènge badha-manu j'aj'i mi dua kaboko.<bt>When he heard that, Yakob's chest thudded, and he was very afraid. So he selected out his people and his animals into two groups.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yetser (tsrr intrans): he became anxious,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yetser (tsrr intrans): he became anxious, hard pressed, in distress yachats (htsh): he divided (transitive)<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>lishney machənot: divided them into two camps, groups</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Na pangee, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Esau mai, ho na age kaboko dhu uru, na kaboko dhu limuri bisa rai, tenge sod'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>He thought, &lt;&lt;If Esau comes, to attack the first group, the last group can flee, seeking safety.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sangasa = dada ; rèbha-rèbha ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">sangasa = dada ; rèbha-rèbha = gemetar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hikkahu (nkh hif): strike, hit nishʔar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hikkahu (nkh hif): strike, hit nishʔar (nif partcpl): left, remaining<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>lifleyTah: for escape</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Hèia Yakob manèngi-mangaj'i, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua! Èu j'aj'i Lamatua nèti baki ja'a Abraham, aa nèti ama ku Isak. Nanene ku lii manèngi ja'a la! Uru èèna, Lamatua ka dhu hia ja'a lèpa asa a'ari ja'a, ètu kabarai ne'e. Lamatua ka dhu moa tèke, peka na pe Lamatua uri pamola j'ara.<bt>Then Yakob prayed, saying, &lt;&lt;God! Your are the God2 of my grandfather Abraham, and my father Isak. Listen to my request! Long ago, God2 is the one who sent me back to my relatives, to this country. God2 is the one who promised saying that God2 would arrange things.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="&quot;ancesta&quot; is used for people farther"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">"ancesta" is used for people farther away than "granfadda" ʔeytivah (ytv hif): I will make things go well with you<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ja'a ne madhutu mola-mola na, bisa boe abhu sasue dènge mamako Lamatua. Uru èèna, lod'o ja'a pège loko Yarden, ja'a kèti dhoka tatea di. Te ngaa limuri ne, ja'a lèpa kèti dènge dhèu dua nau, aa dènge badha-manu ae.<bt>I, according to what is straight/right, should not get God2's love and gentleness. Long ago, the day I crossed the Yarden river, I only brought a walking staff. But now, I am going home taking two groups of people and many animals.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qaTonti: I am too trifling, small,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">qaTonti: I am too trifling, small, unworthy mikol hachasadim: all your faithfulness to our relationship<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>umikol-haʔemet: all the reliability, fidelity, permanence, faithfulness, truth bmaqli: in/with my walking stick<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>ʕavarti: I crossed the boundary (the river)</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Ja'a mangingi, mage dhoka a'a ja'a Esau, mai pare pamadhe ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi. De ja'a manèngi sèna ka Ama Lamatua hia mamuri mi ja'a, dènge ana-dhèu èmu-kamali aa'i-aa'i mi.<bt>I am worried lest my elder-sibling Esau, comes to kill all of us. So I ask that God gives us life/salvation, to me and to all my children/wives.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hatstsiyleni (ntsl hif): rescue me, get"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hatstsiyleni (ntsl hif): rescue me, get me out of trouble yareʔ (yrʔ partcpl): I am afraid<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʔem: mother</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Lamatua dhu jaji tèke, èèna na pala-bagi mi dedha ja'a mamèngi ae-ae, aa hia ana-èpu ja'a bèba-kacanga, sama sèmi salae ètu nebhe dhasi, dhu dhèu ige rare boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>God2 has promised to distribute to me many belssings, and have my descendants multiply, like sand at the shore, which people cannot count.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="uri pamola = urus bekin lurus;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">uri pamola = urus bekin lurus; 10: mamako = gentleness, kelunakan ; pège = langgar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heyTev ʔeyTiyv (yTb hif inf abs):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">heyTev ʔeyTiyv (yTb hif inf abs): I will certainly do good chol: sand<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>yiSSafer (nif): cannot be counted</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Èle ka, Yakob si j'unu ètu era èèna. Asa bèli èèna, na hag'e badha pèri-pèri ngi'u ho rèti hia a'a na.<bt>After that, Yakob mob slept in that place. The following day, he selected out several animals to send to his elder-sibling.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baʔ (bwʔ partcpl): the stuff coming"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">baʔ (bwʔ partcpl): the stuff coming along with him minchah: as a gift to show homage or allegiance and respect<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Na pili nare kahib'i rena dua ngasu ngi'u, kahib'i mone dua nguru ngi'u, kahib'i-kalèbho rena dua ngasu ngi'u, kahib'i-kalèbho mone dua nguru ngi'u,<bt>He chose out 200 female goats, 20 male goats, 200 female sheep, 20 male sheep,</bt><v n="15" />onta rena tèlu nguru ngi'u dènge ana susu, sapi rena èpa nguru ngi'u, canguru ngi'u sapi mone, keled'ei rena dua nguru ngi'u, dènge canguru ngi'u keled'ei mone.<bt>30 female camels with their nursing children, 40 female cows, 10 male cows, 20 female donkeys, and 10 male donkeys.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meyniyqot (ynq hif partcpl fem): nursing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">meyniyqot (ynq hif partcpl fem): nursing their young ʔətonot: female donkeys<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Ka na hag'e ka badha se, èci-èci ka dènge anga na. Hèia na papala ka, èci-èci dènge ana madhenge na. Ka na peka dènge dhèu se'e, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu kako uuru. Pe ja'a dhiu. Te ngaa mi palaladha ho kaboko èci pakaj'èu nèti kaboko dhu leo sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>And he selected out these animals, each one with its companions (=own type). Then he divided each one with its own herder. And he spoke to these herders, saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl go on ahead. And I will follow behind. But you must take care that each group is separated from the other groups.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="@@ grammar of placement of number"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">@@ grammar of placement of number with 10</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕeder ʕeder: divided up into smaller"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕeder ʕeder: divided up into smaller individual flocks or herds lbado: alone, separately from the rest<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>ʕivru lfani: let them go ahead of me rewach: a space between flocks<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ka na peka dènge kaboko dhu uuru tèka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe a'a ku Esau paraga dènge èu, aa na karèi, peka na, &lt;Èu lamu mia? Èu ne, ènu nèti cee? Badha-manu se, unu cee?&gt;<bt>And he spoke with the first group, saying, &lt;&lt;If my elder-sibling Esau meet up with you, and he asks, saying, &lt;Where are you going? Whose slave are you? These animals, whose are they?&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yifgashkha: he will meet you, fall"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yifgashkha: he will meet you, fall in with you ʔanah: where?<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Na mi dhaa, peka na, &lt;Badha-manu se, unu ènu mu, Yakob. Na pa'adhu hia a'a na, Esau. Te ngaa nèngu nuka nèti limuri nèi.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Then you are to respond, saying, &lt;These animals, belong to your slave, Yakob. He is sending them to his elder-sibling, Esau. But he himself is coming behind.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shəluwchah (qal passive partcpl): the gift"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shəluwchah (qal passive partcpl): the gift is being sent vhineh gam-huʔ: and behold, he too<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19-20" />Lii sèmi èèna, na peka kahèi dènge dhèu madhenga badha cahag'e sèra hèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe mi paraga dènge a'a ku Esau, mi hia ne badha-manu se. Aa mi peka dènge ne, ja'a re limuri.&gt;&gt; Lula madhutu a'abhu Yakob, na hia badha se aa'i-aa'i mi Esau, èèna na Esau sèmi nèngu dènge be'a.<bt>The same message/instructions, he also told to the other animal herders, saying, &lt;&lt;When you meet with my edler-sibling Esau, give him these animals. And tell him that I am coming behind.&gt;&gt; Because according to Yakob's thinking, if he gave all these animals to Esau, Esau would receive him well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔakhappərah panaw (kpr piʕel): I will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔakhappərah panaw (kpr piʕel): I will cover his face (with a gift); I will appease him by giving him a gift ʔulay: maybe<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>yissaʔ fanay (nsʔ): he will lift my head (legal expression); pardon me</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Nèti èèna ka, na hia uuru rèti badha se. Te ngaa mèda èèna, nèngu pea ètu èèna era.<bt>That is why he sent those animals ahead. But that night, he still stayed in that place.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob palèka dènge Lamatua<bt>Yakob wrestles with God2</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Mèda na, Yakob kèd'i, ka na pua dhèu èmu na dhèu dua, dènge dhèu èmu piara dhèu dua, dènge ana na dhèu canguru èci sèra, lasi uuru pège asa cabèka loko Yabok.<bt>That night, Yakob awoke, and he ordered his two spouses, and his two comcubine/mistresses, and his eleven children, to go ahead across to the other side of the Yabok river.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maʕavar: a place where you can"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">maʕavar: a place where you can go across a river or a canyon</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Ropa ra d'ai ca bèka loko, ka na hia aa'i mèdha-panyau na asa nèi.<bt>When they all arrived on the other side, he sent all his belongings over there.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00686c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Te ngaa Yakob pea ka mesa-mesa ètu èèna. Hèia dhèu mone èci mai, ka dua ra palèka d'ai oe mèu.<bt>But Yakbo stayed alone there. Then a man came, and the two of them wrestled until near daylight.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiwwater (ytr nif): was left over,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiwwater (ytr nif): was left over, he stayed over yeʔaveq (nif): was wrestling with him. Like Hawaiian haəkoəkoə or even lua (hand-to-hand fighting, including bonebreaking)<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>ʕad ʕəlot hashachar: till the going up of the reddish light before dawn</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Ropa mone ne ne'a na nèngu segi boe Yakob, ka na kalabhe mi kolo keja Yakob, ka gage na tabod'a eele nèti era na.<bt>When the man knew that he couldn't beat Yakob, he pounded on Yakob's hip, and the hip-joint slipped out from its place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiggaʕ (ngʕ): he touched him, he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiggaʕ (ngʕ): he touched him, he hurt him bkhaf: on the hollow, the socket<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>yrekho: his hip socket teqaʕ (yqʕ): Jacob's joint dislocated, got sprained<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>bheʔavqo (ʔbq inf): in the course of his wrestling</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Hèia mone ne lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Patabuli ja'a, te ciki hari, lod'o rea kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then, that man advised, saying, &lt;&lt;Let me go, cause the sun will soon rise.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="palèka = berkelahi dgn bagulat ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">palèka = berkelahi dgn bagulat ; paloka = bersetubuh (kasar); 25: kolo keja = hip ; gage = hip joint ; tabod'a = talapas, slip out ; j'èru keja = cakar pinggang, stand with hands on hips</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shachar: dawn"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shachar: dawn</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa, aku Yakob na, &lt;&lt;Èu hia ja'a mèngi-nale, heka ja'a patabuli èu kèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>But, said Yakob, &lt;&lt;You give me a blessing, before I will release you!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ka mone ne karèi ne, &lt;&lt;Ngara èu ne, cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then that man asked him, &lt;&lt;What is your name?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yakob.&gt;&gt;<bt>He answered, saying, &lt;&lt;Yakob.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Hèia mone ne lii hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu ngara heka Yakob. Te ngaa mulai nèti deo ne'e ne, dhèu paroa èu, <span class="Italic">Isra'el</span>, lula èu lab'a le dhèu rai-haha dènge Ama Lamatua, ka èu segi.&gt;&gt; (Ngara Isra'el sasoa na &lt;dhu palèka dènge Ama Lamatua&gt;.)<bt>Then the man spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;Your name is not Yakob anymore. But beginning now, people will call you iIsra'el , because you have opposed humans and God, and you won.&gt;&gt; (The name Isra'el means &lt;one who has wrestled with God&gt;.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʔamer (nif): be called sarita (srh):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yeʔamer (nif): be called sarita (srh): you contend, strive, struggle<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>yisraʕel: God strives, strive with God</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ka Yakob karèi ne, &lt;&lt;Èu peka ku ngara èu la.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob asked him, &lt;&lt;You tell me your name.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa mone ne peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu neo me'a ngara ja'a, tao ngaa?&gt;&gt; Hèia na hia mèngi-nale mi Yakob ètu era èèna.<bt>But the man told him, &lt;&lt;Why do you want to know my name?&gt;&gt; Then he blessed Yakob in that place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hagidah-naʔ (ngd hif): inform, announce, put"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hagidah-naʔ (ngd hif): inform, announce, put forward</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ka Yakob padhai lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a kèdhi le Ama Lamatua madha dènge madha, te ngaa ja'a mamuri era.&gt;&gt; Nèti èèna ka, Yakob pangare era èèna, <span class="Italic">Peniel</span>, dhu sasoa na, &lt;Rèhu Lamatua&gt;.<bt>And Yakob spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;I have seen God face to face, but I am still living.&gt;&gt; Because of that, Yakob named that place, <span class="Italic">Peniel</span>, which means &lt;The Face of God2&gt;.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakatoo = saling berkutuk ; pakatoo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pakatoo = saling berkutuk ; pakatoo madha dènge madha = saling berhadapan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tinnatsel (nif fem): I escaped, I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tinnatsel (nif fem): I escaped, I was rescued; my life was saved</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ropa Yakob tèke eele era èèna, lod'o dhu rea le. Te ngaa na kako ged'a, lula gage na tabod'a.<bt>When Yakob left that place, the sun had already risen. But he walked with a limp, because his hip-joint had slipped out.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsoleaʕ: limp, stumble along"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tsoleaʕ: limp, stumble along</Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Nèti èèna ka, toke d'ai sange ne'e, dhèu Isra'el ra'a boe sisi isi lasona, lula Lamatua kalabhe patabod'a eele gage bèi-baki ra Yakob.<bt>Because of that, to this day, the people of Isra'el do not eat the meat from the /isi lasona/ (a muscle at the top of the hipbone), because God2 pounded causing the hip-joint to slip out of their forefather Yakob.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ged'a = limp, doka-doka ; padhe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">ged'a = limp, doka-doka ; padhe = patah; 32: isi lasona = a muscle at the top of the hipbone ; isi haree = daging bagian paha</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gid: sinew nasheh: major nerve of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">gid: sinew nasheh: major nerve of the hip region, nervus ischiadicus (nshh forget? forgotten?)? sciatic vein? (a mistake in the Paratext lexicon).<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>exchange w/consultant: [MC] nerve? ; [JEG] The nasheh, or sciatic nerve, in humans passes to the rear of the hip joint. There are muscles with their tendons that run posterior to it, distal to it, and anterior to it. Glossing gid as ‘sinew’ doesn't help, because it means (Concise OED) ‘tendon or ligament’. The ileofemoral ligament that wraps the hip joint is the largest ligament in the human body. The sciatic nerve is the largest nerve in the human body, 2 cm in diameter near the hip. People who butcher animals as regularly as these folks did would be familiar with both, even though they might not go into details on the attachments of the musculature. So ‘the [big] ligament near the [big] nerve’ is probably what they mean. Has anybody asked a rabbi what part the Jews stay away from? UBS: Part of the expression refers to the sinew (or tendon). These are tough white bands of connective tissue that attach the muscle, in this instance, to the hip joint. Translations vary considerably in the way they express this. neb has “sinew of the nerve that runs in the hollow of the thigh,” reb “sinew that is on the hollow of the thigh,” spcl “the tendon that is in the hip joint,” frcl “the thigh muscle that is in the hip joint.” The ball is normally held in the socket by very powerful ligaments that form a complete sleeve around the joint (the joint capsule). Gray's Anatomy: The Sciatic (n. ischiadicus; great sciatic nerve) (Fig. 832) supplies nearly the whole of the skin of the leg, the muscles of the back of the thigh, and those of the leg and foot. It is the largest nerve in the body, measuring 2 cm. in breadth, and is the continuation of the flattened band of the sacral plexus. It passes out of the pelvis through the greater sciatic foramen, below the Piriformis muscle. It descends between the greater trochanter of the femur and the tuberosity of the ischium, and along the back of the thigh to about its lower third, where it divides into two large branches, the tibial and common peroneal nerves. This division may take place at any point between the sacral plexus and the lower third of the thigh. When it occurs at the plexus, the common peroneal nerve usually pierces the Piriformis. In the upper part of its course the nerve rests upon the posterior surface of the ischium, the nerve to the Quadratus femoris, the Obturator internus and Gemelli, and the Quadratus femoris; it is accompanied by the posterior femoral cutaneous nerve and the inferior gluteal artery, and is covered by the Glutus maximus. Lower down, it lies upon the Adductor magnus, and is crossed obliquely by the long head of the Biceps femoris. The nerve gives off articular and muscular branches. The articular branches (rami articulares) arise from the upper part of the nerve and supply the hip-joint, perforating the posterior part of its capsule; they are sometimes derived from the sacral plexus.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob paraga dènge a'a na Esau<bt>Yakob RECIP-meets with his older-sibling Esau</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="33" />
      <v n="1" />Ètu d'ara lod'o èèna kahèi, Yakob ladhe nèdhi Esau, dènge dhèu na èpa ngasu sèra, mai asa rèngu. Ka na papala ana na mi ina ra èci-èci.<bt>That day, Yakob saw Esau, and his 400 people, coming toward them. And he distributed his children to each of their mothers.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yachats: he divided into two or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yachats: he divided into two or more parts</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Na hia dhèu èmu piara sèra dènge ana ra kako uuru. Èle ka, Lea dènge ana-ana na, heka Rahel dènge ana na Yusuf limuri tèka.<bt>He had his mistresses with their children walk ahead. After that, Lea with her children, and then Rahel with her child Yusuf in the back.</bt><v n="3" />Te ngaa Yakob kako uuru nèti rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra. Ropa na padètu dènge a'a na, na patitu kètu urutuu, ka na pacud'u d'ai rai pidhu hari.<bt>But Yakob walked ahead of all of them. When he was near his elder-sibling, he knelt, and bowed to the ground seven times.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pəʕamiym: times ʕad-gishto (ngsh inf): until"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">pəʕamiym: times ʕad-gishto (ngsh inf): until he approached<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Te ngaa lod'o Esau ladhe nèdhi ari na, rai dènge ka, la'e liku nare Yakob. Dua ra paliku dènge pa'uu. Hèia dua ra tangi d'ara pèd'a.<bt>But when Esau saw his younger-sibling, he ran immediately, going to embrace Yakob. The two of them mutually-embraced and mutually-kissed. And the two of them cried emotionally.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəchabqehu (piʕel): he embraced him yippol"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yəchabqehu (piʕel): he embraced him yippol ʕal-tsawwaʔro: he fell on his neck; flung himself on his neck, embraced him affectionately<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yishshaqehu (nshq): he kissed him</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Ropa Esau nèdhi bhèni dènge ana-ana si, ka na karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Se'e se, cee ka se'e?&gt;&gt;<bt>When Esau saw those women and their children, he asked, saying, &lt;&lt;Whose are all these?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yakob peka, &lt;&lt;Rèngu se'e se, dhu Ama Lamatua pala-bagi hia ja'a, ènu a'a ku ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yakob said, &lt;&lt;These here are the one whom God bestowed on me, elder-sibling's slave/servant.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chanan: acted graciously"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">chanan: acted graciously</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Hèia dhèu èmu piara na, dènge ana niki ra lasi pahaha iisi ètu madha Esau.<bt>And then, his mistresses, and their children, came and bowed-in-homage before Esau.</bt><v n="7" />Èle ka, Lea dènge ana-ana na, lasi pahaha iisi mi Esau kahèi. Dhu lasi limuri, Yusuf dènge ina na Rahel lasi pahaha iisi mi Esau kahèi.<bt>So Lea and her children, went and paid homage to esau. At the very end, Yusuf and his mother Tahel also went and paid homage to Esau.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Èle èèna ka, Esau karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu pa'adhu badha pèri nau sèi, èu neo tao ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Esau asked, saying, &lt;&lt;You sent several groups of animals, what was your intention?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yakob dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e, a'a! Ja'a hia mi a'a ku, sèna ka a'a ku sèmi ja'a dènge d'ara taleo.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yakob responded, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this, edler-sibling! I gave them to you, so you would receive me with open/broad insides (favourable).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miy ləkha: what to you? are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">miy ləkha: what to you? are they yours? pagashtiy: I ran into them, I met them along the way (not on purpose)<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>limtsoʔ-chen: to find favor, to make a good impression</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Te ngaa Esau peka, &lt;&lt;Ja'a dènge mèdha-panyau ae kahèi. De hia ia ka ja'a ngaa-ngaa.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Esau said, &lt;&lt;I also have many possessions. So you don't need to give me anything.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This is Middle Eastern politeness. Esau"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">This is Middle Eastern politeness. Esau isn't refusing the gift; heʔll take it eventually.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Te ngaa Yakob b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku, a'a. A'a ku hud'i sèmi la mèdha se, sèna ka j'aj'i mi tadha, peka na, a'a ku sèmi ja'a dènge d'ara taleo. Te ropa a'a ku b'ui mari, ka ja'a sèmi dhu kèdhi b'ui mari nèti Ama Lamatua.<bt>But Yakob replied, saying, &lt;&lt;No, edler-sibling. You must accept these things as a sign that you are receiving me favourably. Cuz when you smile, for me it is like seeing a smile from God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tirtseniy (rtsh): you are pleased with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">tirtseniy (rtsh): you are pleased with me</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />De ja'a manèngi, a'a ku sèmi la mèdha-panyau dhu kab'ua aad'o se. Lula Ama Lamatua be'a titu kèna dènge ja'a ne. Nèti èèna ka, Na hia ja'a unu ngaa-ngaa se aa'i-aa'i.&gt;&gt; Lula Yakob pamako taruu, no'o do no'o boe èèna ka, Esau sèmi nare kahèi.<bt>So, I ask the you accept these things which have no value. Because God has been very good to me. That is why He has given me everything that I own.&gt;&gt; Because Yakob kept coaxing, whether he wanted to or not, Esau accepted them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="b'u'i mari = senyum besar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">b'u'i mari = senyum besar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="birkhatiy: my blessing, my gift huvaʔt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">birkhatiy: my blessing, my gift huvaʔt (bwʔ hof): is brought<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>channaniy: he has acted graciously with me yiftsar bo: he entreated him<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>yiqqach (lqch qal): he took it</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Hèia Esau peka dènge Yakob, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, miu pa'èra ho lati palere. Ja'a lere miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Esau spoke to Yakob, saying, &lt;&lt;If that is the case, get yourselves ready so we-inc can leave together. I will escort you-pl.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niSʕah (nSh): let's depart, be on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">niSʕah (nSh): let's depart, be on our way nelekhah: let's go<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>lənegdekha: in front of you, lead the way</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Te ngaa aku Yakob na, &lt;&lt;Hud'i laa, a'a! A'a ku ladhe mèdhi unu mu. Ana mu se, ana iiki ae era. Rèngu se dhae èra èèna mèka. Aa badha ae ka dhu heka matana. Ladhe ta pakaseti si kako pamèri, ètu d'ara ca lod'o, èèna na madhe aa'i si.<bt>But spoke Yakob, &lt;&lt;There's no need, elder-sibling! You have seen for yourself. These children of mine are still very small. They are not yet very strong. And many animals have just given birth. If we force them to walk quickly, in just a single day, they will all die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yodeaʕ (ydʕ partcpl): you are the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yodeaʕ (ydʕ partcpl): you are the one who knows rakiym: tender (little children), not robust<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ʕalowt (ʕwl partcpl): are nursing dafquwm (dpq): they drive them too hard<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />De be'a risi, a'a ku si kako uuru. Pe ji'i kako mau-mau dhiu. Ladhe èèna na, ja'a dhiu ngad'o a'a ku ètu Seir.&gt;&gt;<bt>So, it would be better, if you would go on ahead. Then we-exc will come behind slowly. Later on, I will follow to meet you at Seir.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ana mu = penghormatan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">Ana mu = penghormatan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔetnahəlah: I will proceed. ləʔiTTiy: in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔetnahəlah: I will proceed. ləʔiTTiy: in my gentleness<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>məlaʔkhah: the work, the pace at which</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Hèia Esau lii hari, na peka, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, ja'a tèke eele dhèu ja'a se cahag'e, sèna ka pad'elo j'ara hia miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Esau spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;If it's like that, I will leave behind some of my people, so they can show you the way.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa, aku Yakob na, &lt;&lt;Hud'i laa, a'a, ee! Sad'i ja'a ke'a le, a'a ku sèmi ja'a dènge be'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>But, said Yakob, &lt;&lt;You don't need to! As long as I know that you have received me well (that's what's important).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔatstsiygah (ytsg hif): let me place"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔatstsiygah (ytsg hif): let me place some of my people. Jacob is actually refusing what Esau wants, but he is being very polite about it.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Tadèngi nare, Esau pakèd'i ka, tèke eele si, lèpa asa Seir.<bt>Hearing that, Esau left, leaving them behind, and returned to Seir.</bt><v n="17" />Te ngaa nèti era èèna, Yakob la'e asa Sukot. D'ai nèi, na tao èmu dènge oka hia badha aa'i-aa'i ra. Nèti èèna ka, era èèna ra pangare na <span class="Italic">Sukot</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;èmu pea taha&gt;).<bt>But from there, Yakob went to Sukot. Arriving there, he built a house, and made corrals for all his animals. That is why that place is named <span class="Italic">Sukot</span> (which means &lt;temporary house of residence&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Te ngaa nèbhu boe ka, Yakob si kako nèti Padan Aram, lasi d'ai rae Sikem ètu rai Kana'an dènge sod'a-mole. Hèia ra patitu paleo, sèna ka ra pea padètu dènge rae èèna.<bt>Finally/eventually Yakob mob went from Padan Aram, going arriving at the village of Sikem in the land of Kana'an in safety (doublet). Then they erected tents, so they could live near that village.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yichan (chnh): set up a temporary"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yichan (chnh): set up a temporary residence, probably tents.</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Rai dhu Yakob patitu paleo ne, hèli nare nèti Hemor, ana Sikem. Kab'ua rai ne, ca ngasu doi iia.<bt>The land where they erected their tents, they bought from Hemor, the child of Sikem. The price of that land was 100 silver coins.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqen (qnh): he bought chelqat: field"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiqen (qnh): he bought chelqat: field (not the usual word); plot of land<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>naTah: he spread out his tent. Probably he camped there for a while, then bought the field he was in. As a nomad, he probably would not have invested money in land unless he was sure he wanted to stay there. qəshiyTah: an old weight, here referring to an amount of money<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ètu era ne, na pudhi hadhu, tao mei korban. Ka na pangare era ne'e, <span class="Italic">El-Elohe-Isra'el,</span> dhu sasoa na &lt;Ama Lamatua nèti Isra'el&gt;.<bt>In that place, he stacked rocks, making a table for sacrifice. And he named this place, iEl-Elohe-Isra'el, which means &lt;the God of Isra'el&gt;.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yatstsev (ntsb hif): he set up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yatstsev (ntsb hif): he set up</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sikem tao pakarehe Dina, ana bhèni Yakob<bt>Sikem does evil to Dina, Yakob's daughter</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="34" />
      <v n="1" />Ca lod'o, Dina, ana bhèni Yakob dènge Lea, la'e pangad'o dènge bhèni anga-aangalai na ètu rae èèna.<bt>One day, Yakob's daughter whom he had from Lea, went to visit with the other young women of that village.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lirʔot: to go see"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">lirʔot: to go see</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Dhèu aae kabarai ne, ngara na Hemor, nèti suku Hewi. Ngara ana mone na, Sikem. Ca tèka, Sikem ladhe nèdhi Dina, ka rai nèti ne, hèia na tao pakarehe ne.<bt>The king of that populace/country, was named Hemor, from the tribe of Hewi. His son was named Sikem. One time Sikem saw Dina, and ran off with her, and then did evil to her.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nasiʔ haʔarets: the chief, minor king,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nasiʔ haʔarets: the chief, minor king, of that land (like some of the aliʔi before Kamehameha who ruled over a fairly small place) yishkav ʔotah: he slept with her<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>yəʕaneah: he humiliated her, raped her</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Sikem d'èi madhe-madhe Dina ne. Ka na solo mako, sèna ka Dina no'o dènge ne.<bt>Sikem fell in love with Dina (&lt;desired die-die). So he tried to coax her sweetly, so that Dina would want him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatidbaq nafsho b-: his soul clung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vatidbaq nafsho b-: his soul clung to her; he became attached to her hanaʕara: the young marriageable girl<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>vaydaber ʕal-lev hanaʕara: he tried to persuade the girl graciously</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Hèia Sikem peka dènge ama na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Lamu karèi Dina hia ja'a, sèna ka ja'a madhèdi dènge ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Sikem spoke with his father, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Go ask for Dina for me, so I can marry her.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="solo mako = bujuk rayu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">solo mako = bujuk rayu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Tatao Sikem ne, Yakob dhu tadèngi le, te ngaa na mau-mau, aa tao boe ngaa-ngaa. Te lod'o èèna, ana mone na sèra, ètu d'ara pad'a madhenge badha rèngu. Ka na mate si mai ku.<bt>Sikem's deed, Yakob had heard about, but he was quiet, and didn't do anything. Because that day, his sons, were out in the fields watching their animals. So he waited for them to come.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="timeʔ (piʕel): dishonor, ravish, profane, defile,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">timeʔ (piʕel): dishonor, ravish, profane, defile, make unclean hechərish (hif): he kept still, was silent, didnʔt raise an objection<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Lod'o èèna, Hemor, ama Sikem, mai padhai lii dènge Yakob, ho neo karèi Dina hia Sikem.<bt>That day, Hemor, Sikem's father, came and spoke with Yakob, wanting to ask for Dina for Sikem.</bt><v n="7" />Ètu talora dua ra padhue-padhai era, ana-ana Yakob lèpa nèti d'ara pad'a. Ropa ra tadèngi Sikem dhu tao pakarehe le ana hèni ra, ka d'ara ra pèd'a, ka ra nasa bia. Ka ra peka, &lt;&lt;Madha j'ara dhu sèmi ne'e ne, lèke boe ètu Isra'el. De ji'i se sèmi boe dhèu tao bhelu-katub'a sèmi èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>While the two of them were still speaking, the children of Yakob came home from the fields. When they heard that Sikem had done evil to their sister, their insides were sick, and they were angry. And they said, &lt;&lt;This kind of thing, is not appropriate in Isra'el. So we will not accept people doing evil like this.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitʕatstsəvu (hitp): they were outraged, felt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yitʕatstsəvu (hitp): they were outraged, felt grieved yichar: he became angry<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>nvalah ʕasah: an intolerable outrage had occurred, a grave sin, sacrilege, offense lishkav<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>yeʕaseh (nif): such as is simply not done</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ka Hemor pamako Yakob, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ana ja'a Sikem d'èi tare'a-re'a ana èu Dina. De ja'a manèngi d'ara èu, sèna ka mo'o la, paleo ana bhèni èu dènge ne.<bt>And Hemor was coaxing Yakob, saying, &lt;&lt;My child Sikem really desires/loves2 your child Dina. So, I ask you to be willing to marry your daughter to him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chashqah: his soul experiences affection, love,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">chashqah: his soul experiences affection, love, desire vitchem: your daughter; daughter and sister<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>tənu: please give</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ladhe mo'o ana-ana èdhi se paleo iisi-aanga ra. Ana-ana mone nèti miu, madhèdi dènge ana-ana bhèni nèti ji'i. Sèmi èèna kahèi, ana-ana mone ji'i madhèdi dènge ana-ana bhèni miu.<bt>If you are willing, our-inc children can marry each other. You-pl sons can marry2 with our-exc daughters. In the same way, our sons can marry2 your daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hitchatnu (hitp): let's enter into relationships"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hitchatnu (hitp): let's enter into relationships by marriage</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Sèna ka èdhi pea pa'oru pa'èci ètu d'ara rai ne'e. Sad'i miu d'èi era mia èèna ka, mi pea la dènge boe ngaa-ngaa. Mi d'aga, sèna ka abhu kakaja ètu ne'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>So that we can live mixed together here on this land. You-pl are free to choose wherever you want to stay. You can do commerce, and gain wealth here.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paleo iisi aanga ra = dalam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">paleo iisi aanga ra = dalam satu ikatan keluarga, kawin-mawin ;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shvu (yshb): settle Səcharuah (imperv): travel|i(10)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shvu (yshb): settle Səcharuah (imperv): travel<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>heʔachəzu (inf impv): be settled in the land</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11-12" />Hèia Sikem peka dènge ama Dina dènge a'a na sèra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu se, sad'i manèngi ngaa, ja'a dhoka madhutu di. Masi ka miu manèngi doi pamèu madha, dènge kab'ua pèri-pèri èèna ka, ja'a hia. Sad'i mo'o ja'a leo dènge ana hèni miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Sikem spoke with Dina's father and elder-siblings, saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl, no matter what you ask, I will obey it. Even if you ask for sexual fine (Idiom: money for washing the eyes), and some bridewealth, I will give it. As long as you agree for me to marry your sister.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="doi pamèu madha = doi tutu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">doi pamèu madha = doi tutu malu (lit. doi cuci mata), rape, hamil sebelum maso minta, atau sebelum orang tua nona tahu ; tihe = bayar (debt, not collocate with bridewealth) ; doi huku ; dhedha = denda</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔemtsaʔ-chen baʕenekhem: If I have found"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔemtsaʔ-chen baʕenekhem: If I have found favor in your sight harbu (rbh hif imperv): make it great<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>mohar: bride price matan: gift<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Te ngaa ana-ana Yakob se re'a le, Sikem dhu tao pakarehe ana hèni ra Dina. Hèia ra karihu-kahadhu, ka ra bèle, peka mi Sikem dènge ama na Hemor,<bt>But Yakob's children already knew that Sikem had done evil to their sister Dina. So they brain-played and spoke deceptively, speaking to Sikem and his father Hemor.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="go make dea sista Dinah come"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">go make dea sista Dinah come pilau [kine]. mirmah: deceit, fraud<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ʔasher: usually a relative clause introducer, but here it gives the cause Timmeʔ (piʕel): he caused to become ceremonially unclean<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i bisa boe hia ana hèni ji'i leo dènge dhèu dhu suna boe. Te èèna na, era makae ji'i èèna!<bt>saying, &lt;&lt;We-exc cannot give our sister to marry a person who has not been circumcised. Cuz that is shameful to us!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nuwkhal (ykl qal): we cannot ʕarlah:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">nuwkhal (ykl qal): we cannot ʕarlah: foreskin<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>cherpah: disgrace</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Te ngaa j'ara na sèmi ne'e: Miu se, hud'i sama ku sèmi ji'i, mone aa'i-aa'i ra, ana iiki, dhèu kapai, hud'i suna ku.<bt>But, the way (out) is like this: You-pl here must be like us-exc, all the males, small kids, adults, must get circumcised.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔakh: only neʔot (ʔwt nif): agree,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔakh: only neʔot (ʔwt nif): agree, consent<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>himmol (mwl nif inf): become circumcised zakhar: male<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Ladhe miu madhutu j'ara ne'e, èdhi heka paleo kèna. Aa ji'i pea ètu rai ne'e hèi, sèna ka èdhi j'aj'i mi èci.<bt>If you follow this way, only-then can we-inc marry. And we can also live in this land, so that we-inc become one.</bt><v n="17" />Te ngaa ladhe miu madhutu boe dad'èi ji'i, aa mo'o boe suna, ji'i ngare hari ana hèni ji'i, ho kèd'i eele rai ne'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>But, if you do not follow our will, and do not get circumcised, we will take back our sister, and will leave this land.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karihu-kahadhu = main otak ; bèle"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">karihu-kahadhu = main otak ; bèle = omo-koso, peka re'a boe ; ago</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Hèia Hemor dènge ana na Sikem ro'o kahèi.<bt>Hemor and his child Sikem agreed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiyTvu (yTb): it was okay with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiyTvu (yTb): it was okay with them</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Te ngaa Sikem no'o heka mate, lula d'ara na d'èi ae Dina. Dhèu isi rai ètu èèna pakab'ua Sikem ne titu kèna.<bt>But Sikem didn't want to wait, because his insides greatly desired/loved Dina. The people of that land had great respect/honour for Sikem.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cuz he tink Jacob daughta real"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">cuz he tink Jacob daughta real nice peopo get mo plenny respeck fo him den fo da odda Hamor ohana guys.<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>ʔechar (piʕel): didnʔt stay, retard, wait around chafets: took pleasure in<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>nikhbad (nif partcpl): was the most honored one</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ka Hemor dènge Sikem lasi asa era pama'ète lii, ètu hèb'a tedhe rae èèna, hèia ra padhue lii ne dènge kabarai sèra. Ra peka, aku rèngu na,<bt>So Hemor and Sikem went to the place of deciding disputes, at the mouth/door of the fence of that village, and the discussed the matter with the populace. They spoke, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shaʕar: gate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shaʕar: gate</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />&lt;&lt;A'ari aa'i-aa'i! Dhèu Isra'el se, d'èi mamuri mera-milu dènge èdhi. De hud'i laa ta pea pa'èci dènge rèngu ètu dedha-rai ne'e. Rai ne taleo, de èdhi bisa pea pa'èci aa'i-aa'i ti. Èdhi se bisa leo dènge ana bhèni rèngu. Aa rèngu bisa madhèdi dènge ana bhèni èdhi kahèi.<bt>&lt;&lt;All you elder-younger siblings! These people of Isra'el want a life of peace and prosperity with us-inc. So let us live united with them on this land. The land is broad, so we can all live together. We can marry their daughters. And they can also marry2 our daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shlemim: peaceable, in a relation of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shlemim: peaceable, in a relation of peace yischaru: wander, pass through the land<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>rachavat-yadayim: is broad on every side [dual]</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Lii manèngi rèngu dhoka èci di, nèti èdhi se. Ra manèngi, èdhi mone se aa'i-aa'i hud'i suna ku, madhutu ad'a rèngu.<bt>They request only one thing from us. They ask that all our males must get circumcised, according to their adat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʔotu (ʔwt nif): they will consent"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yeʔotu (ʔwt nif): they will consent nimmoliym (mwl nif partcpl): who are circumcised<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Ladhe èdhi se pab'ali le dènge rèngu, èèna na badha-manu dènge mèdha-panyau ra j'aj'i unu èdhi. De be'a risi èdhi to'o la madhutu dad'èi ra. Mai sèna ka aa'i-aa'i ti suna! Mo'o, sina ma?&gt;&gt;<bt>When we have mixed with them, then their animals and their possessions will become our property. So it would be best if we agree to follow their desire. Let's all get circumcised! You agree, right?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qinyanam: their possession neʔotah (ʔwt nif):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">qinyanam: their possession neʔotah (ʔwt nif): let's consent<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu sèra sa, sèmi lii padhai lii Hemor dènge ana na Sikem. Hèia dhèu mone aa'i-aa'i ètu rai èèna suna palere-lere.<bt>And all the people there accepted the suggestion of Hemor and his child Sikem. So all the males in that land got circumcised together.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yotsʔey (ytsʔ partcpl pl): all the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yotsʔey (ytsʔ partcpl pl): all the ones going out the city gate. This is a military term for all the able-bodied men. yimmolu (mwl nif): got circumcised. Circumcision was done by somebody else, not by the person being circumcised<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />D'ara lod'o ka tèlu, ropa rèngu dhu suna se, nu'a ra dhu pèd'a era, ka ana mone Dina, Simeon dènge Lewi, rare samala ra, kako mau-mau, lasi asa d'ara kota. Ka dua ra pare pamadhe aa'i-aa'i dhèu mone sèra.<bt>During the third day, when those who had gotten circumcised, their wounds were still painful, then Dina's brothers, Simeon and Lewi, took their swords, and went quietly, going into the city. And the two of them killed off all those men.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bihyotam (hyh inf): of their being,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bihyotam (hyh inf): of their being, when they were koʔavim: in pain from wound fever<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>beTach: securely, in security, unawares, without warning</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Hemor dènge Sikem, ra pare pamadhe kahèi. Hèia ra rèti dènge ka Dina nèti d'ara èmu Sikem, lèpa èmu rèngu.<bt>Hemor and Sikem, they also killed them. then they fetched Dina from the house of Sikem, taking her back home.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Aa ana Yakob dhu cahag'e sèra, maso asa d'ara kota èèna, ra parama rèti aa'i mèu-mèu isi kabarai èèna. Ra nasa, lula dhèu tao pakarehe ana hèni ra ètu èèna.<bt>And some of Yakob's children went into the city, and they robbed/snatched everything in that land. They were angry, because someone had done evil to their sister there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chəlaliym: the slain, the pierced yavozzu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">chəlaliym: the slain, the pierced yavozzu (bzz): they plundered<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>Timmʔu: render unclean, defile, rape</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Ra parama rèti mèdha-panyau dhèu nèti d'ara èmu ra, dènge eo rèti badha-manu aa'i-aa'i ètu d'ara pad'a.<bt>They snatched the possessions of the people from inside their houses, and herded off all their animals in the fields.</bt><v n="29" />Rèti aa'i bhèni dènge ana-ana, aa parame rare aa'i mèdha dhu kab'ua nèti kabarai ne.<bt>They took away the women and children, and robbed all the things of value from that country/political unit.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kol-cheylam: all their wealth tappam: those"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">kol-cheylam: all their wealth tappam: those of a wandering tribe who are hardly fit to march, the weak ones, including children and elderly<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>shavu (shbh): they took them captive</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ropa Yakob ne'a j'ara dhu j'aj'i èèna, na peka dènge Simeon dènge Lewi, &lt;&lt;Miu dua mi se, goa ngaa ka ne'e? Miu paj'èra ja'a! Èèna na, dhèu Kana'an dènge dhèu Peris dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra ètu dedha rai ne'e, tèka d'ara dènge èdhi se. Rèngu se, dhèu ae-ae. Te ngaa èdhi se, dhèu ciki di. Ladhe rèngu se mai age èdhi, na, ra palaho aa'i èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yakob found out what had happened, he spoke to Simeon and Lewi, &lt;&lt;How stupid can the two of you be? You have made trouble for me! Now the people of Kana'an and the people of Peris and all the people on this land, will be angry/upset with us. They are many people. But we are just a few. When they come to attack us, na, they will totally destroy us.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕakhartem: you have made me taboo,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʕakhartem: you have made me taboo, cut me off from social life lhavʔisheni (bʔsh hif): you have made me become odious, stinking<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>mətey: men miSpar: count, number<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>neʔesfu ʕalay (ʔsf nif): be gathered, unite against me, conspire against me hikuni (nkh hif): strike me, hit me in battle, strike me down<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>nishmadti (shmd nif): I will be destroyed, exterminated</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Te ngaa ana se dhaa dènge lii nasa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ama pangee na hud'i laa ji'i soro tèke si, sèna ka ra tao ana hèni ji'i ne, bhèni kajeo!&gt;&gt;<bt>But the children responded with anger, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Does father think that we should just let it be, so that they treat our sister here like a whore/prostitute!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zonah: prostitute, common whore End of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">zonah: prostitute, common whore End of P section.<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob si rai asa Betel<bt>Yakob mob flees to Betel</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="35" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna ka, Ama Lamatua padhai lii dènge Yakob, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, Ama Lamatua dhu pad'elo iisi mi èu, lod'o èu rai nèti madha a'a mu Esau. Kèd'i, lamu dènge ka asa Betel. Ladhe d'ai nèi, mu patitu mei korban hia Ja'a. Aa pea dènge ka ètu èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, God spoke with Yakob, saying, &lt;&lt;I, am God who revealed myself to you, when you fled from your older-sibling Esau. Get up, and go immediately to Betel. When you arrive yonder, you must build a sacrifice table to Me. Then you will live there.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shev (yshb imperv): live hannirʔeh (rʔh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shev (yshb imperv): live hannirʔeh (rʔh partcpl): who allowed himself to be seen<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>barchəkha (inf): on your fleeing</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2-3" />Ka Yakob peka dènge isi èmu na aa'i-aa'i, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Aa'i-aa'i ti lati dènge ka asa Betel. Uru èèna, lod'o ja'a ètu d'ara j'aj'èra, Ama Lamatua ka dhu ladhe-leru ja'a ètu èèna. Ja'a neo tao mei korban ètu nèi. De mi core eele mèdha sogo-tagu miu. Aa mi pamèu iisi mi, ho mi gati mèdha-papake leo, te èdhi neo pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob spoke with his entire household, saying, &lt;&lt;We must all go immediately to Betel. Long ago, when I was in trouble, God is the one who took care of me there. I want to make a table for sacrifice there. So throw away you-pl objects of traditional-worship. And clean/purify yourself, and change into other clothes, cuz we-inc are going to humble ourselves/pay obeisance/worship3 God.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haSiru (Swr hif): they are to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">haSiru (Swr hif): they are to get rid of nekhar: foreign land<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>btukhkhem (twkh): in your midst hiTTaharu (hitp): purify yourselves cultically, get into the proper condition for worshipping God [Catholics today have special rituals to prepare themselves for Holy Communion - many religions do something like that]<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>hachalifu (hif): change your clothes simloteykhem: your clothes<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>haʕoneh (partcpl): the one who answered me, gave me a favorable hearing tsaratiy (tsarah): my distress<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ka ra oru mèdha sogo-tagu, dènge ate-ate<bt>So they collected all their objects of traditional-worship, and their earrings. Then Yakob buried-in-earth all those things by a large tree near the village of Sikem.</bt><note reference="35:4" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Uru èèna, ètu ate-ate se, abhu rupa mèdha sogo-tagu rèngu.<bt>Long ago, on the earrings there were pictures/shapes of their objects-of-traditional-worship.</bt></note>ra aa'i-aa'i ra. Hèia Yakob dhènu mèdha se aa'i-aa'i ra ètu kapua aj'u aae ca kapua dhu padètu dènge rae Sikem.<Annotation class="General" selectedText="byadam: in their hands, in their"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">byadam: in their hands, in their possession (not necessarily "in their house") nzamim: earrings<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>bʔaznehem: in their ears vayitmon: he hid<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ʔelah: mighty tree, often with cultic significance</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Ropa Yakob dènge dhèu na aa'i-aa'i pakèd'i nèti Sikem, Ama Lamatua hia d'ara madha'u mi dhèu-dhèu dhu pea ètu d'ara rae-rae dhu padètu dènge rae Sikem, ka ra bani boe tao karehe mi Yakob si.<bt>When Yakob and all his people left Sikem, God made fearful the people who lived in villages near the village of Sikem, and they did not dare to do evil to Yakob mob.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="silu = pake; 4: ate-ate ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">silu = pake; 4: ate-ate = anting2 ; padhane = kubur (jenazah) ; dhènu = menutup dalam tanah (benda)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiSSaʕu (nSʕ): pull up tent stakes,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiSSaʕu (nSʕ): pull up tent stakes, break camp, start out, march on chitat ʔelohim: terror of God<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>Savivotehem: located around them loʔ radfu ʔacharey: and they did not pursue after, set off after someone to catch up with him with hostile intent<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ka Yakob si d'ai dènge sod'a ètu Betel (dhu uru èèna, ngara na <span class="Italic">Lus</span>), ètu rai Kana'an.<bt>And Yakob mob arrived in safety at Betel (which was formerly named <span class="Italic">Lus</span>), in the land of Kana'an.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hiwʔ (3sg fem pron agreeing with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hiwʔ (3sg fem pron agreeing with ʔarets): which was? in the same land, Canaan?</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ètu ne'e, Yakob pudhi hadhu, tao mei korban. Ka na pangare era ne, <span class="Italic">El Betel,</span> (sasoa na &lt;Betel unu Ama Lamatua&gt;), lula uru èèna Ama Lamatua pad'elo iisi mi Yakob ètu era èèna, lod'o nèngu rai nèti madha a'a na.<bt>There, Yakob stacked stones, making a sacrifice table. Then he named that place, <span class="Italic">El Betel</span>, (which means &lt;Betel's God&gt;), because formerly God had revealed himself to Yakob there, when he fled from his older-sibling.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niglu (glh nif): uncovered himself, let"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">niglu (glh nif): uncovered himself, let himself be seen</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Padètu dènge rae Betel, abhu aj'u aae ca kapua, ngara na <span class="Italic">Alon Bakut.</span> Sasoa na &lt;aj'u tangi dhèu madhe&gt;. Pake ngara ne, lod'o Debora, ina dhu lalau-lalo'o Ribka, madhe, ka padhane ètu karasa aj'u èèna.<bt>Near the village of Betel, there was a large tree, named <span class="Italic">Alon Bakut.</span> It means &lt;tree of crying for the dead person&gt;. It got that name, when Debora, the mother/nanny who had cared for Ribka, died, and they buried her beside that tree.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meyneqet (ynq hif ptcpl): the one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">meyneqet (ynq hif ptcpl): the one who had nursed Rebecca when Rebecca was a baby (rich mothers hired somebody else to do the nursing) tiqqaver (piʕel): she was buried<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Lod'o Yakob lèpa nèti Padan Aram, Ama Lamatua pad'elo hari iisi Na, ka hia na berkat.<bt>When Yakob had returned from Padan Aram, God had revealed Himself, and gave blessing to him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="boʔow (inf): at his coming yvarekh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">boʔow (inf): at his coming yvarekh (piʕel): bestow power for success, prosperity, fertility<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Hèia Lamatua peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Nèti deo ne'e ne, èu ngara heka Yakob, te ngaa <span class="Italic">Isra'el.</span><bt>So the Lord spoke to him, &lt;&lt;Beginning now, your name is no longer Yakob, but <span class="Italic">Isra'el.</span></bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqqareʔ (nif): will not be called"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiqqareʔ (nif): will not be called</Message></Annotation><note reference="35:10" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Isra'el sasoa na &lt;dhu palèka dènge Lamatua&gt;.<bt>Isra'el means &lt;he struggles/wrestled with the Lord&gt;.</bt></note><v n="11" />Ja'a ne, Ama Lamatua dhu Koasa Risi Eele. De èu matana pa'ae-ae, aa ana-èpu èu sèmi èèna kahèi. Bèli-camèd'a, suku-suku mai nèti ana-èpu èu. Aa nèti ana-èpu èu sèra, cèu dhèu aae-dhèu aae.<bt>I am God who is Most Powerful/Authority. So, [I want you to] have lots of children, and also grandchildren! Later various tribes/peoples will come out from your descendants. And from your descendants will appear/come various kings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shadday: another name of the deity,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">shadday: another name of the deity, English translations use "God Almighty." pəreh (imperv): be fruitful<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>rəveh (rbh imperv): become many [repetition of same idea doesn't sound good here SK] qəhal goyim: assembly of peoples<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>mechalatseykha (chalatsayim): from your loins (rib to hip), from your body = by natural descent yeteseʔu: they will come out<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Rai dhu pangèd'u mi baki mu Abraham, dènge ama mu Isak, Ja'a hia mi èu dènge ana-èpu èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>The land/country which I have given/handed-over to your grandfather Abraham and your father Isak, now I give to you, and your descendants.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="natatiy: gave (but they didnʔt take"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">natatiy: gave (but they didnʔt take possession)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="Hk-lb\Hk00221c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13-14" />Lod'o Ama Lamatua peka nare, Yakob patitu dènge hadhu ètu era èèna, sèna ka j'aj'i mi tadha ho na baku bhèlu eele lii Lamatua. Ka na bhori èi anggor dènge èi mènyi mi dedha hadhu na, hèia na mangaj'i mi Lamatua.<bt>When God finished speaking, Yakob erected a stone pillar there, to be a sign so he wouldn't forget the Lord's promise/instructions. Then he poured grape juice/wine and oil on top of that stone, to worship the Lord.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaʕal (ʕlh): he went up yatstsev"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayaʕal (ʕlh): he went up yatstsev (ntsb hif): he set up<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>matstsevah: standing stone, an unhewn, upright stone for cult (here), burial-marking (Rachel, v. 20), or memorial purposes (deal with Laban) yaSSekh (nSk hif): pour a drink offering, libation<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>neSekh: drink offering, libation yitsoq (ytsq): pour (in general)<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Era èèna, na pangare &lt;Betel&gt;.<bt>That place, he named &lt;Betel&gt;.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lingga (BI) = tiang batu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">lingga (BI) = tiang batu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Rahel madhe nara iisi<bt>Rahel dies giving birth</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Èle èèna ka, Yakob si pakèd'i nèti Betel. Ropa rèngu kaj'èu èèna mèka nèti rae Efrata (nuka Betlehem èèna), Rahel dhu d'ai le lod'o nara iisi na. Te ngaa nara iisi carui, hèia na roe titu kèna.<bt>After that, Yakob mob left from Betel. When they were not very far from the village of Efrata (that is Belehem), Rahel arrived at the time for her to give birth. But she gave birth with difficulty2 (hard to carry out), so she became very weak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiSʕu (nSʕ): they departed ʕowd: still|i(16)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yiSʕu (nSʕ): they departed ʕowd: still<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>kivrat-haʔaretz: a certain distance on the ground teled: she gave birth [where does the information that she was pregnant go?]<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>təqash (qshh piʕel): have hard labor, severe pains in childbirth</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ka ropa na pèngu stenga madhe, dhèu ai tadha peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Pa'èra d'ara èu, te mora iisi hari ana mone ca dhèu! De baku paroe iisi.&gt;&gt;<bt>And when she was in hard labour, the midwife (Idiom: person w/sensitive hand) said to her, &lt;&lt;Strengthen your insides (=be encouraged), cuz you are giving birth to a boy! So don't lose heart.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haqshotah (qshh hif inf): in her"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">haqshotah (qshh hif inf): in her difficult labor məyalledet: midwife<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Lod'o Rahel oe ma'ète a'ae, na pangare ana ne, <span class="Italic">Ben-Oni,</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;ana nèti j'aj'èra ja'a&gt;). Ka heka na madhe kèna. Te ngaa Yakob hia ana ne ngara <span class="Italic">Benyamin,</span> (dhu sasoa na &lt;ana ai g'ana&gt;).<bt>When Rahel was about to breath her last (=die), she named the child, <span class="Italic">Ben-Oni,</span> (which means &lt;child of my suffering&gt;). And then she died. But Yakob have the child the name <span class="Italic">Benyamin,</span> (which means &lt;child of right hand/dependable/right-handed child&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pèngu = muku (KM), (labour) contractions,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">pèngu = muku (KM), (labour) contractions, also for defecating ; duku ; dhèu ai tadha = bidan (orang tangan tadha [sensitive])</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="btseʔt nefshah (ytsʔ inf): as her"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">btseʔt nefshah (ytsʔ inf): as her soul was coming out, as her life was ebbing away ben-ʔoni: child of mourning, lamentation for the dead; Son of My Grief<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>binyamin: child of the right side, place of honor for someone particularly valued, oath, south side (on the right when facing east); Son of Good Luck, Son of the South (where they were headed)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ka ra padhane Rahel ètu sebhe j'ara dhu la'e asa Efrata, (dhu limuri ne, ngara na Betlehem).<bt>And they buried Rahel on the side of the road which goes to Efrata, (which now, is named Betlehem).</bt><v n="20" />Hèia Yakob pudhi lutu bhatu ètu ro'a dhèu èmu na èèna. D'ai sange ne'e, ro'a Rahel ne era.<bt>Then Yakob stacked grave stone on the grave of his spouse. To this day, Rahel's grave is still there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mattsevah: memorial pillar ʕal- is usually"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mattsevah: memorial pillar ʕal- is usually looking down on, or looking across at. English renderings of "tomb" are strange for cave burial, and unlikely for a dug gruva; Rachel's Tomb of today is a later structure as far as I can find out.<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>exchange w/consultant: [MC] was this a cave or was she buried underground? ; [JEG] No clues. Rachel's Tomb is still there. IV: Jacob's continuing love for her is evidenced by the memorial pillar (maccEb) he set up over her grave, and its location was still known in Saul's day, when it was described as being on the border of Benjamin at celcah (*Zelzah, 1 Sa. 10:2). The site is unknown today, though Je. 31:15 (cf. Mt. 2:18) suggests it may have been near Ramah, c. 8 km N of Jerusalem. However, Rachel's memory was also preserved at Bethlehem in the time of Ruth (Ru. 4:11), probably because it was near Rachel's burial place.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-ana Yakob<bt>Yakob's children</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Èle èèna ka, Yakob<bt>After that, Yakob</bt><note reference="35:21" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri dhu uru tèka, peka na, &lt;Isra'el&gt;. Isra'el dènge Yakob èèna, dua ngara dhu hia mi ca dhèu.<bt>Old writings say &lt;Isra'el&gt;. Isra'el and Yakob, [are] two names for the same person.</bt></note>pea boe mi ca era sa. Ca tèka, na patitu paleo ètu sebhe manara Eder.<bt>did not live in just one place. One time, he erected tents on the (other) side of the tower (loan) of Eder.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiSSaʕ (nSʕ): pull up stakes, move"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">vayiSSaʕ (nSʕ): pull up stakes, move vayeT ʔhlh (nTh, qetiv ʔahaloh): pitch his tent<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>mehalʔah: beyond</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Lod'o rèngu ètu era èèna, Ruben j'unu dènge Bilha, dhèu èmu piara ama na. Èèna ka, Yakob ne'a j'ara ne'e kahèi.<bt>While they were still there, Ruben slept with Bilha, his father's mistress/concubine (kept spouse). And then Yakob also found out about that event.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section, in the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of P section, in the middle of the verse. bishkon (shkn ptcpl): during the time he was living there<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ana mone Yakob, canguru dua dhèu.<bt>Yakob's sons, were 12 people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="23" />Ana-ana nèti Lea, nuka: Ruben (ana uuru Yakob), Simeon, Lewi, Yahuda, Isaskar, dènge Sebulon.<bt>The children of Lea, were: Ruben (Yakob's oldest child), Simeon, Lewi, Yahuda, Isaskar, and Sebulon.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="24" />Ana-ana Rahel, nuka: Yusuf dènge Benyamin.<bt>The children of Rahel, were: Yusuf and Benyamin.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="25" />Ana-ana nèti Bilha, ènu Rahel: Dan dènge Naftali.<bt>The children of Bilha, Rahel's slave: Dan and Naftali.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="26" />Aa ana-ana nèti Silpa, ènu Lea, nuka: Gad dènge Aser.<bt>And the children of Silpa's, Lea's slave, were: Gad and Aser.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Rara iisi ana se ètu Padan Aram.<bt>Those children were born in Padan Aram.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Isak, ama Yakob madhe<bt>Yakob's father Isak dies</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Èle èèna ka, Yakob la'e ngad'o ama na Isak asa Mamre, dhu dètu dènge Kiryat-Arba (dhu limuri ne, ngara na Hebron). Uru èèna, baki na Abraham pea ètu èèna.<bt>After that, Yakob went to see his father Isak at Mamre which is near Kiriat Arba (which is now, named Hebron). Formerly, his grandfather Abraham had lived there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gar (gwr): he lived as an"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">gar (gwr): he lived as an alien</Message></Annotation><v n="28-29" />Umur Isak d'ai 180 (ca ngasu aru nguru) tèu, heka madhe kèna. Ka ana na Esau dènge Yakob padhane ne.<bt>Isak's age reached 180 years, and then he died. And his children Esau and Yakob buried him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yigwaʕ: breathed his last, expired yeʔaSef"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yigwaʕ: breathed his last, expired yeʔaSef (nif impf): was united with his people, his family = die<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>səvaʕ: sated, satisfied End of P section.<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>exchange w/consultant: [MC] cave or underground? [JEG] Probably cave, since he was living close to it and the family already owned it.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-èpu nèti Esau<bt>The descendants of Esau</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="36" />
      <v n="1" />Ne'e ne, ana-èpu Esau. Ngara Esau dhu leo, Edom.<bt>These are the descendants of Esau. Esau's other name is Edom.</bt><v n="2" />Esau leo dènge ana bhèni Kana'an dhèu dua. Èci dhèu Het, ana bhèni nèti Elon, ngara na Ada. Dhèu èmu na èci hari, dhèu Hewi, ngara na Oholibama. Ama na, ngara na Anah, aa baki na Sibeon.<bt>Esau married two women of Kana'an. One was a Het person, the daughter of Elon, named Ada. His other spouse was a Hewi person, named Oholibama. Her father was named Anah, and her grandfather was Sibeon.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bat: The Samaritan Torah has &quot;Anah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bat: The Samaritan Torah has "Anah was Zibeon da Hor guy boy", which agrees better with verses 20 and 21</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Esau leo kahèi dènge ana Ismael, ngara na Basmat. Ana mone Basmat, ngara na Nebayot.<bt>Esau also married a child of Ismael's, named Basmat. Basmat's son/brother [yes, there is ambiguity here] was named Nebayot.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ada, dhèu èmu uuru Esau, nara iisi Elifas. Basmat matana Rahuel.<bt>Ada, the first spouse of Esau, gave birth to Elifas. Basmat begat Rahuel.</bt><v n="5" />Aa Oholibama matana Yeus, Yalam dènge Kora. Ana Esau aa'i-aa'i ra sèra rara iisi si ètu rai Kana'an.<bt>And Oholibama begat Yeus, Yalam and Kora. All of those children of Esau were born in the land of Kana'an.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ca tèka, Esau pidha asa rai leo cue dhu kaj'èu nèti Yakob. La'e nèti aa'i bhèni-ana niki, dhèu-dhèu sab'a, badha-manu, dènge mèdha-panyau na.<bt>One time, Esau moved to another/different land/country which was far from Yakob. He took all his spouses and children, workers, animals, and possessions.</bt><v n="7" />Esau pacèri dènge Yakob, lula badha-manu ra dènge mèdha-panyau ra ae d'ai seli. Nèti èèna ka, era pea rèngu katata ètu rai èèna.<bt>Esau separated from Yakob, because their animals and their belongings were so many. Because of that, the place where they were staying was crowded on that land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yachdaw: together, in the same place"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yachdaw: together, in the same place laseʔt: carry, support<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Hèia Esau (nuka Edom) la'e pea ètu ledhe ètu Seir.<bt>So Esau (that is Edom) went ot live at the mountain(s) of Seir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katata = basesak"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">katata = basesak</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Se'e se, ana-èpu Esau dhu ra peka na &lt;dhèu Edom&gt;. Rèngu pea ètu era ledhe Seir.<bt>These are the descendants of Esau whom they call &lt;the people of Edom&gt;. They lived in the region of the mountain of Seir.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="10-13" />Ada, dhèu èmu Esau, nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Elifas. Elifas ne, ana mone na, dhèu lèmi, nuka: Teman, Omar, Sefo, Gatam dènge Kenas. Dhèu èmu piara Elifas, ngara na Timna. Nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Amalek.<bt>Ada, the spouse of Esau, gave birth to a son named Elifas. This Elifas had five sons, they were: Teman, Omar, Sefo, Gatam and Kenas. Elifas' mistress/concubine was named Timna. She gave birth to a son named Amalek.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">Dhèu èmu Esau, Basmat, nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu, ngara na Rehuel. Rehuel abhu ana mone dhèu èpa, nuka: Nahat, Sera, Syama, dènge Misa.<bt>Esau's spouse Basmat, gave birth to a son named Rehuel. Rehuel had four sons, who were: Nahat, Sera, Syama, and Misa.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="14" />Dhèu èmu Esau, Oholibama, ana nèti Anah, aa èpu nèti Sibeon, nara iisi ana mone dhèu tèlu, nuka: Yeus, Yalam, dènge Kora.<bt>Esau's spouse Oholibama, the child of Anah, and the grandchild of Sibeon, gave birth to three sons, who were: Yeus, Yalam, dènge Kora.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bat: daughter? Anah is the daughter"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">bat: daughter? Anah is the daughter of Zibeon in the Hebrew and his son in the Samaritan Torah and in verses 20 and 21</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="15-16" />Ana-èpu Esau se pahag'a lème, ka j'aj'i mi suku ae-ae. Èci-èci ka dènge kapala suku ra. Ana-ana Elifas, dhu ana uuru nèti Esau, j'aj'i kapala suku nèti suku Teman, suku Omar, suku Sefo, suku Kenas, suku Kora, suku Gatam dènge suku Amalek. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i se'e, ana-èpu nèti Esau dènge dhèu èmu na Ada.<bt>Esau's descendants were divided and distributed, and becamse many tribes. Each had their own tribal head. The children of Elifas, who was Esau's first child, became the tribal heads of the tribe of Teman, the tribe of Omar, the tribe of Sefo, the tribe of Kenas, the tribe of Kora, the tribe of Gatam and the tribe of Amalek. All of these were the descendants of Esau and his spouse Ada.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔalufim: tribal chiefs"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">ʔalufim: tribal chiefs</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="17" />Ana-ana Rehuel, dhu ana nèti Esau, j'aj'i kapala suku nèti suku Nahat, suku Sera, suku Syama, dènge suku Misa. Aa'i-aa'i se, ana-èpu Esau dènge dhèu èmu na, Basmat.<bt>The children of Rehuel, who was the child of Esau, became tribal heads of the tribe of Nahat, the tribe of Sera, the tribe of Syama, and the tribe of Misa. All of these were the descendants of Esau and his spouse Basmat.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="18" />Ana-ana nèti Esau dènge dhèu èmu na, Oholibama, j'aj'i kapala suku nèti suku Yeus, suku Yalam, dènge suku Kora.<bt>The children of Esau and his spouse Oholibama, became tribal heads of the tribe of Yeus, the tribe of Yalam, and the tribe of Kora.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Suku se'e aa'i-aa'i ra nèti ana-èpu Esau.<bt>These tribes were all the descendants of Esau.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-èpu Seir<bt>The descendants of Seir</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20-21" />Ètu era èèna, abhu dhèu Hori èci, ngara na Seir. Ana-ana na pahag'a palème rai, ka j'aj'i suku ae-ae. Èci-èci ka dènge kapala suku na. Èle èèna ka, ana-ana na se j'aj'i kapala suku nèti suku Lotan, suku Sobal, suku Sibeon, suku Anah, suku Dison, suku Eser, dènge suku Disan.<bt>In that place, there was a Hori person, named Seir. His children were scattered around in various places,s and became many tribes. Each of them with their own tibal head. After that/so, his children became heads of the tribe of Lotan, the tribe of Sobal, the tribe of Sibeon, the tribe of Anah, the tribe of Dison, the tribe of Eser, and the tribe of Disan.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="22" />Ana Lotan nuka: Hori dènge Heman. (Ana hèni Lotan, nuka Timna.)<bt>The children of Lotan were: Hori and Heman. (The daughter of Lotan was Timna.)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="23" />Ana-ana Sobal, nuka: Alwan, Manahat, Ebal, Sefo, dènge Onam.<bt>The children of Sobal were: Alwan, Manahat, Ebal, Sefo, and Onam.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="24" />Ana-ana nèti Sibeon, nuka: Aya, dènge Anah. Anah ne'e ka dhu rage madha èi pana ètu d'ara mamoo, lod'o na madhenga keled'ei ama na.<bt>The children of Sibeon were: Aya and Anah. This Anah is the one who encountered hot springs in the wilderness, when he was watching his father's donkeys.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yemim: hot springs (Vulgate)? mules? vipers?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">yemim: hot springs (Vulgate)? mules? vipers?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="25-26" />Ana bhèni nèti Anah, nuka Oholibama. Aa ana mone na, nuka, Dison. Ana-ana Dison, nuka: Hemdan, Esban, Yitran, dènge Keran.<bt>The daughter of Anah, was Oholibama. And his son was Dison. The children of Dison were: Hemdan, Esban, Yitran, and Keran.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="27" />Ana-ana Eser, nuka: Bilhan, Saawan, dènge Akan.<bt>The children of Eser were: Bilhan, Saawan, and Akan.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="28" />Ana-ana Disan, nuka: Us, dènge Aran.<bt>The children of Disan were: Us, and Aran.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="29-30" />De kapala-kapala suku nèti dhèu Hori sèra, nuka: Lotan, Sobal, Sibeon, Anah, Dison, Eser, dènge Disan. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i se pea ètu rai Seir.<bt>So, the heads of the tribes of the people of Hori, were: Lotan, Sobal, Sibeon, Anah, Dison, Eser, and Disan. All of them lived in the land of Seir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu aae-dhèu aae Edom<bt>The kings of Edom</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Lod'o dhu kabarai Isra'el dènge mèka dhèu aae, te ngaa ètu rai Edom dènge le dhèu aae. Ngara dhèu aae se, dhutu-dhutu, nuka:<bt>When the populace/country of Isra'el did not yet have kings, nevertheless in the land of Edom they already had kings. The names of these kings, in order/sequence, are:</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="32" />Ra ded'e Bela, ana nèti Beor, j'aj'i dhèu aae ètu kota Dinhaba.<bt>They elevated Bela, and child of Beor, to become the king of the city of Dinhaba.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="33" />Ropa Bela madhe, ra ded'e Yobab ho gati ne, j'aj'i dhèu aae. Ama na, ngara na Sera, nèti rae Bosra.<bt>When Bela died, they elevated Yobab to replace him, becoming king. His father was named Sera, from the village of Bosra.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="34" />Ropa Yobab madhe, ra ded'e Husam ho gati na, j'aj'i dhèu aae. Husam ne, nèti rai dhèu Teman.<bt>When Yobab died, they elevated Husam to replace him, becoming king. This Husam was from the land/country of the Teman people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="35" />Ropa Husam madhe, ra ded'e Hadad ho gati na, j'aj'i dhèu aae. Ama na, ngara na Bedad, nèti rae Awit. (Nèngu ka dhu segi dhèu Midian, lod'o ra pamusu ètu Moab.)<bt>When Husam died, they elevated Hadad to replace him, becoming king. His father was named Bedad, from the village of Awit. (He is the one who defeated the people of Midian, when they warred in Moab.)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="36" />Ropa Hadad madhe, ra ded'e Samla ho gati na, j'aj'i dhèu aae. Nèngu ne, nèti rae Masreka.<bt>When Hadad died, they elevated Samla to replace him, becoming king. He was from the village of Masreka.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="37" />Ropa Samla madhe, ra ded'e Saul ho gati na, j'aj'i dhèu aae. Saul èèna, nèti rae Rehobot, dhu ètu sebhe loko.<bt>When Samla died, they elevated Saul to replace him, becoming king. That Saul, was from the village of Rehobot, which was at the edge of the river.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="38" />Ropa Saul madhe, ra ded'e Baal-Hanan ho gati na, j'aj'i dhèu aae. Ama na, ngara na Akbor.<bt>When Saul died, they elevated Baal-Hanan to replace him, becoming king. His father was named Akbor.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="39" />Ropa Baal-Hanan madhe, ra ded'e Hadar ho gati na, j'aj'i dhèu aae. Hadar ne, nèti rae Pau. Aa dhèu èmu na, ngara Mehetabel. Ama Mehetabel, ngara na Matret. Aa baki na, Mesahab.<bt>When Baal-Hanan died, they elevated Hadar to replace him, becoming king. This Hadar, was from the village of Pau. And his spouse was named Mehetabel. The father of Mehetabel, was named Matret. And his grandfather was Mesahab.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40-43" />De kapala-kapala suku dhu j'aj'i nèti ana-èpu Esau, nuka: Timna, Alwa, Yetet, Oholibama, Ela, Pinon, Kenas, Teman, Mibsar, Magdiel, dènge Iram. Rèngu se èci-èci pangare rai ra madhutu ngara rèngu unu ra.<bt>So, the heads of tribed who became descendants of Esau were: Timna, Alwa, Yetet, Oholibama, Ela, Pinon, Kenas, Teman, Mibsar, Magdiel, and Iram. Each of them named their land following their own names.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishpchotam: groups in which there is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mishpchotam: groups in which there is a felt blood relationship, subdivision of a tribe, ethnic group</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">De aa'i-aa'i se'e, lii lolo nèti ana-èpu Esau, dhèu Edom èèna.<bt>So all of this, is the story/stories of the descendants of Esau, the people of Edom.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="moshbotam (moshbah): seat, area of residence"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">moshbotam (moshbah): seat, area of residence ʔachuzatam: their property<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob lèpa hari asa rai Kana'an<bt>Yakob returns again to the land of Kana'an</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="37" />
      <v n="1-2a" />Ne'e ne, lii lole nèti Yakob si. Ca tèka ka, Yakob la'e pea hari asa rai Kana'an. Èèna, era pea ama na Isak nèti uru ka.<bt>This is the story of Yakob mob (=collective). At that time, Yakob had gone to live again in the land of Kana'an. There, is where his father Isak had stayed previously.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="segi = menang ; sèg'i ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">segi = menang ; sèg'i = belah (kayu, kelapa, kepala) ; sigi = kain</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mgurey: stopover place, place where a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">mgurey: stopover place, place where a resident alien lives, home JR: statement with different elaborations -- [overlay?] Lots of participles, piʕels.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf dènge a'a na si<bt>Yusuf and his elder-siblings</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2b" />Tèu èèna, ana Yakob èci, nèti dhèu èmu na Rahel, ngara na Yusuf. Yusuf ne'e, ropa umur na d'ai 17 (canguru pidhu) tèu, nèngu dènge a'a na si, tema le j'aga kahib'i-kalèbho rèngu. A'a na sèra, ana nèti ina leo hari, ngara na Bilha dènge Silpa. Te ngaa Yusuf ne'e tuka tenge lii mi dedha a'a na si, ho la'e pana'e ama na.<bt>At that time, one of Yakob's children, from his wife Rahel, was named Yusuf. This Yusuf, when he was 17 years, he and his elder-siblings, normally watched their goat-sheep (=flocks). Those elder-sibling of his, were children from different mothers, named Bilha and Silpa. But, this Yusuf was a tattle-tale (&lt;habitual seeker of issues) on his elder-siblings, going to report to his father.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taa èèna = waktu itu (~"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">taa èèna = waktu itu (~ tebho) ; lodo èèna = hari itu ; tuka tenge lii = tattle-tale</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00697c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Rèngu hia Yusuf kodho dhu saraga<bt>They give Yusuf a beautiful shirt/clothes</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Lod'o dhu rara iisi Yusuf na, ama na dhu heka le. Nèti èèna ka, na sue Yusuf ne risi eele nèti ana-ana na leo sèra. Ca lod'o ka, Yakob j'au kodho madhera èci dhu saraga bia<bt>When Yusuf was born, his father was already old. Because of that, he loved Yusuf more than his other children. One day, Yakob sewed [can also mean had s.o. sew] a long shirt which was very beautiful for Yusuf.</bt><note reference="37:3" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Ibrani, sasoa na bisa &lt;kodho madhera dhu rupa-rupa warna&gt;, aa bisa kahèi &lt;kodho madhera dhu saraga&gt; nuka kodho madhera dènge ka'ae madhera.<bt>According to the Ibrani language, its meaning can be &lt;a long shirt with various colours&gt;, or can also means &lt;long beautiful shirt&gt;, that is, a long shirt with long sleeves.</bt></note>hia Yusuf.<v n="4" />Ropa a'a na si ladhe-ladhe la'a na ama na sue risi Yusuf, hèia ra mulai tèka d'ara dènge ne, ro'o boe padhai lii dènge ne.<bt>When his elder-siblings saw that his father loved Yusuf more, then they began to begrudge/hate him, not wanting to speak with him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ka'ae (kodho) = lengan, sleeve; ka'ae"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">ka'ae (kodho) = lengan, sleeve; ka'ae kapaj'u = tangan gurita ; saraga</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5-7" />Mèda ca lod'o ka Yusuf nii. Kèd'i nèti bhèj'i ka, na lolo dènge a'a na si lii nii deo na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;We! Mi nanene ku la! Ja'a nii, na èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti, èki are ètu d'ara oka. Kabèdhi laa, are dhu ja'a èki titu dhoo-dhoo. Te ngaa are miu, oke mere are ja'a deo na, ka pacud'u mi unu ja'a.&gt;&gt; Ra nanene rare sèmi èèna, hèia a'a na se'e tabha nasa hari dènge ne.<bt>One night Yusuf dreamed. Arising from his sleep, he told his elder-siblings the story of that dream, saying, &lt;&lt;We! Listen up! I dreamed, that all of us-inc were tying rice/grain [can be specific or generic] in the field/garden. Suddenly, my grain bundle stood up straight. but your grain surrounded that one of mine, and bowed to mine.&gt;&gt; When they heard that, then his elder-siblings became even more angry with him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhoo-dhoo = straight up (not moving)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">dhoo-dhoo = straight up (not moving)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Hèia ra jèke ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;We! Èu ngee na, èu neo j'aj'i dhèu kapai kèna, ho neo paredha ji'i, do?&gt;&gt; Taga na lolo lii nii ne'e, hèia asa ra nasa dènge ne.<bt>Then they scolded him, saying, &lt;&lt;We! You think that you want to become a big/important person, so you can order us around, or (what)?&gt;&gt; Because of the story of this dream, they were angry with him.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00702c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around:horizontalPosition:left">Yusuf lolo lii nii na<bt>Yusuf tells his dream</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Nèbhu boe, Yusuf nii hari ca tèka. Na lolo hari dènge a'a na si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;We! Ja'a nii hari, sèmi ne'e ka. Ja'a kèdhi madha lod'o, hèru, dènge hua-hètu canguru èci. Aa'i-aa'i sèra, pahaha iisi mi ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Not long, Yusuf dreamed another time. He told it again to his elder-siblings, saying, &lt;&lt;We! I dreamed again, like this. I saw the sun, moon, and eleven stars. All of them were bowing2/lowering themselved to me.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="10" />Hèia Yusuf lolo hari lii nii deo na dènge ama na, aa dènge a'a na sèra.<bt>Then Yusuf told again the story of that recent dream to his father, and his elder-siblings.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka ama na jèke ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lii nii ngaa, kèna! Èu ngee na, ja'a dènge ina mu, dènge a'ari èu sèra, mai uu kabaj'èla èu, do? Èu nia ae le èèna, nga!&gt;&gt;<bt>And his father scolded him, saying, &lt;&lt;What (kind of) dream story is this! Do you think that I and your mother, and your elder-younger siblings will come and kiss the soles of your feet, huh? You're way out of line (Idiom: too much, over the top)!&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="11" />Nèti èèna ka, a'a na sèra tèka d'ara bia dènge ne. Te ngaa ama na pangee taruu lii nii èèna ètu d'ara na.<bt>because of that, his elder-siblings hated him heavily. But his father kept thinking about the dream in his insides.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="uu = cium uu = lafalnya"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">uu = cium uu = lafalnya menjadi lunak * contoh: ana uuru = anak sulung ; Èu nia ae le èèna aa! = lu su talalu lebe tu!; 11: ayat 1-2 Yusuf tuka tenge lii = tuka togo li. Artinya;Yusuf suka bicara yang bukan-bukan/ suka karang-karang. (Menurut anggapan kakak-kakaknya). *</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra pahie Yusuf asa Masir, ka na j'aj'i ènu<bt>They sell Yusuf to (location) Masir (=Egypt), and he becomes a slave</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ana tai = pembantu rumah tangga."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">ana tai = pembantu rumah tangga. ate Harafia, anak timbangan *</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ca tèka ka, a'a Yusuf sèra rèti kahib'i-kalèbho ama na, asa era j'u'u dètu dènge rae Sikem.<bt>One time, Yusuf's elder-siblings took htier father's goat-sheep to a grassy place near the village of Sikem.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Shekem is about 40 miles north"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">Shekem is about 40 miles north of Jerusalem. Jacob's main center of operations was near Hebron, 20 miles south of Jerusalem, but the country was dry and the sheep had to be taken where the grass was. Shekem was the nearest town to where they were -- they werenʔt inside the town. (It was the place Simeon and Levi had wasted not too many years before, so maybe it was unpopulated at this time, or else they still terrorized the community.)</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Nèbhu boe ka, ama na peka dènge Yusuf, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'a mu si j'aga kahib'i-kalèbho dètu dènge Sikem. De èu pa'èra, ho lamu ladhe ku si la.&gt;&gt;<bt>Not long after that, his father spoke to Yusuf, saying, &lt;&lt;Your elder-siblings are watching the goat-sheep near Sikem. So, get ready so you can go check up (see) on them.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kahib'i-kalèbho = domba ; kahib'i-ka'ia ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z">kahib'i-kalèbho = domba ; kahib'i-ka'ia = kambing *</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yusuf dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a laku, ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yusuf responded, saying, &lt;&lt;I'll go, father.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hinneni: look! me! = at your"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:30Z" status="Information">hinneni: look! me! = at your orders</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Hèia ama na peka hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu lamu ladhe a'a mu si, dènge kahib'i-kalèbho èdhi. Ladhe ra samia na, mai peka dènge ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then his father spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;You go check up on your elder-siblings, and our-inc goat-sheep. [When you] see how they're doing, come and tell me.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yusuf pakèd'i ka nèti d'ara pad'a Hebron, la'e taruu d'ai Sikem.<bt>So, Yusuf left the broad fields of Hebron, and went on until Sikem.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shalom: peace, see if they are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">shalom: peace, see if they are doing all right vahashiveni (shwv caus): bring back<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>wayyaboʔ: went off towards Shekem A two or three day hike<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="15" />D'ai nèi, na tenge a'a na si, palème d'ara pad'a èèna. Na paraga dènge dhèu mone èci, ka dhèu èèna karèi ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu tenge ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Arriving yonder [+remote], he looked for his elder-siblings, all around the broad fields there. He met/encountered a man, and that person asked him, saying, &lt;&lt;What are you looking for?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="toʕeh: wandering around (Joseph) JR: Jewish"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">toʕeh: wandering around (Joseph) JR: Jewish tradition has it that the guy was the angel Gabriel.<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Yusuf dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a tenge a'a ja'a. Rèngu eo kahib'i-kalèbho dètu ètu era ne'e. De ama, èu paraga dènge si, do aad'o?&gt;&gt;<bt>Yusuf responded, saying, &lt;&lt;I am looking for my elder-siblings. They are herding/shepherding goat-sheep near this place. So father, have you encountered them, or not?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eo = menggembala ana madhutu kahibi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">eo = menggembala ana madhutu kahibi = penggembala / orang yang menjaga *</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00703c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around:horizontalPosition:right">A'a Yusuf si rèdhi mamai na<bt>Yusuf's older siblings see him coming</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Hèia, dhèu deo na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ra aad'o heka ètu ne'e. Te ja'a tadèngi, ra peka na lasi padètu dènge rae Dotan.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then, that aforementioned person spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;They are no longer here. But I heard them say they were going near the village of Dotan.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yusuf la'e taruu, ka paraga dènge si ètu rae Dotan.<bt>So Yusuf continued on, and encountered them at the village of Dotan.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naSʕu (nSʕ): they pulled out, departed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">naSʕu (nSʕ): they pulled out, departed Another 15 miles north, another half day's hard hiking<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ropa ladhe rèdhi Yusuf nèti kaj'èu, ra padhue rare lii èci neo pamadhe ne.<bt>When they saw Yusuf from far, they discussed an agreement to kill him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="merachoq: from a distance vterem: before|i(18)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">merachoq: from a distance vterem: before<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>yiqrav: he approached yitnaklu (hitp): they acted cunningly; laying a trap that will result in his death. Rashi, "filled with craftiness and deceit"<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>lahmito (mwt hif inf): to see him dead, do him in. This is the first chance they have had to kill him in a long time - remote place, father not around, outnumbered. He is coming not to help with the sheep, but to check on the brothers. He's an outsider in age relative to his brothers, not close to any of them: dynamics of large families.</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Èci peka dènge èci, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu ladhe ku la! Mone eele tuka nii na, nuka mai nèi!<bt>they spoke to each other, saying, &lt;&lt;Look at that! The big dreamer boss is coming yonder!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This is the details of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">This is the details of the plan summarized in 18. ʔish: nobody singled out; each of them was thinking the same thoughts and telling them to somebody else<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>baʕal hachlomot: the Lord of Dreams; sarcastic, the Dreamer, Master Dreamer. baʕal "expert" (Moses tells God he's not an expert talker "baʕal dvarim") hallazeh: this, explained as ha + zeh<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>baʔ (partcpl): background participle</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />De mai ho ti pamadhe ne. Ho èèna na, ti core eele ne asa d'ara madha èi madhe èèna. Ladhe d'ai èmu na, ti peka dènge ama peka na, badha hui ra'e ne. Ho èèna na, ti ladhe sèku, lii nii na sèra sa mia!&gt;&gt;<bt>So, let's kill him. Afterwards, we'll throw him into that dry well there. When we arrive back home, we can say to father that a wild animal has eaten him. After that we'll have a look to see where his dream has gone [idiomatic].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pare'a lii =; 19: Mone eele"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">pare'a lii =; 19: Mone eele = The big man, boss (cynical, speaker attitude); 20: ra'e ~ ra'a = 3p-makan ; madha èi madhe = dry well</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lkhu (hlk imperv): let's go somewhere"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">lkhu (hlk imperv): let's go somewhere nashlikhehu: let's throw something down. fling, not a proper burial<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>borah: location, cistern, artificial excavation in rocky soil, usually ten to thirty feet deep, for collecting and storing winter rain. Plastered inside with lime, therefore smooth. Opening smaller than the bottom. Hard to get out of. Also used for storing grain chayah: wild animal<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>raʕah: evil. Used for dangerous animals - lion, bear, ... ʔəkhalat-hu: ate him<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>vnirʔeh (rʔh): become visible mah-yyihyu: what they will become. The rabbis saw this as a test of Joseph's prophetic spirit: is our word going to be fulfilled, or his?<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ropa nanene èèna, hèia a'a na Ruben tenge j'ara ho patabuli eele Yusuf. Hèia na kai ari na si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;We! Èdhi baku pamadhe ne!<bt>Upon hearing that, his elder-sibling Ruben looked for a way to free/releave/save Yusuf. So he forbade his younger-siblings, saying, &lt;&lt;We! We should not kill him!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaatstsilehu (ntsl hif): he rescued him,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yaatstsilehu (ntsl hif): he rescued him, snatched him away. Josephus thinks Reuben is off scouting for new pasture land, so he is away a lot, and this is the first he has heard of the plot yad: hand, power, in their power<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>nakkennu nafesh (nkh hif): we strike him and he dies, we beat him to death</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Be'a risi èdhi kèpe ne, ti tao asa d'ara madha èi madhe nèi. Ètu èèna, era dhu dhèu aad'o, de èci sa rèdhi boe ne. Sad'i baku pasuti raa na.&gt;&gt; Na peka sèmi èèna, lula na tenge j'ara ho patalale Yusuf, ho hia na lèpa hari èmu.<bt>It would be better for us to grab/catch him and put him into that dry well yonder. In that place there are no people, so nobody will see anything. As long as [we/you] don't spill blood.&gt;&gt; He spoke like that, because he was looking for a way to free Yusuf, to send him back home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="panu'e ~ panu'a = melukai ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">panu'e ~ panu'a = melukai ; pasuti = tumpahkan ; parèu = drop, menjatuhkan dari atas ke bawah ; tule = tolak, push, shove; èi madhe = parigi mati</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔal tishpku-dam: donʔt shed blood, making"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔal tishpku-dam: donʔt shed blood, making blood spill out. Reuben, as eldest but out of favor with his father, needs to secure his own birthright against Jacob taking it over. midbar: in the uncultivated place<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>yad ʔal-tishlkhu-bo: donʔt lay a hand on him lemaʕan hatsil ʔoto: in order to save him<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00705c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none:horizontalPosition:center">Ra tule Yusuf asa d'ara madha èi madhe<bt>They shove Yusuf into a well</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ropa Yusuf d'ai madha a'a na si, ra kèpe ne, ka ra rèbhi eele kodho dhu saraga aae ètu ua na.<bt>When Yusuf arrive in front of his elder-siblings, they grabbed him, and they yanked stripping off [with force] the beautiful shirt from his body.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yafshiTu (hif): they stripped him. et"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yafshiTu (hif): they stripped him. et ... et ... et ... things that are relevant later kutanto (ktonet): his tunic, inner garment. Like a long t-shirt, but hand woven and in this case, quite fancy<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Ka ra nuni pa'oro ne, hèia ra tule ne asa d'ara madha èi madhe èèna.<bt>And they dragged him [along the ground], and they shoved him into that dry well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rèbhi = ru'i, take off by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">rèbhi = ru'i, take off by force, tarik dgn paksa, dgn keras; 24: padulu = pegang kasi maso pi bawa ; pa'oro = roroso</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="req: empty, idle; [JEG] &quot;Req&quot; implies"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">req: empty, idle; [JEG] "Req" implies that it wasnʔt in use for anything else, not that it was dry; so the extra statement is added, probably because such cisterns are used for water storage during dry times.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Èle èèna ka, ra lèpa, lasi ra'a-rinu. Ètu talora ra'a-rinu, kabèdhi la ra ladhe rèdhi dhèu canau mai re èèna. Dhèu sèra kako rèti dènge badha onta ra, hue dènge mèdha d'aga, sèmi raa aj'u hèu mèngi, bubhu-bubhu dènge èi na'i rupa-rupa. Dhèu sèra sa, dhèu Ismael, dhu mai nèti rae Gilead neo lasi kaj'èu d'ai Masir.<bt>After that, they went back to eating-drinking. While they were eating-drinking, suddenly they saw a group of people coming. Those people were going taking their onta [=camel, loan] animals, to sell trade goods such as frangrant tree sap, spices [loan] and various medicines. Those people were Ismael people, who were coming from the village of Gileat wanting to go far to Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hue ~ hua2 = muat ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">hue ~ hua2 = muat ; aj'u nidhu = kayu cendana ; bubhu-bubhu = spices ; Ngaa te = padahal, tau-tau</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yisʔu (nsʔ): they raised their eyes,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yisʔu (nsʔ): they raised their eyes, they looked ʔorchat (ʔorchah): caravan<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>nkhoʔt: ladanum; aromatic gum exuded from the leaves of the cistus-rose (Cistus salvifolius, native to Palestine). Zohary identifies it as tragacanth gum, from Astragalus or from A. gummifer on Mt. Hermon. tsri: Jericho balm, a desert plant possibly identified with Balm of Gilead, lot, Commiphora opobalsamum, which is not native to Palestine but comes from Arabia. Commentators suggest it was Balanites aegyptiaca, which is found all over Egypt and Palestine; but both this passage and Gen 43:11 refer to tsri as something that grew in Palestine but not in Egypt. UBS following Moldenke suggests Pistacia lentiscus, the mastic tree, 1 to 3 m. tall, evergreen leaves, with a gummy sap. Zohary doesn't list it.<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>lot: myrrh or stacte (type of resin; FF 147-149,178). "Mor," Greek smyrna? Myrrh is Commiphora myrrha (Cistus salvifolia), a dark red gum with strong aroma and a bitter taste. Arabia, Abyssinia, Somalia coast, but not Palestine or Gilead. More likely "lot" is ladanum and "nkhot" is tragacanth. Zohary identifies it as ladanum, Cistus incanus, widespread in Gilead and elsewhere. lhorid (yrd hif inf): take it down to Egypt<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Èle èèna hèia, Yahuda peka dènge a'ari na sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ee! Be'a risi sèmi ne'e. Èdhi baku pamadhe ne. A'oto na ngaa? Tasa mera mia èèna ka, èdhi bisa boe pahuni raa na.<bt>Then, Yahuda spoke to his elder-younger siblings, saying, &lt;&lt;Ee! It's better like this. We-inc should not kill him. What good/benefit would it do? No matter how, his blood, we-inc would not be able to hide.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This story tracks Joseph, whose sons"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">This story tracks Joseph, whose sons Ephraim and Manasseh carry the most weight among the northern tribes later; but Judah plays an important role, because it is in this story that he takes over the leadership, and his descendants become the important ones in the south. Reuben appears to leave again.<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>betsaʕ: cut, profit kiSinu (kSh piʕel): we cover up<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Be'a risi èdhi pahie ne dènge dhèu Ismael sèi. Èdhi tao ne samia èèna ka oo, nèngu ne'e ari d'èlu èdhi. Nèti èèna ka, baku èdhi pamadhe ne!&gt;&gt; Aa'i-aa'i ra d'èi kahèi dènge lii Yahuda èèna.<bt>It would be better for us to sell him to those Ismael people yonder. No matter what we do to him, he is still our own younger-sibling (=share at least one biological parent). Because of that, we must not kill him!&gt;&gt; All of them agreed with what Yahuda said.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vyadenu ʔal-thi-bo (hyh): our hand will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vyadenu ʔal-thi-bo (hyh): our hand will not be on him</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00709c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none:horizontalPosition:center;verticalPosition:top">Ra rare lii èci ho ra pahie Yusuf mi dhèu d'aga sèra<bt>They agree to sell Yusuf to those merchants</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ropa dhèu d'aga sèra<bt>When the merchants</bt><note reference="37:28a" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Ibrani ae ka dhu peka, na, &lt;dhèu nèti rai Midian&gt;. Abhu dhèu d'èlu-mèu cahag'e peka na dhèu Midian sèra dènge dhèu Ismael sèra, dua ngara, te ngaa ca suku. Rèngu sèra j'aj'i ana-èpu Ismael, aa rèngu pea ètu rai Midian. (Ladhe ètu <span class="Italic">Tuka Pama'ète Lii</span> 8:22-24). Abhu dhèu d'èlu-mèu cahag'e hari dhu peka na, dhèu Midian dènge dhèu Ismael sèra j'aj'i nèti dua suku, te ngaa rèngu sama-sama dhèu d'aga.<bt>Knowledgeable people say that, at that time, they normally sold a young-person slave for 20 silver coins. The Ibrani language writings say these silver coins were <span class="Italic">sikel.</span></bt></note>d'ai era èèna, hèia a'a Yusuf sèra lasi ère rare ne, nèti d'ara madha èi madhe deo na. Ka ra pahie ne mi dhèu Ismael sèra dènge kab'ua 20 (dua nguru) bua doi pudhi.<bt>arrived at that place, then Yusuf's elder-siblings pulled him out from that aforementioned dry well.And they sold him to those Ismael people with a price of 20 silver coins. And the Ismael people took Yusuf to the land of Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rupia / ringgit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">rupia / ringgit</Message></Annotation><note reference="37:28b" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu d'èlu-mèu sèra peka na, taa èèna, ra biasa pahia ènu dhu ngèru era, dènge kab'ua dua nguru doi pudhi. Sasuri lii Ibrani peka na doi pudhi èèna sikel.</note>Ka dhèu Ismael sèra rèti Yusuf asa rai Masir.</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Lod'o ra pahie Yusuf ne, Ruben ne'a boe. Ropa na la'e patigi sa d'ara madha èi madhe na, capa na kabèdhi, ladhe la'a na Yusuf aad'o heka ètu d'ara. Nèti èèna ka, na ciu pamae kodho ètu ngi'u na, lula d'ara na pèd'a ae titu kèna.<bt>When they sold Yusuf, Ruben didn't know about it. When he went to take a peek into that dry well, he was startled, seeing that Yusuf was no longer in it. Because of that, he tore destroying the clothes on his body, because his insides were greatly pained/distressed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Reuben may have come back after"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">Reuben may have come back after his brothers left, or he may have waited for them to leave yiqraʕ: he tore<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>bgadaw: his clothes</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Hèia na la'e sa ari na si, ka na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Ari èdhi aad'o heka ètu era èèna! Ja'a tao samia hari?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he went to his younger-siblings, and spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Iraii! Our-inc younger-sibling is no longer in that place! Now what am I going to do?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patigi = maloi pi dalam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">patigi = maloi pi dalam</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔanah ʔni-ba (ʔan) (boʔ participle): where?;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔanah ʔni-ba (ʔan) (boʔ participle): where?; ʔliterally "where shall I go?" meaning "where can I turn fo help? what can I do? there is no hope left for me"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Hèia ra roro kahib'i ci'u, ka rare kodho Yusuf dhu saraga aae èèna, cèb'u sa d'ara raa kahib'i deo na.<bt>Then they slaughtered a goat, and took Yusuf's beautiful shirt, dipping it into the blood of that goat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishchtu: they slaughtered sʕir: hairy one,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yishchtu: they slaughtered sʕir: hairy one, he-goat<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>ʕizim: the goats (one of their own goats, not a wild goat like the ones that are all over the hills around here) yitblu: dip<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Hèia ra lèpa ka rèti dènge kodho deo na, pad'elo dènge ama na, ka ra peka, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ji'i pili ngare kodho ne'e. Ama ku ladhe sèku la. Tao-tao ne'e kodho ari ji'i Yusuf.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they returned (home) taking that aforementioned shirt, and showed it to their father, and they spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! We-exc retrieved this shirt. Have a look at it. Perhaps this shirt is our younger-sibling Yusuf's.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəshallchu (shlch piʕel): they sent, they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yəshallchu (shlch piʕel): they sent, they had the shirt brought to Jacob, probably by a servant yaviyʔu (bwʔ hif): they caused it to arrive<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>hakker-naʔ (nkr hif imperv, causative): investigate, recognize, know what it is. Recognize, please. (Same word used in Chapter 38, ties the two together.) ʔShirtʔ is not in the construct; there is a hiatus between it and binkha. binkha hiʔ, ʔim loʔ: is this your boyʔs, or not?<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ropa nèdhi kodho deo na, Yakob tadhe dènge. Hèia na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Ne'e kodho ana ja'a. Èle boe badha hui ra'e ana ja'a. Ira iiii! Ana ja'a madhe le!&gt;&gt;<bt>When he saw that shirt, Yakob recognised it straight-away. Then he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Iraii! This shirt is my child's. A wild animal has probably eaten my child. Iraiiii! My child is dead!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yakirah (nkr hif imperf): he recognized"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yakirah (nkr hif imperf): he recognized it chayah raʕah: an evil beast, dangerous animals recognized as a class<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>tarof toraf: torn in pieces, the way a wild animal eats his prey</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Nèti èèna ka, Yakob ciu pamae kodho ètu ngi'u na, ka na pake karo, taga nèti d'ara na susa titu kèna.<bt>Because of that, Yakob tore destroying the shirt on his body, and he wore gunny-sack, because his insides were in great difficulty.</bt><note reference="37:34" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Yakob ciu kodho ètu ngi'u na, ka na pake karo, sama sèmi dhèu Yahudi biasa pake ètu d'ara mamadhe.<bt>Yakub tore destroying the shirt/clothes on his body and wore gunny-sack, like the Yehudi people normally wore in mourning.</bt></note>Na tangi lii ooi-ooi sène nare lod'o nèbhu aae.<bt>He wept in grief for a great long time.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="simlotaw: his clothing yasem: he put"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">simlotaw: his clothing yasem: he put on<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>saq: poor quality material of goat hair covering the bare loins during mourning matnaw: the strong musculature which unites the upper and lower part of the body, lumbar region, hips, small of the back, loins<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>yitʔabel (hitp): he mourned yamim ravim: many days; Rashi says it is 22 years.<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="35" />Ana na, ana mone dènge ana bhèni sèra aa'i-aa'i ra, mai padhai lii pakarej'e d'ara ama ra, te ngaa tao rare boe ne. Aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Sasusa ja'a ne bisa d'ai madhe kèti. Te ja'a bisa boe bhèlu ana èci ne'e.&gt;&gt; Mema d'ara Yakob j'èra taruu, lula na ngee nèdhi ana na Yusuf dhu madhe èèna.<bt>His children, all his sons and his daughters, came to speak comfortingly to their father, but were not able to. He said, &lt;&lt;No! This suffering of mine can be until I die. But I cannot forget this one child.&gt;&gt; It is true that Yakob's insides were in on-going difficulty, because he kept thinking about his child who had died.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii ngob'i-ngob'i = (sobbing) berduka, meratap"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">lii ngob'i-ngob'i = (sobbing) berduka, meratap ; /lii ooi-ooi/ 'in grief'</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaqumu (qwm): they arose, stood up."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yaqumu (qwm): they arose, stood up. Were there other daughters besides Dinah? Probably, as women donʔt get mentioned much unless they do something that calls attention. Might include daughters-in-law too. lnakhmo (piʕel caus): to comfort him about the death, express condolences, reassure<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>ymaʔen: he refused lhitnachem (nkm hitp): to be comforted<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>ʔered (yrd imperf): I will go down ʔavel (adj): in mourning<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>sheʔolah: location, the world of dead people. Not Hell, which is a place of punishment yevk (bkh): he wept for his son, he bewailed him<span class="Italic">(35)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00713c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around:horizontalPosition:left">Yusuf j'aj'i ènu ètu Masir<bt>Yusuf becomes a slave in Masir</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Lod'o-lod'o dhu Yakob ètu d'ara susa era, dhèu d'aga sèra<bt>While Yakob was still grieving like that, those merchants</bt><note reference="37:36" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab madhutu lii Ibrani peka ètu ayat ne'e, na, dhèu d'aga sèra, &lt;dhèu Midian&gt;.<bt>The Bible according to the Ibrani language says that these merchants were &lt;Midian people&gt;.</bt></note>d'ai le Masir. D'ai nèi, ka lasi pahie eele Yusuf dènge dhèu kapai èci ètu nèi, ngara na Potifar. Dhèu ne'e komedhaa j'aga nèti dhèu aae Masir.<bt>had arrived in Masir. Arriving there, they went and sold Yusuf to an important person yonder, named Potifar. This person was commander (loan) of the guards of the king of Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Penggunaan vokal ganda ada dua cara"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">Penggunaan vokal ganda ada dua cara yaitu: suku kata yang diawali konsonan, yang menyusul vokal dobel mendapat tekanan panjang pada suku kata yang ke dua. . Contoh :( ta - ruu ), ( li- nii), ( ta- tee), (nga- ngee), ( lii), ( (dhaa), dll. Sedangkan suku kata yang diawali dengan vokal dobel, mendapat tekanan lunak. Contoh : aado , uuru , eele , oona , iisi. *</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mədanim: Medan, textual variant Midian. Gen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">mədanim: Medan, textual variant Midian. Gen 25:2 they were both Keturah's sons. Judges 8:22,24 Midian = Ishmael. makhru: they sold<span class="Italic">(36) (36) </span>sris: court-official, eunuch sar: king's representative, chief, leader of group<span class="Italic">(36) (36) </span>hattabachim: bodyguards; executioners, slaughterers CHECK (he ran a prison, according to 40)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yahuda dènge dhèu èmu ana na, Tamar<bt>Yahuda and his child-in-law Tamar</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu èmu = istri arti harafiah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">dhèu èmu = istri arti harafiah orang rumah *</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="38" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna ka, Yahuda tèke eele a'ari na, ka la'e pea dènge angalai na èci, ngara na Hira, ètu rae Adulam.<bt>After that, Yahuda left his elder-younger siblings, and went to live with a friend of his, named Hira, in the village of Adulam.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayered: go down; go from the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayered: go down; go from the Judea ridge toward Egypt, to the southwest. Judah may have been around 20; Joseph was 17. vayit (nth imperf): spread out = put up his tents. The brothers split up, and Judah distances himself not only by going elsewhere, but by throwing in his lot with a Canaanite. Rashi thinks Judah became Hirah's business partner.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>Judah is the second emerging leader of the Israel nation. He persuaded his brothers to sell Joseph, not kill him. Rashi defends Judah by saying that if he had told his brothers to return Joseph to their father, they would have done it; but that also implies Judah may have remorse for not having done it. Check on tabachim in 37:36 executioners or bodyguards? Potifar ran his own prison.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ètu èèna, dhèu mone èci, dhèu Kana'an, ngara na Sua. Yahuda d'èi ana bhèni na èci, ka nare j'aj'i dhèu èmu na. Dhèu èmu Yahuda ne'e nara iisi ana mone pagod'o-pagod'o dhèu pèri-pèri.<bt>There, there was a man, a Kana'an person, named Sua. Yahuda like one of his daughters, and took her to be his wife. This wife of Yahuda's gave birth to several sons in succession.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="knaʕni: Rashi follows the Talmud in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">knaʕni: Rashi follows the Talmud in reading "Canaanite" as "merchant", but with no basis. He may be worried about too many women from outside the family marrying in. Shuaʕ: add "w" to distinguish it from a common Pidgin word. LXX calls her Batshua as in Verse 12.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>vayaboʔ ʔeleah: he went to her, had intercourse with her. Standard phrase for the consummation phase of a marriage, implied in Pidgin "marry".</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Ana uuru èèna, ngara na Er.<bt>The first child, was named Er.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatahar (hrh): she became pregnant yiqraʔ:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vatahar (hrh): she became pregnant yiqraʔ: masculine, but in the sequence "pregnant ... bore ..." it could be taken as feminine. Yet the first boy seems to normally have his name given by the father, even when the rest are named by the mother.<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ana ka dua, ngara na Onan.<bt>The second child, was named Onan.</bt><v n="5" />Aa ana ka tèlu, ngara na Sela. Lod'o ina na nara iisi Sela na, Yahuda si pidha le asa rae Kesib.<bt>And the third child was named Sela. When his mother gave birth to Sela, Yahuda mob had already moved to the village of Kesib.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pagodo-pagodo = baiko-baiko *"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">pagodo-pagodo = baiko-baiko *</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatosef (ysf hif): did it again."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vatosef (ysf hif): did it again. Sounds like they came in rapid succession, so Shelah wasnʔt necessarily much younger than Onan. kziv: possibly ʔDeceptionʔ. Jeremiah uses it in that way.<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>blidtah (yld inf): at his birth Martin Ebegg and others at Notre Dame have brought out a new translation that leans more heavily on the Dead Sea Scrolls and the Septuagint than just on the Masoretic text. (Jon Rawlings studied with John Strudnell.)<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ropa ana mone uuru, dhu ngara na Er èèna kapai, ka ama na la'e tenge dhèu hia ne. Ngara ana bhèni na Tamar. Ka dua ra j'aj'i paleo èmu.<bt>When the oldest son, named Er was big, his father went looking for a person for him [= Idiom relating to marriage process]. The name of this woman was Tamar. The two of them married.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The Rabbis thought Tamar must be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">The Rabbis thought Tamar must be Aramean, in order to defend Judah's reputation. Between Verses 5 and 6, Er grows up. Maybe he's 18 by now. This could have been even before Joseph was sold, though the chronology may fit if Er was born soon after.<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Lula Er ne, bhelu-katub'a, ka Ama Lamatua huku pamadhe ne. Nèti èèna ka, nèngu dènge boe kolo.<bt>Because Er was evil, Father God punished him to death. Because of that, he was without peak/tip [Idiom: barren, no descendants]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kajeo = nakal ; kajeo nia"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">kajeo = nakal ; kajeo nia boe = talalu nakal ; dènge boe kolo = Idiom = tèka eele boe ana</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʕ: ugly, disagreeable, unwholesome, bad, morally"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">raʕ: ugly, disagreeable, unwholesome, bad, morally depraved, objectionable. Stative, not a discrete bad action. vaymitehu: he killed him; Er died, when the Lord took his life; allowed his death, took his life, put him to death -- almost like a judicial execution.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Hèia Yahuda paroe nare ana mone ka dua na, ka na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Onan! A'a mu Er madhe, dènge boe ana. Madhutu ad'a èdhi na, èu hud'i leo hari ku dènge dhèu èmu a'a mu ne. Sèna ka èu bisa hia kolo hia a'a mu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yahuda summoned his second son, and told him, saying, &lt;&lt;Onan! Your older-sibling Er is dead, and has no children. According to our-inc adat, you must (re)marry your older-sibling's wife. So that you can give peak/tip (descendents) to your older-sibling.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vyabem ʔotah (bwʔ piʕel imperv): consummate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vyabem ʔotah (bwʔ piʕel imperv): consummate the marriage of a brother-in-law, in which the obligation is fulfilled of marrying one's brother's widow to produce offspring. Dt 15:5 says that the first son born to the uncle will carry the dead man's name, and the uncle's other sons will carry their uncle's name. Onan didnʔt take it that way; he thought he was cut out of starting his own lineage. haqem (qwm hif imperv): raise up a family<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Mema Onan ne'a le ad'a sèmi ne'e. Te ngaa na no'o boe hia kolo mi a'a na Er. Nèti èèna ka, ladhe rèngu j'unu pa'èci, na pasuti eele hua hini nèngu asa li'u, sèna ka Tamar baku dènge babia.<bt>It is true that Onan knew that adat. but he didn't want to give descendants to his elder-sibling Er. Therefore, when they were sleeping together, he spilled his semen (euph &lt; fruit-seed) on the outside, so that Tamar would not be burdened/pregnant.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayedaʕ (ydʕ imperf): he realized zeraʕ:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayedaʕ (ydʕ imperf): he realized zeraʕ: offspring, collective, not singular. Keep the line going. There may be something about the inheritance involved too.<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>hayah: introduces a temporal clauses. This is called a frequentative perfect, and matches baʔ; but it's about the only example there is. vshichet (piʕel): wipe out, spoil, ruin, misuse; he would purposely ejaculate on the ground rather than risk making Tamar pregnant with a child who was not his. She was probably about Onan's age, 16 or 17.<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>lbilti: so that ... not</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Taga tatao Onan sèmi ne'e ka, Lamatua nasa bia dènge ne. Nèti èèna ka, Lamatua huku pamadhe ne kahèi.<bt>Because of Onan's deed like that, God/Lord was very angry with him. Therefore, God/Lord punished him to death as well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hua hini = bibit (halus) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">hua hini = bibit (halus) ; èi mamunu = semen, air mani (embarrasing to mention, not in mixed company)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiraʕ (rʕʕ impf): he was displeasing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayiraʕ (rʕʕ impf): he was displeasing to God, stative.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ropa Yahuda nèdhi ana mone na dua sèra dhu leo dènge Tamar madhe sèmi èèna, hèia Yahuda madha'u. Ka na pangee mage dhoka ana mone ka tèlu èèna, leo hari dènge Tamar na madhe kahèi. Nèti èèna ka, la'e peka dènge Tamar, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Be'a risi èu lèpa hari asa d'ara adhe-aai ina dènge ama mu. Ladhe ana ja'a Sela kapai, na èu lèpa hari mai ho leo dènge ne.&gt;&gt; Hèia Tamar lèpa dènge ka.<bt>When Yahuda saw that his two sons who had married Tamar die like that, Yahuda was afraid. And he thought perhaps if his third son also married Tamar, he would also die. therefore, he went and spoke to Tamar, saying, &lt;&lt;It would be better if you go back to the palms (=care) of your mother and your father. When my child Sela is big, then you can come back and marry him.&gt;&gt; So Tamar went home right away. [can be time, or implying, didn't go live with someone else for awhile].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dara adhe aai = telapak tangan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">dara adhe aai = telapak tangan ; adhe = hati ; èu lèpa hari asa dara adhe aae ina dènge ama mu = said in anger when threatening to divorce</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalato (kalah): woman who is first"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">kalato (kalah): woman who is first under control of her father, then of her husband (and her father in law as the husband's representative); young daughter-in-law. Hittite and Middle Assyrian law (Tiglath-Pileser, reflecting customs that could already have been in force in Abraham's time) specify that if there is no other brother to marry the widow and perpetuate the dead man's line, the dead man's father is to do it, and if he dies, his brothers. Even if Tamar is living at her father's place, she is still under Judah. ʔalmanah: as a widow<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʕad-yigdol (imperf): until he grows up. Sounds like Shelah was 15 or 16, so waiting to become of marriagable age was on the order of maybe a year, not a decade. He might have been Tamar's age. pen: prevention of a theoretically possible event<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>vatelekh (hlk imperf): she went</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Nèbhu-nèbhu hèia, dhèu èmu Yahuda madhe. Na j'èra toke d'ai pa'èle lod'o sasusa na.<bt>After awhile (suggests long time), Yahuda's wife died. He suffered through the end of his time of mourning.</bt><note reference="38:12" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu ad'a rèngu, ladhe dhèu èmu ra madhe, rèngu bisa boe kalua èmu, dènge pake mèdha-papake susa. Toke d'ai pèri-pèri hèru.<bt>Following their /adat/, when a wife died they could not go out of the house, and they wore grieving clothes. They did this for several months.</bt></note>Ka na la'e gale nare angalai na Hira, ka lasi asa rae Timna. Ètu èèna, dhèu rame-rame g'ute rèu kahib'i-kalèbho ho pahia.<bt>And he went and summoned his friend Hira, and they went to/toward the village of Timna. At that place, people were festively shearing/scissoring the hari/fur of goat-sheep to sell.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Batshua: might have been her name"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">Batshua: might have been her name vayirbu (rbh): became many<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>vayinachem (nchm): observe the rites of mourning, was comforted gozzi: shearing<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>reʕehu: his friend</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Dhèu lolo dènge Tamar, peka na, &lt;&lt;To'o mu la'e leru dhèu g'ute rèu kahib'i-kalèbho ètu rae Timna.&gt;&gt;<bt>People/Person told Tamar, saying, &lt;&lt;Your MB/F-in-law is is going to check out people scissoring the hari of goat-sheep in the village of Timna.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ii-iiyala = rame-rame"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">ii-iiyala = rame-rame</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayugad (ngd pass): it was announced"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayugad (ngd pass): it was announced to Tamar hineh: in a quotation, it's a here and now event, not something presented from the speaker's specific point of view within a narrative.<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>lagor (grr inf): shear wool. The Sheep Shearing Festival was a big deal, with lots of wine and festivities. In 1 Samuel 25, David in the Negev hears about Nabal shearing sheep in Carmel, so he sends and hits him up for a reward for having protected his flocks -- which he had done. Abigail takes a large quantity of food that was prepared for the doings and transports it to David. In 2 Samuel 13, Absalom uses the sheep shearing as a pretext for getting one of his brothers drunk, then having him assassinated.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Lod'o èèna, ana limuri Yahuda, ngara na Sela, kapai le. Te ngaa Tamar ne'a le, na, to'o na no'o boe paleo Sela dènge ne. Nèti èèna ka, Tamar tenge j'ara neo katèju hak nèngu. Na bhoke eele mèdha-papake bhèni balu ètu ngi'u na, ka na silu mèdha-papake dhu be'a. Na pake salalu pahutu kètu dènge rèhu na. Ka la'e madhèdi ètu hèb'a tedhe sebhe j'ara rae Enaim, dhu biasa dhèu kako re èèna lasi rae Timna.<bt>Then, Yahuda's youngest child, whose name was Sela, was already big. But Tamar already knew that her F-in-law did not want to marry Sela to her. Because of that, Tamar looked for a way to claim (&lt; pull toward self) her rights. She took off her widow's clothes, and she put on good clothes. She wore a salendang (sash) covering her head and face. And she went and sat at the fence gate on the side of the road (to) the village of Enaim, which people normally went on going to the village of Timna.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatasar (swr hif impf): take off"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vatasar (swr hif impf): take off clothes beged: garments of a particular kind<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʔalmnutah: widowhood meʕaleyah: from her<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>vatkhas (ksh piʕel): covered, concealed. Reflexive use of piʕel "to disguise herself" is rare; hitpaʕel is more likely. batsaʕif: in a wrapper, shawl<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>titʕalaf (ʕlf hitp): wrapped herself up, veiled herself bpetach: at the entrance<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʕenaim: Enaim, two eyes, two wells; fork in the road? open place, crossroads? village name, Two Waterholes? petach ʕenaim, the opening of the eyes? the entrance to Enaim? ʕal-derek timnatah: overlooking the road to Timnath. Timnath may be a play on "conceal."<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>loʔ-nitnah lo lʔishah (nif): the she was not given to Shelah as his wife. Up to this point Tamar is acted upon; from here she acts on her own.</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Ropa Yahuda kako re èèna, na ladhe nèdhi dhèu bhèni èci madhèdi ètu èèna. Na neo laa na dhèu bhèni kajeo, te Tamar dhu lalau iisi dènge mèdha-papake saraga, aa pahutu rèhu na kahèi.<bt>When Yahuda was going by there, he saw a woman sitting there. He assumed she was a whore/prostitute, cuz Tamar had fixed herself up with beautiful clothes, and also covered her face.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayachshveah l-: he thought her to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayachshveah l-: he thought her to be a prostitute, considered. see ... conclude zonah: ordinary prostitute, not one associated with a Canaanite temple (v. 21)<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>khistah (ksh piʕel): she concealed, covered</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Yahuda ne'a nare boe na dhèu bhèni na, dhèu èmu ana na dhu madhe sèra. Hèia na kako la'e padètu dènge bhèni deo na ka, na peka dènge ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ee! Sèmi ja'a dènge èu na, èu manèngi ca ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Yahuda did not know that the woman was the spouse of his children who had died. Then he walked over approaching that aforementioned woman, and spoke to her, saying, &lt;&lt;Ee! If I with you, what do you request?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katèju = memaksakan, pull towards self"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">katèju = memaksakan, pull towards self while feet planted firmly ; silu = wear, put on (clothes), ganti ; salalu = selendang (kuno); 15: neo laa = kira, sangka ; dhèu bhèni kajeo = perempuan nakal, semacam pelacur; lalao iisi</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayet (nth): he turned aside from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayet (nth): he turned aside from his road havah-naʔ (hb, yhb impv): give; come on, now. Rashi takes this as an entreaty. But's it propositioning a prostitute: Hey, come on, let's have sex!<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Tamar dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èèna nèti d'ara d'èi ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Tamar responded, saying, &lt;&lt;That's up to you, father.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Aku Yahuda na, &lt;&lt;Sa mia! Sèmi ja'a hia èu kahib'i ci'u?&gt;&gt;<bt>Said Yahuda, &lt;&lt;How about it? If I give you a goat?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Tamar dhaa hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Bisa ama. Sad'i ama hia ku ja'a mèdha èci ho ja'a kèd'u. Pe pèri lod'o ho ama pa'adhu kahib'i èèna mai oo, ngaa-ngaa tao boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Tamar responded again, saying, &lt;&lt;You can, father. As long as you give me something for me to hold. Later, whenever you send that goat here, then it won't matter.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pee"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">pee</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeshalach: I will send gdi ʕizim"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔeshalach: I will send gdi ʕizim (gadah): a kid from the flock (not definite; in verse 20 he's chosen the kid, and it's definite)<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>Alter, The Art of Biblical Narrative, 1981 ʔim-titen (ntn imperf): if you give<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʕeravon: a security, pledge (like leaving your driver's license at the library desk), something you get back when you finish the deal. Alter: like giving her all his major credit cards. ʕad-shalchekha (shlk inf): until you send it<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18-19" />Hèia Yahuda karèi hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;De ja'a tèka mèdha ngaa mi èu?&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yahuda asked again, saying, &lt;&lt;So, what thing should I hand over to you?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Tamar dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama tèke eele cap, dènge dhari dhu ama inu, dènge tatea dhu ama kèpe èèna hèi.&gt;&gt; Nanene nare ka, Yahuda hia mèdha sèra la'e.<bt>Tamar answered, saying, &lt;&lt;You should leave behind the cap with the rope/cord/string around your neck, and the the walking staff you are holding as well.&gt;&gt; Hearing that, Yahuda gave those things over.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chotamkha: your signet ring. Many commentators"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">chotamkha: your signet ring. Many commentators take this to be a cylinder seal with a cord going through the axis; but that's more Mesopotamian, for clay tablets, and flat seals were more common in Palestine. ftilekha (patil): the cord you use to tie the ring around your neck, like a modern ID tag or a house key. Targums read it as ʔcloakʔ.<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>matkha (mateh): your walking stick vatahar lo: she became pregnant by him. Providential timing (36 hour period during the month)? or smart planning? Everything else is pretty well worked out in advance.<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia dua ra lasi bhèj'i ka. Èle èèna ka, Tamar lèpa la'e èmu. D'ai èmu ka, na bhoke mèdha-papake saraga dènge salalu, ka gati dènge mèdha-papake bhèni balu. Nèti èèna ka, Tamar dènge babia.<bt>Then the two of them went and slept. After that, Tamar went back to her house. Arriving at her house, she took off her beautiful clothes, and the sash, and changed back into her widow's clothes. Because of (all) that, Tamar was pregnant.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsʕifah: the wrapper, veil tilbash: she"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tsʕifah: the wrapper, veil tilbash: she put on<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Nèbhu boe hèia, Yahuda manèngi tolong angalai na Hira, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu mèti kahib'i ne'e hia dhèu bhèni kajeo dhu ètu Enaim èèna, ho mèti hari mèdha ja'a dhu ètu nèngu sèra.&gt;&gt; Lod'o Hira la'e d'ai nèi, na karèi palème, te ngaa paraga boe dènge bhèni èèna.<bt>Not long after that, Yahuda asked for the help of his friend Hira, saying, &lt;&lt;You take this goat and give it to that whore/prostitute who was at Enaim, to get back my things which she has.&gt;&gt; When Hira went arriving yonder, he asked around, but did not encounter that woman.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="reʕehu: his friend. Sounds like Judah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">reʕehu: his friend. Sounds like Judah is playing the big man at the shearing party, canʔt be bothered to go look up a prostitute himself.</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ka na karèi dhèu-dhèu ètu sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Eee! Miu mèdhi dhèu bhèni kajeo dhu biasa madhèdi ètu hèb'a tedhe èèna, do? Na ètu mia, ee?&gt;&gt;<bt>And he asked various people there, saying, &lt;&lt;Eee! Have you seen that whore/prostitute who normall sits at the fence gate there, huh? Where is she, ee?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dhèu sèra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama, ètu ne'e bhèni kajeo aad'o!&gt;&gt;<bt>Those people responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Father, here there is no whore/prostitute!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu bhèni sudha &lt; sundal (kurang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">dhèu bhèni sudha &lt; sundal (kurang pake)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishʔal: ask maqomah: used more of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yishʔal: ask maqomah: used more of towns than of the place along the road where Tamar was sitting. There probably werenʔt people hanging around out there.<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ʔayeh: where? haqdeshah: consecrated woman, cult prostitute, shrine prostitute. May be Spec(zonah). One strong idea in the Canaanite religion was that having sex was a way of worshipping the Canaanite gods of fertility, and so there were both male and female prostitutes connected with the centers of worship. The fees paid to them may have supported the centers as well as the prostitutes themselves<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Hèia Hira lèpa hari peka dènge Yahuda, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a paraga boe dènge bhèni èèna. Ja'a tenge palème, te ngaa dhèu ètu sèra peka aku rèngu na, ètu rae èèna bhèni kajeo aad'o.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Hira went back and told Yahuda, saying, &lt;&lt;I did not find that woman. I looked all over, but the people there told me that in that village there is no whore/prostitute.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Yahuda dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hud'i ka la, nèngu abhu mèdha sèra! Sad'i dhèu baku pamakae èdhi! Ja'a neo b'ae, te ngaa èdhi paraga boe dènge bhèni èèna na.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yahuda responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Let it be, she can have those things! As long as people don't make us-inc ashamed/embarrassed! I wanted to do good, but we couldn't find that woman.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pen nihyeh labuz: lest we become"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">pen nihyeh labuz: lest we become a laughingstock (many commentators, even Holladay's lexicon). But buz is normally contempt, derision, disgrace. That is more likely here too; Judah's personal prestige could take a nosedive if the word gets around that he welshed on paying a prostitute. So he's not going to push the point any further -- easier to get a new seal.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ropa d'ai tèlu hèru hèia, dhèu lasi lolo dènge Yahuda, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu èmu ana èu na tao ngi'u na sèmi dhèu bhèni kajeo. Ka na dènge babia le.&gt;&gt;<bt>When three months had gone, people came and told Yahuda, saying, &lt;&lt;The spouse of your child has made herself like a whore/prostitute. And she is already pregnant.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Nanene nare èèna hèia, Yahuda nasa bia. Hèia na pua dhèu, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lami nuni pa'oro ne mai, ho labhu asa d'ara ai la'e!&gt;&gt;<bt>Upon hearing that, Yahuda was very angry. Then he ordered people, saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl go drag her back here, to burn her up in fire!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="labhu = burn (big fire, appropriate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">labhu = burn (big fire, appropriate for anger) ; tunu = bake, roast (controlled fire)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chdashim: lunar cycles, months zantah: she"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">chdashim: lunar cycles, months zantah: she played the prostitute. The only actual offense here is against Er; Tamar is thought to have had sex with a stranger, rather than with Shelah, who was supposed to perpetuate Er's line. For that matter, Judah is not taking very good care of his own lineage. That's why Tamar comes through as "more righteous".<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>kalatekha: your daughter-in-law hotsiʔuah (ytsʔ hif): produce her, make her come<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>tisaref (nif): she shall be burned up. Two words, short and brutal, no investigation whether the charge is true. Gets Judah off the hook. Stoning was the only option under the Law, but things were not as constrained four centuries earlier.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ka dhèu lasi ka nuni rèti Tamar mai. Te ngaa na pad'elo cap dènge tatea èèna. Ka na pua dhèu lasi peka dènge to'o na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Parisa ku mèdha se'e. Dhèu dhu unu cap dènge tatea ne'e ka dhu ad'u-ue tatao ne'e, ka ja'a dènge babia ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>And the people went and dragged her back. But she showed the cap and the walking staff. And she ordered the people to tell her F-in-law, saying, &lt;&lt;Examine these things now. The person who owns the cap and this walking staff, is the one who has done this deed, and made me pregnant.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mutseʔt (hof particpl): as she was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">mutseʔt (hof particpl): as she was being led out. Going public was her only protection; if she had taken it up with Jacob privately, he might have killed her quietly. Sounds like she had her contingencies pretty well figured out, since she let it go this far. Since she was under Judah's control, they would have waited for him to come before killing her. shalchah: she sent (word? writing?)<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>chamiah: her father-in-law haker-naʔ (nkr hif): investigate as unknown, establish judicially (just as in Chapter 37; now the con that Judah started about Joseph comes back and bites Judah)<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>lmi: who do they belong to? hachotemet: seal, chop, signet ring<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ropa nèdhi mèdha se'e, Yahuda tadhe dènge, na mèdha sèra unu nèngu. Hèia na padhai lii dènge ka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mema dhèu bhèni ne'e sala boe. Ja'a ka dhu sala. Madhutu iia na, ja'a ka dhu paleo bhèni ne'e dènge ana ja'a Sela. Te ngaa ja'a ka ko'o boe.&gt;&gt; Karèi nèti èèna ka, Yahuda pa'èci heka dènge Tamar.<bt>Seeing these things, Yahuda recognised immediately, that those things belonged to him. So he spoke straight-away, saying, &lt;&lt;It is true that this woman is not wrong. I am the one who is wrong. In actual fact, I should have married this woman to my child Sela. But I did not want to.&gt;&gt; Beginning from then, Yahuda no longer joined/united with Tamar.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Madhutu iia na, = yang sebenarnya"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">Madhutu iia na, = yang sebenarnya</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaker (nkr hif): recognized, acknowledged. He"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yaker (nkr hif): recognized, acknowledged. He also has to think of the hereditary promises to his lineage. (promises to genes, JR) ki-ʕal-ken: a reason, long in existence, is finally recognized. At the crunch point, Judah digs down deep.<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />D'ai hèru ka Tamar nara iisi ana dhèu dua.<bt>When the time/month arrived for Tamar to give birth, she bore two children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lidtah (yld inf): for her to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">lidtah (yld inf): for her to give birth tʔomim = toʔmim: twins<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>bbitnahh: in her womb</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Lod'o Tamar nara iisi na, kabèdhi laa ana èci pacèu uuru kacui-aai èci sa li'u mai. Ka dhèu ai tadha dhu panara iisi na nare loa hèngu mea, ka èki mi kanau riti na. Bhèni na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ana uuru ka ne'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>While she was giving birth, suddenly one of the children stuck out his hand first. And the healer/midwife who was helping give birth took a red thread, and tied it to the wrist. The woman spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;This is the oldest/first child.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tiqach: she took it myaledet (yld"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tiqach: she took it myaledet (yld piʕel partcpl): the one helping her have the baby<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>vatiqshor: tied shani: crimson, scarlet; a vivid dye obtained from eggs of the shield-louse, collected on leaves of oak trees; crimson thread<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>yatsaʔ: came out riʔshonah: the first in a series<span class="Italic">(28)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Te ngaa ana èèna ère hari kacui-aai na sa d'ara. Hèia, ana èci na kalua uuru hari. Nèdhi sèmi èèna hèia, bhèni ai tadha èèna peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Waa! Èu èra titu kèna! Nèti èèna ka, èu paseti ho kalua uuru sa li'u.&gt;&gt; Bhèni na pangare ne, <span class="Italic">Peres,</span> (dhu sasoa na, &lt;paseti sa li'u&gt;).<bt>But that child pulled his hand back inside. Then the other child came out first. Seeing that happen, the midwife spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Waa! You are really strong! Therefore, you forced your way out first.&gt;&gt; That woman named him, <span class="Italic">Peres,</span> (which means &lt;force out&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meshiv (shwb hif partcpl): as he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">meshiv (shwb hif partcpl): as he was bringing his hand back in paratsta: you broke out<span class="Italic">(29)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Èle èèna ka, dhu èki dènge loa hèngu mea deo na kalua. Ra pangare ne <span class="Italic">Sera</span> (sasoa na &lt;mea gèu-gèu&gt;).<bt>After that, the one with the red thread tied on came out. they named him <span class="Italic">Sera</span> (which means &lt;bright red/scarlet&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu ai tadha = dukun, healer"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">dhèu ai tadha = dukun, healer ; hèngu = kapas ; loa hèngu = benang (kapas) ; kanau = 1) wrist, pergelangan, 2) bracelet, gelang ; kanau riti = wrist ; riti = kuningan, copper ; tabaga = tembaga; 30: heo lo'a-lo'a = bersinar terang ; mea gèu-gèu = merah manyala; 30: Kata "na" mempunyai beberapa arti : na ( ne ) = dia / nya ; na = singkatan dari èna ; na = jadi ( na, èu lamu kèna do? ).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zarach: the shining forth of light,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">zarach: the shining forth of light, sunrise, blast of light</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf dènge dhèu èmu Potifar<bt>Yusuf and the wife of Potifar</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="39" />
      <v n="1-2" />Dhèu Ismael sèra rèti Yusuf d'ai Masir, hèia ra pahie eele ne dènge dhèu kapai èci ètu nèi, ngara na Potifar. Dhèu ne'e komedhaa sordad'u dhu j'aga ètu dhèu aae Masir. Yusuf j'aj'i ènu ètu èmu Potifar. Ètu èèna, LAMATUA dènge Yusuf, ka sasab'a ngaa dhu na tao, nèti babe'a hua-hua.<bt>The people of Ismael brought Yusuf arriving at Masir, and then they sold off him to an important person there, named Potifar. This person was a commander of the soldiers (loan) who guard the king of Masir. Yusuf became a slave in the house of Potifar.There, the LORD was with Yusuf, and whatever work he did, succeeded well (bore good fruit).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hurad (yrd hofʕal): be brought down"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hurad (yrd hofʕal): be brought down SəriS: court official, eunuch (not in this case)<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>sar: outside Israel, a representative of the king, official, ruler, leader of a group Tabbachim: bodyguards and executioners, slaughterers<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>howriduhuw: they brought him down matsliach (tslch partcpl): successful man<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Dhèu kapai ne'e ladhe-ladhe na, sasab'a Yusuf nèti babe'a hua, ka na ngee ètu d'ara na, LAMATUA tare'a-re'a dènge Yusuf.<bt>This important person was seeing that Yusuf's work was succeeding well, and he thought to himself that the LORD was truly with Yusuf.</bt><v n="4" />Nèti èèna ka, komedhaa ne'e d'èi Yusuf, ka na lèka ne. Hèia na ded'e ne j'aj'i madho ètu èmu na. Aa, na hia ne paredha d'ara èmu nèngu, sèmi èèna kahèi, mèdha-panyau na aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Because of that, this commander liked Yusuf, and trusted him. So he elevated him to be supervisor (assim. loan) in his house. And he gave him command/authority throughout his house, and also over all his wealth/possessions.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yimtsaʔ: found, got chen: agreeableness, charm,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yimtsaʔ: found, got chen: agreeableness, charm, approval, satisfaction<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ysharet: became an attendant, serve yafqidehu (pqd hif): he appointed him<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Lula Yusuf pea ètu èèna, ka Lamatua hia mamuri hua iia mi lamatua èmu, dhèu Masir èèna. Isi èmu na, mèdha-panyau na, oka-tedhe na, aa sasab'a-la'a na, j'aj'i dènge be'a.<bt>Because Yusuf stayed there, the Lord gave the blessings of life to the master of the house, that Masir person. His household, his possessions, his fields, and his work, all happened well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hifqiyd (pqd hif): he appointed yvarekh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hifqiyd (pqd hif): he appointed yvarekh (brkh piel): bless = declare someone endowed power for success, prosperity, fertility<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>biglal: on account of sadeh: fields<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Lula Potifar ladhe-ladhe la'a na Yusuf sab'a dènge be'a, ka na pangee heka ngaa-ngaa, dhoka na'a-ninu di.<bt>Because Potifar kept seeing that Yusuf worked well, he didn't think/worry any more about anything, only just food-drink.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madho = mandor; 5: mèdha-panyyau ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">madho = mandor; 5: mèdha-panyyau = harta benda</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaʕazov: he let go məʔuwmah: something|i(6)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yaʕazov: he let go məʔuwmah: something<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>loʔ-yadaʕ ʔitto: he did not keep account with him kiy ʔim-hallechem: not even the food<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Yusuf ne, mone iia.<bt>Now Yusuf was handsome (&lt;male pretty).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yafeh: good looking, beautiful toʔar: form,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yafeh: good looking, beautiful toʔar: form, shape (woman, cow, olive tree); for a man, appearance, dignity, impressive<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>marʔeh: nice to look at, appearance</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Na pea ètu èèna nèbhu mèka. Te ngaa dhèu èmu Potifar na, d'èi Yusuf. Ka na mai pamako ne ho dua ra j'unu pa'èci.<bt>He had not lived there very long. But Potifar's wife, liked Yusuf. And she came (trying to) persuade him so the two of them would sleep together.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="saraga = gaga sadhoo = ganteng"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">saraga = gaga sadhoo = ganteng ; ngi'u sadhoo be'a ; mone iia = handsome ; bhèni iia = cantik ; sadhoo = tinggi; 7: pamako = bujuk bèli - bèli = tiap hari bèli = besok</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tishshaʔ (nsʔ): lift up her eyes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tishshaʔ (nsʔ): lift up her eyes at shikhvah: lie down with me, sleep with me<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa Yusuf no'o boe. Ka na peka sèmi ne'e ka, &lt;&lt;Baku ina ee! Ja'a ne, ènu Potifar, dhu na pangèd'u le koasa ho ja'a tao ai-hèb'a mi sasab'a nèngu aa'i-aa'i.<bt>But Yusuf did not want to. And he said, &lt;&lt;Don't do this, mother! I am the slave/servant of Potifar, who has entrusted to me power/authority for me to do manage all of his work/affairs.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ymaʔen: he refused hen: 3sg pronoun,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ymaʔen: he refused hen: 3sg pronoun, emphatic here<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ètu d'ara èmu ne'e, abhu boe dhèu èci sa dhu koasa risi nèti ja'a. Aa'i-aa'i dhu ètu d'ara èmu ne'e, na saraka mi kacui-aai ja'a. Dhodhoka ina ku di, aad'o. Tasamia ka, ja'a bisa tao j'ara karehe ne'e. Èèna lèke boe dènge dad'èi Ama Lamatua!&gt;&gt;<bt>In this house, there is nobody whose power/authority is greater than mine. Everything in this house he has turned over into my hands [not Hebraism]. Only mother only, not. How could I do this evil thing. That does not match the will/desires of Father God!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dadugu = bujukan / rayuan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">dadugu = bujukan / rayuan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeynenu: nobody loʔ-chasakh: and he does"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔeynenu: nobody loʔ-chasakh: and he does not hold back<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>ʔeykh: how? chaTaʔti leʔəlohiym: I do something morally wrong against God<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00716c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around:horizontalPosition:left">Dhèu èmu Potifar rarange taruu Yusuf<bt>Potifar's wife flirts continually at Yusuf</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Masi ka sèmi èèna, dhèu èmu Potifar ne pakaseti taruu bèli-bèli. Te ngaa Yusuf ne tao boe madha-dhilu dènge ne.<bt>Even that being the case, Potifar's wife continued to force/pressure every day. But Yusuf did not pay attention to her (Idiom: did not eye-ear her).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rarange = bujuk, rayu = solo-mako"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">rarange = bujuk, rayu = solo-mako (Ndao) ; solo = topi ; mako = lembut paka seti = paksa ; ai hèba-madha dhilu = perhatian *</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔetslah: by her"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔetslah: by her</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ca tèka, Yusuf kako la'e asa d'ara èmu, ho sab'a sasab'a nèngu. Lod'o èèna, dhèu leo aad'o èci sa ètu èmu.<bt>One time, Yusuf went into the house, to do his work. That day, there was nobody else in the house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mlaʔkhto: his business"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">mlaʔkhto: his business</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ka dhèu èmu Potifar na raga mai ka, na kèpe kodho Yusuf, ka na ère ne, hèia na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mai! Ata dhodhoka èdhi dua ti. De mai ho ti j'unu.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Potifar's wife came and found/encountered him, and grabbed Yusuf's shirt, and pulled him, then spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Come! There are only the two of us-inc. So let's go sleep together.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa Yusuf d'èi boe. Ka na parui, hèia kodho na bhoke eele nèti ua na, ka na rai asa li'u. Aa kodho deo na ètu kacui-aai bhèni èèna era.<bt>But Yusuf didn't want to. And he rebelled, so his shirt came off/undone from his body, and he ran outside. And that aformentioned shirt remained in the hands of that woman.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raga = maju ; ata ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">raga = maju ; ata = tinggal</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="titpsehu: she took hold of (thing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">titpsehu: she took hold of (thing or person) bbigdo: by his clothes (any kind of clothes)<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>yanaS (nwS): he fled hachutsah: outside<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ropa dhèu èmu Potifar ladhe laa, na, Yusuf rai li'u le la'e, aa kodho na tèke eele,<bt>When Potifar's wife saw that Yusuf had run away, and left his shirt behind,</bt><v n="14-15" />hèia na paroa dhèu sab'a sèra, ka na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;We! Miu mai ladhe ku laa! Deo na, ana mone dhèu Ibrani na, maso sa d'ara kama ja'a. Na neo pamakae ja'a. Malo ka ja'a pa'oo, ka na rai, tèke eele kodho na ètu ja'a ne. Dhèu èmu ja'a ne, nèti dhèu bhelu asa d'ara èmu, ho hia èdhi ta'e makae!&gt;&gt;<bt>then she summoned the workers, and she spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;We! You come and have a look here! Just now, that Ibrani man came into my room. He wanted to do shameful things to me. Fortunately I shouted out, and he ran, leaving behind his shirt with me here. My spouse has brought this evil person into the house to shame us-inc!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="malo = ontong"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">malo = ontong</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsacheq (piʕel inf): to mock us"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tsacheq (piʕel inf): to mock us həriymotiy (rwm hif): I raised my voice<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00720c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around:horizontalPosition:left">Dhèu èmu Potifar pad'elo kodho Yusuf<bt>Potifar's wife shows Yusuf's shirt/clothes</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Bhèni na kèpe pa'ère kodho èèna, toke d'ai dhèu èmu na lèpa.<bt>The woman held onto that shirt until her spouse came home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tannach (nwch hif): she laid it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tannach (nwch hif): she laid it down</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ropa dhèu èmu na nare d'ara èmu, na lolo peka na, &lt;&lt;A'a! Dhèu Ibrani dhu mèti mai sa èmu ne'e, deo na maso asa d'ara kama ja'a, neo pakarehe ja'a!<bt>When her spouse entered the house, she told him, &lt;&lt;Older sibling! [Vocative of wife to husband] That Ibrani person you brought to this house, earlier came into my room, wanting to do evil to me!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ltsakheq: to play around, fondle, amuse"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ltsakheq: to play around, fondle, amuse himself, insult[?]</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Malo ka ja'a pa'oo, paroa ana sab'a se'e. Hèia na rai tèke eele kodho na, ka ne'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>Fortunately I shouted out, summoning these workers. Then he ran off leaving behind this shirt of his.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kahəriymiy (rwm hif): in lifting up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">kahəriymiy (rwm hif): in lifting up my voice</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Tadèngi nare lii lolo dhèu èmu na, Potifar nasa bia.<bt>Hearing the tale of his spouse, Potifar was furious.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yichar ʔappo: he got hot in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yichar ʔappo: he got hot in his anger</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Hèia na paredha ka dhèu lasi kèpe Yusuf. Ka ra pamaso asa d'ara bèdho dhèu aae.<bt>So he commanded people to go catch Yusuf. And they put him into the prison of the king.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Sohar: prison (Pidgin usually says &quot;jail&quot;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">Sohar: prison (Pidgin usually says "jail" unless youʔre a prisoner. ʔSwry: the ones bound. qereʔ ʔəSiyrey: prisoners of<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>ʔəSuwriym: the ones bound</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Te ngaa LAMATUA bhèlu boe Yusuf. Nèti èèna ka, LAMATUA ladhe-leru ne taruu, ka kapala ètu d'ara bèdho èèna, sue Yusuf ae titu kèna.<bt>But the LORD did not forget Yusuf. Because of thae, the LORD saw to his needs/looked after him continually, and the head of that prison, loved/liked Yusuf greatly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeT (nTh): extended (protection) khased: obligation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yeT (nTh): extended (protection) khased: obligation to the community based on a close relationship, faithfulness, loyalty; leads to protection; or extraordinary kindness even when he didnʔt have to<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>chinno: his favor, his kindly attitude</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Na lèka Yusuf, ka hia ne j'aj'i madho ho laladhe ana bèdho sèra aa'i-aa'i ra. Aa, hia na lalau sasab'a ètu èèna kahèi.<bt>He trusted Yusuf, and made him supervisor to look after all the prisoners. So he also responsibility for the work there.</bt><v n="23" />Lula lèka ne, ka kapala èmu bèdho na, tao heka ai-hèb'a mi ngaa-ngaa ètu d'ara bèdho èèna. LAMATUA ladhe-leru taruu Yusuf, nèti èèna ka, sasab'a ngaa ètu d'ara bèdho na kako dènge be'a.<bt>Because of that, the head of the prison was no longer concerned with (Idiom: no longer hand-mouth) anything in that prison. The LORD continued to look after Yusuf, and therefore whatever work was in that prison, he did it well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="matsliyach (tslch hif partcpl): the one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">matsliyach (tslch hif partcpl): the one causing him to prosper, making him a success End of S section.<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf peka sasoa lii nii, nèti ana bèdho dhèu dua<bt>Yusuf tells the meaning of a dream for two prisoners</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="40" />
      <v n="1-3" />Ètu d'ara bèdho èèna, abhu kahèi dhèu dua, dhu uru na j'aj'i kapala urusan ètu d'ara èmu dhèu aae Masir. Èci lalau dhua èi dhèu aae. Aa èci hari lalau roti dhèu aae. Dua ra tao pasala dhèu aae. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu aae nasa, ka na pamaso si asa d'ara bèdho. Dua ra pea ètu era èci dènge Yusuf.<bt>In that prison, there were also two people, who used to be managing heads (loan: ~department heads) in the house/palace of the king of Masir. One served/managed (palm)wine for the king. And the other served/managed bread (loan) for the king. The two of them had wronged/offended the king. Because of that, the king was angry, and he put them into the prison. The two of them stayed in the same place as Yusuf.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chaTəʔu: miss, be at fault, offend"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">chaTəʔu: miss, be at fault, offend in matters of morals, sin against somebody mashqeh: cupbearer<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>haʔofeh (partcpl): the one baking, the baker yiqtsof: he got angry<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>SariSayw: his court officials sar: head person<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>vayyitten (ntn impf): he put mishmar: guarding<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>Sohar: prison ʔaSuwr (ʔSr partcpl pass): was bound<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Kapala èmu bèdho na, paredha Yusuf lalau dhèu dua se'e. Ra ètu d'ara bèdho na, ele boe ca tèu do dua tèu le.<bt>The head of the prison ordered Yusuf to serve these two people. They were in that prison for one or two years.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="***"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">***</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yifqod: he commissioned, appointed, implies he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yifqod: he commissioned, appointed, implies he noticed Joseph and sought him out for this job yəsharet (piʕel): he was an attendant to them, served them<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Mèda ca lod'o ka, dua ra nii. Ca dhèu ka dènge nii na. Aa, lii nii dua sèra, èci-èci ka dènge sasoa na.<bt>One night, the two of them dreamed. Each person with his own dream. And the two dreams, each had its own meaning.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyakhalmu khlom: they had dreams fitron:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayyakhalmu khlom: they had dreams fitron: in the interpretation<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Bèli mad'ae èèna, Yusuf ladhe na dua ra rèhu susa.<bt>The follwoing day, Yusuf saw the two of them had distressed faces.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zoʕəfim: looked like a mess, wretched,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">zoʕəfim: looked like a mess, wretched, pitiful, ejected, embittered</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ka na karèi si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka mad'ae ne'e, miu dua mi roe-roe?&gt;&gt;<bt>So he asked them, saying, &lt;&lt;Why is it that today, the two of you have soft (fallen) faces?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rèhu mare boe = ganas ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">rèhu mare boe = ganas ; rèhu roe-roe = lemah tenang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="wayyishʔal: he asked them madduaʕ: why?|i(7)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">wayyishʔal: he asked them madduaʕ: why?<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>pneykhem raʕim: bad faces, out of sorts, feeling lousy, discontented</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Hèia ra dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mèda deo na, ji'i nii. Te ngaa ji'i nge'a boe sasoa na samia!&gt;&gt;<bt>So they responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Last night, we-exc dreamed. But we do not know what the meanings are!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yusuf peka dènge dua ra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne'e, èci sa re'a boe sasoa nii, dhodhoka Ama Lamatua di. De miu lolo ku laa. Pe èèna ho ja'a karèi sasoa nèti Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf spoke to the two of them saying, &lt;&lt;Of all the people on this earth, there is not one who knows the meanings of dreams, except only father God. So you tell me now. Later I will ask the meaning from the Lord.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="foter: one who can tell what"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">foter: one who can tell what they mean</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Hèia dhèu dhu lalau dhua èi hia dhèu aae èèna, lolo uuru peka na, &lt;&lt;Ètu d'ara nii, ja'a ladhe kèdhi aj'u anggor ca kapua.<bt>Then the person who served palmwine to the king, spoke first, saying, &lt;&lt;In the dream, I saw a grape (loan) vine/tree (not distinguished).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gefen: vine, creeping plant, grape vine"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">gefen: vine, creeping plant, grape vine</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Aj'u anggor ne dadana nèngu tèlu di. Aj'u na muri mai ka dènge rèu, hela, dènge hua giru-gari dhu madhasa.<bt>That grapevine had three branches. The tree grew up with leaves, flowers, and clusters of ripe fruit.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sarigim: branches of the grape vine."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">sarigim: branches of the grape vine. SK has grown grapes, but they turned out kind of sour. There are vineyards on Maui, in Ulupalakua, and there used to be some on Oʕahu, where Vineyard Street now runs through downtown Honolulu. kforakhat: budding<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>ʕaltah nitstsah: its blossoms came up hivshilu (bshl hif): they ripened<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>ʔashkloteha: its clusters ʕanavim: grapes<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Aa ja'a kèd'u galaa dhu dhèu aae biasa pake ninu. Ja'a puu hua anggor, ka pacèli èi sa d'ara galaa deo na. Hèia kèti asa dhèu aae, hia na ninu.&gt;&gt;<bt>And I was holding the drinking-glass (loan) which the king usually uses to drink. I picked grape (fruits), and squeezed the juice into that glass. Then I brought it to the king, for him to drink.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="giru-gari = cluster, rangkai (pinang, kelapa)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">giru-gari = cluster, rangkai (pinang, kelapa)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kowS: cup, wine cup ʔeqqakh (lqkh):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">kowS: cup, wine cup ʔeqqakh (lqkh): I took, grabbed hold, acquired<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʔeschaT: I squeezed kaf: palm, outstretched hand, open hand<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Tadèngi nare hèia, Yusuf peka dènge ne sèmi ne'e ka, &lt;&lt;Ama, ee. Sasoa nii na sèmi ne'e ka: dadana tèlu, sasoa na di tèlu lod'o ka.<bt>Hearing that, Yusuf spoke to him like this, &lt;&lt;Father, ee. The meaning of that dream is like this: the three branches, mean three days.</bt><v n="13" />Ètu d'ara tèlu lod'o ne, dhèu aae kalua eele ama nèti d'ara bèdho ne'e. Ho na hia hari, ama lalau dhua èi hia dhèu aae sèmi uru na.<bt>In three days now, the king will take you out from this prison. And he will give you back to serve palmwine to the king like before.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yissaʔ roʔshekha (nsʔ): lift your head,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yissaʔ roʔshekha (nsʔ): lift your head, raise high, pardon, accept kindly, be favorable to həshivkha (shwv hif): he will bring back, see that you get back, restore to office<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>kannekha: your place</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Ladhe ama abhu babe'a sèmi èèna, baku bhèlu ja'a, ee? Ladhe ama sue ja'a, peka dènge dhèu aae kalua eele ja'a nèti era ne'e.<bt>If/When you get goodness like that, don't forget me, ee? If you love me, tell the king to take me out of this place here.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="khased: obligation to the community, solidarity,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">khased: obligation to the community, solidarity, loyalty, faithfulness, kindness, grace hotseʔtani (ytsʔ hif): and you will cause me to go out<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Te ja'a ne, madhutu madha j'ara na dhu mola, rèngu se rare ja'a dènge laka-seti, nèti rae dhèu Ibrani. D'ai era ne'e, ja'a tao boe sasala ngaa èci sa. Te ngaa rèngu pamaso ja'a asa d'ara bèdho ne'e. Rèngu tao ja'a sèmi dhèu bhelu-katub'a sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz as for me, if we follow what is true, they brought me by force from the land of the Ibrani people. Arriving here, I have not done a single thing wrong. But they put me in this prison. They treat me like an evil person/criminal.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhelu - katuba = penjahat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">bhelu - katuba = penjahat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gunnov gunnavti: I have been stolen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">gunnov gunnavti: I have been stolen away məʔuwmah: something<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>samu (sym): they put me bor: cistern as in 37, dungeon<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ropa tadèngi nare sasoa nii ne'e be'a mi dedha angalai na, hèia dhèu èci dhu lalau roti na, lolo hari nii nèngu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ari Yusuf. Nii ja'a sèmi ne'e ka: ja'a tèd'u soe pagod'o-god'o tèlu.<bt>When he heard the good meaning of his friend's dream, the other person who serve the bread, told his dream, saying, &lt;&lt;Younger-sibling Yusuf. My dream is like this: I head-carried three layers of baskets.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Salley: baskets of choriy: cake, fancy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">Salley: baskets of choriy: cake, fancy bread<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ètu d'ara soe re dedha tèka na, pènu dènge koki dhèu aae, dhu rupa ae titu kèna. Te ngaa manu-bhui lela mai ka ra'e aa'i koki d'ara soe dhu ètu kètu ja'a na.&gt;&gt;<bt>In the top basket, it was full of all sorts baked goods (includes bread and cakes) for the king. But the birds flew in and ate up all the baked goods from the basket on my head.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tèd'u = jinjing pagodo = bersusun"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">tèd'u = jinjing pagodo = bersusun ; mola-mola = lurus, cocok dgn mimpi ; pagod'o-god'o = bersusun</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕelyown: the top one, upper one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʕelyown: the top one, upper one (also used of God, da one dat stay ova all da odda gods). Da Numba One God?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ropa Yusuf tadèngi nare, ka na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sasoa lii nii ama, sèmi ne'e ka: soe tèlu sèra, sama kahèi dènge tèlu lod'o.<bt>When Yusuf heard that, he responded, saying, &lt;&lt;The meaning of your dream is like this: those three baskets, are also like three days.</bt><v n="19" />D'ara tèlu lod'o ne, mu ladhe, te dhèu aae pua dhèu mai poro rare kètu èu. Ho èèna na, ra kadhoe ngi'u aae èu ètu agarii. Hèia manu-bhui tutu ra'e aa'i sisi èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>In three days, you will see, cuz the king will order people to come and cut off your head. So then they will hang your body/corpse on a pole. Then the birds will peck off your flesh.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tutu = toto"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">tutu = toto</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="talah: he will hang ʕets: tree,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">talah: he will hang ʕets: tree, piece of wood, pole<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ropa d'ai tèlu lod'o, dhu lèke dènge lod'o hari jadi dhèu aae, na tao tatao dhu kapai hia dhèu kapai na aa'i-aa'i sèra. Na paredha ho dhèu lasi kalua eele dhèu dua sèra nèti d'ara bèdho.<bt>In three days, it fell on the birthday of the king, and he made a great feast for all the important people. He commanded for people to go get those two people out of the prison.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yom hulledet (yld qal pass inf):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yom hulledet (yld qal pass inf): birthday mishteh: drinking party, feast<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ka na hia hari mone dhu lalau dhua èi na, sab'e sasab'a nèngu uru na.<bt>And he gave back to the man (can also mean: the official) who served his palmwine, to work his earlier work.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu lalau roti dhèu aae èèna, ra poro eele kètu na, ka ra kadhoe ngi'u na, sama sèmi ngaa dhu Yusuf peka dènge rèngu dua ra.<bt>But, the person who served bread to the king, they cut off his head, and they hung his body, just like what Yusuf had said to the two of them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kadhoe = gantung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">kadhoe = gantung</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Te ngaa mone dhu lalau dhua èi dhèu aae ne, sanèd'e heka Yusuf. Na bhèlu eele lii moa Yusuf.<bt>But the man/official who served palmwine to the king, did not remember Yusuf. He forgot his promise to Yusuf.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">End of P section</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf peka sasoa lii nii dhèu aae Masir<bt>Yusuf tells the meaning of the dream of the king of Masir</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="41" />
      <v n="1" />Pe d'ai dua tèu risi sa, hèia dhèu aae Masir nii. Na nii na, nèngu dhu titu ètu sebhe loko Nil.<bt>After two years had passed, the king of Masir had a dream. In his dream, he was standing on the edge of the Nil river.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miqqets shnatayim yamim: after two years"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">miqqets shnatayim yamim: after two years cholem: dreamed (as background to events)<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʕomed: was standing (background) yʔor: large river, the Nile River<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Kabèdhi laa, nèngu nèdhi sapi pidhu ngi'u dhu kabèb'u bia. Ka'uri ra kale'e. Ra kalua nèti d'ara loko, ka ra'a j'u'u ètu sebhe loko èèna.<bt>Suddenly, he saw seven cows with very fat/healthy bodies. Their skin was shiny (indication of health). They came out from the river, and they ate grass on the edge of that river.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabèb'u = gemuk ; kale'e ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">kabèb'u = gemuk ; kale'e = terang, mangkilat ; nèdhi = dia lihat mèdhi = 1. engkau / kamu lihat 2. hitam mèdhi kale'e = hitam pekat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕolot: they were coming up (background)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʕolot: they were coming up (background) parot: cows<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>yəfot: beautiful, right marʔeh (rʔh): (beautiful) in appearance<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>briʔot basar: fat in flesh; well fed, fat looking cattle tirʕeynah (rʕh impf): grazing<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>baʔachu: in among the reed-land. Possibly an Egyptian word for papyrus or another plant that grows by the Nile, Butomus umbellatus (UBS 125-126), reed grass or reed</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="hk-lb\lb00022c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:bottom" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Nèbhu boe, sapi pidhu ngi'u dhu leo hari, kalua nèti d'ara loko deo na. Ngi'u sapi sèra malaka-god'a. Ra titu padètu dènge sapi kabèb'u sèra.<bt>A little later, seven other cows came out from that river. The bodies of those cows were scrawny/gaunt. They stood near those fat cows.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔakherot: other raʕot marʔeh: ugly in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔakherot: other raʕot marʔeh: ugly in appearance, just the opposite of the others<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>daqqot basar: scanty of meat, skinny taʕmodnah: they were standing<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>ʔetsel: beside ʕal-sfat: on the bank of the river, edge<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Hèia sapi malaka pidhu ngi'u sèra, dhèle aa'i pidhu sapi dhu kabèb'u sèra. Hèia dhèu aae kabèdhi, ka na marèi dènge.<bt>Then the seven scrawny cows swallowed up the seven fat cows. Then the king woke up straightaway.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="malaka goda = sangat kurus; lawan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">malaka goda = sangat kurus; lawan kata kabèbu = gemuk*; 4: dhèle = telan cag'ag'a = terkejut ; marèi (1) = sadar, bangun dari tidur ; marèi masi (2) = evaporate salt from sea water, proses pembuatan garam, siram air di bedeng tembakau</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="toʔkhalnah: eat up, swallow down yiyqats:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">toʔkhalnah: eat up, swallow down yiyqats: wake up (intrans)<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Nèbhu boe ka, dhèu aae bhèj'i luu hari. Ka na nii hari ca tèka. Lii nii na sèmi ne'e ka: nèngu ladhe nèdhi are pidhu huri dhu isi pènu, bhodho nèti laa are dhu sub'u.<bt>A little later, the king went back to sleep. And he had another dream. The dream was like this: he saw seven ears/heads of grain full of grain, appearing from a fertile grain stem.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiyshan: he fell asleep shibbəlim: ears"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yiyshan: he fell asleep shibbəlim: ears of wheat, the spiky clusters that grow on top of the grass-like wheat stalk. The Egyptian variety produced three to seven spikes of wheat. The ones in the dream were healthy and big, heavy enough with ripe grain to make the stalk bend some<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>ʕolot (participle): growing up, coming up qaneh: stalk, main support<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>briʔot: the ears of wheat were fat and healthy, just like the cattle</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Èle èèna ka, nèdhi hari are pidhu huri dhu isi aad'o, aa dhu kamale dhae-dhae sène, lèke lai ngèlu dhu pana.<bt>After that, he looked again, (seeing) seven grain heads without grain, and they were horribly shrivelled, effected by the hot wind.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="daqqot: meager, skinny, stalks where the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">daqqot: meager, skinny, stalks where the wheat berries had not developed or were too small and dry to bother with, no nutritional value shəduwfot: scorched by the east wind from the Sinai, too hot and dry to grow<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>qadim: east side, east wind tsomchot: sprouting<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ka pidhu huri are dhu isi aad'o sèra, dhèle aa'i pidhu huri are dhu isi pènu deo sa. Hèia dhèu aae kabèdhi ka nèti bhèj'i. Heka nèngu ne'a kèna, nèngu dhu nii hari di.<bt>Then, the seven grain heads which had no grain, swallowed up those seven grain heads which were full of grain. Then the king suddenly awoke from his sleep. At that point he realised that he had dreamed again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhodho = muncul ; laa are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">bhodho = muncul ; laa are = batang padi sub'u (2) = subur; 6: kamale dhae-dhae = Max</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tivlaʕnah: they gulped down, swallowed whole"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tivlaʕnah: they gulped down, swallowed whole (used of the whale swallowing Jonah) məleʔot: full -- all the nutrition they could possibly hold<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>yiqats: came to an end, ended the night = woke up</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Mad'ae aae èèna, d'ara isi na be'a boe. Hèia, na paredha dhèu lasi paroa aa'i dhèu ai tadha dènge dhèu d'èlu-mèu, ètu rai Masir mai paraga dènge ne. Ka na lolo lii nii na sèra dènge si. Te ngaa dhèu èci sa bisa boe peka sasoa lii nii deo sa mi dhèu aae.<bt>The next morning, his insides were not good (felt upset). So he ordered people to go summon all the diviners and knowledgeable people in the land of Masir to come meet with the king. And he told his dream to them. But not one person could tell the meaning of those dreams to the king.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dèlu-mèu = clever"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">dèlu-mèu = clever</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tippaʕem rucho (nif): he was disturbed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tippaʕem rucho (nif): he was disturbed in his spirit, the natural spirit every person has that means he or she is alive vayishlakh: he sent a message<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>charTummey: soothsayer-priests of Egypt, they led the worship of the gods and they recognized signs of the future chakhameha: (the landʔs) wise men, skilled in wisdom<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>yəSapper (piʕel): he recounted, told the story powter (partcpl): explainer of dreams<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00723c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Dhèu sab'a dhu lalau dhua èi padhai lii dènge dhèu aae<bt>The worker who serves palmwine speaks to the king</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ka mone dhu lalau dhua èi dhèu aae èèna, heka sanèd'e nèdhi Yusuf kèna. Hèia la'e peka dènge dhèu aae, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ja'a mangaku sala.<bt>Then the man/official who served the king's palmwine, only-then remembered Yusuf. Then he went to speak to the king, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! I need to confess a wrong.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chətaʔay: my fault mazkir (zkr hif"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">chətaʔay: my fault mazkir (zkr hif participle): in mentioning, remembering<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Uru èèna, dhu ama ku nasa dènge ja'a, dènge angalai ku èci na, ka pamaso ji'i asa d'ara bèdho,<bt>Previously, when you were angry with me, and with my other friend, you put us into prison,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qatsaf: get angry with somebody ʔofiym:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">qatsaf: get angry with somebody ʔofiym: bakers<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />mèda ca lod'o ka, ji'i dua mi nii. Èci-èci ka dènge nii na. Aa sasoa nii se'e, sama boe kahèi.<bt>one night, the two of us dreamed. Each had his own dream. And the meaning of these dreams were also not the same.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kfitron: in interpretation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">kfitron: in interpretation</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ètu d'ara bèdho na, abhu ana mone Ibrani èci. Uru èèna, nèngu j'aj'i ènu nèti komedhaa j'aga dhèu aae. Ji'i lolo lii nii ji'i dènge ne, ka na peka sasoa lii nii sèra dènge ji'i.<bt>In that prison there was an Ibrani man. Previously he had been a servant/slave of the commander of the king's guards. We told our dreams to him, and he told us the meanings of our dreams.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔish: each one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔish: each one</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Nèti èèna ka, ama dhèu aae ded'e hari ja'a. Aa angalai ja'a na, abhu huku madhe. Se'e se j'aj'i sama sèmi ngaa dhu ana mone Ibrani na peka.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because of that, father king elevated me up again. And my friend got death punishment. These things happened just like what that Ibrani man had said.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="talah: he hanged"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">talah: he hanged</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Nanene nare lii ne'e hèia, dhèu aae pua dhèu lasi lai-lai rare Yusuf nèti d'ara bèdho mai. Ka Yusuf pamèu iisi na, aa na gati mèdha-papake na, ka na la'e paraga dènge dhèu aae.<bt>Hearing what he said, the king ordered people to go quickly to fetch Yusuf from the prison. And Yusuf cleaned himself up, and he changed his clothed, and he went to meet the king.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəriytsuhuw (rwts hif): they ran and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yəriytsuhuw (rwts hif): they ran and brought him ygallach: he shaved<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>yəchallef (piʕel): he changed simlotayw: mantle and under-wrapper<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Ropa na d'ai madha hèia, dhèu aae peka, &lt;&lt;Ja'a nii, te ngaa dhèu èci sa re'a boe sasoa lii nii sèra. Te ngaa dhèu peka na èu me'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>When he arrived in front, the king said, &lt;&lt;I dreamed, but there is not one person who can tell me the meaning of those dreams. But people say you know/are able.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karohe = cepat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">karohe = cepat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shamaʕti: I have heard"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">shamaʕti: I have heard</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Hèia Yusuf dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama dhèu aae. Ja'a èèna ka oo, ke'a boe ngaa-ngaa kahèi. Dhoka Ama Lamatua di dhu ne'a, ho Na peka sasoa lii nii sa, dènge lèke. Na neo peka lii dhu be'a mi ama dhèu aae.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Father king. I also do not know anything. Only Father God is the one who knows, so He will tell you the true meaning of those dreams. He wants to tell good things to you, father king.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bilʕaday: except for, with extension &quot;I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">bilʕaday: except for, with extension "I am not involved" yaʕneh (ʕnh nif): be provided with an answer<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Hèia dhèu aae lolo ka, lii nii sèra dènge ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ètu d'ara nii èèna, ja'a titu ètu sebhe loko Nil.<bt>Then the king narrated the dreams to him, saying, &lt;&lt;In the dream, I was standing on the edge of the Nil river.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sfat: bank of river, lip, edge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">sfat: bank of river, lip, edge yʔor: major river, flowing all the time<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ja'a ladhe la'a na sapi pidhu ngi'u dhu kabèb'u bia, dènge ka'uri dhu kale'e. Ra kalua nèti d'ara loko mai, ka ra'a j'u'u ètu sebhe loko èèna.<bt>I suddenly saw seven cows with fat bodies, and shiny skins. They came up out of the river, and ate grass at the edge of that river.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vifot toʔar: beautiful in form, nice"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vifot toʔar: beautiful in form, nice appearance tirʕenah (rʕh): grazed, pastured<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Hèia sapi pidhu ngi'u dhu leo mai hari. Rèngu se'e dhu malaka-god'a. Ètu rai Masir ne'e, ja'a kèdhi mèka sapi dhu malaka-god'a sèmi èèna!<bt>Then there were seven other cows who also came. These ones were scrawny/gaunt. In this land of Masir, I have never seen cows so scrawny like that!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dallot: scrawny, skinny raʕot toʔar: bad,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">dallot: scrawny, skinny raʕot toʔar: bad, ugly in appearance<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>raqqot basar: thin, lank in their meat roaʕ: bad quality (laughed)<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Dhu pamalaa ja'a, pidhu sapi dhu malaka-god'a sèra, kabèdhi laa dhèle aa'i pidhu sapi dhu kabèb'u se.<bt>What surprised me was the seven scrawny cows suddenly swallowed up those seven fat cows.</bt><v n="21" />Sapi dhu malaka sèra dhèle aa'i, te ngaa ngi'u ra malaka taruu sèmi èèna ka. Hèia ja'a kabèdhi dènge ka.<bt>When the scrawny cows had swallowed them up, they nevertheless continued staying scrawny like that. Then I woke up.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tavoʔnah: they entered ʔel-qirbenah: the inner"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tavoʔnah: they entered ʔel-qirbenah: the inner part of their body<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>nowdaʕ (ydʕ nif): become known marʔehen: their appearance<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>batəchillah: at the beginning</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Èle èèna ka, ja'a bhèj'i luu hari, ka nii hari ca tèka. Ja'a kèdhi pidhu huri are dhu isi pènu, kalua nèti laa are ca kapua dhu sub'u.<bt>After that, I went back to sleep, and had another dream. I saw seven heads of grain full of grain, come out from a single fertile stalk.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaʔereʔ (rʔh): I saw qaneh: one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vaʔereʔ (rʔh): I saw qaneh: one stalk<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>mleʔot: full of grain</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Èle èèna ka, ja'a kèdhi hari, pidhu huri are dhu isi aad'o, aa dhu kamale dhae-dhae, lèke lai ngèlu pana.<bt>After that, I saw again, seven grain heads without grain, and they were all withered up, affected by the hot wind.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsənumot: hard, barren daqqot: scanty, used"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tsənumot: hard, barren daqqot: scanty, used of hairs an beards of grain<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>shədufot: scorched by the wind tsomkhot: in sprouting<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Ka pidhu huri are dhu bèdhu sèra dhèle aa'i pidhu huri are dhu isi pènu sèra. Èle èèna ka, ja'a kèd'i nèti bhèj'i. Ka ja'a lolo lii nii se'e mi dhèu d'èlu-mèu se'e, te ngaa èci sa bisa boe peka sasoa lii nii sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>The seven grainheads which are blind (=empty) swallowed up the seven grainheads that were full of grain. After that, I awoke from sleep. And I narrated these dreams to these knowledgeable people, but not one could tell the meanings of those dreams.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="laa = batang; 23: kamale dhae-dhae"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">laa = batang; 23: kamale dhae-dhae = layu*; 24: bèdhu = buta*, tidak ada isi</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tivlaʕəna: they swallowed up charTummiym: soothsayer"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tivlaʕəna: they swallowed up charTummiym: soothsayer priests (v. 8)<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>maggid li (ngd participle): putting forward an opinion, solution, explanation</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00727c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Yusuf peka sasoa nèti lii nii dhèu aae<bt>Yusuf tells the meaning of the kings dream</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Hèia Yusuf padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama dhèu aae! Lii nii dua sèra, sasoa na dhoka èci di. Ama Lamatua peka le, mi ama dhèu aae, ngaa dhu Na neo tao.<bt>Then Yusuf spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Father king! Those two dreams, have only one meaning. Father God has foretold to the king, what He is going to do.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="higgid (ngd hif): announce, tell"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">higgid (ngd hif): announce, tell</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Sasoa na sèmi ne'e ka: pidhu sapi dhu kabèb'u, dènge pidhu huri are dhu isi pènu sèra, sasoa na, tèu dhu bècu-manèsa pidhu tèu. Sasoa ra dhoka èci di.<bt>Its meaning is like this: the seven fat cows, and the seven grainheads full of grain, their meaning is seven years of bounty/abundance (doublet). Their meanings are the same.</bt><v n="27" />Sèmi èèna kahèi, pidhu sapi dhu malaka-god'a, dènge pidhu huri are dhu isi aad'o, sasoa na, tèu manganga pidhu tèu.<bt>In the same way, the seven cows that are scrawny, and the seven grainheads with no grain, their meaning is seven years of famine/hunger.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bècu-manèsa = kelimpahan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">bècu-manèsa = kelimpahan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʕav: famine, hunger"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">raʕav: famine, hunger</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />De Lamatua dhu peka mema le, ngaa dhu Nèngu neo tao. Èèna sama kahèi, dènge ngaa dhu ja'a peka deo na.<bt>So, the Lord has foretold what He is going to do. That is the same as what I just said.</bt><v n="29" />Ladhe bèli-camèd'a, ètu rai Masir ne'e, d'ara pidhu tèu, èdhi abhu bècu-manèsa palème rae.<bt>In the future, in this land of Masir, for seven years we-inc will get bounty/abundance throughout the land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="savaʕ: be satiated, have plenty to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">savaʕ: be satiated, have plenty to eat</Message></Annotation><v n="30-31" />Èle èèna na, heka èdhi abhu manganga d'ara pidhu tèu. D'ara pidhu tèu na, manganga madèu aae. Toke èdhi abhu boe nganga'a calamusi sa, ètu dedha rai Masir ne'e. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i manganga ae titu kèna, ka ra bhèlu eele uru na dhu rèngu abhu le babècu pidhu tèu.<bt>After that, only-then will we get hunger/famine for seven years. During those seven years, the hunger/famine1 will be a great famine2. To-the-point that there will not be even a tiny bit of food in this land of Masir. Every person will have great hunger, and and they will completely forget the previous seven years of bounty.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nishkach (nif): be forgotten killah (klh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">nishkach (nif): be forgotten killah (klh piʕel): complete, finish; prepare; come to an end, cease; consume, waste; destroy; make to pine away<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>yiwwadaʕ (ydʕ nif): be known savaʕ: plenty<span class="Italic">(30)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />De ladhe ama dhèu aae abhu nii dua hari, sasoa na, Ama Lamatua ka dhu ator tèke. Nèbhu heka, ngaa dhu Na ator ne, j'aj'i kèna.<bt>So, if/since father king got the dream two times, it means that Father God has already established it. It will not be long before what He has arranged will happen/begin to happen.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ato = ator*"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">ato = ator*</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishshanot (shnh nif inf): be repeated"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hishshanot (shnh nif inf): be repeated paʕmayim (dual): two times<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>nakhon (kon nif): stable, secure, decided, agreed upon, reliable məmaher (piʕel participle): is hurrying<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Nèti èèna ka, ja'a manèngi sèmi ne'e: be'a risi ama dhèu aae tenge dhèu d'èlu-mèu èci, dhu bisa tao ai-hèb'a la'a dènge be'a. Aa ded'e ne, ho ladhe-leru kabarai ne'e dènge be'a.<bt>Therefore, I ask/suggest like this: it would be good for father king to look for a very clever/intelligent/capable person, who can manage (Idiom: do foot-mouth) well. And appoint him, to see-to-the-needs-of the populace well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʕattah: introducing a new thought or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vʕattah: introducing a new thought or section, now yereʔ (rʔh jus): let him look for, pick<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>navon (byn nif): be perceptive chakham: skilled, experienced, wise man (41:8)<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>yəshitehu (shyt): set him, appoint him; implies giving him the authority to act</Message></Annotation><v n="34" />D'ara pidhu tèu dhu bècu èèna, be'a risi ama dhèu aae ded'e hari dhèu, ho ra oru-pakaboko nganga'a dhu risi eele. Nganga'a dhu risi sèra, bagi mi lèmi ho tèke ca pala.<bt>During the seven years of bounty, it would be good for father king to appoint other people, to gather/collect (doublet) the excess food. That excess food, divide into five parts to save/store one part.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pəqidiym: officers yafqed: appoint|i(34) (34) |rchimmesh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">pəqidiym: officers yafqed: appoint<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>chimmesh (piʕel): levy a 20% tax</Message></Annotation><v n="35" />Ana kabarai ne'e, hud'i madhutu dènge be'a paredha ama dhèu aae, ho pakaboko are-are dhu risi eele, nèti rae-rae ètu rai Masir ne'e. Aa ra soli sa d'ara soka ho j'aga paie.<bt>This populace must follow/obey well the commands of the king, to collect the excess grain from the villages around this land of Masir. And they must pour/fill into the grainbins/grainhouses to guard it well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqbətsu: let them collect yitsbru-var: stack"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yiqbətsu: let them collect yitsbru-var: stack up<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>ʕariym: cities</Message></Annotation><v n="36" />Sèna ka pidhu tèu dhu manganga nèi mai te, èdhi dhu sadia le nganga'a. Dènge j'ara sèmi ne'e, èci sa madhe boe manganga.&gt;&gt;<bt>So that, when the seven years of hunger/famine come, we-inc have already prepared food. In this way, nobody will die of hunger.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="soka = lumbung; 36: ana kabarai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">soka = lumbung; 36: ana kabarai = penduduk ; isi rai = 1) angota masyarakat, rakyat, 2) hasil bumi, 3) isi + rai = fill soil into s.t. ; rai = 1) tanah, 2) lari, 3) ikat pagar bebak dgn tali /rai oka/</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="fiqqadown: deposit tihyeyna (fem): they will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">fiqqadown: deposit tihyeyna (fem): they will be<span class="Italic">(36) (36) </span>loʔ-tikkaret (krt nif): so that it will not be destroyed, ruined, consumed</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu aae ded'e Yusuf j'aj'i ai g'ana na ètu rai Masir<bt>The king appoints Yusuf to be his right hand (=assistant, rep) in the land of Masir</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Ropa tadèngi lii padhai lii Yusuf ne, dhèu aae dènge dhèu kapai sèra, sèmi ngaa dhu na peka dènge dhèu aae èèna.<bt>When he heard what Yusuf was saying, the king and the important people accepted what he had said to the king.</bt><v n="38" />Ka dhèu aae padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Roh Ama Lamatua hia le koasa mi Yusuf ne'e. Nèti èèna ka, èdhi abhu heka dhèu dhu risi nèti nèngu.&gt;&gt;<bt>So the king spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;The Spirit of God has given power/authority to Yusuf here. Therefore, we-inc have not yet found a person greater/more than him.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ai g'ana = wakil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">ai g'ana = wakil</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hanimsaʔ: meet by chance? find by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hanimsaʔ: meet by chance? find by searching?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu aae padhai lii dènge Yusuf, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua peka dènge èu, ngaa-ngaa se'e aa'i-aa'i. Nèti sèmi ne'e ka, heka ji'i nge'a kèna èu ne'e tare'a-re'a dhèu mèu. Aa mamèu èu ne, risi eele dhèu ètu mia-mia.<bt>After that, the king spoke to Yusuf, saying, &lt;&lt;God has told you all of these things. so noly now do we know the you are truly a wise/clever/knowledgeable person. And your knowledge/wisdom is greater than people everywhere.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="howdiyaʕ (hif): made known"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">howdiyaʕ (hif): made known</Message></Annotation><v n="40" />Nèti èèna ka, deo ne'e kahèi ja'a ded'e èu j'aj'i ai g'ana ja'a. Sèna ka èu j'aj'i dhèu kapai ètu d'ara èmu ja'a. Aa ana kabarai ja'a nanene lii paredha èu. Dhoka ja'a di dhu risi nèti èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Therefore, I now appoint you to be my right hand (=assistant, #2, rep). So that you will be the big person in my house. And my populace will listen to/obey your commands. Only I am greater than you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aka = hikmat/ akal (tipudaya)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">aka = hikmat/ akal (tipudaya)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕal-beytiy: over my house yishshaq (nshq):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʕal-beytiy: over my house yishshaq (nshq): put themselves in order, accomodate themselves<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>raq hakkisseʔ: only in regard to the throne am I greater than you</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41-42" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu aae puru eele kadheli dhu dènge cap nèti ai na, ka na pasaluu mi ai Yusuf. Ka na padhai lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dènge ne'e ne, ja'a ded'e èu, j'aj'i ai g'ana ja'a ètu rai Masir.&gt;&gt; Hèia na papake kodho madhera dhu milu èci mi Yusuf, aa na pa'inu rate hualaa cakoko mi ladha-goro na.<bt>After that, the king took off the ring with its cap from his finger, and he slipped in on Yusuf's finger. And he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;With this here, I appoint you to be my right hand in the land of Masir.&gt;&gt; Then he clothed a long shirt/clothes which is fine on Yusuf, and he hung a gold chain on his neck.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kadheli = cincin ; pasaluu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">kadheli = cincin ; pasaluu = slip on (ring) ; milu = rata, bersih, ; pa'inu = kalungkan ; hualaa = emas ladhagoro = leher ; cakoko</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaSar (nif): put away, take off"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yaSar (nif): put away, take off Tabbaʕto: his seal-ring<span class="Italic">(41) (41) </span>yalbesh (hif): caused him to wear shesh: Egyptian linen cloth<span class="Italic">(41) (41) </span>ravid: necklace zahav: gold<span class="Italic">(41) (41) </span>tsawwaʔro: his neck</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu aae hia hari Yusuf kareta ka dua nèngu. Ka na hia dhèu lasi uuru, ho pa'oo peka na, &lt;&lt;We! Patalele j'ara oo! Pahaha iisi mliu!<bt>After that, the king gave Yusuf his second cart (loan). And he had a person go ahead, and clall out saying, &lt;&lt;We! Make way oo! Show respect (lower yourselves)!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ai g'ana = wakil ; patalele"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">ai g'ana = wakil ; patalele = make way, don't block, jangan menghalangi</Message></Annotation><note reference="41:43" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Ibrani dhu asli, sasoa na bisa &lt;pacud'u&gt;, do &lt;pakabua&gt; kahèi.</note>Dhèu kapai neo re ne'e!&gt;&gt; Dènge j'ara ne'e, dhèu aae ded'e le Yusuf, j'aj'i ai g'ana na ètu rai Masir.<bt>A big person is about to pass by here!&gt;&gt; In this way, the king elevated/appointed Yusuf to be his right hand in the land of Masir.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />Hèia dhèu aae padhai lii dènge Yusuf, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Èu dhu me'a le ja'a ne dhèu aae. Te ngaa ja'a peka le dènge ana kabarai Masir aa'i-aa'i, peka na, ladhe èu hia boe ijin, rèngu bisa boe tao ngaa èci sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the king spoke to Yusuf, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this. You know that I am king. But I have told the entire populace of Masir, saying, if you have not given permission (assim. loan), they cannot do a single thing.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ladhe èu hia boe ijin ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">ladhe èu hia boe ijin =</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vilʕadeykha: without you yariym (rwm hif):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vilʕadeykha: without you yariym (rwm hif): cause to move: SK "Simon says!"<span class="Italic">(44)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00731c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Yusuf dènge dhèu èmu na<bt>Yusuf and his spouse</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Èle ka, dhèu aae pangare Yusuf madhutu ngara Masir, na <span class="Italic">Safnat Panea.</span> Aa, na hia Yusuf madhèdi dènge ana bhèni èci, ngara na Asnat. Ama dhèu èmu na, ngara na Potifera. Nèngu ne'e ka dhu j'aj'i ama agama ètu d'ara kota On.<bt>Then the king named Yusuf according to a Masir name, <span class="Italic">Safnat Panea.</span> And he had Yusuf sit with (=marry) a woman named Asnat. The father of his spouse was named Potifera. He was a *priest (&lt;father of religion) in the city of On.</bt><note reference="41:45" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ngara kota On madhutu lii Yunani, &lt;Heliopolis&gt;.<bt>The name of the city of On according to the Greek language is &lt;Heliopolis&gt;.</bt></note>Dènge j'ara ne'e, Yusuf j'aj'i dhèu kapai ètu rai Masir.<bt>In this way, Yusuf became a big/important person in the land of Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hia madhèdi = marry s.o. off,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">hia madhèdi = marry s.o. off, kawinkan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yetseʔ: came out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yetseʔ: came out</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />Lod'o na j'aj'i dhèu kapai ètu rai Masir, umur nèngu 30 (tèlu nguru) tèu le. Hèia na kako palème rai Masir.<bt>When he became a big person in the land of Masir, his age was already 30 years. Then he went throughout the land of Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕamdo (ʕmd inf): when he began"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʕamdo (ʕmd inf): when he began to serve</Message></Annotation><v n="47" />Ètu d'ara pidhu tèu dhu bècu-manèsa ne'e, oka-tedhe pènu dènge nganga'a.<bt>During the seven years of bounty/abundance, the fields (doublet) were full of food.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="liqmatsiym: produced by fistfuls"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">liqmatsiym: produced by fistfuls</Message></Annotation><v n="48" />Hèia Yusuf kaboko nganga'a dhu risi, ka na tèka paia si. Ètu era mia dhu na pakaboko nganga'a, ètu èèna kahèi na soli asa d'ara soka.<bt>So Yusuf gathered the excess food, and stored it carefully. In the places where he collected the food, he also filled/poured the grainhouses.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqbots: he collected, assembled towchah: its"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yiqbots: he collected, assembled towchah: its midst<span class="Italic">(48)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="49" />Are dhu pakaboko nare, ae titu kèna. Èci èèna ka, dènge salae ètu nebhe dhasi, ka dhèu uku rare heka.<bt>The grain which had been gathered, was huge (amount). It was much like sand at the edge of the sea, which people cannot count/measure.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gud'a = gudang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">gud'a = gudang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitsbor: he heaped up bar: grain|i(49)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yitsbor: he heaped up bar: grain<span class="Italic">(49) (49) </span>chowl: sand harbeh (rbh hif): he made it great<span class="Italic">(49) (49) </span>chadal: he ceased from an activity miSpar: number, count<span class="Italic">(49)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50" />D'ai mèka tèu manganga, dhèu èmu Yusuf, Asnat nara iisi le ana mone dhèu dua.<bt>Before the years/season of hunger/famine, Yusuf's spouse, Asnat gave birth to two sons.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bəTerem: before"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">bəTerem: before</Message></Annotation><v n="51" />Ka Yusuf padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua tao j'ara ne'e, sèna ka pabhèlu ja'a nèti j'aj'èra dhu lod'o ja'a kalua nèti d'ara èmu ama ku.&gt;&gt; Nèti èèna ka, ana uuru, na pangare ne <span class="Italic">Manase</span> (dhu sasoa na ele boe &lt;bhèlu&gt;).<bt>And Yusuf spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Father God has made a way for me so that I can forget my sufferings from when I came out from my father's house.&gt;&gt; That is why the oldest child, he named <span class="Italic">Manase</span> (which means something like &lt;forget&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nashshaniy (nshh piʕel): he made me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">nashshaniy (nshh piʕel): he made me forget ʕəmaliy: my heavy, wearisome labour; produce of labour; weariness, trouble, vexation; sin, wickedness<span class="Italic">(51)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="52" />Lod'o na abhu ana ka dua, na padhai lii hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a abhu j'aj'èra ae d'ai seli ètu era ne'e. Te ngaa sasue dènge ladhe-leru Ama Lamatua ka, ja'a abhu ana ètu ne'e.&gt;&gt; Ka na pangare ana ne'e <span class="Italic">Efraim.</span><bt>When he got the second child, he spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;I got great suffering in this place. But, by the love and care/attention of God, I have gotten this child.&gt;&gt; And he named this child <span class="Italic">Efraim.</span></bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hifraniy (prh hif): he made me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hifraniy (prh hif): he made me fruitful ʕanyiy: my misery<span class="Italic">(52)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="41:52" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ètu d'ara lii Ibrani, <span class="Italic">Efraim</span> sasoa na &lt;abhu ana&gt;, do &lt;rai hèu mèngi&gt;, do &lt;asa ae&gt;.<bt>In the Ibrani language <span class="Italic">Efraim</span> can mean &lt;get a child&gt; or &lt;fertile land&gt; or &lt;increase_number&gt;..</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="53" />Nèbhu boe ka, èle pidhu tèu dhu bècu-manèsa na.<bt>Not long after that (vague time), the seven years of bounty-abundance ended.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tikhleynah (fem): they finished"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tikhleynah (fem): they finished</Message></Annotation><v n="54" />Aa pidhu tèu manganga madèu d'ai kèna, sama sèmi dhu uru èèna Yusuf peka le. Ètu era leo, dhèu manganga le. Te ngaa rae-rae ètu Masir nganga'a ae era, lula ra pakaboko rare asa d'ara soka.<bt>And the seven years of hunger/famine1 famine2 arrived, just like Yusuf had said previously. In other places, people were already hungry. But the villages in Masir still had much food, because they had collected it in the grainhouses.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tichilleynah (chll hif): they began"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tichilleynah (chll hif): they began</Message></Annotation><v n="55" />Te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu, kabarai Masir manganga kahèi. Ka lasi asa dhèu aae ho ra manèngi nganga'a. Aa dhèu aae pua si lasi asa Yusuf, sèna ka ra madhutu paredha Yusuf.<bt>But eventually, the populace of Masir also became hungry. And they went to the king to ask for food. And the king sent them to Yusuf, so that they could follow Yusuf's commands.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kura noo-noo = semakin kurang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">kura noo-noo = semakin kurang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitsʕaq: the people cried out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yitsʕaq: the people cried out</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="56" />Te ngaa rai manganga ètu mia-mia asa tabha, toke d'ai rae-rae ètu rai Masir. Nèti èèna ka, Yusuf bhoke aa'i soka nganga'a sèna ka pahie dènge dhèu Masir.<bt>But the hunger/famine increased everywhere, to the point of arriving at the villages of the land of Masir. That is why Yusuf opened all the grainhouses of food so that he could sell it to the people of Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiftach: he opened yishbor: he sold"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yiftach: he opened yishbor: he sold grain<span class="Italic">(56) (56) </span>yechəzaq: it was heavy</Message></Annotation><v n="57" />Lula manganga ae titu kèna, ka dhèu nèti mia-mia mai hèli nganga'a ètu Yusuf ètu rai Masir.<bt>Because the hunger/famine was great, people came from everywhere to buy food from Yusuf in the land of Masir.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">A'a Yusuf lasi hèli nganga'a asa Masir<bt>Yusuf's elder-siblings go to buy food in Masir</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="42" />
      <v n="1" />Tèu èèna, Yakob tadèngi dhèu palolo na abhu are ètu Masir. Ka na peka dènge ana na si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ana ee! Miu nga tao madhèdi mau-mau ka laa?<bt>That year/seaon, Yakob heard people telling that there was grain in Masir. And he told his children, saying, &lt;&lt;Children, ee! How come you're (just) sitting around quietly (=not doing anything constructive)?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyarʔ: become aware (not just with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayyarʔ: become aware (not just with eyes) shever (shvr): grain for sale (not that Egypt had a crop and Palestine didnʔt; neither had a crop)<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>lammah titraʔu (rʔh hitp): looking at each other; donʔt just stand there, do something!</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ja'a tadèngi na ètu Masir pahia nganga'a. Hua iia lami hèli, sèna ka èdhi baku madhe manganga.&gt;&gt;<bt>I have heard that in Masir they are selling food. It would be better for you to go buy it, so that we do not die of hunger.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rədu (yrd): go down (Egypt is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">rədu (yrd): go down (Egypt is always "down", and Jerusalem and the Judean highlands are always "up")</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ka a'a Yusuf canguru dhèu se'e pa'èra ka, lasi hèli nganga'a asa Masir.<bt>So Yusuf's ten older-siblings got ready to go buy food in Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="akhey-yosef: Joseph's half brothers"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">akhey-yosef: Joseph's half brothers</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Te ngaa Yakob hia boe ari Yusuf dhu ngara na Benyamin, la'e dènge a'a na si. Te, na pangee, &lt;&lt;Mage dhoka, ana ne'e abhu hari j'aj'èra ètu talora j'ara.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yakob did not allow Yusuf's younger-sibling, who was named Benyamin, to go with his elder-siblings. Cuz he thought, &lt;&lt;Perhaps this child will also get suffering/difficulty on the journey.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="akhi-yosef: Joseph's full brother pen: so"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">akhi-yosef: Joseph's full brother pen: so that not, lest, prevention of a theoretically possible event<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yiqraʔenu: (distaster) happens ʔason: mortal accident<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Lula dhèu ae nèti mia-mia tadèngi le abhu nganga'a ètu Masir, ka ra lasi hèli asa nèi. Manganga ne d'ai le rai Kana'an kahèi. Ka ana-ana Yakob se,<bt>Because many people from all over the place had heard that there was food in Masir, they went to buy it yonder. The famine had already also reached the land of Kana'an. And the children of Yakob,</bt><note reference="42:5" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri madhutu lii Ibrani peka na, &lt;ana-ana Isra'el se&gt;. Te ngaa Yakob dènge Isra'el ne, ngara nèti ca dhèu.<bt>Ibrani language writings say &lt;Isra'el's children&gt;, But Yakob and Isra'el and Yakub, are names for the same person.</bt></note>lasi hèli kahèi asa Masir.<bt>also went to buy in Masir.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00730c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">A'a Yusuf se patitu kètu urutuu, pahaha iisi mi Yusuf<bt>Yusuf's elder-siblings bow to show respect to Yusuf</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Tèu èèna, Yusuf j'aj'i ai g'ana dhèu aae Masir. Ladhe dhèu nèti mia-mia mai hèli are, Yusuf ka dhu pahia. Nèti èèna ka, lod'o a'a na si d'ai nèi, rèngu patitu kètu urutuu, ho tab'e Yusuf toke rèhu rèngu oe d'ai rai.<bt>At that time, Yusuf had become the king of Masir's right hand. When people from everywhere came to buy grain, Yusuf was the one who sold it. that is why, when his elder-siblings arrived yonder, they bowed down to greet Yusuf with their faces down to the ground.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shaliyT: ruler, tyrant, the one with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">shaliyT: ruler, tyrant, the one with the power hammashbir (shbr hif partcpl): the one who did the selling<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>vayyishtakhvu (shkh hitp): bow down deeply, do homage, prostrated themselves ʔappayim (dual): their faces, their nostrils?<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7-8" />Ropa Yusuf ladhe nèdhi a'a na si, na tadhe le èèna. Te ngaa Yusuf tao iisi sèmi dhèu Masir. Nèti èèna ka, rèngu tadhe boe ne hèi. Hèia na jèka si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ee! Miu se nèti mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yusuf saw his elder-siblings, he recognised them immediately. but Yusuf had made himself like a Masir person. That is why they did not also recognise him. Then he scolded/spoke harshly to them, saying, &lt;&lt;Ee! Where are you from?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i se nèti Kana'an. Ji'i mai hèli nganga'a sa ama wakil.&gt;&gt;<bt>So they responded, saying, &lt;&lt;We-exc here are from Kana'an. We have come to buy food from father assistant (loan).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyakirem (nkr hif): he recognized them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayyakirem (nkr hif): he recognized them vayyitnaker (also nkr hitp): he kept his identity from them<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>qashot (qasheh): hard, difficult, heavy, severe meʔayin: from where?<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>vayyakker (nkr hif narr): he recognized hikkiruhu (nkr hif): they did not recognize him<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Hèia Yusuf sanèd'e lii nii na uru na. Ka na pamadha'u si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a lèka boe! Miu se'e dhèu mata-mata. Miu mai tenge rahasia rai Masir, ho èèna na mai musu rai ji'i!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf remembered his dream from before. And he cause them fear (deliberately), saying, &lt;&lt;I don't believe you! You-pl here are spies (loan). You have come to find out the secrets (loan) of the land of Masir, so you can come and make war on our-exc land!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu mata-mata = spy ; musu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">dhèu mata-mata = spy ; musu = menyerang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məraglim (regel): roamers, spies ʕerwat: nakedness,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">məraglim (regel): roamers, spies ʕerwat: nakedness, undefended areas<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Te ngaa ra dhaa peka na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o, ama! Ji'i se'e dhoka ana pua-paleha nèti ama di. Tare'a-re'a ji'i mai sa ne'e ne, neo hèli nganga'a di. Leo nèti èèna, aad'o.<bt>But they responded, saying, &lt;&lt;No, father! We are only father's servants (doublet). We have truly come here just to buy food. Other than that, there is nothing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕavadekha: and your slaves, servants"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʕavadekha: and your slaves, servants</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Ji'i aa'i-aa'i se'e, ana nèti ca ama di. Ji'i mai mata-mata boe rai ama ku si ne'e. Ji'i se'e dhèu be'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>All of us here, are children from one father. We did not come to spy out your land here. We here are good people.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nakhnu: we kenim: honest people: SK"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">nakhnu: we kenim: honest people: SK laugh.<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Te ngaa Yusuf jèka si dènge lii mèdhu hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;He! Omo koso! Baku kapod'e-kabèli ja'a. Miu se'e tare'a-re'a dhèu bhelu. Miu mai tenge rahasia rai ne'e!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yusuf scolded them with an even harsher voice, saying, &lt;&lt;He! That's nonsense! Don't lie (doublet) to me. You here are really evil people. You have come looking for the secrets of this land!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ka ra peka, &lt;&lt;Aad'o ama! Ji'i se'e ana pua-paleha ama ku di. Ji'i mai nèti rai Kana'an. Ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi nèti ca ama, canguru dua dhèu. Ari ji'i dhu limuri tèka, pea dènge ama ji'i. Aa ari ji'i èci aad'o heka!&gt;&gt;<bt>So they said, &lt;&lt;No, father! We here are merely your servants. We come from the land of Kana'an. We all are from one father, 12 people. Our youngest sibling is staying with our father. And another younger-sibling is no more!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shneym ʕasar: twelve haqqaTon: the youngest"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">shneym ʕasar: twelve haqqaTon: the youngest (Benjamin would have been in his late twenties or early thirties, no longer a kid, but still the youngest in the family)<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ʔeynennu: he does not exist (in other words, he's dead)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00733c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Yusuf jèka a'a na si<bt>Yusuf scolds his elder-siblings</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Hèia Yusuf dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Lèke sèmi lii ja'a deo na! Miu se'e dhèu mata-mata.<bt>Then Yusuf responded, saying, &lt;&lt;No! It is as I just said! You here are spies.</bt><v n="15" />Na! Karèi sèmi èèna, na miu hia ku tadha èci, sèna ka ja'a ke'a lii padhai lii miu deo sa, tare'a, do aad'o. Ja'a subha ee! Ladhe ari miu dhu limuri na, d'ai boe ne'e, miu èci sa bisa boe kalua nèti rai ne'e!<bt>Na! Therefore you must give me a sign/proof, so that I know what you just said is true, or not. I swear (oath)! If your younger-sibling, the youngest one, does not arrive here, not one of you will get out of this land!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tibbachenu (nif): you will be put"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tibbachenu (nif): you will be put to the test chey: as surely as Pharaoh lives<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>tetsʔu (ntsʔ imperf pl): come out bəvoʔ (inf): in coming<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />De hua iia miu pua dhèu èci la'e, ho nèti ari miu dhu limuri èèna asa ne'e mai. Aa miu dhu leo se, ja'a taha. Ja'a neo ke'a miu se'e peka tare'a, do aad'o. Ladhe aad'o, miu se'e tare'a-re'a mata-mata.&gt;&gt;<bt>So, it would be better for you to send one going to bring your youngest sibling back here. And the rest of you, I will detain. I am going to find out if you are speaking the truth, or not. If not, you are truly spies.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heʔaSru (ʔSr nif imperv): you are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">heʔaSru (ʔSr nif imperv): you are to be kept yibbachənu (nif): your words will be tested<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ka Yusuf pua taha si d'ara bèdho tèlu lod'o.<bt>And Yusuf ordered to detain them in prison for three days.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="subha = sumpah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">subha = sumpah</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyeʔəSof (ʔSp narr): he took away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayyeʔəSof (ʔSp narr): he took away</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00735c.tif" rtfFormat="width:9.0cm;textWrapping:none">Yusuf pamaso a'a na si asa d'ara bèdho<bt>Yusuf puts his elder-siblings into prison</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />D'ai lod'o ka tèlu, Yusuf la'e padhai lii dènge ra ètu d'ara bèdho, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne'e, ca dhèu dhu madha'u dènge Lamatua. Aa ja'a madhutu dad'èi Na taruu. Sèna ka miu mamuri, ja'a neo patabuli miu. Te ngaa hud'i dènge ku lii pajaji.<bt>On the third day, Yusuf went to speak to them in prison, saying, &lt;&lt;I here, am a person who fears the Lord. And I always obey His will/desires. So that you can live, I am going to free/release you. But there is a promise/requirement from me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕəsu (ʕsh imperv): do this wichyu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʕəsu (ʕsh imperv): do this wichyu (hyh imperv): stay alive<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>yareʔ: fear, shudder at, be in awe of, hold in deference</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Ladhe miu se'e tare'a padhai lii dhu mola, miu pad'elo ku ngaa èci j'aj'i mi tadha. J'ara na sèmi ne'e: ja'a taha ca dhèu ètu d'ara bèdho ne'e. Dhèu leo lèpa ho mèti nganga'a hia a'ari miu, te ra tatae miu lami mèti nganga'a.<bt>If you are really speaking the truth, you must show me something as a sign/proof. This is how is is: I will detain one person here in prison. The other people can go-home taking food for your relatives (&lt; elder-younger siblings), cuz they are waiting for you to bring food.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʔaSer mishmarkhem: your detention place, the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yeʔaSer mishmarkhem: your detention place, the prison where I would have kept you all<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>raʕəvon: hunger</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />D'ai nèi, miu mèti ari miu dhu limuri èèna mai asa ne'e, ho j'aj'i bukti, tare'a miu se'e dhèu be'a. Sèna ka ja'a baku huku pamadhe miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Arriving yonder, you will fetch your youngest sibling bringing him here, to be proof (loan), that you really are good people. So that I do not punish you with death.&gt;&gt; When they heard this, they agreed/accepted it.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa ra tadèngi rare ne'e, ra d'èi kahèi sèmi èèna.<Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʔamnu (ʔmn nif): your words will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yeʔamnu (ʔmn nif): your words will be confirmed</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ka ra padhue-padhai ka èci dènge èci, peka na, &lt;&lt;Waa! Ne'e ne, èdhi heka abhu b'ala kèna, lula sala dhu èdhi ad'u-ue mi dedha ari èdhi uru na. Èdhi ladhe tèdhi nèngu j'èra titu kèna, d'ai na manèngi sasue èdhi, te ngaa èdhi pusi boe ne. Nèti èèna ka, èdhi abhu j'aj'èra sèmi ne'e ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>And they discussed among themselves, saying, &lt;&lt;Waa! Now only-now are we getting reciprocated. Because of the wrong that we-inc did (doublet) to our younger-sibling previously. We saw his great suffering, to the point that he begged us, but we paid no attention to him. That is why, we are getting this suffering/sifficulty now.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔəval: introducing a statement that may"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔəval: introducing a statement that may not be pleasing to the hearer ʔəshemiym (pl): guilty<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>raʔiynu: we saw tsarat: distress<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>hitchanno (chnn hitp inf): his pleading for pity, praying for mercy</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Hèia Ruben pasanèd'e si, peka na, &lt;&lt;We! Ari-ari ja'a, ee! Uru na ja'a kai le miu, ho baku paj'èra ana èèna, si? Te ngaa miu-miu se'e ka dhu mo'o boe nanene lii ja'a. Nèti èèna ka, lod'o ne'e èdhi dui tare raa ari èdhi Yusuf èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Ruben reminded them, saying, &lt;&lt;We! Younger siblings, ee! Formerly I forbade you, to not cause suffering to that child, right? But you all didn't want to listen to/obey me. That is why today, we are shoulder-carrying the blood of our younger-sibling Yusuf.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔal-tekhetʔu: donʔt you sin against him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔal-tekhetʔu: donʔt you sin against him yeled: boy, young man; also used of a fetus<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>hinneh: focus on the current situation nidrash (nif): is being sought, is required<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Rèngu padhai lii ae-ae sèmi èèna, re'a boe na Yusuf ne'a lii rèngu kahèi. Lod'o Yusuf padhai lii dènge rèngu, na pake lii Masir, ho èèna na dhèu leo lole hari pake lii Ibrani.<bt>They kept speaking at length like that, not knowing that Yusuf also understood their language/what they were saying. When Yusuf spoke with them, he used the Masir language, so then another person retold it into the Ibrani language.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="salin ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">salin =</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meliyts (lyts hif partcpl): interpreter bayinotam:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">meliyts (lyts hif partcpl): interpreter bayinotam: between them<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Tadèngi ra padhai lii sèmi èèna hèia, Yusuf kèd'i eele si, la'e tangi asa era leo. Tangi nare, la'e hari pa'èci dènge si. Ka na pua dhèu èki Simeon ètu madha a'ari na sèra.<bt>Hearing them speaking like that, Yusuf left them and went to cry in another place. When he finished speaking, he went to join them again. And he ordered people to bind/tie Simeon in front of his elder-younger siblings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyiSSov (Sbb narr): he turned away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayyiSSov (Sbb narr): he turned away vayyashav (shwb narr): he came back. Speiser thinks it is used adverbially, as ʕʕWhen he was able to face them again.ʔʔ<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>vayyeʔəSor (ʔSr narr): he tied him up, had him tied up</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">A'a Yusuf sèra lèpa asa Kana'an<bt>Yusuf's elder-siblings return to Kana'an</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Èle èèna ka, Yusuf paredha dhèu sab'a sèra, ho soli are asa d'ara karo a'a na si. Aa tao hari doi kab'ua are sèra, asa d'ara karo ra èci-èci. Ra tèke ètu hèb'a karo sèra. Na pua dhèu sab'a se'e, ho hia si dènge gee. Ka dhèu sab'a se'e lalau ka, madhutu ngaa dhu Yusuf paredha.<bt>After that, Yusuf commanded his workers, to pour grain into his elder-siblings' gunny-sacks (assim. loan). And they replaced the money of the price of the grain inside each of their gunny-sacks. They placed them in the mouths of their sacks. He ordered these workers to give them trailfood. And the workers arranged things according to what Yusuf had commanded.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaytsaw (tswh piʕel narr): he ordered"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vaytsaw (tswh piʕel narr): he ordered klihem: their grain bags (kli = useful object, gear, vessel, receptacle)<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>bar: grain hashiv (shwv hif inf): give back<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>ʔel-saqqo: into his bag (poor quality material of goat hair) tsedah: provisions for a trip<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Èle ka, a'a na si hua karo nganga'a sèra asa dedha badha keled'ei. Ka ra pakèd'i dènge ka.<bt>After that, his elder-siblings loaded the gunny-sacks of food on top of their keledei (donkey-loan) animals. Then they left.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parèko j'ara = bekal ; gee"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">parèko j'ara = bekal ; gee = trailfood (umum)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyisʔu (nsʔ narr): they loaded chamoreyhem:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayyisʔu (nsʔ narr): they loaded chamoreyhem: their donkeys<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ropa d'ai talora j'ara, ra ae. Dhèu èci bhoke karo na, ho neo ani keled'ei na. Na ladhe la'a na, doi na ètu dedha are, ètu d'ara karo èèna.<bt>When they were on the journey, they stopped/rested. One of the people opened his gunny-sack wanting to animal-feed his keledei. He looked, and there was his money on top of the grain, inside that sack.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyiftach (ptch narr): he opened mispowʔ:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayyiftach (ptch narr): he opened mispowʔ: fodder<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>malon: lodging, camping-ground for the night (modern "hotel") bpi: in the mouth of (the bag)<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>ʔamtachto: load, bag</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Capa na cag'ag'a! Hèia na paroa a'a na si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Irii! Miu mai ladhe ku laa! Madhe èdhi kèna. Ra tao hari doi ja'a asa d'ara karo ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>He was taken aback! Then he summoned his elder-siblings, saying, &lt;&lt;Awii! You-pl come have a look! We're dead! They have replaced my money inside this sack.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00737c.tif" rtfFormat="width:9.0cm;textWrapping:none">A'a Yusuf nèdhi hari doi na ètu d'ara karo<bt>Yusuf's elder-sibling sees his money inside the gunny-sack</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ladhe rèdhi èèna ka, ra ele ngangee, aa madha'u bia. Ka ra papeka ka, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua tao èdhi samia ka ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>When they saw that, they unable to think, and were terrified. And they spoke to each other, saying, &lt;&lt;Father God is doing what to us-inc here?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="huwshav: returned, brought back vayyetseʔ libam:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">huwshav: returned, brought back vayyetseʔ libam: their heart went away = their courage failed, their determination stopped<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>vayyecherdu (chrd narr): and each looked with trembling at his brothers</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Hèia ra kako taruu ka, lasi d'ai Kana'an. D'ai nèi ka, ra lolo dènge ama ra, ngaa dhu rèngu paraga ètu rai Masir.<bt>Then they continued on, going to Kana'an. Arriving yonder, they narrated to their father, what they had encountered in the land of Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyagidu (ngd narr): they reported haqorot"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayyagidu (ngd narr): they reported haqorot otem (qrh partcpll plur fem): the things (neutral) that happened to them<span class="Italic">(29)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Ra lolo, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama, ee! Ai g'ana dhèu aae Masir èèna, bhelu titu kèna. Na jèka taruu ji'i. Na peka na ji'i la'a j'aj'i mata-mata ho neo pa'ele iie rai Masir.<bt>They narrated, saying, &lt;&lt;Father, ee! The right hand of the king of Masir, is really evil/cruel. He kept speaking harshly to us. He said that we are spies who wanted to destroy the land of Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dibber (dbr piʕel): he spoke qashot"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">dibber (dbr piʕel): he spoke qashot (qasheh): hard, difficult, heavy, severe<span class="Italic">(30)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Ka ji'i dhaa, peka na, &lt;Aad'o! Ji'i se'e padhai lii mola-mola. Ji'i mata-mata boe.<bt>So we responded, saying, &lt;No! We speak truthfully. We are not spies.</bt><v n="32" />Ji'i se'e, dhèu be'a-be'a. Ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi, j'aj'i nèti ca ama, dhèu canguru dua. Te ngaa èci madhe le. Aa ari dhu limuri èèna, dènge ama ji'i ètu Kana'an.&gt;<bt>We here, are good people. All of us are from the same father, 12 of us. But one has died. And our youngest sibling is with our father in Kana'an.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Na peka hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;Ja'a neo kèdhi, na, miu se'e dhèu be'a, do aad'o! Miu èci, pea mi ne'e. Aa leo lèpa mèti nganga'a hia a'ari miu, sèna ka ra baku madhe manganga.<bt>He spoke again, saying, &lt;I want to find out if you are good people, or not! One of you must stay here. The others can go-home taking food for your relatives, so they do not die of hunger.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hanikhu (nwkh hif imperv): leave behind"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hanikhu (nwkh hif imperv): leave behind raʕavon: hunger, famine<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>batechem: for your houses qakhu (lqkh): take away<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="34" />Hud'i miu mèti ku ari miu èèna mai sa ne'e, heka ja'a ke'a kèna, tare'a-re'a miu se'e dhèu be'a, mata-mata boe. Èèna na, heka ja'a patabuli dhèu miu dhu ja'a taha ne. Aa dènge sèmi èèna, ja'a heka ko'o kèna, miu kako palème dedha rai ne'e.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>You must fetch for me your younger-sibling, bringing him here, only-then will I know that you really are good people, and not spies. Then, only-then will I release your person who I detained. And in that way, only-then will I permit you to walk around this whole land.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeten: I will give tiScharu: pass"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔeten: I will give tiScharu: pass through, wander around<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Lolo èle hèia, heka ra bhoke karo-karo rèngu dhu pènu dènge are sèra. Te ngaa ra cag'ag'a ladhe la'a na doi rèngu sèra aa'i-aa'i ra, ètu hèb'a karo. Rèdhi sèmi èèna, Yakob dènge ana-ana na madha'u titu kèna.<bt>When they finished narrating, only-then did they open their gunny-sacks which were full of grain. But they suddenly saw all of their money in the mouths of the gunny-sacks. Seeing that, Yakob and his children were very afraid.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məriqim (ryq partcpl): as they were"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">məriqim (ryq partcpl): as they were emptying tsəror-kesfo: a bundle of his money<span class="Italic">(35)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Hèia Yakob padhai lii dènge si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu se, pa'ele le ana-ana ja'a. Yusuf aad'o heka. Sèmi èèna kahèi, Simeon. Ne'e miu neo mèti hari Benyamin kèna? Miu se'e, tare'a-re'a neo paj'èra ja'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob spoke to them, saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl are causing my children to disappear. Yusuf is no longer. In the same way, Simeon. Now you want to also take away Benyamin? You here are really wanting to cause me suffering!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="oti shikkaltem (piʕel): you have bereaved"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">oti shikkaltem (piʕel): you have bereaved me, deprived me of my children</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Hèia Ruben peka dènge ama na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama, ee! Pangèd'u laa Benyamin asa ja'a mai. Ja'a tago kore. Ja'a jaji kèna mi ama ku, èèna ja'a kèti hari na mai. Te ngaa ladhe aad'o, na ja'a hia ana ja'a, mone dhèu dua sèra ho ama pamadhe aa'i si.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Ruben spoke to his mother, saying, &lt;&lt;Father, ee! Tunr-over Benyamin to me. I will take responsibility. I promise to father, that I will bring him back here. But if not, I give my children, two sons, for father to kill them.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tamiyt (mwt hif): may you kill"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tamiyt (mwt hif): may you kill ʔəshiyvennu (shwb hif): I will bring him back<span class="Italic">(37)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Te ngaa Yakob dhaa hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Bisa boe! Miu bisa boe mèti Benyamin. Te a'a na Yusuf, madhe le. Ne'e, di nèngu ka mesa na. Ladhe na abhu calaka ètu j'ara, miu tabha babia mi ja'a, toke madhe kèti.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yakob responded again, saying, &lt;&lt;No way! You cannot take Benyamin. Cuz his elder-sibling Yusuf, is dead. Now he is alone. If he gets misfortune on the journey, you-pl will increase my burden, until I die.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləvaddo: in his aloneness, he alone"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ləvaddo: in his aloneness, he alone nishʔar (shʔr nif): remains<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>qəraʔahu: befall, meet him ʔaSown: misfortune, mischief, accident<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>vəhoradtem (yrd hif narr): you will bring down seyvatiy: my grey hairs, my old age<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>yagown: grief shəʔowlah: to Sheol, the place of the dead<span class="Italic">(38)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="42:38" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Ibrani peka na, &lt;&lt;toke d'ai ja'a puru asa Sheol (èèna era dhèu madhe sèra)&gt;&gt;.<bt>The Ibrani language writings say &lt;&lt;until I descend down to Sheol (the place of the dead people)&gt;&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">A'a Yusuf sèra lasi hari asa Masir, rèti dènge Benyamin<bt>Yusuf's elder-siblings go back to Masir, taking along Benyamin</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="43" />
      <v n="1" />Tèu èèna, ètu rai Kana'an asa tabha manganga.<bt>At that time, in the land of Kana'an the hunger/famine was increasing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʕav: famine kaved: heavy, oppressive, grievous|i(1)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">raʕav: famine kaved: heavy, oppressive, grievous<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Isi èmu Yakob ra'a aa'i le nganga'a dhu ca hari na, ana na si lasi hèli ètu Masir. Ka na padhai lii dènge ana na si, &lt;&lt;Be'a risi lami hari hèli nganga'a asa rai Masir.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yakob's household had eaten all the food which previously his children had gone to buy in Masir. And he spoke to his children, &lt;&lt;It would be better for you-pl to go back and buy food in the land of Masir.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="killu: they finished INFing shuvu: go"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">killu: they finished INFing shuvu: go back<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>lanu: for us (the sons, Jacob too, and their families) məʕaT: a little<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Te ngaa Yahuda b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama, ca hari na ai g'ana dhèu aae Masir dhu pasanèd'e le ji'i, aku nèngu na, ji'i bisa boe pad'elo rèhu mi nèngu, ladhe ji'i ngèti boe ari ji'i dhu limuri, Benyamin èèna.<bt>But Yahuda responded2, saying, &lt;&lt;Father, previously it was the king of Masir's right hand who warned/reminded us-exc, saying, we could not show our faces to him, if we did not bring our youngest sibling, Benyamin.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haʕed heʕid: decisively, solemnly (as in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">haʕed heʕid: decisively, solemnly (as in swearing a witness)</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Nèti èèna ka, ama ku hud'i laa hia ji'i ngèti Benyamin. Heka ji'i bisa la'a hèli nganga'a hia ama ku kèna.<bt>Because of that, father must let us take Benyamin. Only-then can we go buy food for father there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məshalleach (shlch piʕel partcpl): sending nerdah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">məshalleach (shlch piʕel partcpl): sending nerdah (yrd): we will go down<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>nishbərah: we buy grain</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Te ngaa ladhe ama patabuli boe nèngu, ji'i oo la'a boe kahèi. Lula dhèu Masir na peka le sèmi èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>But if father does not release him, we-exc also will not go. Because that Masir person has spoken like that.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Hèia Yakob jèke si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka miu lolo dènge dhèu èèna, peka na, miu dènge ari èci era? Miu tenge j'ara ho paj'èra tabha ja'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob scolded them, saying, &lt;&lt;Why did you-pl tell that person, saying you still had another younger-sibling? You are looking for ways to add to my difficulties!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasanède = 1) remind, 2) warn"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">pasanède = 1) remind, 2) warn</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="həreʕotem (rʕʕ hif): you did evil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">həreʕotem (rʕʕ hif): you did evil haʕowd: that there is still one<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ka ra dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku nasa ama, ee! Te lula dhèu ne, karèi taruu-taruu neo ne'a a'ari èdhi. Na karèi peka na, &lt;Tasamia? Ama mi era, do? Miu dènge hari ari dhèu mone dhu leo, do?&gt; Sèmi èèna na, ji'i dhaa tasamia hari? Pakaseti ka ji'i dhaa ka laa, dènge mola-mola. Te pe, cee ne'a na pua ji'i ngèti hari ari ji'i sa nèi?&gt;&gt;<bt>So, they reponded, saying, &lt;&lt;Don't be angry, father, ee! Because that person kept asking wanting to know about our-inc relatives/family. He asked, &lt;How about it? Do you still have a father? Do you have any other younger brothers?&gt; In that way, how else could we respond? We were forced to respond truthfully. Cuz later, who (could have) known that he would order us to bring our younger-sibling yonder?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shaʔowl shaʔiyl moladtenu (moledet): our relations,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">shaʔowl shaʔiyl moladtenu (moledet): our relations, descent, parentage<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>haʕod: still vanagged-lo (ngd hif): put something up conspicuously in front of someone, lay it all out, tell everything, speak out<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>həyadoaʕ nedaʕ (inf abs): did we have any idea? horidu (yrd hif): bring down (to Egypt), cause to go<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8-9" />Ka Yahuda padhai lii hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama hud'i patabuli ku Benyamin la'e dènge ji'i. Ja'a jaji mema, ladhe j'aj'i ngaa-ngaa mi ngi'u ari ji'i ne'e, ja'a ka dhu gati ne. Ladhe ja'a kèti heka nèngu mai asa d'ara kacui-aai ama ku dènge mamuri, hud'i laa sasala na ama ku pasae mi dedha ja'a toke madhe. Nèti èèna ka, ama ku hia la, ho ji'i sama-sama la'a dènge ne, te ji'i neo pakèd'i kèna. De karohe mai lati ka, sèna ka cahag'e baku madhe manganga.<bt>Then Yahuda spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;Father, must release Benyamin to go with us-exc. I promise directly, if anything happens to this younger-sibling of ours, I am the one who will replace him. If I do not bring him back to father alive (and well), that wrong father can cause me to shoulder-carry until death. Because of that, father allow for us to go together with him, cuz we want to leave right away. So we can leave immediately, so that some/none die of hunger.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naʕr: marriageable male while still single"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">naʕr: marriageable male while still single vnaqumah (qvm): stand up, get up; used to intensify an action, weʔll be on our way<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>Tappenu (Taf): our children ʔeʕervenu: I will stand surety for him, guarantee, pledge myself<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>tvaqshenu: you will seek, require it from me həviʔotiyw (bwʔ hif): cause him to come back<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>vhitstsagtiyw: produce him, bring him forward vkhaTaʔti: be blameworthy, be guilty<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ladhe sèmi èdhi mate boe panèbhu sèmi ne'e, na, èdhi lati-mai dua hari le.&gt;&gt;<bt>It is probable that if we had not waited so long like this, we could have gone back-and-forth two times already.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karohe = segera"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">karohe = segera</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="luwleʔ: if not hitmahmahnu (mhh hitpalpel):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">luwleʔ: if not hitmahmahnu (mhh hitpalpel): we lingered here and there, delayed<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Hèia ama ra padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, na, miu nanene! Lami mere isi rai èdhi dhu be'a risi, sèmi: dhua nasu oni, bubhu-bubhu, raa aj'u hèu mèngi, èi na'i salap, kanari<bt>Then their father spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;If that's how it is, you-pl listen! Go get the best contents/produce of our-inc land, such as: honey (&lt;bee molasses), spices, aromatic tree sap, medicinal salves (loan), kanari and other nuts. So that you-pl can take them to that king of Masir's right hand (man). And tell him that these are eye-signs (small gifts to show they were thinking of him).</bt><note reference="43:11" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri madhutu lii Ibrani peka na, <span class="Italic">&lt;shaqed&gt;.</span> Isi na èci èèna ka dènge isi kanari.<bt>The writings according to the Ibrani language says <span class="Italic">&lt;shaqed&gt;.</span> It's contents are like kanari nut.</bt></note>dènge kab'ui dhu leo sèra. Ho sèna ka mèti hia ai g'ana dhèu aae Masir èèna. Aa peka dènge ne, ne'e ne tadha mata.<Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔefoʔ: now, then mizimrat: strength, strong"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔefoʔ: now, then mizimrat: strength, strong point; the best produce of the land<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>bikhleykhem: in your things, your baggage horiydu (yrd imperv): go down = go to Egypt<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>minkhah: gift, present tsəri: mastic, resin: (gummy sap) of Pistacia mutica (Zohary p. 31 P. lentiscus). In other passages Moldenke suggests that it is Balanites aegyptiaca, Jericho balsam, found in the Jordan and Dead Sea valleys<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>dəvash: honey nkoʔt: a resin (cistus-rose, rock-rose, Astragalus gummifer, A. tragacantha?)<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>loT: myrrh or stacte baTniym: pistachio nuts<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>shqediym: almonds</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Aa miu mèti doi risi eele nèti ca hari ni, sèna ka miu bisa hia hari doi kab'ua are uru sèra la'a, dhu miu mèdhi ètu d'ara karo miu sèra. Tao-tao dhèu sèra re'a boe, ka tèka sala.<bt>And you should take extra money this time, so that you can give money of the price of the previous grain, which you saw inside your gunny-sacks. Probably those people did not know that they misplaced them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishneh: doubling muwshav (shwb hofʕal): that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">mishneh: doubling muwshav (shwb hofʕal): that was returned to you<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ʔamtəchoteykhem: your bags tashiyvu (shwb hif imperv): return something<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ʔuwlay: perhaps mishgeh: inadvertent mistake, oversight<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>huʔ: that (thing that happened)</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Miu mèti ari mu. De èèna na lèpa hari lai-lai!<bt>You will take your younger-sibling. So, return home quickly!</bt><v n="14" />Ja'a sanao-maena, sèna ka, Ama Lamatua dhu dènge Koasa Kapai Risi Eele èèna, sab'a mi d'ara ai g'ana dhèu aae Masir èèna, sèna ka na sue miu. Aa na hia hari Benyamin dènge Simeon lèpa palere dènge miu. Te, ladhe ana ja'a se ele, hud'i laa ja'a pasae j'aj'èra ne'e taruu.&gt;&gt;<bt>I hope and trust (doublet), that, Father God who is Most Powerful, will work on the inside/heart of that right hand (man) of the king of Masir, so that he loves/pities/favours you-pl. And he will give back Benyamin and Simeon to return home together with you-pl. But, if my children disappear, I must shoulder-carry this suffering/difficulty continually.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabui = kacang (kacang ijo [kabui"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">kabui = kacang (kacang ijo [kabui iiki], kacang tanah [kabui aae lèu], kacang nasi [kabui aae]) ; tadha mata</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔel: very old Semitic term for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔel: very old Semitic term for deity, used in compounds rachəmiym: loving feeling, compassion, grant you mercy before him<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>shakholtiy: I am bereaved of children</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Hèia lasi pakaboko tadha mata sèra dènge doi, ka lasi asa Masir. Rèti kahèi dènge Benyamin. D'ai nèi ka lasi paraga dènge Yusuf.<bt>Then they gathered the eye-signs, and the money, and went to Masir. They also took Benyamin. Arriving yonder they went to meet with Yusuf.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔanashim: men (poetic) vayaʕamdu: they stood|i(15)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔanashim: men (poetic) vayaʕamdu: they stood<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Ropa Yusuf nèdhi Benyamin dènge a'a na si, na pua kapala urusan na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lere mèti dhèu se'e sa èmu ja'a! Ho èèna na, pare sapi ci'u, mi pananasu nganga'a dhu be'a. Sèna ka lod'o nètu none, ra'a dènge ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yusuf saw Benyamin with his elder-siblings, he ordered his department head/chief of staff, saying, &lt;&lt;Escort these people to my house! There, slaughter a cow, and cook good food. So that, at midday they will eat with me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'oru = collect portion from each"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">pa'oru = collect portion from each person; 16: panasu = bamasak = pananasu ; lodo nètu = tengah hari, siang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="utəvoach tevach: prepare a slaughtering vəhakhen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">utəvoach tevach: prepare a slaughtering vəhakhen (kwn hif): prepare (meat)<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>tsahərayim: noon time</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Hèia kapala urusan èèna, tao sama sèmi lii paredha Yusuf èèna. Na lere nèti dhèu sèra asa èmu Yusuf.<bt>Then the chief of staff did what Yusuf had commanded. He escorted those people to the house of Yusuf.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ropa ra kako lasi èmu èèna, a'a na sèra madha'u bia. Ètu talora j'ara, ra papeka, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;We! Nga tao ka na pua rèti èdhi sa ne'e? Mage dhoka na neo pasusa èdhi. Lula doi dhu ra tao hari asa d'ara karo èdhi ca hari na. Ra sangaja rèti èdhi sa ne'e, sèna ka ra kèpa èdhi j'aj'i ènu nèngu. Ho èèna na, ra parama rara keled'ei èdhi sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>While they were going to that house, his elder-siblings were terrified. On the way/journey, they spoke among themselves, saying, &lt;&lt;We! Why did he order them to bring us here? It's probably that he's going to make trouble for us. Because of the money that they replaced into our gunny-sacks that time. They are deliberately bringing us here, so that they can grab us and make us his slaves. Then they will snatch our keledei (donkeys).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parama rara = rampas ame"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">parama rara = rampas ame</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="huwvʔu (bwʔ hofʕal, passive of causative):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">huwvʔu (bwʔ hofʕal, passive of causative): were brought təchillah: the first time<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>lhitgolel (gll hitpol roll): fall upon, attack ləhitnappel (npl hitpaʕel): attack<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Nèti èèna ka, ropa ra dètu èmu Yusuf na, ra padhai lii dènge kapala urusan èèna, peka na,<bt>That is why, when they were nearing Yusuf's house, they spoke with the chief of staff, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiggəshu: they approached him petach: opening|i(19)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayiggəshu: they approached him petach: opening<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="20" />&lt;&lt;Ama! Baku nasa dènge ji'i, te ca hari na dhu ji'i mai hèli nganga'a ètu ne'e.<bt>&lt;&lt;Father/sir! don't be angry with us-exc, cuz of that time when we came to buy food here.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bi ʔadonai: to open a conversation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">bi ʔadonai: to open a conversation with a superior, "excuse me, sir, but ..." = "may any bad consequences of what I say affect me" yarod yaradnu: we came (down) here to Egypt. Why the infinitive absolute? politeness, with biy?<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>təchillah: the first time, the beginning</Message></Annotation><v n="21-22" />Ropa ji'i lèpa d'ai talora j'ara, ji'i ae ngara iisi, ho bhèj'i ciki. Hèia ji'i bhoke karo ho neo panga'a badha. Ladhe la'a na, doi bab'ae ji'i èci-èci ka ètu d'ara karo sèra. Ji'i nge'a boe cee ka dhu tao la'a! Nèti èèna ka, ji'i ngèti hari doi sèra ka se'e. Ji'i manèngi sèna ka ama ku baku nasa. Aa ji'i ngèti doi ka risi kahèi, neo hèli hari nganga'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>When we were on the journey home, we stopped to rest, to have a sleep. Then we opened our gunny-sacks to feed our animals. Wouldn't you know that our payment money was there in each of our gunny-sacks. We do not know sho place them! therefore, we have brought that money again here. We ask that father not be angry (also =we apologize). And we have brought extra money also, wanting to buy more food.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Hèia kapala urusan èèna dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mau-mau, baku madha'u! Ele boe Lamatua miu èèna ka dhu hia miu berkat ètu d'ara karo sèra. Ca hari na, ja'a sèmi le doi miu aa'i-aa'i. Miu pakèlu boe!&gt;&gt; D'ai èmu ka, na patalale Simeon pa'èci dènge rèngu.<bt>Then the chief o-s responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Calm down, don't be afraid! It was probably your-pl Lord/God2 who gave you that blessing (loan) in your gunny-sacks. At that time, I received all of your money. You have no debt (to settle)!&gt;&gt; Arriving at the house, he released Simeon to join them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakèlu = berutang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">pakèlu = berutang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bmishqalo: as he had weighed it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">bmishqalo: as he had weighed it out, by weight (= what he paid) shalom: being whole, intact, at ease, unaffected, in good shape<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>maTmon: hidden treasure shimʕown: Simeon<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>vayyowtseʔ (ytsʔ hif narr): he brought him out</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ka aa'i-aa'i ra lasi asa d'ara èmu Yusuf. Hèia kapala urusan èèna hia èi ho ra rase haga ra. Aa na ani keled'ei si hèi.<bt>And all of them went into Yusuf's house. Then the chief -o-s gave them water to limb-wash their feet. And he also fed their donkeys.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyirchətsuw (rkhts narr): they washed feet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayyirchətsuw (rkhts narr): they washed feet miSpoʔ: fodder<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Ka na peka dènge si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe èèna na, lod'o nètu miu mi'a dènge ai g'ana dhèu aae.&gt;&gt; D'ara ra tatae Yusuf lèpa, rèngu lalau paie tadha mata ra sèra.<bt>And he told them, saying, &lt;&lt;In a bit, you will lunch with the king's right hand.&gt;&gt; While they were waiting for Yusuf to return (home), they carefully prepared/arranged their eye-signs.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyakhiynuw (kwn hif): they made it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayyakhiynuw (kwn hif): they made it ready</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ropa Yusuf d'ai èmu, aa'i-aa'i ra patitu kètu urutuu ètu madha na. Ka ra j'ole tadha mata sa hia ne.<bt>When Yusuf arrived at the house, all of them knelt before him. And they slid-across their eye-signs to him.</bt><v n="27" />Hèia Yusuf karèi si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia? Miu be'a-be'a, do? Tasamia dènge ama miu dhu heka èèna? Na be'a-be'a, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf asked them, saying, &lt;&lt;How is it? Are you-pl well? How is your old father? Is he well, or (what)?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ènu ama dhu heka na, dhu ama matana ji'i, be'a-be'a.&gt;&gt; Hèia ra patitu kètu urutuu pahaha iisi hari mi Yusuf.<bt>They responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Father's old servant, our birth father, is well. [=appropriate lg to a king or high official]&gt;&gt; Then they bowed, humbling themselves again to Yusuf.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Hèia Yusuf ladhe palème, ka nèdhi ari na Benyamin. Rèngu dua ra se, ina-ama èci. Hèia, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ooo! Ne'e ne ka ari miu dhu limuri, dhu ca hari na miu lolo èèna, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf looked around, and saw his younger-sibling Benyamin. The two of them had the same mother-father. Then he said, &lt;&lt;Ooo! This here is your youngest sibling, whom you told me about that day, right?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka na lii dènge Benyamin, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ana, ee! Ja'a sanao, sèna ka Ama Lamatua hia èu mamuri dènge mera-milu.&gt;&gt;<bt>And he spoke to Benyamin, saying, &lt;&lt;Child, ee! I hope that God gives you life and peace-prosperity.&gt;&gt; [=language of blessing]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yahənkha (chnn): may God be gracious"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yahənkha (chnn): may God be gracious to you</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ropa ladhe nèdhi Benyamin ne, d'ara Yusuf karej'e bia, lula na sue ari na ae titu kèna. Na taha nare heka d'ara na. Ka na kako eele si la'e sa d'ara kama na. Ka na tangi ngob'i-ngob'i ètu èèna.<bt>When he saw Benyamin there, Yusuf's insides were overjoyed, because he really loved his younger-sibling. He could no longer restrain/control himself. So he left them and went into his room. And he cried/sobbed there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaymaher: he hurried nikhmaru (kmr hof):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vaymaher: he hurried nikhmaru (kmr hof): was agitated, emotional (Pidgin "funny kine" refers more to unfamiliar or abnormal or undefined feelings than to humor.)<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>rachəmayw: his love, compassion livkot (bkh cry): to weep<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>chadrah (cheder): to a chamber</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Tangi nare hèia, la'e riu katanga madha na. Èle èèna ka, na pa'èra d'ara na, ka la'e hari paraga dènge si. Hèia na pua dhèu sab'a sèra lasi lalau nganga'a.<bt>When he finished crying, he washed his face. Then he strengthened his inside, and went back to meet them again. Then he ordered the workers to prepare food/set the table.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="riu (1) = cuci muka ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">riu (1) = cuci muka ; riu (2) = meruncing (vt) ; riu-riu = kayu yg ditanam di air yg ujungnya nampak di atas pramuka air (utk bekin tanda berlabuh, atau untuk tangkap ikan)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyirchats: he washed vayitʔappaq (hitpaʕel): pulled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayyirchats: he washed vayitʔappaq (hitpaʕel): pulled himself together, restrained himself, collected himself<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>shimu: put the food where it belongs, bring on the food</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ra lalau nganga'a hia Yusuf mei leo. Aa a'ari na sèra ra'a mei leo. Dhèu sab'a dhèu Masir sèra, ra'a ètu mei rèngu mesa ra. Lula dhèu Masir sèra madenge ladhe madhèdi ra'a pa'èci dènge dhèu Ibrani.<bt>They served food, giving Yusuf his own table. And his elder-younger siblings ate at their own table. The Masir workers, ate at their own table. Because the Masir people feel repugnant if they sit to eat together with Ibrani people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləvado: by himself, at a separate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ləvado: by himself, at a separate table loʔ yukhlun: they cannot<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>toʕevah: abhorrent, loathsome, detestable (cultic, then moral)</Message></Annotation><note reference="43:32" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu Masir madenge dènge dhèu Isra'el, lula dhèu Isra'el dhèu j'aga kahib'i-kalèbho.<bt>The people of Masir were grossed-out with the people of Isra'el, because the people of Isra'el were people who watched goat-sheep.</bt></note><v n="33" />Kapala urusan èèna ator sèna ka a'ari Yusuf sèra, madhèdi patangara dènge Yusuf. Na ator hia si madhèdi mulai nèti a'a uru, padhutu-dhutu toke ari ra dhu limuri. Ropa ra ladhe rèdhi j'ara madhèdi sèmi èèna, ra malaa.<bt>The chief o-s arranged so that Yusuf's elder-younger siblings sat facing Yusuf. He arranged so they sat beginning from the oldest, folowing in sequence until the youngest. When they saw the way they sat like that, they were amazed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bəkhor: firstborn tsaʕir: youngest|i(33) (33) |rvayyitməhu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">bəkhor: firstborn tsaʕir: youngest<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>vayyitməhu (tmh): they look in astonishment, stunned, benumbed, transfixed with astonishment reʕehu: the one they had dealings with, their friend<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="34" />Yusuf pua dhèu sab'a sèra, bagi nganga'a nèti mei nèngu, hia a'ari na sèra. Aa'i-aa'i ra abhu nganga'a dhu ae sama. Dhoka Benyamin di abhu ae risi a'a na si lèmi hari. Ka ra'a-rinu d'ai bècu.<bt>Yusuf ordered the workers to divide up the food from his table to his elder-younger siblings. All of them got the same amount of food. Only Benyamin got five times more than his elder-siblings. And they ate-drank until full/satiated.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="masʔot: share vayishkru: got drunk|i(34) (34)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">masʔot: share vayishkru: got drunk<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>terev (rbh): it was more yadot: hands, five times<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>vayyishtuw: they drank vayyishkəruw: they got drunk with him<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Moo hualaa pudhi Yusuf ele<bt>Yusuf's silver cup disappears</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="44" />
      <v n="1" />Ra'a-rinu rara hèia, Yusuf paholo dènge kapala urusan na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ssst! Èu lamu isi are asa d'ara karo dhèu sèi, papènu d'ai hèb'a. Èle èèna na, èu tao hari doi ra, asa d'ara karo ra èci-èci.<bt>When they finished eating-drinking, Yusuf whispered with his chief o-s saying, &lt;&lt;Ssst! You go fill grain into the gunny-sacks of those people, filling them up to the mouth. Then put back their money, into each of their gunny-sacks.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This scene is the peak of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">This scene is the peak of the Joseph and Judah story. They were the ancestors of the two major forces in Hebrew society for the next 600 years. vaytsav (tswh piel impf): give order, command<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>malleʔ (piʕel imperv): fill ʔamtəchot: sacks, bags<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʔokhel: food yukhlun: they are able [to hold]<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>sʔit (nsʔ inf): to carry sim (imperv): put<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Aa more moo hualaa pudhi ja'a èèna, ho tao asa d'ara hèb'a karo ari ra dhu limuri èèna.&gt;&gt; Ka na la'e tao madhutu lii paredha Yusuf.<bt>And take my silver cup, to place into the mouth of the youngest sibling there.&gt;&gt; And he wnet and did what Yusuf had ordered.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="moo = cup, mug with handle"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">moo = cup, mug with handle for drinking ; paholo = bisik, bakusu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gviʕi gviaʕ: my drinking bowl tasim"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">gviʕi gviaʕ: my drinking bowl tasim - imperfect after imperatives, but not initial. It's the cup that is fronted.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>shivru (shever cs): his grain The rabbis assumed that the brothers already knew that their money had been returned, perhaps as compensation for all that Joseph has put them through. But if Joseph's manager was conducting a search of their bags, he would not have let them see the money that was there.<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Asa bèli d'ara cika lii sa, Yusuf hia si lèpa. Rèti nganga'a dènge keled'ei rèngu.<bt>Then early the next morning, Yusuf let them return (home). They took their food and their donkeys.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔur (ʔwr partcpl): as it was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔur (ʔwr partcpl): as it was becoming day; the morning became light, grew light vhaʔanoshim: v- may be consecutive to haboker ʔor; but it is on the noun. Maybe it has something to do with hemah?<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>shullchu (puʕal): were sent away [who sent them?], they were allowed to go hemmah: they<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>chəmoreyhem: their donkeys</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ra lasi dhae kaj'èu mèka nèti d'ara kota, ka Yusuf paredha kapala urusan, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu karohe lamu magèla si. Ladhe paraga dènge si, èu peka sèmi ne'e: &lt;Nga tao ka miu pake d'ara aapa sèmi èèna mi ai g'ana dhèu aae? Miu b'ala babe'a na dènge tatao karehe sèmi ne'e!<bt>They had not yet gone very far from the city, then Yusuf commanded the chief o-s, saying, &lt;&lt;You go and chase them quickly. When you meet them, say like this: &lt;Why are your insides so evil toward the king's right hand? You have repaid his goodness with evil deeds like this!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hem yatsʔu (pf): they went forth,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hem yatsʔu (pf): they went forth, went on their way et: they left that particular city; also Ecclesiastes 7:18 (usually takes min)<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>hirchiqu (hif): they went far rdof: set off after them to catch up to them, can be hostile<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>hissagtam (nsg hif): reach, overtake shillamtem (piʕel): you repay, balance things out<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>raʕah: evil tachat: instead of<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Nga tao ka, miu mana'u mèti moo hualaa pudhi na? Miu me'a boe, do? Mèdha èèna na, na pake boe ho dhoka ninu di! Te ngaa biasa na pake ho ne'a tasamia dènge mamuri dhèu. Èèna, mèdha sogo-tagu! Tatao miu ne, mema seli-kolane!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Why have you-pl stolen his silver cup? Don't you know? That is his thing which he uses not just to drink! But he normally uses it to know how people's lives are. It is an object of traditional-worship! This deed of your, is really beyond the limits!&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Asa bèli dara cika lii sa,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">Asa bèli dara cika lii sa, = papagi hari buta ; cika lii = burung berkicau (early morning bird); 4: kaca'a laa = takuju sa; 5: malare ~ ladhe kalua = method specific diviination ; seli kolane = kalewat batas, keterlaluan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishteh: (shth imperf): would drink. Also"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yishteh: (shth imperf): would drink. Also Psa 105. nachesh (piel) ynachesh (piʕel imperf: can seek and give omens, practice divination, learn things through divination, find out unknown information<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>hreʕotem (rʕʕ hif): you do evil</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00749c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Rèngu abhu moo hualaa pudhi na ètu d'ara karo Benyamin<bt>They get/find the silver cup inside Benyamin's gunny-sack</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Èle èèna ka, kapala urusan èèna la'e magèle si toke abhu. Ropa na raga si, hèia na peka sèmi ngaa dhu Yusuf moa èèna.<bt>Then, the chief o-s went pursuing them until he caught them. When he encountered them, he told them what Yusuf had instructed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayassigem (nsg): overtake, catch up with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayassigem (nsg): overtake, catch up with</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ka ra bari ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama peka ngaa èèna? Ji'i subha. Ji'i se'e bisa boe tao karehe sèmi èèna!<bt>And they asked-back (=protested), saying, &lt;&lt;What is father saying? We-exc swear. We here cannot (possibly) do evil of that sort!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chalilah: aversive, negative interjection: far be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">chalilah: aversive, negative interjection: far be it from us meʕəsot (ʕsh inf cs): to do<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ama, èu me'a era, si ma? Doi-doi ca hari sa, dhu ètu d'ara karo ji'i sèra, ji'i hia hari le sa ama, to? Tasamia ka ji'i bisa mana'u hualaa iia do hualaa pudhi ètu d'ara èmu dhèu kapai èèna! Bisa boe!<bt>You yourself know, right? The money from that day, which was in our gunny-sacks, we already gave it back to father, right? How could we steal gold or silver from the house of that important person. No way!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hen: here it is! ʔamtchotenu: our"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hen: here it is! ʔamtchotenu: our sacks<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>heshivonu (shwv hif): we brought it back ʔekh: how?<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>nignov: we steal ʔo: or<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ama parisa la! Ladhe abhu mèdha èèna ètu d'ara karo cee, na huku pamadhe ne! Aa hud'i laa, ji'i dhu leo se'e, j'aj'i ènu èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>You go ahead and inspect! If you find that thing in someone's gunny-sack, punish him to death! And it must be that the rest of us, become your slaves.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bari = tanya bale; 8: si"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">bari = tanya bale; 8: si ma ~ si na ma</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Joseph created a lot of possible"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">Joseph created a lot of possible outcomes, any one of which would benefit him. He wanted Benjamin and he wanted his father; reconciling with his brothers may have been a lower priority. yimmatseʔ (mtsʔ nif impf): is found, is discovered<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>mit (mwt): he dies, let him die nihyeh: we will become<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Hèia kapala urusan na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Sèmi ne'e. Ladhe abhu moo èèna ètu cee, na dhoka nèngu di j'aj'i ènu ja'a. Miu dhu leo lèpa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the chief o-s responded, saying, &lt;&lt;No! It will be like this. Whoever I find that cup at, only he will be my slave. The rest of you will go on home.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gam-ʕatah: The servant takes the brothersʔ"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">gam-ʕatah: The servant takes the brothersʔ rash statement as meant, not as uttered. He gives them the benefit of the doubt (we are honest men), so he softens his restatement of the consequences if the cup is found. ken-huʔ: thus it; if that's how it is<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>ʔatem: you guys nəqiyim (naqi pl): innocent, exempt from blame, free<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ra papuru ka karo sèra. Ka ra bhoke dènge.<bt>They lowered their gunny-sacks. And they opened them up (without waiting).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaymahəru (piʕel cs): they hurried, acted"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vaymahəru (piʕel cs): they hurried, acted quickly vayoridu (yrd hif): they took down<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Hèia kapala urusan èèna parisa karo sèra èci-èci, mulai nèti karo unu a'a na, toke d'ai ari limuri tèka. Ka nèdhi moo èèna, ètu d'ara karo Benyamin.<bt>Then the chief o-s inspected each of their gunny-sacks, beginning from the gunny-sack of the oldest, until reaching the youngest. And he saw that cup inside Benyamin's gunny-sack.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaychappes (chfs piʕel): look thoroughly for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vaychappes (chfs piʕel): look thoroughly for something hechel (chll hif pf): begin<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>killah (klh piʕel pf): finish, end with yimmatseʔ: was found. It doesn't mention the money; with the manager conducting the search, he would not have let them see what he saw.<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Rèdhi sèmi èèna hèia, d'ara a'a na sèra j'èra ma'ète mae-mae sène. Hèia ra paca'e hari ka karo deo sa asa dedha keled'ei, ka ra lèpa hari asa d'ara kota.<bt>Seeing that, the insides of the elder-siblings were shredded with suffering. Then the reloaded those aforementioned gunny-sacks on top of the donkeys, and they went back to the city.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hue ~ hua"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">hue ~ hua</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqrʕu: tear, tear into pieces simlotam:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yiqrʕu: tear, tear into pieces simlotam: their mantles (heavy outside robes)<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>vayaʕmoS: they loaded the animals khamoro: his male donkey<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>vayashuvu (shuv): they went back</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ropa ra d'ai èmu Yusuf, na ètu èmu era. Hèia ra patitu kètu urutuu ètu madha na.<bt>When they arrived at Yusuf's house, he was still there in the house. Then they knelt before him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔechaw: his brothers ʕodennu: still him|i(14)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔechaw: his brothers ʕodennu: still him<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>vayippəlu (npl): threw themselves down, get down quickly, fling themselves down. A unique way of putting it, not the ordinary ceremonial "bowing to the ground."</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Yusuf jèka si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;He! Nga tao ka miu tao ne'e mi ja'a! Miu me'a boe, ja'a ne dhèu kapai ètu ne'e. Ja'a pake na'i dhu bisa ke'a tatao dhèu, dhu dhèu leo re'a boe!&gt;&gt;<bt>Yusuf scolded them, saying, &lt;&lt;He! Why did you do this to me! You didn't know that I am an important person here? I use medicine/magic/power to find out people's deed, which other people cannot know!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maʕaseh: deed nachesh (piʕel inf) ynachesh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">maʕaseh: deed nachesh (piʕel inf) ynachesh (piʕel imperf): he divines; he can certainly divine<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>ʔish asher kamoni: a man such as I</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Hèia Yahuda dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Irii! Te Ama Lamatua pasabhoka kèna sasala èdhi. Pe ji'i peka lii mia hari, ama? Ji'i sili iisi sa mia hari? Ladhe ama neo taha ari ji'i ne'e, na be'a risi, taha ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi. More ji'i aa'i-aa'i, j'aj'i mi ènu ama ka laa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yahuda responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Awiii! God has unveiled our wrong. What can we (possibly) say, father? How can we (possibly) defend ourselves? If you want to detain this younger-sibling of ours, it would be better if you detained all of us. take us all, to be your slaves now.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasabhoka = unveil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">pasabhoka = unveil</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nitsTadaq (tsdq hitp): prove ourselves to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">nitsTadaq (tsdq hitp): prove ourselves to be innocent ʕavon: activity that is crooked or wrong, conscious, intentional offense, sin, guilt incurred by an offense, punishment. ʔet: the specific evil thing?<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>hinnennu (particle, 1pl suf): here we are gam: both ... and<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>nimtsaʔ (mtsʔ nif): was found, was caught bayado: in his hand, under his control<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Te ngaa Yusuf dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Abhu moo èèna ètu cee, na nèngu di dhu j'aj'i ènu ja'a. Miu dhu leo, lèpa hari dènge mera-milu sa ama miu!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yusuf responded, saying, &lt;&lt;No! Whoever we found the cup in, he is the one who will be my slave. The rest of you, go on home in peace-prosperity to your father!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chalilah: far be it from me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">chalilah: far be it from me lshalom: being whole, intact, in prosperity, peace, unaffected, whole, unmolested. Joseph is planning ahead move by move like a chess player.<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>End of P section</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yahuda manèngi sèna ka nèngu gati Benyamin<bt>Yahuda asks that he replace Benyamin</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sui = 1) tebus, 2) belah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">sui = 1) tebus, 2) belah (ikan)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Hèia Yahuda la'e padètu asa madha Yusuf, ka na padhai lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama wakil! Ja'a ke'a koasa ama sama sèmi koasa dhèu aae! Uru nèti èèna, ja'a manèngi ama baku nasa dènge ja'a. Ja'a neo padhai lii ciki dènge ama.<bt>Then Yahuda approached in front of Yusuf, and spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Father representative! I know your power/authority is the same as the power/authority of the king! Therefore, I ask that you not be angry with me. I want to talk over a bit of something (insignificant) with you, father.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiggash (ngsh): step up, come near,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayiggash (ngsh): step up, come near, approach. This passage is important enough that Jewish tradition gives the section the title Vayiggash. Here Judah assumes the guilt for Joseph's disappearance and takes the responsibility. In the entire chapter, everything Judah says and everything Joseph says have to go through interpreters, and Joseph has to pretend he doesn't understand Judah. bi ʔadoni ydaber-naʔ: with your permission, on me, my lord, let there come whatever unwelcome or hurtful thing our conversation might bring<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>naʔ: please, urgency bʔazney ʔadoni: in the ear of my lord<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>vʔal-yichar ʔapkha (chrh impf): donʔt burn, donʔt become angry, break out ki khamokha: since you are like Pharaoh. Identical in some regard; you can be as deadly or as forgiving as Pharaoh. Josh 14:11, 1Sm 30:24; Ez 18:4; Dn 11:29; Jdg 8:18; Is 24:2 not exactly being said that the first thing is like the second, nor that the second is like the first, but that the first is like the second AND the second is like the first. Gn 18:25, Lv 7:7, Lv 24.16, Gn 44:18, Hg 2:3, Ec 9:2<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Med'a na, ama karèi le ji'i, peka na, &lt;Ama miu, dènge ari miu dhu èci na, era do?&gt;<bt>Yesterday [can be literal or extended], you asked us, saying, &lt;Your-pl father, and that one younger-sibling of yours, are still there, right?&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shaʔal: asked ʕvadaw (sg): your slave|i(19)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">shaʔal: asked ʕvadaw (sg): your slave<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00744c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Yahuda la'e padètu-dètu asa madha Yusuf<bt>Yahuda approaches before Yusuf</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ka ji'i dhaa peka na, &lt;Ama ji'i heka d'ai seli le. Aa ari ji'i dhu limuri èci. Lod'o nara iisi ari ji'i ne'e, ama ji'i na heka le. Ari ji'i dhu limuri ne'e dènge a'a d'èlu na èci, te ngaa na aad'o heka. Ina ra madhe le. Ka di nèngu ka mesa na. Nèti èèna ka, ama ji'i ne sue ne titu kèna!&gt;<bt>And we responded saying, &lt;Our father is extremely old. And we still have another younger-sibling. When our younger-sibling was born, our father was already old. Our youngest sibling has an older sibling (sharing at least one parent), but he is no longer. Their mother is already dead. And he is alone. Because of that, our father loves him dearly!&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Why does Moses go into such"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">Why does Moses go into such detail in this scene? Longacre may have an answer. David Klines, who has written the definitive lexicon in 9 volumes, addresses it in _The Theme of the Pentateuch_. This section develops Judah's character. When the brothers sold Joseph, probably none of them had children of their own. Since then, Judah has gone through the loss of two sons and Tamar's decisive acton to perpetuate his line. At the same time, he has seen his father mourning Joseph for years; and now that he has lost his, he knows from experience how his action has torn up his father. He is determined that no traumatic agony like that will happen again with Benjamin. So the question of Benjamin's actual guilt or innocence never comes up. zaqen: old<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>zqunim: time and circumstance of the aged, in his old age qatan: small, young<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>met: he died. Rashi comments that Joseph doesn't ask about the dead brother. He's not playing games; he wants to know about his father. vayyiwater (ytr nif): is left over, remains over<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>lvadow: alone, in solitude ʔahevo: loves him<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ka ama pua ho ji'i ngèti ari ji'i na mai, sèna ka ama nèdhi ne.<bt>So you ordered us to bring our younger-sibling here so that you could see him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="horiduhu (yrd hif imperv): bring down"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">horiduhu (yrd hif imperv): bring down (to Egypt) vʔasimah (sym): so I can put my eyes on him. v- gives the consequence here; little logical apparatus, but a lot of causal ties. Sarna "So I can pay special attention to him"; but bringing Benjamin there in the first place was the proof Joseph needed that they were genuine, or as he put it to them, "not spies."<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ʕeyni: my eyes</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Ka ji'i dhaa na, &lt;Ana èèna, bisa boe tèke eele ama na mesa na. Ladhe na tèke eele, na ama ji'i na tatu madhe dènge kèna.&gt;<bt>And we responded that &lt;That child cannot leave his father alone. If he leaves him, our father will surely die.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hanaʕar: the young man, marriageable male"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hanaʕar: the young man, marriageable male while still single laʕazov, ʕazav: leave behind, abandon. hypothetical situation + result given again without "if."<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Hèia ama dhaa na, &lt;Ladhe miu mèti boe ari miu na, baku mi pad'elo hari rèhu mi sa ne'e.&gt;<bt>So you responded, &lt;If you do not bring your younger-sibling, you will not show your faces to me here again.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yered: come down to Egypt tosifun"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yered: come down to Egypt tosifun (ysf hif): add, increase, go on, do something again. Joseph knows how long the famine is going to last, and this is probably the early part of it. So he knows the brothers will have to come again for more grain.<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Èle èèna ka, ji'i lèpa. D'ai nèi ka, ji'i lolo lii dhu mu moa sèra dènge ama ji'i.<bt>After that, went went home. Arriving there, we narrated your instructions to our father.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕalinu (ʕlh): go up, go to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʕalinu (ʕlh): go up, go to Palestine vanaged-lo (ngd): reported to him<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Nèbhu-nèbhu, nganga'a ji'i èla. Hèia ama ji'i pua hari ji'i mai hèli nganga'a sa Masir ne'e.<bt>Eventually, our food ran out. Then our father sent us again to come and buy food here in Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shivru (imper): buy grain mʕat: little"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">shivru (imper): buy grain mʕat: little bit<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Te ngaa ji'i dhaa na, &lt;Ama, ee! Ji'i la'a heka sa nèi. Te ai g'ana dhèu aae na dhu moa le, aku nèngu na, ladhe ji'i ngèti boe ari ji'i dhu limuri na, bisa heka ji'i pad'elo rèhu sa nèi. De ladhe ari ji'i la'e hèi, na heka ji'i la'a kèna.&gt;<bt>But we responded, &lt;Father, ee! We cannot go yonder. Cuz the king's right hand has promised, saying, if we do not bring our youngest sibling, we cannot see his face again there. So, if our younger-sibling does [not] also go, we can no longer go.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nukhal (ykl): we can only go"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">nukhal (ykl): we can only go there. Hypothetical at this point. yaradnu: we go down to Egypt<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>ʔenenu (3sg suf): he is not there. Judah is appealing to Joseph as a man, on humanitarian grounds.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ama ji'i peka hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;Miu me'a kahèi, si ma? Dhèu èmu ja'a Rahel èèna, ana na dhoka dua di.<bt>Our father spoke again, saying, You all know, right? My spouse Rahel had only two children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔishti: Only Rachel counts. Judah by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔishti: Only Rachel counts. Judah by now is mature and has had children of his own. He can accept the fact that Rachel is the favorite wife, not his mother Leah. Parallel to Esau coming to terms with what Jacob had done to him.</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Ana uuru èèna, aad'o heka. Ele boe badha hui na'e aa'i le. Nèti èèna ka, ja'a kèdhi heka rèhu na toke d'ai sange ne'e.<bt>The first child is no longer. Probably a wild animal has eaten him up. Therefore, I have not seen his face again to this day.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yetseʔ: he has gone out haʔechad:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yetseʔ: he has gone out haʔechad: one of them<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>ʔakh: surely, assurance or emphasis. Also restrictive and contrastive. It narrows down the options: the only thing left for me to conclude is that the lions got him. tarof toraf (trf pual): torn in pieces by wild animals<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>rʔitiw: I will not see him. Jewish commentators regard Jacob as still holding out a hope that Joseph is alive -- the evidence is that he's dead, but maybe Iʔll see him now. ʕad: during, continuing; unto<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>hennah: 3fem pl. Owens treats -h as locative. Up to now?</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Ladhe miu mèti hari ana limuri ne, ho sèmi na abhu j'aj'èra, èèna miu paj'èra ja'a dhèu heka ne'e. Ladhe sèmi èèna na, ja'a madhe dènge kèna.&gt;<bt>If you take his youngest sibling, and he gets suffering/difficulty, then you will have cause me suffering as an old man. If it is like that, I will just die.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ulqachtem: you are taking hold of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ulqachtem: you are taking hold of him, seizing. The u- has conditional force. meʕim: away from [with] my presence<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>qarahu (qrh): befalls him ʔason: mortal accident<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>horadtem (yrd hif): you will bring down seyvati: my gray-headedness<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>braʕah: in evil, harm. In 47:8 when Jacob meets Pharaoh he says his years are "few and raʕah," so it must have been a major part of his mindset that life is crummy.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30-31" />Nèti èèna ka, ama, ladhe ja'a lèpa kèti boe dènge ari ji'i ne, ama ji'i madhe dènge kèna. Te samanga na dhu pa'èki dènge ana ne'e di. Dènge ètu d'ara haheka na ne'e, ladhe ji'i tao ne tabha j'èra, tatu na madhe dènge kèna.<bt>Therefore, father/sir, if we do not bring home this younger-sibling of ours, our father will just die. Cuz his *spirit is bound to this child. And in his old age, if we do (something) to add suffering, certainly he will die straight away.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʕatah: and now ʔenenu: he is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vʕatah: and now ʔenenu: he is not there; Samaritan Pentateuch and translations have ʔitanu (wit us)<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>qshurah (qshr partcpl fem): tied up together, bound together met: he will die. Some translators read "and the boy dies"; but Jacob is both topic and subject of the whole sequence.<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>byagon: torment, trouble</Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Ngaa hari, ja'a moa le mi ama ku, peka na, &lt;Ja'a ka dhu tago ana ne'e. Ladhe ja'a kèti heka ana ne'e mai sa madha ama, ja'a ka tago sasala na, toke d'ai ja'a madhe.&gt;<bt>Furthermore, I have promised my father, saying, &lt;I am the one who will be responsible for this child. If I do not bring back this child before father, I will bear the wrong, until I die.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ètu dara haheka na = in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">ètu dara haheka na = in his old age; 32: Ngaa hari, = furthermore (CNJ)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕarav: stand surety for him, pledge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʕarav: stand surety for him, pledge myself, mortgage my life (like cosigning a note) ʔviʔenu (bwʔ hif): I bring him. v- is hypothetical<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>chataʔti: I have been guilty</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Nèti èèna ka, ja'a manèngi sèmi ne'e, ama wakil: hud'i laa ja'a ka pea mi ne'e gati nèngu, sèna ka ja'a j'aj'i ènu ama wakil. Hia ne lèpa dènge a'a na si.<bt>Therefore, I make this request, father rep: Allow me to stay here replacing him, so that I become father rep's slave. Let him go home with his elder-siblings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeshev-naʔ: may your servant stay. The"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yeshev-naʔ: may your servant stay. The series of jussives is very deferential. But the proposal is bizarre in terms of known Near Eastern laws. tachat: instead of. The first place the idea of substitution comes up = hyper<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>yaʕal: go up to Palestine</Message></Annotation><v n="34" />Ladhe ana ne'e la'e boe, ja'a bisa boe lèpa kahèi. D'ara ja'a la'e boe ladhe j'aj'èra ama ji'i toke madhe.&gt;&gt;<bt>If this child does not go, we-exc also cannot go home. My insides could not stand to see our father suffer until he dies.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔekh: how? yimtsaʔ: will find, will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔekh: how? yimtsaʔ: will find, will happen to<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf patadhe ngi'u mi a'ari na, aa na manèngi sèna ka ama na si pidha asa Masir<bt>Yusuf introduces himself to his elder-younger siblings, and he asks his father to move to Masir</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="45" />
      <v n="1" />Ropa tadèngi nare lii Yahuda na, d'ara Yusuf roe bhilu, toke taha nare boe ètu madha dhèu sab'a na sèra. Nèti èèna ka, na hia ra lasi asa li'u, sèna ka mesa na di, dènge a'ari na ètu d'ara èmu. Dènge j'ara ne'e, nèngu bisa patadhe iisi na, mi a'ari na sèra.<bt>When he heard what Yahuda said, Yusuf's insides were torn/sad, to the point that he could not restrain/control himself anymore in front of his workers. That is why he had them go outside, so he could be alone with his elder-younger siblings inside the house. In that way, he could introduce himself to his elder-younger siblings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lhitʔappeq (hif): pull himself together, collect"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">lhitʔappeq (hif): pull himself together, collect himself, restrain himself. With "But," this gives the idea he canʔt control himself. hanitstsavim (nif partcpl): the ones standing, stationed; not milling around like a cocktail party<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʕalaw, maʕalay: does this mean Joseph was seated and they were standing? or were they facing him? Or were they his bosses? hotsiyʔu (ytsʔ hif): let everybody go out!<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʕamad: to stand; to stand (before), i.e. serve, minister to; to be set over; to confide in; to stand by hitwaddaʕ (ydʕ hitp): when he made himself known. Use of "wen" here is interesting<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Hèia dhèu sab'a se'e kalua asa li'u, ka Yusuf tangi dènge d'ara pèd'a. Lii tangi na mèdhu, ka dhèu-dhèu Masir ètu li'u sèra tadèngi kahèi. Mesa boe dhèu ètu li'u sèra, te dhèu ètu èmu dhèu aae tadèngi kahèi.<bt>Then the workers went outside, and Yusuf cried bitterly/emotionally. He wept loudly, and the Masir people outside heard it. Not only those people outside only, but also the people in the king's house also heard.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dara roe bhilu = hati ancor"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">dara roe bhilu = hati ancor (sedih) ; patadhe iisi = patadhe ngi'u</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bivakhi: in weeping. Joseph canʔt do"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">bivakhi: in weeping. Joseph canʔt do anything but bawl and let it all come out. min: because of his expression? in front of him?<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ka Yusuf peka mola-mola dènge a'ari na si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'ari, ee! Ja'a ne'e ka Yusuf èèna! Ama ku mamuri era, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yusuf spoke honestly with his elder-younger siblings, saying, &lt;&lt;Elder-younger siblings, ee! I here am that Yusuf! My father is still alive, right?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa tadèngi rare, a'a na sèra madha'u titu kèna. Ra bisa heka bhoke hèb'a padhai lii ngaa èci sa.<bt>When they heard that, his elder-siblings were very frightened. They could no longer open their mouths to say anything.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nivhlu (bhl nif): were terrified, out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">nivhlu (bhl nif): were terrified, out of their senses</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Hèia Yusuf paroa si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mai ku padètu-dètu dènge ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf summoned them, saying, &lt;&lt;Come here close to me.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka ara lasi padètu sa madha Yusuf. Ka na peka hari, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, Yusuf, dhu uru èèna, miu pahia eele asa Masir ne'e.<bt>And they approached in front of Yusuf. And he spoke again, &lt;&lt;I here, am Yusuf, who long ago, you sold off here to Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gshu-naʔ (ngsh): approach, come near, step"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">gshu-naʔ (ngsh): approach, come near, step up naʔ: entreaty? permission? A great man doesn't use naʔ; it's for a subordinate speaking to his superior. So suddenly the relationship is different.<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>mkhartem: you sold. The repetition of "I am Joseph" does not indicate a second source; Joseph has to penetrate their state of shock, and they canʔt believe what is happening. mitsraymah: into [slavery in] Egypt (locative)<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Miu se tare'a pahie eele ja'a. Te ngaa mage miu madha'u, aa baku peka cee ka dhu sala. Lula Ama Lamatua ka dhu hia uuru ja'a mai sa ne'e. Ho dènge j'ara ne'e, Na pake ja'a ho hia mamuri mi dhèu ae. Sèna ka baku madhe manganga.<bt>It is true that you sold me off. But you must not be afraid, and not go accusing about who did wrong. Because God is the one who sent me here on ahead. So that in this way, He (could) use me to give life/save many people. So that (you/they) would not die of hunger.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔal-teʕatsvu: do not be distressed, worried,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔal-teʕatsvu: do not be distressed, worried, grieve vʔal-yikhar (khrh): do not become hot, angry<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>bʕehekhem: in your own eyes, angry with yourselves? hinah: to here<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>lmikhyah: for preservation of life, means of living; to result in life. It's rare in the Hebrew Bible to have anybody reflecting on the past and the reasons why something happened. This is not an interpretation of Joseph's earlier dreams; it's a fulfillment.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Rai manganga ne heka dua tèu kèna. Lèmi tèu era. Bèli-camèd'a dhèu tao heka oka-tedhe, sèla heka, aa abhu heka nganga'a hèru èj'i lai.<bt>Tthe hunger/famine has only been going two years. There are still five years (to go). In the future, people will no longer make fields (doublet), no longer plant, and no longer get any food from the planting season.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ki: used frequently. He's making sense"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ki: used frequently. He's making sense out of a lot of things all at once. All of a sudden seeing God's purpose blows Joseph away - an integrative experience. shnatayim (dual): two years<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>haraʕav: the famine. He doesn't ask how they are, or anything about his father. He gets right down to the main business, preserving life. bqerev: in the middle of<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʕod: still khariysh: time of plowing<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>qatstsiyr: grain harvesting activity (April to June)</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Dènge j'ara dhu èdhi te'a boe ne, Ama Lamatua hia ja'a mai asa ne'e uru nèti miu. Sèna ka, miu dènge ana-èpu miu abhu mamuri.<bt>In this way that we do not understand, God allowed me to come here ahead of you-pl. So that you-pl and your children-grandchildren (=descendants), could live/be saved.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hèru èj'i lai = musim tanam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">hèru èj'i lai = musim tanam</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lasum (sym inf): to set up,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">lasum (sym inf): to set up, put in place shəʔerit: a means of survival? remainder, remnant, what is left, remnant of a people who have been destroyed, make sure there are survivors<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>ʔarets: land of Egypt? land of Canaan? the world? lhachəyot (chyh hif): to keep you alive<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>lifleytah: for escape, deliverance</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />De dhu lèke, nèti boe tatao miu ka ja'a d'ai era ne'e, te ngaa tatao Ama Lamatua di. Nèngu ka dhu hia ja'a j'aj'i ai g'ana dhèu aae Masir. Ka ja'a j'aj'i mi kapala urusan ètu d'ara èmu dhèu aae. Abhu boe dhèu leo èci sa dhu kapai risi nèti ja'a.<bt>So what is true, it is not because of your deed that I arrived in this place, but the deeds of God. He is the one who allowed me to become the right hand of the king of Masir. And I have become the chief-of-staff in the house of the king. There is not a single other person who is greater than I.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʕatah: logical? I canʔt read it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vʕatah: logical? I canʔt read it temporally. It's like Verse 5: now then (before a negative). Almost like "furthermore" henah: here<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>vaysimeni: put me in the position of (is va- consecutive, or a follow-on with additional information about ki haʔlohim?) beto: his house -- his government? his extended family?<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>moshel (mshl 2 partcpl): as ruler</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />De miu lami ka lai-lai ne, ho peka lii padhai lii ja'a ne dènge ama ku, sèmi ne'e: &lt;Yusuf, ana ama ku, mamuri era! Nèngu j'aj'i le dhèu kapai ètu rai Masir. Na manèngi ama ku la'e lai-lai asa nèi.<bt>So, you-pl should go home quickly, to tell my message to my father, like this: &lt;Yusuf, my/our father's child, is still alive! He has become an important person in the land of Masir. He asked father to go quickly yonder.</bt><v n="10" />Ho èèna na, ama pea ètu rai Gosen padètu dènge nèngu. Era na be'a aa taleo. Sèna ka ama bisa piara kahib'i-kalèbho, kahib'i-ka'ia dènge sapi aa'i-aa'i ra. Aa na manèngi kahèi ho ama la'e dènge ana-èpu, dènge isi èmu, dènge mèdha-panyau, ho pea taruu mi nèi.<bt>Later father can stay in the land of Gosen near to him. That place is good and wide/open. So that father can raise all your sheep-goats, goat-goats, and cows there. And he also asks that father go with your children-grandchildren, and your household, and possessions, to live yonder continually.</bt><note reference="45:10" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Rai Gosen èèna, ngara era èci ètu rai Masir.<bt>That land of Gosen, is the name of a place in the land of Masir.</bt></note><v n="11" />Ladhe ama pea ètu Gosen, nèngu ladhe-leru ama ètu nèi. Te rai manganga lèmi tèu era. Sèna ka na tenge j'ara ho ama dènge ana-èpu, aa dènge badha-manu bisa mamuri dènge be'a.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>If father lives in Gosen, he will care for father there. Cuz the famine still has five years to go. So that he can find a way for father and the children-grandchildren, and the animals to live well.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kahib'i-ka'ia = kambing; 11: badha-manu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">kahib'i-ka'ia = kambing; 11: badha-manu = segala jenis hewan piara</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Yusuf peka nare hèia, na padhai lii hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu unu mi mèdhi le, si? Aa èu kahèi, Benyamin. Ja'a ne'e, tare'a-re'a Yusuf.<bt>[When] Yusuf finished saying that, he spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;You have seen for yourselves, right? And you also, Benyamin. I here, am really Yusuf.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roʔowt (pl particpl): seeing (force?) While"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">roʔowt (pl particpl): seeing (force?) While I am speaking to you. ki-fi (peh ʔmouthʔ): according to? It is my mouth that is speaking to you.<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>hamdabber (dbr piel pt): the thing I am saying, the one who is speaking</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />De miu peka dènge ama èdhi, na, ja'a ne'e dènge koasa kapai titu kèna, ètu kabarai Masir ne'e. Aa lolo dènge ama, ngaa aa'i-aa'i dhu miu mèdhi le ètu ne'e. Ho èèna na, karohe mèti ama sa ne'e mai!&gt;&gt;<bt>So tell our-inc father, that I have great power/authority, here among the populace of Masir. And narrate to father, everything that you-pl have seen here. And then, hurry to bring father here!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vhigadtem (ngd hif): report, announce something"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vhigadtem (ngd hif): report, announce something kvodi: my weight, weightiness, impressive appearance, respect<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>mihartem (piʕel): hurry horadtem (yrd hif): you bring him to Egypt<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Èle èèna ka, liku nare ari na Benyamin, hèia dua ra tangi.<bt>After that, he embraced his younger-sibling Benyamin, and the two of them cried.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayipol ʕal-tsawwəʔərey (nfl): he fell on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayipol ʕal-tsawwəʔərey (nfl): he fell on Benjamin's neck, used to describe an emotional greeting yevk (bkh imperf): cry<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>bakhah: why does the aspect change?</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Sèmi èèna kahèi, na liku nare a'a na si èci-èci, ka na uu si. Ka heka ra bani padhai lii dènge ne kèna.<bt>In the same way, he embraced each of his elder-siblings, and he kissed/sniffed them. Then, only-then did they have the courage to speak with him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nashsheq (nshq piʕel): kiss vayevk ʕaleyhem:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">nashsheq (nshq piʕel): kiss vayevk ʕaleyhem: and he cried over them<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>khen: thus. Understated. dibbəru (piʕel): they talked. In Hebrew the focus changes ʔhe wept over them ... the brothers talked with himʔ but in Pidgin it seems more coherent to keep the focus on Joseph.<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu aae Masir sèmi nare a'ari Yusuf sèra<bt>The king of Masir receives Yusuf's elder-younger siblings</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ropa dhèu aae dènge dhèu-dhèu kapai na sèra, tadèngi rare a'ari Yusuf mai asa Masir, ra karej'e kahèi.<bt>When the king and the important people heard that Yusuf's elder-younger siblings had come to Masir, they were also happy.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haqol: sound, voice, this word yitav:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">haqol: sound, voice, this word yitav: it went over well in the estimation of Pharaoh<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ka dhèu aae peka dènge Yusuf, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ari! Peka dènge a'ari èu sèra, ho hua ka nganga'a asa dedha keled'ei rèngu, sèna ka rèti sa Kana'an.<bt>And the king spoke to Yusuf, saying, &lt;&lt;Younger-sibling! Tell your elder-younger siblings to load food on top of their donkeys, to take it back to Kana'an.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taʕanu: load your animals bʕirkhem: beasts"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">taʕanu: load your animals bʕirkhem: beasts (grazers)<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>laxu-boʔu: go and arrive there</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Aa peka dènge si, rèti ama mu dènge ana-èpu aa'i-aa'i, mai pea sa ne'e. D'ai ne'e, pe ja'a hia rèngu rai, era dhu hèu mèngi risi, sèna ka rèngu bisa mamuri nèti isi rai èèna.<bt>And tell them, to bring your father, and all the children-grandchildren to come live here. Arriving here, I will give them land, a place that is very fertile, so they can live off that land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʔetnah: and I will give ʔikhlu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vʔetnah: and I will give ʔikhlu: they will eat<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>chelev: fat, best part, select</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Aa hia rèti mema dènge kareta pèri-pèri nèti ne'e, ho sèna ka hua ana iiki-ana iiki dènge ama mu.<bt>And have them take several carts from here, so they can load the small children and your father.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsuwweytah (tswh pual): are ordered, receive"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tsuwweytah (tswh pual): are ordered, receive command. Variant reading LXX and Vg: tsaweh ʔotam ʔyou command themʔ ʕgalowt: wagons (not chariots), carts<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>lətapkhem: for the ones who are hardly fit to march: women, children, the elderly linsheykhem (ʔishah, pl cs nʔshey): for your wives<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>unəsaʔtem: and carry them</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Baku ra pangee mèdha-panyau dhu rèngu bisa boe nedhe rèti, te, ngaa-ngaa dhu be'a ètu rai Masir ne, èèna na j'aj'i unu rèngu.&gt;&gt;<bt>They should not think/worry about the possessions which they are not able to bring, cuz whatever is good here in this land of Masir, it will become their possession.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʕeynkhem: your eyes ʔal-takhos ʕal (khws):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vʕeynkhem: your eyes ʔal-takhos ʕal (khws): do not let your eyes begrudge your household furnishings, do not be troubled about them<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Tadèngi sèmi èèna, ka Yusuf hia si kareta pèri-pèri bua, dènge parèko ra'a j'ara, sama sèmi lii paredha dhèu aae. Aa a'ari na<bt>Hearing that, Yusuf gave them several carts, and trailfood to eat on the journey, just like the king had commanded. And his elder-younger siblings</bt><note reference="45:21" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu sasuri dhu uru-uru sèra, peka na &lt;&lt;ana-ana nèti Isra'el sèra madhutu lii paredha dhèu aae.&gt;&gt; Isra'el ne, ngara leo nèti Yakob.<bt>According to the oldest writings, they say &lt;&lt;Isra'el's children follow the command of the king.&gt;&gt; Isra'el is another name for Yakob.</bt></note>pa'èra ka, ho lèpa madhutu lii paredha dhèu aae.<bt>made ready to return home according to the command of the king.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsedah, tsidah: provisions"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tsedah, tsidah: provisions</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Ka Yusuf hia si mèdha-papake dhu hiu, ca dhèu ca pasa. Te ngaa Benyamin, na hia doi iia tèlu ngasu, dènge mèdha-papake dhu hiu, lèmi pasa.<bt>And Yusuf gave them new clothes, one set one person. But as for Benyamin, he gave him three hundred silver coins, and five sets of new clothes.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lukhulam: to all of them. Still,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">lukhulam: to all of them. Still, Joseph loves Benjamin and his father more than the other brothers, if he could be said to love them at all. khalifot (khlf piel): substitute clothing, special gala changes of clothes<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>smalot: mantles or wrappers (both garment and under-blanket)</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Yusuf pa'adhu mèdha-panyau dhu be'a risi nèti Masir hia ama na. Rèngu hua mi dedha keled'ei canguru ngi'u. Sèmi èèna kahèi, na hia are, roti, dènge nganga'a ae-ae, dhu j'aj'i parèko j'ara, lod'o dhu rèngu mulai pakèd'i nèti Kana'an asa Masir. Nganga'a se, ra hua ètu dedha keled'ei dhu leo hari canguru ngi'u.<bt>Yusuf sent2 the best things of Masir to his father. They were loaded on top of ten donkeys. In the same way, he sent1 grain, bread, and many kinds of food, as trailfood, for when they began to leave from Kana'an to Masir. This food, they loaded on top of ten other donkeys.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kzot: according to the following (equivalent"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">kzot: according to the following (equivalent to a colon) ʕsarah: ten<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>khamorim: male donkeys nosʔim: carrying<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>mitov: some of the wealth ʔatonot: female donkeys<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>bar: cleaned, threshed grain mazon: food<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Èle èèna ka, na hia si lèpa, aa na moa si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu baku patao-palaha ètu talora j'ara, ee!&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, he sent them home, and he instructed them, saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl must not argue/fight on the journey, ee!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="doi iia = uang perak ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">doi iia = uang perak ; pasa = pasang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔal-tirgəzu (rgz): quake, be perturbed; donʔt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔal-tirgəzu (rgz): quake, be perturbed; donʔt be emotionally upset (agitation, fear), fly into a passion (rage). Sarna, do not engage in mutual recrimination. Other rabbis take it as "donʔt be afraid of robbers."</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob tadèngi na Yusuf mamuri era<bt>Yakob hears that Yusuf is still alive</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Hèia ra pakèd'i ka lasi sa ama ra ètu Kana'an.<bt>Then they left and went to their father in Kana'an.</bt><v n="26" />D'ai nèi ka, ra lolo dènge ama ra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ana mu Yusuf na, dhu mamuri era di. Na j'aj'i le dhèu kapai, ka na paredha ètu rai Masir!&gt;&gt;<bt>Arriving yonder, they narrated/reported to their father, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Your child Yusuf is still alive. He has become an important person, and governs in the land of Masir!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Yakob tadèngi hiu-hiu na, loo-loo sène, te na lèka boe.<bt>At the moment when Yakbu had just heard this, he was confused, and didn't believe it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaggidu (ngd): report moshel (partcpl): the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayaggidu (ngd): report moshel (partcpl): the ruler<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>vayyafag (fwg impf): feeble, numb, cold. Rashi, Jacob was unable to believe them heʔəmin (ʔmn hif): believe, convinces. In general, Jacob did not put trust in what they said. Rashi, ceased to believe<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Te ngaa ropa na tadèngi nare lii lolo rèngu sèra, aa na ladhe nèdhi kareta dhu Yusuf pa'adhu mai ho hua ne asa Masir, heka na lèka kèna.<bt>But, when he had heard their report, and had seen the carts which Yusuf had sent to carry him to Masir, only-then did he believe.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="laseʔt (nsʔ inf cs): to carry"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">laseʔt (nsʔ inf cs): to carry vatkhi ruwakh: and his spirit came alive<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Hèia na padhai lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hea! De ana ja'a dhu mamuri era di! Ja'a heka karej'e kèna. Ja'a hud'i laku kèdhi ku ne, heka ja'a madhe dènge karej'e kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Awiii! So my child is still alive! Only-now am I happy. I must go see him, so I can die happy.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tadèngi hiu-hiu = sa'at dengar partama"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">tadèngi hiu-hiu = sa'at dengar partama ; loo-loo = naa-naa = bingung-bingung</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rav: that's plenty. Enough! I have"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">rav: that's plenty. Enough! I have enough information, Iʔm convinced by the evidence! Jewish commentators consider "rav" to take in more than the whole. ʔelkhah (hlk): I will travel<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>bterem: before</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob dènge isi èmu na pa'èra mèdha neo pakèd'i asa rai Masir<bt>Yakob and his household prepare their things to leave for the land of Masir</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="46" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna ka, Yakob<bt>After that, Yakob mob prepared their things, and they left from Kana'an. When they arrived at the village of Barseba, and slaughtered an animal as a sacrifice (assim. loan) to God2, whom previously his father Isak had worshipped.</bt><note reference="46:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Ibrani peka na, &lt;&lt;Isra'el pa'èra ka mèdha ra, ka ra pakèd'i&gt;&gt;.<bt>The Ibrani language writings say &lt;&lt;Isra'el prepared his belongings, and they left&gt;&gt;.</bt></note>si pa'èra ka mèdha ra, ka ra pakèd'i nèti Kana'an. Ropa ra d'ai rae Barseba, ka na roro badha tao korban hia Lamatua, dhu uru na ama na Isak mangaj'i.<Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiSSaʕ (nSʕ qal): pull up stakes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayiSSaʕ (nSʕ qal): pull up stakes and go, set out o a trip vkol-ʔasher-lo: and everything he had -- people, animals, belongings<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>bʔerah (bʔer): watering place, well of underground water vyizbach zbachim: he slaughtered large and small cattle (cows, goats, and sheep) as communion sacrifices (not sin offerings, but communion between the one sacrificing and the deity to whom the sacrifice is offered, who is himself a partner in the act). See ʕola 2Kings 10:24, minkha 1 Samuel 2:19, shlamim 1 Kings 8:63, also 2 Kings 10:19 for other kinds<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00760c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Rèngu pakèd'i, tèke eele rai Kana'an<bt>They go, leaving behind the land of Kana'an</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Mèda ca lod'o ka na nii. Ètu d'ara nii ne'e, na tadèngi na Ama Lamatua paroa ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yakob! Yakob! Èu kèd'i ho nanene ku la!&gt;&gt;<bt>One night he dreamed. In this dream, he heard God summoning him, saying, &lt;&lt;Yakob! Yakob! Get up and listen to me!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao, Ama?&gt;&gt;<bt>So he responded, saying, &lt;&lt;What is it, father?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bmarʔot: vision, apparition (not a dream)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">bmarʔot: vision, apparition (not a dream) yaʕqov yaʕqov: would God have said it twice if he had been talking Pidgin? or only in Hebrew?<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ka Lamatua peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, Ama Lamatua dhu ama mu mangaj'i nèti uru ka. Mage èu madha'u kahèi lamu Masir. Te èèna na, Ja'a tao ana-èpu èu j'aj'i suku kapai ètu rai nèi.<bt>And the Lord said,&lt;&lt;I here am the God whom your father worshipped from long ago. You must not be afraid to go to Masir. Cuz there, I will make your children-grandchildren become a great tribe in that (remote) land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔal-tiraʔ: do not be afraid merdah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔal-tiraʔ: do not be afraid merdah (yrd inf cs) = min rədah: to go down, source of fear<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>gadol: great (wealthy, important) ʔsimxa (sym): I will place you as a great nation, establish you, set you up as<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ja'a laku hèi Masir sama-sama dènge èu. Ho ladhe èèna na, Ja'a kahèi dhu kèti hari ana-èpu èu lèpa asa rai Kana'an ne'e. Ropa èu madhe, na, ana mu Yusuf madhèdi ètu baboa èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>I will also go to Masir together with you. So that later, I will bring your descendants back to this land of Kana'an. When you die, your child Yusuf with be sitting at your side.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baboa = samping"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">baboa = samping</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔaʕalkha (ʕlh hif): I will bring"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔaʕalkha (ʕlh hif): I will bring you back up [to Canaan] gam-ʕaloh (inf): why gam? why the infinitive absolute, hifʕil + qal? Waltke &amp; OʔConnor "I will surely bring you up again"<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yashit (shyt): put. BT: a pretty nice genuine idiom "will be at your side when you die." SS: For Buddhists, close da eyes mean pau, da spirit gone</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Èle èèna ka, Yakob dènge ana-ana na sèra,<bt>After that, Yakob and his children,</bt><note reference="46:5" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Ibrani peka na, &lt;&lt;Ana-ana Isra'el rèti dènge ama ra Yakob.&gt;&gt;<bt>The Ibrani language writings say, &lt;&lt;Isra'el's children take their father Yakob.&gt;&gt;.</bt></note>lasi taruu tèke eele rae Barseba. Ra paca'e ne dènge bhèni-ana iiki na asa kareta sèra dhu dhèu aae Masir pa'adhu hia si.<bt>continued going, leaving behind the village of Barseba. They put up their women-small kids on the carts which the king of Masir had sent for them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tappam (taf): their children laseʔt (nsʔ):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tappam (taf): their children laseʔt (nsʔ): to lift someone up, carry, support, transport<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="6-7" />Rèti aa'i mèu-mèu mèdha-panyau dènge badha-manu dhu j'aj'i kakaja rèngu ètu rai Kana'an. Hèia Yakob dènge ana-èpu na, bhèni-mone aa'i-aa'i ra pakèd'i ka lasi rai Masir.<bt>They took all their possessions and animals which were their wealth in the land of Kana'an. Then Yakob and all his children-grandchildren, male-female left, going to the land of Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miqneyhem: their possessions, especially cattle rəkusham:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">miqneyhem: their possessions, especially cattle rəkusham: property, goods gained by work, not by purchase [CHECK]<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>rakshu: they had acquired zarʕow: his seed, his descendants, offspring<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>heviʔ (bwʔ hif): bring (main verb) End of S section<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-èpu Yakob dhu madhutu lasi sa Masir<bt>Yakob's children who accompanied him to Masir</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ana-èpu Yakob dhu madhutu lasi asa Masir, nuka se'e:<bt>Yakob's children-grandchildren who accompanied him arriving in Masir, are these:</bt><note reference="46:8" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Ibrani peka na, &lt;&lt;ana-èpu Isra'el&gt;&gt;.<bt>Ibrani language writings say, &lt;&lt;Isra'el's children-grandchildren&gt;&gt;..</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ruben, ana uuru na.<bt>Ruben, the first child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bkor: firstborn"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">bkor: firstborn</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ana-ana na ka: Henok, Palu, Hesron dènge Karmi.<bt>His children were: Henok, Palu, Hesron and Karmi.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="10" />Simeon, dènge ana-ana na: Yemuel, Yamin, Ohat, Yakin, dènge Sohar. Dènge Saul kahèi, ana na nèti dhèu èmu na bhèni Kana'an.<bt>Simeon, and his children: Yemuel, Yamin, Ohat, Yakin, and Sohar. And also Saul, a child from his spouse, the woman from Kana'an.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="11" />Lewi, dènge ana-ana na: Gerson, Kehat, dènge Merari.<bt>Lewi, and his children: Gerson, Kehat, and Merari.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="12" />Yahuda, dènge ana-ana na: Sela, Peres, dènge Sera. Ana Yahuda dhu leo, Er dènge Onan, madhe le ètu Kana'an. Na nèti dènge ana-ana Peres, Hesron dènge Hamul.<bt>Yahuda, and his children: Sela, Peres, and Sera. Yahuda's other children, Er and Onan, had already died in Kana'an. He took Peres' children, Hesron and Hamul.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="13" />Isaskar, dènge ana-ana na: Tola, Pua, Ayub, dènge Simron.<bt>Isaskar, and his children: Tola, Pua, Ayub, and Simron.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="14" />Sebulon, dènge ana-ana na: Seret, Elon, dènge Jahleel.<bt>Sebulon, and his children: Seret, Elon, and Jahleel.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Rèngu se'e, ana-ana nèti Yakob dènge dhèu èmu na Lea, lod'o rèngu pea ètu Mesopotamia. Ana bhèni rèngu èci, ngara na Dina. Ana-èpu nèti Yakob dènge Lea, aa'i-aa'i ra 33 (tèlu nguru tèlu) dhèu.<bt>These ones were the children off Yakob and his spouse Lea, when they were living in Mesopotamia. They had one daughter, named Dina. All of the children-grandchildren of Yakob and Lea, were 33 people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="16" />Aa Yakob abhu ana-ana dènge dhèu èmu dhu leo hari. Nuka: Gad, dènge ana-ana na: Sifion, Hagi, Suni, Esbon, Eri, Arodi dènge Areli.<bt>And Yakob had children with his other spouses. They were: Gad, and his children: Sifion, Hagi, Suni, Esbon, Eri, Arodi and Areli.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="17" />Aser, dènge ana-ana na: Yimna, Yiswa, Yiswi, Beria, dènge ana hèni ra èci, ngara na Sera.<bt>Aser, and his children: Yimna, Yiswa, Yiswi, Beria, and their sister, named Sera.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Beria, dènge ana le kahèi: Heber dènge Malkiel.<bt>Beria, along with his children: Heber and Malkiel.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra, canguru èna dhèu. Ana-èpu nèti Yakob dènge dhèu èmu na Silpa. Silpa ne'e ka dhu Laban hia j'aj'i ènu nèti Lea, dhèu èmu uru Yakob na.<bt>All of them were 16 people. The children-grandchildren of Yakob and his spouse Silpa. This Silpa is the one whom Laban gave to be a slave to Lea, Yakob's first spouse.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="19" />Aa ana-ana nèti Yakob dènge dhèu èmu na bhèni leo hari, ngara na Rahel, nuka: Yusuf dènge Benyamin.<bt>And the children from Yakob and another spouse, named Rahel, were: Yusuf and Benyamin.</bt><v n="20" />Lod'o èèna, Yusuf leo le dènge Asnat ètu Masir. Ama Asnat èèna, ama agama ètu kota On. Ngara na, Potifera. Ana-ana Yusuf dènge Asnat: Efraim dènge Manase.<bt>At that time, Yusuf had already married Asnat in Masir. Asnat's father, was the religious head (=*priest) in the city of On. His name was Potifera. The children of Yusuf and Asnat were: Efraim and Manase.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiwwaled (nif): were born"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yiwwaled (nif): were born</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="21" />Benyamin madhutu hèi lasi Masir dènge ana-ana na: Bela, Beker, Asibel, Gera, Naaman, Ehi, Ros, Mupim, Hupim dènge Aret.<bt>Benyamin also accompanied [his father] to Masir with his children: Bela, Beker, Asibel, Gera, Naaman, Ehi, Ros, Mupim, Hupim and Aret.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ana-èpu Yakob dènge dhèu èmu na Rahel, canguru èpa dhèu.<bt>Yakob's children-grandchildren with his spouse Rahel, were 14 people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yulad (qal pass): were born"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yulad (qal pass): were born</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="23" />Dhèu èmu Yakob èci hari, ngara na Bilha. Ana-ana ra, Dan, dènge Naftali.<bt>Yakob's had another spouse, named Bilha. Their children were Dan, and Naftali.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ana Dan, ngara na Husim.<bt>Dan's child was named Husim.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** made separate paragraph"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">*** made separate paragraph</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="24" />Ana nèti Naftali: Yasel, Guni, Yeser dènge Silem.<bt>Naftali's children were: Yasel, Guni, Yeser and Silem.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Yakob dènge dhèu èmu na Bilha, ana-èpu rèngu dhèu pidhu. Bilha ne, ènu nèti Rahel, dhu na abhu nèti ama na Laban.<bt>Yakob and his spouse Bilha had 7 children-grandchildren. This Bilha, was a slave of Rahel's, whom she got from her father Laban.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />De ana-èpu Yakob dhu lasi Masir, aa'i-aa'i ra dhèu 66 (èna nguru èna) dhèu. Se'e se, ige mèka dènge dhèu èmu nèti ana-ana nèngu sèra.<bt>So, Yakob's children-grandchildren who went to Masir, all of them were 66 people. These ones did not take count of their children's spouses.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yotsʔey: who set out yəreko: back"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yotsʔey: who set out yəreko: back of his (Jacobʔs) upper thigh, another way of talking about the genitals and procreation<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>milləvad: alone, not counting</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Ladhe tabha dènge ana-ana Yusuf dhu ina na nara iisi ètu Masir dhèu dua, na Yakob dènge ana-èpu aa'i-aa'i ra si, 70 (pidhu nguru) dhèu.<bt>If (we) add the two children of Yusuf, whom their mother bore in Masir, Yakob and all his children-grandchildren, were 70 people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="habaʔah: in this case, who ended"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">habaʔah: in this case, who ended up in Egypt (two grandkids already there) End of P section.<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob paraga hari dènge ana na Yusuf<bt>Yakob meets up again with his child Yusuf</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ropa ra dètu dènge Masir, Yakob pua Yahuda la'e uuru, paroa Yusuf ho mai paraga dènge ne ètu Gosen. Ropa ra d'ai Gosen,<bt>When they were nearing Masir, Yakob sent Yahuda oging ahead, to summon Yusuf to come meet with him in Gosen. When they arrived in Gosen,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="samech - major section, P readings"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">samech - major section, P readings for the year, thru 48; 49:1-26 is another, then 49:27-c50 lfanayw: ahead of him (twice<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>horot (yrh hif inf): direct, teach. No direct object, problematic.</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Yusuf ca'e nare kareta na, mai paraga dènge ama na. Ropa ra paraga, liku nare ama na, ka na tangi nèbhu bia.<bt>Yusuf got onto a cart, coming to meet with his father. When they met, he embraced his father, and cried for a very long time.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʔəSor: tie the chariot to the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yeʔəSor: tie the chariot to the horses, harness the chariot; bind himself with a vow? prohibit? merkavto: his chariot, a two-wheeled vehicle pulled by horses. There were war chariots, state chariots used for parades, and traveling chariots<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>liqraʔt: to confront, but in a good sense, more like "meet" vayeraʔ (nif): be seen, appear<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>vayyippol (npl qal): he fell ʕal-tsawwaʔraw: on his neck, embraced him - emotional scene. Rashi, Jacob did not reciprocate the same way. But it's told from Joseph's point of view, so the brothersʔ reaction might be taken for granted, and Jacob's likewise. Parallel to Joseph meeting his brothers.<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>yevk: cried ʕod: for a time<span class="Italic">(29)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00753c.tif" rtfFormat="width:8.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:bottom">Yusuf paraga dènge ama na Yakob<bt>Yusuf meets with his father Yakob</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Hèia Yakob padhai lii dènge Yusuf, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ana, ee! Ja'a unu ku kèdhi le èu. Aa ja'a ke'a le èu mamuri era. De ladhe ja'a madhe èèna ka oo, ngaa-ngaa tao heka.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob spoke with Yusuf, saying, &lt;&lt;My child, ee! I have seen you for myself. And I know that you are still alive. So even if I die now, it doesn't matter anymore.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔamutah (mwt): let me die; I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔamutah (mwt): let me die; I am willing to die, -h cohortative hapaʕam: once, at last, now<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>ʔachrey: afterwards rʔoti (rʔh inf cs): for me to see<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>ʕodkha: you still (not "again")</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ka Yusuf peka dènge a'ari na aa'i-aa'i, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a laku peka ku dènge dhèu aae, sèna ka ne'a na a'ari ja'a mai le nèti Kana'an.<bt>And Yusuf spoke to all his elder-younger siblings, saying, &lt;&lt;I will go speak to the king, so that he knows that my relatives have come from Kana'an.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeʕleh: let me go up (not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔeʕleh: let me go up (not to Canaan, but to Pharaoh mauka Goshen? Or going to the top) cohortative in group setting, open to group veto - in grammars, Jouen, Gesenius. Segol he, no qamets. vʔaggidah (ngd hif imperf): and I will report, inform (cohortative)<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>ʔomrah: I propose to say (cohortative)</Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Aa, pe ja'a peka kahèi dènge ne, miu biasa ani kahib'i-kalèbho dènge sapi. Nèti èèna ka, miu mèti dènge badha-manu dènge mèdha-panyau miu nèti Kana'an.<bt>And I will also tell him that you-pl normally raise goat-sheep, and cows. That is why you have brought along your animals and possessions from Kana'an.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roʕe (rʕh partcpl cs): into caring"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">roʕe (rʕh partcpl cs): into caring for tsoʔn: small cattle (sheep and goats) - Egyptians donʔt like sheep or nomads, but Joseph shrewdly buffers the meeting, doesn't say they are traders<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>ʔanshe miqneh: cattle breeders; people who own their own cattle (miqneh ʔproperty, livestockʔ). Not coming as freeloaders or refugees or boat people. vəqaram: their herds, cattle (FF 62)<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="33" />De ladhe dhèu aae paroa miu, ho na karèi miu biasa sab'a ngaa,<bt>So, if the king summons you, to ask about what your normal work is,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vhayah ki-: v- it will happen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vhayah ki-: v- it will happen that (=and then)? when he summons you, he will say ... [?] yiqraʔ: he will summon<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="34" />na, miu dhaa ne peka na, miu se aa'i-aa'i mi nèti ana iiki ka mai piara badha, sama sèmi bèi-baki ji'i. Sèna ka na pua miu pea ètu rai Gosen.&gt;&gt; Yusuf peka sèmi èèna, lula dhèu Masir madenge pea pa'èci dènge ana madhutu badha.<bt>you need to respond saying that you all from small age onward have raise animals, just like your ancestors. So that he will order you to stay in the land of Gosen.&gt;&gt; Yusuf said this, because the Masir people are repugnant to live together with animal herders.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="minʕurenu (nʕurim): from our youth baʕavur:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">minʕurenu (nʕurim): from our youth baʕavur: in order that<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>teshvu (yshv): you may live toʕavat: they loathe, abhor, treat as an abomination, with horror, detestable 43:22. Ramses III had 3,000 people taking care of cattle. 1 Kg 4, daily provisions 10 fattened cows, 10 range ...<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu aae hia a'ari Yusuf era pea<bt>The king gives a place to live to Yusuf's relatives</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="47" />
      <v n="1-2" />Èle èèna ka, Yusuf dènge a'ari na dhèu lèmi, lasi paraga dènge dhèu aae. D'ai madha dhèu aae, ka Yusuf patadha si dènge dhèu aae, ka na peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama dhèu aae! Ama ku dènge a'ari ku mai le nèti Kana'an. Rèngu mai dènge kahib'i-kalèbho, sapi, dènge mèdha-panyau aa'i-aa'i ra. Nuka ra ètu rai Gosen nèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Yusuf and five of his siblings went to meet with the king. Arriving before the king, Yusuf introduced them to the king, and said, &lt;&lt;Father king! My father and my relatives have come from Kana'an. They've come with their goat-sheep, cows, and all their (other) possessions. Now they are off in the land of Gosen.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaged (ngd hif): announced hinnam: focus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yaged (ngd hif): announced hinnam: focus marker: calls attention to next sentence or next word or the preceding word. As a discourse marker: response after being summoned: Here am I! or introduces unexpected event, or introduces a challenge. As a conjunction: introduces observation, or introduces a condition or assumption; here they are! Fait accompli with Joseph's relatives, wisely planned and scripted.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>miqtseh: from the end, border; to the last man vayyatstsigem (ytsg hif imperf): he set them; brought them forward, produced them -- an official introduction<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00755c.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Yusuf padhai lii dènge dhèu aae Masir<bt>Yusuf speaks with the king of Masir</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Dhèu aae karèi si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sasab'a miu ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>The king asked them, saying, &lt;&lt;What is your work?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ra dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i se, ana madhutu badha, sama sèmi bèi-baki ji'i sèra.<bt>They responded, saying, &lt;&lt;We here, are animal herders, just like our ancestors.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maʕəseykhem: what's your line of work,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">maʕəseykhem: what's your line of work, occupation? roʕeh tsoʔn: taking care of small animals (specifically sheep and goats). How did they keep from offending the Pharaoh?<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>gam ... gam: as we do, so our ancestors did</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Limuri ne'e, ètu rai ji'i Kana'an, hèru hadhu madhera, ka nganga'a dènge j'u'u tèdhi heka. Nèti èèna ka, ji'i mai taha asa kabarai ne'e. Ngèti dènge badha-manu ji'i. De ji'i manèngi ama dhèu aae, ho hia ji'i pea ètu rai Gosen, sèna ka ji'i piara badha ji'i ètu nèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Now, in our-exc land of Kana'an, there is a long drought, and there is no food or grass to be found/seen. Therefore, we have come temporarily to this country. We have brought our animals. so, we request father king, to allow us to stay in the land of Gosen, so that we can raise our animals there.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lagur (inf): dwell as an alien."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">lagur (inf): dwell as an alien. Not necessarily temporary; we want to immigrate without native born status. mirʕeh: pasturage<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>khaved: heavy, difficult raʕav: famine<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yeshvu-naʔ: please let them settle down, sit down. Requesting permission to settle</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia dhèu aae padhai lii dènge Yusuf sèmi ne'e: &lt;&lt;Ama mu dènge a'ari mu ètu ne'e le.<bt>Then the king spoke with Yusuf like this: &lt;&lt;Your father and your relatives are already here.</bt><v n="6" />De hud'i laa rèngu tao kabarai ne'e, sama sèmi kabarai rèngu. Madhutu kake'a ja'a, Gosen èèna era dhu be'a risi nèti era leo ètu rai Masir ne'e. De be'a risi rèngu pea ètu èèna ka la. Aa ladhe rèngu cee dhu ladhe-leru badha dènge hua iia, na ja'a hia badha ja'a ho na piara si ètu èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>So, let them treat this country just like it is their country. According to my understanding, Gosen is the best place among other places in this land of Masir. So, it would be best for them to just stay there. And if someone of them is gifted at caring for animals, I will give my animals for him to raise them there.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kakèdhi = penglihatan ; kake'a ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">kakèdhi = penglihatan ; kake'a = pengertian, pemahaman, pengetahuan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hiʔ: = ʔerets meTav: best|i(6) (6)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hiʔ: = ʔerets meTav: best<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>hoshev (yshb hif): to cause to sit, dwell, to be inhabited; settle them chayil: capacity, power, qualified<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>vsamtam (sim): put them in a position, appoint sare: officers in charge of, princes, chiefs<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>miqneh: possession (cattle; fields)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Èle èèna hèia, Yusuf patadhe ama na dènge dhèu aae. Ka Yakob manèngi mi Ama Lamatua, sèna ka hia mèngi-nale mi dhèu aae.<bt>After that, Yusuf introduced his father to the king. And Yakob asked God to give blessings to the king.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mèngi-nale = berkat (kesehatan, harta benda,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">mèngi-nale = berkat (kesehatan, harta benda, keuntungan)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyaveʔ (bwʔ hif): he brought yaʕəmidehu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayyaveʔ (bwʔ hif): he brought yaʕəmidehu (ʕmd hif): to stand; to stand (before), i.e. serve, minister to; to be set over; to confide in; to stand by, defend; to stand firm, remain, endure; to resist; to persist, persevere; to stand still, stop; to stand up, arise; to be constituted, set, appointed; introduced him<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>vayvarekh: formal greeting, asking after well-being, wish long life, O king, live forever</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Dhèu aae karèi Yakob, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama umur pèri tèu kèna?&gt;&gt;<bt>The king asked Yakob, saying, &lt;&lt;How old are you, father?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This is a polite question"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">This is a polite question</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00757c.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Yusuf dènge Yakob padhai lii dènge dhèu aae Masir<bt>Yusuf and Yakob speak to the king of Masir</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Yakob dhaa, &lt;&lt;Umur ja'a cangasu tèlu nguru tèu kèna, te ngaa ja'a pea boe mi ca era sa. Bèi-baki ja'a sèmi èèna kahèi. Ladhe pakasame dènge rèngu, na umur ja'a kura nèti rèngu. Te ngaa mamuri ja'a pènu dènge j'aj'èra.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yakob responded, &lt;&lt;My age is 130 years, but I have not just lived in one place. My ancestors also were the same. If (one) compares with them, my age is less than theirs. But my life have been full of difficulties/suffering.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mguwray: my stay, my residence, my"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">mguwray: my stay, my residence, my stays in various places, not as a citizen mʔat: hundred<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>mʕaT: few, little raʕim: bad quality, ugly, disagreeable, no value, adverse<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>hissigu (sgh hif): make great; reach the same number, attain to ʔavotim: Abraham and Isaac<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Hèia Yakob manèngi parmisi neo lèpa. Te ngaa kalua mèka nèti d'ara èmu, na manèngi hari ca tèka mi Lamatua ho sèna ka hia berkat mi dhèu aae.<bt>Then Yakob asked permission (loan) to return home. But before he left the house/palace, he again asked God2 to give blessing2 to the king.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="berkat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">berkat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayetseʔ: he went out (formal leave-taking)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayetseʔ: he went out (formal leave-taking)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Èle èèna ka, Yusuf pad'elo era pea hia a'ari na si ètu Gosen, madhutu lii pua dhèu aae deo na. Era èèna be'a titu kèna. (Ra pangare era èèna &lt;Rameses&gt;.) Ka ama na dènge a'ari na sèra pea taruu ètu èèna.<bt>After that, Yusuf designated a place for his relatives to live in Gosen, following the recent command of the king. That place was very good. (They called that place &lt;Rameses&gt;.) And his father and his relatives continued to live there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayoshev (yshv hif): settle, let them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayoshev (yshv hif): settle, let them live somewhere ʔachuzzah: landed property, long term<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>tsiwwah (tswh): order, direct, command</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Hèia Yusuf sadia nganga'a hia ama na, a'ari na, dènge ana dhèu èmu ra, aa'i-aa'i ra, nèti dhèu kapai toke d'ai ana susu.<bt>Then Yusuf supplied food for his father, his elder-younger siblings, and their children-spouses, all of them, from the adults until the nursing babies.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ana susu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">ana susu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaykhalkel (polpel) ... lechem: he provided"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vaykhalkel (polpel) ... lechem: he provided food (over and over) lfi: for the mouth of, their need<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>Taf: lexicon says "drops" [?], but could be those who are not strong enough to march: women, children, and the elderly</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tèu manganga ètu rai Masir<bt>The famine time in the land of Masir</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Taa èèna, rai manganga titu kèna, tèdhi boe nganga'a ca lamusi sa ètu mia-mia. Nèti Masir toke Kana'an, dhèu-dhèu manganga roe ca palèpa, taga nèti ra'a-rinu heka. Dhèu bisa heka sab'a ngaa-ngaa, lula manganga titu kèna.<bt>At that time, the famine was great/severe, with not even a little bit of food anywhere. From Masir to Kana'an, people were so weak from hunger they were run-down, because there was no more food-drink. People could no longer do any work, because their hunger was so great.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʕav: famine telah (lhh): the land"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">raʕav: famine telah (lhh): the land was languishing, in bad shape<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>mippəne: as a result of</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Dhèu-dhèu nèti d'ara rae-rae ètu Masir, sèmi èèna kahèi dhèu-dhèu nèti d'ara rae-rae ètu Kana'an, mai hèli nganga'a ètu Yusuf. Doi-doi dhu na sèmi sèra, na pakaboko aa'i ka, la'e tèke asa èmu dhèu aae.<bt>People from the villages of Masir, and people from the villages of Kana'an, came to buy food from Yusuf. The money which he received from them, he collected it all, and took it to store in the house of the king.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayəlaqqeT (piʕel): Joseph gathered in all"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayəlaqqeT (piʕel): Joseph gathered in all the money -- Joseph wen collect all da money from da peopo? o all da money end up with Joseph? Scraped up. Gleaning, not much left, dredging up nimtsaʔ (nif): that was to be found<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>shever: grain hem: them<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>shovrim: people buying grain, act of buying yaveʔ (hif): brought<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Tèu èèna, èla aa'i doi dhèu Masir dènge dhèu Kana'an ka ra bisa heka hèli nganga'a. Hèia ra mai roma iisi mi Yusuf, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama wakil! Hia ku ji'i nganga'a ciki la, sèna ka ji'i baku madhe manganga. Te doi ji'i, èla aa'i mèu-mèu le.&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time, all the money of the people of Masir and the people of Kana'an ran out, and they couldn't buy anymore food. So they came complaining-seeking-mercy to Yusuf, saing, &lt;&lt;Father rep! Give us a little food, so that we don't die from hunger. Cuz our money is all gone.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ca palèpa = lemah suak, sonde"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">ca palèpa = lemah suak, sonde bisa bagarak; 15: roma iisi = mengeluh meminta belas kasihan (seeking pity/mercy)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayitom (tmm): The money ran out,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayitom (tmm): The money ran out, got used up, spent, gone vayaboʔu: they came, not all at once, but probably family by family, or delegations<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>havah (yhv imperv): give namut: we die<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>negdekha: in front of you ʔafeS: ceased = yitom?<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Hèia Yusuf dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe tare'a doi miu aad'o heka, na sèmi ne'e ka la! Mèti badha miu, ho pasilu dènge nganga'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf responded, saying, &lt;&lt;If it is true that you have no more money, this is how it will be! Bring your animals, to exchange for food.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="havu (yhv imperv): give (mortage?) miqnekhem:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">havu (yhv imperv): give (mortage?) miqnekhem: your possessions (property, fields). Livestock in general, not individual cows.<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>ʔetnah lakhem (ntn imperf): I will give to you (elliptical object). ʔafeS: come to an end<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ka dhèu se'e mai pasilu badha ra dènge nganga'a. Badha-badha sèmi jara, kahib'i-ka'ia, kahib'i-kalèbho, sapi, dènge keled'ei. Lula tèu èèna, Yusuf dhu moa tèke le.<bt>So these people came and exchanged their animals for food. They were animals like horses, goats, sheep, cows, and donkeys. Because that year, Yusuf had instructed that.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hia pasilu nganga'a dènge badha sèmi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">hia pasilu nganga'a dènge badha sèmi èèna.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaviʔu (bwʔ hif): brought basusim: in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yaviʔu (bwʔ hif): brought basusim: in exchange for horses, 1st time mentioned<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>vaynahlem (nhl piel): guide, help along, saw them through, supply them with</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Tèu mai na, rèngu mai hari sa madha Yusuf, ka ra peka, &lt;&lt;Ama wakil, ee! Ji'i peka tare'a-re'a kèna. Doi ji'i dènge badha ji'i ama pasilu aa'i-aa'i le. Limuri ne'e, ji'i dènge heka ngaa-ngaa. Dhu ètu ji'i dhodhoka ngi'u dènge rai ji'i di.<bt>The next year, they came again before Yusuf, and said, &lt;&lt;Father rep, ee! We-exc are speaking the truth. Our money and our animals, you have exchanged all of them. So now we have nothing else. All we have is only our bodies, and our land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="titom (tmm): be completed, consumed yavoʔu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">titom (tmm): be completed, consumed yavoʔu: they came<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>shenit: second nkhached: keep hidden, cover up<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>ʔim-tam (tmm): if it is used up miqneh habhemah: cattle, animals<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>nishʔar (nif): remain, left bilti: except, only<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>gəwiyyatenu: our bodies ʔadmatenu: our earth; dust; land, region, country; ground, land, field; our land<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>Does "sell our bodies" imply slavery, or does it sound like prostitution?</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Baku tèke eele ji'i madhe manganga. Te ladhe ji'i madhe na, cee ka dhu sab'a oka-tedhe se'e? De hua iia, ama wakil more ji'i, ho j'aj'i ènu mu. Aa more aa'i rai ji'i kahèi. Pe, èèna na, ama hia hini ho ji'i sèla hia ama. Gaji dènge kab'ua rai ji'i, ama pasilu dènge nganga'a. Sad'i ji'i baku madhe manganga.&gt;&gt;<bt>Don't leave us to die from hunger. Cuz if we die, who will work the fields (doublet)? It would be better if father rep takes us to become your slaves. And take all our land as well. Later, you can give us seed for us to plant for you. The wages and the price of our land, you can exhange for food. As long as we do not die from hunger.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="namut: we die qneh (qnh): acquire,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">namut: we die qneh (qnh): acquire, buy<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>nihyeh: we will be ʕvadim (ʕeved): slaves<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>ten-zeraʕ: give seed; the Nile is still running niHyeh: we will live<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>tesham (shmm): become desolate; to be laid waste, to be withheld</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Lula rai manganga ae, ka dhèu Masir pahie aa'i rai rèngu. Nèti èèna ka, Yusuf hèli nara aa'i rai ètu Masir j'aj'i mi pusaka dhèu aae.<bt>Because the famine was great, the people of Masir sold off all their land. That is why, Yusuf bought up all the land of Masir as an inheritance for the king.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiqen (qnh): acquire, buy, get maxru:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayiqen (qnh): acquire, buy, get maxru: they sold<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>ʔish: each one, one by one. This happened farm by farm, not all at once sadehu: their fields<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>Hazaq: the famine lay heavy on them; to be heavy = severe, difficult (of events) thi (fem): it became<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna ka, dhèu Masir aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i ènu nèti dhèu aae.<bt>In this way, all the people of Masir became slaves of the king.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕam: a people, viewed as an"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʕam: a people, viewed as an ethnic unit with internal solidarity, but may also be used for part of an ethnic group or the people associated with a leader heʕvir (ʕvr hif): made them pass through an area, sent them to the other side, turned his eyes to the other side, cause someone to cross over. Probably Joseph did it. OR made them slaves Samar, LXX heʕvid<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>leʕarim (ʕir): to the cities (also means populations of cities) needed so that they could move massive quantities of food miqtseh ... vʕad qatsehu: from a border ... as far as their border<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>gvol-mitsraim: from the border that is the boundary of Egypt, same word for the country and the people, always sounds like a plural, with mitsri as a rare gentilic noun or adjective Maybe "make um move house from one side Egypt to da odda side"?<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="47:21" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Abhu sasuri lii Ibrani dhu peka kahèi na &lt;&lt;Yusuf pidha eele dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra asa d'ara kota.&gt;&gt;<bt>There are Ibrani language writings which also say &lt;&lt;Yusuf moved everyone inside the cities.&gt;&gt;</bt></note><v n="22" />Dhoka rai unu ama agama sèra di, Yusuf hèli nare boe, te dhèu aae hia taruu dhèu se nganga'a na. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu se pahie boe rai rèngu.<bt>Only the land owned by the religious heads, Yusuf did not buy, cuz the king continued to give them food. That is why these people didn't sell their land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raq: only choq (chqq), chuqqam: something"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">raq: only choq (chqq), chuqqam: something prescribed; portion, limit of life, task, something due to the priests (their income)<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Lod'o èèna, Yusuf peka dènge ana kabarai sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Naa! Miu j'aj'i le ènu nèti dhèu aae. Ja'a hèli kore aa'i le, rai miu hia dhèu aae. De mere hini se'e ho lami sèla ka mi dedha rai sèra.<bt>At that time, Yusuf spoke with the populace, saying, &lt;&lt;Naa! You have become slaves for the king. I have bought off all your land for the king. So, take this seed to go plant on that land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hen: 3 pl fem pronoun. Text?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hen: 3 pl fem pronoun. Text? heʔ-lakhem: lo, behold, to you<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>zeraʕ: seed zraʕtem: plant them<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Ladhe miu puu-g'ètu na, bagi mi lèmi. Ho ca pala hia dhèu aae. Aa èpa pala sèra, miu tao hini dènge mi pake mi'a-minu dènge a'ari miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>When you harvest (doublet), divide it into five. One portion is for the king. And four portions are for you to use for seed and to eat-drink with your relatives.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="puu-g'ètu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">puu-g'ètu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təvuʔot: whenever there are harvests (produce"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">təvuʔot: whenever there are harvests (produce or yield of the land) ntatem: you will give them<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>chəmiyshiyt: one fifth, 20% ʔarbaykhʕ: four<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>hayadot (yad): hands, places; parts? laʔsher: for whatever<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>bateykhem: your homes ləTapxem (Taf):for your children<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Hèia ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama pamamuri ji'i le, de ji'i manèngi tarima kasi. Ji'i neo j'aj'i ènu nèti dhèu aae.&gt;&gt;<bt>So they responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Father (you) have saved (cause to live) us, so we are grateful. We want to become slaves of the king.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hechəyitanu (chyh hif): you caused us"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hechəyitanu (chyh hif): you caused us to live, kept us alive, preserved us nimtsaʔ-chen bʕeyney (impf): we will find favor in your eyes, may we ...h<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Nèti èèna ka, Yusuf tao madha j'ara ne'e, j'aj'i ad'a kabarai ètu Masir. Ladhe ra puru rare are na, ra bagi mi lèmi pala. Ho ca pala rèngu hia mi dhèu aae. Aa èpa pala rèngu abhu. Te ngaa rai ama agama sèra, dhèu aae hèli boe. Ad'a èèna, ra pake taruu.<bt>Because of that, Yusuf made that a regulation, and it became adat for the populace of Masir. When they harvested their grain, they divided it into five parts. So one part they gave to the king. And four parts they got. But the land of the religious heads, the king did not buy. That adat, they used continually./they continue to use.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu saba = pegawai; dhèu saba"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">dhèu saba = pegawai; dhèu saba oka tedhe = kuli ; ènu = jongos</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yasem (sym): put, established ʔotah (fem):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yasem (sym): put, established ʔotah (fem): it<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>ləchoq: as a share, allotment (food, territory, work) ʔadmat: land<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>lachomesh: fifth part raq: only<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>lvadam: only for them</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf jaji na nèngu padhane ama na Yakob ètu era ro'a bèi-baki ra<bt>Yusuf promises that he will bury his father Yakob in the burial place of their ancestors</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Karèi nèti lod'o èèna, dhèu Isra'el pea taruu ka ètu Masir, ètu rai Gosen. Ra j'aj'i dhèu kaja, aa ana-èpu rèngu asa tabha ae.<bt>From then on, the people of Isra'el continued to live in Masir, in the land of Gosen. They became rich people, and their descendants kept increasing in number.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishev: sat down, settled vayeʔachazu (ʔchz"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yishev: sat down, settled vayeʔachazu (ʔchz nif): they lay hold of, grasped; they were seized?<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>vayifru (prh): they were fruitful, multiplied vayirbu (rbh): they became numerous<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ètu Masir, Yakob mamuri hari 17 (canguru pidhu) tèu era. J'aj'i umur Yakob aa'i-aa'i ra, 147 (cangasu èpa nguru pidhu) tèu.<bt>In Masir, Yakob lived another 17 years. So the age of Yakob all up, was 147 years.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yHi (Hyh): lived, was alive shvaʕ"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yHi (Hyh): lived, was alive shvaʕ ʕesreh: 17<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>shne Hayaw: the years of his life shevaʕ: 7<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>ʔarbaʕim umʔat: 140</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Lod'o dètu na madhe èèna, na paroa Yusuf, ka na padhai lii dènge ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ana Yusuf! Ja'a rasa na, mamuri ja'a madhera heka. Nèbhu heka, Lamatua paroa ja'a lèpa kèna. Èèna ka ja'a manèngi sèna ka ladhe èu sue ja'a, èu subha sèna ka baku padhane ja'a ètu rai Masir ne'e.<bt>When approaching his death, he summoned Yusuf, and spoke with him saying, &lt;&lt;Child Yusuf! I feel that, my life doesn't have long to go. Soon, the Lord will call me home [yes, it is or has become a Dhao idiom for death too]. So I ask that if you love me, you swear and oath that you will not bury me here in the land of Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyiqrvu: they drew near, came near"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayyiqrvu: they drew near, came near (the days for Israel to die) vayyiqraʔ: he summoned, called<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>ʔim-naʔ matsaʔti chen bʕeyneyka: Please, if I have found favor in your eyes. In terms of Joseph's position and power? He's asking for a lot of effort. sim-naʔ: I would like you to put<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>yrekhi: fleshy portion of my upper thigh, the back part (where the angel touched Jacob Gn 32:32), area of sexual organs where the hand was placed when making a solemn oath, also in 46:26 chesed: obligation to the community, solidarity, loyalty of a son to a dying father<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>veʔmet: reliability, security, permanence, lasting kindness (khesed veʔmet), fidelity, faithfully, truly ʔal-naʔ: donʔt<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>tiqbreni: you bury me</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Èu hud'i mèti ngi'u aae ja'a, ho padhane asa era ro'a bèi-baki èdhi. Ho èu padhane ja'a ètu èèna. Ne'e ne, dad'èi d'ara ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>You must take my body, to bury it in the burial place of our-inc ancestors. You must bury me there. This is the will/desire of your father.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yusuf dhaa ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Be'a ama! Ladhe dad'èi ama ku kèna, na ja'a madhutu.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yusuf responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Good, father! If that is your will, I will follow/obey.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vshakhavti: I will lie down, sleep"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vshakhavti: I will lie down, sleep (means he's going to die) unsaʔtani: you will carry me up (Egypt to Canaan is always "up")<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>biqvuratam: in their burial place, grave, tomb</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ka Yakob padhai lii hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;De ladhe sèmi èèna, èu hud'i subha uuru ku, ho ke'a na èu madhutu dad'èi ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yakob spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;So, if that is how it is, you must swear-oath first, so I know that you will follow your father's will.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yusuf subha madhutu dad'èi Yakob. Ka Yakob patitu kètu urutuu ètu dedha era j'unu na, ka na manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua.<bt>So Yusuf swore-oath according to the will of Yakob. And Yakob knelt on top of the bed/sleeping place, and he gave thanks to God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="subha uuru ku = sumpah dulu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">subha uuru ku = sumpah dulu ( buktikan pengakuan ) ; subha uru = melakukan sumpah mendahului orang lain.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishavʕah (shb nif imperv): yishtaHu (Hyh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hishavʕah (shb nif imperv): yishtaHu (Hyh hitp): he bowed his head (to Joseph)? To God? Rashi, upon the head of the bed, the divine presence above the head of the sick man? Standard ritual for oath.<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>ʕal-rosh: over the head (does this refer to the bed? Rashi takes it to be that.) ha miTah: the couch; ha maTih ʔstaffʔ? LXX.<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob manèngi Lamatua ho hia mèngi-nale mi ana-ana Yusuf, Efraim dènge Manase<bt>Yakob asked God2 to give blessing to Yusuf's children, Efraim and Manase</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="48" />
      <v n="1" />Nèbhu boe ka, dhèu lasi peka dènge Yusuf na, ama na pèd'a aae. Hèia la'e nèti dènge ana na, Efraim dènge Manase, sèna ka lasi ladhe baki ra Yakob.<bt>Not long after that, people went and told Yusuf that his father was very sick. So he went taking his children Efraim and Manase, so they could go see their grandfather Yakob.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hinneh: just choleh: weak, tired, ill|i(1)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hinneh: just choleh: weak, tired, ill<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ropa Yakob tadèngi Yusuf si mai le, ka na pakaseti madhèdi.<bt>When Yakob heard that Yusuf mob had come, he forced himself to sit up.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatyagged (ngd hif imperf): [somebody] announced"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vatyagged (ngd hif imperf): [somebody] announced to Jacob vayyitchazeq (chzq hitp): took courage, showed himself courageous, took strength; Jacob sat up in bed, but it took almost all his strength CEV. Showing respect to Joseph. Also used of Joseph pulling himself back together after crying.<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Hèia na padhai lii dènge Yusuf, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ana Yusuf, ee! Ama Lamatua dhu dènge Koasa Kapai Risi na, uru èèna, Na pad'elo le iisi Na dènge ja'a ètu rae Lus, ètu rai Kana'an. Ètu nèi, Na moa tèke mi ja'a.<bt>Then he told Yusuf, saying, &lt;&lt;Child Yusuf, ee! God who is Most Powerful, previously He revealed Himself to me at the village of Lus, in the land of Kana'an. At that (remote) place, He promised/instructed me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shadday: traditionally: Almighty One; better: All-sufficient"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">shadday: traditionally: Almighty One; better: All-sufficient One (= the One every good and perfect gift comes from). The rabbinic analysis of this word is that it is a compound word composed of the relative she, "who" and the word day, "enough: she-day," the one who is (self-)sufficient" (Babylonian Talmud, Hagigah 12a)... Another possibility, and this is the most widely accepted today, is that shadday is to be connected with the Akkadian word, s]adu "mountain." Thus El Shaddai would translate into English something like "God/EI of the mountain," i.e. God's abode. nirʔah-ʔelay (nif): be seen, appear<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>vayvarekh ʔoti (brk piʕel): bestow power for success, prosperity, fertility, declare that someone has been given power for success, prosperity, fertility (like the Army slogan "Be all you can be"</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Na padhai lii, peka na, &lt;Bèli-camèd'a Ja'a hia ana-èpu èu j'aj'i ae, ho rèngu j'aj'i suku dhu kapai. Rai ne'e ne, ja'a hia j'aj'i unu rèngu, ho j'aj'i pusaka ra toke d'ai rai-haha èle.&gt;<bt>He spoke, saying, &lt;In the future, I will give you many descendants, so they become a great tribe. This land here, I give to become their property, as their inheritance (assim loan) to the end of the world.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hinəni: here I am, I am"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hinəni: here I am, I am now making you fruitful. mafrkha (prk hif ptcpl): making you fruitful (lots of descendants)<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>vhirbitikha: (rbh hif): I have made you have many children, have made you great untatikha liqhal ʕamim (ntn): I have given you an assembly of nations; God promised not just to give Israel a lot of descendants, but that a whole company of different nations would descend from him.<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ʔachuzat: property</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Aa ana èu Efraim dènge Manase èèna, hak rèngu sèmi ne'e ka: lod'o dhu ja'a d'ai Masir na, mere iisi le rèngu dua ra. Masi ka sèmi èèna, ja'a tao rèngu sèmi ana d'èlu ja'a, sama sèmi Ruben dènge Simeon.<bt>And, your children Efraim and Manase, their rights are like this: When I arrived in Masir, the two of them were already here. Even that being the case, I make them like my own birth children, just like Ruben and Simeon.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hanoladim (yld nif partcpl): who were"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hanoladim (yld nif partcpl): who were born ʕad-boʔi (bwʔ inf cs): before my coming<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>li-hem: they will be mine (= adoption)</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Aa ladhe bèli-camèd'a èu abhu hari ana, na èèna di unu èu kèna. Ja'a tao boe rèngu sèmi ana d'èlu ja'a. Pe pusaka ra, rèngu abhu nèti a'a ra, Efraim dènge Manase.<bt>And if, in the future, you have more children, those are your own (property). I will not make them like my own birth children. Later, their inheritance, they will get from their older-siblings, Efraim and Manase.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="moladtkha (moledet): offspring, family holadta (yld"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">moladtkha (moledet): offspring, family holadta (yld hif): that you may father<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʕal shem ʔəchehem: more than the name of their brothers - domination? bnachlatam: taking possession, occupation of; possession, domain; inheritance; lot (assigned by God); as far as their property rights are concerned? Rashi thinks so.<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ja'a tao sèmi èèna, sèna ka èdhi sanèd'e ina mu Rahel. Lod'o ji'i mai nèti Mesopotamia asa Kana'an, d'ai talora j'ara, ina mu madhe ropa nara iisi aa'i. Èèna na, ji'i dètu rae Efrata ètu rai Kana'an. Lod'o èèna, ja'a susa d'ai seli. Ka ja'a padhane ne ètu sebhe j'ara la'e asa rae Efrata.&gt;&gt; (Limuri ne, rae èèna ra gati ngara na <span class="Italic">Betlehem</span>.)<bt>I am doing that, so that we remember your mother Rahel. When we came from Mesopotamia to Kana'an, on the journey, your mother died while giving birth. There, we were near the village of Efrata in the land of Kana'an. At that time, I was in great strife. And I buried her along the side of the road going to the village of Efrata.&gt;&gt; (Now, that village has changed its name to <span class="Italic">Betlehem</span>.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haji = roba (nama)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">haji = roba (nama)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="metah ʕali: she died on me;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">metah ʕali: she died on me; and it affected me deeply bʕod kivrat-ʔerets: a stretch of land; a little distance. About The amount of land you can cover in two hours.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ropa Yakob<bt>When Yakob</bt><note reference="48:8" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Ibrani peka na &lt;&lt;Isra'el padhai lii&gt;&gt;.<bt>Ibrani language writings say &lt;&lt;Isra'el spoke&gt;&gt;.</bt></note>padhai lii nare sèmi èèna hèia, na boti kètu na, ladhe nèdhi ana-ana Yusuf ètu èèna. Hèia na karèi Yusuf, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Se'e se, ana cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>finished speaking like that, he lifted his head, and saw Yusuf's children there. So he asked Yusuf, saying, &lt;&lt;These here, whose children are they?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="boti kètu = angkat kapala"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">boti kètu = angkat kapala</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qachem (lqch imperv): bring them kavdu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">qachem (lqch imperv): bring them kavdu: were heavy, dull; it means he could barely see anything<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>vayyaggesh (ngsh hif): he brought them close vayyishshaq (nshq): he kissed them<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>vayəchabbeq (piʕel): embraced them</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ka Yusuf dhaa, &lt;&lt;Se'e, ana dhu Ama Lamatua hia ja'a ètu Masir.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yusuf answered, &lt;&lt;These are the children which God gave me in Masir.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Yakob peka hari, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, na hia ra mai padètu dènge ja'a, ho ja'a manèngi Ama Lamatua hia si mèngi-nale.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yakob spoke again, &lt;&lt;If that is the case, have them come near to me, so I can ask God to give them blessing.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="10" />Yakob heka le, aa musi madha na ahu le. Na ladhe nèdhi be'a heka. Hèia Yusuf nèti ana na sèra padètu asa madha Yakob, ka na liku nare si, aa na uu si dua ra.<bt>Yakob was already old, and his eyeballs werre cloudy. He could not see well anymore. So Yusuf took his children near, in front of Yakob, and he embraced them, and he kissed the two of them.</bt><v n="11" />Ka na peka dènge Yusuf, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nèbhu nare sange ne'e, ja'a pangee na, ja'a bisa heka kèdhi rèhu èu. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua, tao risi eele nèti ngaa dhu ja'a ngee, toke ja'a bisa kèdhi ana-ana èu kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>And he spoke to Yusuf, saying, &lt;&lt;For a long time, I have thought that I would never again see your face. But God, has done beyond what I thought, to the point that I could also see your children.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ahu le = kabur ; rango-rango"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">ahu le = kabur ; rango-rango = samar-samar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rʔoh (rʔh inf cs): to see"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">rʔoh (rʔh inf cs): to see loʔ pillalti (piʕel): I had formed an expectation that I would not see you again, I presumed<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>herʔah (hif): God has made/let me see your offspring gam: even?<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Hèia Yusuf hari eele ana na dhèu dua sèra nèti madha Yakob,<bt>Then Yusuf pulled back his two children from in front of Yakob,</bt><note reference="48:12" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Ibrani peka na, &lt;&lt;Yusuf pa'eso ana na nèti talora aae kètu urutuu Yakob.&gt;&gt;<bt>Ibrani language writings say &lt;&lt;Yusuf reversed his children from between Yakob's knees.&gt;&gt;</bt></note>ka na patitu kètu urutuu na, aa na pacud'u rèhu na d'ai rai, ètu madha ama na.<bt>and he knelt, and he bowed his face to the ground, in front of his father.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yotseʔ (ytsʔ hif): he caused them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yotseʔ (ytsʔ hif): he caused them to go meʕim? seated on the bed next to Judah? Theyʔre young men.<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>birkayw: his knee(s); out from between his knees? (Rashi, but improbable) by his knees? yishtaHu (Hyh hitp): he prostrated himself<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>lʔappaw: at his face</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Èle èèna ka, Yusuf kèd'i. Na nare ana na dhèu dua sèra, ka na hia ra titu padètu-dètu dènge ama na. Na patitu ana uuru na Manase, re bèka g'ana Yakob. Aa ana ka dua, Efraim, re bèka kariu Yakob.<bt>After that, Yusuf stood up. He took his two children, and he had them stand near his father. He stood the oldest child Manase, at Yakob's right side. And the second child, Efraim, at Yakob's left side.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yamino: his right hand mismoʔel: on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yamino: his right hand mismoʔel: on the left<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>yagesh (ngsh hif): he made them approach close</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Te ngaa ropa Yakob soro ai na neo manèngi mèngi-nale hia ana dua sèra, na soro ai g'ana na mi kètu Efraim, aa ai kariu mi kètu Manase.<bt>But when Yakob stretched out his hands wanting to bless those two children, he stretched our his right hand to the head of Efraim, and his left hand to the head of Manase.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishlach: stretch out, send yashet (shyt):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yishlach: stretch out, send yashet (shyt): he set, put<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>tsaʕir: the younger one sikel: he laid his hands crosswise<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>habxor: the firstborn</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Ka na manèngi Ama Lamatua hia berkat mi Yusuf, peka na,<bt>And he asked God to give blessings2 to Yusuf, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hari eele = kasi geser ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">hari eele = kasi geser ; iha = pangkuan, lap ; pa'eso = kasi geser</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Baki mu Isak,<bt>&lt;&lt;Your grandfather Isak,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dènge ama na Abraham,<bt>and his father Abraham,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dua ra madhutu taruu dad'èi Ama Lamatua.<bt>the two of the always/continually followed/obeyed the will of God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ama Lamatua ladhe-leru ja'a kahèi, nèti ana ngèru toke d'ai deo ne'e ne.<bt>God has also watched over/cared for me as well, from the time I was a young man until now.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hithalləkhu (hlk hitp): they walked ʔvotay:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hithalləkhu (hlk hitp): they walked ʔvotay: my fathers, ancestors<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>haroʕeh: who shepherded meʕodi: from before continually<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="16" />Na pakaj'èu ja'a nèti rupa-rupa sasusa.<bt>He distanced/saved me from various sorts of difficulties.</bt><note reference="48:16" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Ibrani peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a manèngi sèna ka ana pajuu Ama Lamatua nèti sorga mai ho pakaj'èu nèti ja'a rupa-rupa j'aj'èra.&gt;&gt; Te ngaa abhu kahèi dhèu d'èlu-mèu peka na, Ama Lamatua ka dhu pad'elo iisi Na, ropa Na pake ana pajuu na nèti sorga mai ho patalale Yakob nèti rupa-rupa j'aj'èra. Ladhe ètu <span class="Italic">Lii Lolo Uuru</span> 16:7; 21:17; 22:11,15.<bt>The Ibrani language writing says &lt;&lt;I request that *God's servants from heaven (angels) come free/distance/save me from all kinds of difficulties/sufferings.&gt;&gt; But there are some knowledgable people who say that God revealed Himself when He used his servants from heaven to free Yakob from all kinds of difficulties. See <span class="Italic">Genesis</span> 16:7; 21:17; 22:11,15.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">De ja'a manèngi sèna ka Na hia mèngi-nale mi ana èu se'e, dènge ana-èpu ra.<bt>So, I ask that He give blessing to these children of yours, and their descendants.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa ladhe ra manèngi-mangaj'i mi Ama Lamatua,<bt>And if they worship God,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ra bhèlu boe ale kolongara baki Abraham, kolongara Isak, aa kolongara ja'a,<bt>they will not forget to mention the names/reputations of grandfather Abraham, the name/reputation of Isak, and my name/reputation,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka ana-èpu rèngu asa bèba-kacanga,<bt>so that their descendants will increase greatly (doublet),</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="asa bèb'a ka canga = berkembang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">asa bèb'a ka canga = berkembang biak</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ho j'aj'i kapai ètu rai-haha ne'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>to become great/important on this earth.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="malʔakh: the angel goʔel (partcpl): the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">malʔakh: the angel goʔel (partcpl): the one delivering; first mention of redemption?<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>raʕ: evil yəvarekh: may he bless<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>yiqqareʔ (nif): my name will be called vyidgu (dgh): may they multiply - related to "fish", multiply like fish<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>larov: into a multitude bqerev: interior, in the midst of, here in the world<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Te ngaa ropa Yusuf ladhe nèdhi ama na tao ai g'ana na mi kètu Efraim, hèia kèpe nare ai ama na, ho tao sa kètu a'a na Manase.<bt>But, when Yusuf saw his father had place his right hand on the head of Efraim, then he took his father's hand, to put it on the head of his elder-sibling Manase.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayeraʕ (rʕʕ): he was sad, displeased,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayeraʕ (rʕʕ): he was sad, displeased, discontented, something wrong (raʕ here for a mistake, not absolute evil) vayitmokh: he took hold of his father's hand<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>lhaSiyr (Swr inf): to change it, to put it where it belonged</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ka na peka dènge ama na, &lt;&lt;Ama, ee! Baku tao sèmi èèna. Nèngu ne, ari Efraim. Nèngu ana limuri. De ai g'ana ama hud'i tao sa kètu a'a na Manase. Lula èèna hak ana uuru.&gt;&gt;<bt>And he said to his father, &lt;&lt;Father, ee! Don't do like that. He is younger-sibling Efraim. He is the youngest. So father's right hand must be place on the head of his edler-sibling Manase. Because that is the right of the oldest child.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Te ngaa ama na Yakob d'èi boe. Ka na peka na, &lt;&lt;Ana, ee! Ja'a ke'a. Ladhe èèna na, Manase j'aj'i èra, aa ana-èpu na tabha ae, ho j'aj'i suku kapai. Te ngaa ari na Efraim èèna, bèli-camèd'a kapai risi hari nèti nèngu. Sèmi èèna kahèi ana-èpu na ae risi eele hari, ho ladhe èèna na, rèngu j'aj'i suku-suku dhu kapai aae.&gt;&gt;<bt>But his father Yakob didn't want to. And he said, &lt;&lt;Child, ee! I know. Later on, Manase will become strong, and his descendants will increase (in number), to become a great tribe. But his younger-sibling Efraim, in the future will be even greater than he. Similarly his descendants will be even more, so the in the future they become several great/influential tribes.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaymaʔen: he refused vʔulam: on the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vaymaʔen: he refused vʔulam: on the other hand<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>haqaton: the young(er) one mloʔ: full number, abundance, extent<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ka na peka dènge ana se dua ra, &lt;&lt;Ladhe dhèu Isra'el manèngi Ama Lamatua ho hia mamèngi-nale mi dhèu, rèngu ale ngara miu dua mi hèi. Ladhe èèna na, ra peka sèmi ne'e: &lt;Ji'i sanao sèna ka Ama Lamatua hia mamèngi-nale mi èu, sama sèmi Na hia mi Efraim dènge Manase.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>And he spoke to these two children, &lt;&lt;If the people of Isra'el ask God to give blessing to people, they will also mention your two names. In the future, they will speak like this: &lt;We hope that God gives blessings to you, just as He gave to Efraim and Manase.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dènge j'ara ne'e, Yakob ale uuru ngara Efraim nèti ngara a'a na Manase.<bt>In this way, Yakob mentioned first the name of Efraim, before the name of his elder-sibling Manase.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ysimkha: may he put you lifney:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ysimkha: may he put you lifney: ahead of<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Èle èèna, hèia Yakob padhai lii dènge Yusuf, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ana, ee! Ja'a nèbhu heka madhe. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua dènge miu, ho èèna na nèti hari miu asa era pea-palu'u bèi-baki miu.<bt>After that Yakob spoke to Yusuf, saying, &lt;&lt;Child, ee! I will soon die. But God is with you-pl, so that later (He) will take you back to the place of residence (doublet) of your ancestors.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heshiv (shwb hif): he will take"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">heshiv (shwb hif): he will take you back</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Te ngaa ne'e ne, ja'a hia èu risi eele nèti a'ari èu. Aa ja'a hia tabha èu, ledhe ètu rai Kana'an èèna, dhu uru na ja'a kore nèti dhèu Amori, lod'o ja'a segi rèngu ètu d'ara pamusu.&gt;&gt;<bt>But now, I am giving you more that your elder-younger siblings. An I give adding to you a/the mountain in the land of Kana'an, which previously I took from the Amori people, when I beat them in a war/battle.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rai èta-èsu = tampa kelahiran ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">rai èta-èsu = tampa kelahiran ; èsu = tali pusat, umbilical cord ; èta = potong (pake bambu bidan) ; era pea-palu'u = tempat tinggal ; palu'u = sembunyikan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shkhem: mountain-ridge (shoulder) End of P"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">shkhem: mountain-ridge (shoulder) End of P section.<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob peka tatao ana na si èci-èci, aa manèngi berkat nèti Lamatua<bt>Yakob tells about the deeds/characteristics of each of his children, and asks for blessings2 from God2</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="49" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia Yakob pua ana na aa'i-aa'i ra pakaboko. Ropa ra kaboko aa'i, na peka dènge si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ana ja'a aa'i-aa'i! Mai padètu dènge ja'a. Te ja'a neo peka dènge miu j'ara mamuri mi èci-èci lod'o limuri.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob ordered all of his children to gather. When they had gathered, he spoke to them, saying, &lt;&lt;All my children! Come close to me. Cuz I want to tell you the life way/path for each of you in the future (&lt;days behind).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heʕasfa (nif impv): be gathered, come"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">heʕasfa (nif impv): be gathered, come together ʔagidah (ngd): put forward, announce, explain<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>yiqraʔ: will happen, befall you bʔacharit hayamim: outcome, end of the days<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ka na peka mema dènge ana-ana na si, aku nèngu na,<bt>And he spoke directly to each of his children, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e, ana-ana Yakob! Mai titu lingu mere ja'a.<bt>&lt;&lt;It's like this, children of Yakob! Come and stand around me.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Mi nanene, ama miu Isra'el ne, neo padhai lii.<bt>Listen to me, your-pl father Isra'el wants to speak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hiqqavtsu (nif impv): assemble"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hiqqavtsu (nif impv): assemble</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />
      <span class="Italic">Ruben!</span> Èu ne, ana ja'a dhu uru tèka! Èu ne'e tatea ja'a, dènge ai g'ana ja'a. Dhèu pakab'ua risi èu.<bt><span class="Italic">Ruben!</span> You are my oldest child! You here are my staff, and my right hand (=assistant, rep). People respect/honour you most.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kochi: my strength ʔoni: my generative"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">kochi: my strength ʔoni: my generative power, ability to make a woman pregnant<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>yeter: over and above, remaining, have precedence sʔet: nobility, dignity<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>ʕaz: power, strength</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Te ngaa d'ara èu èra boe, sama sèmi rii dhasi dhu la'e-mai la'e-mai. Cag'ag'a laa, èu lamu j'unu dènge dhèu èmu ja'a, ka pakaj'alu era j'unu ama èu. Tatao èu èèna ka, pamanahu eele kolongara ca dhèu a'a.<bt>But your insides/character is not strong/stable, like currents in the sea going back-and-forth back-and-forth. Suddenly, you go sleep with my spouse, and defile your father's bed. That deed of yours, will cause to fall your rank/reputation as elder-sibling.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paga = pangkat ; rii ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">paga = pangkat ; rii = arus</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Te ngaa dara èu èra boe,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">Te ngaa dara èu èra boe, me'a boe dadèi èu tasa mia. Cag'ag'a laa, èu lamu j'unu dènge dhèu èmu ja'a Bilha, ka pakaj'alu era j'unu ama èu. Tatao èu èèna ka, pamanahu eele paga ca dhèu a'a.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pachaz: undisciplined, reckless: koniaku is kind"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">pachaz: undisciplined, reckless: koniaku is kind of like jello or tofu that isn't stiff, wishy-washy; but only Japanese recognize it. ʔal-towtar (ytr hif): do not excel<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ʔaz (not ʕaz): then? emphasis? chillalta: you profaned<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yətsuwʕi: my couch End of P section.<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />
      <span class="Italic">Simeon</span> dènge <span class="Italic">Lewi!</span> Miu dua mi ca rupa. Miu dua mi, malai titu kèna ded'e samala, ho paj'èra dhèu.<bt><span class="Italic">Simeon</span> and <span class="Italic">Lewi!</span> The two of you are one type/form. The two of you, are quick to pick up the fighting-sword, to cause people trouble/suffering.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kli chamas: an instrument of violence"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">kli chamas: an instrument of violence mkeroteyhem: their weapons; text not clear<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ladhe miu pare pama'ète kalua haga sapi, ho ra kapod'e reo-reo ètu era, na lèke dad'èi miu kèna. Aa bhabhelu miu hari, ladhe miu kadhi ngutu, na mi pamadhe dhèu. Nèti èèna ka, ja'a pahae boe lii padhai lii miu. Aa ja'a d'èi boe tao madha-dhilu mi lii langu miu.<bt>When you cut separating the leg tendon of a cow, so they twist around-and-around in place, it matches your desires. And even more evilly, if you eat/grind teeth (=very angry), then you go and kill someone. That is why I cannot value your words/advice. And I do not want to pay attention to (Idiom: place eye-ear) your disputes.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Sodam: their circle of confidants qəhalam:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">Sodam: their circle of confidants qəhalam: their assembly<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʔal-techad: donʔt join kvodi: my good reputation, my honor<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʔappam: their anger birtsonam: their liking to do arbitrarily whatever they like<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʕiqqəru (piʕel): hamstring, cripple</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Nèti èèna ka, ja'a dhoo bhelu-katub'a miu ne, te seli-kolane nga! Dènge nanasa miu dhu dènge boe sasue ciki sa hèi. Ladhe èèna na, miu pasae unu mi, bhelu-katub'a miu sèra. Ho èèna na, Lamatua ceb'e ana-èpu miu, asa g'ana asa kariu. Ka ra paceb'a asa mia-mia, ètu dedha rai Isra'el.<bt>Therefore, I curse your evil, cuz (they) are beyond the limits! And your anger which has not even a little bit of love/pity. You yourselves will bear (responsibility for/results of) your own evil. So later, God2 will scatter your descendants, to the right and to the left. And they are scattered everywhere on the land of Isra'el.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pahae = menghargai; 7: ceb'e ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">pahae = menghargai; 7: ceb'e = hambur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔarur: cursed ʕevratam: their arrogance|i(7) (7)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔarur: cursed ʕevratam: their arrogance<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>qashatah: harsh, severe ʔechalləqem: I will set them aside, scatter them<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>vʔafitsem (fwts): disperse End of S section.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="hk-lb\lb00047c.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Singa mone dènge singa rena<bt>Male lion (loan) and female lion</bt></fig>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="8" />
      <span class="Italic">Yahuda!</span> Ngara èu ne, sasoa na, &lt;koa-kio&gt;. A'ari èu èèna na ra koa èu, aa ra pacud'u kètu ho pakab'ua èu. Èu ne, j'èli musu èu, toke ra bisa heka doa kètu.<bt><span class="Italic">Yahuda!</span> Your name means &lt;praise&gt;. (doublet) Your elder-younger siblings praise you, and they bow their heads to honour you. You here will step on your enemies, until they can no longer raise their heads.</bt><v n="9" />Èu ne, sama sèmi singa ngèru dhu èra, ho tenge nganga'a unu mu. Aa èu ne, sama sèmi singa mone, dhu tèku iisi neo bhèj'i; èci sa bani boe pagagai dènge èu. Èu kahèi sèmi singa rena, dhu madhenge ana; èci sa bani boe gagu. Èci èèna ka dènge èu. Dhèu èci sa bani boe padadisi, aa bani boe tao macam-macam mi dedha èu.<bt>You here, are like a strong young lion (loan), who hunts for food on its own/for its own food. And you here, are like a male lion, which stretches its body about to go to sleep; nobody dares to flick/bother you. You are also like a female lion, which guards its children; nobody dares to disturb (you). It is the same with you. Nobody dares to bother2 (you), and does not dare to do just anything to you.</bt><v n="10" />Èèna na èu mèd'u paredha. Ana-èpu èu oo rèd'u paredha padhutu-dhutu, toke abhu èci dhu hak nèngu risi eele nèti cahag'e, ho nèd'u paredha na. Ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne'e, pahaha iisi ho nanene lii paredha nèngu hèi.<bt>In the future you will hold rule/authority/government. Even your descendants will hold rule in succession, until there is one who has rights more than others, to hold that rule. And all the peoples on this earth, will also humble themselves to listen to/obey his commands.</bt><note reference="49:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 1:3</note><v n="11" />Èèna na, èu ne mamuri dènge karej'e-karae. Èu neo ngaa, na abhu. Èu neo tao ngaa, na j'aj'i! Aa ladhe èèna na, badha-manu, dènge isi rai nèti oka-tedhe èu, asa ae d'ai ceb'e lebhe eele hèi.<bt>Later you will live in happiness (doublet). Whatever you want, you will get. Whatever you want to do, it will happen! And in the future, the animals (doublet), and the produce of the land from your fields (doublet), will increase (in number) to the point that they are thrown out [image of excess abundance].</bt><v n="12" />Nganga'a-nginu èu, dhu be'a hua, aa dhu èle boe.<bt>Your food-drink, is so good, and do not run out.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="koa = puji ; j'èli raruri"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">koa = puji ; j'èli raruri = injak dgn tekanan kaki sambil putar-putar telapak kaki ; doa = 1) angkat (kepala), 2) KM doak; 9: padadisi = pagagai = bakorek, baganggu ; kalau = gerak ; tèku = kunci, tarik; 11: ceb'e lebhe eele = tabuang-buang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="13" />
      <span class="Italic">Sebolon!</span> Rai pusaka dhu èu unu, kapai seli, nèti nebhe dhasi toke d'ai too dènge kota Sidon. Kapa-kapa mai nèti mia-mia ho panahu dènge be'a ètu d'ara hèb'a-namo dhasi èu.<bt><span class="Italic">Sebolon!</span> The land of your inheritance, is huge, from the edge of the sea until arriving at the city of Sidon. Ships (loan) come from everywhere to anchor safely in your harbour (doublet) beach.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chof yamim: beach, shore yishkon: settle"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">chof yamim: beach, shore yishkon: settle down, inhabit<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>lchof: as a harbor? We have the Waiʕanae Boat Harbor here, a major center for sport and small scale fishing. The trawlers and large freighters and passenger ships go out of Honolulu Harbor, and the long liners and sport fisherman go out of Kewalo Basin. End of S section.<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="14-15" />
      <span class="Italic">Isaskar!</span> Èu ne, sama sèmi keled'ei dhu èra, te ngaa èu kètu hadhu papake na aad'o. Ladhe èu j'unu ètu talora j'ara,<bt><span class="Italic">Isaskar!</span> You are like a strong donkey, but your rock head (=stubbornness) is impossible (to deal with). If you go to sleep on the journey, there is nobody who can get you up to continue on the journey. But, if you see that the village at the other end (of the journey) is nice/good, without even anyone ordering you, you carry off your burden and go. That is certainly how you are! [Hamilton discusses credibly a number of problems with majority interpretation as "slaves", both internal to this passage, as well as external, and extrabiblical.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="garem: bones sticking out? strong? castrated?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">garem: bones sticking out? strong? castrated? rovets: lies down on his chest, possibly exhausted from work, or maybe just lazy as the next verse suggests.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>beney hamishpatayim: between his two saddlebags mnuchah: resting-place<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>naʕemah: nice, pleasant, agreeable vayet (nth): bends down his shoulder<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>shikhmo: his shoulders, with both the neck and the back liSbol (Sbl inf): to carry a load<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>maS: lowest form of work, complete enslavement, cheap day labor End of S section.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>garem: bones sticking out? strong? castrated? rovets: lies down on his chest, possibly exhausted from work, or maybe just lazy as the next verse suggests.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>beney hamishpatayim: between his two saddlebags mnuchah: resting-place<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>naʕemah: nice, pleasant, agreeable vayet (nth): bends down his shoulder<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>shikhmo: his shoulders, with both the neck and the back liSbol (Sbl inf): to carry a load<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>maS: lowest form of work, complete enslavement, cheap day labor End of S section.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>garem: bones sticking out? strong? castrated? rovets: lies down on his chest, possibly exhausted from work, or maybe just lazy as the next verse suggests.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>beney hamishpatayim: between his two saddlebags mnuchah: resting-place<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>naʕemah: nice, pleasant, agreeable vayet (nth): bends down his shoulder<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>shikhmo: his shoulders, with both the neck and the back liSbol (Sbl inf): to carry a load<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>maS: lowest form of work, complete enslavement, cheap day labor End of S section.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>garem: bones sticking out? strong? castrated? rovets: lies down on his chest, possibly exhausted from work, or maybe just lazy as the next verse suggests.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>beney hamishpatayim: between his two saddlebags mnuchah: resting-place<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>naʕemah: nice, pleasant, agreeable vayet (nth): bends down his shoulder<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>shikhmo: his shoulders, with both the neck and the back liSbol (Sbl inf): to carry a load<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>maS: lowest form of work, complete enslavement, cheap day labor End of S section.<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="garem: bones sticking out? strong? castrated?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">garem: bones sticking out? strong? castrated? rovets: lies down on his chest, possibly exhausted from work, or maybe just lazy as the next verse suggests.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>beney hamishpatayim: between his two saddlebags mnuchah: resting-place<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>naʕemah: nice, pleasant, agreeable vayet (nth): bends down his shoulder<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>shikhmo: his shoulders, with both the neck and the back liSbol (Sbl inf): to carry a load<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>maS: lowest form of work, complete enslavement, cheap day labor End of S section.<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="49:14" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Ibrani, pake dua sasoa: &lt;&lt;bhèj'i ètu talora dua era&gt;&gt; dènge &lt;&lt;j'unu ètu talora dua mèdha pasaa&gt;&gt;.<bt>According to the Ibrani language, there can be two meanings: &lt;&lt;sleep between two places&gt;&gt; or &lt;&lt;sleep between two cargo sacks&gt;&gt;.</bt></note>dhèu èci sa bisa boe pakèd'i èu ho kako taruu. Te ngaa ladhe èu mèdhi rae ètu ca bèka nèi be'a, èci sa dhae pua mèka èèna ka, mu pasae mèti le mèdha-panyau èu ho lamu. Tatu èu sama sèmi èèna ka!</p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="16" />
      <span class="Italic">Dan!</span> Ngara èu ne, sasoa na, &lt;dhèu pama'ète lii&gt;. Aa èu ne, dènge ana-èpu èu, ladhe bèli-camèd'a pama'ète lii nèti dhèu èu Isra'el sèra, dènge boe bia ca bèka.<bt><span class="Italic">Dan!</span> Your name means, &lt;person who decides disputes (=judge)&gt;. So you and your descendants will in the future decide the disputes of your own people of Isra'el, and not be unfair/unjust (Idiom: not be heavy on one side).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yadin (dyn): will judge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">yadin (dyn): will judge</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Aa èu ne, sama èci èèna ka dènge mege kaisao dhu j'unu ètu sebhe j'ara. Dhèu ca'e jara ho èèna na, èu kadhi haga jara èèna nèti kabodho, toke dhèu manahu sa rai.<bt>And you are like a green-tailed snake [only type of poisonous snake around] which sleeps at the side of the road. A person on a horse goes there, and you bite the foot/leg of the horse from behind, resulting in the person falling to the ground.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mege kai-sao = ular ijo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">mege kai-sao = ular ijo</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shfifon: possibly the horned snake, Zamenis"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">shfifon: possibly the horned snake, Zamenis diadema. There are 23 species of snakes around the Palestine area (though this was in Egypt), and 20 of them are poisonous.&gt;&gt; ʔorach: way, path<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʕiqqəvey: hooves of horses vayipol (nfl impf): fall down<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>rokhvo: his rider</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />O LAMATUA! Ja'a ke'a na Èu hia mamuri mi ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi.<bt>O LORD! I know that You will give life/save all of us.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lishuʕatkha (yshwʕ): for your help qiwwiti:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">lishuʕatkha (yshwʕ): for your help qiwwiti: I am waiting for something tensely, eagerly -- not just twiddling my thumbs till something happens.<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="19" />
      <span class="Italic">Gad!</span> Ngara èu, lii na oe èci èèna ka dènge, &lt;age&gt;. Ladhe èèna na, dhèu parapo mai age èu, te ngaa èu kabèli hari age si, ka mu segi si.<bt><span class="Italic">Gad!</span> Your name sounds almost the same as &lt;oppose/challenge/attack&gt;. Later on, robbers will come and attack you, but you will turn around and attack them (back), and you will beat them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="papara-pakèj'i = bamusu, potong-tikam ; age"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">papara-pakèj'i = bamusu, potong-tikam ; age = lawan, nantang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gdud: raiding party, troop division, hosts"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">gdud: raiding party, troop division, hosts (pun) ygudenu (gwd): attack (pun)<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>yagud: he will attack aqev: in the end<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="20" />
      <span class="Italic">Aser!</span> Ladhe èèna isi rai nèti oka-tedhe èu be'a risi, d'ai èu tao koki dhu be'a bia, ka dhèu aae-dhèu kapai mai hèli ètu èu.<bt><span class="Italic">Aser!</span> Later on the produce from your fields will be very good, to the point that you can make the best baked-goods, and kings and important people come to buy them from you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shmenah: with oil in it, rich"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">shmenah: with oil in it, rich maʕadannim: delicacies<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="hk-lb\lb00034c.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Badha rusa<bt>Deer animal</bt></fig>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="21" />
      <span class="Italic">Naftali!</span> Èu ne sama sèmi rusa hui, dhu dhèu èci sa ator rare boe èu. Ana-ana matana èu, bhèni iia dènge mone iia.<bt><span class="Italic">Naftali!</span> You are like a wild deer, which nobody is able to manage. Your birth children are female-beautiful and male-handsome.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rusa j'ami = rusa hutan ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">rusa j'ami = rusa hutan ; matana = kandung (yg kau lahirkan)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕayyalah: female fallow deer, Dama mesopotamica,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʕayyalah: female fallow deer, Dama mesopotamica, extinct there since 1914, Fauna p. 20 shluchah (pass): is let get away<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>hannoten (ntn partcpl): giving, producing ʕemer: branched antlers? fawns? words?<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ʕimrey-shafer: antlers End of S section.<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="22" />
      <span class="Italic">Yusuf!</span> Èu ne, sama sèmi aj'u loro dhu dètu dènge madha èi. Dadana na loro asa tembok dhu dedha aae.<bt><span class="Italic">Yusuf!</span> You are like a climbing tree (=vine) which is near a spring. Its branches crawl over a very high wall.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="porat (partcpl fem): fruitful tsaʕədah: mount"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">porat (partcpl fem): fruitful tsaʕədah: mount up (like branches growing up and over a wall)<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>shuwr: wall</Message></Annotation><note reference="49:22" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii madhutu Ibrani ètu d'ara ayat ne, mèu iia boe. Abhu dhèu mèu peka na, &lt;aj'u dhu loro&gt;, aa cahag'e hari na &lt;badha keled'ei&gt;.<bt>The Ibrani language writings in this verse (lona) is not very clear. There are knowledgeable people who say it's meaning is &lt;climbing tree/vine&gt;, and still others who say &lt;donkey animal&gt;.</bt></note><v n="23" />Abhu kahèi dhèu tèka d'ara dènge èu, sama èci èèna ka, dènge musu dhu neo kataki èu.<bt>There are also people who are angry/upset with you, as if (they are) enemies who want to shoot-arrows at you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaymarəruwhuw (mrr piʕel): they made his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vaymarəruwhuw (mrr piʕel): they made his life bitter, provoked him varov: and it was abundant<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>vayisTəmuhuw: they bore a grudge baʕaley chittsim: masters of arrows = archers<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Te ngaa Ama Lamatua dhu ja'a mangaj'i na, bera-bera dènge èu. Ho Na pa'èra ai èu, ka èu kataki si hari, masi ka nèti kaj'èu èèna ka. Èu segi si, lula Ama Lamatua dhu tolong èu. Mema koasa Na risi aa'i ngaa-ngaa! Nèti èèna ka, Nèngu j'aj'i era sarai ja'a, lula Nèngu na ka dhu madhenge ja'a.<bt>But the God whom I worship, accompanies you. So He strengthens your hand, and you shoot-arrows back at them, even from afar. You beat them, because God helps (loan) you. His power/authority is truly greater than everything! That is why He has become my place to lean/depend on, because He is the one who watches-over me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="teshev: sat, stayed ʔeytan: firm|i(24) (24)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">teshev: sat, stayed ʔeytan: firm<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>vayyafozzu (pzz): was nimble, agile zəroʕey: the force of<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>zroʕey yadaw: the power of his hand ʔavir: strong, powerful<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Aa Nèngu madhenge èu kahèi. Dènge Na pala-bagi hia èu mèngi-nale nèti dedha-liru, nèti rai-haha, dènge berkat ho matana ana ae-ae dhu ngi'u èra.<bt>And He also watches over you. And He divides out to you blessings1 from the sky, from the earth, and blessings2 to bear many healthy children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vyaʕzrekha: he supports you ʔet shadday"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vyaʕzrekha: he supports you ʔet shadday (accusative + shadayim dual): two breasts = yoa wife wen she make milk fo yoa kids OR<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>ʔel shadday: Almighty God rovetset: crouching, lying<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>the breast and the womb; part for the whole</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Ledhe-ledhe ra ele boe. Aa mamèngi-nale dhu ja'a peka mi èu ne, dedha risi nèti ledhe aa'i-aa'i ra. Sèna ka hud'i laa berkat se aa'i-aa'i sabhori asa èu, lula èu ne risi nèti a'ari èu se aa'i-aa'i si.<bt>The mountains never disappear. And the blessings1 which I am telling upon you about are greater than all the mountains. May all these blessings2 be poured over you, because you are greater than all of these elder-younger siblings of yours.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="loro = melata; 24: sarai ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">loro = melata; 24: sarai = sandaran, harapan, (tempat bergantung); 26: busa = anjing ; higher, bigger, more than eternal</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gavru: exceed, excel over taʔəwat: delightful"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">gavru: exceed, excel over taʔəwat: delightful things<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>givʕot: hills qadqod: girigiri (the whorl of hair over the back of the skull); head, crown of head, top of head, hairy crown, scalp; from qdd ʔbowʔ, possibly the part of the head you see when somebody bows to you. Most translations say "brow," but it's not the forehead.<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>nəzir: one dedicated as a prince, singled out End of P section.<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="hk-lb\bk00045c.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Busa hui ètu rai Isra'el<bt>Wild dogs/canines in the land of Isra'el</bt></fig>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="27" />
      <span class="Italic">Benyamin!</span> Babani èu sama sèmi busa hui dhu manganga. Mad'ae aae era, na kèd'i le èèna, ho bata-magèla badha hui, ho j'aj'i mi nganga'a na. Aa, ladhe d'ai ka mèda, la'e papala dhu sisa hia mi ana-ana nèngu. Babe'a ana-èpu èu sèmi èèna kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt><span class="Italic">Benyamin!</span> Your courage/daring is like (that of) a hungry wild dog. While still morning, it gets up to go hunt (doublet) wild animals, to be its food. And when night comes, it goes and divides out the rest (of the meat) to his offspring. The goodness of your descendants are also like that.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bata-magèla = usir, berburu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">bata-magèla = usir, berburu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zʔev: wolf, Canis lupus yitraf: he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">zʔev: wolf, Canis lupus yitraf: he tears in pieces<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>ʕad: prey ychalleq (piʕel): divide booty<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>shalal: prey, booty</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Sange ne'e ka, Yakob peka dènge ana-ana na, tasa mera mia mamuri rèngu pala lod'o limuri, èci-èci ka dènge ana-èpu rèngu. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i se'e ka, j'aj'i mi bèi-baki nèti canguru dua suku dhèu Isra'el.<bt>That's the extent of Yakob foretelling to his children, about how their life/charactistics in the future, each one with their descendants. All of these became the ancestors/forefathers of the 12 tribes of the people of Isra'el.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob madhe<bt>Yakob dies</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29-30" />Èle èèna ka, Yakob manèngi sèna ka ana-ana na pajaji mema, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nèbhu heka, ja'a madhe. Ladhe bèli-camèd'a ja'a madhe, na miu hud'i padhane ku ja'a asa d'ara ro'a baki ku Abraham. Ro'a ne, ètu d'ara loe padètu dènge rae Makpela, dènge Mamre ètu rai Kana'an. Uru na baki Abraham ka dhu hèli loe dènge oka na, ho j'aj'i mi era ro'a nèngu. Na hèli pama'ète nèti dhèu suku Het, ngara na Efron.<bt>After that, Yakob asked his children to promise ahead of time, saying, &lt;&lt;I will soon die. In the future when I die, you must bury me in the burial ground of my grandfather Abraham. That burial place is in a cave near the village of Makpela, and Mamre in the land of Kana'an. Formerly grandfather Abraham is the one who bought the cave with its field, to be for his burial place. He bought it outright from a person of the Het tribe, named Efron.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaytsaw (tswh): ordered neʔəSaf (nif): meet,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vaytsaw (tswh): ordered neʔəSaf (nif): meet, gather, be gathered, be taken away<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>məʕarah: cave laʔəchuzzat: as a possession<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>qever: grave, sepulcher</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Ètu era èèna, ra padhane baki èdhi Abraham dènge bèi èdhi Sara; ama ja'a Isak dènge ina ku Ribka ètu èèna kahèi. De èèna na, miu hud'i padhane ja'a mi era èèna, ètu sebhe ro'a dhèu èmu ja'a Lea.<bt>In that place, they buried our-inc grandfather Abraham and our grandmother Sara; my father Isak and my mother Ribka are also there. So there you must bury me in that place, beside the grave of my spouse Lea.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shammah: to there"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">shammah: to there</Message></Annotation><v n="32" />De mage mi bhèlu, padhane ja'a ètu d'ara loe dhu baki Abraham ku hèli nare èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>So, don't forget to bury me in that cave which granfather Abraham had purchased.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="loe = 1) goa, 2a) berhenti,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">loe = 1) goa, 2a) berhenti, 2b) tenang ; ro'a = kuburan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miqneh hasadeh: the landed property"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">miqneh hasadeh: the landed property</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Yakob padhai lii nare sèmi èèna, na bhèj'i dènge ka ètu dedha koi na, hèia na madhe dènge ka.<bt>When Yakob finished speaking like that, he slay down/slept on top of that bed, and then he died.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyeʔəSof: collect, take in, take away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayyeʔəSof: collect, take in, take away vayyeʔaSef (nif): meet, gather, be gathered, be taken away<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="50" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia Yusuf liku nare ama na, ka na tangi. Na uu ama na pèri-pèri hari.<bt>Then Yusuf embraced his father, and he wept. He kissed his father repeatedly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayipol (nfl): let himself fall, throw"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayipol (nfl): let himself fall, throw himself down; a sign of grief, often seen on TV reports of Mid East funerals</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ka na paredha dhèu dhu tuka urus dhèu madhe mai lalau ngi'u aae ama na dènge bubhu-bubhu, sèna ka baku ele iie.<bt>And he commanded the people who habitually arrange dead people to come look after his father's corpse with spices, so that it did not decay.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lachənoT: to embalm, Egyptian style"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">lachənoT: to embalm, Egyptian style</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Sasab'a tuka lalau ngi'u aae ama na, d'ai èpa nguru lod'o, madhutu j'ara sasab'a rèngu. Dhèu Masir aa'i-aa'i madhutu tangi kahèi mamadhe Yakob ne'e. Ra beke pidhu nguru lod'o, tao sèmi dhèu kapai rèngu madhe.<bt>The work of the people who looked after his father's corpse lasted 40 days, according to the ways of their work. Masir people also all participated in mourning/crying for Yakob's death. They mourned/waked for 70 days, doing like they would for an important person who died.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayimlʔu-lo: they filled up 40 days"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayimlʔu-lo: they filled up 40 days on him; it took them 40 days to do it vayivku (bkh): they cried = observed a mourning period<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Èle beke pidhu nguru lod'o, hèia Yusuf peka dènge dhèu sab'a na sèra, &lt;&lt;Mi nanene! Mèti ku lii ja'a ne asa dhèu aae, peka sèmi ne'e:<bt>When the 70 days of mourning were finished, Yusuf said to his workers, &lt;&lt;You all listen! Take my message to the king, and say like this:</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔim-naʔ matsaʔti chen bʕeynekhem: if I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔim-naʔ matsaʔti chen bʕeynekhem: if I have found favor in your eyes bʔazney farʕoh: in Pharaoh's ear; privately, not as a formal request<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />&lt;Lod'o ama ku oe madhe, na moa sèna ka ja'a laku padhane ne asa rai Kana'an. De ja'a manèngi ho ama dhèu aae hia ja'a ijin laku padhane ama ku. Ladhe èle na, ja'a lèpa hari mai.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;When my father was almost dead, he made me promise to go bury him in the land of Kana'an. So I ask that father king give me permission (loan) to go bury my father. When it is over, I will come back here.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishbiyʕaniy (shbʕ hif): he caused me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">hishbiyʕaniy (shbʕ hif): he caused me to swear an oath qivriy: my tomb<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>kariti (krh): I have dug (maybe a shelf inside the Makpelah burial cave?)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ropa tadèngi, hèia dhèu aae dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe èu dhu moa le mi ama mu sèmi èèna na, lamu ho padhane ne ètu nèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>When he heard that, the king responded, saying, &lt;&lt;If you have promised your father like that, go and bury him yonder.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ka Yusuf pakèd'i ka, la'e padhane ama na. Dhèu ae madhutu lasi dènge ne kahèi. Sèmi kapala urusan nèti dhèu aae, dènge dhèu kapai aa'i-aa'i nèti Masir.<bt>So Yusuf left, going to bury his father. Many people also accompanied him. Such as the department heads of the king, and all the important people of Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ziqney: senior officials"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ziqney: senior officials</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />A'ari Yusuf dènge dhèu-dhèu sab'a ra aa'i-aa'i, lasi padhane Yakob. Dhu ata ètu Gosen dhoka dhèu èmu ra, ana iiki, dènge badha-manu ra di.<bt>Yusuf's elder-younger siblings and all their workers went to bury Yakob. Those who remained in Gosen were only their spouses, small children, and their animals (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Tappam: their people who were too"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">Tappam: their people who were too weak to walk - children and older people ʕazvuw: were left behind<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Sordad'u ae madhutu kahèi. Cahag'e ca'e kareta, aa cahag'e hari ca'e jara. Taga dhèu dhu madhutu na, ae d'ai seli, nèti èèna ka, rombongan dhu rèti dhèu madhe ne, madhera titu kèna.<bt>Many soldiers (Port loan) also accompanied them. Some rode carts, and some rode horses. Because the people who accompanied them were so many, that is why the entourage (loan) which took the dead man was very long.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ata = sisa; 9: Ana patèta"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">ata = sisa; 9: Ana patèta = tentara (lii pacele)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rekhev: contingent of chariots parashim: horsemen,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">rekhev: contingent of chariots parashim: horsemen, cavalrymen<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>machaneh: encampment, contingent</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Rèngu lasi, ka ra pège loko Yarden ètu era èci, ngara na Atad. Era ne'e, dhèu biasa mai j'èli are. D'ai era ne'e, Yusuf si tangi mamadhe ama na. Aa ra beke hari pidhu mèda.<bt>They went, and they crossed the river Yarden at a place named Atad. This place, (is where) people normally came to step on grain (to get it off the stalks). Arriving at this place, Yusuf mob wept for the death of his father. And they mourned/waked for 70 more nights.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pège = menyebrang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">pège = menyebrang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="goren: threshing floor, threshing camp ʔatad:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">goren: threshing floor, threshing camp ʔatad: boxthorn<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>vayyiSpəduw: they beat their breast, sounded a lament miSped<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>vayaʕas ʔevel: he made mourning rites</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ropa dhèu Kana'an ètu sèra, ladhe na ra j'èra ae titu kèna, hèia ra papeka, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;We! Miu laladhe ku laa! Babeke mamadhe dhèu Masir se, ra susa bia nga! J'ara tatangi rèngu sèmi nèi ni ka.&gt;&gt; Nèti èèna ka, ra pangare era èèna, ngara na <span class="Italic">Abel-Misraim.</span> Sasoa na, &lt;sasusa dhèu Masir&gt;.<bt>When the people of Kana'an there saw their great suffering, they said to themselves, saying, &lt;&lt;We! Have a look at this! The mourning oof the death of these Masir people, is very sorrowful! The way they weep is something else (idiom).&gt;&gt; That is why they named that place, with the name, <span class="Italic">Abel-Misraim.</span> It means, &lt;the grief of the people of Masir&gt;.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Hèia ana-ana Yakob se, tao madhutu sèmi lii moa rèngu uru na.<bt>Then the children of Yakob, did according to what they had promised previously.</bt><v n="13" />Ka nedhe rèti ngi'u aae Yakob na, lasi padhane asa d'ara loe dhu padètu dènge rae Makpela dènge Mamre. Abraham hèli nare era ne'e nèti dhèu suku Het, ngara na Efron, ho j'aj'i mi era udhu rui rèngu.<bt>They picked up the corpse of Yakob, and went to bury it inside the cave near the villages of Makpela and Mamre. Abraham had purchased this place from a person of the Het tribe, named Efron, to be their family burial ground.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="udhu-rui = kumpul tulang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">udhu-rui = kumpul tulang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bimʕarat: in a cave in a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">bimʕarat: in a cave in a field qanah: buy<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ʔəchuzzat: possession</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf pa'èra d'ara a'a na si<bt>Yusuf encourages his elder-siblings</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Yusuf padhane nare ama na, hèia nèngu dènge a'ari na lèpa hari asa Masir. Sama-sama dènge dhèu leo dhu madhutu sèra.<bt>When Yusuf had buried his father, then he and his elder-younger siblings returned to Masir. Together with the other people who had accompanied them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ropa rèngu d'ai Masir, a'a Yusuf se mulai madha'u. Lula ama rèngu aad'o heka, ka ra papeka, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;We! Ta pangee ku la! Sèmi Yusuf tèka d'ara dènge èdhi era, ho na b'ala tatao karehe èdhi mi nèngu uru èèna, na èdhi tasamia?&gt;&gt;<bt>When they arrived in Masir, Yusuf's edler-siblings began to be afraid. Because their father was no longer, they spoke among themselves, saying, &lt;&lt;We! Let's think about this! If perchance Yusuf is still angry/upset with us-inc, and wants to avenge/repay our-inc evil deeds to him long ago, what are we going to do?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="luʔ: suppose yisTəmenuw: still bears a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">luʔ: suppose yisTəmenuw: still bears a grudge (but doesn't say anything)<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>hashev yashiv (shwv): pay back, take revenge gamalnu: we perpetrated, rendered<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Hèia rare lii èci, ka ra hia lii la'e asa Yusuf, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama wakil. Ji'i sanèd'e era, lod'o ama èdhi mamuri era, na pua ji'i<bt>So they reached an agreement and they sent word to Yusuf, saying, &lt;&lt;Father rep. We-exc still remember that when our-inc father was still alive, he ordered us-exc</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaytsawwuw: they made an an appointment"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vaytsawwuw: they made an an appointment</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />ho padhai lii dènge ama wakil, peka na, &lt;Yusuf hud'i bhabhèlu eele ka sasala a'a na si. Lula uru na ra paj'èra ne.&gt; Ji'i nge'a kahèi ama èdhi ne, karèi nèti uru ka mai, na mangaj'i dhoka mi Ama Lamatua di. Ji'i kahèi j'aj'i ana pajuu Lamatua. Nèti èèna ka, ji'i mai manèngi abho, lula uru na ji'i paj'èra le, ama wakil.&gt;&gt;<bt>to speak with father rep, saying, &lt;Yusuf must completely forget the wrong of his elder-siblings. Because long ago they cause him suffering.&gt; We also know that our father, beginning from long ago, worshipped only God. We also are the servants of the Lord. Therefore, we come to ask forgiveness (assim. loan; focussing on act of seeking forgiveness), because long ago we have caused (you) suffering, father rep.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa tadèngi lii ne'e, hèia Yusuf tangi.<bt>When he heard this message, Yusuf wept.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔannaʔ: I pray! Please! saʔ (nsʔ):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔannaʔ: I pray! Please! saʔ (nsʔ): forgive<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>peshaʕ: revolt, rebellion chaTTaʔtam: sin against you<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Èle èèna ka, a'a na si mai unu ra, ka patitu kètu urutuu ètu madha na. Hèia ra padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Hud'i laa ama tao ji'i j'aj'i ènu ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, his elder-siblings came themselves, and bowed before him. Then they spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Father must make us your slaves.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Te ngaa Yusuf padhai lii dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Miu se a'a ja'a! Miu baku madha'u ia ka! Dhoka Ama Lamatua di, dhu dènge hak hia huku mi dhèu. Te ja'a ne, aad'o.<bt>But Yusuf spoke with them, &lt;&lt;You here are my elder-siblings! You-pl should no longer be afraid! Only God is the one who has the right to punish people. But as for me, (I) don't.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tachat: in the place of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">tachat: in the place of</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Mema tare'a, uru na miu mere lii èci, ho neo paj'èra ja'a. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua ka dhu ub'a eele tatao miu dhu karehe èèna, j'aj'i mi babe'a. Nèti èèna ka, Na ded'e ja'a j'aj'i dhèu kapai ètu ne'e, sèna ka dhèu ae abhu mamuri dènge karej'e.<bt>Yes it is true, that long ago you-pl agreed to cause me suffering. But God is the one who completely changed your evil deed, to become something good. That is why He elevated me to become an important person here, so that many people could get life/saved in happiness.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chəshavtem: planned lmaʕan: in order to|i(20)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">chəshavtem: planned lmaʕan: in order to<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Nèti èèna ka, ja'a peka dènge miu kèna! Baku madha'u ia ka. Ja'a pamoa dènge miu se, èèna na, ladhe-leru miu, dènge ana-èpu miu aa'i-aa'i ra.&gt;&gt;<bt>That is why I said that to you! You should no longer be afraid. I promise you, that in the future, I will look out for you, and all your children-grandchildren.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="uba ; hèu mèngi = sweet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">uba ; hèu mèngi = sweet fragrance</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dènge lii padhai lii sèmi ne'e ne, Yusuf pa'èra hari d'ara a'a na si.<bt>By speaking like that, Yusuf encouraged the insides of his elder-siblings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔəkhalkel (kwl pilpel): provide for vaynachem:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʔəkhalkel (kwl pilpel): provide for vaynachem: he reassured them<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>vaydiber ʕal-libam: he spoke to their hearts; he tried to persuade them graciously</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mamadhe Yusuf<bt>Yusuf's death</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Èle èèna ka, Yusuf pea taruu ètu rai Masir, dènge a'ari na si, aa'i-aa'i ra. Nèngu mamuri d'ai 110 (cangasu canguru) tèu.<bt>After that, Yusuf continued to live in the land of Masir, with all of his relatives. He lived until 110 years.</bt><v n="23" />Nèngu d'ai hari nèdhi ana-èpu Efraim kahèi. Aa na leru èpu Manase, nuka ana-ana nèti Makir.<bt>He was able to also see Efraim's children and grandchildren. And he took care of Manase's grandchild, who were the children of Makir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕal-birkey Yosef: on Joseph's knees; as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">ʕal-birkey Yosef: on Joseph's knees; as if they were born to him (not just sitting on Grandpa's knee, but almost like a hanai relationship; also used of Zilpah bearing kids for Leah)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Yusuf peka mi a'a na si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'a ku si ee! Ja'a rasa na mamadhe ja'a dètu le! Te ngaa ja'a parcaya, Ama Lamatua tatu ladhe-leru miu. Bèli-camèd'a Nèngu ka dhu lere miu kalua nèti rai ne'e. Nèngu kahèi dhu nèti hari miu lèpa asa rai dhu Na padhadha le pake lii subha, ho hia mi baki èdhi Abraham, Isak dènge ama èdhi Yakob.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yusuf spoke to his elder-siblings, saying, &lt;&lt;My elder-siblings! I feel that my death is near! But I believe that God will certainly look out for you-pl. In the future He is the one who will take you out from this land. He is the one who will lead you from this land. He is also the one who will take you back home to the land which He oath-swore to give to our-inc grandfather/forefather Abraham, Isak, and our-inc father Yakob.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paqod yifqod: he will take care"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">paqod yifqod: he will take care of (also verse 25) nishbaʕ (nif): he swore an oath<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Ka Yusuf manèngi mi a'ari na si, sèna ka ra subha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu hud'i jaji ku mi dedha ja'a. Ladhe lod'o d'ai Ama Lamatua nèti hari miu asa rai Kana'an, miu hud'i mèti ngi'u aae ja'a asa nèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yusuf asked his elder-younger siblings for them to oath-swear, saying, &lt;&lt;You must promise to me. When the day arrives for God to take you back to the land of Kana'an, you must take my corpse yonder.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="soo-subha"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">soo-subha</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Èle èèna ka, Yusuf madhe ètu Masir, dènge umur nèngu 110 (cangasu canguru) tèu. Hèia ra tao bubhu mi ngi'u aae na. Ka ra tao asa d'ara kopa.<bt>After that, Yusuf died in Masir, with an age of 110 years. Then they place spices on his corpse. And they put (him) in a coffin.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kopa = coffin, peti mayat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z">kopa = coffin, peti mayat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayachanTu: they embalmed, mummified. Kind of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:40:31Z" status="Information">vayachanTu: they embalmed, mummified. Kind of like preparing a kaʕiwi. baʔaron: inside a box (in this case, a coffin or mummy case). The same word is used for the Ark of the Covenant.<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
  </book>
</bible>